([{"id":"2486881:Topic:36170","contributorName":"3a3pgvbd6kqxd","title":"Open Position - Web Developer","description":"<p>All,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>ITRE has an opening for a web developer, with an emphasis on CMS, visual communications, multimedia, design, configuration - and some coding. Brief description:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>To provide support and consult on web development, design, coding, and modifying hosted websites. Provide web application development and web communications support, as well as maintain duties for web-based projects which include interactive multimedia, graphics, tutorials, and social media. To provide additional support of Web-Server related operating systems, software licenses, annual maintenance, system backups, network security, firewall, and anti-virus maintained by the university technology office.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/41568\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/41568</a></p>","createdDate":"2014-08-28T17:00:01.284Z","updatedDate":"2014-08-28T17:00:01.404Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:36448","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","title":"Announcement: NC State WordPress Templates","description":"Campus Partners,\n\nUniversity Communications would like to announce that the new NC State WordPress Web Templates are now available on the brand site. The new templates are responsive (mobile-friendly) and utilize NC State's version of Twitter's Bootstrap, Univers web font and the new branding utility bar.\n\n<a href=\"http://brand.ncsu.edu/downloads/#web-templates\">http://brand.ncsu.edu/downloads/#web-templates</a>\n\nWe hope these Web templates, along with the information and assets released via the new brand site, will be valuable to our partners in creating on-brand communications.\n\nIf you have any questions or would like to share feedback about the new templates, please email us at ncstatebrand@ncsu.edu.\n\nThank you,\n\nLuis\n\n--\nLuis Chac\u00f3n\nDirector of Web Communications\nNC State University\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/</a>","createdDate":"2014-06-25T15:18:19.117Z","updatedDate":"2014-06-25T15:18:19.254Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:36252","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","title":"Open Senior Developer position","description":"Was hoping you could help spread the word that Web Communications is recruiting a Senior Developer position to help launch the new NC State brand and participate in the NCSU.EDU redesign. This position will get to work with talented developers, graphic designers, social media specialists, content strategists and a new marketing team. They'll help guide the new NC State web presence as we use the new brand to establish our digital first approach to marketing communications.\n\n<a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/35583\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/35583</a>","createdDate":"2014-06-21T20:58:12.808Z","updatedDate":"2014-06-21T20:58:12.913Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:36141","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","title":"New NC State Brand Website","description":"<p>NC State Developers,</p>\n<p>The new\u00a0<a href=\"http://brand.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">brand website</a> has been out for a few weeks and I'm wondering if you have any questions UCOMM can help address. If you prefer to contact us directly, please use ncstatebrand@ncsu.edu and we'll be happy to follow up with you. We hope the new site is informative and will help you in develop on brand communications.<br/><br/></p>\n<p>I did want to mention that we will be releasing an official <strong>NC State WordPress theme</strong> in the next few weeks. The new theme is built using the <a href=\"http://brand.ncsu.edu/downloads/#bootstrap\" target=\"_blank\">NC State version of Twitter's Bootstrap</a>. We're also providing <a href=\"http://brand.ncsu.edu/downloads/#web-fonts\" target=\"_blank\">Univers as a web font</a>, free of charge. More information about web fonts, bootstrap and other digital assets can be found via the brand site:\u00a0<a href=\"http://brand.ncsu.edu/\">http://brand.ncsu.edu/</a><br/><br/></p>\n<p>Thank you,</p>\n<p>Luis</p>\n<p>--\u00a0</p>\n<div>Luis Chac\u00f3n</div>\n<div>Director of Web Communications</div>\n<div><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/</a></div>","createdDate":"2014-05-21T03:34:55.042Z","updatedDate":"2014-05-21T03:34:55.174Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:36429","contributorName":"2w9u9ep1snbip","title":"PDF Library - Combining PDF Documents (PHP)","description":"<p>Hi everyone,</p>\n<p>I'm working on a project where I need to stitch some existing PDF files together along with some that I'll be generating from text in a DB. I'm working in PHP (Zend Framework 2) so a PHP solution would be nice but I'm flexible.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I've done some research in the past but it's pretty ugly out there with unmaintained projects or others have were merged together, etc. I'm up against a wall so I thought I'd see if anyone has some knowledge in this area that could offer some help/advice/sample-code.</p>","createdDate":"2014-05-07T19:35:45.019Z","updatedDate":"2014-05-07T19:35:45.165Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:35908","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Looking for Clean WordPress Theme","description":"<p>I'm looking for a simple WordPress theme that is extremely clean in terms of lines and layout. See attached for what my end user has in mind.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks for any suggestions!</p>","createdDate":"2014-04-16T20:44:17.202Z","updatedDate":"2014-05-08T14:32:55.142Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/1-JAER_HomePage.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:36335","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"<p>Jason Maners brought this theme to our attention and is working with it,\u00a0<strong><a href=\"http://alxmedia.se/themes/hueman/\" target=\"_blank\">http://alxmedia.se/themes/hueman/</a></strong></p>","createdDate":"2014-05-08T14:32:54.670Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:36230","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>You can't get more basic than twenty twelve!</p>","createdDate":"2014-05-02T13:49:19.029Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:35723","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>I might try looking around here: <a href=\"http://themeforest.net/category/wordpress\" target=\"_blank\">http://themeforest.net/category/wordpress</a></p>","createdDate":"2014-04-17T13:26:02.441Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:35785","contributorName":"0zj9mgzp9xa63","title":"Ruby on Rails","description":"<p>{First Post}</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Hello all, hope I'm in the right spot with this one. I just joined NCSU Web Developers, and all though I'm not a computer science major I do have a fascination with coding and hope to actually be good at it one day. I'm posting this because I just wanted to see if any of you had any experience with Ruby on Rails (Rails). I've just started learning the basics of it and would love to find someone who was a better mentor than Youtube.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks for reading #GoPack</p>","createdDate":"2014-03-27T15:31:32.616Z","updatedDate":"2014-03-27T15:31:32.719Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:35886","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Making Billboard Better","description":"<p style=\"font:bold 22px Arial; margin-bottom:20px;\">Today, the Extension IT team held a brief brainstorm session to discuss the optimal \"timing\" and arrangement of our newest billboard slide deck.</p>\n<div style=\"font:15px/1.3 Arial; color:#333;\"><ul>\n<li><strong>Should we display slides for 15 seconds, 30 seconds, longer?</strong></li>\n<li>Should all slides display for the same amount of time?</li>\n<li>If the slides change too fast, will the flickering of the LED screen distract nearby staff members in the office?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Many of our billboard slides contain either a short url or QR code which will allow the viewer to access (presumably from their smartphone) additional content pertinent to the slide. The problem is ... even if you set a slide to display for 15 - 30 seconds, there's no guarantee your content consumer won't walk into the room at second #26 ... and suddenly find themselves hard pressed to pull out their smartphone and fire up their QR Scanner in time.</p>\n<p>If you miss a slide, no big deal right? If your digital signage owner was conservative with the slide deck, you may only have to wait 2 minutes or so for the slide to come back around ... but the situation could be far worse if there are 12+ slides rotating at 30s intervals.</p>\n<p><strong>At one point, I found myself suggesting we hack a motion detector or low-end camera up to our RaspberryPi</strong> (which powers our Billboard display [<em>thanks Everette!</em>]) and do some Microsoft Kinnect -like\u00a0 'gesture' based detection allowing the user to push slides forward and back with a big sweeping hand motion.</p>\n<p>Yeah, that would be cool, really cool - but not extremely practical. Even though we're probably headed in that direction at some point ... that's the future, not the present.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Here's the solution that I think actually has some chops and users would actually appreciate.</p>\n<p><a target=\"_self\" href=\"discussions/2-ScreenShot20140206at3.46.14PM.png\"><img class=\"align-left\" src=\"discussions/3-ScreenShot20140206at3.46.14PM.png?width=750\" width=\"750\"/></a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>You could physically stick a QR code onto the frame of the TV, mount, or just below it which would point to a responsive page containing thumbnail images of all the slides in the deck.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>This would be useful if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You were only able to catch a glimpse of what you though was an important slide, but didn't want to wait for the digital sign to loop back around.</li>\n<li>You're a digital sign owner and want a quick overview of what's displaying on your sign without logging in to actually manage the sign</li>\n<li>You typically find the slide line-up on a particular display to be quite useful and informative and would like to take a peak at the slides once in a while when you're away</li>\n<li>More ... ?</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","createdDate":"2014-02-06T20:51:38.323Z","updatedDate":"2014-02-06T20:53:19.055Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34939","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"WordCamp RDU 2013 will be on campus!","description":"<p>Hey folks! Thanks to our friends at Engineering and after a lot of campus meetings, email, and scouting, I'm happy to report that this year's WordCamp RDU will be taking place in Engineering Building II on Centennial Campus, November 23rd and 24th!</p>\n<p>In past years this event has been held downtown at the Sheraton but by having the event on campus they've been able to cut down on costs a good deal: this year's event is only $35. Your ticket gets you a day and a half of sessions, plus lunch, some coffee and other snacks. There will be three tracks: Users, Power Users, and Developers, plus a keynote (TBA). And if this wasn't a good enough deal for ya, we have a coupon code for campus students and developers. Use the code \"NCSTATE\" (no quotes) to get an extra $10 off your ticket price.</p>\n<p><span>They're still recruiting for speakers so please consider contributing:\u00a0<a href=\"http://2013.raleigh.wordcamp.org/become-a-speaker/\">http://2013.raleigh.wordcamp.org/become-a-speaker/</a>. They'll also be looking for volunteers to help out with stuff so if you have students who might not be able to afford the price of admission you can have them contact the organizers to see if they can get in free in exchange for helping out.</span></p>\n<p><span>Please spread the word to your groups and if you have any questions feel free to drop me a note (jmriehle@ncsu.edu) or contact the other organizers. I hope to see many of you there in November!</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2013-09-06T20:30:10.455Z","updatedDate":"2013-09-06T20:30:10.581Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34731","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Branding Bar oddity","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>One of our units is having an issue with the Branding Bar not displaying correctly in Firefox. Any ideas why?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://oied.ncsu.edu/chocolate/\">http://oied.ncsu.edu/chocolate/</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2013-08-29T16:12:50.553Z","updatedDate":"2013-08-29T16:12:50.691Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:35036","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"OIT Looking for PT web person","description":"<p>Hey folks! Please feel free to pass along to any interested parties...</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-057c63b1-c6a9-d0be-ce01-c7e84fba3688\"><span>The Office of Information Technology is looking for a part-time undergraduate or graduate student to help with multiple web-related projects. Primary tasks include web content migration and some content review, CMS site administration, and customer support/training. Experience with WordPress, Drupal, usability, accessibility and/or HTML/CSS is preferred. Work hours are flexible with the expectation of 10-15 hours/week. Hiring range of $9-$12/hour, based on experience.<br class=\"kix-line-break\"/><br class=\"kix-line-break\"/>Please submit a resume and letter of interest to</span> <span>jen_riehle@ncsu.edu</span> <span>by Friday, September 13th, 2013.</span></span></p>","createdDate":"2013-08-28T20:44:24.934Z","updatedDate":"2013-08-28T20:44:25.053Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34827","contributorName":"2ds7qt1avuxws","title":"no-sql?","description":"<p>Does anyone know if MongoDB or some other no-sql database is in use on campus?</p>","createdDate":"2013-07-26T22:26:32.299Z","updatedDate":"2013-07-29T13:19:05.345Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:34524","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>Nowhere I know of. \u00a0At least not in OIT.</p>","createdDate":"2013-07-29T13:19:04.785Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34711","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Campus video conferencing survey","description":"<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>As a faculty or staff member, do you currently use video conferencing or plan to use it in the future?</span></p>\n<p>The Office of Information Technology (OIT) is working with a consultant to conduct a campus-wide survey to gain a better understanding of your video conferencing needs, from desktop video chats to high-quality tele-presence sessions. We invite you to participate by taking the <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/vcsurvey\">Video Conferencing Survey</a> by Monday, June 10.</p>\n<p>Your feedback will help develop a needs assessment and begin the process for developing a plan for more comprehensive, customer-focused video conferencing solutions on campus.</p>\n<p>Please share this survey with colleagues who may have an interest in video conferencing. \u00a0Everyone is welcome to participate. \u00a0For more information about this initiative, send an email to Cheri Renninger or Josh Jury of OIT Communication Technologies at <a href=\"mailto:oit_ct_uc@remedy.ncsu.edu\">oit_ct_uc@remedy.ncsu.edu</a>.</p>\n<p><span>\u00a0</span></p>","createdDate":"2013-06-04T16:54:51.114Z","updatedDate":"2013-06-04T16:54:51.269Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34702","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Looking for FileMaker Expertise","description":"<p>We have a unit in the Division of Academic &amp; Student Affairs (DASA) that relies on a home-grown application built with FileMaker. The original developer is not available, so we are looking for someone on campus with Filemaker expertise (as used for web application development) who can consult with us to consider options for further development or migration to another platform. Please contact me directly if you or someone you know might fit the bill. Leslie Dare at <a href=\"mailto:ladare@ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">ladare@ncsu.edu</a>. Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2013-05-17T11:13:43.858Z","updatedDate":"2013-05-17T11:13:43.979Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34664","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Job Opening at UNC System Office","description":"<p>The folks in General Administration have an opening and have asked me to share this link:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://uncgacareers.northcarolina.edu/applicants/jsp/shared/position/JobDetails_css.jsp?postingId=145346\">https://uncgacareers.northcarolina.edu/applicants/jsp/shared/position/JobDetails_css.jsp?postingId=145346</a></p>","createdDate":"2013-05-01T19:07:41.481Z","updatedDate":"2013-05-01T19:07:41.607Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:34463","contributorName":"3j1n2h0mx8u6l","title":"Looking for webpage builder for small but timely job","description":"<p>I have a grant-funded project in which I need 2-3 additional pages built into our current website (which is in WordPress platform). We are nearing the final stretch of gathering cost estimates for this project, and OIT suggested I contact you. The primary content of the new pages include:<br/> <br/>1. a searchable map backed by a simple database, and <br/>2. a form for visitors to complete to let us know we are missing data for the map<br/><br/>Attached are the project specs in greater detail. We'd like the project completed over the next month or two. Any help getting the word out ASAP to local web developers up to this task would be greatly appreciated!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Sincerely,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Marcy Bauer<br/>mjbauer2@ncsu.edu<br/>919-515-0277<a target=\"_self\" href=\"discussions/4-Onlinedatabase_mapspecsheet.docx\"></a></p>","createdDate":"2013-04-29T14:14:14.315Z","updatedDate":"2013-04-29T14:14:14.480Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/5-Onlinedatabase_mapspecsheet.docx","discussions/6-Database_websitewireframe_DRAFT.pptx"]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:33831","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Job Opening in Outreach Technology","description":"<p>Our group, Outreach Technology, is hiring a new developer. \u00a0The focus of the job will be on mobile app development and web/api backend services. \u00a0You can read more about the job at\u00a0<a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/20779\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/20779</a>. \u00a0If you have any specific questions, feel free to hit me up.</p>","createdDate":"2013-03-12T12:51:32.518Z","updatedDate":"2013-03-12T12:51:32.830Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:33264","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Processing forms in Wordpress","description":"<p>Hi all,</p>\n<p>I am setting up a form on a WordPress site. I've done this various ways, from using a Form to DB plugin that allows the user to browse the form submissions, to coding custom Wordpress page templates that store and retrieve data to/from the MySQL DB without a plugin.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>My question is, I am now needing to submit credit card payments to NC State's Nelnet gateway. This requires my form to specify a required URL in the \"action=\" attribute. If you've processed forms in Wordpress before, you probably know that you need to leave \"action=\" blank.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So, how do I submit forms to Nelnet through Wordpress?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-31T18:21:21.779Z","updatedDate":"2013-01-31T18:21:21.902Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:33034","contributorName":"3dl4ekwu0vtvo","title":"Need part-time Moodle developer","description":"<p>Hi All,</p>\n<p>I have an industry colleague who needs a part-time Moodle developer.</p>\n<p>If you are interested or know an experienced Moodle developer, contact me and I'll share the job details.</p>\n<p>Thanks,<br/>Mary</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-07T20:00:25.009Z","updatedDate":"2013-01-07T20:00:25.127Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:33227","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","title":"Continuous Integration and Deployment - Who's doing what ?","description":"<p>I'm currently working on applications in Wolftech I.T., and have been working on a lightweight release process.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The historical approach is to initiate a project in a beta folder with access to production filesystem and database resources.\u00a0While I've migrated the apps I'm working on into a fully isolated development environment, there are still \u00a0gaps to bridge in deployment.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I'd like to hear how others are addressing software release processes:</p>\n<p>- Version control, particularly release tagging/branching</p>\n<p>- Continuous Integration, including automated testing (Is anyone using Jenkins for C.I. ?)</p>\n<p>- Deployment automation, including database migrations and releasing patches</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-12-19T15:47:12.769Z","updatedDate":"2013-01-17T14:50:41.591Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:33346","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>Just an update on this. \u00a0I now have a Jenkins box up and running, and have a one-click build and deploy mechanism setup to deploy our WebRegistry app. \u00a0It checks out the code from GitHub, installs the required dependencies, sets the correct permissions, copies configuration files, runs database migrations, and switches the symlink of our staging or production release to the newly released code. \u00a0One click. \u00a0I can't tell you how happy this makes me :)</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Jenkins is really flippin sweet. \u00a0I am going to get all of our apps in there as we migrate them to GitHub so that every deployment can be as easy as logging into a web page and clicking a button. \u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-17T14:50:41.120Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33043","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>It certainly does work in OIT land, as I just got done with a first shot at deploying this way. \u00a0Also, Jenkins is pretty darn sweet.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-11T18:26:11.464Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33147","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Yeah, I think we benefit from the <a href=\"http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.2/mod/core.html#options\" target=\"_blank\">FollowSymlinks option</a> (among others) on the OIT web servers. IIRC, Engineering servers have a lot more limitations to reduce the surface area for abuse by users because the user base is much larger and not limited to employees.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-10T15:44:36.574Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33146","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Right, I was lumping history differences into \"edits\". That's what I get for typing too fast, ha!</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-10T15:35:45.714Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33241","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"<p>Vagrant is more about making isolated,\u00a0reproducible\u00a0development environments using VirtualBox. Puppet/chef or even shell scripts can be used to provision the environments. We were thinking it could be a good tool for setting up environments for part-timers and work studies, and as a workaround for those who otherwise prefer the \u00a0<span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">DOS</span> Windows platform.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-09T19:14:24.367Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33341","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"<p>Using symlinks for deployment staging and cutover was one of the first things I looked at (and it certainly doesn't work on our servers). I didn't want to believe it, but I do understand the motivation for the prohibition.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-09T19:03:45.076Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33145","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>As far as symlinks, we're likely working on very different versions of webservers if you are on Engineering's webservers. \u00a0They are a much different animal than the rest of the webservers from OIT.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-09T16:04:16.421Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33240","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>Garrison was the one working on the environment deployment, and I think he was using Puppet, so I don't really know about Vagrant.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-09T16:02:55.520Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33239","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"<p>Got it on the branch syncing. I don't think a reset --hard is equivalent to a pull --rebase; the latter could have an unresolved conflict from history rewriting on the remote or a local commit. Conflicts are uncommon but still potentially there.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-09T04:26:22.716Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33143","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Have you looked at Vagrant?\n\nHow does one get symlinks to be visible to the Web server on AFS? Or do you have some control over the lockdown on link following (afaict it is no follow on what I've seen).","createdDate":"2013-01-08T19:37:01.687Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33237","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Yes, fetch with hard reset is the right way to go. One of the options for pull makes this easy if you haven't made any local edits: <code>git pull --rebase</code></p>\n<p>I was referring to rebase --onto for the neutral copy change management so that you can keep a feature branch synced with master until the feature branch is completed.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-08T15:28:46.520Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33140","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>This is a big deal to us, so we are working on changing up our process. \u00a0Here is what we do now, and then where we are planning to go very soon.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>What we do now...</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>We all have local development environments on OS X. \u00a0We are using Zend Server CE, but MAMP would work as well.</li>\n<li>All our source code is under version control in SVN or Git.</li>\n<li>All our production apps run out of AFS</li>\n<li>We have a staging environment setup in AFS that we deploy to first. \u00a0We tag our code in SVN or Git, and then export out directly to the staging environment.</li>\n<li>We have staging databases setup as well. \u00a0We copy the production DB to the staging DB, then run any DB migrations we have created for the new release.</li>\n<li>We have a script that sets permissions on the correct directories.</li>\n<li>We test in stage</li>\n<li>Once we are satisfied with staging, we do the entire process again into production.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This has worked for us for a few years, but it has become a huge pain lately as we are doing a lot more deployments. \u00a0It (usually)\u00a0takes 2 of us to do all of this stuff in a timely manner, and there is a lot of areas for screwing up. \u00a0So, I'm currently working on moving to something more automated.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Where we are going...</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>We are working on VM's that exactly mirror our production environment that each dev can run on their local machines. \u00a0This will ensure that we are all on the same development\u00a0environment\u00a0 and that the environment we are developing for will be exactly that as production.</li>\n<li>All of our source code will remain in Git or SVN, but we are going to start migrating all of our applications to GitHub private repos as they are way easier to manage than SVN, especially when you are dealing with naive developers like part time students. \u00a0The process of pull requests is much more simple than dealing with patch files like we do now.</li>\n<li>We have created some phing scripts to handle external dependencies, file permissions, and the execution of our DB migration script. \u00a0The process would be: \u00a0Checkout the code -&gt; run the phing script -&gt; profit.</li>\n<li>We are going to change up how we do deployments to AFS to take advantage of symlinks. \u00a0What we will do is deploy a tag to a releases directory (/releases/application-name/1.0.0). \u00a0Then, in our staging or production environments, use symlinks to map the directory to the release folder. \u00a0What that means is that once we get everything the way we want it in staging, we just have to change the symlink over for production and the same code will execute. \u00a0This limits downtime and makes it stupid simple to roll back.</li>\n<li>I am currently working on getting a jenkins environment going so that all of this can be automated. \u00a0</li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>As far as testing, we have unit tests written for a good chunk of our core framework, but we need to do better about it for the rest of our code. \u00a0All our unit tests would be integrated as part of our jenkins environment.</p>\n<p>We are in the infancy of our migration to our new way of doing things, but I will report back once we have things setup.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2013-01-08T15:25:15.451Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33036","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Oh, and thanks for the reply.","createdDate":"2013-01-08T14:36:23.851Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33337","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"ZFS sounds interesting.\n\nI am thinking in a deployment context, that a fetch+hard reset on origin+tag checkout would be preferable to a pull/merge or rebase. Merge and rebase both have the side-effect of creating new commits and changed hashrefs, whereas reset updates the HEAD reference to point to an existing commit.","createdDate":"2013-01-08T14:30:14.273Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33334","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Some things we've done:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>operate on a <strong>copy</strong> of the database and filesystem (zfs snapshots make this much easier)</li>\n<li>using SVN or git for new version deployment (update the branch/tag in a neutral location so that the server can do a simple update/rebase)</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2013-01-08T13:50:55.352Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:33128","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Tracking users in Wordpress","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I've been tasked with updating a training module by converting it to Wordpress. I've found a member-management plugin that will let people register on the site. But I also need to be able to track their completion of various content pieces within the site.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Anyone know how to do this easily and elegantly? I haven't found any plugins that will combine the to-do list functionality with the member management piece. I am tempted to just write some MySQL code myself, but I haven't done that within Wordpress before. I've never written any plugins either.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Help!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-12-18T18:08:43.163Z","updatedDate":"2013-02-01T00:56:00.378Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:33352","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"Have you looked at Gravity forms?","createdDate":"2013-02-01T00:55:59.906Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33052","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Elizabeth, so first of all I apologize, I didn't see this until now. My first thought on reading this was of a plugin called Sensei from WooThemes (<a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/sensei/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.woothemes.com/products/sensei/</a>), although this is really kind of serious overkill for what you need. It's also very similar to the functionality campus gets from Moodle - have you considered managing this with Moodle instead of WordPress?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If you don't want to do that I would recommend looking into a custom content type. Again, maybe it's too late and you already have a\u00a0separate\u00a0database and everything but you should be able to create a custom content type with options that for the modules and users and who's done what - I imagine that would be much simpler than writing something form scratch.</p>","createdDate":"2013-01-31T19:16:52.996Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:33326","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Update: It looks fairly easy to create a MySQL database alongside the WP ones. At this point, unless someone has the perfect plugins to recommend, I am ditching the idea of plugins and simply using the new DB to track the users and their training.</p>","createdDate":"2012-12-18T18:29:40.985Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32944","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Suggestions for local web developer's?","description":"<p>I feel like we've talked about this before but I couldn't find a post on it. Does anyone have any recommendations for good local web design/development companies or contractors? Preferably those that do web applications development as well? We have someone who is looking for off-campus help but isn't sure where to start so I thought I'd ask if any of you are aware of some good companies. It would be especially helpful if they're familiar with campus, though that's not a requirement.\u00a0</p>\n<p>Should we keep some kind of list on here for people to reference in the future?</p>","createdDate":"2012-11-20T19:31:19.010Z","updatedDate":"2012-11-20T20:37:35.890Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:32742","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>AtlanticBT does some pretty good work.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2012-11-20T20:37:35.391Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32239","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Joomla Expertise?","description":"<p class=\"p1\">Does anyone on campus have more than a basic understanding of Joomla?</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p2\">We have a client/site that may need some attention soon, and OIT Design is not a Joomla shop in any sense.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">So, i'm just wondering if anyone on campus has experience with it, and could work with a client site (for pay as i understand the situation).</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Let me know if you have questions or can act as a Joomla resource.</p>","createdDate":"2012-10-10T19:29:22.557Z","updatedDate":"2012-10-10T19:29:22.695Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32529","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"WordCamp is coming to Raleigh","description":"<p>Hey folks!</p>\n<p>In case you aren't aware WordCamp, the WordPress conference, is coming to Raleigh in a month or so. The event will be at the Sheraton Hotel, across from the Convention Center downtown, on Saturday and Sunday, Nov 3rd and 4th.</p>\n<p>The tickets are outrageously cheap -- $40 -- so other than the tragedy of giving up your weekend (the weekend of an NCSU home game, I might add) there's no reason so miss this if you use WordPress.</p>\n<p>Website:\u00a0<a href=\"http://2012.raleigh.wordcamp.org/\">http://2012.raleigh.wordcamp.org/</a></p>\n<p>Hope to see you there!</p>","createdDate":"2012-10-09T21:17:27.835Z","updatedDate":"2012-10-09T21:17:27.957Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32232","contributorName":"1ja0p602qofub","title":"Content Management Analyst position in DELTA","description":"<p>DELTA has a new Content Management Analyst position in the Applications Development group. This person will be the primary person responsible for managing a content management service using Equella.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This position has been posted online (<a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/13162\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/13162</a>). Please share with anyone that might be interested.</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-27T17:49:35.506Z","updatedDate":"2012-09-27T17:49:35.622Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31910","contributorName":"078ozyfvp6t5x","title":"Web Developers for hire - Part-Time on Campus","description":"<p>Hello everyone,</p>\n<p>I am part of the founding team of an IT company and we are looking for up to three part-time web-developers.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Required Skills include: php (ZEND), CSS, XML, html (html 5 is a plus), MySQL (or any database knowledge), and javascript.</strong></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Anything else, such as java or python would be very beneficial.</p>\n<p>Please send resumes and other correspondence to <em><strong>josh 'at' penesec.com</strong></em></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-18T15:52:43.493Z","updatedDate":"2012-09-18T15:53:18.452Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31772","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"WP WRAP plugin no longer works?","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p>I've used the WRAP plugin many times but now it doesn't seem to work on my new sites! I locked myself out of my site and had to go in the back end and delete the plugin folder.</p>\n<p>I do think I have the latest version.</p>\n<p>Anyone know what could be the problem? Users really like WRAP instead of having to remember passwords.</p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-14T18:17:33.234Z","updatedDate":"2012-09-30T02:06:56.529Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:32436","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Doh! Thanks, Jen.</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-30T02:06:56.148Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31775","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>The only time I have issues with it is when I forget to add the WRAP auth lines to the htaccess file. The README for the plugin includes the exact text you need but it's essentially the \"wrapauth\" and \"known-user\" options and that's all you need.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If that's not your problem let me know the sites giving you trouble and I'll kick 'em around and see what they do. :)</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-14T18:39:52.324Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31972","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"Job Opening for ITECS Web Programmer","description":"<p>If you're interested or know of people who might be, see <a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/12899\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/12899</a>, Position Number 00060467.</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-31T20:41:31.063Z","updatedDate":"2012-08-31T20:41:31.502Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31970","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Branding bar & Bronto","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I am posting this to the main forum due to the overlap in topics. Our office is using Bronto for an HTML newsletter. The web version has the branding bar:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/oied/digest/diversity-digest_9-4-12.html\">http://www.ncsu.edu/oied/digest/diversity-digest_9-4-12.html</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>However, the email version doesn't like the inline frames and omits the branding bar:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/9xl8x9a\">http://tinyurl.com/9xl8x9a</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Any suggestions for adding the branding in a different but equally elegant way? The fallback would be to just use the brick logo as an image in the header.</p>\n<p><br/>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-08-31T14:09:33.061Z","updatedDate":"2012-09-14T18:11:59.709Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:32163","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Update: I just used the NC State logo instead of the branding bar. HTML newsletters are picky.</p>","createdDate":"2012-09-14T18:11:59.295Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32058","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Help finding a style","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I am trying out a new form plugin on I site I inherited, and it works fine for my purpose, except the response choices (radio buttons, etc) have too much line spacing. I've searched, and I can't find the style that controls them, even with Firebug.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here is the form: <a href=\"http://oied.ncsu.edu/womens-center/ipv-data-collection-form\">http://oied.ncsu.edu/womens-center/ipv-data-collection-form</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Any ideas?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-28T19:20:38.146Z","updatedDate":"2012-08-29T02:22:25.589Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:32067","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Thanks, Nick! That also helped!</p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-08-29T02:22:25.229Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:32063","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Thanks so much, Jonathan!</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-29T02:21:57.663Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31749","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>There's also this section \u00a0in your style.css that might be causing some problems.... specifically the \"ol\" tag.</p>\n<div class=\"cssRule insertInto cssEditableRule editGroup\"><div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">span.wpcf7-list-item</span>\u00a0{</div>\n<div class=\"\"><div class=\"cssPropertyListBox\"><div class=\"cssProp focusRow editGroup\"><a class=\"cssPropDisable\">\u00a0\u00a0</a><span class=\"cssPropName editable\">display</span><span class=\"cssColon\">:</span><span class=\"cssPropValue editable\">block</span><span class=\"cssSemi\">;</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\">}</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"cssRule insertInto cssEditableRule editGroup\"><div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">ol</span>\u00a0{</div>\n<div class=\"\"><div class=\"cssPropertyListBox\"><div class=\"cssProp focusRow editGroup\"><a class=\"cssPropDisable\">\u00a0\u00a0</a><span class=\"cssPropName editable\">line-height</span><span class=\"cssColon\">:2.5em</span><span class=\"cssSemi\">;</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\">}</div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\">Change the line height to something else and you should be good to go too:</div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\">ie:\u00a0</div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>wpcf7-form ol {</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>\u00a0line-height: 1.0em;</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>}</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>\u00a0</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>\u00a0</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>\u00a0</span></div>\n<div class=\"editable insertBefore\"><span>// working off the top of my head while a few other things are happening... so i might have that wrong :-)</span></div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2012-08-28T20:22:27.157Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:32060","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<div class=\"cssRule cssEditableRule insertInto editGroup\"><div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">twentyten/style.css line 612 has a lot of bottom margin on the radio button:<br/></span></div>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">\u00a0</span></div>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">.entry-content input</span> {</div>\n<div class=\"\"><div class=\"cssPropertyListBox\"><div class=\"cssProp focusRow editGroup\"><span class=\"\">\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0</span><span class=\"cssPropName editable\">margin</span><span class=\"cssColon\">:\u00a0</span><span class=\"cssPropValue editable\">0 0 24px</span><span class=\"cssSemi\">;</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\" editable insertBefore\">}</div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2012-08-28T19:48:41.981Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31967","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"demo.drupal.ncsu.edu","description":"<p>If you were interested in testing out Drupal, or wondering what the Hosted Drupal Website service that we're providing now does.... you can now play around with a sandbox/demo site:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://demo.drupal.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.drupal.ncsu.edu</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The site resets itself every 3 hours. All you have to do is login and give the tires a good kick. Instructions/quick-start guides can be found on <a href=\"http://drupal.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal.ncsu.edu</a>\u00a0if you're wondering what you might want to test out.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I have only just now got it up and running, but feel free to wrap/log in and take a look.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-08-23T18:34:07.136Z","updatedDate":"2012-08-24T13:38:11.887Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31857","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Here's a new sibling site for\u00a0<a href=\"http://demo.drupal.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">demo.drupal.ncsu.edu</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://officialdemo.drupal.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://officialdemo.drupal.ncsu.edu</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Same concept.... it will reset itself every 3 hours, and uses the \"official\" nc state theme, for people who are considering that as their Drupal flavor.</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-24T13:38:11.591Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32054","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"OIT Design Drupal Services news....","description":"<p class=\"p1\">Just a quick note to let you all know about a a couple of new things on the Drupal front from OIT Design.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">You can now request a Hosted Drupal Site via Web Registry (<a href=\"https://webregistry.ncsu.edu\">https://webregistry.ncsu.edu</a>).\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">All the information about our service, and OIT's Drupal services is available here: <a href=\"http://drupal.ncsu.edu/\"><span class=\"s1\">http://drupal.ncsu.edu</span></a></p>\n<p class=\"p3\"></p>\n<p class=\"p4\">We also have a Google Group to let people know about what we're doing, and when we have announcements about the service (new things, maintenance, etc). To subscribe to the group, go to:</p>\n<p class=\"p3\"></p>\n<p class=\"p5\"><span class=\"s2\"><a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/group-oitdesign-drupal\">http://go.ncsu.edu/group-oitdesign-drupal</a></span></p>\n<p class=\"p5\"><span class=\"s2\">\u00a0</span></p>\n<p class=\"p5\"><span class=\"s2\">If you have any questions about our services, let me know.</span></p>","createdDate":"2012-08-23T12:51:36.183Z","updatedDate":"2012-08-23T12:51:36.367Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31847","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Branding bar plugin - width on mobile devices","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p><br/>Can anyone tell me how to adjust my branding bar width to display correctly on mobile devices while using the plugin? Example: oied.ncsu.edu/advance. The branding bar isn't wide enough.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-20T21:30:16.604Z","updatedDate":"2012-08-21T14:59:30.110Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31849","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Bless you, kind sir.</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-21T14:59:29.750Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31742","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Your footer image is 1000px so it's confusing the body tag's concept of 100%. If you set the body tag to have the <span class=\"cssPropName editable\">min-width</span><span class=\"cssColon\">:\u00a0</span><span class=\"cssPropValue editable\">1000px</span><span class=\"cssSemi\">;</span> (similar to the #page rule), it fixes the branding bar size relative to the rest of the page.</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-20T22:02:23.040Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:32028","contributorName":"38dwd1leu61vn","title":"Web Developer Position in WebComm","description":"<p>Hi folks,</p>\n<p>As some of you may know, we're starting the process of filling the web developer position left by Jeff Laiosa.\u00a0 We've now got the job listed online through Human Resources.\u00a0 So if you, or someone you know may interested, please spread the word.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/9951\">https://jobs.ncsu.edu/postings/9951</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-27T16:00:37.405Z","updatedDate":"2012-06-27T16:00:37.533Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31301","contributorName":"1tuzi3e9fr7e2","title":"ESRI JavaScript API","description":"<p>I work with Extension Forestry on campus and have been tasked with setting up an interactive mapping service. I used ArcGIS's ArcServer previously but wanted to migrate to the JavaScript API to allow for more customization. I am not a programmer by trade (though I do have a GIS concentration and took a class in Python) and have hit a few roadblocks in getting things up and running with JS. I was wondering if anyone here had any experience with this or knew someone who might. Thanks!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Jessica</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-13T20:27:52.560Z","updatedDate":"2012-06-14T19:05:35.424Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31599","contributorName":"1tuzi3e9fr7e2","description":"<p>Of course I'll be out of town tomorrow, as well as for the next one on the 29th! But I hadn't realized this was going on until your comment. This could be useful. If I'm still struggling by then (I'm hoping I won't be but so far its been just one big wall) I'll likely attend the July 6th one. Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-14T19:05:35.147Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31669","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"<p>I don't know anything about ESRI specifically, but I do have a lot of experience with Javascript. \u00a0What kinds of problems are you having? \u00a0If you're coming to co-working tomorrow, I'd be happy to sit down with you and help you try and overcome the roadblocks.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Garrison</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-14T14:18:30.811Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31296","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Drupal Resources for Campus","description":"<p class=\"p1\">For a while now, I've had some Drupal resources ready for campus, but did not publicize them while i was testing it with a few select people. But, enough of that secrecy\u2026.there's resources that might benefit some of you out there already.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">If you'd like to get your hands on some of the resources (modules, themes, features), visit\u00a0<a href=\"http://drupal.ncsu.edu/\"><span class=\"s1\">http://drupal.ncsu.edu</span></a>\u00a0and click on Downloads.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The more exciting news is that we're also working on an environment for folks to be able to quickly deploy a new Drupal site. That information is also on <a href=\"http://drupal.ncsu.edu/\"><span class=\"s1\">drupal.ncsu.edu</span></a>. While I can't take on too many requests at the moment, I know there are people out there who would benefit from this service. We have 4 or 5 sites deployed already, and i have room for a handful more (before i take a step back to monitor the load on the hosting server).\u00a0Some of the built-in highlights include: WRAP Auth, customizable theme, mobile-friendly (not responsive yet) &amp; accessible theme, featured content slider, photo gallery feature, contact forms, rss, google calendar integration and automated backups.\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">To borrow a phrase from Jen's Wordpress announcement: \"We're not exactly shouting this from the rooftops yet,\" but we're definitely ready to move this forward.\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">So if you, or someone you know, needs a website, have them check out <a href=\"http://drupal.ncsu.edu/\"><span class=\"s1\">http://drupal.ncsu.edu</span></a>, read the information there and see if it's the right fit. Combined with our efforts with WordPress, I think these two platforms will help to improve the standard of websites here at NC State in a pretty efficient way.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Please put your question/comments/concerns/excitement below\u2026or better yet, come to the <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events\"><span class=\"s1\">co-working days</span></a> to talk to me about this.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>","createdDate":"2012-06-07T20:09:08.025Z","updatedDate":"2012-06-07T20:09:08.180Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31291","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"WordPress resources","description":"<p>Posted about this earlier today but wanted to make sure the basic links were available to the WordPress group. Thanks!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>OIT Flexible WordPress theme:\u00a0<a href=\"https://github.com/ncsumarit/oitflex\">https://github.com/ncsumarit/oitflex</a></p>\n<p>WordPress generic sites deployment available via: <a href=\"http://wordpress.ncsu.edu\">http://wordpress.ncsu.edu</a> (currently in beta)</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-05T18:47:59.511Z","updatedDate":"2012-09-14T18:50:15.711Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31778","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Sorry I'm slow, Ellen! Yes, you can start using WordPress! I'd say don't send 'em my way. Instructions for requesting the blog (foo.wordpress.ncsu.edu) or hosted (your URL, pointed to our wordpress hosted solution) wordpress sites are available at wordpress.ncsu.edu. The hosted version has a 30-day free trial and sign-up for that is managed via Web Registry (webregistry.ncsu.edu).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The only thing I would mention is that people seem not to be reading the site (shocking, I know) - there are not unlimited themes and plugins available and people keep being surprised by that. :P We're trying to add more, so if someone has a request I will entertain those requests, but I make no promises to enable everything they request.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Hope this helps -- thanks for the interest!</p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-09-14T18:50:15.392Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:32166","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>So sorry, I am bad at responding, I just saw this-- :P</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So we didn't want to make a theme that matched the NCSU homepage: the redesign for our 125th year was upcoming and we weren't sure how much that was going to affect the design. In addition there are branding rules about who can use that look 'n feel so we needed a really generic theme.</p>\n<p>Due to the lack of time I decided to just build it off twentyeleven. This theme isn't rocket science, it's really basic tweaking to allow some layout options, color choices, campus images and a few other helpful things. I did have to make some pretty significant updates to the navigation to make that properly accessible but in general the design and function is basic, even a little uninspired. :-/</p>\n<p>I have high hopes for more elaborate and improved future themes but time is the issue, especially with the rollout of our WordPress services (wordpress.ncsu.edu).</p>\n<p>Thanks for the interest! Let me know if you have any other questions!</p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-09-14T18:46:36.154Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31861","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"<p>Hi Jen and others,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Is\u00a0<a href=\"http://wordpress.ncsu.edu/\">http://wordpress.ncsu.edu/</a>\u00a0ready to go? \u00a0I have had some inquiries for Wordpress installs, so can I sent them to you?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Ellen</p>","createdDate":"2012-08-28T17:27:52.601Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31488","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<p>Nice work! \u00a0I really like your theme. \u00a0Now that we've gone through a web redesign (<a href=\"http://www.ecu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ecu.edu</a>) we need a new theme choice for users of \u00a0<a href=\"http://blog.ecu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.ecu.edu</a> (see <a href=\"http://blog.ecu.edu/techtips\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.ecu.edu/techtips</a>\u00a0for example) that has all the current WordPress bells and whistles while keeping our branding. \u00a0What did you use as a starting point, Jen?</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-08T13:57:45.818Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31584","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"WordPress News for Campus","description":"<p>Hey folks!</p>\n<p>We've been using Wordpress a lot over here in OIT and have been working on a generic theme that, while not like the NC State homepage, would be an easy-to-use theme for NC State users. The theme offers an array of NC State branded color schemes and header graphics and has several layout options. It also\u00a0attempts to go above and beyond accessibility requirements.\u00a0A few notes about the theme...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It\u2019s a child theme of\u00a0<a title=\"WordPress.org\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/themes/twentyeleven\" target=\"_blank\">twentyeleven</a>\u00a0so you will need to make sure that theme is installed, available and un-modified in your WordPress environment.</li>\n<li>The theme is still under construction and will be updated from time to time as new features are available or corrections needed. When installed with<a title=\"WordPress.org\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/theme-updater/\" target=\"_blank\">\u00a0the \u201cTheme Updater\u201d plugin</a>\u00a0the theme will notify you when there\u2019s a new version released to Github, and will allow a one-click update to the new version.</li>\n<li>I encourage you to use this theme with the\u00a0<a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-BrandingBar\" target=\"_blank\">NC State Branding Bar plugin</a>, developed by Outreach Technologies. As a reminder, there is also a\u00a0<a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-WrapAuthentication\" target=\"_blank\">WRAP Authentication plugin</a>\u00a0available for NC State sites.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you'd like to use the theme it's available for download from <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsumarit/oitflex\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>. Please feel free to let me know if you have any problems or feature request - while I make no promises I'd like to make the theme as functional as possible. Hope you find it useful!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>In other news we're also working on an environment for folks to be able to quickly deploy a new generic WordPress site for a blog or project- whatever they need. That site is now up and running at <a href=\"http://wordpress.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://wordpress.ncsu.edu</a>.</p>\n<p>We're not exactly shouting this from the rooftops yet but we\u00a0definitely\u00a0want some guinea pigs to go in there and try things out. It uses our theme and authentication with WRAP; the brand bar is deployed to all sites by default. There's not too much choice on there with respect to plugins or widgets but it'll certainly get you a site quickly and is great for users who don't want put a lot of effort into their site, or support staff who don't want to spend a lot of time supporting the site. :)</p>\n<p>So if you, or someone you know, needs something to play around in we encourage you to go and check this out. It is a development space but we don't plan to take it down without letting everyone know and we can help migrate content out if it comes to that.</p>\n<p>Questions? Concerns?\u00a0Excitement? Let us know! Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-05T14:10:35.222Z","updatedDate":"2012-06-05T14:10:35.332Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31461","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"NC State Co-Working Day Review & Upcoming Schedule","description":"<p>Last Friday (June 1st) we had the first NC State Web Developer's Co-Working day, and I think it was a big success for everyone who attended.\u00a0If you attended, please respond with your thoughts on the day.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>We had people from different groups within OIT, Engineering, Education, CNR, DELTA (sorry if i left anyone out).\u00a0There were a lot of things going on in the room... drupal, wordpress, mobile development, push notification services... i think i remember django &amp; python mentioned .... and probably a lot more that i didn't overhear too.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I will be adding the co-working days to the <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events\" target=\"_self\">events section</a>\u00a0here on the Ning site, so please RSVP if you're planning on attending. It will help people see what others are working on, and which groups will be represented in the room. <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events\" target=\"_self\">Look for the events here</a>\u00a0in the next few days.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The motto of these co-working days is #collaborationNotConfrontation.... so please find time to attend.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Some of the tweets from the day, so you can see what we were all thinking:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>\"I'm completely convinced that we should have been doing this \u00a0coworking thing a long time ago\"</em></li>\n<li><em>\"Co-working day #1 was definitely a success\"</em></li>\n<li><em>\"So far I've learned all sorts of cool stuff that the ITECS folks are doing. Coworking Works. #collaborationNotConfrontation\"</em></li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2012-06-04T18:00:00.997Z","updatedDate":"2012-06-05T13:05:25.980Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31581","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Usually it takes all of us showing up at UNC Cause to figure out what we're all working on and where we're overlapping -- this is much easier! Seriously, it was a great idea (thanks, Nick!) and I'm already looking forward to the next one. Thanks to everyone who participated!</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-05T13:05:25.532Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31573","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Fantastic to meet some people for the first time and get some ideas about what people might be working on. It's quite likely that someone else has already dealt with a problem you are working on (as we saw on Friday). Especially useful that some who might not self identify as web developers/designers showed, as the range of expertise helped in a big way.</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-04T19:05:04.002Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31470","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>I learned a ton about what other folks were doing, and not just \"I'm working on x\" but \"let me show you how x works\". \u00a0Lots of good ideas thrown around. \u00a0I was also extremely productive. \u00a0I will definitely be coming back and would encourage others to do so as well.</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-04T18:44:55.773Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31652","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>FYI -- I've added the co-working days to the <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events\" target=\"_self\">events page</a>\u00a0here on Ning for June, July and August.</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-04T18:37:34.328Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31555","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"<p>I think it was a great success!</p>","createdDate":"2012-06-04T18:18:05.965Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31457","contributorName":"0ibhlpq3ag3an","title":"Web Designer Reaching Out","description":"<p>Hi everyone. I am moving back to the Raleigh area in a few days and am looking for a position in Web Design. If you guys hear of anything please give me a shout. Thanks. Please check out my portfolio at <a href=\"http://mikedemar.com\">http://mikedemar.com</a></p>","createdDate":"2012-05-30T01:07:41.268Z","updatedDate":"2012-05-30T13:23:42.920Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31644","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<p>Greetings, all. \u00a0I just wanted to post to those people I've met here on NCSU Web Developers that I personally know Mike and the work he has done for ECU. \u00a0He's a fantastic graphic designer, identity designer, and web designer. \u00a0He played an active role in our Web Working Group during the web site redesign process, he's done countless template designs for our huge Student Affairs section of the ECU web site, he's done template designs we're currently making available to the entire University CMS user base, and he's played an influential role in the management of Inner Pirate, ECU's social media outlet. \u00a0Mike works great within the confines of a CMS, or in the freedom of complete design control. \u00a0He <em>knows</em>\u00a0HTML, CSS, JavaScript, jQuery, and how those interact with server side back end systems.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>We're losing him because he's moving back to Raleigh with his wife, and we're very sorry to see him go. \u00a0If anyone knows of NCSU (or other) positions for a super sharp front end / identity / design person, Mike's your man.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Good luck with the search, Mike!</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-30T13:23:42.436Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31548","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"NC State Co-Working Day #1","description":"<p class=\"p1\">I am sending this out to the Ning group, (x-posted to the web developer listserv too), after some discussion/rsvp's from some developers on campus. We are starting up a\u00a0<span class=\"s1\">co</span>-<span class=\"s1\">working</span>\u00a0day, at least every month for NC State.\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">I know some on the list do more web development than others, so i'll let you all figure out if this is something that you'd benefit from attending (or could provide benefit to others by attending). See below for details:</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Friday June 1st, 2012</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Avent Ferry Technology Center</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>AFTC-106 Multi-Purpose Room</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>I have it reserved from 8:00am until 4:00pm.\u00a0</b></p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">There's no schedule, no set agenda, just bring yourself, your laptop.\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">About <span class=\"s1\">co</span>-<span class=\"s1\">working</span>...</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0-- Don't show up with nothing to work on.\u00a0 Have something in mind, whether\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 it is something from your current work or some project you would like to start.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0-- If you have some problem that you have been struggling with, bring it.\u00a0 The\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 point of these things is to take advantage of others expertise.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0-- Come prepared to help other people.\u00a0 This is not only about getting help for\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 yourself, but helping other folks on campus and improving your colleagues lives. \u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p4\">\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0-- Don't worry if you don't know something.\u00a0 Ask questions, answer questions,\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 participate.\u00a0 This will be a positive environment so nobody is going to make\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 fun of anyone for not knowing something. Everyone has expertise in their\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 own environments, so don't be scared to share it.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0-- That's about it.\u00a0 Remember, this is supposed to be fun, educational, and\u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p3\">\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0 productive. \u00a0</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Please RSVP here:</p>\n<p class=\"p5\"><span class=\"s2\"><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/a/ncsu.edu/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dG9sOTFHNVAtZUVtYUtBQURzMFE1MFE6MQ\">https://docs.google.com/a/ncsu.edu/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dG9sOTFHNVAtZUVtYUtBQURzMFE1MFE6MQ</a></span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">We have 13 confirmed already, and do not have unlimited space, so RSVP please, so we can avoid problems on the day.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\">--Nick</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-29T20:10:41.775Z","updatedDate":"2012-05-29T20:10:41.965Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31533","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"NC State Drupal Meetups","description":"<p>I just finished a great meet up with the Library folks (shout out to Charlie, Angie, Jason and Eric), and one of the things we discussed was getting together on a more regular basis to talk about Drupal.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I know we're not the only 2 groups on campus using Drupal, so we're interested in getting as many people in the same room as possible, so we can help each other and discuss what we're all working on. We threw ideas around like a regular meet up, and/or a co-working day where we can work on our own projects &amp; each others for portions of the day.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This is about things like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Who is using Drupal and what for? Websites? Web Applications?</li>\n<li>Drupal 6 or 7? Hopefully not Drupal 5...right?</li>\n<li>What modules are you using?\u00a0</li>\n<li>Did you know that there are NC State Drupal modules for WRAP, the Brand Bar, Roles and a few more things?</li>\n<li>How did you configure your Drupal site and why?</li>\n<li>How do you do XYZ in Drupal?</li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>See...totally informal...totally open. This will not be anything formal with presentations etc (although if requested im sure that can be accommodated).\u00a0</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Depending on the interest level, we might have the meet up soon, or if no one cares, then the library and I are planning on touching base every couple of months (with more frequent meetings as necessary).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So first things first.... reply to this thread if you're interested in meeting up, then we'll take it from there. I'll post this thread link to the mailing list as well of course.</p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-05-08T21:26:41.909Z","updatedDate":"2012-05-23T14:21:37.998Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31546","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Just sent this out to a few people, but all are welcome (if we have enough space, so RSVP early).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">I have scheduled the first co-working day and location.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Friday June 1st, 2012</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Avent Ferry Technology Center</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>AFTC-106 Multi-Purpose Room</b></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>I have it reserved from 8:00am until 4:00pm.\u00a0</b></p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">There's no schedule, no set agenda, just bring yourself, your laptop. This is the first time i'm doing this, let alone organizing one\u2026 so if anyone has any suggestions, recommendations before the day, let me know.</p>\n<p class=\"p2\"></p>\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s1\">Please RSVP here:\u00a0<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/a/ncsu.edu/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dG9sOTFHNVAtZUVtYUtBQURzMFE1MFE6MQ\"><span class=\"s2\">https://docs.google.com/a/ncsu.edu/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dG9sOTFHNVAtZUVtYUtBQURzMFE1MFE6MQ</span></a></span></p>","createdDate":"2012-05-23T14:21:37.624Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31450","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>I've included Bethany, Ted, Greg on a separate email about the co-working days. If anyone else comes late to this thread, contact me directly and i'll let you know about the co-working days.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I'll be posting something to the ning site soon.</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-15T18:14:42.156Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31631","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"<p>I'd love to meet with other Drupal folks!</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-14T14:22:09.246Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31445","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>As another related topic, we're talking about having some regularly scheduled co-working days for web developers on campus. So it's possible we might piggy back onto that process, and just have some drupal time during one of those.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>But it looks like there's at least a few different people involved already (Andrea Davis responded off list as well).... so i'll try and pull some kind of plan together once we get our heads around the co-working days and/or drupal meetups.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>There's nothing stopping us getting together just about drupal of course, i just don't want to saturate our schedules with multiple meetups when one might suffice.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I hope to have this all worked out in the next week or two at most.</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-11T19:35:19.157Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30925","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"<p>I'm in!</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-11T19:31:54.720Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30921","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Ted -- is university housing under Student Affairs (or the new DASA)? If so, you should speak to Leslie Dare who does a lot of work with us for Drupal sites... which means I could save you a whole lot of time.</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-11T14:26:34.656Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31442","contributorName":"ruy64xldrlf1","description":"<p>I'd be interested.</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-11T14:21:46.288Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30915","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>I recently went to a\u00a0<a href=\"http://groups.drupal.org/tridug\" target=\"_blank\">TriDUG</a> \"co-working day\" in Durham at <a href=\"http://www.bullcitycoworking.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Bull City Coworking</a>\u00a0and met a bunch of other Drupal people. \u00a0It's a pretty nice concept because you can sort of tune in on a conversation when you want or just work on your own stuff if you'd rather do that. \u00a0Little group or whole-group discussions just happened organically.</p>","createdDate":"2012-05-09T12:30:01.399Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31328","contributorName":"32bclt191nnvq","title":"giving file permissions in server","description":"<p>Hi all,</p>\n<p>My goal: to populate the recent news section of our website dynamically when a new page is added in the \"Recent\" folder of my directory.</p>\n<p>My approach: I have an xml file recent.xml and whenever a new page is created in \"Recent\" directory, I add a new child to my xml file.</p>\n<p>I display the recent news section from this xml file.</p>\n<p>This works perfectly on my localhost but it does not work on the server. I have given 777 permission on the entire folder but it does not work.</p>\n<p>Can someone help me in this regard. Thanks in advance</p>","createdDate":"2012-04-12T22:35:26.261Z","updatedDate":"2012-04-12T22:35:26.343Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31326","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Looking for NCSU Bronto user","description":"<p>Hi everyone,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Please let me know if you are successfully using Bronto for mass mailing.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thank you!</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-04-12T14:39:08.656Z","updatedDate":"2012-04-17T15:27:13.620Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30805","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"DrupalCamp Charlotte 2012","description":"<p></p>\n<p>Just wanted to let people know about: \u00a0<a href=\"http://drupalcampcharlotte.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupalcampcharlotte.com/</a>\u00a0---\u00a0June 10th, 2012</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I know a bunch of the guys who will be running this event, and am going to try and attend myself.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I can answer questions about it if necessary, but try to get in touch with them via the website.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I am going to try and pull a meet up together soon (or later) for people interested in Drupal here on campus. If you're using Drupal, or want to know more, post something here so i can gauge interest.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-27T17:27:31.235Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-29T13:27:35.540Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:30902","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"<p>I'm interested in a group on campus and going to Drupal Camp in Charlotte</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-29T13:27:35.134Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30810","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"<p>I'm interested, I don't currently use Drupal, but hear good things about it. I'd be interested in learning more about implimenting it.</p>\n<p>Christine</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-27T18:39:27.105Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30889","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"What has changed in Postini?","description":"<p>Our office has been using MailChimp for a weekly e-newsletter since November. Up until two weeks ago, we were successfully sending our newsletter out to over 500 subscribers. Something changed in Postini about two weeks ago so that our newsletter now goes to quarantine instead of readers' inboxes.<br/><br/>I contacted MailChimp, and they said the messages are being sent successfully on their end, and that they recommend us \"whitelisting\" their IP addresses.<br/><br/>I then contacted the Help Desk, but they said they are unable to do this.<br/><br/>We have an urgent need for our newsletter to be delivered. I have no way of contacting the entire subscriber list to advise them how to unquarantine our messages. Before this problem, we had about a 27% read rate. Today, we have a 2% read rate. If we are unable to communicate our news and events, our programs will be negatively impacted.<br/><br/>Can anyone help? Does Bronto work better? We really like MailChimp.<br/><br/>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T14:01:37.848Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-26T19:35:39.488Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31122","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Tim, thank you! I will contact you offline to meet ASAP.</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T19:35:39.138Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30896","contributorName":"2z4go72vu0j6m","description":"<p>Aye, that works. \u00a0We have people who do that on campus already. \u00a0Properly configured and monitored, Mj2 will take care of:</p>\n<p>\u00a0- sending messages at a constant rate</p>\n<p>\u00a0- unsubscribing bouncing/disabled addresses</p>\n<p>\u00a0- and the IP reputation</p>\n<p>One cons of course being that I monitor the service for abuse. \u00a0There's been more than one cautionary tale go out about tkl coming down on list spammers. \u00a0It's even in the SLA you agree to when you get a list:</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0<a href=\"http://lists.ncsu.edu/lists_services_intro/owner_resp.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://lists.ncsu.edu/lists_services_intro/owner_resp.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \" Lists which negatively impact the service or that do not hold up these responsibilities will be removed from lists.ncsu.edu. \"</p>\n<p>Another con is that you have to learn Mj2 and how it operates (which I've been told at times reads like stereo setup instructions (I must apologize on that one since most came from its predecessor which I wrote)). \u00a0However, the \"pro\" of this is that once you get your list setup correctly the first time, even large lists of upwards of 50k people work very well. \u00a0If you are going to do some sort of service like that, you might want to schedule some time with me and I can give you the \"tour\" (so to speak) of Mj2 and how it can help you. \u00a0</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I've been working with email for over 25 years now and so many things have changed. \u00a0With the introduction of hosted services for NCSU (Postini &amp; Google) things have radically changed from where a person could just run a unregulated mail merge on their machine and spam to their heart's content with nothing to stop them. \u00a0Regulation came as one of the costs when we turned to Google since many of their policies are not at our whim to change.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>-- tkl\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T19:29:53.956Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31158","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Thanks for taking the time to reply, Tim. I understand what is happening. Perhaps some of our readers got tired of receiving our messages and marked us as spam instead of just unsubscribing. Hopefully we can get around this using some of your suggestions.</p>\n<p>Regarding your earlier message about using Mj2 with any provider -- are you saying we could set up a listserv and use MailChimp to send the message to this single address, then Mj2 would send it out to all the subscribers, and thus we would avoid getting caught in quarantine? That might be the best of all worlds!</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T17:14:04.508Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31157","contributorName":"2z4go72vu0j6m","description":"<p>Mj2 uses email, so any email sender can be used to interface to it. \u00a0I know CES uses this to synchronize their subscribers.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T17:02:25.277Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31154","contributorName":"2z4go72vu0j6m","description":"<p>You are actually asking the wrong question. It's not what's happened to<br/>Postini, but usually it's \"What's happened to my direct mailings?!\".</p>\n<p>Postini operates by means to heuristics; an experience-based technique<br/> for solving problems that are not exhaustive searches but methods which<br/> try to speed up the process and hopefully find a satisfactory solution.<br/>What does that mean? Well, in layman's terms it means Postini guess.</p>\n<p>Now Postini makes guesses based off many factors:</p>\n<p>- the spamish-ness of the message (key words, content of the message,<br/>links within the message, etc)</p>\n<p>Always try the message to yourself first. See what the spam score is<br/>in the header by using the Postini header analyzer:</p>\n<p><a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://www.google.com/postini/headeranalyzer/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.google.com/postini/headeranalyzer/</a></p>\n<p>Make sure you aren't using words like \"password\" and \"userid\", those are in\u00a0</p>\n<p>most phishing email.\u00a0</p>\n<p>- but most people don't know that it also makes decisions based on</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0o the IP reputation of the sender<br/>\u00a0 \u00a0o how fast you are sending the messages<br/>\u00a0 \u00a0o how many bounces you have in your subscriber base<br/>\u00a0 \u00a0o the reputation of your sending address</p>\n<p>I'll go into each of these below:<br/> o IP Reputation<br/> ---------------<br/> Every time someone clicks the \"report this as spam\" button, entries go<br/> back to postmasters. These postmasters collect this data and submit<br/> IP addresses into lists such as SBL (Spamhaus block lists), ROXUS, njabl,<br/> blockade, etc. These are lists that NCSU doesn't control (though we do<br/> submit bad hosts that are complained about to them.) These lists are<br/> munged by Postini services in their proprietary way to produce changes to<br/>the heuristics for IP addresses.</p>\n<p>You can see your ip reputation on many online services:<br/><a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://www.commtouch.com/check-ip-reputation\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.commtouch.com/check-ip-reputation</a></p>\n<p>o How fast you send<br/> -------------------<br/> Postini looks closely for spammer activity. Spammers want to get in, push<br/> their load, and then leave. Does your activity look like a spammer?<br/> If you try to mass send as fast as you can messages, it could be the case<br/> that Postini sees the start of your message stream and thinks \"this is the<br/> same message going to a lot of people. I will up the spamishness score on<br/> these messages because it looks like a lot of similar messages going to a<br/>lot of different people.</p>\n<p>So while your message started out as a nice email to your subscribers,<br/> somewhere in the middle Postini started marking it as spam and putting it<br/>in your quarantine.</p>\n<p>o The # of bounces in your subscriber base<br/> ------------------------------------------<br/> Postini looks at bad addresses/bounces because again that's the same as a<br/> spammer's profile. They have a mass of addresses and they want to try<br/> each and every one because a spammer's goal is to send their message to as<br/> many people in as short a time as possible; so each address to them is<br/>a potential sale.</p>\n<p>When Postini sees the bounces, it believes you are a spammer since no one<br/> but a spammer would send to addresses that bounce or are inactive. This is<br/> the number one reason why messages get blocked. You have a subscriber<br/> list that has a lot of bad addresses on it and Postini will stop your<br/>message after as few as 10 bounces of addresses that it knows are bad.</p>\n<p>o Lastly, the reputation of your address<br/> ----------------------------------------<br/>\u00a0Is your address being reported as a spammer? That can happen as people report your message as spam.<br/>You can get around this by:</p>\n<p>\u00a0- Having people opt into your mailings<br/>\u00a0- Have people add your to their approve senders list.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T16:59:22.503Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30894","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>OK, do we have a Majordomo Web API?</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T14:31:40.978Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30892","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>I should add that my office is also currently looking for a solution to replace a number of existing listservs with an updated tool. We were on the verge of going with Google Groups when we learned that non-NCSU email addresses are not allowed in NCSU Google Groups. Our lists contain alumni and colleagues at other institutions.</p>\n<p>Either we are not aware of a better mailing tool available to NC State, or we have a need that isn't being met yet.</p>\n<p>We want a tool that offers easy HTML emails, statistics, won't get caught in NCSU quarantine, and one-click subscribe/unsubscribe.</p>\n<p>Do we have this?</p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-03-26T14:12:51.689Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30796","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"Dustin Wheeler joins ITECS web team","description":"<div style=\"color: #222222; font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.918);\">I am happy to announce that Dustin Wheeler will be joining ITECS April 2 as our new web programmer, replacing Damian Hall. He is coming to us from the Materials Science and Engineering department, where he has been the webmaster. \u00a0We're excited to have his experience and expertise in ITECS!</div>","createdDate":"2012-03-21T17:26:36.100Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-21T17:26:36.204Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30860","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Can we make WRAP mobile friendly?","description":"<div style=\"color: #000;\"><p>It looks as though a recent redesign of the WRAP page has made it ever more user friendly for those of use who rely on it to authenticate into University pages on the go. <strong>Thanks</strong> to whoever help make this happen.</p>\n<p>Here's just a brief brainstorm on maybe taking it a few steps further...</p>\n<div style=\"padding-left: 25px;\"><p>a) Can we use the autocomplete=off and autocapitalization=off attributes on the input tags so that I don't always fumble inputting my username as 'Mjvy...' instead of 'mjvy...'</p>\n<p>b) Is it possible to both <em>select your affiliation</em> AND <em>input your username and password</em> all on one screen? Using a majority default for the affiliation ('NC State University'). Though, I can understand for security reasons if that's not plausible.</p>\n<p>c) For those of us who have fingers the size of <a href=\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2012/02/02/sports/HANDSsilo/HANDSsilo-popup-v2.jpg\">Rob Gronkowki's hands</a>, can we increase the size of the input fields and login button for smaller resolution devices using a CSS media query?</p>\n<p>d) Can we hide the \"what is my userid\" text, and toggle it behind an 'FAQ' link? Granted we're probably not adding a ton of value by hiding it, doing so simply reduces noise in the interface.</p>\n<p>e) Can we load the branding bar asynchronously using javascript? iFrame's can slow the rendering process in some browsers.</p>\n<p>Any other ideas or suggestions?</p>\n</div>\n<p style=\"margin-top:20px;\"><strong>Try out both variations on your mobile device:</strong><br/> <br/>\nCurrent WRAP page:<br/>\n<a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/itecswrap\">http://go.ncsu.edu/itecswrap</a><br/>\n<br/>\nSlightly More Responsive Example:<br/>\n<a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/rewrap\">http://go.ncsu.edu/rewrap</a><br/>\n</p>\n</div>\n<h3 style=\"font: bold 25px Arial; color: #c00; margin-top:20px; background: #eee; padding: 5px;\">Desktop</h3>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-desktop.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-desktop.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 1</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-desktop.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-desktop.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 2</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-desktop.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-desktop.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">Responsive (single screen)</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"clear: both; height: 1px; margin-bottom: 20px;\"></div>\n<h3 style=\"font: bold 25px Arial; color: #c00; background: #eee; padding: 5px;\">iPad</h3>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-ipad.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-ipad.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 1</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-ipad.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-ipad.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 2</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-ipad.png\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-ipad.png?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">Responsive (single screen)</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"clear: both; height: 1px; margin-bottom: 20px;\"></div>\n<h3 style=\"font: bold 25px Arial; color: #c00; background: #eee; padding: 5px;\">My Droid A855 (\u2026 yeah it's old)</h3>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-droid-a855.jpg\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-1-droid-a855.jpg?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 1</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left; margin-right: 20px;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-droid-a855.jpg\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/wrap-screen-2-droid-a855.jpg?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">WRAP Screen 2</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"float: left;\"><br/> <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-droid-a855.jpg\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/rewrap/screenshots/rewrap-droid-a855.jpg?width=230\" style=\"border: 1px solid #666; margin-bottom: 0;\" width=\"230\"/><span style=\"display: block; margin-top: 0;\">Responsive (single screen)</span></a></div>\n<div style=\"clear: both; height: 1px;\"></div>","createdDate":"2012-02-15T21:20:10.246Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-20T19:53:33.704Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31115","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Jonathan,</p>\n<p>Whoops. Yes, we can work on those items but again, I can't get in there to make those changes myself so there's a bit of jumping through hoops for even the smallest changes. I'll work on those things and we'll probably make the changes later in the semester, again while students are away from campus.</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-20T19:53:33.756Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30790","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Awesome! Good job!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>It's me being picky, but can we make it validate? (The Quirks mode makes me twitch)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>HTML4 doesn't support self closing tags (consider HTML5's &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;)</li>\n<li>link tags always need to be in the head</li>\n<li>image borders go on the img tag instead of the a tag</li>\n<li>Accessibility: inputs need id=\"\" to match for=\"\" on labels; alt text is required for images</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2012-03-08T14:01:34.506Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31105","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Ok, we've done some work to address these problems in conjunction with updates for the 125th anniversary brand changes. To address the requests one-by-one...</p>\n<p><strong>a) Can we use the autocomplete=off and autocapitalization=off attributes?</strong>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We did set autocap to \"off\" but left autocompletion on as is was generally thought to be beneficial.</p>\n<p><strong>b) Is it possible to both\u00a0<em>select your affiliation</em>\u00a0AND\u00a0<em>input your username and password</em>\u00a0all on one screen?</strong></p>\n<p>We looked into this, and even looked into skipping the \"affiliation\" screen altogether but that's still being used surprisingly often. So they both need to stay.</p>\n<p><strong>c) For those of us who have fingers the size of\u00a0<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2012/02/02/sports/HANDSsilo/HANDSsilo-popup-v2.jpg\">Rob Gronkowki's hands</a>, can we increase the size of the input fields and login button for smaller resolution devices using a CSS media query?</strong></p>\n<p>Done. Enjoy!</p>\n<p><strong>d) Can we hide the \"what is my userid\" text, and toggle it behind an 'FAQ' link?</strong></p>\n<p>For accessibility and usability purposes we felt we needed to leave that there. It's informative and saves a click for those who are lost and, as you said, there's not a ton of value in hiding it.</p>\n<p><strong>e) Can we load the branding bar asynchronously using javascript?</strong>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The mobile version doesn't use the brand bar, simply a red bar with the logo (which has been switched to the new version).\u00a0</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>And follow-up re: Shib vs. WRAP is that there are efforts being made to consolidate these and make authentication to one valid to the other while campus continues to move toward a fully Shib solution. As I understand it this process is going well but the ultimate plans for switching things are not yet underway so there's no timeline for a change like this. Bottom line: it's definitely going to happen but no one can say for sure when.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Questions? Comments? Thanks for the feedback, Mike!</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-07T16:16:05.561Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31139","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>That's a question for Harry and Charles - above my pay-grade. I know that WRAP came first, and I believe that Shib is supposed to be \"the future\" of authentication on campus since it's the solution for the rest of the UNC System. As to when that shift will happen and why Shib and WRAP aren't more strongly tied together at this point, I'm unsure.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-21T18:57:19.662Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30871","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Mike covered the design concerns, so I'll ask a technical question:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Shouldn't WRAP auth be provided by Shibboleth so that all WRAP does is provide the WRAP cookie? At least for me, I still have to enter my credentials multiple times. It seems like this would allow visits to a WRAP site and a Shibboleth site (in either order) to require a single login. Sure, there's the \"duration\" question that hasn't been answered, but the smart defaults seem smart enough to me.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-20T19:29:32.870Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31093","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Thanks for the comments and great work Jen!</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-16T16:18:36.637Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30867","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>I did the rework of the site, built in part from the previously-completed Shib site updates so credit goes to those folks as well.</p>\n<p>Some of these things are beyond my control, like having to go through the affiliation page. Also, I believe Charles Brabec takes what I give him and tweaks some of the things such as the inclusion on the brand bar (to ensure a secure connection). Other items, however, are definitely doable (bigger text? Ok!).</p>\n<p>I'll touch base with Charles and Harry about these things and see what we can do. Chances are these things will not take place until the end of the semester but perhaps we could make some of the changes over Spring Break. I may also ping you, Mike, offline to ask for more details or suggestions. Thanks!</p>\n<p>Other WRAP feedback??</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-16T16:03:19.049Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30864","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>The affiliation thing has always be weird to me. \u00a0Sometimes I have to select it, sometimes I don't. \u00a0Never understood the reasoning or the situation which makes me have to choose it or not. \u00a0Seems like an\u00a0unnecessary\u00a0step to me, but I dunno. \u00a0All good suggestions, Mike.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-16T13:23:01.180Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30857","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Re-thinking the \"Org Chart\"","description":"<div style=\"font-family: Arial; color: #000;\"><p>Recently, we began re-thinking how org charts are created, maintained, and often later published (along with all of their shortcomings), and we wanted to know if we could do better than your typical InDesign File, PDF, or Word Doc which usually just contains names and position numbers or short generic working titles.</p>\n<p>Our discussions ultimately resulted in a rapidly prototyped, minimal viable product we called 'org chart' and today, I'm opening it up to the NCSU web community to tinker with (and hopefully provide some feedback).</p>\n<p><strong>Feel free to create your own chart at:</strong><br/> <a href=\"http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/orgchart/\">http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/orgchart/</a></p>\n<p>Here's what our <strong>ITECS Webteam</strong> looks like:<br/> <a href=\"http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/orgchart/itecs_webteam\">http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/orgchart/itecs_webteam</a></p>\n<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You can actually add an existing chart (say the 'ITECS Webteam') as a node to another chart (say for 'ITECS').</li>\n<li>If someone leaves the university, and their unity is no longer valid, their node becomes 'blank' or vacant automatically (until you go and update it)</li>\n<li>If someone moves offices, changes phone numbers, email addresses, gets married, etc. Their listing will automatically update (thanks LDAP!)</li>\n</ul>\n<br/> <br/>\n<p>A special thanks to Matt Fields, mafields@ncsu.edu, (ITECS Student Web Developer) for all of his hard work on this project<br/></p>\n<p><span class=\"font-size-3\"><em><strong>What are your thoughts? Could this be a valuable tool? Would you use it?</strong></em></span></p>\n</div>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T18:35:47.227Z","updatedDate":"2012-02-23T14:43:54.223Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31096","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Great suggestion Elizabeth! Thank you!</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-23T14:43:54.257Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30779","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Nice! I would also like a way to query because I currently have a sortable staff phone list in addition to an org chart. Right now they are two separately maintained pages -- would be great to have it come from the same place.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-23T14:29:19.929Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30772","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Thanks for all the great suggestions Jason!</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T20:13:07.352Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31134","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>One other usability thing. \u00a0It would be cool if I could zoom in and out. \u00a0With larger organizations like OIT, it would be kinda hard to manage with it being as large as it is. \u00a0Also, the nav bar with \"add a person\" etc scrolls left when my orgchart gets too bit. \u00a0It would be cool if that were sticky at the top left.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>One last thing. \u00a0I kinda had the feeling that it was saving automatically, so I almost screwed myself up and forgot to save. \u00a0An automagic saving thing could be cool.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Sorry for all the suggestions, but I really like where you guys are going!</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T19:38:55.127Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31084","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>That is awesome. \u00a0We made a rather crappy org chart thing in OIT People that I'd be more than happy to replace.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Ideas...API so I can query the thing. \u00a0OIT People is used to populate jabber groups and other things, which is done via the API. \u00a0It would be cool if I could query the orgchart and find out who exists in the chart.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I don't see a way to edit the visibility (listed or not) after I have initially set it. \u00a0That would be a good feature to have. \u00a0</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This thing is great. \u00a0Well done!</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T19:22:48.930Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30854","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","title":"The 125th Anniversary Branding Bar","description":"<p><b id=\"internal-source-marker_0.15327602834440768\" style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Times; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; font-size: medium; font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">North Carolina State University will begin a year-long celebration of its 125th Anniversary on March 7, 2012. Online, we\u2019ll kick off with a transformation of the university\u2019s website, followed by an updated version of the branding bar that incorporates part of the 125th Anniversary logo.</span> <br/><br/><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">If your site is currently using the centrally provided branding bar, the anniversary bar will automatically be updated on March 7, 2012. If your site is not currently using the approved strip, your Web administrator will need to visit</span> <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/brandingbar\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #0000ff; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">go.ncsu.edu/brandingbar</span></a> <span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">and generate the custom code to bring your site to compliance.</span><br/><br/><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The branding bar may not be required for certain entities operating under unique circumstances. Exceptions will be handled on a case-by-case basis. Web Communications will provide support for the branding bar but will rely on college-, unit- and entity-level internal Web or IT staffs to implement the strip. For implementation, exceptions, or other questions, email Web Communications at</span> <a><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #0000ff; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">web_ feedback@ncsu.edu</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Cambria; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">.</span></b></p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T22:00:27.214Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-27T03:19:57.470Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31123","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>we've posted the different color options per your suggestion:\u00a0<a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/brand/125/\" target=\"_blank\">ncsu.edu/brand/125/</a></p>","createdDate":"2012-03-27T03:19:57.182Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31112","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>Good idea, we'll post them on <a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/brand/125/\" target=\"_blank\">ncsu.edu/brand/125/</a></p>","createdDate":"2012-03-14T20:37:19.288Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31107","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>NC State red is #CC0000.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-08T20:57:28.965Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30792","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Luis,</p>\n<p>Is it possible to get the various 125 graphics like <a href=\"http://m.ncsu.edu/images/layout/125logo.png\">http://m.ncsu.edu/images/layout/125logo.png</a> posted for use to <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/downloads/web-downloads/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/downloads/web-downloads/</a> ?</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-08T20:51:29.574Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30877","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"<p>Is there no longer a consensus on what we use for \"red\" in the logo? I now see many different values:</p>\n<p>old bar logo = #cc0000, as we've been using</p>\n<p>125th brand guide uses #e31836, a lighter, slightly fuscia red</p>\n<p>new brick provided for WRAP uses #db0b01, also lighter, and just vaguely orange</p>\n<p>homepage is using at least two reds: #cc0000 and #ae0001</p>\n<p>I didn't see any text describing the prescribed red in the new brand book.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-07T16:03:59.577Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30788","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>I sent out a reminder that the brand bar is being updated tomorrow. Email us at\u00a0<a href=\"mailto:web_feedback@ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">web_feedback@ncsu.edu</a> if the brand bar isn't displaying properly.</p>","createdDate":"2012-03-07T00:33:25.701Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31140","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>At this moment, we don't have a mobile friendly version of the branding bar. For now, I suggest you place the brick on your home screen and have it link to m.ncsu.edu. The brick can be replaced by the new NC State logo that will be unveiled on March 7.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Take a look at this screen cap of our On Campus app: <a href=\"http://a5.mzstatic.com/us/r1000/089/Purple/c3/32/d5/mzl.cazdxnym.320x480-75.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">http://a5.mzstatic.com/us/r1000/089/Purple/c3/32/d5/mzl.cazdxnym.320x480-75.jpg</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>We've added NC State to our title/header area that traditionally works as a home button and have the brick on the home screen.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-21T19:03:33.174Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31088","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>We can't publicly display the logo before March 7th. We encourage you to work with your College/Division Communicators who have probably requested the 125 Brand Book that shows the new 125th Anniversary Branding Bar. Or contact us at ncsubrand@ncsu.edu for a private link.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T22:03:02.651Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30769","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","description":"<p>Is the new one mobile ready? I've got a few wordpress sites running WP Touch Pro and the current one doesn't fit the mobile theme</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T19:58:33.319Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31080","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>What does the new one look like?</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-14T15:31:01.899Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30945","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"NC State Academic Calendar (Google) Changing...","description":"<p>On Tuesday February 7, 2012....the NC State Academic Calendar that is hosted on Google will be changing locations.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If you are using this calendar in any way, you will need to replace the existing calendar address with the new one.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The new calendar information can be found here:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/academiccalendargoogle.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/academiccalendargoogle.html</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This is particularly important for those of you who may be using the existing calendar to feed into any web applications, or web sites.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-03T12:52:24.117Z","updatedDate":"2012-02-13T15:42:43.117Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:30853","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Yeah, just checked. She had the list of University Closings. It's good that R&amp;R is providing the R&amp;R calendar. Thanks again for the information.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:42:43.141Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30850","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>The real version is the one here:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/academiccalendargoogle.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/academiccalendargoogle.html</a></p>\n<p>The old one is the one with the calendar ID:</p>\n<p><span>\"ncsu.edu_37353035333737362d323337@resource.calendar.google.com\"</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The old one now has a recurring appointment, every day, that tells people to subscribe to the new calendar...as the old one is going away.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Margaret may have created one, but that was never an \"official\" one managed by OIT or the Google Apps @ NC State team. I would recommend you use the official one that is now managed by Reg &amp; Rec.\u00a0You can suggest including more information to them, as they are now managing the whole thing. That was part of the reason to hand over...so OIT was not responsible for copy/pasting, or fetching from things Reg &amp; Rec could more easily do.....after all...they are the source of the data.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:27:15.050Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31128","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Which calendar is the one that is going away? I think right now I'm using Margaret's version.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>With respect to the new calendar (not sure who should get these questions): Any chance we could get a little more information? \"Enrollment Begins\" on March 20th is a bit vague. I do like that the individual sessions (8W1 and 8W2) indicate as such for their specific days. However, it would be useful to do the same thing for the \"regular\" session (1).</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:11:44.434Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30754","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Choosing between mail/group/feed tools","description":"<p>Hi all,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>One of my user groups is transitioning away from their old majordomo listservs. There are tons of communication tools to choose from. They have a nice website in WordPress, so they could set up a feed for their posts. Or, they could get fancy with an HTML mailing tool. Or they could use Google Groups. Or...?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>They currently have a subscriber base of over 2000 students to whom they send out various types of communications such as advertising for events, job postings, reminders, etc.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Anyone have other options or preferences?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>","createdDate":"2012-02-02T15:47:06.968Z","updatedDate":"2012-02-29T18:54:40.475Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:30786","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>My apologies for not returning to update this thread. At the moment, we cannot allow non-ncsu.edu addresses as members of google groups. We are working on making that possible, but I don't have a timeline on that just yet.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>In simple terms, we're working on putting in to place the same checks and balances that MJ2 (lists.ncsu.edu) has to prevent spamming and phishing attacks that come from within one of our groups/lists. If we opened up Google Groups to external addresses without these checks and balances, it would put our system at risk of exploitation, as we have no proactive way of monitoring or preventing bad things from happening, should a spam/phisher become a member of a group (accidentally or on purpose).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So for now, people who need list services for non-ncsu people need to use MJ2 or a service other than Google Groups.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I can provide more information if needed.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-29T18:54:40.515Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30785","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Hi again,</p>\n<p>Agreeing with your advice, I was set to go with Google Groups along with a WordPress feed but found out from the Help Desk that non-NCSU addresses are actually not allowed on NCSU Google Groups.</p>\n<p>From what I know of Bronto and other similar external mailing tools such as MailChimp, Constant Contact, etc, they are not really community-based but more one-way messaging, unless I am missing a different aspect of what they do.</p>\n<p>Any other ideas? I checked into using non-NCSU Google Groups, and there is a University policy about mandatory availability of information in third party systems in case of legal requests, so that deters me from going that route.</p>\n<p>This user group already has a web interface built on top of majordomo listservs. I might actually have to go in and update that rather than move to something new. (Your colleague Jen R. knows all about this.)</p>\n<p>Thanks for any further help,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-29T16:54:05.751Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31076","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>I'm reasonably confident that WUPH will one day be realized, signaling the end of days. ;)</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:05:48.048Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30757","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>Good consideration. Picking something that lets them do one post and send it off different ways sounds good. Maybe it's all instead of just one. Reminds me of that episode of The Office... <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ytc9-wGCHW0\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ytc9-wGCHW0</a>.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-02T17:11:36.001Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31063","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>If you're communicating with only students (or users with @ncsu.edu addresses), then Google Groups would be a good match. There are daily sending limits imposed on non-ncsu.edu addresses in google groups...but if it's all students then that won't be an issue.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>It depends on what types of messages you're going to send out, and how important tracking/statistics are. If you're just wanting to send emails out and not care about readership, opened envelopes etc...then a Google Group would be fine i think. If you're wanting a little more management of the list and messages....then you might want to look into partnering with Bronto or someone like that.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>At the very least, I would \u00a0make sure that anything that's sent to the mailing list, is also posted on the website, and is available via RSS. If you use Wordpress, then publicize the RSS feed, as well as link back to the webpage that has all the information sent via email. That way you're allowing users to get the information in various ways.....making it more likely that your message will get out.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-02T16:44:08.219Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30744","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"Zend Framework online text","description":"<p>I found a\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.survivethedeepend.com/zendframeworkbook/en/1.0\" target=\"_blank\">website</a> with an online book for Zend. The book is titled Zend Framework: Surviving the Deep End. It looks good but I haven't read it yet.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-30T21:11:54.458Z","updatedDate":"2012-01-30T21:31:11.412Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31056","contributorName":"19vwhcbsj245a","description":"<p>Of any online ZF articles I've found, Surviving the Deep End has been the most\u00a0thorough\u00a0and helpful.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-30T21:31:11.492Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31043","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","title":"InControl Orlando Web Dev Conference. Worth the Money?","description":"<p>I'm looking into this conference in Orlando.\u00a0Looking at the schedule/sessions anybody think it's worth $900?<br/><br/><a href=\"http://2012.incontrolconference.com/schedule/\">http://2012.incontrolconference.com/schedule/</a></p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T20:11:02.202Z","updatedDate":"2012-01-26T22:04:32.151Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31049","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","description":"<p>Good points Nick. <br/><br/>I guess the most interesting sessions to me are the ones that would be more beneficial to learn from in a live session as opposed to a book/online training\u00a0<br/><br/>- Web Workflow</p>\n<p>- ROI Social Media</p>\n<p>- Content Strategy<br/><br/>DH Hill has a really nice set of up to date coding books but I'm not sure how up to date and effective the information would be for the ever changing social media/mobile web design landscape. And sometimes those coding sessions can demonstrate the most beneficial skills to focus on so I don't have to read the entire Javascript Bible to get things done. (not that here's anything wrong with that)<br/><br/>Then there's the invaluable networking aspect.\u00a0</p>\n<p><br/>The other thing is this conference is targeted toward graphic designers. I'm sure I'll learn a lot about the latest trends to holding visitors attention on pages (visually) and keeping them on a site. Not sure how in depth the coding will be.<br/><br/>Decisions...decisions....\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T22:04:32.199Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31046","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Whether it's worth the money fully depends on what you're wanting to get out of the conference.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I'm usually of the opinion that most conferences end up being more beneficial because of the people you meet, the conversations you have, and the things you pick up that you just HAVE to try when you get back to your office.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If you're looking for a hands-on training experience, where you actually get taught a particular set of skills for an application, a language or something like that....then i'd look carefully at the session descriptions, and then weigh the cost of travel + conference against a specific training course that may be online or closer to home.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T21:25:12.350Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30736","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","title":"Javascript to Fill Form for Credit Card Registration","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p>We at the African American Cultural Center are going to have a writer's conference in march.\u00a0I opted to use a Yahoo storefront from the options for accepting credit cards on the controller's office website. While waiting for this to be approved I was told we should have folks fill out the regular credit card form:<br/><br/><a href=\"https://quikpayasp.com/ncstate/commerce_manager/payer.do?orderType=NCSU%20Controllers%20Office\">https://quikpayasp.com/ncstate/commerce_manager/payer.do?orderType=NCSU%20Controllers%20Office</a><br/><br/>It's got a lot of fields and a lot of numbers to fill in so I'd like to have a javascript that fills out the administrative fields for them.\u00a0The scripts that I've tried haven't worked. I suspect it's because the form is hosted on quikpayasp.com not on ncsu.edu. Is there a way around that?<br/><br/>I'm also considering making a div and putting the instructions about what to enter in each field next to the frame with the form.<br/><br/>I'm also considering swtiching to EventBrite but I'd like to get this worked out first since we've done all the paperwork.<br/><br/>Here's my test code<br/><br/>&lt;html&gt;</p>\n<p>&lt;head&gt;<br/>&lt;title&gt;Test Form Filler&lt;/title&gt;<br/>&lt;/head&gt;<br/>&lt;body class=\"bodyclass\" id=\"bodyid\"&gt;</p>\n<p>&lt;form&gt;<br/> &lt;p&gt;Javascript Puts Joe in this field&lt;/p&gt;<br/> &lt;p&gt;&lt;input id=\"username\" name=\"username\" type=\"text\"/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;<br/><br/>&lt;iframe src=\"https://quikpayasp.com/ncstate/commerce_manager/payer.do?orderType=NCSU%20Controllers%20Office\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"900\" width=\"900\" id=\"targetFrame\"&gt;<br/><br/>&lt;p&gt;Your browser does not support iframes.&lt;/p&gt;<br/><br/>&lt;/iframe&gt;<br/> &lt;/form&gt;<br/>&lt;/div&gt;</p>\n<p>&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;</p>\n<p>document.getElementById('username').value=\"joe\";</p>\n<p>var o = document.getElementsByTagName('targetFrame')[1];<br/>o.contentWindow.getElementById('epay_AmountMethod_userChoice1').value=\"NC State\";</p>\n<p>&lt;/script&gt;</p>\n<p>&lt;/body&gt;<br/>&lt;/html&gt;</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T19:58:42.166Z","updatedDate":"2012-02-08T20:57:49.927Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31070","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","description":"<p>Thanks a lot Nancy. I got in touch with Mitchell and he was able to point me in the right direction.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-08T20:57:49.965Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31068","contributorName":"3herub2xatqwz","description":"<p>You might try Mitchell Nipper, Enterprise Applications Services.\u00a0 If he's not the appropriate person, he can probably tell you who is.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-07T13:21:40.268Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31061","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>I'm not sure, because our previous contact no longer works at the university.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-01T21:10:52.206Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30943","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","description":"<p>Thanks Mike.</p>\n<p>Who do I contact for that?</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-01T19:32:07.866Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30749","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>They're perfectly capable of pre-filling those administrative fields for you.</p>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/payecf\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu/payecf</a></p>","createdDate":"2012-02-01T18:17:48.898Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30839","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Garrison already covered the security same-domain issues, and even though it says getElementsByTagName('targetFrame') instead of getElementById('targetFrame'), it probably won't let you reach into the other frame.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>There are still 3 possibilities:</p>\n<p>\u00a0- quikpayasp might let you set default initial values on their management screens</p>\n<p>\u00a0- quikpayasp might let you set default initial values on the query string (worth investigating)</p>\n<p>\u00a0- quikpayasp might (somewhat unlikely) let you embed custom javascript</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-01T15:42:19.142Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30740","contributorName":"3e456sgrw2tp1","description":"<p>Thanks.<br/><br/>The first part about security is really the bigger issue. I think I'm going to drop the javascript idea and try my other options.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-27T18:04:12.249Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31052","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"<p>Hey Abbenyi,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You're actually going to run into several issues with your code as it stands now. \u00a0The primary issue is a security issue in that the origin of the iframe is different than the origin of the page, so you're not going to be able to access content in that iframe. \u00a0The browser just won't let you.</p>\n<p>Also, your Javascript that you've got there will be running whenever the page is loaded (not necessarily the iframe's page), so there's no guarantee that the iframe you're trying to access is loaded. \u00a0You'd need to check if the iframe has finished loading before accessing the content inside it.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Hope that helps!</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Garrison</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-27T14:13:09.370Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30827","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Making WolfAlert Better","description":"<div style=\"color: #000; font: 15px/1.5 Arial;\"><p>While I was sitting in my office this afternoon, meeting with some colleagues, someone in the room received a WolfAlert message. Immediately, the others in the room looked for verification on their mobile device, while I spun around to my computer to check GMail and <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">www.ncsu.edu</a> for more information. Surprisingly, nothing. Panicked? Confused? Maybe. Was it a real alert? Was it an errant test? Why hadn't anyone else received one? Finally, a few minutes later I had both a text message and an email, success!</p>\n<p><em>So then it occurred to me.</em></p>\n<p>If one of the perceived inadequacies (and I'm sure there are others) of the WolfAlert system is the time it takes for the actual 'alert' to reach you (despite most users having multiple arteries of communication), how do we make it better? How do we make it faster?</p>\n<p><b>Enter \"Maps\".</b></p>\n<p>What if a campus administrator could click on a campus building (where an alert has originated) and immediately get a list of all of the students who are scheduled to be in class in that building (+/- 30minutes), all of the faculty scheduled to teach, all of the staff listed with offices, and do the same for the 5 or 6 closest buildings nearby automatically,... with one-click.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Would this reduce the stress on the system?</li>\n<li>Would individuals closest to the WolfAlert be alerted sooner as a result?</li>\n<li>Would you reduce disruption and panic from spreading to otherwise unaffected areas? Granted, you could always send out a tier-2 alert to the remaining community members.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Other ideas for WolfAlert delivery...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Automatically expire all WRAP cookies upon receiving an alert, put an issue on the WRAP page</li>\n<li>Do the same for Nomad?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What are your thoughts?</p>\n<p><em>For the record. I received the WolfAlert at mail.google.com (in Firefox) at 12:51pm, the text message at 12:59 from Verizon Wireless.</em></p>\n</div>","createdDate":"2012-01-25T18:56:06.850Z","updatedDate":"2012-01-26T14:38:19.620Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:30733","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>It was slow. \u00a0I think I saw it on twitter first then got the text message a little bit later. \u00a0A few folks I was with never got the alert at all. \u00a0I did get the email before the text though, which in my opinion, seems counter intuitive.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T14:38:19.663Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30831","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Jonathan - we did think about those folks who may be in an affected building (maybe for an unscheduled advising session) that wouldn't appear in any of our data feeds, however ... looking at my own experience yesterday, we felt it was pretty likely that those individuals would receive the alert from the folks around them, or pick up on the fact that there was a lot of chatter/movement in the hallway outside their room without having to actually receive the alert themselves. Admittedly, this is a pretty bold assumption.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Glad to know you and others received the alert within a 10 minute window. Anyone else experience any unusual latency?</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-26T12:50:06.898Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31041","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Thoughts:</p>\n<p>\u00a0- Alerting people in descending risk order is an interesting idea, but is an attempt to optimize an inherently broken system. Also, alerting only \"affected\" individuals would mean that the people who are just there unscheduled would be left out in the cold.</p>\n<p>\u00a0- Why can't WolfAlert do a broadcast message rather than sending the messages in serial (which is what causes the large delays)? This is a more difficult problem to solve, but e-mails can do this already, so it's mostly a matter of having the appropriate kind of interface with the external systems.</p>\n<p>\u00a0- WRAP cookies can't auto expire unless the WRAP module on the servers do a check a WRAP command and control server (which I don't believe exists).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This is definitely an issue that would be good to speed up, but it looks like they were able to contact everyone I've spoken with within 10 minutes of the time in the e-mail (12:50 - 13:00), so they've improved quite a bit since the last time I timed it. My e-mail arrived at 12:57pm and my text message was at 12:56pm.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-25T20:51:40.298Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:30928","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Link checker that accepts .php files?","description":"<p>Anyone? Preferably one that checks an entire site? Unless I goofed, my old friend the W3C link checker does not accept them. Alas! Thanks.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-24T20:25:11.383Z","updatedDate":"2012-01-25T20:43:42.495Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31038","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"<p>OK, whew. I thought it had been working before. This site isn't WRAPped. Maybe something with my header tags...</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-25T20:43:42.531Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30931","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>I think the W3C one works, just ran one of my sites against it without problems. Perhaps the site is behind WRAP?</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-25T20:36:53.693Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:31026","contributorName":"32bclt191nnvq","title":"MySQL for wordpress","description":"<p>Hi</p>\n<p>Our department would like to have a blog set up with wordpress. However, we need a MySQL installation on the server. OIT is charging a 100$/yr charge for installing MySQL in our server's AFS space. I didnot understand why we are getting charged when MySQL is an open source database.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Thanks in advance,</p>\n<p>Ramana Malladi</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-24T17:05:15.383Z","updatedDate":"2012-01-24T18:23:15.867Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:31032","contributorName":"32bclt191nnvq","description":"<p>Thanks Nick</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-24T18:23:15.954Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31029","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>The reason you are charged, is because the database takes up space on the server, which needs to be backed up....all of which costs money to maintain (staffing, hardware etc).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You aren't really getting charged for \"mysql\" ... you're getting charged for OIT hosting the mysql database for you. This is the exact same model as consumer web hosting companies (bluehost, dreamhost, godaddy etc).... They all allow you to create and manage mysql databases...and you pay them for the hosting...not for the software itself.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Having said all that...I HIGHLY recommend you look at <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/whs\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu/whs</a>\u00a0(OIT's new Web Hosting Service) which, for $20/month...gives you unlimited databases and hosting space up to 10Gb (i think db's count against the quota...maybe). It's a cPanel environment...and it's a very attractive option. I host as much of my stuff as possible on there, as it's a much easier platform to use as opposed to paying per database, and using AFS.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Check it out...it might be the right solution for you.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-24T18:16:56.867Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:24427","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Using Hyphens in Domain Names","description":"<p>All -</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I need advice on the good/bad/ugly on using hyphens in a domain name. Sometimes a domain name is much more readable with the hyphen, but seems \"awkward\" (for lack of a better word) in print and when stating it verbally.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The domain in question (that I will be requesting <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/web-hosting-service/request-web-hosting-account\">per instructions</a> .... do don't any of you try to steal it first!) is:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>student-success.ncsu.edu</li>\n</ul>\n<p>versus</p>\n<ul>\n<li>studentsuccess.ncsu.edu</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Any thoughts on which way we should go? Any technical bug-a-boos I should be aware of if the hyphen is used?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I want to go without the hyphen but worry about read-ability.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>This is a strong candidate to be the new domain name for the new Division of Student Services &amp; Programs website (merger of DUAP and Student Affairs).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-09-22T17:26:27.222Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-26T14:11:06.716Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:24827","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Here are my thoughts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hyphens in human readable URL paths are SEO friendly (underscores should not be used to separate words), but I'm not sure if this translates the same way for the domain</li>\n<li>Explaining the URL to a user: \"student success 'all one word' dot NCSU dot E D U\" versus \"student (hyphen) success dot NCSU dot E D U\" both have a possible issue in spoken word, though I'm not sure people will really try to type a literal space...</li>\n<li>PHP 5.3.2 has a minor bug in its URL validation function filter_var() which considers all hyphens in domain names to be invalid, however, we've been able to work around it for our hyphenated domains (shouldn't be a barrier for the long term, just something to keep in mind when using the awesome filter_var() function in your applications)</li>\n<li>Side note: success isn't part of the division name's string literal, which may or may not be confusing; might want to make sure that you SEO well for \"student services\", \"dssp\", \"student affairs\" and \"duap\" and try to pick up useful 301 value from old DUAP and Student Affairs pages if possible (by sending them to an appropriately relevant page on the new site).</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2011-09-26T14:11:06.752Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:24326","contributorName":"ruy64xldrlf1","title":"Online Accessibility Summit - September 27","description":"OIT and the Library are co-sponsoring the Second Annual Online<br/> Accessibility Summit on September 27 from 10:00AM - 7:00PM. The online<br/> conference consists of a series of 1 hour presentations on<br/> <br/> 10:00 AM Color for the Colorblind<br/> 11:00 AM The Inexactness of Web Accessibility<br/> 12:00 PM Accessibility &amp; HTML5<br/> 1:00 PM Screenreaders, ARIA &amp; HTML5<br/> 3:00 PM Captioning Strategy<br/> 4:00 PM Integrating Accessibility Across Devices<br/> 5:00 PM Watch Your Language<br/> 6:00 PM Everything I Know about Accessibility I Learned from Star Wars<br/> <br/> The full conference details can be viewed at<br/> <a href=\"http://environmentsforhumans.com/2011/accessibility-summit/#.TmYnV4L-VBk\" target=\"_blank\">http://environmentsforhumans.com/2011/accessibility-summit/#.TmYnV4L-VBk</a>.<br/> <br/> The conference is free and open to everyone at NC State. You may<br/> attend any or all of the presentations, and no sign up is required. It<br/> will be held in D.H. Hill in the Multimedia Seminar Room, located on<br/> the second floor of the East Wing. It is located between the Assembly<br/> Room and the DLI/DELTA offices. If you are unable to attend the<br/> meeting, recordings will be made available.<br/> <br/> If you have any questions please contact Greg Kraus (<a href=\"mailto:greg_kraus@ncsu.edu\">greg_kraus@ncsu.edu</a>).<br/> <br/>","createdDate":"2011-09-22T15:55:57.569Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-22T15:55:57.615Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1102"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:23735","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"Google Public Calendars: Payroll Deadlines","description":"<p>Only loaded through current fiscal year.\u00a0 Hoping HR will maintain something like this in the future when Google Apps move is completed for faculty/staff.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Biweekly:</p>\n<p>--XML: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic\">https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic</a></p>\n<p>--iCal: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics\">https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics</a></p>\n<p>--HTML: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York\">https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=brqvhgile6oaoa3rll5akrie8o%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York</a><br/><br/></p>\n<p>Monthly:</p>\n<p>--XML: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic\">https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic</a></p>\n<p>--iCal: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics\">https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics</a></p>\n<p>--HTML: <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York\">https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=n9mu3ivhh4dercbahr3m2page0%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-09-20T18:24:27.008Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-20T18:24:27.110Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:17527"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:24129","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Where do we go from here?","description":"<p>As I started planning for the next web developers meetup (which should be on October 6), I did a little examination of the group and where we have gone over the last few years.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We have brought back monthly meetups and had a variety of topics.\u00a0 There are not as many different people presenting as I would hope, but we've had a few folks step up.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The Ning site had excellent momentum, but over the last few months has been deserted.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The leadership of the group has fallen completely on OIT's shoulders, which is fine, but it is not how a true community should function.\u00a0 There should be shared leadership, but we just haven't seen that.\u00a0 I enjoy organizing the group, but the interest level as a whole has decreased and I want to make sure that the hard work people put in to organize and present are worth while to people.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>So my questions to you, the community, are simple.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Where do we go from here?\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Do we continue the meetups?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Do we continue the social network style community, like Ning?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Is there anyone out there interested in becoming more involved with the organization and planning efforts of the group?</p>","createdDate":"2011-09-20T15:15:10.346Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-26T14:34:59.763Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:24927","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>This group is an extremely useful resource. I'm not sure where it should go, but I feel it should always exist to encourage information sharing and improve the quality of web development (along with the supporting infrastructure) here at NC State.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I enjoy the meetups, but I think there might be room for something a little different. Perhaps once or twice a year some kind of \"here's what we have planned for the next 6 months to a year\". I know I'd be interested in a Shibboleth status and deployment plan/user implementation guidelines presentation (because we're transitioning away from WRAP, right?).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I think a social network aspect (Ning or otherwise) is really useful for people with questions (especially because it doesn't flood a mailing list) or who want to share some code for review or testing.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Sorry, no.</p>","createdDate":"2011-09-26T14:34:59.792Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:24028","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Help importing an iCal file into Google Calendar by URL","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Anyone have experience with this? I am generating an .ics file from a MySQL database using PHP. Everything seems in order. It's a very basic file that validates using an iCal validator:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<pre><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">BEGIN:VCALENDAR </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">VERSION:2.0 <br/>PRODID:-//NC State OIED//NONSGML v1.0//EN </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">BEGIN:VEVENT </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">UID:46820d23041d10c2da73c36870ae7dd3@oied.calendar@gmail.com </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">DTSTAMP:20110915T153340Z <br/>DTSTART:20111013T110000Z </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">DTEND:20111013T150000Z </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">SUMMARY:OIED Staff Meeting (Location TBA) </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">END:VEVENT<br/></span><span class=\"font-size-1\" style=\"font-family: courier new,courier;\">END:VCALENDAR</span><br/><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">I went in to Google Calendar's settings, selected \"Import by URL\" and specified the URL where the </span><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">file is output. Google Calendar accepted the link and it is displayed in the list of calendars. Yet, the</span><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">event is not showing, even after waiting and refreshing. I guess I will need to play around with this</span><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">some more, but if anyone sees an obvious problem, please let me know.</span><br/><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">Thanks,</span><br/><span class=\"font-size-2\" style=\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">Elizabeth</span></pre>","createdDate":"2011-09-15T15:45:46.173Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-15T22:05:21.424Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:24035","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks, that might work but I just stumbled on the Google Calendar API. It has a Zend-PHP library that is way better than coding these files manually. I was trying to take a shortcut but it turned out to be a longcut.","createdDate":"2011-09-15T22:05:21.454Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:24032","contributorName":"18kjomwgbimzh","description":"Remove the spaces after VCALENDAR and VEVENT. <br/>","createdDate":"2011-09-15T19:02:33.393Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:23727","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"Intel to Universities: No Patents, Please, Just Open Source","description":"<p><em>...many universities have campus IP policies that, at least in writing (typically not in practice), require researchers to get the permission of a central technology transfer office before they open source a technology...</em></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.innovationexcellence.com/blog/2011/09/12/intel-to-universities-no-patents-please-just-open-source/\">http://www.innovationexcellence.com/blog/2011/09/12/intel-to-universities-no-patents-please-just-open-source/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-09-14T12:59:05.446Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-14T12:59:05.580Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:22150","contributorName":"3jgdccfjvfpif","title":"WordPress TimThumb.php exploit","description":"<p>Hi everyone,</p>\n<p>This is just a friendly heads up to let you know that a pretty ugly exploit is going around right now related to a PHP script that several WordPress themes and plugins have included in their codebase.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>This security web site's last three blog posts (as of 8/18/2011) are all focused on the exploit. One of the posts is a list of themes / plugins that include the script. It's worth checking out if you use WordPress.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.sucuri.net/\">http://blog.sucuri.net/</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-08-18T13:30:12.796Z","updatedDate":"2011-08-18T13:30:12.873Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:21726","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Adobe Tools with Apple OSX Lion","description":"<p>Hey folks.</p>\n<p>Some of you may have heard rumors about problems with Adobe products running on the newest version of Apple's OS, Lion. Apparently there are \"unusual user experiences\" with Flash Catalyst and Flash Builder and with Adobe Acrobat on the latest version of Safari. Additional details are below but if you are heavy users of these products Adobe advises users not to upgrade to Lion.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I don't think there are many folks on campus using the Flash tools and I know there are work-arounds for the Acrobat issues but if you have questions let me know and I'll pass them along to our Adobe rep.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n\n<p><span>Here is an summary of the known issues</span></p>\n<p><b><span>Is Adobe aware of any major issues, bugs, or unexpected user experiences when using CS5, CS5.5, or Adobe Acrobat\u00ae products with Mac OS X Lion?\u00a0</span></b><span>We have thoroughly tested our CS5, CS5.5, and Adobe Acrobat solutions in conjunction with Apple to confirm they perform to the high standards and level of performance, quality, and user experience our customers expect. In our testing, we did discover a few functional areas that display unusual user experiences. The most notable issues are:</span></p>\n<p><span>\u2022 Adobe Flash\u00ae Catalyst\u00ae CS5.5 and Adobe Flash Builder\u2122 4.5 software are generally compatible with Mac OS X Lion; however, we have discovered issues that may degrade the user experience or affect use of the products. We do not recommend that these customers upgrade to Mac OS X v10.7.</span></p>\n<p><span>\u2022 Flash Catalyst CS5 and Flash Builder 4 will not work on Mac OS X v10.7. Adobe does not intend to update either of these products for use on Mac OS X v10.7. It is recommended that customers using these versions not upgrade to Mac OS X v10.7.</span></p>\n<p><span>\u2022 Adobe Acrobat and Adobe Reader\u00ae currently support viewing PDF documents both inside and outside the Apple Safari browser on Mac OS X. Adobe Reader plug-in and Acrobat plug-in are not compatible with the Safari 5.1 browser, which will ship with Mac OS X 10.7 and for 10.6 in July 2011. Adobe Reader and Acrobat will continue to work as standalone applications on Mac OS X 10.7 and 10.6, and will render PDF documents outside of the browser. In addition, Safari 5.1 renders PDF documents natively</span><span>.</span></p>\n<div><p><span>Adobe and Apple have worked closely together to test that Adobe\u00ae Creative Suite\u00ae 5 and CS 5.5 suite editions and individual products run reliably on Intel\u00ae based systems running Mac OS X Lion (v10.7) with optimal performance and user experience. Earlier versions of Adobe Photoshop\u00ae (CS3 and CS4) software were also tested with Lion, and issues that were discovered are being documented and addressed by working closely with Apple.</span></p>\n<p><span>\u00a0</span></p>\n<p><span>We have posted an article on our support site with specific information about individual products.\u00a0<a href=\"http://kb2.adobe.com/cps/905/cpsid_90508.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://kb2.adobe.com/cps/905/cpsid_90508.html</a></span></p>\n<br/></div>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-21T15:17:01.292Z","updatedDate":"2011-07-21T15:17:01.381Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:21428","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Texting Services/App","description":"<p>Our recruitment and retention coordinator here at CNR is interested in exploring options for sending text messages to students on an opt-in/opt-out basis.\u00a0 I was wondering if anyone else on campus is doing anything like this.\u00a0 If so, can you tell me a little bit about what you are doing?\u00a0 Especially what service you are using.</p>\n<p>Anyone else have knowledge of applications or services for this kind of function?\u00a0 I think ideally someone could opt-in via texting a code to a number (like \"JOIN\" to 123456 or \"LEAVE\" 123456), but the primary feature desired is being able to text a large group of contacts all at once.</p>\n<p>We are looking at the services listed that <a href=\"http://mashable.com/2008/04/19/send-text-messages/\" target=\"_blank\">Mashable recommends</a> as well as a <a href=\"http://bronto.com/products/mobile-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">new service being introduced by Bronto</a>.\u00a0 Google Voice only lets you do 5 at-a-time, which isn't nearly enough.</p>\n<p>Any recommendations or thoughts would be appreciated.\u00a0 Thanks.</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T19:14:14.534Z","updatedDate":"2011-07-12T13:03:23.589Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:21329","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"cool -- lemme know if you need help getting something working. I am by no means an expert, but I've messed in it enough to make simple things happen. I had the easiest time just making my code and uploading it to them (instead of hosting it myself), but as you get more complex, you may end up hosting the files here on campus.","createdDate":"2011-07-12T13:03:23.616Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21628","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Awesome Nick, this looks perfect.\u00a0 Thanks!\u00a0 I'll play around with a dev account and when/if we decide to go production with it we will definitely see if a non-profit discount is available.. though 1\u00a2/text is cheapity cheap.<br/>","createdDate":"2011-07-12T12:57:32.079Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21438","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Inbound/Outbound SMS: 1\u00a2 per message (US), 2\u00a2 per message (International)</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>That's pretty good. If you wanted, you could always let them know you're from a non-profit state agency so they might be able to get you a reduced bulk rate or allow you to prepay so that you don't have to deal with a monthly bill (which can be a problem when spending is frozen).</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-12T12:30:02.447Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21435","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>That's easy.....check out Tropo --- <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://tropo.com\">http://tropo.com</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>They sent a guy to do a talk with us at the Triangle PHP User's Group a few weeks ago, and within about 30 minutes (still during the meeting) I had a simple little text-to-response app set up (App is a strong word...it was a script).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\nIf you send a text message to\u00a0\u00a0(919) 500-7845, you'll see the thing I set up. If you text it a valid ncsu username (like njyoung) it will respond with their ncsu directory information.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>So...you could do the same type of thing, except on the other end is a piece of logic that takes the caller id, saves it in a database (if the text sent in is JOIN), or removes the caller id if the text sent in is LEAVE. Given a couple of hours, you could easily have that set up using a test account (free) on tropo. Then all you'd have to do is set up another app to send to everyone who's stored in your database (which you'd use Tropo to do as well).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n\n<p>The issue you're going to deal with, with any provider is the cost of texting the large group. If you can find somewhere that has a good cost-per-text-message price structure, then jump on it. I am pretty sure Tropo has competitive pricing.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Let me know if you need more information mate.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T23:13:56.677Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:20932","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Feedback? New Civil Engineering Dept Website Launched","description":"<p><a href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">ITECS</a> is pleased to announce the launch of a brand new website for the Department of Civil, Construction, and Environmental Engineering. Our webteam has been working closely with their faculty/staff over the past several months to re-think their content, design, and delivery. We hope you like it!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>If you're willing and able, please leave us your thoughts, feelings, comments AND criticisms regarding the new site here (please don't be shy, we can take it!).</strong></span></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Some of the new features include:</em></p>\n<p>a) a pretty-url for faculty/staff bios: <a href=\"http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/faculty/kumar-mahinthakumar\">http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/faculty/kumar-mahinthakumar</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>b) automatically generated list of active research grants for each faculty member. Thanks WolfTech! <a href=\"http://www.wolftech.ncsu.edu/grants/\">http://www.wolftech.ncsu.edu/grants/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>c) Automatically generated list of courses taught. Thanks SIS! Along with an ajax powered tooltip for automatically pulling in course descriptions for any course mentioned in text (ex: CE XXX).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>d) Better directions to visit the dept/campus! Thanks Google.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>e) A list of dept affiliated publications. Thanks to the SPR folks at the Library! <a href=\"http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/repository/scholpubs/ws/wsinfo.php\">http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/repository/scholpubs/ws/wsinfo.php</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>f) [Hopefully] We made the academics information more clear: <a href=\"http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/academics/\">http://www.ce.ncsu.edu/academics/</a> * we stayed away form audience based nav and went straight to the topics!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Here's a screen grab of the old site, in case we need to jog your memory:</p>\n<p><a target=\"_self\" href=\"discussions/7-oldwebsitedeprecatedjune2011.jpg\"><img class=\"align-left\" src=\"discussions/8-oldwebsitedeprecatedjune2011.jpg?width=750\" width=\"750\"/></a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-07T17:13:04.283Z","updatedDate":"2011-07-15T12:52:44.731Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:21330","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Even Microsoft wants you to \"Join the Cause\": <a href=\"http://www.ie6countdown.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ie6countdown.com/</a>","createdDate":"2011-07-15T12:52:44.756Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21443","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"The more you make IE6 crash, the better.\u00a0 That should be a guiding rule for web design.","createdDate":"2011-07-13T18:07:05.467Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21441","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<p>IE6 (no, I'm not running it, I use Windows XP mode in Windows 7 for my own web testing) aborts completely on the site and won't render anything. \u00a0IE8 shows the site nicely, and as others have mentioned don't have CSS rounded corners (the academics page, in particular). \u00a0I'm running IE9 release (not beta), and you <strong><i>DO</i></strong>\u00a0get rounded corners (again, on the academics page).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>One of the tools I've used to help with the browser version/OS combination explosion is Adobe's Browser Labs:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://browserlab.adobe.com/en-us/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://browserlab.adobe.com/en-us/index.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Am I giving you grief for making IE6 crash? \u00a0No, just wanted you to have the data point to do as you see fit.</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-13T13:39:07.352Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21630","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"For shame... I know!\u00a0 :)","createdDate":"2011-07-12T13:00:26.799Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21626","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"By the way, I know that the Spring 2012 data showed up, but that's just a copy of Spring 2011, so it's not reliable data yet. It'll probably be mostly accurate sometime in September.","createdDate":"2011-07-12T12:46:32.057Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21328","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"IE9 Beta? ;) On that note, IE10 Platform Preview 2 is available, so it sounds like they're on a somewhat faster development cycle now.","createdDate":"2011-07-12T12:43:11.619Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21235","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>Yup, very simple to use.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>So, I opened up IE (not something I do often), and lo and behold I see all the rounded corners are gone.\u00a0 Graceful degradation or progressive enhancement at work.\u00a0 But, I noticed that the Univers font stuff is showing up as glyphs.\u00a0 I think this is because I still have IE9 Beta installed, but I think you might want to add a backup font stack for the spots where you point to UniversBold.</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T21:05:38.914Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21433","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Charlie, thanks for the compliments on the UI / IA. We were definitely striving for simplicity (and with that, less maintenance) in this redesign. We tried to eliminate / consolidate as much content as we could, or offload it to authoritative sources at the university level (admission info, degree audits, etc).</p>\n<p>You're also correct about the CMS, <em>there isn't one</em>. We've had pretty good success building out sites using simple static content, dressed up with some dynamically generated content (from various university feeds) and then handing off the site to it's owner (who will typically make updates with Adobe Contribute).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Re: How do you measure up? &lt;- Admittedly, it's been a while since I test drove the site with FF5, I'll give it another run. Thanks.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>As for the rounded corners and boxes... if you load the website in IE, you'll get consistency. ;-)</p>\n<p>Seriously, good suggestion though, we're going to give that some thought. I think the boxes will be a better default.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T20:17:17.779Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21431","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>I think this is an interesting site.\u00a0 Overall it's really simple, yet information-dense.\u00a0 It's a good example of how you can use Javascript (jQuery) and advanced CSS to more of it's UX-improving potential.\u00a0 For example, no sub-menus, but you can toggle different buttons on pages to reveal more information.\u00a0 The content on the site is pretty concise and effective too.\u00a0 Great job!</p>\n<p>Oh this is bugging me:</p>\n<p>The \"How do you measure up?\" section on the home page doesn't line up quite right when I look at it (FF5).\u00a0 Adding a few pixels to the width and adding a few pixels to a margin-top to #measureUpMetricsUl .metricLabel made it look lined up.</p>\n<p>Couple of questions:</p>\n<p>I noticed that much of the site uses rounded corners on boxes, but some boxes don't.\u00a0 Would it be better if everything or nothing had rounded-corners?\u00a0 This is a real question.</p>\n<p>And, are you using a CMS?\u00a0 Just curious, because I can't imagine that being possible...</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T20:00:38.008Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21233","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Jonathan - <strong>Thanks for the great feedback</strong> (and also your solutions), we've already started making some of those adjustments.","createdDate":"2011-07-11T14:34:49.080Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21228","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<div class=\"cssRule cssEditableRule insertInto editGroup\"><div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">First: Very nice improvement! I really like the color coded program sections.</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">Now the comments:</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">The \"Faculty and Staff\" part of #nav is wrapping for me, which feels awkward; width: 590px solves it on my screen.</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">There's a lot of vertical whitespace. Personally, switching from 40px to 20px helped a lot on my screen (#header, #contentShell, etc). Have never been a fan of more than 20px at the bottom of the page, so #body's 100px isn't really my thing, but I'm not an artist just a user.</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">It might be nice if the biographical section dropped out based on whether there is content to show (unless your goal is to use the large space to *convince* faculty and staff to fill in the blank).</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\">Automatically generated list of courses is very nice. To take it to the next level, you may want to consider allowing for the course information to account for the class information. Specifically: Special Topics courses are now showing as \"<span>Special Topics in Transportation Engineering\", when the Topic Description \"</span>Unconventional Intersection Design\" <span>would be a nice bonus.</span></div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">On academics, this helps me with the \"Going beyond degree\" section not floating cleanly:</span></div>\n<div class=\"cssHead focusRow\"><span class=\"cssSelector editable\">.noMr + .section</span> {</div>\n<div><div class=\"cssPropertyListBox\"><div class=\"cssProp focusRow editGroup\"><span>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0</span><span class=\"cssPropName editable\">clear</span><span class=\"cssColon\">:\u00a0</span><span class=\"cssPropValue editable\">left</span><span class=\"cssSemi\">;</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\" editable insertBefore\">}</div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\" editable insertBefore\">The validator only had a few complaints:</div>\n<ul>\n<li>div.clearfix cannot be inside p#about</li>\n<li>#bachelorOfScience has an obsolete summary attribute</li>\n<li>a few ampersands on the bio pages need escaping</li>\n</ul>\n<br/>\n<div class=\" editable insertBefore\">Last, for how long are you going to have the canary yellow ITECS link at the bottom of the page? It's quite bold, so for a long term link, I would hope you could soften it a bit to black or gray.</div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2011-07-11T13:57:22.723Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:20327","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"HTML Email Boilerplate","description":"<p>Ran across this and thought it looked very cool.\u00a0 An essential tool for any of you that are automating the sending of HTML emails.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://htmlemailboilerplate.com/\">http://htmlemailboilerplate.com/</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-06-07T16:05:53.805Z","updatedDate":"2011-06-07T16:05:53.933Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:19935","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Looking for Wiki Recommendations","description":"<p>I'm currently using MediaWiki to run two different documentation sites:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://studentaffairs.ncsu.edu/sats/wiki/index.php?title=SATS_Documentation_Home\">Wiki for Division Techies</a></p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://studentaffairs.ncsu.edu/sats/wikis/help/index.php?title=Main_Page\">Wiki for Division Employees</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>However, our content has bloated on the Techies site and it's time to re-organize a bit (which is a pain). So we are taking this opportunity to consider which wiki software might be best.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Any advice, specific to this type of content? Anyone used dokuwiki, or tikiwiki, or others? <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.wikimatrix.org/wizard.php\">This site lets you compare</a>, but I'm very unfamiliar with most of them. I guess navigation is one of the things I miss from a more standard website, but we love the instantaneous nature of publishing in a wiki.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We're even thinking about a WordPress site (not a wiki, I know) as a possible alternative, thinking that between static pages and posts, and categories and tags, it might work.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>All advice appreciated.</p>","createdDate":"2011-06-01T21:06:01.952Z","updatedDate":"2011-06-15T11:07:43.279Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:20532","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Tony, thanks for the insights. I'll give it a try as you suggest. Hope you are having a great summer.","createdDate":"2011-06-15T11:07:43.369Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:20827","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"When we were looking at the possibility of rolling out a campus-wide available-to-all wiki, we did examinations and prototype installations of <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.mediawiki.org/\">MediaWiki</a> and <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.dokuwiki.org/dokuwiki\">Dokuwiki</a>. \u00a0MediaWiki, by virtue of the success of Wikipedia, is the 800 lb gorilla in this space. \u00a0That being said, the permissions features of Dokuwiki are far superior. \u00a0MediaWiki essentially operates on the Wikipedia model of \"anyone can make edits to anything\", which is fine, but often the folks in EDUland want more lockdown ability. \u00a0<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.ecu.edu\">Our campus</a>\u00a0uses Microsoft Active Directory for directory services, which can be used as the authentication and authoization mechanism with a Dokuwiki plugin. \u00a0It's a nice system that lets you create pages, collections of pages, and apply user, group, or \"anyone\" ability to have multiple privileges from nothing, to read, to edit, to create, to add multimedia. \u00a0Give it a try.","createdDate":"2011-06-14T14:50:57.449Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:20228","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I've seen other wikis used in the past, but I've only had a positive experience with MediaWiki. Sorry, I'm not much help.","createdDate":"2011-06-03T12:29:12.346Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:19933","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Invitation to Participate in Survey on Web Content Management","description":"<p>I am looking for web communication\u00a0professionals at NC State University to help me with some research I am conducting as part of my Master\u2019s degree program by participating in an online survey.\u00a0 If you play a role in the publishing and maintaining of content on the web at NCSU than your participation would be greatly appreciated.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The purpose of this research is to better understand the nature in which web publishing is handled within organizations at a large public university.\u00a0 The research will attempt to understand how organizations manage web content, as well as the results of that management.\u00a0 The goal of this research is to present some recommendations for organizations on managing web publishing.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Your participation would be completely voluntary and very much appreciated.\u00a0 All data collected in the survey will be made anonymous and held confidentially.\u00a0 The survey shouldn\u2019t take more than 15 minutes to complete.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>To participate in this survey please follow the link below:<a href=\"https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/2MSYDXM\" target=\"_blank\"><br/>https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/2MSYDXM</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks in advance for your time,\u2028<br/>Charlie Morris</p>\n<p>---------------------------------</p>\n<p>M.S. Information Science Candidate, 2011<br/>UNC Chapel Hill<br/><a href=\"mailto:cdmorris@email.unc.edu\">cdmorris@email.unc.edu</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Distance Education and Web Coordinator<br/>College of Natural Resources<br/>North Carolina State University<br/><a href=\"mailto:charlie_morris@ncsu.edu\">charlie_morris@ncsu.edu</a><br/>Office: 919.515.0307<br/>Fax: 919.515.7231</p>","createdDate":"2011-06-01T13:05:01.365Z","updatedDate":"2011-06-01T13:05:01.488Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:19634","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Adobe Accessibility Resources","description":"<p>In response to questions about accessibility for Adobe Creative Suite 5.5 Adobe\u00a0representative\u00a0Patrick Koster has sent the following\u00a0resources. I sent these to the webdev list but thought it might be a good idea to make them available for the long-term so here they are...</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Adobe is committed to enabling all people to use Adobe software and formats. Accessibility is important to users with various disabilities who want to engage in digital workflows as well as to publishers, authors, and developers who need to comply with global accessibility standards.</p>\n<p>Adobe is committed to accessibility and strives to address accessibility in its products and services. Adobe's strategy includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Providing product accessibility support and reporting on compliance with standards</li>\n<li>Maintaining relationships with assistive technology vendors to ensure that Adobe software works well with end user tools</li>\n<li>Supporting developers and authors who need to meet accessibility standards</li>\n<li>Providing information and resources for end users with disabilities</li>\n<li>Providing leadership in accessibility through participation in accessibility standards and collaboration with organizations interested in accessibility</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Adobe has a team solely dedicated to accessibility who has developed the following resources:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adobe landing page with links to accessibility information<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ongoing series of Adobe TV accessibility tutorials<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://tv.adobe.com/show/accessibility-adobe/\">http://tv.adobe.com/show/accessibility-adobe/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adobe accessibility blog<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.adobe.com/accessibility/\">http://blogs.adobe.com/accessibility/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adobe accessibility feedback form\u00a0<br/><i>(share your comments, questions, and suggestions for improvement here)</i><br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/feedback.html\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/feedback.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adobe product-specific accessibility information:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Acrobat<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/acrobat/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/acrobat/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Captivate</p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://help.adobe.com/en_US/captivate/cp/using/WSc1b83f70210cd1011d7107e311c7efcf707-8000.html\">http://help.adobe.com/en_US/captivate/cp/using/WSc1b83f70210cd1011d7107e311c7efcf707-8000.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Creative Suite<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/creativesuite/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/creativesuite/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Dreamweaver<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/dreamweaver/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/dreamweaver/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Fireworks<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/fireworks/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/fireworks/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Flash Pro<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/flash/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/flash/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Flex (RIA)<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/flex/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/flex/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Illustrator<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/illustrator/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/illustrator/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>InDesign<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/indesign/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/indesign/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Photoshop<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/photoshop/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/photoshop/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Information for users with disabilities<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/user_info.html\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/user_info.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adobe product accessibility standards compliance (VPAT) information<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/compliance/\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/products/compliance/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Additional external accessibility resources<br/><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/additional_resources.html\">http://www.adobe.com/accessibility/additional_resources.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<div><p><b>Patrick Koster</b>\u00a0| Education Solution Consultant | Adobe Systems<b>\u00a0</b></p>\n</div>\n<p>321.723.4408\u00a0office | 321.759.4722 mobile |\u00a0<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:pkoster@adobe.com\">pkoster@adobe.com</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-27T18:38:41.541Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-27T18:40:02.289Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:18834","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Online document repository tool","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I am looking for a tool to create a secure online document repository. I am setting up a MySQL database for numerical data but also need a secure place to upload documents associated with each record.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I could use afs space with WRAP and link to the documents within the MySQL table but wondered if there are some good document management tools that offer more.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks,</p>\n<p>Elizabeth</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-09T18:56:26.790Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-11T15:02:08.731Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18939","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"We have played around with Google Docs but my office may shy away from putting confidential case documents on a public space, even if it is the almighty Google.","createdDate":"2011-05-11T15:02:08.760Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:19127","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"You might consider whether shared folders inside Google Docs can meet your needs. My groups in OIT have been moving to this model for most if not all of our shared documents.","createdDate":"2011-05-11T14:52:37.647Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18840","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks! Only the administrators will have the ability to upload files, so that may work. We will be able to monitor the space usage. I would love to see the PHP files if you can send them to me.","createdDate":"2011-05-10T15:06:45.130Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18837","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>You could also place the files in a directory that is not within the document root and map requests for files through a PHP file that does authorization (assuming you needed finer grain controls). I believe we have an aging homebrew which does something similar.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>It's not the kind of headache that I would recommend though, because AFS lockers fill up fast when you start letting people upload whatever they want. In particular, our tool has some <strong>ugly</strong> logic to help it span lockers because it kept running out of space.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-10T13:40:50.986Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:18726","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Services / Identification Application","description":"<p>Our group has been tasked with creating an application for the provisioning of web services on campus in conjunction with the new web hosting environment.\u00a0 Our goal is to standardize and streamline the signup process for all OIT web services into a single application so that it is easy for people to figure out how to get a site up and running.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The application will likely include</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Domain request and approval</li>\n<li>CPanel hosting signup</li>\n<li>Locker signup</li>\n<li>Web addons such as database services</li>\n<li>Billing for all of these</li>\n</ul>\n<p>As we were thinking about this, we thought this would also be an excellent opportunity to revive the discussion around knowing who is responsible for a given website on campus.\u00a0 The requirements have been discussed on here and in other forums at length, but I wanted to see what you guys think of the process and what kind of feedback you could give us as far as what you want to see from a developer perspective.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>For reference, here is the past thread that we discussed the author information:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/author-information-for-ncsu\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/author-information-for-ncsu</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Any feedback or suggestions would be appreciated.\u00a0 We are currently meeting with folks in OIT to develop a requirements document, which we plan on sharing with the community for discussion.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-06T14:09:15.708Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-10T13:50:09.498Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18937","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>I think one of our goals is to maintain some central information about sites, while also providing a downloadable file or something that can be put in webspace where ever the site is hosted (and subsequently linking back to the central database for the most up-to-date information).\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The important part, at least to me, is to ensure that the data is maintained in a decent manner.\u00a0 I was thinking of a notification system which prompted a \"renewal\" of a domain, which would require a yearly check of the contact information for a site.\u00a0 Billing (x2) and Technical (x2) contacts, as well as associated department and unit.\u00a0 We could do some neat stuff on the backend to monitor disabled accounts that are used as contacts and notify the secondary contacts.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Just brainstorming for now, but that was the road I was thinking about.\u00a0 Also, I have no issue automatically generating the humans.txt thing if that is what works for folks.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-10T13:50:09.574Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18935","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Keeping it simple is key.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Department/Unit</p>\n<p>Top Level Contact Name (Primary / Project Manager)</p>\n<p>(Optional) Backup Contact Name (Secondary / Project Lead)</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The goal is to find out who owns a site because you want them to make changes. Otherwise, you think they are perfect and you want to ask them for information/advice.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-10T13:28:48.662Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18933","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>The format described for humans.txt seems like a neat way to high five each other after a job well done, but I have concerns about its ability to stand the test of time. In particular, how much of a contribution would get you added to the \"Thanks\" section? How much until you are part of the \"Team\"? You might consider \"Team\" to be the \"original squadron\" who brought the site into the world, but that just means that the person who does all the future maintenance on the site would never really qualify for the list. It also means that the slob who set the site up to fail the following year (because they hard coded the launch year into the application) continues to get positive credit for all of the work that other people had to do to resolve the issues.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Sorry, it's just reminiscent of things I've seen before that (like this standard) contain \"Last Updated\", \"Components\", \"Software\" and \"Standards Implemented\" that don't stay up to date and are rendered inaccurate the moment someone makes a \"small change\".</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-10T13:23:18.806Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18930","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>We went with humans.txt when we launched the HTML5 Framework</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://humanstxt.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://humanstxt.org/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once the application has processed a request, will you be including links to existing resources for new web developers as part of this project? Links like these:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>NCSU web tools: <a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/tools/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsu.edu/tools/</a></p>\n<p>Accessibility</p>\n<p>Framework/Templates</p>\n<p>Brand Book</p>\n<p>Ning/web developer's list</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I'm sure there are other 'helpful links' that should be included but thought I'd suggest a few.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-10T03:30:21.243Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:18345","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Ref Cardz available","description":"<p>We have been donated a whole bunch of Ref Cardz from DZone (thanks guys!)\u00a0 If you are not familiar with them, here is the website:\u00a0 <a href=\"http://refcardz.dzone.com/\">http://refcardz.dzone.com/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We have cardz on:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ColdFusion 9</li>\n<li>Leveraging ColdFusion Exposed Services from Java</li>\n<li>Core HTML</li>\n<li>Agile Adoption</li>\n<li>Windows Presentation Foundation</li>\n<li>Flex and Spring Integration</li>\n<li>Java GUI Developer</li>\n<li>Adobe Flash Builder 4</li>\n<li>Adobe Cold Fusion Builder</li>\n<li>Lean Software Development</li>\n<li>Continuous Integration</li>\n<li>Getting Started with AJAX</li>\n<li>SOA Patterns</li>\n<li>Getting started with MyEclipse</li>\n<li>Netbeans Java Editor</li>\n<li>JDBC Best Practices</li>\n<li>GWT - Google Web Toolkit</li>\n<li>Design Patterns</li>\n<li>Flex 4 and Spring 3 Integration</li>\n<li>Enterprise Integration Patterns</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There are about 100 of each of these, so there are plenty to go around.\u00a0 If any of these pique your interest (and a few of them should) please come to my office in B21 Hillsborough building and pick up as many as you want.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-04T19:08:07.600Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-04T19:08:07.738Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:18235","contributorName":"1wyb5uen56o9y","title":"Redirect to mobile site","description":"<p>Hi,</p>\n<p>I work at LPS Program Office as a web developer. I have developed a Mobile version of the LPS program site and would like mobile browsers to automatically redirect to this site. I have tried using PHP for this but I am not well versed with PHP so I am guessing I am doing something wrong or the server does not allow PHP code on the site.</p>\n<p>The PHP code used was downloaded from the site - <a href=\"http://studiohyperset.com/another-mobile-redirect-code-update/1557\">http://studiohyperset.com/another-mobile-redirect-code-update/1557</a>.</p>\n<p>I have tried few other variations as well. I have also tried editing the .htaccess to enable this feature but that does not seem to work as well.</p>\n<p>I will be glad for any help and guidance on this issue.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-03T17:45:45.971Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-04T20:33:33.989Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18241","contributorName":"1wyb5uen56o9y","description":"<p>Hi Guys,</p>\n<p>Thanks for all your responses, the PHP code for redirecting the site is working like a charm. And yes I did download the code from the Google Codes site. I have added a few more user agents to the original code. I have tested this site with firefox User Agent Switcher (<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/user-agent-switcher/\" target=\"_blank\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/user-agent-switcher/</a>) and used user agent library from TechPatterns (<a href=\"http://techpatterns.com/forums/about304.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://techpatterns.com/forums/about304.html</a>).</p>\n<p>The site can be viewed at <a href=\"http://lps.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://lps.ncsu.edu</a>. Hope the redirection works as well as it did with the user agent switcher on my desktop.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-04T20:33:34.074Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18343","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Be aware that they posted a version of the code to their Google Code site on April 12th that is much better than the code on the page you linked in the original post.","createdDate":"2011-05-04T14:15:37.256Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18436","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>I guess it depends on what kind of device your \"mobile site\" is optimized for.\u00a0 There isn't really a simple way to check to see if a user is using a mobile phone or not, but there is an excellent library called WURFL (<a href=\"http://wurfl.sourceforge.net/\" target=\"_blank\">http://wurfl.sourceforge.net/</a>) that will do device detection to see what kind of device a user is viewing your site with.\u00a0 There is a PHP wrapper for WURFL and tutorials on the site about how to use it.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The way it works is looking at the HTTP headers of a given request to determine the browser and device, then it looks up the USER_AGENT string in its XML database and returns all sorts of good information to you.\u00a0 One of the flags it returns is \"mobile\" which will identify the browser as being located on a mobile phone or not.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>You can do some USER_AGENT string checking yourself if WURFL is too much, but you will be limited to type-matching.\u00a0 It's pretty easy if all you want to match are iphones or a particular blackberry or android device, but to capture ALL mobile devices, you would need something like WURFL to sit in your code.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-04T12:10:31.106Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18238","contributorName":"1wyb5uen56o9y","description":"<p>Hi Nick,</p>\n<p>Thanks for the response. The PHP code is working.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-03T22:52:24.285Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18340","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Before you go any further, create a file and put this inside of it:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>&lt;?php echo 'php is working'; ?&gt;</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Then save it as test.php, and go to the url for that file in your web browser (ie: <a href=\"http://yoursite.whatever.com/test.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://yoursite.whatever.com/test.php</a>).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>If you see the message \"php is working\" displayed on the page, then at least you know that php is enabled for your server. Let us know if that works, and then we can talk about solutions for redirecting mobile devices to another site.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-03T17:59:19.878Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:17932","contributorName":"0oju841si4h4m","title":"question: searchable web pages","description":"<p>How do I make an area of my website that is WRAP searchable within that area, is it possible?</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-25T14:16:44.266Z","updatedDate":"2011-04-28T14:14:33.861Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18429","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>What Nick said...you are going to have to implement something programmatically.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The Zend_Search_Lucene component to zend framework makes this pretty easy, but you are going to have to handle all the indexing and searching mechanisms yourself.\u00a0 <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.search.lucene.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.search.lucene.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The only real other way to do this is if you had access to a Google search appliance.\u00a0 They cost $$$$ but allow for the indexing of user-protected resources.\u00a0 However, that is probably way out of the range of scale that you need.</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-28T14:14:33.953Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17937","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>If you need to secure the actual pages, then I don't know how to do that using something easy like Google Custom Search. When searching for your particular problem, I did stumble upon this though: <a href=\"http://www.google.com/support/webmasters/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=74536\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.google.com/support/webmasters/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=74536</a> (Google's First Click Free service). I haven't used it, but it might work for you.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The only way I know how to do something that's specifically for WRAP, would be to build your own search function. I've used Zend Framework to build a search engine for OIA -- <a href=\"http://oia.ncsu.edu/dice/search\" target=\"_blank\">http://oia.ncsu.edu/dice/search</a>. It's not protected for just WRAP users right now, but considering I built it from the ground up, it's trivial to set a restriction on the search function and results pages to just logged in users.</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-25T16:18:34.291Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17935","contributorName":"0oju841si4h4m","description":"<p>Nick \u2013 I have a directory that is WRAP and I want a custom search for just that directory and only for people who are wrapped in.</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-25T15:39:42.665Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18127","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Tom -- can you provide a little more detail? I'm confused about exactly what you'd like to do.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>IE: are you trying to have a few pages on your site be searchable, but only for people who are wrapped in?</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-25T15:04:35.643Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:17237","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"Google Public Calendar \"NC State University Holidays/Closings\"","description":"I've created a public calendar in Google for North Carolina State University closings based on:\n<a href=\"http://www7.acs.ncsu.edu/hr/employment/closings.asp\">http://www7.acs.ncsu.edu/hr/employment/closings.asp</a>\n\nDates with open-ended repeats are:\n--Martin Luther King Day - third Monday of January\n--Memorial Day - last Monday of May\n--Labor Day - first Monday of September\n--Thanksgiving - fourth Thursday and Friday of November\n\nAll other dates are entered manually; as of this writing they are out to 2013. Weekends are not included. No distinction is made between paid holidays and closings that require employees to take leave.\n\nThere are various ways to connect to this calendar:\n--Zoneless HTML - <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec@group.calendar.google.com\">https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec@group.calendar.google.com</a>\n--XML - <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic\">https://www.google.com/calendar/feeds/acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic</a>\n--iCal - <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics\">https://www.google.com/calendar/ical/acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com/public/basic.ics</a>\n--HTML - <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York\">https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=acogfe8m08j8gavggv6ckargec%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York</a>\n\nIf you have a Google calendar account, you can add this by URL under \"Other Calendars\".","createdDate":"2011-04-14T20:00:40.296Z","updatedDate":"2011-04-19T13:10:24.021Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:17527","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:17930","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"I was wondering if they would link to your google calendar page. I added a link on the Current Students landing page: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/current-students/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/current-students/</a> (yellow box on the right).<br/>","createdDate":"2011-04-19T13:10:24.073Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18026","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"which group? Google @ NC State? Looks like that page lists the official information, which is where we pull from.","createdDate":"2011-04-19T11:49:44.672Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17928","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>Has your group coordinated with Registration &amp; Records to add it to this web page:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/registrar/calendars/</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-04-18T19:12:56.484Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17244","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks Nick. That seems like a useful tool. It's a bit busy for me to use on a regular basis though, but I'm glad that it's easily available to students (and others) who are lucky enough to be using Google Apps @ NC State.<br/>","createdDate":"2011-04-18T13:48:05.543Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17739","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>FYI -- we have an official NC State Academic calendar in the Google Apps @ NC State service. We describe it here:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://google.ncsu.edu/page/subscribe-the-nc-state-academic-calendar-google\" target=\"_blank\">http://google.ncsu.edu/page/subscribe-the-nc-state-academic-calendar-google</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-04-15T15:07:25.249Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17735","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thank you so much for this!!! In case anyone else runs into issues on an Android phone, you might need to clear you Calendar Storage and resync to get a new calendar. Make sure to move any local calendar items to a remote calendar and sync them first!","createdDate":"2011-04-14T21:35:01.734Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:17326","contributorName":"halmeeks","title":"Notes from HTML 5 Video Preso","description":"<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Here's a list'o'links on HTML 5 video. Feel Free to add more.</p>\n<p><br/><strong>Sample Versions</strong><br/><br/>This takes for freaking ever to load because the webm/ogv files are too big. Get the p2p-video.zip.<br/><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video.html\">http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video.html</a><br/><br/><strong>Archives of somewhat messy late-nite examples using Adobe/Kaltura Video Framework</strong><br/><br/><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video_mp4.zip\">http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video_mp4.zip</a><br/><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video.zip\">http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/p2p_video/p2p_web_pages/p2p_video.zip</a><br/><br/><strong>Delicious Bookmarks URL</strong><br/><br/><a href=\"http://www.delicious.com/hal2k/html5%20video\">http://www.delicious.com/hal2k/html5%20video</a><br/><br/><strong>Specific Sites Worth Visiting</strong></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>HTML 5 Video Overview</p>\n<a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/video.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://diveintohtml5.org/video.html</a>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>HTML 5 Video Player Comparison<br/><a href=\"http://praegnanz.de/html5video/\">http://praegnanz.de/html5video/</a><br/><br/>HTML5 Video Accessibility Slideshow<br/><a href=\"http://blog.gingertech.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/summit2010/\">http://blog.gingertech.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/summit2010/</a><br/><br/>OpenCast List of HTML5 Web Resources<br/><a href=\"http://opencast.jira.com/wiki/display/OC/HTML5+Web+Resources\">http://opencast.jira.com/wiki/display/OC/HTML5+Web+Resources</a><br/><br/>Mozilla Drumbeat<br/><a href=\"https://www.drumbeat.org/en-US/projects/webmademovies/\">https://www.drumbeat.org/en-US/projects/webmademovies/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>HTML 5 Video, Canvas etc overview</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.infoworld.com/d/application-development/html5-in-the-browser-canvas-video-audio-and-graphics-808\">http://www.infoworld.com/d/application-development/html5-in-the-browser-canvas-video-audio-and-graphics-808</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>HTML 5 MPEG-4 Patent Licensing \"Know your Rights\"</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.engadget.com/2010/05/04/know-your-rights-h-264-patent-licensing-and-you/\">http://www.engadget.com/2010/05/04/know-your-rights-h-264-patent-licensing-and-you/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Content Conversion Tools</strong></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Miro Video Converter</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.mirovideoconverter.com/\">http://www.mirovideoconverter.com/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Firefogg</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://firefogg.org/\">http://firefogg.org/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Media Converter</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://media-converter.sourceforge.net/\" target=\"_blank\">http://media-converter.sourceforge.net/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Avanti - FFMPEG frontend for Windows</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://avanti.arrozcru.com/\">http://avanti.arrozcru.com/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Cool HTML 5 Video Web Examples</strong></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>http://planete-a-vendre.arte.tv/fr/paysans-ethiopiens/</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-07T16:56:15.524Z","updatedDate":"2011-04-13T14:03:31.096Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:4173","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:17627","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Yeah, the Validator would probably accept it for HTML5, but XHTML5 it would probably complain. I saw somewhere that the html is supposed to match the root node of the document (which is html in both, although non-XML HTML is case insensitive).","createdDate":"2011-04-13T14:03:31.147Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17235","contributorName":"ruy64xldrlf1","description":"<p>Why &lt;!DOCTYPE HTML&gt; ?\u00a0 Because Dreamweaver put it in there that way. :) I just checked and the W3C Validator seems to like it.</p>\n<p>You are correct about the WebVTT format.\u00a0 I used an SRT format since the plugin worked with that.</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-13T12:37:06.733Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17431","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Really like the Dive into HTML5 resource. The important thing to note is that buggy useragents have the bad habit of forcing us to modify code...<br/><br/>By the way, WebVTT is the not-yet-implemented text track standard that they're pushing for HTML5.<br/><br/>Also Greg, is there a specific reason that you're using &lt;!DOCTYPE HTML&gt; instead of the typical &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; ?","createdDate":"2011-04-12T20:00:58.328Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17427","contributorName":"ruy64xldrlf1","description":"<p>Here are the resources from my part.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Basic HTML5 Video</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5video.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5video.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>HTML5 Video with Captions</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5videocaptions.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5videocaptions.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>HTML5 Video with Fallback to JW Player</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5videofallback.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://accessibility.oit.ncsu.edu/dev/video/html5/html5videofallback.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Dive into HTML5 from Mark Pilgrim</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/video.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://diveintohtml5.org/video.html</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>NOTE: I did some more testing and the native HTML 5 video controls are fairly accessible.\u00a0 There are a few glitches, but it's fairly good.\u00a0 As HTML 5 progresses we should see better support.</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-11T19:58:19.047Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:17026","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Go Links Stats Change...","description":"<p>I meant to post this here the other day when I made the change (and posted to the OIT Design Blog), but I forgot (my apologies).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Here's the blog post for full information: <a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2011/04/04/go-links-optional-statistics\" target=\"_blank\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2011/04/04/go-links-optional-statistics</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Here's the summary:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Statistics for all existing links (before the change) are still enabled</li>\n<li>Statistics for all new links are off by default</li>\n<li>Statistics can be toggled on and off via the link details screen</li>\n<li>Link creators are prompted about this when they create a new link.</li>\n<li>This was done to avoid database bloat, as many link owners may not care about the hits their links get (and those that do care, can turn the stats on).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you have any questions, you can post here on on the OIT Design blog page.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Just for fun, here's the latest Go Links stats:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>1415 User Specified Links</li>\n<li>3130 Total Go Links</li>\n<li>61834 Total Hits</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2011-04-07T00:14:15.680Z","updatedDate":"2011-04-08T13:04:45.903Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:17231","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks Nick!","createdDate":"2011-04-08T13:04:45.931Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17228","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Whenever a link gets a hit, if the stats are enabled, it stores this info:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>current timestamp</li>\n<li>referrer</li>\n<li>remoteAddress</li>\n<li>browser string</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disabling or enabling stats does not affect any previously stored information. It simply starts or stops collecting at the time you toggle the setting. If you want to clear your stats for a link though, you can (there's a button on the stats page).</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-07T13:28:08.011Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17127","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Aww, but millions upon millions of rows is such fun!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>How much information are you keeping in that table? Strict hits or more information like date etc?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Also, if I disable stats, does it delete the old hits?</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-07T12:56:05.926Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:16528","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Brand tools:  Wordpress plugins, Drupal modules, PHP Library","description":"<p>We've been workin</p>\n<p>g on a few plugins for NC State-related things and we wanted to share them with you guys.\u00a0 Some are new, some are just updates.\u00a0 The Drupal stuff was done by Nick Young in OIT DEO, all the wordpress stuff has come out of Outreach Technology so direct your feedback respectively.\u00a0 If you find issues, please submit them using the issue tracker on GitHub as opposed to emailing or IMing us.\u00a0 Pull requests welcome...<br/><br/><strong>NC State Branding Bar Plugin for Wordpress and Drupal - OIT DEO</strong><br/><br/>This plugin implements the NC State branding bar for both Wordpress and Drupal.\u00a0 These will work with any theme you have installed on both platforms.\u00a0 They are completely configurable based on the options provided by Web Communications (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/</a>).\u00a0 All of the code for these plugins is shared on github...<br/><br/>* Wordpress 3.x:\u00a0 <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-BrandingBar\">https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-BrandingBar</a><br/>* Drupal 6:\u00a0 <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Module-Drupal-6--NC-State-Branding-Bar\">https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Module-Drupal-6--NC-State-Branding-Bar</a><br/><br/><strong>NC State WRAP Authentication Plugin for Wordpress 3.x - OIT OT</strong><br/><br/>I've updated this plugin quite a bit to be more integrated.\u00a0 It is very similar in action to the original WRAP plugin I put out there, but this one has been completely retooled and should work a little more efficiently.<br/><br/>* Wordpress 3.x:\u00a0 <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-WrapAuthentication\">https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/Plugin-Wordpress-WrapAuthentication</a><br/><br/><strong>NC State PHP Library for PHP 5 - OIT OT</strong><br/><br/>One of the things we realized when working on this stuff was that we needed a centralized library for a lot of the functionality found in the branding bar and in some other future projects.\u00a0 We've formalized this library into a centralized PHP library that you all are welcome to use and integrate into your projects.\u00a0 It is definitely a work in progress and is no way a final piece of work, however we are standardizing all of our plugins off of it.<br/><br/>* PHP 5.x:\u00a0 <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/PHP-Ncstate\">https://github.com/ncsuwebdev/PHP-Ncstate</a><br/><br/>If you all wouldn't mind taking a few minutes to look over these plugins and install them that would help a lot.\u00a0 We've tried to do a lot of testing in house with these, but it would be awesome if you guys were able to give them a whirl too. <br/><br/>This also marks a new direction for some of us in OIT with using GitHub to store and release projects and code.\u00a0 It has worked great so far.\u00a0 If you also have code or projects that you would like to contribute and have published to GitHub, please let me know and we can add you to the ncsuwebdev group.</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-29T18:47:36.995Z","updatedDate":"2014-02-05T19:51:17.732Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:35623","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"<p>Any chance you have a link to the Mediawiki WRAP plugin? Is that still out there?</p>","createdDate":"2014-02-05T19:51:17.279Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30130","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Nice. Finally.</p>\n<p>Coincidentally, I have started the work on upgrading some of the NC State Drupal 6 modules to Drupal 7. More news on how to get all those in an efficient method coming soon.</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-02T14:55:05.061Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30129","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Just under 9 months later, the active trail issue is marked fixed! (In 7.x git at least)</p>","createdDate":"2012-01-02T14:32:59.933Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16927","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"actually---talking to some of the guys I know from App State and UNCC (that I hung with at DrupalCon), there are still critical bugs in Drupal 7 that will in fact erase your data. I can't remember what those were in particular, but they do exist...and again...people are not happy. Most of the community would have preferred they wait to fix the critical bugs and release \"late.\" But instead, the private-sector \"commercial\" aspirations of the Drupal maintainers (Acquia) seemed to trump that logic, and push for a big worldwide release date party to generate buzz (which left most of the community in the dark about what to do with this new upgrade).","createdDate":"2011-04-01T13:04:42.803Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16926","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Yeah, I understand that completely. The big thing for the Drupal release was \"Critical = We Can't Fix it Later\". With the long drawn out process that was the Drupal 7 development, I do understand that too. Drupal 7 release is more of a technology preview that will do it's best not to mess up your data and is a supported release. Stuff just might not display correctly until those bugs are fixed (barring issues that are unknown).","createdDate":"2011-04-01T12:59:53.794Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16536","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>One of the major ones that i discovered, was that the \"Active Trail\" is not set on custom menus. Drupal 7 comes out of the box with \"Primary\" and \"Secondary\" menus, and those get set correctly. But if you create a custom menu (like pretty much every Drupal site on the planet ends up using), then the Active Trail is not set.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>What's the problem with that, you say?</p>\n<p><br/>Well, the effect is that all the javascript/css that creates the nice drop-down, or expanding menus....it doesn't work on custom menus. Also, the contextual pieces of Drupal that \"know\" what page you are on, and therefore can set the menus, styles, regions appropriately based on what trail is active...that doesn't work either in this context.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>This is the particular thread on Drupal.org about it: <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/942782\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal.org/node/942782</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>After chatting in IRC and to people at DrupalCon, this is not the only situation, and is in fact indicative of the process taken to release Drupal 7 \"on schedule.\" A lot of people are unhappy about it, and the consensus is that if something as centrally important as menus isn't working properly, then what else is still buggy? Translation: Use Drupal 6 until Drupal 7 is at version 2 at least :-)</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-31T14:00:11.384Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16535","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>Thanks for the summary!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>If it's not too difficult, I would be very interested in knowing which bugs were treated in this way. Knowing the sticking points would be very helpful when evaluating upcoming solutions.</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-31T13:44:08.869Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16534","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Yes -- i have played *a lot* with Drupal 7.....and while it is a great improvement on Drupal 6....it's simply not ready for primetime yet.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>It has \"major\" bugs...which the core Drupal maintainers downgraded from \"critical\" to \"major\" in the run up to the launch ---- this is because they decided early on that they wouldn't launch D7 until all critical bugs were fixed. So instead of actually fixing them, they reclassified them to a lower rank. To me....that's a very disappointing way to go about things from a central standpoint.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>But....there are a lot of very very cool things in Drupal 7. The back end is cleaned up immensely for theming (much easier to figure out where things are supposed to go)...and functions/api calls are much more consistent (ie: drupal_add_css() and drupal_add_js() now work the same....which they didn't in D6).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>To sum up...Drupal 7 is fine for very simple sites that really don't do much at all. But if you're going to be using what Drupal is good at (dynamic blocks, regions, menus, content)...then definitely wait until at least a couple of revisions before you use it on a production site.</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-31T10:58:24.610Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16631","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This is a bit of a tangent, but have you played with Drupal 7 at all? It seems like they've done a lot of work since Drupal 6, but I haven't heard much about the experience people have had with it here on the Web Dev ning.","createdDate":"2011-03-30T20:43:41.011Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16729","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks Jason. If you're in the code again at some point, I wouldn't be opposed to capitalizing the second W in WolfWare. I remember having to fix that in several places when I was working on the initial version of the new site.","createdDate":"2011-03-30T20:42:46.165Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16630","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"scratch that....1.0.3 is now ready and on github...found a problem with contrib themes not displaying the bar correctly due to a limitation on the drupal_add_css function in Drupal 6.","createdDate":"2011-03-30T20:05:31.769Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16533","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Done and done. Version 1.0.2 is out on github now, and it includes the SSL option, and site search.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-30T18:45:05.972Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16337","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'll be changing the Drupal plugin to work the same as the wordpress one too (SSL on/off). Should be able to have that done sometime today.","createdDate":"2011-03-30T14:56:46.255Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16727","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I've updated the PHP library to have the SSL-er-ized version of the branding bar, and also updated the wordpress plugin to allow a user to decide whether or not to use the secure version.\u00a0 Thanks for the feedback guys.\u00a0 Keep it coming.","createdDate":"2011-03-30T14:14:39.615Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16531","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Haven't had a chance to dig into the code. But you can make all your links be protocol independent (http/https) by using the following syntax.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1em; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent; clear: both; word-wrap: break-word;\"><code style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 1px 5px; border-width: 0px; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: Consolas,Menlo,Monaco,'Lucida Console','Liberation Mono','DejaVu Sans Mono','Bitstream Vera Sans Mono','Courier New',monospace,serif;\">&lt;a href=\"//<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/folder/file.php\" target=\"_blank\">www.ncsu.edu/folder/file.php</a>\"&gt;link text&lt;/a&gt;</code></p>","createdDate":"2011-03-30T13:23:24.595Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:16627","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\" id=\"LC35\"><span class=\"p\">First, I would like to thank all of you for providing these useful tools. I thought there might have been a Drupal 6 and Mediawiki WRAP Auth Plugin too, but those may not have been an OIT project. I'll see if I can dig it up, because I thought I was using it.</span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"><span class=\"p\"><br/></span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"><span class=\"p\">As far as the Branding Bar code, I didn't see a way to use the HTTPS version. I believe the path is different, so it isn't just a str_replace('http:', 'https:', self::BRAND_URL).</span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"><span class=\"p\"><br/></span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\"><span class=\"p\">Also, I would like to suggest a couple changes to the quicklinks:<br/></span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\" id=\"LC36\">\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0<span class=\"s1\">'Vista Courses'</span> <span class=\"o\">=&gt;</span> <span class=\"s1\">'http://vista.ncsu.edu/'</span><span class=\"p\">, // Replace with WolfWare (<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://wolfware.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://wolfware.ncsu.edu</a>), this is Vista's last semester.</span></div>\n<div style=\"background-color: transparent;\" class=\"line\" id=\"LC38\">\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0<span class=\"s1\">'Wolfware Courses'</span> <span class=\"o\">=&gt;</span> <span class=\"s1\">'http://courses.ncsu.edu/'</span><span class=\"p\">, // Change text to WolfWare Classic or perhaps WolfWare Classic Courses<br/></span></div>","createdDate":"2011-03-30T12:56:25.121Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:15141","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Need Assistance with .NET Project","description":"<p>All -</p>\n<p>I am looking for some assistance on a project in Student Affairs. We are looking at an online prescription service that would tie into our other Student Health systems. It requires some .NET programming to setup and maintain. It involves downloading some files from the vendor to our OIT-hosted domain (studentaffairs.ncsu.edu), and then some programming to connect the site to our pharmacy database.</p>\n<p>Here is what I need.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>1. Someone to help me evaluate just how much time/effort it will take to set it up, and then maintain over time.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>2. If setup/maintenance are within our budget, then I need help identifying someone to assist with this work.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>In the end, we will pay for the work, but I'm hoping there is a friendly colleague out there who can do me the favor of assisting with the assessment of the project as described above.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks in advance for any advice you may have.</p>","createdDate":"2011-03-04T14:43:43.006Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-04T14:43:43.128Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:14726","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"University Web site rankings","description":"FYI<br/> <br/> RE:<br/> <a href=\"http://www.webometrics.info/top12000.asp\">http://www.webometrics.info/top12000.asp</a><br/> <br/> Of the top 12,000:<br/> <br/> UNC = 23<br/> Duke = 33<br/> NC State = 50<br/> <br/> <a href=\"http://www.webometrics.info/about_rank.html\">http://www.webometrics.info/about_rank.html</a>","createdDate":"2011-02-24T14:23:40.586Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-25T14:14:00.816Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:14827","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"ECU = 526","createdDate":"2011-02-25T14:14:00.842Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:14629","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"#50 in the world is fantastic! Go Pack!","createdDate":"2011-02-25T13:49:53.018Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:14626","contributorName":"3jgdccfjvfpif","title":"WordPress 3.1 just dropped","description":"Here's the release post:\u00a0<a href=\"http://wordpress.org/news/2011/02/threeone/\">http://wordpress.org/news/2011/02/threeone/</a>","createdDate":"2011-02-23T15:27:26.481Z","updatedDate":"2011-04-20T20:29:56.464Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:17931","contributorName":"3ggtou3xgbk6l","description":"<p>The white screen problem seems to be an issue with Atahualpa 3.6.4, and the theme developer has suggested several fixes that don't work for me.\u00a0\u00a0When I tried to upgrade WordPress without upgrading\u00a0Atahualpa, I lost center screen functionality.\u00a0 In the end\u00a0I backed up my files, deleted all the WordPress files from\u00a0the server folder and reinstalled from a fresh download of WordPress 3.1.1.\u00a0 Then\u00a0I copied\u00a0the WP files that I had changed back to the server\u00a0and reloaded Atahualpa 3.5.3\u00a0 It works now, and I love the new network adminstrator menu--makes it much easier to move from site to site.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks again!</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-20T20:29:56.552Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17827","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Sounds like PHP is producing a fatal error. I'll send you an e-mail.","createdDate":"2011-04-15T19:47:52.304Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17240","contributorName":"3ggtou3xgbk6l","description":"<p>Has anyone had trouble installing WordPress 3.1 or 3.1.1?\u00a0 I've tried to install both and just get a white screen when I type in my site url or log-in url.\u00a0 I've re-installed 3.0.5 twice now because that seems to be the only thing that works.\u00a0 go.ncsu.edu/rdo</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-15T15:00:11.752Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:13447","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"\"My [Insert Institution Here]\"","description":"<p>Greetings from your fellow web devs down US 264!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We're looking at various options for improving our web site experience for people affiliated with the university (faculty, staff, students, inclusive). \u00a0One of the ideas we're thinking about is a \"My ECU\" which will allow you to have the ability to add links to a personal collection of bookmarks. \u00a0This would (possibly) appear on the home page if you've authenticated, along with your own customizable page of links that would be sortable/editable.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>What I would like to know is if anyone there, whether at Central IT, college, department, or some other level has anything like this. \u00a0If not, have you considered it? \u00a0If you have, why did you choose not to move forward?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Also, since we don't have NCSU credentials, it would help us in our redesign efforts if someone could show us what happens (screenshot would be awesome!) when you log in (suitably anonymized of course) to Pack Portal. \u00a0We've got a bunch of portals of various kinds, and having them under a united login would be a desired goal.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thoughts, comments, questions all welcome!</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>PS: Yes, we understand that bookmarks have been done well by both browsers and 3rd party sites like Delicious, X-Marks, etc. \u00a0One of our goals is to help reduce the \"why isn't my link on the home page\" requests from various campus entities.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-17T14:45:23.243Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-23T16:16:34.883Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:14530","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<p>That mirrors our experience with the home page. \u00a0We have added click tracking via Google Analytics for the icons (and some of the other areas) on our home page to see the traffic. \u00a0The biggest usage, by far, is the e-mail icon, OneStop icon (that's our rough equivalent of your MyPack Portal), and the BlackBoard icon.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks, Jason, for the QuickLinks link. \u00a0That provides an interesting and informative look at what we were actually considering. \u00a0We actually are re-evaluating our strategy due to a demo of OneStop 2 (latest generation of the software). \u00a0We'll be working with that team to make sure we don't duplicate functionality and provide an experience that ties the home page / campus content with the OneStop content.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks, everyone, for your insights. \u00a0We're definitely in agreement that if you can't do something well don't do it at all.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>We'll try to add what thought processes we've had/will have in case they provide some reciprocal help for your folks at NCSU.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-23T16:16:34.916Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:14231","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a target=\"_self\" href=\"discussions/9-eoshomeclicks.jpg\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"discussions/10-eoshomeclicks.jpg?width=721\" width=\"721\"/></a>We use a custom 'quick launch' screen of sorts for our default browser homepage in our Engineering student computing labs.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/home\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/home</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>It's a little bit of a blend between Opera's new tab page and Google Chrome's new tab page. Since we pretty much 'guessed' at which links or pages would be useful to students (working from our labs) we've decided to gather a little click data. You can see the results above.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>*Note: We're actively working on opening this tool up for other webdev's at NC State to use for analyzing clicks within your own user interfaces. Coming soon...</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>-Mike</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-23T14:14:12.243Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:14229","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>I'd say the last thing you would want to pattern something after is MyPack Portal, but that's solely a personal opinion.\u00a0 I find that I only log into the thing to do administrative stuff (like Jonathan mentioned).\u00a0 I definitely wouldn't want to use it as a homepage, that's for sure.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I think what was done at NC State was to introduce the idea of Quick Links, which I think are personalized.\u00a0 I wasn't involved in that process, but you can see the result of that in the homepage (upper right corner, above search).\u00a0 Here is more info about those:\u00a0 <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/about-site/customize-quicklinks/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/about-site/customize-quicklinks/index.php</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Maybe someone from University Communications could weigh in a little more on what is done to solve the actual problem of \"my link is not on the homepage and I want it to be\".</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-22T16:27:01.017Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:14527","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>I think Mike's on the right track. Because of variety and discontinuity, attempting to offer a service such as that has a tendency to simply add to the confusion. Rather than add personalized links, you could just have a \"{Faculty,Staff,Students} Landing Page\". People are going to keep track of their links in their own way, but a static page with useful groupings of *actually useful* links can help close the gap. If you wanted to make it dynamic-ish, you could consider adding a \"Suggest a Link\" feature.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>MyPack Portal is mostly how we get access to the HR and Student data systems. They added some links to other tools, but it's usually a lot easier (meaning that I have encountered fewer issues) to go directly to those tools instead. Other than when I go to download my W2, I avoid it as much as possible. Technical notes: It has inadequate browser support for non-IE users.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-21T15:40:07.058Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13457","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Tony,</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I think a lot of different institutions have tried the 'MyXXXX' approach, and the problem is, none of them seem to do it consistently, which ruins the user experience, or does not meet the expectations the user may have had.</p>\n<p>Here's an example... on the new <a href=\"http://www.mae.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering website</a>, we have a link to 'MyMAE', which is just a list of internal department forms and documents (mostly for faculty and staff). You should also note that this is a static list of flat files and there's no magical identification going on behind the scenes to serve you personalized content, which is what initially comes to mind when you see 'MySomething'. Disappointing to the user? Sure.</p>\n<p><br/>Shortly after we launched the site with this new 'MyMAE' area, there was a lot of confusion. People were writing in and saying they couldn't find any of the forms that were on the site previously, so to eliminate confusion and make the location of the forms more clear to users, I added another link (directly beside MyMAE) for 'Forms', the link pointed to the exact same page that MyMAE did, but it was surprising how many folks clicked one versus the other.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a target=\"_self\" href=\"discussions/11-mymaevsforms.gif\"><img class=\"align-full\" src=\"discussions/12-mymaevsforms.gif\" width=\"483\"/></a></p>\n<p>While the trend above shows that 'MyMAE' consistently received more clicks than 'Forms',\u00a0 I have to believe that many of the clicks for 'MyMAE' were simply done out of curiosity. (Note: the MyMAE page has one of the highest bounce, and highest exit rates in the site - this tells me users are seeing the page, and fleeing the page... \"this is not what I thought it was going to be\"). In the end, I think you're better off being more 'clear' than 'clever'. Don't take the MyXXXX approach unless you're really going to do some sort of personalization, or go the full 10 yards.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>-Mike</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-17T19:31:12.768Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:13935","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Creative Commons Attribution","description":"<p>Do you get content (like images) via a Creative Commons search to use in your projects?\u00a0 Do you ever come upon this verbiage?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\"<strong>Attribution</strong> \u2014 <span id=\"attribution-container\">You must attribute the work in the manner specified by the author or licensor (but not in any way that suggests that they endorse you or your use of the work).\"</span></p>\n<p><span>(</span><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/deed.en\" target=\"_blank\">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/deed.en</a>)</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I see this frequently, like for this <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/andercismo/2349098787/\" target=\"_blank\">image</a> off of Flickr.\u00a0 The problem is that I don't see any specifics about \"a manner specified by the author.\"\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Basically my question is this, how do you give credit?\u00a0 Is a &lt;!-- comment --&gt; enough?\u00a0 Or do you put in text under the image like \"credit <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/andercismo/2349098787/\" target=\"_blank\">andercismo</a>\".\u00a0 Just trying to get a feel for what's best practice and/or what people are doing.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-17T13:32:28.579Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-18T17:44:45.502Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:14327","contributorName":"342r1a4s0h1s3","description":"<p>Some info from Creative Commons here:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#How_do_I_properly_attribute_a_Creative_Commons_licensed_work.3F\">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#How_do_I_properly_attribute_a_Creative_Commons_licensed_work.3F</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Looks like you have some discretion as long as you follow the spirit/intent of the license.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-18T17:44:45.544Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13938","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>Removing a watermark is one (obviously evil) thing, but when the author doesn't specify how they should be credited (and there is no watermark) it leaves some ambiguity.\u00a0 Still, I see your point.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I think I'll adopt the practice of just adding a visible credit line to the page where I've used an image that I've found via Creative Commons.\u00a0 Not necessarily immediately under the image, maybe in the content section of the page, maybe at the footer, but definitely visible/not hidden.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>ps. you can find free-to-use-content via Flickr's <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/search/advanced/\" target=\"_blank\">advanced search</a>.\u00a0 There are <a href=\"http://search.creativecommons.org/\" target=\"_blank\">other places</a> to find CC licensed content too.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-17T15:46:30.948Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13450","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>Personally, I think you should have a visible attribution to the original author/photographer/owner of the image. If it's just in a comment or something that's not instantly visible to the regular user, then I'd be pretty annoyed if i was the owner of the image.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I think about it in these terms:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://i.imgur.com/F4nDH.png\"><img class=\"align-left\" style=\"padding: 5px;\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/F4nDH.png\"/></a></p>","createdDate":"2011-02-17T14:51:21.780Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:13928","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","title":"1 Very Good Reason To Be Careful When Combining JavaScript Files","description":"<p>Other than the issues that have been mentioned before about the benefits of long term caching by using static files (especially shared static files), an interesting item showed up in my feeds today:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Combining multiple JavaScript files can cause your - normally functional - JavaScript to error out.</strong></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>The situation in question is caused by a state change triggered by stock jQuery setting strict mode. This causes all other lines in the same file (i.e. all of the lines in all the other files that have been dynamically combined into a single \"file\") to be limited to the capabilities available in strict mode.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>From <a href=\"http://ed.agadak.net/2011/02/great-time-to-use-firefox-4\" target=\"_blank\">the source</a>:</p>\n<p>Firefox 4 supports <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Strict_mode\">ECMAScript 5 <tt>\"strict mode\"</tt></a>, which makes writing JavaScript code easier and cleaner. Amazon.com combines multiple files, e.g., its own code and jQuery, into a single file to speed up the site; however, jQuery uses strict mode, which applies to the whole file, and some of other other code was no longer valid.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-16T17:08:38.314Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-16T17:14:51.113Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:13931","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Of course, if all of your JavaScript is strict mode compliant, then this won't be an issue.","createdDate":"2011-02-16T17:14:51.157Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:13629","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Wordpress in NCSU AFS --- Problems with auto-upgrade","description":"<p>I have a wordpress website installed in AFS (v 3.x) and i can't get it to auto-upgrade via the admin panel.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I assume it's something to do with the ownership of files (which i figured out from a bunch of searching on google)...but even after owning the files to the account that apache is running under, it still doesn't work.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>So...my question is....does anyone else have a wordpress site, installed on AFS, that you have successfully configured to auto-upgrade via the admin panel?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Any help/direction/support/encouragement/validation-that-im-not-missing-something-obvious would be appreciated.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>--Nick</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-11T18:40:33.528Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-02T14:00:50.678Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18626","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I tried following the link and it took me back to this page, haha. In case anyone is interested in the relevant documentation:<br/><br/><a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Editing_wp-config.php#WordPress_Upgrade_Constants\" target=\"_blank\">http://codex.wordpress.org/Editing_wp-config.php#WordPress_Upgrade_Constants</a>","createdDate":"2011-05-02T14:00:50.817Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18228","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>Add define('FS_METHOD', 'direct'); to the top of your wp-config.php file.\u00a0 Works like a champ now.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/reuteras/status/61015985389453312\" target=\"_blank\">Ahh the wonders of Twitter</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-04-29T18:38:32.630Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:14026","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'd probably start debugging the code. It should be easy to find out why it thinks it needs to use FTP instead. The hard part will probably be figuring out why when you know the answer to the first question.","createdDate":"2011-02-14T14:39:40.288Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13443","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yeah --- i tried giving www:servers.php rlidwk access to the entire directory as a test, and it didn't change a thing. Still prompts for FTP credentials.","createdDate":"2011-02-14T14:29:03.237Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13442","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>that's pretty much what i thought was the situation. It's not a big deal, as the future solution will be \"move to the web hosting environment where this is not an issue.\" Thanks for the details...that is in line with everything i read and found on the topic.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-14T14:28:07.291Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13440","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>To expand on Charlie's post, you need to make sure that the server running the code has access to that location in AFS. Typically this is achieved by running the following command (once per directory):<br/>fs sa directory_where_wordpress_writes www:servers.php rlidwk</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>This assumes that the server is in this list:</p>\n<p>pts mem www:servers.php</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Where is it installed?</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-14T14:15:17.403Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13433","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>I have the same problem, tried a bunch of different things, nothing works.\u00a0 I emailed help@ncsu.edu, here's the response:</p>\n<p>\"<br/>Unfortunately it looks like the answer is going to be not possible.\u00a0 There's 2 issues in the way...<br/><br/>1) Directory ownership.\u00a0 According to the WPAU documentation the directory has to be owned by the userid running apache.\u00a0 On our servers the apache daemon process is owned by the special user 'apache', and your directories are owned by you.\u00a0 I would have hoped that allowing the pts group www:servers.php to have write access would solve that, but apparently it did not (as it was already set on your directories).<br/><br/>2) ftp access.\u00a0 The WPAU documentation looks like it only uses the ftp if the permissions do not allow writing (although it is unclear, so I'm not positive about that).\u00a0 Regardless, whether because it always needs ftp access or it needs ftp access because of the permissions/ownership, the ncsu ftp servers do not allow user access for security reasons.\u00a0 They actually only give ftp access to a couple of special directories that allow anonymous access.<br/><br/>So it appears you're going to have to do the manual update process.\"</p>\n<p>call 1438311 if you'd like to read the whole thing.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-11T19:42:00.805Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13430","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>additionally....here's the wordpress doc that lists out what i'm \"supposed\" to do...but obviously I (or they) are missing something.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Updating_WordPress\" target=\"_blank\">http://codex.wordpress.org/Updating_WordPress</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Excerpt....</p>\n<blockquote><p>Note that your files all need to be owned by the user under which your Apache server executes, or you will receive a dialog box asking for \"connection information,\" and you will find that no matter what you enter, you won't be able to update. See man chown. If you do not know which user runs the httpd the output of ps auxw | grep -E 'http|apache|www' or ps auxw might help, see man ps.</p>\n</blockquote>","createdDate":"2011-02-11T18:50:39.672Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:13426","contributorName":"01ctx8zxuzbgl","title":"Anyone Using CAPTCHA?","description":"<div>Is anyone at NCSU using CAPTCHA on their web forms?\u00a0 If so, I would appreciate any thoughts or comments from the web development community\u00a0on what you are using.\u00a0 I am looking for a solution to protect a few forms that we have at the College of Textiles.</div>\n<div>\u00a0</div>\n<div>Thanks!</div>","createdDate":"2011-02-10T19:12:14.832Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-11T13:52:13.379Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:13727","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"As was mentioned on the webdevelopers mailing list, because we typically are just submitting a form rather than creating an e-mail account (a la Google), using a very simple (even static!) CAPTCHA such as \"Type the number 7.\" or \"2 + 1?\" can prevent automatic scripts (which are very unlikely to target you) from triggering spam. Additionally, it helps to lock down those forms so that they cannot send user-generated content to users of their choosing. This typically involves having a \"To: \" user list that is defined by the application and not by the web form. If it's a \"Share this Link\" tool, you can use static content to help prevent e-mails about sites that sell pills or otherwise.","createdDate":"2011-02-11T13:52:13.423Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:13228","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>I haven't used anything for CAPTCHA that's been outside of a CMS in a while. Most of the time, I just find a highly rated or installed plugin/module for Wordpress or Drupal, and use that.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>For wherever you're using CAPTCHA though, I'd suggest you make sure it's doing it in an accessible way, so that you don't leave screen-readers without a method of submitting your form.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-10T20:45:18.388Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12877","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Link Checkers","description":"Any recommendations for a good link checker? W3C is good, but only checks on page at a time (unless I'm not seeing other options). Anything out there that would check dozens of pages in an entire site?","createdDate":"2011-01-26T18:12:33.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-27T20:37:43.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12889","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Thanks, Jonathan. My search within this site didn't turn that thread up...glad to know of it!","createdDate":"2011-01-27T20:37:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12886","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>+1 to Kyle's recommendations.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Also, here's the older thread where we discussed some options:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/link-checking\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/link-checking</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-01-27T20:35:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12882","contributorName":"3af3czr863egr","description":"<p>I use two:</p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://home.snafu.de/tilman/xenulink.html\">Xenu</a> / Windows</p>\n<p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://kde-apps.org/content/show.php?content=12318\">klinkstatus</a> / kde</p>\n<p>Both are excellent at performing link checking for sites</p>","createdDate":"2011-01-27T10:13:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12779","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","title":"Research Project Web Design","description":"I get asked this question all the time - \"Do you know a web designer on campus that can create a website for our research project?\" I used to have a few grad students that would be willing and able to do this work, but they have graduated. I've tried to use some outside vendors, but they are too costly for what our faculty needs.\u00a0 Who do you refer people to? Does our Communications office offer these services? I know OIT used to, but do they still have a department?","createdDate":"2011-01-06T16:11:20.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-06T18:39:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12785","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"Thanks Jen - it is good to know that you guys are available (albeit swamped :)","createdDate":"2011-01-06T18:39:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12782","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p>Bethany - OIT does indeed still do this kind of work. Nick Young and I work with web clients external to OIT on a contract basis. We do new sites, redesigns, site maintenance and the occasional web application job. We're super-swamped right now- actually we're pretty much always swamped- but more so now because we're also very involved in the campus web hosting that OIT is trying to roll out. Any new jobs would have to go on a waiting list that currently stretches through July at the earliest. You can read a bit more about what we do here:\u00a0<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/design\">http://oit.ncsu.edu/design</a>.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I know the Web Communications Office also does contract work and there may be some folks in the various colleges who help out as well, but as far as I know that's everyone on campus. I'd love to get a more concise list of folks, even freelancers, who do a lot of contract web work for the university; it seems like that would be a great resource.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-01-06T18:28:17.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12749","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","title":"Bug Tracking/Project Management System","description":"<p>An LMS sub-committee is investigating possible bug tracking/project management systems that would allow us to effectively track feature requests and improvements to Moodle on our campus.<br/><br/>We have a few basic requirements for this system: (we have a good deal more, but these are the top ones)<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 All users should be able to vote on requests (aka Digg).<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 Categories for requests and sorting of categories(ie. Fast track, bug fixes)<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 LAMP Infrastructure<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 FREE/Open Source (if possible)<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 Public &amp; Private Notes<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u2022 Customizable intake fields<br/><br/>If you have worked with or know of any systems that would meet these needs, please send me an e-mail (bethany_smith@ncsu.edu).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks guys! We could use all the help we can get to see what is out there and available.</p>\n<p>-Bethany</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-15T20:58:52.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-12-16T15:59:58.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12755","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"<p>Thanks Jason!</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-16T15:59:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12752","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<p>My suggestion would be look into something like crowdsound (<a href=\"http://crowdsound.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://crowdsound.com</a>).\u00a0 It is not a download-yourself solution, but it is free.\u00a0 It's what we use to manage the meetups for the web developers, which allow people to vote.\u00a0 Not sure it will exactly fit your needs, but it is free.\u00a0 Other pay options are things like UserVoice (<a href=\"http://uservoice.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://uservoice.com/</a>) and Get Satisfaction (<a href=\"http://getsatisfaction.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://getsatisfaction.com</a>).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>For more traditional bug/feature tracking, we have used RedMine (<a href=\"http://redmine.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://redmine.org</a>) which is a free Ruby on Rails app.\u00a0 We used to use Mantis (<a href=\"http://mantisbt.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://mantisbt.org</a>) which is LAMP-based, but it was a bit...cluttered.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Hope that helps.</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-16T15:54:59.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12735","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"NCSU WRAP Authentication for Wordpress 3.0","description":"<p>A while ago, I made a plugin for Wordpress to allow for WRAP authentication.\u00a0 When Wordpress 2.8 came out, it completely broke and I never got around to fixing it...until now.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>I've updated the plugin to work (and requires) Wordpress 3.x.\u00a0 You can find the code and installation instructions at <a href=\"http://github.com/jfaustin/NCSU-Wordpress-WRAP-Plugin\">http://github.com/jfaustin/NCSU-Wordpress-WRAP-Plugin</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Please send me any feedback or issues you have, including recommendations for the instructions.\u00a0 I've had a few people go through them, so I think (hope) they are pretty accurate.</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-10T16:42:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-12-10T16:42:41.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12689","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Recent Changes to Go Links","description":"Just wanted to let you all know about some recent changes to the Go Links service. All of these are detailed on our blog here: <a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu</a> but here's a quick list:<br/><ol>\n<li>Ability to turn off the toolbar --- <br/><a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/19/you-asked-for-it-you-got-it-go-links-without-the-toolbar/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/19/you-asked-for-it-you-got-it-go-links-without-the-toolbar/</a><br/><br/></li>\n<li>No more social networking icons -- <a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/go-links-removal-of-social-media-buttons/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/go-links-removal-of-social-media-buttons/</a><br/><br/></li>\n<li>QR Codes for all Go Links -- <br/><a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/go-links-qr-codes-a-perfect-match/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/go-links-qr-codes-a-perfect-match/</a> <br/> <a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/qr-codes-for-go-links-just-got-more-awesome/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/12/qr-codes-for-go-links-just-got-more-awesome/</a><br/><br/></li>\n<li>Streamlined mobile themes -- <br/><a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/04/streamlined-mobile-themes-for-go-links/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/2010/11/04/streamlined-mobile-themes-for-go-links/</a><br/></li>\n</ol>\nThe service has been a hit (approaching 10,000 hits already), so I wanted to say thanks to anyone who gave constructive feedback to make the service better.<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Nick<br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-11-19T16:16:15.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-11-22T20:01:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12710","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Welcome. I'll deleted them if you haven't already.","createdDate":"2010-11-22T20:01:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12705","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"good find. I have prevented this from happening again. Can you remove the two you created, or do you want me to?\n\nIf anyone's wondering, I left a hole where you could create a link like \"go.ncsu.edu/.qr\" and also \"go.ncsu.edu/foo.qr\" which would then create an associated QR Code at \"go.ncsu.edu/foo.qr.qr\"\n\nI've plugged the hole, and now you cannot create a go link that contains the exact string \".qr\" which will solve the problem, while not affecting usability of the service.\n\nThanks Jonathan.","createdDate":"2010-11-22T16:12:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12702","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Hey Nick, was testing out QR codes. A couple interesting ones that I tagged and shared with you.","createdDate":"2010-11-22T15:53:10.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12687","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Windows 7 + Dreamweaver CS4 creating weird random files","description":"See <a href=\"http://screencast.com/t/9Sh5qZM8ztY\">http://screencast.com/t/9Sh5qZM8ztY</a><br/><br/>Happening to anyone else?\u00a0 Seems like when I perform a synch operation DW decides to create a bunch random character files.\u00a0 If you open these files in a text editor they are actually duplicates of some of the files that were affected by the synch operation.\u00a0 Very random.\u00a0 Never happened when I was in XP.<br/><br/>Side note:\u00a0 when defining a site connection in DW CS4 and Windows 7, when you try to choose a folder from the local folder definition, DW will always choose a folder above that folder.\u00a0 So, you are forced to type in (or paste) the location of the local directory.\u00a0 PITA.<br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-11-19T15:18:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-11-19T15:20:03.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12676","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Time Change and Dreamweaver","description":"I got back from UNC CAUSE today and I've found that all the websites I manage at CNR seem to want to download more recently modified files from the server when I synchronize.\u00a0 After taking a look, it appears that all of the files last modified timestamp has been increased by 1 hour.\u00a0 I guess this is due to the time change.<br/><br/>I thought this was really weird, and I don't understand why this would be happening, any thoughts?<br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-11-10T20:20:54.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-18T13:25:53.978Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:15826","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Thanks for the info!\u00a0 But, alas, did not work for me. Even tried a restart after clearing the cache.\u00a0 I'm forced to download the entire site(s) once again.\u00a0 Not the end of the world I suppose, but an annoyance? Yes.","createdDate":"2011-03-18T13:25:54.021Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:15728","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<blockquote>When you change your clock settings, files will show as different. I made the mistake of leaving DW open the evening that the clock rolled back for Daylight Savings Time and when I did a synchronization the next day, Dreamweaver reported over 1000 files had changed. That made it quite difficult to find the 3 files that actually had changed. - <a href=\"http://www.communitymx.com/blog/index.cfm?newsid=626\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.communitymx.com/blog/index.cfm?newsid=626</a></blockquote>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<blockquote><p>Deleting the cache file will most likely clear the problem. The cache can also get corrupted when the clocks change for daylight saving time. - <a href=\"http://www.ipvac.com/kb/entry/146/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ipvac.com/kb/entry/146/</a></p>\n</blockquote>\nThe second link seems to indicate that it might be a Mac DW issue.<br/>","createdDate":"2011-03-18T12:38:25.656Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:15626","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"happened again :(","createdDate":"2011-03-17T13:13:32.297Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12700","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"thanks anyways!","createdDate":"2010-11-22T13:25:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12698","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"sorry -- i check it, but had nothing to say :-(\n\nWe haven't heard about this from anyone, or if we have, Jen didn't hasn't shared any tickets like that with me.","createdDate":"2010-11-22T13:08:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12686","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"guess this isn't affecting anyone else, or no one checks this forum","createdDate":"2010-11-19T15:13:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12684","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I've only synched 3 (fairly large) sites so far, and it has indeed been all of them - every file.. I wonder if any other DW+Contribute people on campus are noticing this problem too. Maybe I'll ping OIT","createdDate":"2010-11-11T13:58:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12681","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Did this affect all files or only files that were modified within the window from when the time change would normally occur (October) until the actual time change (November)? There were a lot of computers and other devices with a clock that did not have their time change data updating automatically, leaving them to think that the time change was still occurring in October. Thus, any instance where the date was stored as a string would be off by an hour.","createdDate":"2010-11-11T13:30:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12674","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Looking for nice online training examples","description":"Hi all,<br/><br/>We are looking to redesign our online training modules to bring them up to date and make them more visually interesting and easy to use.<br/><br/>Our current design is familiar to anyone who has gone through the online <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/project/oeo-training/harassment/\">DHPR training</a>. Yes, I know it is outdated.<br/><br/>If anyone has some examples of training that they like, please post the URLs. If a password is required, screen shots would suffice.<br/><br/>Thanks!<br/>Elizabeth<br/>","createdDate":"2010-11-05T17:14:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-12-16T16:36:38.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12758","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<p>Right in the middle of that list is the way-awesome <a target=\"_self\" href=\"http://net.tutsplus.com/\">net.tutsplus.com</a>. \u00a0I vote for that as a great example of high quality user contributed (but curated) content. \u00a0If you haven't explored their site, notice they have vector software, PhotoShop, basic web design, and other areas of specialization.</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-16T16:36:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12746","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>These seem to be more reference than online training. It's a nice list though. I'm happy to see that w3schools is at the top. There may be better specific references out there, but w3schools is a solid general reference.</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-14T19:35:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12742","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"<p>We have a profile question on membership sign-up at the\u00a0Raleigh Durham Web Design Meetup, that asks for member's favorite reference and tutorial sites.\u00a0</p>\n<p>Last year I sorted and ranked the top links from several hundred member profiles and came up with this list:\u00a0</p>\n<ul class=\"fakeOL\" type=\"1\">\n<li><a href=\"http://w3schools.com/\" target=\"_blank\">w3schools.com</a>\u00a0(15)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://google.com/\" target=\"_blank\">google.com</a>\u00a0(13)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://smashingmagazine.com/\" target=\"_blank\">smashingmagazine.com</a><img class=\"brImage\" src=\"http://img1.meetupstatic.com/img/clear.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"0\"/>\u00a0(10)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://adobe.com/\" target=\"_blank\">adobe.com</a>\u00a0(8)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://alistapart.com/\" target=\"_blank\">alistapart.com</a>\u00a0(8)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://csszengarden.com/\" target=\"_blank\">csszengarden.com</a>\u00a0(7)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://net.tutsplus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">net.tutsplus.com</a>\u00a0(6)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://lynda.com/\" target=\"_blank\">lynda.com</a>\u00a0(5)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://php.net/\" target=\"_blank\">php.net</a>\u00a0(5)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://sitepoint.com/\" target=\"_blank\">sitepoint.com</a>\u00a0(5)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://w3c.org/\" target=\"_blank\">w3c.org</a>\u00a0(5)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Perhaps some of these are way off-base from your question, but a few, especially the Wordpress-based sites (smashingmagazine, alistapart, and net.tutsplus) are quite visually interesting.\u00a0The <a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/WebDesign2-0/messages/boards/thread/7938650\" target=\"_blank\">original posting is here.</a>, and contains the runner-ups and honorable mentions too.\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2010-12-14T14:50:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12695","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thank you, I will check it out!","createdDate":"2010-11-19T18:39:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12692","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I haven't done a lot of online training, but I've enjoyed the options on <a href=\"http://lynda.com\" target=\"_blank\">lynda.com</a> whenever i've needed to use it.\n\nWhat I like from online training is when i can jump into any particular point of the course, without having to go through from the start every time -- ie: skip to chapter 23 instead of having to page through chapters 1-22 first.","createdDate":"2010-11-19T18:35:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12598","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"New Go Links released...in production now","description":"The new version of Go Links is now released: <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu\">http://go.ncsu.edu</a><br/><br/>After many months of working through new policies to govern the links, as well as implementing those policies inside the application itself, it's now ready for use. Thanks have to go to Tim Jones and Harry Nicholos for working through those policies, and getting us to the stage of opening up this as a campus-service.<br/><br/>Here's the cliff's notes version of the Golinks usage policy:<br/><ul>\n<li>Go links must not violate any existing policy (specifically the domain naming policy)</li>\n<li>If you are unsure if a link you create is \"permitted\" then you should check with administrators before creating or publicizing it.</li>\n<li>You can and will be required to modify or remove any link if it violates a policy.</li>\n<li>\"I already printed this link on 10,000 brochures\" is not an excuse to violate the use policy.\u00a0</li>\n</ul>\nBasically...don't do something you shouldn't, like set up go/biology to point to a economics website. Make sense<br/><br/>I know some of you had links in the previous version, and those should all remain functional...they just won't show up under your account when you log in. I will be sending an email to all previous owners letting them know, and that they can request ownership to be transferred back to them.<br/><br/>Questions, comments, bugs....let me know....enjoy!<br/>","createdDate":"2010-10-15T14:28:46.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-10-20T13:32:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12636","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Totally amused.","createdDate":"2010-10-20T13:32:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12634","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"But it only executes the page load if the page in the iframe is different from the one that was loaded - and even then, it goes to the location that the iframe is at, not the original link location.","createdDate":"2010-10-19T17:07:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12632","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The problem with this example is that it does the same thing as the current link does (except that this one requires javascript). Changing the location.href causes a page reload because it is akin to typing a new web address into the location bar and pressing enter.","createdDate":"2010-10-19T14:15:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12631","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Your wish is granted....\n\nLog into Go Links, and under the \"My Links\" menu, you should see 'Browse All Go Links'\n\nFrom there (and also from the My Links page), you can search by Target URL to display all or part of the target. IE: if you search for post, it will return go links with targets going to <a href=\"http://www.postoffice.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.postoffice.com</a> and postini.com and mypostbox.net.\n\nI'll think about a way to put in a save-able method so you can do quick lookups of all your webspaces, instead of just searching one by one.\n\nBut...this should amuse you for a while :-)","createdDate":"2010-10-19T14:13:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12628","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Even though HTTP is supposed to be stateless, it's often used in a stateful way. It would be nice to be able to close the toolbar without repeating whatever action would be performed by issuing another HTTP GET for the URL in the link.\n\nExample: Say I create and send out a link to a page that initiates a file download. Opening the link will load the page telling the browser to prompt for a location to save the downloaded file. I then close the toolbar, which reloads the page, prompting me again to choose a location to save a file.","createdDate":"2010-10-19T13:12:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12627","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I can look into this and see if there's a good solution.\n\nIt got me thinking though....what's the reason you want to close the toolbar without refreshing the target page? I'm just wondering what the use-case is, and why there's a need to change the way it works now.","createdDate":"2010-10-19T11:43:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12626","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"No idea how cross-browser compatible this is... plus, it's untested and off the top of my head, so there's likely to be syntax errors.<br/>\n<br/>\n<pre>&lt;a title=\"Close this toolbar\" id=\"addElementButton\" class=\"ui-state-default ui-corner-all navElementModal linkButton closeToolbarButton\" name=\"addElementButton\"&gt;Close this toolbar&lt;/a&gt;function closeBar(){    document.getElementById(\"toolbarContainer\").style.display=none<br/>\n    var currentLocation = document.getElementById(\"rf\").contentWindow.location.href;<br/>\n    if(currentLocation != {variable with the goLink target URL}){<br/>\n        location.href = currentLocation<br/>\n    }<br/>\n}<br/>\n</pre>\n<br/>\nWould something like that do the trick?\n\nEdit: ugh, ning is badly mangling the input. You should be able to copy/paste it into notepad or something else to see it, though.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T19:38:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12625","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"All sounds fine to me. Thanks Nick.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T18:53:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12624","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Hrmm..i'd have to think about that one.\n\nOne of the benefits of using Golinks, is that the URL in the browser's address bar is the golink. If i have the toolbar in a div that gets hidden (without then refreshing the page) the golink would remain in the address bar, but there would be no way to find the actual URL you had subsequently surfed to inside the browser. The premise, is that as long as the golink is displayed in the address bar, there needs to be the links to report abuse, or to contact the owner. When the golink url is gone, then there is no need for the toolbar, which is why the \"close\" button reloads the page completely.\n\nIf you (or anyone else) has ideas about how to implement that request without affecting the intended use of golinks, I'd like to hear it.\n\nI'm not sure, given the way golinks is designed to work, that I could make that happen in the way you want it to. But i can think about it.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T18:44:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12623","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yeah...makes sense to me. If i dont hear anyone come up with some pitfalls, then I'll put it on my to-do list to add in there.\n\nI'm thinking something like an ability to search, or save a search that matches a string to part of a link Target...so you can easily keep an eye on things that you'd typically manage.\n\nI dont think there needs to be any authorization on it. I mean...who cares if someone in Engineering wants to know about all the golinks that point to a target in cnr.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T18:31:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12622","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Oops - upon rereading, I can see how that'd be confusing.\n\nYes, I meant that upon closing the link bar, make it simply disappear rather than reload the entire target page - something akin to having all of the link bar elements inside a div, then setting the \"display\" stylesheet property fpr that div to \"none\". Obviously you'd want to do some work to make sure it degrades gracefully, but that should be enough to give you the idea of what I'd like to see.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T18:30:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12620","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I want to be able to see all of the Go Links that have been made on websites that are managed by the College of Natural Resources. This includes cnr.ncsu.edu/* as well as a few other project lockers here and there. cnr.ncsu.edu/* gets at 80 or 90 percent of it I'd guess.\n\nFor example, I created:\ngo.ncsu.edu/xmas that is a shortcut for <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/fer/ext/extensionchristmastrees.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://cnr.ncsu.edu/fer/ext/extensionchristmastrees.html</a>\n\nDoes this make sense now?","createdDate":"2010-10-18T18:08:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12619","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"That might be possible....it would be fairly simple to look at all the targetUrls of all golinks.\n\nI can't think off the top of my head why this would be a bad thing, or how it would/could be misused....which is what i try to think of before implementing something that seems pretty obvious.\n\nAnyone else think of a problem making a page that would let people search for all golinks that do a string match for the start (or all) of a golinks target?","createdDate":"2010-10-18T17:58:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12618","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"not sure what you mean... the \"Close this toolbar\" button loads whatever the target of the link is...that's by design, so that it goes directly to the page that was specified by the link owner.\n\nI'm basically replicating the way Google or other sites work to close their parent frame by opening the target frame in the full window.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T17:56:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12617","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Fair enough - though I can see valid reasons for wanting to be rid of it on select links.\n\nThat said, can you please re-work the link bar so that it doesn't reload the page that's being visited?","createdDate":"2010-10-18T17:22:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12616","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Sounds like he wants the Google Webmaster Tools equivalent for Go Links. He tells Go Links \"I own cnr.ncsu.edu\" and after confirming that, he can see all of the Go Links that go to cnr.ncsu.edu and its subdomains.","createdDate":"2010-10-18T13:23:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12613","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The API is available --- go to the My Account link once you've signed in, and then click the \"Connections to NC State Golinks\" tab. The only reason I need to be contacted to help get anything set up, is the permission requirement that only employees can create links. There's a little magic i do in the background involving ldap lookups that requires me to give you extra permissions if you're going to programmatically (via api) create links.\n\nThe reason more specifics aren't listed right this moment, is that the domain policy (briefly discussed at last week's web developer's meetup) is not fully finalized yet. Once that is done, the pieces that affect go links will be added to the help/policy information on the golinks site too.\n\nThat's why for now, it's very bland about \"email webcomm\" for questions.\n\nIf you can explain what you mean about \"see all the golinks that were made from web spaces i manage\"...i might be able to make something work for you. I'm just not sure what you mean.","createdDate":"2010-10-15T22:28:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12611","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Cool service! Couple things:\n\n1. Maybe the API should just be available, not available on request.\n2. Similarly with who manages and who has say-so on whether something stays up or not. I think that that should be listed on the site for transparency's sake. Doesn't have to be names, but at least something like \"web communications office\" or whoever it is.\n\nSorta wish I'd be able to see all the golinks that were made from web spaces I manage. Possible?","createdDate":"2010-10-15T21:28:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12609","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"no -- not automatically.....you can close the toolbar after visiting, but not by default. This is to ensure that the visitor gets the chance to report abuse, if someone creates a link that goes somewhere it shouldn't.","createdDate":"2010-10-15T19:09:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12607","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Is there a way to have a visited link not show the link bar?","createdDate":"2010-10-15T19:06:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12604","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"For questions about policies, approvals, abuse/misuse issues, or mediation questions, email: webcomm@remedy.ncsu.edu\n\nFor development/code/application questions, please email:\noitdesign@ncsu.edu","createdDate":"2010-10-15T18:07:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12601","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<i>\"you should check with administrators before creating or publicizing it\"</i>\n\nWho should we check with specifically?","createdDate":"2010-10-15T16:00:09.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12576","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","title":"HTML5 Template and RSS Widget","description":"<p>Web Communications would like your feedback on a couple of web resources being developed for the campus community. The first is an easy-to-use RSS widget based on <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/ajaxfeeds/\">Google AJAX Feed API</a>. The second is an html 5 aria template system that uses most of the NC State core styles and typography.</p>\n<h3>RSS Widget</h3>\n<p>Lets you embed RSS feeds anywhere on a web page. Web managers can use a configuration page to create all of the necessary code.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/university-communications/web-communications/rss-widget/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/university-communications/web-communications/rss-widget/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Uses <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/ajaxfeeds/\">Google AJAX Feed API</a>, which means all the needed documentation is handled by professionals. Configuration page simply supplies the needed html code for easy implementation.</p>\n<h3>HTML5 Template</h3>\nThe purpose of the template is to offer a solid foundation for custom on-brand website design. Web Communications has started using this \"framework\" for new websites, including the chancellor installation site. The code base should give developers a good starting point for most projects, offering an alternative to the NC State template.<br/>\n<p>Template system includes three possible configurations: three-column, two-column and two-column-with-horizontal-navigation (with an optional superfish jQuery plugin). The template uses 75% of NCSU.EDU font style. Developers can bypass template styles by using a local stylesheet.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://framework.webcommdev.com/\">three-column</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://framework.webcommdev.com/2-col-vert.php\">two-column</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://framework.webcommdev.com/2-col-horiz.php\">two-column-with-horizontal-navigation</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Current features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>html 5, should work on all modern browsers and IE6</li>\n<li>Photoshop starter file</li>\n<li>customizable header background and font colors <br/><ul>\n<li>re-configure branding/utility strip color combos</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Non-image banner</li>\n<li>new right column bright styles</li>\n<li>wordpress style captioned images</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Planned features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>wordrpess theme</li>\n<li>image gallery, similar to <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/about-nc-state/chancellor/gallery/\">chancellor's office</a> and <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/about-nc-state/campus-tour/2010/09/hillsborough-st-retrospective.php\">Hillsborough Street Retrospective</a>.</li>\n<li>optional shadowbox (lightbox) code</li>\n<li>Story/Feature player (jQuery UI Tabs) similar to ncsu.edu</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The template is php-based, using a configuration file and a series of include files. No advanced php code is used, making it a viable option for most web developers.</p>\n<h4>UPDATE (10-19-2010)</h4>\n<p>RSS Widget has been updated. Basic format uses unordered lists instead of googles default code. Headline and Teaser option sets heading at an H5 level.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>UPDATE (2-2011)<br/></strong></p>\n<p>Framework is now available for download:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/university-communications/web-communications/framework/\" target=\"_blank\">HTML 5 Accessible PHP Framework info page</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebcomm/NCSU-HTML-5-Accessible-PHP-Framework\" target=\"_blank\">GitHub download page</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/setup-tutorialscreencast-for\" target=\"_self\">Ning Video Tutorial blog post</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2010-10-07T17:30:33.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-05-06T15:43:47.540Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:18829","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>Thanks for looking at this Kaushal.\u00a0 Yeah, I think what I may end up doing is just going back to the way we used to do it which is just making the whole breadcrumbs area editable and let users just type it all in...\u00a0 and FWIW I'm on CS4 and the menu is the same.</p>","createdDate":"2011-05-06T14:50:22.892Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18431","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"Added the framework info to the web downloads page and the brand book homepage, thanks for the suggestion.","createdDate":"2011-05-02T18:13:39.314Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18331","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>Has anyone used this in a Dreamweaver/Contribute project?\u00a0 I am right now.\u00a0 The template works great, and I'm adding new editable/optional regions as well as new sub-templates. All working out nicely.</p>\n<p>One problem I'm having though is with breadcrumbs.\u00a0 The problem is that the label for the breadcrumbs often blocks and obstructs the controls for manipulating the repeating region.\u00a0 I love the idea, but I wish there was a way to deal with this - like being able to move the label..\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-28T17:22:33.620Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18328","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p>Any chance we can get this template linked in either</p>\n<p>here: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/downloads/web-downloads/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/downloads/web-downloads/</a></p>\n<p>or here: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/category/design-examples/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/category/design-examples/</a> ?</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-28T12:43:57.062Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:18326","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"<p>absolutely, we presented at a Ning meeting back in February and launched an information page with a link to GitHub. We should have definitely updated this thread with the new information:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>HTML 5 Accessible PHP Framework info page</strong>: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/university-communications/web-communications/framework/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/university-communications/web-communications/framework/</a></li>\n<li><strong>GitHub download page</strong>: <a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebcomm/NCSU-HTML-5-Accessible-PHP-Framework\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/ncsuwebcomm/NCSU-HTML-5-Accessible-PHP-Framework</a></li>\n<li><strong>Ning Video Tutorial blog post</strong>: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/setup-tutorialscreencast-for\" target=\"_self\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/setup-tutorialscreencast-for</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>","createdDate":"2011-04-26T13:16:42.317Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17942","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I believe they have this project on GitHub: \ufeff<a href=\"https://github.com/ncsuwebcomm/NCSU-HTML-5-Accessible-PHP-Framework\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/ncsuwebcomm/NCSU-HTML-5-Accessible-PHP-Framework</a>","createdDate":"2011-04-26T12:41:14.387Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:17939","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Hi Luis, any update on this?\u00a0 We have some requests that could probably make good use of this template.\u00a0 Is it ready to use?","createdDate":"2011-04-25T19:29:16.160Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12633","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"Wanted to give an update on some the progress Web Communications has made based on the feedback we've received. Updated the RSS widget to display the default format as an unordered list and the headline + teaser option now uses an H5 for the headline.\n\nWe're close to having the framework code ready for some of our beta testers. We're hoping to receive feedback on the overall structure, we're still updating the jQuery dropdown menu template that will be released a bit later.","createdDate":"2010-10-19T17:02:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12597","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"thank you for the detail reply, we're looking into this - making this a completely accessible framework is one of our core goals. I also found out that tabbing works completely differently on the mac. you need to enable it to mimic PC tabbing with the keyboard.\n\nWill update this group as soon as we correct the tabbing issues.","createdDate":"2010-10-14T18:10:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12596","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The obvious first place people expect a search box to be would be the top-right, right?\n\nI'd say either put it in the header, towards the top right corner of the headertop div, or at the very top of the right column, above the first block/widget.\n\nIf you put it in the right column though, im not sure how that would work with a template that doesn't have a right column. That's why my vote would be for including it in the headertop div.","createdDate":"2010-10-14T11:21:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12595","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"glad you brought that up, we weren't 100% sure what the best approach would be so we wanted the ning group to help come up with a solution. we discussed a left nav search link that takes you to a custom search page or a search box in the header. A lightboxed search even came up.\n\nWe'd like to hear what this group suggests. thoughts?","createdDate":"2010-10-14T01:55:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12594","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Luis -- just noticed that you don't have a placeholder for a search box.\n\nYes, there is a search ncsu link in the brand bar, but there will need to be one for the individual site using this template.","createdDate":"2010-10-12T12:59:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12592","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I'm running into problems with Firefox and the branding bar when I try tabbing my way through the document (I'm looking at the two column with horizontal navigation). When I load the page and start tabbing I see the entire branding bar outlined, then a vertical dotted line right after NC State University brick. If I immediately hit tab again there is no response but if I wait ~5 seconds before tabbing then I see Campus Directory outlined. For this 5 seconds something is eating keystrokes. Continuing to press tab without waiting for the \"timeout\" never gets the focus to move. IE 8 doesn't do this. I haven't tried Opera or Chrome.\n\nOnce I wait the 5 seconds I can tab and I see Libraries, MyPack Portal, Campus Map and Search NCSU.EDU each in turn receive focus and and become outlined. After that nothing is seen to receive focus on the screen -- nothing is outlined in the site navigation bar as it is tabbed through until you apparently get to Industry Info when the drop down opens up. Tabbing though that shows the links to be underlined. You need to have something like a:hover, a:focus { text-decoration: underline; } for the menu items. It's not accessible without this visual indication of focus. Your side links for Facebook and Twitter lose their underline when hovered over but have no visual indication of focus via tabbing either. Neither do the links at the bottom of the page.\n\nDisabling javascript stills allows the Industry Info drop down to show with the mouse but it is completely lost with the keyboard. Tabbing through the document with javascript disabled never causes the drop down to show. I think this is an accessibility issue as well.\n\nThe Colour Contrast Analyzer plugin for Firefox doesn't show any issues with that page. Most things validate to AAA level with a few at AA level for \"small\" text.\n\nI haven't looked at any of the other pages.","createdDate":"2010-10-08T13:57:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12590","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"Next step is for Web Communications to release all of the template source files to any ning members who are interested in helping us test it. Please contact me directly (luis_chacon@ncsu.edu) or post a comment if you'd like to be a 'beta tester'.\n\nWe're aware there might be accessibility concerns with the drop down menu. We picked the <a href=\"http://users.tpg.com.au/j_birch/plugins/superfish/\" target=\"_blank\">jQuery plugin superfish</a> since it has keyboard accessibility built in. We'd appreciate any feedback and/or suggestions on how we can adjust superfish to make sure it's 100% accessible.","createdDate":"2010-10-08T02:06:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12588","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"sorry about that, the rss widget page should be available to everyone now. I do wonder if we should wrap it for just NCSU or just leave it wide open. We do plan to have a bit more info on this page, officially this tool is still in \"beta\".\n\nAs we discussed in the meet up, we'd love other groups to help develop other flavors of the templates. We appreciate OIT Design's willingness to help develop a Drupal theme, it should be a very valuable resource for the web developer community. As I mentioned Web Communications plans on releasing a Wordpress theme that will compliment the drupal theme.","createdDate":"2010-10-08T01:41:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12579","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"would like to be able to see the RSS widget configurator ... but it seems i'm not allowed. *sniff*.\n\nThe templates look clean and useful, and I'll be particularly interested in getting a hold of a WordPress &amp; Drupal version of these templates. We (OIT Design) are routinely asked for exactly this type of thing, but we haven't had anything to provide as far as an \"official university template.\" But...if you can provide these two common CMS themes, then I think there'll be a lot of very happy people.\n\nSo i guess the final question is...how do we get our hands on the starter files?","createdDate":"2010-10-07T18:28:09.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12568","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"Qualtrics Survey instrument","description":"I received a survey from <a href=\"http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/north-carolina-state-university/\">http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/north-carolina-state-university/</a>.\u00a0 Is this a service for campus to use?\u00a0 Any information on who, when, why and how it was acquired? <br/>","createdDate":"2010-10-06T15:26:18.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-10-29T14:23:29.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12660","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"We're (ECU) are providing Qualtrics to all our our students, faculty, and staff. We've got the unlimited plan (unlimited users, unlimited surveys). It's an amazing system, and I say this as someone who has written a custom web survey tool (and understand the complexities of what they've accomplished). They've got really nice import/export, excellent panel creation, ridiculous numbers of types of questions, and an impressive completely web 2.0 based editing system. They have toll free telephone support, web support, and we defer pretty much all support to them. Your Qualtrics inbox talks about their webinars, both for new and advanced users. As you would see in an Ebay rating A+++++.","createdDate":"2010-10-29T14:23:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12584","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I did a quick survey in a couple of minutes. Easy peasy. I'm liking it so far.\n<a href=\"http://ncsu.qualtrics.com//SE/?SID=SV_ba5JqzjwnFGuMQs\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsu.qualtrics.com//SE/?SID=SV_ba5JqzjwnFGuMQs</a>","createdDate":"2010-10-07T18:36:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12582","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"looks like a nifty little $_GET method of making it look like it's all customized for you.\n\nSee for a couple of easy typed in examples....\n\n<a href=\"http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/western-carolina-university\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/western-carolina-university</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/university-of-north-carolina-at-charlotte/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.qualtrics.com/academic-solutions/university-of-north-carolina-at-charlotte/</a>","createdDate":"2010-10-07T18:33:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12574","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I received mail from the contact/licensing person for this app. Intend to follow up with her.\nNancy Whelchel, Ph.D.\nAssistant Director for Survey Research\nUniversity Planning and Analysis","createdDate":"2010-10-06T17:01:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12571","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I dont think its OIT. At least I haven't heard of it...","createdDate":"2010-10-06T16:52:19.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12555","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"OIT Lunch & Learn: Mobile Devices & Applications: Tap Into What's New","description":"This is a follow-up to an earlier discussion we had (back in May) that\nwas a lot of fun, while being informative, too. Basically, everyone\nwill share cool apps that they use or are aware of for their various\ndevices.<br/>\n<br/>\nIt's during lunch this coming Tuesday, from 12-1:00 in 216 Scott Hall. Read more information or sign-up: <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/event/lunch-learn-mobile-devices-applications-tap-whats-new\">http://oit.ncsu.edu/event/lunch-learn-mobile-devices-applications-tap-whats-new</a>","createdDate":"2010-09-24T18:16:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-24T18:16:31.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12552","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"Photo gallery tools","description":"What do people use for creating photo galleries at sites, including slideshows, text annotation, etc.?\u00a0 We have a beta version of an app built a couple of years ago, <a href=\"http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/packsnaps/\">http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/packsnaps/</a> but at a crossroads with it.\u00a0 We are pointing people to Flikr and Picasa, but, of course, the photos end up residing off site.\u00a0 Is this a problem or not?\u00a0 Do people in Drupal run galleries?\u00a0 In any case, I welcome solution ideas that individual users can deploy themselves.\u00a0 <br/>","createdDate":"2010-09-24T13:17:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-10-04T14:54:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12565","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Professionally, I haven't had to to this for anyone.\n\nPersonally, I run zenphoto <a href=\"http://www.zenphoto.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.zenphoto.org/</a> on my LAMP server <a href=\"http://server.brabec.com/zen/\" target=\"_blank\">http://server.brabec.com/zen/</a>","createdDate":"2010-10-04T14:54:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12561","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"If you're wanting to do local hosting, then I'd put in a plug for WordPress 3.0 and the many image handling plugins available. We have one called <a href=\"http://alexrabe.de/wordpress-plugins/nextgen-gallery/\" target=\"_blank\">NextGEN Gallery</a> that's pretty impressive. Not to mention the countless themes (many even free) available that turn WordPress into a professional caliber portfolio site.","createdDate":"2010-09-28T21:01:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12543","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"HTML 5 is not a singularity","description":"<div><img style=\"padding: 5px; float:left;\" src=\"discussions/13-xlg_champion_0.jpg?width=209\"/>The future is starting to arrive! \u00a0But one of the problems I've seen recently is that people talk about the arrival / implementation of some of the HTML 5 features as this singularity that will change the course of history forever and change everything everyone knows about web development.</div>\n<div><br/></div>\n<div>The happy (sad?) fact of the matter is that this just isn't true.<br/><div><br/></div>\n<div>There was a really nice article on Smashing summarizing the history of HTML4 -&gt; XHTML 1.0 -&gt; HTML 5 and debunking a lot of these myths about HTML5. \u00a0Rather than rehash it here, I'll let you go peruse it. \u00a0Here's the link: <a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2010/09/23/html5-the-facts-and-the-myths/\">HTML 5: The Facts and the Myths</a>.</div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2010-09-23T15:07:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-23T15:09:05.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12507","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Students scheduling appointments with faculty","description":"<div>\u00a0</div>\n<div>I've had a few requests lately, and many a time in the past for that matter, for an online tool to facilitate students signing up for time slots on a faculty's calendar.\u00a0 This is for advising, mock\ninterviews and lots of other stuff I imagine would apply too.</div>\n<div>\u00a0</div>\n<div>Do any of you know\u00a0 if there are any options available right now?\u00a0 Or would we have to use something third party?\u00a0 Just curious especially with the students moving to\nGoogle, maybe something has changed.</div>\n<div>\u00a0</div>\nIf anyone on campus is using something or built something to facilitate this, I would love to hear about it.<br/><br/>Thanks.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-09-21T17:42:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-22T13:49:59.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12527","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"We used Doodle to set up our individual meetings at the beginning of this year. Just need to get people to list their availability for for a week or so and then schedule their appointments so that everyone gets a time that works for them. Worked out beautifully.","createdDate":"2010-09-22T13:50:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12525","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Well, you could use Doodle for this if you say to a student, hey, only pick one slot.\n\nBlackboard Vista and Moodle have sign up options too, but again, not integrated with a faculty calendar.\n\nMy first suggestion to the people who ask is indeed paper/pencil or use the phone :), KISS method.","createdDate":"2010-09-22T13:23:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12523","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"In my class last semester, we had to schedule a time to meet with the instructor, and we use a signup sheet that we passed around the room. I know it's pretty high-tech, but most people seemed to understand how to use the system. :-P\n\nBut seriously, we use Doodle to schedule the accessibility committee meetings, and that seems to work pretty well, but that's not really the same situation. That's just picking a single time that works for everyone, not a bunch of times for individual meetings.\n\nI don't know of anything other than a Google calendar like Nick suggested that would work very well. Seems like that's the obvious and simplest solution.","createdDate":"2010-09-22T13:10:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12517","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Yes! &lt;chant&gt;Do it!&lt;/chant&gt;\n\nUntil that day... any other thoughts? People using other stuff? <a href=\"http://doodle.com\" target=\"_blank\">Doodle.com</a> is a really simple non-fancy solution. Any other more elegant/fancy solutions out there? Anything that is working fine for someone?","createdDate":"2010-09-21T20:18:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12514","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"This was a subject brought up in the NexGen (employee email) committee, and there was a pretty obvious solution:\n\n1. The faculty member (if they had a Google account), could simply create a sub-calendar\n2. Give permission to whoever they want (public, specific people)\n3. Let permitted people request appointments, that can then be approved, denied etc\n\nYou can set up free busy times, as well as work hours on google calendar, so, assuming everyone is on the same system (employees AND students), then this type of situation would be as easy as employees scheduling appointments with other employees....something that's been going on for years.\n\nSeems like there would be no need to \"build\" something if we could just all get on the same system.","createdDate":"2010-09-21T18:24:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12489","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"TriPUG meetup on Zend Framework","description":"I think I had posted this to the mailing list, but wanted to post here too. \u00a0I am going to be presenting at the TriPUG (triangle php user group) meetup next week about Zend Framework. \u00a0There had been a few requests to talk about that at our monthly meetups, but for those interested you should come out and network with some of your fellow PHP developers.<div><br/></div>\n<div>If you wanna go, please RSVP at\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/mysql-144/calendar/14671348/\">http://www.meetup.com/mysql-144/calendar/14671348/</a>\u00a0. Free food too :)</div>","createdDate":"2010-09-16T14:19:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-17T12:51:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12501","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm usually busy on Tuesdays. Just wanted to see if it's more or less like the TriLUG meetings which always seem to fall on a Thursday.","createdDate":"2010-09-17T12:51:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12499","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"This is the first one we have done it Raleigh. The other ones seem to be spread out on other days. Is tuesday a bad day?","createdDate":"2010-09-16T17:54:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12492","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Are the meetings typically on Tuesday?","createdDate":"2010-09-16T17:20:41.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12472","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"New Go Links App ready for testing...","description":"After a long, long, long delay, I've been able to finish off some pieces of the new Go Links Application, and get it out for testing.<br/><br/>If you're interested in helping me find bugs, or things that could be tweaked, wrap in and test the new app here:<br/><br/><a href=\"http://go.oitdesign.ncsu.edu\">http://go.oitdesign.ncsu.edu</a><br/><br/>You can submit bugs/issues/notes here:<a href=\"http://go.oitdesign.ncsu.edu/oitdesignprojects\"></a><br/><br/><a href=\"http://go.oitdesign.ncsu.edu/oitdesigntickets\">http://go.oitdesign.ncsu.edu/oitdesigntickets</a><br/><br/>.....or just email me at nick_young at ncsu dot edu :-)<br/><br/>Obviously, the links on this version of Go Links will go away after a period of time, because I just needed a place to open this up for testing.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-09-15T12:21:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-16T12:52:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12486","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thank Nick! That makes a lot of sense.","createdDate":"2010-09-16T12:52:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12484","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The first part is easy.....I don't see the tag name you used and shared with me. I only see the links that are shared with me, and the fact that it was you who did it (username). They are not organized by tag name.\n\nI have not built a mechanism to remove yourself from having something shared with you. That's an interesting thought, and something I might build in. I will not build in the capability for you to remove other people from a tag that may be shared with you though. That's the owner of the tag's responsibility.\n\nI guess it might be possible for me to create a process of transferring ownership of a tag though, which could keep all the links shared within it. That's something for me to think about.\n\nWhen a link's owner is changed, it is removed from all tags that the previous owner may have added it to. It is then the new owner's responsibility to reshare that link in whatever way they see fit. The tags are specific to the person who created them, no one else.","createdDate":"2010-09-15T19:51:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12483","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I guess I mean: If you have a tag called \"Awesome Links\" and I have a tag called \"Awesome Links\" what happens when I share my tag with you? It seems like then you'd have two tags called \"Awesome Links\". So when you get the dialog to add a new link that you have determined to be awesome, how do you know to which tag to assign it? (Assuming they both show up in the list). Can you remove yourself from a tag that was shared with you? I see that I can unshare tags from people that I shared. Can you add/remove other people from tags that were shared with you? Or will you need to recreate tags and retag the links for links associated with a tag that you did not create but that you now control (likely due to the original tag creator leaving the university)?\n\nSorry, just applying problems that I ran into with some external applications for transferring ownership after a separation.","createdDate":"2010-09-15T19:40:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12481","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"tags are not globally unique. They all have their own ID number, so you can have Faculty Support Links, and I can have Faculty Support Links....everyone can have Faculty Support Links! Fun for the whole family.\n\nArbitration will be handled like any other domain naming space issue. There will be a remedy queue for conflicts that cannot be resolved by the parties concerned, and administrators of the application/service can re-own/disable/delete any link in the system.","createdDate":"2010-09-15T15:40:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12478","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Are tags globally unique? If I take a tag, does that mean that no one else can use it? How were you planning to handle arbitration for links like \"Faculty Support\"?","createdDate":"2010-09-15T14:53:24.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12470","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Buying a domain name","description":"A faculty member is considering purchasing a domain and asked me this:<br/><br/>\"1.Do you recommend the privacy option (ie, not look-up-able on WHOIS)?\n<div><br/></div>\n<div>2.Do you think <a href=\"http://domain.com/\">domain.com</a> and <a href=\"http://namecheap.com/\">namecheap.com</a> look legit?</div>\n<div>I don't know how to tell.\"<br/><br/>I don't either... anyone care to comment on either of these questions?<br/><br/>thanks..<br/></div>","createdDate":"2010-09-15T12:07:20.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-15T12:47:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12475","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Just my opinions, so take it for what its worth:\n\n1) Definitely. It's so much nicer to not get the email/snail mail spam from those domain buyer people.\n\n2) I'd either buy my domain from my hosting provider or buy from one of the main dudes (godaddy, register.com, etc) unless you are savy enough to know how to update DNS info.","createdDate":"2010-09-15T12:47:17.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12462","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Card Sorting Software","description":"Hey folks,<br/><br/>Anyone out there have any experience using any IA software?\u00a0 Specifically card sorting software?\u00a0 I have been playing with <a href=\"http://www.optimalworkshop.com/optimalsort.htm\">http://www.optimalworkshop.com/optimalsort.htm</a> a bit, but wonder if there are other/better tools out there.\u00a0 OptimalSort is nice because it lets you easily send your card sorting exercise out to your audience or whoever and let them try.<br/><br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-09-10T13:11:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-17T15:36:08.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12505","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I can see how the dialogue would be quite valuable, but I'd be concerned about influencing the participant. Instead, I'd prefer to hear their stream of conscious rather than actually have a back and forth with them to avoid explaining things which are supposed to be self explanatory.","createdDate":"2010-09-17T15:36:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12503","contributorName":"abecrystal","description":"Call me old school, but I actually like doing card sorting in person with real, physical cards (index cards or Post-It's). I find the dialogue with the participant is often just as valuable as the results of the sort...","createdDate":"2010-09-17T14:02:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12468","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I think it definitely helps to play around with how the information should be organized in the menus of your site. I also think it's interesting to hear from your target audiences about how they'd organize the site's menus - tells you where they would expect to find things. And yeah, I think you have to choose your target audience and then select people who are members of that audience.. then take the results with a grain of salt! :)\n\nJust something I've been playing around with lately, I admit that I haven't actually given this a full-fledged try out yet..","createdDate":"2010-09-13T13:47:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12465","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I had not heard of this before. Do you find card sorting to be particularly effective?\n\nMy concerns would be accurately identifying my audience. It seems like if I select from a population (or allow the population to self select) I will end up with results that are skewed towards my expected results (or skewed towards squeaky wheels).","createdDate":"2010-09-13T13:42:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12443","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Version Control on Campus?","description":"We are heavy users of Subversion, but I was just wondering if anyone else used Git or (gasp) CVS?\u00a0 Just curious as to what people were using.<br/><br/>If you don't use version control, what is preventing you from doing so?\u00a0 Have you given it a shot and just didn't continue?\u00a0 Maybe you just aren't aware of it or what it is?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-09-02T16:08:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-09-02T19:43:23.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12450","contributorName":"3af3czr863egr","description":"Personally: git, for everything right now. I used svn until about 2 years ago. I would <i>never</i> start a project without either, ever.","createdDate":"2010-09-02T19:43:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12446","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"svn internally\ncvs for some external things (such as open source projects)","createdDate":"2010-09-02T16:46:42.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12374","contributorName":"abecrystal","title":"Last chance for discounted early-bird tickets to \"UX 101\"","description":"<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size:large;\"><i>Early bird registration for\u00a0</i><a href=\"http://morebetterlabs.com/ux101\" target=\"_blank\"><b><i>the UX 101 workshop</i></b></a><i>\u00a0ends TODAY, Monday 8/16/10.</i></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\"><br/></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">UX 101 is an introduction to how we think about and design great user experiences, including process, research, design, and practical \"how-to\" tips. The workshop is ideal for anyone who wants to contribute to UX, but doesn't have academic or professional training in the field.\u00a0</span></div>\n<div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\"><br/></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">At UX 101, we'll be talking about...</span></div>\n<div><ul>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">The Big Picture: What defines a good user experience? \u00a0[<a href=\"http://blog.morebetterlabs.com/post/862661990/ux-101-sneak-peek-1-what-is-bad-user-experience\" target=\"_blank\">sneak preview of \"Good vs. Bad User Experiences\"</a>]</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">Strategy: Product Planning, Prioritization, Brainstorming [<a href=\"http://blog.morebetterlabs.com/post/893541013/ux-101-sneak-peek-2-ux-strategy-and-the-power-of\" target=\"_blank\">sneak preview of \"UX Strategy\"</a>]</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">Research: Interviews, Data Analysis, Usability Testing [<a href=\"http://blog.morebetterlabs.com/post/942205214/ux-101-sneak-peek-3-ux-research-and-the-power-of\" target=\"_blank\">sneak preview of \"UX Research\"</a>]</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">Design: Sketching, Storyboards, Workflows, Prototyping [<a href=\"http://blog.morebetterlabs.com/post/948147838/ux-101-sneak-peek-4-user-experience-design-and-the\" target=\"_blank\">sneak preview of \"UX Design\"</a>]</span></li>\n</ul>\n<div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\"><br/></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\">For those who couldn't make it to the \"UX 101\" event in July, I recommend checking out the slides and the 1-page \"worksheet\" handout -- it will give you some quick ideas, activities, and resources from the event...</span></div>\n<div><ul>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: small;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; border-collapse: collapse;\"><a href=\"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-worksheet.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(66, 99, 171);\">http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-worksheet.pdf</a></span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; border-collapse: collapse;\"><a href=\"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-slides.ppsx\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(66, 99, 171);\">http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-slides.ppsx</a></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div><br/></div>\n<div><br/></div>\n<div>Two ways to save on the workshop:</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div><ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://triupa.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Join TriUPA</a>, and\u00a0<b>save $100</b>\u00a0with discount code \"triupa\" --\u00a0<a href=\"http://ux101.eventbrite.com/?discount=triupa\" target=\"_blank\">http://ux101.eventbrite.com/?discount=triupa</a></li>\n<li><b>Save $50</b>\u00a0with discount code \"ncsu-webdev\" --\u00a0<a href=\"http://ux101.eventbrite.com/?discount=ncsu-webdev\">http://ux101.eventbrite.com/?discount=ncsu-webdev</a></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<div><br/></div>\n<div>Any questions?</div>\n<div><ul>\n<li><a href=\"mailto:ux101@morebetterlabs.com\" target=\"_blank\">ux101@morebetterlabs.com</a></li>\n<li>Abe --\u00a0919.593.6129</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div>Hope to see some Lean Startup folks at the workshop!</div>\n<div><br/></div>\n<div>Best,</div>\n<div>--Abe</div>","createdDate":"2010-08-16T16:23:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-16T16:25:51.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12340","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"testing","description":"testing","createdDate":"2010-08-12T14:24:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-12T14:56:18.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12346","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Worked. :-)","createdDate":"2010-08-12T14:56:19.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12322","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Custom ncsu.edu domain for this site?","description":"With the new Ning features, one of the abilities we get it so create a custom domain for our ning site.\u00a0 Something like <a href=\"http://mynetwork.ncsu.edu\">http://mynetwork.ncsu.edu</a> which would point here.\u00a0 What do you guys think it should be?\u00a0 Options I was thinking were:<br/><br/><a href=\"http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu\">http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu</a><br/><br/><a href=\"http://webdev.ncsu.edu\">http://webdev.ncsu.edu</a><br/><br/><a href=\"http://developers.ncsu.edu\">http://developers.ncsu.edu</a><br/><br/>I'm leaning towards webdevelopers.ncsu.edu but I wanted to see if anyone had a strong opinion otherwise.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-08-11T18:04:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-25T22:37:20.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12427","contributorName":"2iy3irh599qo1","description":"My suggestions (in order)\n\n1. devnet.ncsu.edu\n2. webdev.ncsu.edu\n3. wolfweb.ncsu.edu\n\nIt would be great if we can keep it less than or equal to 8 letters in size.","createdDate":"2010-08-25T22:37:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12383","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"webdevissupercool.ncsu.edu? Too long?","createdDate":"2010-08-19T16:58:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12373","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Getting approval for the domain name can easily be solved. I'm not worried about that at all. The cookies thing is the only thing that concerns me really. And if it in any way could compromise security, then I think we can just get a simple redirect for <a href=\"http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu</a> -&gt; <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com</a> and not use any of the domain masking stuff provided by Ning.","createdDate":"2010-08-16T13:25:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12372","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'd defer to Charles on this. He posted some of his concerns below.","createdDate":"2010-08-16T13:22:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12370","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"There's also the question of clearing a new .ncsu.edu subdomain with the appropriate committee. I am also a little nervous about giving WRAP cookies to ning. Legal would have to be involved. Fun for the whole family.","createdDate":"2010-08-15T23:45:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12367","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"that's what we do for the Google Apps @ NC State service ---- point CNAME records to our DNS for resolution and verification that we own the domain. A Records aren't that much different, so i don't see a problem from a policy perspective.","createdDate":"2010-08-13T13:13:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12366","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Yeah, part of what we got when we upgraded was the ability to lose all the ads. I think we can even create our own ads if there is something we want to promote, but I'm not sure how all that works.\n\nDo you think it is a deal breaker to point a subdomain here as a DNS record?","createdDate":"2010-08-13T13:07:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12365","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My guess is that once you set the A record and let Ning know about the domain you want it to try and masquerade as, Ning will update all of the links to keep it within that ncsu.edu domain. If this were the case, Ning would be receiving any base domain (ncsu.edu) cookies. Thankfully there don't appear to be advertisements, because that seems like a can of worms itself.","createdDate":"2010-08-13T13:02:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12364","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"It's actually a DNS mapping it looks like. More information here:\n\n<a href=\"http://help.ning.com/cgi-bin/ning.cfg/php/enduser/std_adp.php?p_faqid=2920\" target=\"_blank\">http://help.ning.com/cgi-bin/ning.cfg/php/enduser/std_adp.php?p_faqid=2920</a>\n\nI'm not sure the ramifications of cookies though. We can certainly do a redirect without Ning.","createdDate":"2010-08-13T12:45:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12362","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Is it a redirect, or will all of the pages be served out of the ncsu.edu domain? I ask because I wouldn't really want all of my ncsu.edu cookies given to ning (i.e. WRAP).","createdDate":"2010-08-13T12:42:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12359","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'd like to avoid \"ning\" being in the URL in case something happens and we have to move away from it (like if they go out of business or something).","createdDate":"2010-08-13T12:27:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12356","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"webdev is short and easy, webdevelopers is more formal but longer. Personally, I can be happy with any of the three.","createdDate":"2010-08-13T12:25:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12353","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"How about ning.ncsu.edu/web ? Then we could organize all ncsu ning sites ?","createdDate":"2010-08-12T19:43:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12343","contributorName":"0tsgrb8k0z34k","description":"I think webdev.ncsu.edu is short and easy to type out... but if we're going the more formal route then webdevelopers.ncsu.edu","createdDate":"2010-08-12T14:52:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12338","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"webdev.ncsu.edu, but no strong feeling against <a href=\"http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://webdevelopers.ncsu.edu</a>","createdDate":"2010-08-12T13:03:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12332","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"My .....\n\n1st choice: webdevelopers.ncsu.edu\n2nd choice: webdev.ncsu.edu\n3rd choice: ncsuwebdev.ncsu.edu","createdDate":"2010-08-11T20:45:32.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12315","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"NCSU Google Sites","description":"Some of us staff/faculty do not yet have NCSU Google accounts, but we're burning to know how <a href=\"http://sites.ncsu.edu\">http://sites.ncsu.edu</a> will be used for campus web sites (maybe a topic for a webdev meetup?).\u00a0 We have experience embedding a Google site or two in university URLs, e.g., <a href=\"http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/ispe/\">http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/ispe/</a> is really at <a>http://sites.google.com/site/ispencsuchapter/</a>, but I assume that there will eventually be some policy for governing NCSU Google web URLs, maybe? \u00a0 In any case, what's the plan for pointing people to this new service and managing it?\u00a0 Will we have standard templates or template elements?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-08-06T19:17:21.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-19T18:17:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12390","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'm on what is now affectionately called \"The Google Apps @ NC State Team,\" but please qualify everything I'm about to say with a \"<i>nothing has been decided yet</i>.\"\n\nI think the obvious benefit of Google sites is that it has the potential to replace a lot of the functionality of the www4 space that exists now. I am not knowledgeable about everything that the www4 space can do, but from what some people have said, Google sites is not have complete feature parity.\n\nHaving said that, I am a believer that Google Sites can and even should take the place of a lot of what www4 serves up now, just so we can take advantage of more of the benefits of outsourcing (bandwidth, maintenance, revision history, sharing etc).\n\nRight now, our policy regarding Google sites is the same as the policy for web content at NCSU, with the exception that if you have a Google Apps account, you can self-provision a site. Site owners are still governed by the existing acceptable use policies and all that lovely legal language.\n\nNaming conventions become difficult, because we currently don't have a way to proactively reserve or restrict the names (and therefore URLs) for sites. So...the presiding wisdom in cases of misuse, or a when site named \"sites.google.com/a/ncsu.edu/chancellor\" contains objectionable material, or material that has nothing to do with the chancellor, we (OIT/ the service owner) reserve the right to remove or replace that the site.\n\nIn future, we hope to develop or take advantage of tools that will allow us to monitor these sites, while still allowing the self-service features that make it such an attractive service.\n\nLike any service, it will not fit the needs of every single audience, but it will meet a lot of them. So....i think that we can and should move more content to Google Sites, and in the process cut down on the burden we place on our internal infrastructure.\n\nI'll be happy to answer any and all Google-related questions...but i might need some time to get back to you on some topics :-) ..... even if the answer is \"we don't know yet.\"","createdDate":"2010-08-19T18:17:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12388","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"You mean the google committee? I really have no idea...that's a Nick question I think.","createdDate":"2010-08-19T17:52:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12379","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Jason - do you know if notes/meeting minutes from this committee are published anywhere?","createdDate":"2010-08-19T16:54:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12336","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I asked our Engineers' Council, which oversees all engineering student organizations, to review OrgSync last year, and they pretty much panned it. They are generally content to use their AFS lockers and a shared Google calendar to do most of what they need to do, but they still have problems with individual site design and finding someone in the org willing and able to manage the web site. I think a Google sites backend would probably work for many of our orgs at <a href=\"http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/orgs\" target=\"_blank\">http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/orgs</a>, with an easier learning curve and handoff year-to-year. If you need students to look into Google sites, let me know. I can ask our Engineers' Council to help.","createdDate":"2010-08-12T12:30:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12335","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"OrgSync is one of those things that sounds like a great idea until you actually try to implement it for groups who have very different needs. It's very much a one-size-fits-some type of application and a good many student groups are pushing back. I'd be surprised if it gets any more popular than it currently is given its limitations.","createdDate":"2010-08-12T12:07:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12328","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Absolutely. And student organization sites. I'm not convinced that <a href=\"http://ncsu.orgsync.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsu.orgsync.com/</a> (OrgSync) is going to catch on.","createdDate":"2010-08-11T18:43:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12325","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Let me preface my comments by saying that I'm speaking with absolutely no knowledge about the actual discussions going on with this. It's just what I'd like to see.\n\nTo me, it's the perfect opportunity to get rid of www4 space both for faculty/staff and for students. The biggest argument I have heard to keep www4 space is for easy URL access to a file. I know some people still use it for posting personal websites as well. However, Google Docs now lets you upload any file type you want and share it easily. And web hosting is so cheap now and full of features, www4 doesn't make sense to host a website.\n\nIf we were able to move that direction, I think to try to do too much governing with it would be a mistake. I'd think that URL's would be handled like www4 ones are now where it would be something like <a href=\"http://sites.ncsu.edu/jfaustin/\" target=\"_blank\">http://sites.ncsu.edu/jfaustin/</a>.\n\nBasically, I feel like Google Sites is the perfect opportunity to replace www4 with a better, cheaper (free), outsourced service, while still providing everyone with an account the ability to quickly put up a web page.\n\nJust my $0.02.","createdDate":"2010-08-11T18:17:48.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12282","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","title":"Wibiya Toolbar","description":"I received a \"request\" to look at the Wibiya Toolbar <a href=\"http://www.wibiya.com/\">http://www.wibiya.com/</a> based on its use on the Admissions site <a href=\"http://admissions.ncsu.edu/why-ncstate/visit/\">http://admissions.ncsu.edu/why-ncstate/visit/</a>\u00a0 Has anyone used this? Seems a bit pricey for a piece of javascript.\u00a0 We currently aren't using anything like Drupal *yet* so I don't have anything to really compare it with.\u00a0 <br/>","createdDate":"2010-08-03T19:36:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-19T17:03:49.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12386","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Wonder how many days it will be before someone comes a knocking on my door asking for this too. Seems like this could be something that eventually could be created/maintained by campus-level web people - much like the top \"utility bar.\" Anyway, thanks for sharing.","createdDate":"2010-08-19T17:03:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12291","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"That seems a bit overpriced for a div that's fixed to the bottom of the page. You could fairly easily create one that looks nice and doesn't load so much junk from another domain. Plus, you could make it fit with your site's design.\n\nThis of course assumes that you have the web resources available. Hiring someone would obviously be more expensive than that.","createdDate":"2010-08-04T13:12:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12288","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"Ranges from $4.95 - 29.95 per MONTH.","createdDate":"2010-08-04T12:44:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12285","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I personally find those things incredibly annoying from a user perspective. Maybe I'm missing the cost somewhere? How much is it?","createdDate":"2010-08-04T11:45:27.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12266","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"University Web Sites: An InfoGraphic","description":"Courtesy of XKCD:<br/><br/>Permalink: <a href=\"http://xkcd.com/773/\">http://xkcd.com/773/</a><br/><br/><p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"http://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/university_website.png\"/></p>\n<br/>","createdDate":"2010-07-30T12:29:23.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-04T19:16:04.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12305","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Agreed. When we had the branding folks over for a presentation, we asked about the possibility of a Full Name version of the branding bar. They seemed receptive, but I've been so busy with preparing for the Fall, I haven't checked to see if they have that available.\n\nFor what it's worth, ncsu.edu has the full name at the very top of the page.","createdDate":"2010-08-04T19:16:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12302","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Can't help but laugh at the intersection, \"Full name of school.\" I wish we DID use the university's full name rather than a graphical logo. Abbreviations don't communicate to people worldwide and are always supposed to be written out, at least on first use. Plus, clear references are better for search engine optimization.\n\nYes, these things needed to be said.","createdDate":"2010-08-04T15:32:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12296","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"Spot on!","createdDate":"2010-08-04T15:10:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12294","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Things that I would look for would definitely not include Social Networking tools, but that might be different from the norm.","createdDate":"2010-08-04T13:18:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12277","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"But they forgot to add the Social Networking tools :) But which side would they go on? hmmmm","createdDate":"2010-08-03T19:31:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12273","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"For those people who want to see the alt text joke (or don't know about it):\n\n\"People go to the website because they can't wait for the next alumni magazine, right? What do you mean, you want a campus map? One of our students made one as a CS class project back in '01! You can click to zoom and everything!\"","createdDate":"2010-08-02T13:19:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12269","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I saw that this morning. Pretty darn accurate. Maybe they will do one about the creation of university websites...that should be interesting.","createdDate":"2010-07-30T14:12:46.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12221","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"We are now Ning Plus","description":"I don't expect much to change, but we have now paid for Ning for the next year on the Ning Plus plan.\u00a0 OIT provided the funds to do that, so that is a good thing.\u00a0 I'm going to make my way through some of the new features in the next few days.\u00a0 Just wanted to let you know.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-07-21T16:04:06.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-07-23T12:58:28.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12254","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thank you Jason (and all the other folks) for continuing to develop this community. It's so nice to not be a lonely island. :)","createdDate":"2010-07-23T12:58:29.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12196","contributorName":"abecrystal","title":"Slides from user experience  talk","description":"Thanks all for coming out, and sharing your perspectives on user experience in the academic web context.<div><br/></div>\n<div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\">I've posted the handout and slides online for anyone who is interested...</span></div>\n<div><ul>\n<li style=\"margin-left: 15px;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\"><a href=\"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-worksheet.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 204);\">http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-worksheet.pdf</a></span></li>\n<li style=\"margin-left: 15px;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\"><a href=\"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-slides.ppsx\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 204);\">http://dl.dropbox.com/u/596773/MoreBetterLabs_UX-101-slides.ppsx</a></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\"><br/></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\">\"UX 101\" workshop information:</span></div>\n<div><ul>\n<li style=\"margin-left: 15px;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\"><a href=\"http://morebetterlabs.com/ux101/\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 204);\">http://morebetterlabs.com/ux101/</a></span></li>\n<li style=\"margin-left: 15px;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\">Save $50 if you register before August 15th! \u00a0Discount code:\u00a0<b>NCSU-WEBDEV</b></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\"><br/></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, sans-serif; border-collapse: collapse;\">Let me know if you have any questions!</span></div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2010-07-07T19:54:18.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-07-07T19:54:18.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12136","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"QR Codes","description":"I've received this question on <a href=\"http://twitter.com/ncsu_oit\">@ncsu_oit</a>: <span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"status-content\"><span class=\"entry-content\">\"Do you all use QR codes? Do you think they will catch on on-campus?\"<br/><br/>Is anybody using or considering them? I'd like to give some kind of response.<br/><br/>Thanks!<br/>John Martin<br/>Office of Information Technology<br/>Outreach, Communications, and Consulting<br/>Information News Services<br/>(919) 513-1196<br/></span></span></span>","createdDate":"2010-06-11T13:38:07.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-03T19:33:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12280","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"I went to a conf this summer and saw a good deal of QR codes on some of the paper literature that was being handed out. Might be an interesting thing to add to business cards or any of our print material for our colleges and units.","createdDate":"2010-08-03T19:33:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12195","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Neat. I guess that explains why Zebra Crossing is trying to push formatting details as well. It would be fairly complicated to disseminate information if there wasn't a de facto standard out there for how the data should be interpreted.","createdDate":"2010-07-07T17:42:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12194","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Sorry for the late reply. It will do one of a few things. You can encode various types of information, so it'll either read that info, or if it's a link it'll take you to that link, or ask you if you want to dial the phone number if it finds a phone number, etc. It just depends on the type of information that is stored and how the particular scanning application responds to that particular type of info. But basically you can do contact info, calendar events, telephone numbers, geolocations, links, email address, text messages, and a few other things.","createdDate":"2010-07-07T13:09:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12149","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm not sure what you mean by \"check into class\". If you mean for attendance, we can't even trust them to not sign other peoples names let alone have them scan multiple QR codes. :)\n\n@Garrison, thanks for the links on uses and creation of QR codes. It seems like a lot of planning has to go into these. Ensuring that links remain relevant, preventing \"valid concert ticket\" code generation, and encouraging users to \"click\" your \"links\" in the first place. They kept it rather tame when they considered the possibility of rick-rolling. I fear that a new wave of otherwise unidentifiable posters with only QR codes featuring links to shock websites is incoming.\n\nWhen you snap a QR code, what does it do?","createdDate":"2010-06-14T13:23:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12146","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"We're considering building a web application that tracks information about our various pieces of hardware in engineering. You could theoretically embed a machine ID #, some contact info and other data into a QR code, print it out as a sticker and put it on something (like a laptop)...\n\nIf you're a business (like a restaurant) you could post a QR code in your window out front and passerby's could use their phone to quickly pull up reviews, a menu, or even 'check in' with foursquare...\n\n^ Which is actually an interesting thought... could students register their devices and scan a QR code to check into class? Hmmm...","createdDate":"2010-06-11T19:14:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12142","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I pretty much agree with Jonathan. It only seems to make any kind of sense as far as getting from real life things to information on the web. I know Android has native support for the QR codes, and there's a free iPhone app called Neo Reader that reads them, but I don't know what else.\n\nBut here's an article about 5 unique uses for QR codes: <a href=\"http://mashable.com/2009/01/07/qr-codes/\" target=\"_blank\">http://mashable.com/2009/01/07/qr-codes/</a>\n\nAnd here you can make your own: <a href=\"http://zxing.appspot.com/generator/\" target=\"_blank\">http://zxing.appspot.com/generator/</a>\n\nYou can also make them directly with Google's Charting APIs: <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/chart/docs/gallery/qr_codes.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://code.google.com/apis/chart/docs/gallery/qr_codes.html</a>","createdDate":"2010-06-11T16:12:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12139","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"First thought is: What's the point?\n\nSecond thought is: This seems like a way to easily get people from brick and mortar to the web. If they see a poster, or a sign if it has a QR code in one of the corners, it would make it easier for their mobile device to find out more information.\n\nThird thought is: What devices support this?\n\nFinal thought is: Is there any use for this on the web? It seems like clicking a link would be easier than having two phones so you can take a picture of the web on the other phone.","createdDate":"2010-06-11T15:00:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12038","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"CS5 and SVN","description":"So I've just downloaded a trial of CS5 for myself and I've been reading through the what's new material on Adobe's site (see <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/contribute/upgrade/?view=compare\">http://www.adobe.com/products/contribute/upgrade/?view=compare</a>).\u00a0 One thing I'm curious about is the SVN integration.\u00a0 I know that Dreamweaver has attempted <a href=\"http://mrmx.blogspot.com/2009/02/dreamweaver-cs4-subversion-suckage.html\">with mixed results</a> to incorporate Subversion, but this is the first I've seen with Contribute.\u00a0 Can anyone tell me what the advantage might be in using SVN over Contribute's built-in check-in and check-out plus rollbacks system?\u00a0 Might this only be appealing to folks who already using SVN as their primary version control system?<br/><br/>ps. CS5 has several other new features that look promising, like content types..<br/>","createdDate":"2010-06-09T17:40:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-06-10T13:00:36.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12128","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"SVN is a few million times better than CVS. Contribute's current system is probably similar to CVS except nonstandard. Honestly, I don't understand how incorporating Subversion support would be difficult. Rather than include their own versions, just include the Subversion installer which only runs if Subversion is not already installed. Then they just need to make calls to the command line utilities.\n<code>\nfunction delete_file(filename) {\n\u00a0\u00a0folder = basename(filename);\n\u00a0\u00a0if (file_exists(folder . '.svn')) {\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0exec('svn rm ' . filename);\n\u00a0\u00a0}\n\u00a0\u00a0// normal delete file code\n}\n</code>\n\nAlso, I'm not entirely sure that Contribute's current system isn't just a form of RCS, which would be a real problem if you have multiple versions of the website or a load balanced solution that isn't using a shared network mount. I tried to glean some information about it from <a href=\"http://blogs.adobe.com/contribute/\" target=\"_blank\">Adobe's Contribute Blog</a>, but it appears to be written by people who are unable to form complete sentences. FWIW, here's the <a href=\"http://blogs.adobe.com/contribute/2010/05/subversion_in_contribute_cs5.html\" target=\"_blank\">Contribute CS5 Subversion</a> post.","createdDate":"2010-06-10T13:00:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:12034","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Slides from Google Analytics Presentation","description":"Not that they will be all that helpful, because the majority of the presentation was demonstration, but here's the slides on SlideShare:\u00a0 <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/l3fseq\">http://go.ncsu.edu/l3fseq</a><a target=\"_blank\"></a>","createdDate":"2010-06-07T13:27:59.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-06-07T13:28:32.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11998","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Requirements for a Semester Data API","description":"There was some discussion on the mailing list a few weeks ago about the desire to have a centralized source to find out information about semesters.\u00a0 I'd like to hear some feedback about what information everyone would want from that, what method calls would be important, etc.\u00a0 I'd like us to brainstorm without limitations such as \"that's not available\" because it could be...just not anywhere that people know about :)<br/><br/>My initial thoughts for requirements are:<br/><ul>\n<li>Service should be publicly available with no authentication</li>\n<li>Service should be accessible via URL calls</li>\n<li>Service should return data in XML or JSON formats dependent on the request</li>\n<li>Service should be centrally hosted, backed up, and supported</li>\n</ul>\nThese are the initial methods I came up with:<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Method:\u00a0 getCurrentSemester</span><br/>Args:\u00a0 None<br/>Purpose:\u00a0 Get information about the current semester<br/>Return value:\u00a0 Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end date (UNIX timestamp), name<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Method:\u00a0 getSemester</span><br/>Args:\u00a0 $timestamp<br/>Purpose:\u00a0 Get information about the semester that lies within\u00a0 the passed timestamp<br/>Return value:\u00a0 Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end date (UNIX timestamp), name<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Method:\u00a0 getNextSemester</span><br/>Args:\u00a0 None (Optional $timestamp?)<br/>Purpose:\u00a0 Get information about the next available semester <br/>Return value:\u00a0 Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end\ndate (UNIX timestamp), name<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Method:\u00a0 getPreviousSemester</span><br/>Args:\u00a0 None (Optional $timestamp?)<br/>\nPurpose:\u00a0 Get information about the previous available semester <br/>\nReturn value:\u00a0 Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end\ndate (UNIX timestamp), name<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Method:\u00a0 getSemestersForYear</span><br/>Args:\u00a0 $year (YYYY)<br/>\nPurpose:\u00a0 Get information about all semesters in a given year<br/>\nReturn value:\u00a0 Array of structures containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end\ndate (UNIX timestamp), name<br/><br/><br/>What else would be needed by you folks?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-06-01T14:54:54.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-11T17:19:36.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:12321","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Yesterday, I met with Dave Van Emden (who is the guy working with me on semester data in Oracle) to talk a little bit about getting access to the semester data that is stored in Oracle. Here is the lowdown:\n\nThe data that is stored about a semester is somewhat more dynamic than I had originally thought. Apparently, many of the dates change quite often, including the official beginning and ending of a semester. There is a fear among the data stewards about putting information out there as \"official\" until they are confirmed, so there will be a limit on how far in the future semester data can be delivered.\n\nAlso, there are several different semester calendars that are stored in Oracle based on who they effect. Grad students, Undergrads, Ag Institute, Vet Med and Non-degree seeking students all have different calendars. The API which we create is going to need to be able to handle any of those options to return data.\n\nThere are quite a few more dates in the system than just semester start and end dates. These are the dates we can get:\n\nFirst Day Of Classes\nLast day of classes\nLast day for Wait list\ndrop deadline\nLast date to cancel\nlast date to withdraw (no penalty)\nLast date to withdraw (penalty)\nFull graded date (when we look at status and suspend students)\ngraduation application dates\n\nDave is looking into exam dates as well, which would be great to include. My thought is to be able to provide all of these dates through an API for each semester.\n\nWhile going into the future to look for semester data is iffy, looking into the past will not be so bad. We will have access to lots of historic data.\n\nDave is working on setting up the access we need in Oracle, so we are going to start setting up some infrastructure here to be able to support an API.","createdDate":"2010-08-11T17:19:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12019","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"For wolfware.ncsu.edu \"current\" right now is the combination of 2106 (Summer I and Summer 10 Week) and 2107 (Summer II) and will remain that way until the fall semester.\n\nFor another one of our apps, \"current\" right now is 2106, 2107, and 2108 because it deals with courses and registrations.\n\nHowever, the real multiple semesters problem hasn't really been solved, because most of our stuff just needs \"Summer\". My plan to solve it is to always return an array of semesters which contain active courses. Something like this: SELECT DISTINCT STRM, SESSION_CODE FROM PS_NC_DNRM_SCHE_VW WHERE START_DT &lt;= '2010-07-22' AND END_DT &gt;= '2010-07-22' However, I am under the impression that SIS uses another table with only the default semester dates so it should be faster (but which would not take into account modified course dates). Mainly I want to make sure that I don't lock students out of their courses too early or leave the courses open too long, so precision is important.\n\nThe unique key for a semester is the combination of STRM and SESSION_CODE. The unique key for a class section is STRM and CLASS_NBR (there is another unique combination of around six fields, but I prefer to join on two columns instead of six). It is a given that Summer Ten Week will be current at the same time as Summer II. STRM is a 4 digit number such that 2101 = 2010 Spring. Rather than splice a 0 into the second character position, I believe that it is cleaner to set the epoch at 1800 (as it predates the university and 210 + 1800 = 2010). The problem being that the year 2100's Spring semester will likely be represented as 3001 (though we're likely to switch systems long before then, but the epoch addition seems to be more legible and would continue to work if we keep that representation).\n\n...hmm, think I got carried away again. I believe I answered your questions. Please let me know if you have more.","createdDate":"2010-06-02T13:05:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12017","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"So how would you handle the multiple semesters at once problem when you query for a current semester? I think this action is a critical requirement, so is it a given that there /could/ be more than one semester returned?\n\nI am in agreement with keeping the data points that are returned from a search (such as getCurrentSemester) to be as minimal as possible. The amount of data returned by default should be the minimum, with the option to return additional data if required.\n\nMaybe I'm n00bing it up, or maybe I just don't deal with semester data enough, but I didn't really even know that there was a difference in a 10w semester vs. a 5w semester, so this discussion is really beneficial. Also I didn't know about the STRM, so that is good knowledge to have. That was kinda why I wanted to get this out there so it could be discussed as opposed to just throwing something together that wasn't flushed out.\n\nKeep it coming! great info to be had here...","createdDate":"2010-06-01T23:51:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12014","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"IMPORTANT: We need to clearly define \"current semester\". I have a feeling that this API draft doesn't take into account the special situations that occur during the summer. 2106 started 2010-05-24 and will typically end on 2010-06-25. 2107 starts on 2010-07-01 and will typically end on 2010-08-04. However, that noticeably doesn't include 2106 10W (the other two are both 5W), which typically goes from 2010-05-24 to 2010-08-04. Of course, there are 70 cases where 10W extends until 2010-08-09, meaning that 2106 ends after 2107 and exists simultaneously with 2107 for its duration. Please note that I have excluded the exceptions to these generalities (date ranges which did not have more than 11 entries). How we handle this case is rather important, but it may make sense to be particularly clear about what we are asking, because if I am trying to ask the question \"What is the current semester?\", I should probably get the same result as the question \"What semesters have ongoing courses?\". Of course, we need to also be able to use this to be able to answer the question sequence: \"What semesters have ongoing courses?\", \"From those semesters, which courses am I taking?\". In theory, 2106 5W classes should not be returned after June 25th. In practice, we'll probably want to leave all summer classes active for the duration (in an attempt at providing a consistent experience). So then, do we say that 2107 is active for the full duration as well? It may depend on the situation. As such, it would be good to provide a decent chunk of information about the whole 5W 10W non-unique STRM datasets. Specifically, if we can specify STRM, we'll also have to specify the SESSION_CODE (at least for xxx6 STRMs).\n\nNot exactly a fan of the name \"getNoClasses\". As conflicting as it is, I'd prefer something like \"getClosures\". I would guess that there is an official name for that from the University Schedule, so it may make sense to use that.\n\nNot a fan of having the default semester \"object\" be so bloated, but I would like to be able to get the full blob in one pull by specifying the details via parameters. I guess you could default to everything, and specify a comma separated list of types a la WoWArmory's RSS parameters.","createdDate":"2010-06-01T20:36:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12012","contributorName":"36s2enpzomc97","description":"Exactly what I'm thinking","createdDate":"2010-06-01T17:32:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12008","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I think you've covered the requirements pretty well. I can't think of anything else I would want to query.\n\nI think the default data returned should definitely pertain to the current semester, especially since this will probably be the most sought after data (or most frequently requested).\n\nOptional query parameters...\n1) A specific year\n2) A specific semester - accepted in both formats maybe... strm (2098) &amp; also full text ('Fall 2008'?)\n\nQuerying for a year returns data for all of the semesters... where as querying a single semester does exactly what you'd expect it to.\n\nBy default I think each &lt;semester&gt; returned in the response should contain:\n1) Start and End Date\n2) Exam Start and End Date\n3) Full Text Equivalent (so folks who query strm=2098 can easily get 'Fall 2008').\n4) No Class Dates (&amp; Datesets) along with a Label for the closing (ex: Fall Break)\n\nWe could also include things like 'last day to add a class' as Jason suggested or we could require another optional parameter to return that data...\n\nwebservices.ncsu.edu/../&amp;format=json&amp;strm=2098&amp;<b>show_dates=all</b>","createdDate":"2010-06-01T17:28:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12005","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"For your getNoClasses method, I assume you mean the list of holidays or breaks or whatever?","createdDate":"2010-06-01T16:17:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12002","contributorName":"36s2enpzomc97","description":"Other data that would be useful from where I sit:\n\nimportant dates in a given semester:\nlast day to add class w/out instructor permission\nlast day to add class period\nlast day to drop/withdraw from a class\n\n<b>Method: getNoClasses</b>\nArgs: $semester\nPurpose: Get information about dates when classes are not in session for students\nReturn value: Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp), end date (UNIX timestamp), name\n\n<b>Method: getReadingDays</b>\nArgs: $semester\nPurpose: Get reading day dates for given semester\nReturn value: Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp) and end date (UNIX timestamp)\n\n<b>Method: getExamDates</b>\nArgs: $semester\nPurpose: Get exam dates for given semester\nReturn value: Structure containing start date (UNIX timestamp) and end date (UNIX timestamp)","createdDate":"2010-06-01T15:40:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11925","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Does your group use Remedy?","description":"I'm just curious to see how many other web groups are using the <a href=\"http://remedy.ncsu.edu/project/\">Remedy (Action Request System)</a> to track their support tickets and internal web projects...<br/><br/>In ITECS, we use Remedy almost religiously and we're always trying to improve how we're using it. <br/><br/>One of our goals for the next year is to create a better 'product' list for our team. Our current product list literally contains a list of 'products' (specific websites and webtools) that we manage. Before any help ticket can be closed, it must have a product assigned to it. However, we're now realizing that this approach isn't actually all that useful to us because it doesn't allow us to easily summarize the types of requests we are fielding.<br/><br/>For instance, if an end user writes to us asking for WRAP access to \"Internal Tool A\", we'll tag that call with the product name 'Internal Tool A'. We thought this approach was great because it would enable us to summarize our support efforts on a product by product basis at the end of the year. <br/><br/>However, there's a couple problems with that...<br/><br/>1) You might notice that some products have a larger call volume than others and immediately accuse them of being clunky or problematic. However, you then realize that not all support tickets are bug reports, some of them are for feature requests... so you'd be jumping to conclusions prematurely without first investigating the types of being calls attributed to that product<br/><br/>2) There's a good chance you have a product that has a larger user base than your other products, it's probably going to get more call tickets assigned to it simply because of that<br/><br/>.. I'm sure you can see the rest.<br/><br/>What we're proposing (internally) is that we re-structure this product list to more or less fit the 'types' of requests we get:<br/><br/><ul>\n<li>Request for WRAP Access</li>\n<li>Request for Database Access</li>\n<li>Environment Troubleshooting (Apache or PHP)</li>\n<li>Request for Server Write Access</li>\n<li>Content Management System Support</li>\n<li>Request for Sign-up / Registration System</li>\n<li>...</li>\n</ul>\n^ This new structure will hopefully show us (in our reports) exactly where we are spending most of our time and resources. Once that picture becomes clearer, we'll know where we should make improvements and invest in projects that will make us more efficient.<br/><br/>So a few quick questions...<br/><ol>\n<li>Does your group use Remedy?</li>\n<li>Do you use Remedy as both a project management tool and support ticket tracking system or just one of the two?\u00a0</li>\n<li>Do you use Remedy to create reports summarizing the work your group does?<br/></li>\n<li>What are the main types of web requests that your group deals with most frequently?</li>\n<li>Would it benefit us (as the university web developer community) to have a single web product list in Remedy that all groups would use?</li>\n</ol>\nSuggestions? Comments? Thoughts?<br/><br/>-Mike<br/><br/><br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-05-13T19:39:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-14T14:04:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11931","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Jason Austin's answers for 1-4 are close enough to mine that I didn't want to duplicate.\n\n5. Because Remedy isn't really how we do project management, it would mostly be additional overhead to include our \"products\" which are mostly internal and rarely applicable to other units.","createdDate":"2010-05-14T14:04:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11929","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"1. Does your group use Remedy?\n\nYep, at CNR we do.\n\n2. Do you use Remedy as both a project management tool and support ticket tracking system or just one of the two?\n\nMostly just for a support tracking system although it is used informally for project tracking. I for example created a product for \"Web Dev Requests\" and will use that product for any kind of project-type task. There's also the Origin field which contains \"Project\" which I'll also use for anything that requires a bit more coordination and long-term effort. Again, fairly informal, but a way to differentiate the simpler requests from the more complex project-type tasks.\n\n3. Do you use Remedy to create reports summarizing the work your group does?\n\nWe do, our boss will run reports from time to time and I'll run reports for myself from time to time just to see where I'm at. Dan Green's group created a pretty nice and basic reporting Web tool a while back and I used to use that but it has been disabled. I think that's due to the fact that you can get reports from a new system run by OIT which I actually haven't played with yet.\n\n4. What are the main types of web requests that your group deals with most frequently?\n\nThe largest number of requests regard Adobe Contribute and permissions. We have 50+ Web editors (though only about 7 or so are very active) so it's pretty common that someone will request a key, or a re-activation of their key. These calls come in frequently but are very simple. There are many other common themes of requests, such as new site requests and the projects that surround bringing those up, righting display problems for older websites, upgrading existing sites with dynamic content and various sundry questions about working on the Web (URL, images, metadata, other best practice issues). This is a 10,000 ft view by the way, not exactly a formal analysis of calls.\n\n5. Would it benefit us (as the university web developer community) to have a single web product list in Remedy that all groups would use?\n\nAt CNR we define all products we use and like ITECS we force a product choice on the closing of a call. If you look at the Products field and browse to CNR you'll see what we've got, including a subcategory for Web. Keep in mind that if a product appears in our CNR category and somewhere else in the Remedy product tree it isn't duplicate products, they share the same ID, just show up in two different spots on the tree.\n\nMike you might want to bring these questions to the Remedy Advisory committee that's headed up by Larry Robinson at OIT. I do think there's value in having uniformity in the support metrics we all use. But I also think it's more important for individual shops to figure this out on their own. Definitely worth a discussion either way.","createdDate":"2010-05-14T13:11:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11927","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"1. Does your group use Remedy?\n\nSparingly. It didn't really jive with what we wanted to do.\n\n2. Do you use Remedy as both a project management tool and support ticket tracking system or just one of the two?\n\nOnly support stuff, and usually only when it comes from an external-to-OIT source.\n\n3. Do you use Remedy to create reports summarizing the work your group does?\n\nNo\n\n4. What are the main types of web requests that your group deals with most frequently?\n\nBug and feature requests. We really wanted a more granular and consistent way of handling these.\n\n5. Would it benefit us (as the university web developer community) to have a single web product list in Remedy that all groups would use?\n\nI think it would benefit us, as a community, to have a single list of web products anywhere. I started going down that road once, but didn't get very far. An integrated system where people could go to access these tools, download the source, see who the group is that created the tool, etc would be completely awesome.\n\n---\n\nWe have implemented Redmine as our choice for ticket tracking. It gave us a good bit of flexibility, integrated with SVN, had a wiki for documentation, and great tracking tools. It's lacking in reports, and it is a Ruby app so getting it going on campus was a bit of a pain, but it has worked well for us for the last year+.\n\nIt has some very loose project management aspects in it, but not nearly good enough. I know the libraries have used Basecamp and we have messed with it some. Since it is for-pay, that introduces some additional challenges, but if there is enough interest perhaps we could explore a community license for it or something.","createdDate":"2010-05-14T13:00:03.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11924","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"NCDEVCON Free and at NCSU May 22-23","description":"Looks like Shawn Dunning's crew has been busy moving and shaking in the web dev world.\u00a0 NCWEBDEV is sited at the College of Textiles nine days hence.<br/><br/><a href=\"http://ncdevcon.com/page.cfm/schedule\">http://ncdevcon.com/page.cfm/schedule</a><br/><br/>Hrm, maybe I can get a few sessions in before *and* after the Eos Reunion...<br/>","createdDate":"2010-05-13T14:07:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-14T14:18:07.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11933","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Note that the primary focus here is on Adobe products. Even though the presentations are mainly a combination of Cold Fusion, Flex, and AIR, some of the Web track presentations might be interesting (\"HTML email marketing: Designing, coding &amp; sending\", \"Organizing Your jQuery\", \"Taming The JavaScript beast\") for the rest of us. Hopefully they'll post slides.\n\nOf the Cold Fusion track, I'll be interested to see how much \"Database Tips and Tricks for Programmers\", \"Intro to Caching\" and \"Writing Readable Code\" translate to other platforms/languages.","createdDate":"2010-05-14T14:18:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11915","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Would You Like a Central 'Did you know?' Database","description":"I was brainstorming a little this morning about a website\nwe're revamping in the College of Engineering and I was thinking\nwouldn't it be great if we had a central database or web service for\nthe university that could return a random quote or fact about NC\nState...<br/>\n<br/>\nHere's basically how it would work...<br/>\n<br/>\n1) A visitor would come to Department X's website...<br/>\n2) Behind the scenes, the Department X's website would make a request\nto some simple address like\n\"webservices.ncsu.edu/rest/random-fact-generator.php\"<br/>\n3) The web service would query the central database and pull out a\nrandom fact or quote pertaining to the university and send it back to\nDepartment X's website so that it could be included somewhere on the\npage for the user to see. <br/>\n<br/>\nBenefits...<br/>\n1) This would really help enable department, organization, and unit webmasters to promote the same sort of unified message<br/>\n2) We improve brand consistency across a variety of university sites (and do so relatively easily)<br/>\n3) We're taking a little weight off some of our units by providing a\nsource of high quality content, they don't have to create as much\nthemselves<br/>\n4) We're also automating a source of content for folks, effectively giving them less to keep up with<br/>\n<br/>\nHere are some examples of interesting facts that the service might generate...<br/>\n<br/>\n- \"Did you know? NC State offers the 2nd best value among the nation\u2019s public colleges and universities (Princeton Review, 2006)\"<br/>\n- \"Did you know? NC State ranks 5th in Best Overall University Value among public universities (U.S. News &amp; World Report, August 2006)\"<br/>\n- \"Did you know? Over 95,000 NC State alumni still live in North Carolina\"<br/>\n- \"Did you know? Robert Gibbs, Whitehouse Press Secretary was an NC State Graduate\"<br/><br/><ul>\n<li>What do you think?</li>\n<li>Are any of you maintaining a similar service internally?</li>\n<li>Would you benefit from this kind of service?</li>\n<li>Are there any cons?</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2010-05-12T14:05:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-19T15:15:09.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11942","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Yeah, I think this is a good idea. There's always a lot of discussion amongst campus communicators about \"Points of Pride\" and how we need them. From a central messaging standpoint, it would be a great way to provide a repository of key marketing messages available for various units on campus to pull from.\n\nI suppose there's a significant amount of improved control that comes with developing a single-purpose tool, but I wonder if a dedicated wordpress instance might be able to help with a bit of it. Offer out a variety of tagged/categorized fact feeds via RSS and a nifty little \"add this feed to my page\" tool (PHP and Javascript persuasion plus whatever anyone else wants to build) so the non-developer Web managers can plop it on their pages. Wordpress would allow for multiple user access to specific buckets of facts, so people could pull from other lists or create their own.\n\nDunno, just wondering if it'd work. Either way, very cool idea. Back in 2007 when I first started, one of the key homepage promo blocks was the \"By The Numbers\" block that displayed a random fact on the homepage. Wasn't as smart as the tool you're describing, but the concept was there. We later abandoned that so we could re purpose the space for, well, crisis communications early on, and now we've moved to what we call internally \"engagement\" promos. Gotta love the buzzwords.\n\nWould love to help with this project as it's appropriate, so let me know if we can do anything.","createdDate":"2010-05-19T15:15:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11923","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Yeah, I think in order for this particular service to be successful you'll need some quality assurance measures in place. I was envisioning this as more or less a service that the communications group would provide/manage.\n\n@nick - great idea for aging the quotes, I think it helps a little when some of these things are given a date like \"(From the 2006 Princeton Review)\", but you're right... there comes a point when 2006 isn't as recent as it once was and we need to move on.\n\n@jonathan - great suggestion on the data dump/cache.\n\nI also think 'tagging' entries would be really beneficial, but you're right it could be a challenge to execute. Would users be allow to create and issue their own tags or would the service automatically tag things from a predefined list?\n\nA database like this may really not be all that difficult to manage if you're careful about your fact selection, choosing mostly facts that have a longer shelf life. And I don't think we're talking about a massive amount of entries here... heck if I had 100 different interesting facts or bullet points I could randomly pull, that would probably be enough.","createdDate":"2010-05-12T18:38:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11921","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"* What do you think?\n\nNeat idea, but I don't quite understand the added value unless we can manage our own categories. We'll want to be able to control what ends up on our website and I'm not confident that the decision makers would trust outside editing.\n\n* Are any of you maintaining a similar service internally?\n\nNo.\n\n* Would you benefit from this kind of service?\n\nCurrently, no. However, if the availability was greater than or equal to the website/application using it and the decision makers wanted to include this functionality, it would make sense to avoid duplication and offload the data maintenance and software support.\n\n* Are there any cons?\n\nJason and Nick already mentioned the data aging issue (the Robert Gibbs quote is tied to his continued employment). Also, service availability and response rate would have to be excellent. As a stopgap for slow responses, allowing for a data dump (JSON?) would allow for local caching and randomization which would limit service traffic. Last, I'm not sure what the acceptance rate would be if the quote list wasn't being managed by the website/application's decision makers. People rarely hand over even partial content control to outside forces.\n\nOverall, this seems like a neat little service that would be at least a convenient way to make each page load \"unique\". SELECT quote FROM quotes WHERE quote_category IN ('technology', 'oit', 'computers') ORDER BY RAND() LIMIT 1","createdDate":"2010-05-12T18:21:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11919","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Awesome idea.\n\nPros --- will be easy to use, implement...pretty much all the obvious benefits of a central source for information (ie: one version of the truth).\n\nCons --- keeping quotes up to date.\n\nMaybe for each quote you could require an \"expiration\" date be stored, so that if the quote is something like \"Did you know? NC State offers the 2nd best value among the nation\u2019s public colleges and universities (Princeton Review, 2006)\" ....then it will stop being displayed randomly when that information is old/stagnant/not-pertinent.\n\nOr...maybe a duration for the quotes...so you would put in a \"only display this quote between January 15th and March 23rd, 2011.\"\n\nThink about making it possible to categorize the quotes too, maybe like a tagging system, so that websites can specify a particular term for which quotes they want to display.\n\nFor example, OIT might want to only display quotes that are tagged with \"oit, technology, computers\" or something like that.\n\nI think this is great. I think our website clients would be very interested in this type of service. I'm already thinking down the line of how cool it would be to integrate it as a widget or a module block in Wordpress/Drupal. That way it would be super simple for people to drop in and not have to touch any code at all.\n\nLet me know if/when you want beta/bug testers or help at all. I'll be happy to assist if possible.","createdDate":"2010-05-12T14:40:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11917","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think that would be kinda cool. I think the only challenge would be keeping the information up-to-date and relevant, but any time somebody is talking about putting together web services which can be leveraged by lots of other people, I think its a good idea :)","createdDate":"2010-05-12T14:36:59.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11882","contributorName":"1ttn1970su7k6","title":"Open Base Directory Restriction","description":"Hi folks,<br/><br/>I know next to nothing about Wordpress, but what I've heard has made me interested in learning more.\u00a0 <br/><br/>Do you know if there are any issues about Wordpress and our Open Base Directory Restriction?\u00a0 <br/><br/>Thanks.\u00a0 <br/>Kathi McBlief<br/>","createdDate":"2010-05-05T12:27:18.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-05T13:25:29.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11886","contributorName":"1ttn1970su7k6","description":"Hi Jason.\n\nI didn't realize that the engineering servers were the only servers to have this restriction. Makes sense.\n\nI guess we can experiment with Wordpress first to see if we actually have a problem and then take it from there.\n\nMany thanks!\n\n-Kathi","createdDate":"2010-05-05T13:25:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11884","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm not sure, but the open base dir restriction is only on the engineering servers and not on the OIT servers. If there was a restriction, it would likely be a problem that could be worked around.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T13:20:08.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11850","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"the case of the mysterious acirc character (&acirc;)","description":"So if anyone has any ideas about this please let me know.\u00a0 We're finishing up a site migration for Extension Forestry in which a lot of content was copy pasted from the old to the new site.\u00a0 Suppose that makes sense.\u00a0 The part which I don't get is that certain pages seem to have character issues.\u00a0 For example:<br/><br/><a href=\"http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/educational_opportunities/plt/prek-8_curriculum.php\">http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/educational_opportunities/plt/prek-8_curriculum.php</a>\u00a0 and<br/><a href=\"http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/educational_opportunities/plt/\">http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/educational_opportunities/plt/</a><br/><br/>Notice a lot of &amp;acirc; characters?\u00a0 There's also a handful of other character problems too.\u00a0 And feel free to click around, some pages render fine, others don't.\u00a0 What's stranger is that when I look at the files on the server, where an &amp;acirc; character shows up in the browser there is literally nothing extra in the code itself.\u00a0 <br/><br/>Some other contextual info: we've got some people working on Macs and others on PCs. Though that may be a red herring.<br/><br/>Anyone who has some thoughts/ideas holler at me.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-05-03T19:30:38.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-06T14:55:59.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11898","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Heheh...\n\nyeah, I don't know, I created the only existing .htaccess files and they don't include charset info.. and the server settings (server is run by Extension btw) don't seem to play role because some pages did correctly render with utf-8 while others did not independent of the directory..\n\nI'm glad I was able to get a good fix to my problem, but I definitely want to get to the root of the problem. So far I'm sticking with my theory that Mac Adobe Contribute users magically turn files into ISO-8879-1.","createdDate":"2010-05-06T14:55:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11897","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Not quite Charlie. The Content-Type header *is* being sent by the server. You might want to check .htaccess files, server configuration files, and all included files that make up the site hierarchy to figure out which one is setting it to ISO-8859-1 (which someone probably set years ago to \"fix\" a problem they were having).","createdDate":"2010-05-06T14:26:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11892","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Yeah I think it must have been the case of Byte Order Mark overriding my META charset. So you're saying that because I had set my DTD to XHTML Transitional 1.0, but the content type was set to \"text/html\" instead of \"application/xhtml+xml\" the browser treated this document as if it was html and ignored the DTD and instead defaulted to HTML 4 or 5 (and it sounds like 5 given that what forced the ISO-8879-1 was the Byte Mark Order)?\n\nIf I've got that right then theoretically the charset confusion would be righted if I changed my content type to \"application/xhtml+xml\". Is that what you're saying?\n\nThanks again by the way for the input.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T16:01:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11891","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"One more link. <a href=\"http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/guidelines.html\" target=\"_blank\">XHTML 1.0 - HTML Compatibility Guidelines</a>. It doesn't exactly illustrate the differences but it does hint at the consequences of serving XHTML as HTML with guidelines to avoid problems.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T15:00:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11890","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"Another thing that can be useful to eliminate situations like this when pulling data from a MySQL database is to call mysql_query(\"SET NAMES utf8\") immediately after connecting.\n\nAccording to the manual, \"SET NAMES indicates what character set the client will use to send SQL statements to the server. Thus, SET NAMES 'cp1251' tells the server, \u201cfuture incoming messages from this client are in character set cp1251.\u201d It also specifies the character set that the server should use for sending results back to the client. (For example, it indicates what character set to use for column values if you use a SELECT statement.) \"","createdDate":"2010-05-05T14:59:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11864","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"META is supposed to be used by the browser when there is insufficient information available via the content type header. Since the content is _not_ being parsed as XHTML, the XML rules do not apply and the rules for HTML do instead (4 or 5 depending on what the browser decided). Reading left to right in order of highest to lowest precedence the rules are:\n\nHTML 4: User override (through browser options) &gt;&gt; Content-Type header &gt;&gt; META http-equiv=\"Content-Type\"\n\nHTML 5: User override &gt;&gt; Content-Type header &gt;&gt; Byte Order Mark &gt;&gt; META charset &gt;&gt; META http-equiv=\"Content-Type\"\n\nThe content type header clearly stated it was ISO-8879-1, so there was no ambiguity to resolve, so the META tag was ignored. Note that DTDs are usually not parsed by browsers for HTML.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T16:25:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11863","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"I hope I made it clear that the \"correct\" content type that the W3C recommends, is one which most people avoid <i>because</i> it enforces strict XML validation. What I should have emphasized is that you can force the character encoding to be UTF-8 on the content type, even if it is sent as (strictly speaking incorrect) text/html.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T15:53:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11862","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"the meta tag is literally the first line after the DTD, and ..\n\nAnyway, I love your solution, definitely forced utf-8. Thanks.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T15:02:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11861","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"You can set the content type of your document (server side) with PHP, that should help...\n\nheader('Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8');\n\nAlso, see examples of <a href=\"http://www.w3.org/International/O-HTTP-charset\" target=\"_blank\">how to pass the content type header in other languages</a>.\n\nIf you prefer the meta tag approach, I've read several arguments for placing meta tag as far up the document as you can.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T14:18:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11859","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Very interesting, thank you to both. I was looking over the W3C documentation over charsets and I found this doc <a href=\"http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/charset.html#h-5.2.2\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/charset.html#h-5.2.2</a>\n\nWhat I don't get is why the response header contains charset=ISO-8859-1 at all. I mean I have the charset defined in the meta tag. Some of the pages on the site render correctly and show utf-8 in the response headers, while others show ISO-8859-1. By what that doc says from W3C, the precedence of what the encoding is for the user-agent is set by the server, then by the meta tag and then by individual elements in order of precedence. I know the server isn't globally overriding the meta tag so then it's not overriding anything.\n\nI did see this one nugget from that doc: \"Some servers examine the first few bytes of the document..\" Could that mean that because some pages were edited last by a Mac user that a Mac changes the encoding?\n\nI know there's more to this discussion, just trying to understand this piece first to identify the problem...","createdDate":"2010-05-04T13:39:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11856","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Mitch is correct about the encoding issue. The page is being served as ISO-8859-1, when it should be UTF-8. You can verify this by going to View -&gt; Character Encoding -&gt; UTF-8 and notice that all the \"bad\" characters go away. They are due to the UTF-8 encoding for characters beyond the ASCII set using more than one byte (but being rendered as two characters in ISO-8859-1).\n\nYou may want to avoid serving the files with the *correct* Content-Type that Mitch recommends, as it can cause issues with the page if it was not designed for strict standards mode. Long term, it is better to ensure that you are designing the pages with the correct Content-Type in place.\n\nAdditionally, you need to consider which browsers you are supporting. IE7 and below will not accept the *correct* Content-Type. Quoting from <a href=\"http://blogs.msdn.com/ie/archive/2005/09/15/467901.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">the IEBlog post on IE7 XHTML compliance</a>: \"Why aren\u2019t we supporting XHTML when it\u2019s served as the \u201capplication/xml+xhtml\u201d media type in IE7? I made the decision to not try to support the MIME type in IE7 simply because I personally want XHTML to be successful in the long run.\" Seems like a \"my bloated architecture wouldn't let me code in proper support before we had to ship the final version so now we can't serve proper XHTML until Windows 7 is the legacy version\" excuse to me.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T12:59:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11852","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"It is an encoding issue. The non-breaking space, encoded in UTF-8 (the document makes the claim to be in UTF-8) is hex C2A0 (two bytes) but in ISO-8859-1 it is hex A0 (one byte). My browser thinks your page is ISO-8859-1. This is due to the Content-type header being incorrect.\n\nIt is more often the case than not that a Web server incorrectly serves XHTML with a content type of HTML. Your file lacks an XML encoding value in the declaration, which would take precedence over the META tag, but the content type header takes precedence over both, and the header is wrong. Here is the Firefox Web Developer dump of the headers your server provided:\n\nDate: Mon, 03 May 2010 21:03:32 GMT\nServer: Apache/2.2.14 (Unix) mod_ssl/2.2.14 OpenSSL/0.9.8e-fips-rhel5 DAV/2 PHP/5.3.2\nX-Powered-By: PHP/5.3.2\nKeep-Alive: timeout=15, max=100\nConnection: Keep-Alive\nTransfer-Encoding: chunked\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1\n\n200 OK\n\nIdeally, the server should be serving XHTML files with a default of UTF-8, with a content type of \"application/xhtml+xml\" .\n\nBe warned that since you have been serving as HTML, your pages haven't been parsed as XML in the way that XHTML demands, so switching the content type will introduce draconian error checking of XML and will doubtlessly cause some pages to completely fail to display... unless you really are producing clean, well-formed XHTML.\n\nYou might take a stop-gap approach by using a .htaccess file to <a href=\"http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.0/mod/core.html#forcetype\" target=\"_blank\">force a charset</a> of UTF-8 on the documents.","createdDate":"2010-05-03T21:32:09.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11837","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"\"upload file\" PHP code in AFS","description":"Need some help. I am creating a form using inFORM in my web AFS space. I need to allow the user to upload an image file as part of the form.<br/><br/>I've seen some PHP code for this, and have tried to make use of it in the past...but to no avail. In consulting with one of my favorite web gurus (Eddie Lovett), it appears it's a permissions issue within AFS of some sort.<br/><br/>Ideas?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-28T21:06:05.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-28T21:24:57.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:859","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11841","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Charles -- thanks much. I'll play with this and run my code by you. Thanks!","createdDate":"2010-04-28T21:24:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11839","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"You have to setup write permissions in the AFS directory for the PHP servers, just like you do with inFORM when saving data to a file from the cgi servers.\n\nQuick for-example:\ncd /afs/unity/web/m/mylocker\nmkdir uploads\ncd uploads\nfs sa . www:servers.php write\n# then you would set your php script to save uploaded files to /afs/unity/web/m/mylocker/uploads\n\nBe very, very careful about letting people view these uploaded files from a URL. That's why my quick example has the uploads directory outside of the htdocs tree: those files cannot be accessed via a URL. The single most common attack against our webservers is when someone finds an uploader like this, uploads \"mybackdoorshell.php\" to that directory, and then runs it from a URL.\n\nIf you want extra help getting this setup safely, please drop me an email.\n\nCharles","createdDate":"2010-04-28T21:18:11.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11828","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"File Comparison Utility","description":"Does anyone have a favorite file comparison utility? There are a bunch out there, and I'm interested in something for both Windows and Mac.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-28T13:33:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-08-15T15:24:41.032Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:21765","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"<p>Since the old thread was resurrected...</p>\n<p>I like meld for unix-like systems. When checking up on what platforms are supported, I also found this: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_file_comparison_tools\" target=\"_blank\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_file_comparison_tools</a></p>","createdDate":"2011-08-15T15:24:41.174Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:21749","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Found this <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/187064/graphical-diff-for-mac-os-x\" target=\"_blank\">thread from SO</a> recommending a couple diff tools for the Mac.\u00a0 I started using <a href=\"http://sourcegear.com/diffmerge/\" target=\"_blank\">DiffMerge</a> and it's working nicely.","createdDate":"2011-08-09T13:00:38.183Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11888","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"I'll second WinMerge for Windows, it's fantastic.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T14:52:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11847","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Some good editors have diff capabilities built in for the file types they edit. I often use the Vim capability to diff two files, just because it launches quickly. I've also used WinMerge. The oXygenXML editor can difference files and directories as well, with a special mode for structured markup files (XML, XHTML): <a href=\"http://www.oxygenxml.com/xml_diff_and_merge.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.oxygenxml.com/xml_diff_and_merge.html</a> (disclaimer: my company is listed as an oxygen reseller.) Aptana Studio (Eclipse based)has folder and file comparisons too. I found this <a href=\"http://www.michaelflanakin.com/articles/CompareDiffTools.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">table</a> too.","createdDate":"2010-05-01T15:43:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11845","contributorName":"342r1a4s0h1s3","description":"For Windows, I love <a href=\"http://winmerge.org/\" target=\"_blank\">WinMerge</a>. I'm currently looking for something for Mac. Starting to try out <a href=\"http://kdiff3.sourceforge.net/\" target=\"_blank\">KDiff3</a> but haven't quite fallen in love with it.","createdDate":"2010-04-30T21:57:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11835","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Very much helps...thanks, Jonathon. I've read of diff, and used some ancient version long ago, but wanted a colleague's recommendation. Appreciated!","createdDate":"2010-04-28T21:02:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11830","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"What kinds of files? For text, diff is the industry standard (diff -u for unified diffs which is the standard patch format). For versioned text, svn diff is identical (along with the cvs, git, etc. equivalents). Tortoise SVN has a neat graphical diff for versioned images. It's rather difficult to readably get the differences between binary formats like word documents.\n\nIf I can assume we're talking about text (plaintext, html, xml, etc.), diff is the way to go. There's guaranteed to be a windows version and it's free. If you want something that's a bit more graphical, there's always Eclipse (also free) which can do file comparisons (pick the two and click 'compare with each other', which probably works for directories as well).\n\nHope that helps! :)","createdDate":"2010-04-28T15:21:14.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11827","contributorName":"j5xdwf5o65y4","title":"Play Framework","description":"This is my first post here and Id thought Id share something I came across a little while back. Its another web framework! But this time around, its not aimed at Python, Ruby, or PHP. Its for Java.<br/><br/>Its the easiest framework to learn that Ive found. That probably has to with the fact that its Java and Ive been accustomed to that for the past 2 years. What makes it shine, though, are all the features:<br/>\u00a0- Got a bug? Play will point it the specific line and whats wrong in the web browser. Once you fix it, reload, an viola! Everything compiled on the fly.<br/>\u00a0- Its pretty fast. Youd think that compiling would take a while, even for larger applications, but it doesnt.<br/>\u00a0- One of the best template systems Ive ever seen (based on Groovy)<br/>\u00a0- Has a nice plugin system and repository of plugins<br/>\u00a0- Java!<br/><br/>Pay the website a visit: <a href=\"http://www.playframework.org/\">http://www.playframework.org/</a><br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-27T14:39:13.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-27T14:39:13.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11705","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Ning going premium only...What to do?","description":"<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2010/04/15/nings-bubble-bursts-no-more-free-networks-cuts-40-of-staff/\">http://techcrunch.com/2010/04/15/nings-bubble-bursts-no-more-free-networks-cuts-40-of-staff/</a><br/><br/>and<br/><br/><a href=\"http://creators.ning.com/forum/topics/ning-update\">http://creators.ning.com/forum/topics/ning-update</a><br/><br/>So....what do you guys think?\u00a0 We basically have 2 options.\u00a0 Move to some kind of open source solution that is on campus or shell out the money to keep the app here at Ning.\u00a0 I'm not really partial to having to manage it ourselves, but it's not like the web developers group is actually funded by anyone, so I don't know.\u00a0 I'd love to hear your opinions.<br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-15T19:52:58.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-09T16:59:55.447Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11880","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Jason may be able to provide more information about this -- he mentioned it to me yesterday. It's definitely something we're need to be looking into to see if we \"qualify\" and what that gets us.\n\nIf the EDU version doesn't get us the tools we need to sufficiently manage the community (i'm thinking spam controls if nothing else), then we may still need to go with the pay version.\n\nBUT...if it's fully featured like the $200 per year model, then that's awesome, as it looks like that's all we need.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T12:04:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11879","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I don't know Dan. I saw the same thing in an interview that Mashable did with Ning's CEO yesterday. I assume more info is going to come out about this, so until then it is a wait and see thing. In other news, OIT is willing to pony up the $200 a year for the Ning Plus, so at least we know we are covered one way or another. Too bad we can't actually sign up until the next fiscal year so we could take advantage of end-of-year money (can't sign up until sometime in July). Either way, I feel like things are looking up.","createdDate":"2010-05-05T12:01:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11877","contributorName":"3d59zvph0dryj","description":"Assuming the folks that concern themselves with policy / transparency / accountability / above board-ness / purity etc. can determine a suitable vehicle for <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/ning-going-premium-onlywhat-to?commentId=2486881%3AComment%3A11711\">donation/sponsor/whatever</a> I'm still more than happy to cover NING PLUS for a year. :)","createdDate":"2010-05-04T21:22:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11876","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Agreed. If members aren't excessive with video or photo posting that level could last for a very long time.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T21:15:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11871","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yep -- the $200 per year seems like a steal, and a deal, and has everything in it we would \"need\" and a little more on top. Considering that would be around a dollar per user per year, that seems like a pretty good cost model for our little community. I know the members aren't ponying up the $1, but it's at least a simple metric to compare what we're getting for the fee.\n\nI say go for it. Consider this one vote for the $19.95 plan.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T17:59:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11867","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"The new rates for Ning have been posted. I'm working on getting the funds to make this happen. It appears the $19.95/month plan will fit us fine. Thoughts?\n\n<a href=\"http://about.ning.com/announcement/plans.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://about.ning.com/announcement/plans.php</a>","createdDate":"2010-05-04T17:17:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11752","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"An audio discussion from the Education community about Ning going non-free: <a href=\"http://audio.edtechlive.com/foe/ningdiscussion.mp3\" target=\"_blank\">http://audio.edtechlive.com/foe/ningdiscussion.mp3</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-21T13:08:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11751","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"We're running WordPress MU at ECU, and I've just started reading about Buddy Press myself. I found the information because I came across a <a href=\"http://wpmu.org/ning-to-buddypress-importer-plugin/\" target=\"_blank\">Ning to Buddy Press user importer plugin</a>. As previously discussed, setting up a server requires time and commitment that a hosted service wouldn't require. Nevertheless, if self-hosting becomes the choice, I second the vote for Buddy Press.","createdDate":"2010-04-19T15:08:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11750","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We're supposed to be hearing their pricing plans next week sometime, so I don't know what kind of cost we are looking at. There are some less-than-fun policies of the university that limit sponsorship and the like, but I am hoping we won't have to get there. My guess is that OIT will step up, and if not them, someone else in the university.","createdDate":"2010-04-19T14:33:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11749","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Jason, what would be the dollar cost of \"going premium\", in such a way as to satisfy the Ning requirement?\n\nI agree with Jay that members can help support the site through donations. I may be too skittish but I wouldn't want to involve my company formally with a sponsorship without having clear guidelines set up and approvals from your NCSU direct reports. But member donations could at least defer a migration and allow it to happen on your time rather than on Ning's premium-only schedule, even if as a matter of principle the group chooses to move elsewhere.","createdDate":"2010-04-19T14:19:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11748","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"Mashable came out with a <a href=\"http://mashable.com/2010/04/18/ning-alternatives/\" target=\"_blank\">great article about Ning and some alternatives</a> Personally, I'm leaning towards <a href=\"http://wpmu.org/ning-to-buddypress-importer-plugin/\" target=\"_blank\">Buddy Press</a> from a teaching standpoint. We use <a href=\"http://cedncsu.ning.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Ning at the College of Ed</a> and pay premium services to have the Ads removed. It currently cost us $19.95 a month, but we locked in at an early rate 2 years ago.","createdDate":"2010-04-19T13:23:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11746","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It seems like a number of the alternatives are going to be offering tools to convert Ning sites, which may make a transition easier.","createdDate":"2010-04-19T13:03:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11743","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"<a href=\"http://venturebeatprofiles.com/company/profile/ning/competitors\" target=\"_blank\">http://venturebeatprofiles.com/company/profile/ning/competitors</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.siterapture.com/sitesimilarsites.asp?SiteID=161\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.siterapture.com/sitesimilarsites.asp?SiteID=161</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-16T18:35:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11742","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm with you on this one. Where I agree with Jason in that it is a pain to convert to a new service, I think that deeper we intertwine ourselves with Ning the worse off we will be. I think this is a great opportunity for the community to find a healthier (ad-free) way of life. However, we still don't know the pricing model, the data export format or how the Ning meta-community will respond. Let's keep an eye on things as they progress and evaluate our options.\n\nAs a side note, Ning has raised about $119 million in VC funding.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T18:11:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11741","contributorName":"1ttn1970su7k6","description":"I would like to know how much they are charging.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T17:38:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11737","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I like the chatroom idea too. Is jabber the easiest or IRC or what?","createdDate":"2010-04-16T15:22:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11736","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I like the idea of establishing a jabber chatroom for the group, it helps you get feedback and advice really quickly when you're having a problem or just want to generate some rapid discussion. However, I still think we should retain Ning (or a similar service) because there are times when I'm just too busy to keep up with what's happening in a chatroom and prefer to digest a days worth of discussion at a later time (Ning is great for that).\n\npossibly another alternative... Google Wave ?\n\n-Mike","createdDate":"2010-04-16T15:19:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11735","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"my quick shallow response: Yes. I would very much prefer to stay here on Ning. I hate to think of the time it would take to import or move to another service. I also think that if we were to move, we'd end up losing some people in the transition, which just hurts the community as a whole.\n\nCount me in for a few bucks to keep the community alive, although i share the hope/expectation that we'll be able to find the money within OIT to pay for the service.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T13:42:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11734","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I've thought a little more about this and would like to weigh in.\n\nAs one of the main administrators of this site and the web developers group, this portal of information is very important to me. We have worked extremely hard, as an administrative group and the community as a whole, to build this site into a valuable and reliable resource for web developers and designers both on and off campus. We have almost 250 members and over a year and a half worth of content. That is a whole lot of stuff and people to move, and there is no guarantee that it will be transferable (although Ning will give us our data if we decide to leave...in what format, I don't know).\n\nI feel like if we move to another free service, we could only be prolonging the inevitable. Ning is moving to a pay model because it cannot sustain itself and the demand which it created. Other social networking sites like this have spun off from Ning and have proceeded to fail swiftly. I don't want to have to go through the work of moving all our users and our content now, then having to do it again when the next service goes under, or goes for-pay, or whatever. However, this is a risk that we took by going with a \"in-the-cloud\" service as opposed to standing up our own.\n\nSeveral folks have suggested installing our own service on campus, which <i>could</i> be done. However, I don't believe it <i>should</i> be done. Standing up a service ourselves is in no way, shape, or form free. There are costs for the web hosting, bandwidth, and maintenance that take time and resources that are already constrained. We, as the administrative team, just don't have time to do it and maintain it.\n\nSo, in my opinion, if Ning's pricing structure is reasonable, I say we stay. We can find the resources. Heck, I'm sure there are people on here (like Jay, and myself) who would be willing to shell out the dough from our own pockets if the University won't step up. However, I feel like OIT can probably secure the funding. If it can't we'll find someone else that can. Bottom line, this group is very valuable to the continuity of web design, development and communication for NC State. I believe many folks recognize that, and I hope they will come through for us.\n\nLet's see what Ning does first, but I honestly don't see us moving off of this service. I've already started the ball rolling up my management chain to get a budget for the web developers group for us to use to bring in speakers, run the Ning site, etc. We'll figure out a way to make this happen, one way or another.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T13:25:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11732","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Agreed. Free is important and free hosted is preferred (don't want to have to worry about whose server it is on and if we're keeping it up to date, etc.). I posted a link to Yuku below and it looks interesting. I haven't checked out the other options, but Yuku has a neat <a href=\"http://www.yuku.com/portal/competition\" target=\"_blank\">\"Here's how we're better than Ning\"</a> page","createdDate":"2010-04-16T12:46:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11731","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"From the ning-update comments, here is a alternative and a thread about alternatives:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.yuku.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.yuku.com/</a>\n<a href=\"http://creators.ning.com/forum/topics/alternatives-1\" target=\"_blank\">http://creators.ning.com/forum/topics/alternatives-1</a>\n\n\nI imagine that most people are going to end up at the same ning-clone, so you might just want to see what the very passionate crowd flocks to as their new, free solution.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T12:26:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11727","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"My opinion is that if there is a viable free alternative out there (that we trust enough to move to), then i'd say we do that. But also....I think we've proven the value of this community, and i would hope we could raise the minimal funding required for a paid account on Ning if necessary.\n\nWithout going into too much detail about my annoyance of their dissolving the free option, I think that a paid service would be worth it....BUT....only if that paid service gets us the things we need for this community.\n\nI'm specifically talking about better spam prevention and user management. If we pay for the service, then i think we can expect a higher level of service. While it was free, i could understand us having to do a little more manual processes to handle the spam. But if there's no assurance or proof that a paid account would solve these problems...then I'm out....and i say let's move somewhere else.\n\nI don't think moving to pure bulletin board configuration is the answer...like phpBB. Having managed several of these in the past, i dont feel like phpBB meets the needs of this community. Yes...it could serve as a place to foster discussion, but i think the other pieces like Events, the new Meetup Plugin, Blogs, and Video/Photo options are important too. If there are modules/plugins to make phpBB do all this, then i'm all for it. But from my experience, phpBB is more for basic discussions only.\n\nSo....after all that...i say we wait to find out the pricing model, and then revisit the discussion at that time. Being one of the few admins who manage the Ning website itself, it's of the utmost importance to me that whatever we stay on, or move to, is easy to maintain.\n\nWould it be helpful if we planned on discussing this in person at our next meetup? By then we could know the pricing, and figure out where we go from there. Just a thought.","createdDate":"2010-04-16T03:42:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11725","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I'm open to a number of these ideas - phpBB would work and Moodle does have a lot of the elements we need; heck maybe we even do something relatively simple like a WordPress blog.\n\nI think the real downfall of moving is the exit strategy. I'm not sure how prepared Ning is for getting people off of Ning but there's a lot of content in here that's very valuable and I'd hate to leave it behind. As Mike said, we just got this thing going.\n\nAgain, depending on the cost I think we consider sticking around. I'm mad and want to bail out of spite but that's rarely the right answer. Snooping around for details on the current premium offerings I think there may also be some tools that we would use if we do go with the upgrade. So I say we wait and see... who know, the backlash may even be sufficient to make the Ning folks back off the plan a little, or at least grandfather us in at a reduced rate.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T21:05:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11723","contributorName":"3d59zvph0dryj","description":"Just throwing this out too as a possible alternative:\n\n<a href=\"http://sites.google.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://sites.google.com/</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:57:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11722","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Humm, sadness on that. There's Facebook, I suppose, it has many of the features (calendar/events, discussion, files) that Ning does. We could also see what options there are for FLOSS tools that do Ning-ly kinds of things and get them installed on some under-utilized server.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:46:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11720","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"This will have a huge impact. Unlike Facebook where tons of users provide content for free, which in turn helped establish Facebook as a valued brand, Ning does not seem to have any identity of its own. I always have to repeat myself several times before people grok what I'm talking about when I mention a Ning based site.\n\nY'all may not like it (I don't), but imagine how the 69 employees they laid off must feel. They are trying to get to a survival mode.\n\nI don't think the cash costs are really that high on a per member basis. I'd be more concerned about the intangible costs.\n\nUnless it is funded by donations, someone has to put the support cost into a budget item. I imagine that is getting harder to do these days. Even if funded by membership fees or corporate sponsorship, someone will still need to manage an account, whether in the form of a bank account or just a manila envelope and a ledger sheet. But funds are a lot easier to collect through an integrated payment system tied to a bank account set aside specifically for the site.\n\nNot so sure about groupsite.com. The basic service only allows 5 subgroups. \"Add more pages\" is an add-on expense. You may end up in the same boat after discovering what the limitations are.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:45:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11718","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I guess it's going to depend on how much they want. If it's $5 or $10 a month that's not bad. If it's $100 a month then we should start looking for something else. Apparently we won't know for ~2 weeks how much we can expect to pay.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:40:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11716","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Yeah, Ning is nice, but I won't be heartbroken if we move to something else. If I were to set some requirements about something we move to I'd make a list of things like:\n\n-ability to create and participate in discussion forums\n-ability to follow a thread by email\n-profiles\n-calendar of events\n\nNice to have:\n-RSS options\n-ability to create events and invite members\n-personal blogs\n\nI would throw out phpBB, that wouldn't be so bad. Moodle could work too..\n\nAnother random thought. it might also be nice to have a jabber room dedicated to web design/dev. Jabber would be nice regardless of what site we have I suppose.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:33:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11711","contributorName":"3d59zvph0dryj","description":"I've got a marketing and <a href=\"http://cuthrell.com/solutions/startups/\" target=\"_blank\">sponsorship budget</a> for 2010. If someone from the NCSU team can price up what it would take to stay here I'll throw my hat in the ring to dig into that number.\n\n-Jay\nNCSU Class of <s>1994</s> <s>1995</s> 1996","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:17:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11709","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Seems like we finally got a good thing going,... I would hate to basically have to start over with some other service. Might be worth the cost.","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:11:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11707","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I think this is a dumb move on Ning's part. I'm sure they could better monetize their free offerings while still keeping it free for the users...but it's their loss really. I'm sure this decision will create a really great opportunity for some other competing company to step up and embrace the exodus from Ning.\n\nThere's a similar service called Groupsite (<a href=\"http://www.groupsite.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.groupsite.com</a>) that's free for the basic service. Never used it, but might be worth looking into. I wonder if we can export our content from here somehow?","createdDate":"2010-04-15T19:58:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11682","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"HTML 5 Browser Support","description":"I ran the HTML 5 browser support test at <a href=\"http://www.html5test.com\">http://www.html5test.com</a> on a bunch of browsers and I thought I'd share the results.\u00a0 I'm going only post the results for Chrome, Safari, and Firefox because Opera didn't so so hot and IE failed miserably on nearly every single test case.\u00a0 That browser is pretty much irrelevant when it comes to anything...ever.<br/><br/>Chrome 5.0.342.9 - 137 / 160<br/>Safari 4.0.5 - 113 / 160<br/>FF 3.6.3 - 101 / 160<br/>Opera 10.1 - 38 / 160<br/>IE 8 - 19 / 160<br/>IE 7 - 11 / 160<br/>IE 6 - 11 / 160<br/>IE 5 - 7 / 160<br/><br/>Just click on the image to see the full size version.<br/><br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Chrome</span> 5.0.342.9<br/><p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a target=\"_blank\" class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/14-chromehtml5test.png\"><img src=\"discussions/15-chromehtml5test.png?width=100\"/></a></p>\n<br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Safari 4.0.5<br/></span><p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/16-safarihtml5test.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/17-safarihtml5test.png?width=94\" alt=\"\"/></a></p>\n<br/><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Firefox</span> 3.6.3<br/><p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/18-firefoxhtml5test.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/19-firefoxhtml5test.png?width=96\" alt=\"\"/></a></p>\n<br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-12T17:43:32.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-05-03T19:24:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11849","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"guess there's always the acid tests too","createdDate":"2010-05-03T19:24:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11773","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"By the way, those responsible for the HTML5 Test are working on a <a href=\"http://beta.html5test.com/\" target=\"_blank\">new version</a> which is currently available for beta testing. Chrome 5.0.342.9 (beta channel) scores a 167 and 4 bonus points (without any runtime flags). IE8 still scores an abysmal 28 and no bonus points. I always find these \"tests\" neat because they encourage vendors to have \"high scores\" or \"compliance\" which pushes the state of the art to a new level. :)","createdDate":"2010-04-26T20:07:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11713","contributorName":"211tgo999ov7e","description":"It definitely isn't complete since it leaves out the handful of things of the spec that IE does support. For example, postMessage (supported in all browsers) and the onhashchange event, which is a personal favorite of mine though is only now getting support in Chrome (5+) and Firefox (3.6+).","createdDate":"2010-04-15T20:20:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11703","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Quirks Mode is a great resource: <a href=\"http://www.quirksmode.org/compatibility.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.quirksmode.org/compatibility.html</a>\n\nHere's their CSS3 stuff: <a href=\"http://www.quirksmode.org/css/contents.html#CSS3\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.quirksmode.org/css/contents.html#CSS3</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-15T13:11:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11700","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I don't know of anything like the html5 test, but this site is useful for it: <a href=\"http://css3please.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://css3please.com/</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-14T17:23:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11699","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Is there a CSS3 test out there?","createdDate":"2010-04-14T17:12:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11696","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Nice catch Mitch. I didn't realize that 5.0.x wasn't the stable build. I'm clearly not part of the Chrome userbase. :)","createdDate":"2010-04-14T12:38:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11695","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Incidentally, the stable build of Chrome at 4.1.249 comes in at a score of 118. There is a lot of stuff in that beta.","createdDate":"2010-04-13T20:26:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11693","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks for the link to this neat test. It will be interesting to see how well Opera 10.5 (released for Windows) and Firefox 3.7 (still alpha) score on this. I'm always excited to see what Chrome is doing to shove the browser community into the future rather than waiting the community (or allowing Internet Explorer) to catch up. I think that they've really taken up the flag on this that has been carried by Firefox, Webkit, and Opera for a long time. By being bold they're doing a great job of legitimizing open, progressive browser standards. For many IE users, they consider it to be the sole \"explorer\" for the \"Internet\". However, the vast majority of people recognize Google as providing a high quality Internet experience and will trust them to provide their browser (among their other tools).\n\n/happydance","createdDate":"2010-04-13T13:23:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11690","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Yep, when you enable the geolocation support it goes to 142/160.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/20-chrome_with_geolocationhtml5test.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/21-chrome_with_geolocationhtml5test.png?width=129\" alt=\"\"/></a></p>","createdDate":"2010-04-12T19:38:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11685","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Surprised by the soft support for geolocation in Chrome. I thought that was just recently added.\nThink the score might increase if you use the --enable-geolocation startup parameter?","createdDate":"2010-04-12T19:18:20.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11661","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","title":"Wordpress MU at State","description":"Does anyone have experiences to share regarding use of the Wordpress MU system? <br/><br/>I recently received a request to incorporate blogs into a .org domain hosted at NC State.\u00a0 Wordpress is the leader, and I'm wondering if there is anything grievous I should watch out for. (I ran into open_basedir=\".\" installing Joomla a while ago.) \u00a0 <br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-12T00:17:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-12T20:26:30.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11691","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Thanks for your insights Tony. Our application is initially being discussed to support a few designated posters, but I can see the possibly of it shifting toward a more broad based community blogging,","createdDate":"2010-04-12T20:26:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11683","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Yes, that's one of our lackings, sadly. We don't have a good \"See our blogs\" which highlights various blogs \"out there\". One I contribute to is <a href=\"http://blog.ecu.edu/techtips\" target=\"_blank\">TechTips</a>.\n\nI just mentioned that we're doing LDAP (really Active Directory, but WordPress only does LDAP) to give you a bit of details about our setup. It's easy enough to do manual user management, including specifying people as blog owners and letting people manage multiple blogs. The Dashboard of MU handles multi blog roles easily, so that you are admin of X while being simple contributor of Y.\n\nOur blogs.ecu.edu is available to all faculty, staff, and students. We also take requests for \"custom\" blogs with user-requested names. The requestor is given admin access, which lets you add other users. We don't allow non-registered users, which in our setup effectively means that we (even admins) can't add non-ECU people to the system. We do not restrict blog owners if they want anonymous comments, though.\n\nPlugins and themese can be requested, and the only vetting we do is to make sure the plugins work nicely with MU and don't offer the possibility of exposing user information (say, because plugin author didn't do a fully MU-compatible plugin).\n\nJust for further info, here are hte plugins we're running:\nAddToAny, Calendar, Contact Form 7, DBD Login Style, FD Feedburner Plugin, Feedburner Widget, Flickr Widget, GD Star Rating, MobilePress, PollDaddy Polls, Popularity Contest, SI CAPTCHA Anti-Spam, SlideShare, Smart YouTube, Sociable, Twitter Tools, Viper's Video Quicktas, Wibiya Toolbar, Wordpress Popup Scheduler, WPMU Fast Verifictation for Google Webmaster Tools and Yahoo! Site Explorer, WPTouch iPhone Theme.","createdDate":"2010-04-12T19:11:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11674","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Jason, it is very good to know that tidbit of information. Depending on when a stable release is settled upon, we may be able to go with that.","createdDate":"2010-04-12T14:30:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11673","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Thanks Tony. We don't use unity ids due to the fact that the \".org\" membership is not connected in any way to a status as a student or staff at NC State. Forgive me if I confuse the acronyms, but we are supported by ITECS with hosting platform similar/identical to that running the engineering school Web. I have the sysadmins there to thank for on going support of our LAMP setup. They do a great job. The environment is rather strict though -- with good reason.\n\nYour example could help the project people I'm supporting to think about how they will use the blogging. I am a little confused about the navigation though. When I go to the blog.ecu.edu site, I can only find one blog by Stephen Corey. None of the links I tried got me on to a path of discovering anything more than the Welcome page.","createdDate":"2010-04-12T14:26:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11671","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm not sure of anything on campus that runs MU, but there is plenty of wordpressing going on. I know lots of universities have implemented this though, so it seems as though its a viable solution. And it appears that MU support will be default in Wordpress 3.0 which is due out soon... (<a href=\"http://mashable.com/2010/04/03/wordpress-3-0/\" target=\"_blank\">http://mashable.com/2010/04/03/wordpress-3-0/</a>)","createdDate":"2010-04-12T13:57:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11667","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"We're using WordPress MU to server as our campus blogging system. We're using LDAP for authentication and user management. Every person's Pirate ID (I think you guys at NCSU call it unity id) / password will log you in. If it's the first time you've logged in, then you get a new blog created as <a href=\"http://blog.ecu.edu/sites/pirateid\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.ecu.edu/sites/pirateid</a>. Some of the plugins users have requeted don't play well in MU vs. single user, but we have been able to use a fair number. We also grabbed a free theme pack for your users, a collection of themes that work well with MU. That's the other thing you might want to watch for, is that some of the free themes you've run across might not work nicely in MU.\n\nWe're running a separate web server vs. database server, but both are RHEL 5.4 stock, with no additional repositories necessary to support MU. I don't think we had to enable any \"interesting\" settings in php.ini, but I can check for you.\n\nI'll also double check with our primary MU installer/configuration manager to see if there's any tips we can pass on.\n\nExecutive summary: It should Just Work.\n\nPS: You can see our blog blog at <a href=\"http://blog.ecu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.ecu.edu</a> and see some of the support for our users plus (some) of the plugins we've added.","createdDate":"2010-04-12T12:09:15.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11636","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","title":"We Know Where You've Been Going on the Internet","description":"Your privacy on the Internet is in shambles and you can blame ugly purple links.<br/><br/>L. David Baron, a Firefox developer, has put up an interesting post about <a href=\"http://dbaron.org/mozilla/visited-privacy\">the dangers of :visited links and how to keep your web history private</a>.<br/><br/>For those of you who don't want to click through, through the use of CSS and/or JavaScript, I can use brute force style guess and check to see if you've been to websites and record that information. This is surprisingly simple because of the :visited CSS pseudo-class.<br/><br/>You might not be worried if you're careful about what you leave in your history or how you browse when you go to potentially embarrassing web pages. However, there are some thing to keep in mind. The solution being proposed will noticeably impact the usefulness of :visited differentiations. Other than colors, you will not be able to alter the CSS for a :visited link. Whatever background images or font sizes/faces/decoration that you set for regular links will carry over to the :visited links to prevent from additional attack vectors.<br/><br/>Also, if you have any code that takes advantage of this security vulnerability, then you're probably going to lose this battle.<br/><br/>Users who want to be safe from such exploits need to disable visited links, which can be done in Firefox 3.5 and newer\nusing the <code>layout.css.visited_links_enabled</code> preference in<br/>\n<code><a href=\"http://kb.mozillazine.org/About:config\">about:config</a></code>. This is also a great option for those who despise visited link styles.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-06T19:05:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-06T19:07:48.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11584","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Detect Browsers via jQuery","description":"Today in the Web Developer Meetup, Garrison mentioned the jQuery plugin to do browser detection....<br/><br/>here it is:<br/><br/><a href=\"http://jreject.turnwheel.com/\">http://jreject.turnwheel.com/</a><br/><br/><br/>Enjoy......if for no other reason, please use it to reject ie6.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-04-01T18:40:21.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-01T18:40:22.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11561","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","title":"Virtual Wrap on Text Fields","description":"<ul>\n<li>Using Dreamweaver for HTML editing</li>\n<li>Using inForm<br/></li>\n</ul>\nWhen I create online forms, I want to make sure that if the user hits the return key that it indeed serves as a return in a text box, as opposed to acting as an \"enter\" command and submitting the form.<br/><br/>Thus, I use \"virtual wrap.\" However, \"virtual wrap\" is only available on a Textarea (with multiple lines) and not on a Text Field (which is a single line).<br/><br/> The end result is that on every form I create, every single text box is at least 2 lines, and not very clean looking. Here is a sample:<br/> <a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/student_affairs/survey/pmp/\">http://ncsu.edu/student_affairs/survey/pmp/</a><br/><br/>I'd like to be able to have single line text boxes for those items that are truly just one line, but don't know how any alternative coding to the virtual wrap solution. <br/><br/>Anybody got suggestions?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-28T12:59:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-30T17:17:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11574","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Excellent! This does exactly what I want it to do. Thanks!","createdDate":"2010-03-30T17:17:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11572","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"Leslie,\n\nYou need to add a little javascript, it's pretty straight forward and you can find it at <a href=\"http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex16/disableenter.htm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex16/disableenter.htm</a>\n\nBasically you will include the Java Script in the header and then add a \"onKeyPress\" to it. The website has pretty good instructions. Let me know if you get stuck.","createdDate":"2010-03-30T15:12:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11568","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm confused about why you want to make a one line field that can accept line feeds.\n\nGiven that, you can set the textarea height to \"one line\" using CSS. Something like the following might work.\n\ntextarea.text_field {\nheight: 1em;\n}\n\n&lt;textarea class=\"text_field\"&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;\n\n\nAlso, for what it's worth, wrap=\"virtual\" doesn't do anything on my version of Firefox, so I'm not sure if that's an Internet Explorer hack or what.","createdDate":"2010-03-30T14:49:35.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11553","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Social Media Use @ NC State","description":"In my Wednesday, March 24, 2010 class of <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Social Media and Technical Communication</span>, a course in NC State's <a href=\"http://english.chass.ncsu.edu/graduate/ms/msprogram.php\">Master of Science in Technical Communication</a> curriculum, I did my presentation on how social media is being used in a business. I chose NC State as the \"business\" about which to present.<br/><br/>I've made <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/nematome/social-media-at-nc-state\">the presentation</a> available on Slideshare if anyone's interested.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-26T19:17:16.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-26T19:17:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11533","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Internal Site Search","description":"Hey web dudes.<br/><br/>I'd like to embed a customized search engine on a directory page for one of our departments.\u00a0 All the pages that I want to search live in a single sub-directory.\u00a0 So I could use Google Custom Site Search, but then I lose some control and I don't have as many options with interface design (for example, pretty sure you can't use logged search terms as suggestions).\u00a0 So I'd like to experiment with installing a PHP open source search engine like <a href=\"http://www.sphider.eu/\">Sphider</a><br/><br/>Anyone have any experience with playing with open source PHP/MySQL search engines?\u00a0 I like Sphider, but the templating system is a little restrictive.\u00a0 I'd like something that I can just call within a given page.\u00a0 Thoughts?\u00a0 Comments?<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-25T13:19:37.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-30T14:56:20.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11570","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks for the link. I googled it and it looks like the community answer is <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/555523/file-get-contents-vs-curl-what-has-better-performance\" target=\"_blank\">cURL wins the performance battle</a>.","createdDate":"2010-03-30T14:56:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11551","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I basically made slight modifications to <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/ajaxsearch/documentation/#fonje\" target=\"_blank\">some example code</a> I uncovered in Google's API docs, they were already using cURL (hopefully for a good reason, Google usually has one. Here's <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/gdata/articles/using_cURL.html\" target=\"_blank\">their rant on cURL</a>), but yeah I don't see why file_get_contents wouldn't work. Making that change alone would save several lines of code.\n\nThanks for the suggestions below.","createdDate":"2010-03-26T16:11:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11547","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"By the way, you could probably use this instead of the preg_match and str_replace: list($requestedUrl, $querySegment[0]) = explode('?', $_SERVER['REQUEST_URI'], 2);\n\nOf course, there's always $_SERVER['QUERY_STRING'] which has the $querySegment and $_SERVER['PHP_SELF'] which has the $requestedUrl built in.\n\nWhen filtering the empties out of the $url_parts, you can use array_filter() if you want to be extra cautious.\n\nFWIW, sizeof($results)&gt;0 can be represented by !empty($results). isset and empty are language constructs so they don't incur function overhead.\n\nThanks for the nice search ajax api example. It's nice to have a resource for using these useful tools.","createdDate":"2010-03-26T13:41:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11546","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Mike,\n\nWhy cURL and not file_get_contents? Is there a noticeable difference in your testing?\n\nMy main opposition to cURL is the ugly and verbose initialization and configuration functions.","createdDate":"2010-03-26T13:20:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11541","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Here's an example of that code in action:\n<a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/programs/international/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/programs/international/</a>","createdDate":"2010-03-25T15:25:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11540","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Charlie,\n\nYou can execute google searches for your site using PHP and cURL. We do this for the 404 error pages on a lot of our domains. We take the domain.ncsu.edu/missing-directory/some-file-request.php and break it out into \"missing directory some file request\" and ask google to return a list of suggested pages...\n\nHere's the code:\n<a href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/search-google/php-code.txt\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/preview/search-google/php-code.txt</a>\n\nEnjoy,\nMike","createdDate":"2010-03-25T15:15:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11536","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"We use the Zend Framework implementation of Lucene extensively in Classmate and that's worked really great for us. It's super flexible, very fast, and powerful. It's not too difficult to get setup either, but you can't just drop it in and have it work.\n\nYou can find info on how to get started with Zend Search Lucene here: <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/learning.lucene.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/learning.lucene.html</a>","createdDate":"2010-03-25T13:54:40.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11530","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"NC State's ASPSA looking for a Student Web Developer","description":"<div>The Academic Support Program for Student Athletes (ASPSA) is looking for assistance in creating and building a new website.\u00a0 We are\nseeking an experienced individual who has demonstrated creativity,\nefficiency, and proficiency in website building and maintenance.\u00a0 This\nwould be a great opportunity for a student who would like some\npractical experience working with an agency on website design and\nstructure or for students who are in need of an internship or summer\nproject in the area of website development.\u00a0 The site is strictly\ninformational based and the student would be given the content to post,\nbut would be responsible, in collaboration with our department, for\nbuilding the look, design, and layout of the website.\u00a0 The anticipated\ncompletion date for the site would be August 1, 2010.<br/></div>\n<div>Please let me know what else you might need!<br/><br/><div>Alison R. Ruff</div>\n<div>Assistant Director<br/>Academic Support Program for Student Athletes<br/>North Carolina State University<br/>332\u00a0Case Academic Center, Box 7104<br/>Raleigh, NC\u00a0 27695</div>\n<div>919-515-4502</div>\n<div>919-515-1619 Fax</div>\n<div><a href=\"mailto:alison_ruff@ncsu.edu\">alison_ruff@ncsu.edu</a></div>\n<br/></div>","createdDate":"2010-03-23T20:39:02.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-23T20:39:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11323","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"SACS Accreditation?","description":"I had extremely good luck tracking down the PRR site maintainer, and have gotten good ideas from all over NCSU for some of the things we're doing with that at ECU.\u00a0 It's now time for SACS Accreditation renewal, and our team has been tasked with providing \"something\" to be able to provide a work space while the documentation is being collected, created, and edited as well as a way to transform the work space into a completely standalone CD or DVD that contains all information.<br/><br/>Does anyone out there in NCSU Web Developers land know how NCSU is/has handled this task?\u00a0 We're rummaging through ideas and have several ways of providing a usable collaborative space.\u00a0 It's the standlone disc at the end that's been the challenge.<br/><br/>Pointers to NCSU staff/teams who have done this, or even ideas if this problem were dropped in your lap, gratefully accepted.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-10T18:58:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-12T14:00:44.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11426","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Perhaps Mediawiki? I know there's an export tool for that which people use to create yearly \"releases\" of Wikipedia similar to the encyclopedia of yesteryear.\n\nI would also wonder if Google Docs wouldn't achieve your goals.\n\nIt's unclear what sorts of data and who the participants are, so it's difficult to know what solution would be appropriate.","createdDate":"2010-03-12T14:00:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11371","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"I don't know anything about the kinds of collaborations you need to enable for a SACS team, but what about Adobe Contribute? I heard that Ellen McDaniels was having some good success in using that to facilitate collaborative editing while maintaining control over the standardized content.","createdDate":"2010-03-11T13:26:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11362","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Tony,\n\nAt my former institution, the SACS accreditation information was collected used to create an HTML website that could easily be copied and stuck on a CD. This meant that the SACS visitors could use the CD's information without an Internet connection, and it was synchronized with the live website (up until the CD was burned).\n\nThat was at a much smaller institution, and the scale will probably be a problem for you at ECU.\n\nIf there was a way to stand up a CMS instance, maybe Drupal (i dont know if it would work), that has a \"<a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/html_export\" target=\"_blank\">export to HTML</a>\" plugin or module, that might work.\n\nIE: Create all the content and attachments using Drupal, assigning permissions to everyone for their specific areas, and then when the content is completed, just export the site to an HTML version and dump to a disc.\n\nDon't know if it would work, but it's an idea :-)\n\nI'm happy to chat with you about how we did it at the smaller institution if you need more details. The SACS process there lasted a couple of years due to financial probation, but the academic and information gathering side of things went really well. We were even commended from the SACS visitors for how effective the CD was for them.","createdDate":"2010-03-11T13:05:41.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11046","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"New Accessibility Guidelines and Standards","description":"Here is the presentation that Saroj gave at the March meetup as well as the document she referenced with the summarization of the new accessibility guidelines.<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-04T20:39:03.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-08T14:07:10.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/22-Revision508_WCAG2.docx","discussions/23-workingwithaccessibilitystandards.ppt"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11653","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Fun stuff! I have some ideas that I'm trying to send in an e-mail, but SMTP is acting up.","createdDate":"2010-04-08T14:07:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11649","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"This is not golden, maybe not even silver or brass, but it is a start at implementing the algorithm as a jQuery plugin.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.agilemarkup.net/examples/Contrasty/jQueryContrastyTest.html\" target=\"_blank\">jQueryContrastyTest.html</a>","createdDate":"2010-04-07T21:46:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11648","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My options were the nose-less :( and the more appropriately oriented but less clear muted emotion -_-","createdDate":"2010-04-07T12:26:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11638","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"We who are old enough use ASCII :-(","createdDate":"2010-04-06T20:02:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11637","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks Mitch. Sadly, no Linux version.\n\nSide note: Ning needs emoticons.","createdDate":"2010-04-06T19:14:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11634","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Also, <a href=\"http://www.paciellogroup.com/resources/contrast-analyser.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.paciellogroup.com/resources/contrast-analyser.html</a> for a desktop utility.","createdDate":"2010-04-06T16:33:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11629","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Someone provided a link to a Luminosity / Constrast Ratio tool:\n<a href=\"http://juicystudio.com/services/luminositycontrastratio.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://juicystudio.com/services/luminositycontrastratio.php</a>\n\nThanks!!","createdDate":"2010-04-05T20:09:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11409","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This is linked to by the docx: <a href=\"http://www.access-board.gov/sec508/refresh/report/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.access-board.gov/sec508/refresh/report/</a>\n\nIt is very useful for specific explanations of things such as the \"situations listed below\" from 3-F. Most importantly: 6. DECORATION, Formatting, Invisible Objects: If a NON-TEXT OBJECT is pure DECORATION, or used only for visual formatting, or if it is not presented to users, then it must be implemented such that it can be ignored by ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY.\n\nOf course, I'm still concerned by how vague 3-A is: \"Color must not be used as the only visual means of conveying [something]\". So does bold count?\n\nAlso, calculating the Contrast Ratios using the Relative Luminance of the text and the background over which it lays using the conditional parts calculations which are piecewise combined to form a normalized value for colors which are not black or white is ... interesting. Anyone know of a tool that will take RGB 0-255 and map it to the Relative Luminance? Bonus points for taking two RGBs in hex and providing a Relative Luminance for both and the associated Contrast Ratio.\n\n5:1 Contrast Ratios that you probably want to avoid:\n#009100 : #000000 and #FFFFFF : #AD00FF","createdDate":"2010-03-11T15:04:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11036","contributorName":"0g1pmuyk03upi","title":"CSS Issue - IE 7","description":"All, <br/><br/>I seem to have an CSS styling issue, only with IE 7. Could someone please let me know what the fix is?<br/><br/>Problem: I am trying to create a drop down navigation bar with list and applying CSS styles to it. Everything looks fine, except when you try to select a list item in the drop down, the selection range is bigger in IE 7. The selection range works fine in other browsers. <br/><br/>Please see attached screenshots. As you can see, in the IE 8 screenshot, the gray background perfectly fits the text, but in the IE 7 screenshot it does not fit the text, also the link to the webpage only appears on the text and not on the whole box. <br/><br/>I have also attached the CSS. The website is WRAP protected, and the link is <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/internal_audit/new\">http://www.ncsu.edu/internal_audit/new</a><br/><br/>If someone has a solution please let me know. Also, email me if you have any questions/clarifications on the issue.<br/><br/>Thank you, <br/>Satya<br/>","createdDate":"2010-03-04T15:40:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-10T13:38:17.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/24-IE8Screenshot.Bmp","discussions/25-IE7Screenshot.Bmp","discussions/26-primary.css"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11299","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"You might be running into a quirks mode issue. Have you run the page through the W3C HTML Validator? Also, there's a lot of CSS hacks in the file you provided; it might be a good idea to remove the CSS hacks that refer to IE5, Opera 7, IEmac and the like.\n\nIt's difficult to diagnose without being able to see the page in action. Have you tested it in Firefox?","createdDate":"2010-03-10T13:38:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11038","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I'm not in the list of valid users to see the website, so I can't see it in action. Plus I don't have anything that has IE7 on it. So I can't be of much help in actually helping fix it. But I can suggest trying a reset script that basically puts all the defaults on a level playing ground so what you see is only what you apply. I suspect this might fix your issue. I recommend the reset script from Yahoo's YUI toolkit.\n\nYou can read about and get it here: <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/reset/\" target=\"_blank\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/reset/</a>\n\nI'd also recommend the base and fonts scripts. And I highly recommend grids for your layout, but that's a separate discussion altogether.\n\nJust make sure you include the reset and base files before any of your custom stylesheets.\n\nHope that helps!\n\nGarrison","createdDate":"2010-03-04T15:47:15.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:11002","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Super Simple Mobile Device Detection","description":"for some reason, the feeds and announcements on Ning aren't doing as good a job as i'd hoped. So this is just a quick plug for the post i put up yesterday about doing simple device detection<br/><br/>I updated the examples today to include the use of sessions to cache the detected device, which means you could easily implement this in an application, dreamweaver template or whatever. But this is just a start that i thought might help people be able to play around with Mobile device detection without having to reinvent the wheel.<br/><br/>Ning post here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/mobileweb/forum/topics/simple-device-detection\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/mobileweb/forum/topics/simple-device-detection</a><br/><br/>Examples &amp; Code here: <a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/njyoung/device-detection/\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/njyoung/device-detection/</a><br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-24T20:47:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-03T23:26:56.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11030","contributorName":"2skeqjhmxavkg","description":"Look also this project \"Apache Mobile Filter\".\n\nOpenSource Project: Apache Mobile Filter - <a href=\"http://www.idelfuschini.it/apache-mobile-filter-v2x.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.idelfuschini.it/apache-mobile-filter-v2x.html</a>\nTest Page: <a href=\"http://www.apachemobilefilter.org/test/php_test.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.apachemobilefilter.org/test/php_test.php</a>\nMobile Test Page: <a href=\"http://www.apachemobilefilter.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.apachemobilefilter.org</a>\n\nLet me know your opinion","createdDate":"2010-03-03T23:26:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11005","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It shows up on the \"Most Recent Activity\" feed, but that one gets bombarded by things like status changes and RSVPs. Were this a standard forum I'd definitely *bump* this thread. It's a useful example, particularly for those looking to have a more complete integration with the varied devices out there.","createdDate":"2010-02-25T14:01:18.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10995","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Simple Device Detection Example","description":"I put a PHP code snippet together the other day as a way to to quick device detection. It was a really quick project, and i figured other people might want to use it too instead of reinventing the wheel.<br/><br/>I can't take any credit whatsoever for this though....it was pulled out of the Mobile Framework that is being used on the <a href=\"http://m.ncsu.edu\">http://m.ncsu.edu</a> site. I just stole the relevant parts.<br/><br/>Here's the example (which has a zip file to download the code as well):<br/><br/><div style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/device-detection-example\">http://go.ncsu.edu/device-detection-example</a><br/></div>\n<br/>As it says on the example page, this is intended to be a quick way to do device detection, and to subsequently switch style sheets based on the result. <br/><br/>As you'll see, this is really just good for single page projects. I have another method that uses a PHP file as the CSS file to do all the detection/processing, and it is linked from that same page above. The 2nd example will cache the device detection result, meaning it's useful in templates or larger applications.<br/><br/>If anyone has improvements or suggestions, please let me know.<br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-23T20:01:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-25T16:19:03.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11009","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"thanks for catching that css omission. It's updated in the example and the zip file now.\n\nAs for the pieces of the regex, i'm not sure. I'm no expert on the regex part, as i grabbed this directly from the mobile framework we're using for the m.ncsu.edu site. Maybe someone else can weigh in on this?","createdDate":"2010-02-25T16:19:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11003","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Ah, ok. I still wonder if the following line would throw a warning when the index was not defined (can we assume it is always defined?):\n\nif ($_SERVER['HTTP_USER_AGENT']) {\n\nInstead, the explicit equivalent seems like a better practice:\n\nif (!empty($_SERVER['HTTP_USER_AGENT'])) {\n\nFor the sake of simplicity, I'll also assume that the WURFL service returns valid XML (simplexml throws lots of warnings when it is not). And where I'm not sure what the non-greedy match anything is doing (given that it is not fixed at the start of the line), it's probably just because I haven't thrown any test strings at it to find out why it's needed.\n\nSo, moving on, the iphone-styles.css is missing a hash/pound (#) before the link color.\n\nPlease know that I think this is a nice example, which would get a lot of use for sites that want to offer heavy (or even just specific) mobile customization. Thank you Nick for making this example available with a more keen eye for the needs of the user (taking into account the limitations they may be facing).\n\nFor those interested in knowing the upper bound on how long those sessions will last (without activity): echo session_cache_expire() . ' minutes'; // set in the php.ini by session.cache_expire","createdDate":"2010-02-25T13:55:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11001","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Thanks for posting that suggestion Jonathan.\n\nI wanted to post an extremely easy to implement solution for device detection. So, instead of using the cached files (which as you suggest requires a directory, permissions set and a bunch more lines of code), i figured it would be easier to use sessions.\n\nSo....on the site, i have updated the examples to use session variables to store the device type, and therefore only make one call to the WURFL service. This makes it super simple to download the example and use it without having to create any other directories or set permissions.\n\n<a href=\"http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/njyoung/device-detection\" target=\"_blank\">http://oitdesign.ncsu.edu/njyoung/device-detection</a> has everything that people will need to do this now.","createdDate":"2010-02-24T20:43:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10999","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The caching isn't working. I think it's related to the fact that PHP files aren't sending (and shouldn't) a far future expires header. Additionally, that relies on the browser cache (which can't help you when your site is flooded by unique users). Rather, you could do something like this:\n* cd njyoung/device-detection\n* mkdir cache\n* fs sa cache www:servers.php rlidwk\nThen within the PHP, prepend within the function:\n$cacheFolder = 'cache/'; // A more-absolute path would be preferable\n$ua = $_SERVER['HTTP_USER_AGENT'];\n$cachefilename = $cacheFolder . md5($ua);\n// If you only want it to cache once ever, remove the mtime, or adjust the cache duration as needed (86400 = 1 day)\nif (file_exists($cachefilename) &amp;&amp; filemtime($cachefilename) &gt; time() - 86400) {\n// NOTE: Only use one of these lines, depending on what you write to the cache file. Unless you need other data in the xml file, it might be better to go with just the $type result (less overhead)\n$res = simplexml_load_file($cachefilename);\n$type = file_get_contents($cachefilename);\n}\nelse {\n// NOTE: Put all of your current code here (and wrap the if ($ua) call in a !empty() so that it is if (!empty($ua)) { } ).\n\n// Again, only use one of these, depending on which one you picked above\nfile_put_contents($cachefilename, $result, LOCK_EX);\nfile_put_contents($cachefilename, $type, LOCK_EX);\n}","createdDate":"2010-02-24T13:53:19.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10993","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Any experience working with Google Scholar?","description":"Recently, we started pulling in a list of research publications for each of our departments in the College of Engineering using the <a href=\"http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/repository/scholpubs/ws/ws.php?service=search&amp;limit=0&amp;type=affiliation&amp;query=23\">feed provided by the library</a> (thanks guys!). We output these lists in various places, here's an example: <a href=\"http://www.or.ncsu.edu/research/\">http://www.or.ncsu.edu/research/</a><br/><br/>We also provide a link on each page for faculty members to submit publications that aren't yet listed. (This is our way of hopefully pushing them [gently of course] all to a single source).<br/><br/>There was a good post on the Google Webmaster Central Blog the other day announcing their support for a new rich snippet to be used in our html that would <a href=\"http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2010/01/introducing-new-rich-snippets-format.html\">help Google index our events</a>. We're going to give this a whirl with the Engineering Career Fair website.<br/><br/>I was wondering if maybe someone in the library was aware of anything similar we should be doing with our mark up for scholarly pubs and Google Scholar? <br/><br/>When we generate these lists of research publications, where should we be linking to?<br/>The only place I see in the feed that we can link to is <span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"border-collapse: separate; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; font-size: medium;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><a href=\"http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/repository/scholpubs/search?page=detail&amp;amp;cid=\">http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/repository/scholpubs/search?page=detail&amp;amp;cid=</a>[INSERT CITATION ID]</span></span> , is that correct?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>-Mike<br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-23T19:30:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-03-17T14:54:55.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11479","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Here's some documentation I found on Google's Rich Snippets... <a href=\"http://www.google.com/support/webmasters/bin/topic.py?hl=en&amp;topic=21997\" target=\"_blank\">there's specific markup you can use to help Google index People, Ev...</a>... but not too much along the lines of Scholarly publications.\n\nHere's the response I got back from Google's Scholar team when I asked the same question...\n\n<span style=\"font-style:italic; color:#c00;\">\nThanks for your recent email to Google Scholar. We've included answers to\na number of frequently asked questions in our response below. If you have\na question or concern that is not addressed by these answers, please reply\nto this email for further assistance.\n\nLibrary Links Program - Getting Started:\nIf you'd like your institution's electronic holdings to be made available\nthrough our Library Links program, you can do so by choosing the Google\nScholar option in your link resolver. We're working with vendors to make\nregistration and updates as easy as possible for you. If you don't see\nthis option, please contact your link resolver for information on when it\nwill be available.\n\nUpdating Your Library Links:\nIf you would like to make updates to an existing Library Links\nconfiguration, please contact your link resolver directly, as they are\nbest suited to help you make these changes. Once any changes have been\nmade with your link resolver, Google Scholar should reflect these updates\nwithin 1-2 weeks. If you have any further questions after getting in touch\nwith your link resolver, please reply to this message and we'll be happy\nto help.\n\nHomegrown Link Resolver - Getting Started:\nIf you have a homegrown link resolver, you'll have to provide some\ninformation to us about your links and holdings. To provide us this\nnecessary information, please confirm that you've successfully completed\nthe steps at this link:\n<a href=\"http://scholar.google.com/intl/en/scholar/libraries.html#start4\" target=\"_blank\">http://scholar.google.com/intl/en/scholar/libraries.html#start4</a>. Once you\nhave posted these files on your site, please reply to this email and\nprovide those links to us. We'll then pass your details on to our\nspecialists for review and inclusion.\n\n\nIf you continue to have questions or concerns about Google Scholar, please\nreply to this email and one of our specialists will assist you.\n\nSincerely,\n<strong>The Google Team</strong>\n</span>","createdDate":"2010-03-17T14:54:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11475","contributorName":"2x4fgj5slop6l","description":"Hi Mike,\n\nThe web service returns the URL to the landing page for each citation. The URL element occurs at /searchResponse/citation/url If we have the full-text the URL will point to the landing page for that. Otherwise, the URL will point to the SPR. The value that the SPR offers to Google Scholar, or vise versa, is unclear to me. I also wonder if pointing back to the landing page as the canonical URL would be appropriate. I'm not aware of any specific markup to enhance indexing of these citations, though.","createdDate":"2010-03-17T14:40:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10969","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Submit your meetup talks and vote on what you want to hear!","description":"I mentioned in our last meetup that we wanted to give the community a way to voice your opinion on what you want to hear as topics at future meetups.\u00a0 What we have done is setup a service to allow us to do this.\u00a0 It is accessible from the main navigation above ^ in the \"Meetups\" page.<br/><br/>The deal is that you can submit talks that you would like to give.\u00a0 Once your talk is in there, other folks in the community have the ability to vote \"thumbs up\" or \"thumbs down\" on your talk.\u00a0 Anyone in the community can vote and submit talks, so if you have something you want to share, please submit your talks.<br/><br/>About 2 weeks before the meetup, we will look at the list and grab the talk with the most votes to be presented at that meetup.\u00a0 Once it has been given, we will take it out of the list.<br/><br/>Basically, this gives the community the chance to vote up topics that you are interested in.\u00a0 So submit your talk ideas and vote away!","createdDate":"2010-02-18T19:35:31.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-18T19:35:31.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10681","contributorName":"0auiw0nx5h3m1","title":"Drupal and Cron","description":"Hello,<br/><br/>When triggering <a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php</a> the following is entered in /var/log/messages:<br/><br/>Feb 11 15:59:10 empedocles drupal: <a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu</a>|1265929150|php|128.196.139.209|<a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php</a>||0||mysql_query() [function.mysql-query]: Access denied for user 'apache'@'localhost' (using password: NO) in /data/websites/edu/arizona/d2l/help/includes/common.inc(1685) : eval()'d code on line 7.<br/>\u00a0<br/>Feb 11 15:59:10 empedocles drupal: <a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu</a>|1265929150|php|128.196.139.209|<a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php</a>||0||mysql_query() [function.mysql-query]: A link to the server could not be established in /data/websites/edu/arizona/d2l/help/includes/common.inc(1685) : eval()'d code on line 7.<br/><br/>Feb 11 15:59:10 empedocles drupal: <a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu</a>|1265929150|cron|128.196.139.209|<a href=\"http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php\">http://help.d2l.arizona.edu/cron.php</a>||0||Cron run exceeded the time limit and was aborted.<br/><br/>After looking at drupl_cron, and seeing how far the code gets, it looks like the module_invoke_all hook isn\u2019t doing its thing. <br/><br/>\u00a0<br/>Thanks,<br/>Dwight<br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-12T15:09:31.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-12T17:50:03.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10689","contributorName":"0auiw0nx5h3m1","description":"Thanks Jonathan, I will check these settings.\nDwight","createdDate":"2010-02-12T17:50:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10687","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The mysql_connect command appears to be being called with the default parameters, which results in the web server user \"apache\" attempting to make the connection to the mysql database without a password being specified. Make sure that the appropriate settings.php file is being included (such as sites/default/settings.php). <a href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/function.get-included-files.php\" target=\"_blank\">get_included_files()</a> will let you know which files have been included at a specific point in the execution.","createdDate":"2010-02-12T17:46:15.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10670","contributorName":"0g1pmuyk03upi","title":"Text Only website","description":"All, <br/><br/>Is there an application that we have on campus that we can use to create a text-only website. If we do not have an application available on campus, is there one available that can be used to convert / create a text-only version of an existing website. <br/><br/>Any help is appreciated. <br/><br/>Thank you, <br/>Satya<br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-10T21:03:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-15T13:46:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10683","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"If the goal... \"is for users that do not like graphics, and also to help users read better\"...\n\nYou can still accomplish this using CSS...\n\nHide all images...\nimg {display:none;}\n\nIncrease the contrast on your print...\nbody {color:#000; background:#fff;}\n\nMaybe you even adjust the spacing between lines and font size?\np {font-size:1.3em; line-height:1.5;}\n\n^ sure you could go into a lot more detail here, targeting only specific elements, classes or ids... and even playing with layout...\n\nBUT a lot of these considerations should be already factored into your default design, otherwise you're almost implying your website isn't usable/readable as it is, but you're giving users a way to make it that way...?","createdDate":"2010-02-12T16:32:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10677","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Sorry, I don't know of a tool that will do this.\n\nMost browsers allow you to disable images or CSS entirely at the click of a button. When you disable images and CSS, the goal is to have a website which still delivers both the navigation and content so that the accessibility still exists for users using text-only browsers (such as lynx) or accessibility software (such as screen readers).\n\n&lt;rant&gt;This might not be the nice thing to say, but it seems like these users should use a viewer which does this for them rather than put the pressure on you to meet their awkward demands.&lt;/rant&gt;","createdDate":"2010-02-12T13:37:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10674","contributorName":"0g1pmuyk03upi","description":"No, I have created a CSS to deal with the printer friendly version. This is for users that do not like graphics, and also to help users read better.","createdDate":"2010-02-11T13:46:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10672","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"What is the goal? To have a printer friendly version?","createdDate":"2010-02-11T13:26:21.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10649","contributorName":"0g1pmuyk03upi","title":"Secure (HTTPS) Pages for AFS websites","description":"All, <br/><br/>I wanted to know if its possible to create HTTPS pages on our departmental website which is located on AFS. Is there any other secure way that we can transmit information securely (encrypted). <br/><br/>Any suggestion would be appreciated. <br/><br/>Thank you, <br/>Satya<br/>","createdDate":"2010-02-04T14:04:32.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-04T16:35:04.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10656","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"There's some SSL stuff under <a href=\"https://ssl.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">https://ssl.ncsu.edu/</a>","createdDate":"2010-02-04T16:35:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10653","contributorName":"0g1pmuyk03upi","description":"Thanks Billy, will send in a call.","createdDate":"2010-02-04T14:32:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10651","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"Not all the vhosts are IP-based, but since IA is under <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">www.ncsu.edu</a> you should be able to. However when I try to load the main ncsu page over SSL, I get an error. I'd send in a call because you should be able to.","createdDate":"2010-02-04T14:26:25.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10620","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","title":"Newer Security Features - Featuring Chrome 4, Apache","description":"Neat post about the new security features in Chrome 4:\n<a href=\"http://blog.chromium.org/2010/01/security-in-depth-new-security-features.html\">http://blog.chromium.org/2010/01/security-in-depth-new-security-features.html</a>\n\nAnd here's how you can implement a couple of them easily in Apache (assuming you don't need to provide your content from iframes, otherwise it takes a little more work):\n<a href=\"https://secure.grepular.com/ClickJacking_and_SSL_Protection_in_Apache\">https://secure.grepular.com/ClickJacking_and_SSL_Protection_in_Apache</a>","createdDate":"2010-01-28T19:41:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-01-28T19:41:26.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10617","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"IMHO 7 Reasons Why Higher Ed Is the Toughest Gig in All the Web","description":"I saw this blog post today and it spoke to me.\u00a0 We have a tough job folks, and really the reasons in this blog post are only part of it.<br/><br/><a href=\"http://doteduguru.com/id4372-imho-7-reasons-why-higher-ed-is-the-toughest-gig-in-all-the-web.html\">http://doteduguru.com/id4372-imho-7-reasons-why-higher-ed-is-the-toughest-gig-in-all-the-web.html</a><br/><br/><br/>","createdDate":"2010-01-27T15:33:44.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-01-28T14:09:32.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10619","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Lost my message so bullets it is:\n* Grads are a waste of money because what they provide typically isn't maintainable. Only if it's a one time deal (that some developer isn't going to have to clean up or maintain later) or if the grad is a genius who wants to donate something out of the kindness of their heart will it be worthwhile.\n* Our salaries *are* public record, so when a flashy little app that took 2 months of developer time gets trashed because the customer changes their mind, they've just wasted SALARY / 6 dollars of your budget.\n* Collaboration *is* incentivized, because it means that there's less overhead that keeps you from doing the things you need to do. Saving a million dollars per year through collaboration and not creating custom implementations means that you can hire 10-20 developers so you can get the work done that is sitting on the back burner or filed away next to Duke Nukem Forever.","createdDate":"2010-01-28T14:09:32.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10539","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"NC jQuery & JavaScript Camp: Winter 2010","description":"In case you missed it in the calendar sidebar or activity display, I added an awesome event coming to Durham: <a href=\"http://ncjquerycamp2.eventbrite.com/\" target=\"_blank\">NC jQuery &amp; JavaScript Camp: Winter 2010</a>\n\nIt's a cheap (15 early bird, 20 normal, 50 sponsor) entry fee, and you can meet one of the folks from the <a href=\"http://yayquery.com/\" target=\"_blank\">YayQuery pod cast</a> (highly recommended). Hope to see some of you there!","createdDate":"2009-12-31T13:59:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-31T13:59:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10241","contributorName":"2ufpp019au6o6","title":"Looking For Web Development Service","description":"Hi, My name is Jennifer Clark, recently I have shiffted from Dallas to New York, we have a small business which is running successfully in Dallas, now we are opening a branch in New York, I am the one who have to take care the of the business and promote it as well. I am planning to make a web site of our branch, I am new to this city and looking for some local based company whom I can trust for the Website Development for my site, I came to know about webplore.com through one of my friend. Anybody any suggestion about this company as well you can also suggest me any other web development company also.","createdDate":"2009-12-07T04:32:33.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-07T04:33:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10127","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"State of the University Web Department Survey","description":"I follow the .eduGuru blog (<a href=\"http://doteduguru.com\">http://doteduguru.com</a>) and they recently did a survey about University Web Departments and how they were run. Here are the results.\n\n<a href=\"http://doteduguru.com/id3967-state-of-the-university-web-department-survey-results.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://doteduguru.com/id3967-state-of-the-university-web-department-survey-results.html</a>\n\nI wasn't really surprised by any of the results. A higher-than-I-thought response was the number of universities that don't have a \"homepage committee\". I guess at smaller institutions you don't have to committee-er-ize everything, but I did think that was interesting.","createdDate":"2009-11-23T18:39:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-02T14:06:55.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10232","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks Tony! I have a few quick questions if you don't mind.\n\nIs your CommonSpot installation purchased or licensed for a set time period? (If licensed, for how many years?)\nIs the cost on a site license basis or a per user basis?\nIs it hosted by Paperthin, ECU or a 3rd party?\nIn which programming language is it written?\nIn how many written languages is the interface available?\nLastly, any idea how much it costs? In total or per year or otherwise.","createdDate":"2009-12-02T14:06:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10231","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"As glad-to-be-here guests, I guess I'll chime in with ECU's answers to these questions (I don't know if we participated):\n\n1) Size [student body]: 20,000-30,000 (27,677)\n2) Landscape: Decentralized (mostly, but like you at NCSU we've got both kinds)\n3) Umm, I keep flipping on what the question is asking, but since we have a campus CMS, I think that makes us decentralized. However, for the top level pages we have ITCS, and within that we've got our \"Consulting Team\", which is a total of 7 people. That's not really a \"true\" number, however, because we've got the enterprise folks who keep the servers happy (another 10 or so people in total). In addition, we've got the Marketing group for design issues, another 10 people there, plus the very high level Web Oversight Committee.\n4) For those parts of the site that are centralized, it's determined by staff\n5) Ful time staff count: uhh, we actually have 600 registered contributors, of which I'd guess half that are active to very active.\n6) Centralized CMS that everyone uses (although there are some holdouts, which are being required to have at least a token presence in the next few months)\n7) Purchased CMS\n8) Company: Paperthin Product: CommonSpot\n9) Home page controlled by: see above (combo of Marketing + Consulting Team + Web Oversight Committee)\n10) Home page committee? Yes\n11) Redesign: &lt; 1 year ago (and we do continuous iterative redesign)\n12) Redesign handled: in-house\n13) Programming language: ColdFusion","createdDate":"2009-12-01T13:51:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10228","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Anyone know the correct answers for NCSU as an institution?","createdDate":"2009-11-30T14:28:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10129","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Wow, just wow. I can't believe they tried to extrapolate data from the responses they received. It looks like half the people who responded don't know anything about their institution (filling in things like \"Microsoft\" and \"Adobe\" for their CMS). Honestly, if you want to see margin of error, ask the same set of questions here and see how many people get it wrong.\n\nActually, that would probably make for a worthwhile result set: rather than just have 253 respondents (from 253 separate universities?), have multiple people from each school respond and make sure that an answer that isn't subjective has a majority before using the data.\n\nRealize of course that I don't think I'll get these correct, but that's the point. I'll be skipping the \"title\" question, because it's pointless, and the last two because they're entirely subjective.\n\n1. How large is your institution? He means how many students, which I will guess is around 34788\n2. What is the landscape of your web environment? Here he acts like centralized and decentralized are polar opposites. I'd say we're both.\n3. If centralized, how large is the full time staff? My guess is the centralized group would probably be OIT. Of course, it's hard to tell how much of the Org Chart would be counted for this metric. I would definitely include ISO, in addition to the usual suspects, but what is the qualifying test per person to determine inclusion as \"web environment full time staff\"?\n4. If centralized, how is priority determined? I believe Jason said they make their own decisions, but that's from an outside POV.\n5. Roughly how many full time staff institution wide work on all the web sites? a billion! Or I could just count the number of people on the ning (195) pretend they all work at NCSU and multiple by some arbitrary number (2.5) because market penetration is low. 487.5 people\n6. What is the state of a content management system (cms) at your institution? Decentralized by site/department (that's my guess at least)\n7. If you use a CMS, how was it adopted? The only CMS *I* currently use is Open Source, even though our main website was developed in house (it's not really a CMS).\n8. If your CMS was built elsewhere, what is the name/company of that CMS? The CMS website I mentioned is Wordpress.\n9. What department controls your institutions home page? OIT, I think? Or is it University Communications? I'm not really sure.\n10. Does your institution have a home page committee? Not that I know of. Do branding recommendations count?\n11. When was your last home page redesign? Mine or the institution? It was probably a couple years ago either way.\n12. How was your last home page redesign handled? In house I assume.\n13. What is the primary programming language that runs your institution\u2019s Web environment? Depends on who you ask. Probably PHP. We have a lot of ColdFusion though. Not sure if there's any ASP out there, but there's probably a bit of Perl and Java (I can think of at least one example of each).\n\nWell there you go. I'd be interested in seeing the correct answers. hehe. I still don't understand how 8% of respondents decided that LAMP was a \"programming language\".","createdDate":"2009-11-24T14:20:04.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10106","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Fluid","description":"<a href=\"http://fluidapp.com\" target=\"_blank\">Fluidapp.com</a>\n\nFluid is Mac only, so if you don't have a Mac \u2013 or even if you do \u2013 you might want to check out Prism from Mozilla Labs. (<a href=\"https://mozillalabs.com/blog/2007/10/prism\">https://mozillalabs.com/blog/2007/10/prism</a>)\n\nHow many web browser tabs do you have open right now? Go ahead and check, I'll wait.\n\n...waiting...\n\nBack yet?\n\nOk, good. How many did you have? If you're like me, you probably answered somewhere around 20. Now go back and count how many of those are web apps or sites that you keep open all the time. These include things like Google Docs, Gmail, Facebook, Google Wave, Digg, maybe Twitter, Google Calendar, Yahoo! Mail, Flickr, Google Reader, the list goes on and on.\n\nWouldn't it be nice if those things acted a little more like desktop applications and left your browser free for doing just that, browsing?\n\nEnter Fluid.\n\nFluid is an application that builds applications. Basically, it lets you create a site specific browser (SSB) with the url and icon you provide. This application can live in your applications folder just like any other application and has all the properties of any other desktop application.\n\nEvery Fluid app also has a javascript API that allows web applications to be able to do things like add badges to the dock icon or fire Growl notifications. This is especially useful for apps like Gmail where you want to see if you've got new messages without having to leave what you're doing.\n\nThere is built-in support for GreaseMonkey-compatible userscripting too, so you can still add things like dock badges to apps that don't have support built-in already. I've pasted my userscript for adding a dock badge for unread messages for Google Wave below if you're interested.\n\nDownload Fluid and free up your browser for browsing today!\n\nFluid_Google_Wave.user.js - Put this in your Google Wave userscripts folder and then reload your userscripts. I'll also attach it below so you can download it easily.\n<pre>(function(){\n        if (window.fluid){\n\n                // Provides a simple API to get Wave information\n                FluidWave = {\n\n                        getUnreadCount: function(){\n                                var match = document.title.match(/\\(([0-9]+)\\)/);\n                                return match ? match[1] : 0;\n                        }\n\n                };\n\n                // Badge updating\n                setInterval(function(){\n                        window.fluid.dockBadge = FluidWave.getUnreadCount() || null;\n                }, 1000);\n\n        }\n})();\n</pre>","createdDate":"2009-11-17T13:32:50.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-17T14:59:43.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","fileAttachments":["discussions/27-FluidGoogleWave.user.js"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10111","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"I've been using Prism to run Google Calendar and Wave. It isn't so much the fact that it doesn't run in a tab -- we could do that under Windows already just by dragging a link from the address bar to the desktop and opening pages in a new window -- but running thickish apps like Wave and Calendar in their own process reduces the individual memory footprint of any one of them (even as it eats up a bit more more space overall).\n\nTheoretically it also compartmentalizes the impact of unstable apps to a single process too. But mostly the encapsulated link looks like a distinct app on the desktop, so I find it reduces the time I spend scanning for the right window, and I notice the difference.\n\nBTW, nice tips about the user javascripting; it reminds me a little of the scripting features built-in to the doomed OS/2 desktop manager (every folder and file icon was user scriptable using interfaces exposed by the SOM).","createdDate":"2009-11-17T14:59:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10108","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"If you haven't figured this out already, Fluid is a Mac only application....\n\nIf you're on Windows, try \"Prism\" from Mozilla...... <a href=\"https://wiki.mozilla.org/Prism#Installer\" target=\"_blank\">https://wiki.mozilla.org/Prism#Installer</a>\n\nWorks pretty much the same way from what i can tell -- im going to start using it for my common browser tabs -- Personal GMail, Work GMail :-), Google Calendar. I'll post back here if i run into problems.","createdDate":"2009-11-17T13:58:26.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10087","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"yslow","description":"Pretty neat-o:\n<a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yslow/\" target=\"_blank\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yslow/</a>\n\nWorks with Firebug to give you a report on how long any page takes to load, gives your page an overall grade and gives advice about what to fix. Good for page load optimizing.","createdDate":"2009-11-12T21:40:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-17T14:02:45.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10109","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I learned something today while validating that page you linked: \"Note: &lt;tfoot&gt; must appear before &lt;tbody&gt; within a table, so that a browser can render the foot before receiving all the rows of data.\"\n\nAlso, in case you were wondering about the other one: \"To validate a blockquote element as strict HTML, the element must contain only other block-level elements, like this:\n\n&lt;blockquote&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Here is a long quotation here is a long quotation&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/blockquote&gt;\n\"","createdDate":"2009-11-17T14:02:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10103","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"We're using this approach on our Eos Software Catalog page:\n<a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/software/catalog/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/software/catalog/</a>\n\nI stand corrected, the HTML Tidy/Validtor plugin I'm using with Firefox (incorrectly) reports finding no errors. However, a pass through the <a href=\"http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/software/catalog/&amp;charset=(detect+automatically)&amp;doctype=Inline&amp;group=0&amp;user-agent=W3C_Validator/1.654\" target=\"_blank\">W3C's official html validator</a> reports all of the errors you would expect.\n\nPlugin removed.","createdDate":"2009-11-16T20:59:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10102","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'd be interested in seeing an XHTML page which validates without close tags. It would also make me very sad. The point of XML is that it can be treated as a structured language, which is easily parsed and devoid of arbitrary linguistics.","createdDate":"2009-11-16T20:00:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10092","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Surprisingly, even XHTML 1.0 Strict pages will validate with this approach. Although, I will admit... it's quite awkward and takes some getting used to. Whenever I use this approach to optimize a page, I will include a detailed note in the comments and include the link to Google's explanation. It just seems pretty unorthodox. I'm curious if leaving those tags open has any effect on js libraries like jQuery (for DOM traversal, etc)...","createdDate":"2009-11-13T17:50:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10091","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Interesting. I tend to use XHTML 1.0 Transitional as my DTD. I guess I'm just a neat freak who needs to have open and closing tags for everything - makes me nervous to have unclosed tags like &lt;li&gt;list item &lt;li&gt;next list item. I'm surprised to hear that Google says you can reduce page load time up to 20% by eliminating end tags where acceptable. That's nutty. Regardless, I've got a few bigger more obvious fish to fry before I can really get into the fine tuning of optimization, such as reducing http requests.","createdDate":"2009-11-13T13:28:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10089","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I've been using YSlow for a while now and have been quite pleased with it. Google produces a similar plugin for firebug called <a href=\"http://code.google.com/speed/page-speed/\" target=\"_blank\">PageSpeed</a>. I think YSlow is generally more user friendly and does a better job communicating the changes you need to make for performance gains, although I really do like the Page Speed Activity recorder which helps you visualize (in real time) how the various components of your page are loaded. There's no harm in installing both plugins.\n\nDuring my various site optimization endeavors this year, I learned that the HTML 4 DTD allows you to omit certain end tags from your document. For example you are not required to close a table cell or row. This will dramatically cut down your document size if your page has a massive table. On average, Google estimates you can trim your document size by 5-20% using such a technique.\n<a href=\"http://code.google.com/speed/articles/optimizing-html.html\" target=\"_blank\">Read Google's Post on Optimizing HTML</a>","createdDate":"2009-11-13T13:17:47.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10059","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Zend PHP Conference Recap","description":"Hey everyone.\n\nJust wanted to let you know that on Friday at noon in the B-3 Conference room in the Hillsborough building, I will be giving a recap of a bunch of the stuff I picked up at the Zend PHP Conference I attended a few weeks ago.\n\nThis will be pretty much an overview of what I heard at the conference, so it will not be too in depth. If you are interested, please sign up with classmate: <a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate/workshop/index/details/?workshopId=140\" target=\"_blank\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate/workshop/index/details/?workshopId=140</a>","createdDate":"2009-11-10T13:43:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-10T13:43:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:10049","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"SimplePie is as simple as pie","description":"Pre-requisites for reading this post: 1. You know what a blog is. 2. You understand what RSS does (knowing what it stands for is not a requisite). 3. You like to get the most \"bang for your buck.\"\n\n<img style=\"float:right;\" src=\"http://simplepie.org/images/logo_simplepie_horizontal.png\"/>Let me introduce you all to a handy little open-source project known as <a href=\"http://simplepie.org/\" target=\"_blank\">SimplePie</a>. SimplePie is, in my estimation, the most developed RSS parsing package available (next is <a href=\"http://magpierss.sourceforge.net/\" target=\"_blank\">Magpie</a>). In general terms the way it works is this: a blogger blogs a blogpost &gt; RSS feed is fed &gt; SimplePie puts the new info on a page that you choose. It works through the magic of PHP (of course) and can be fed any kind of XML feed like ATOM or RSS 1.0/2.0. Anything that an RSS feed pushes out, SimplePie can render on your page in a looping fashion.\n\nAn example then: WolfBlogs + departmental webpage. A little while ago our college (the College of Natural Resources) began using the Library's blogging software that they labeled \"WolfBlogs\" (of course it has \"wolf\" in it). This was because our college needed to update the way we handled news, we needed modern methods to reach larger audiences and thus extend the reach of stories created. And because I like using existing services over re-inventing wheels, we went with WolfBlogs. But this article is about SimplePie, so back to that. <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/prtm/news/\" target=\"_blank\">Take a look at this</a>. What you are seeing is SimplePie's handiwork. These are the last 5 entries from \"<a href=\"http://blogs.lib.ncsu.edu/cnrnews/\" target=\"_blank\">CNR News Central</a>\" that were tagged \"prtm\". Here's <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/fer/news/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">another example</a> where you replace \"prtm\" with \"fer.\" By the way, these are departmental acronyms. Additionally it makes a nice long listed <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/prtm/news/archive.php\" target=\"_blank\">archive</a> too for people who are interested in that sort of thing.\n\nSimplePie is billed as putting the simple back into Really Simple Syndication and I'd agree. Setup is a snap. Simple as throwing an include in your site and adjusting some simple server privilege settings. SimplePie doesn't really write on a given page, but it does write to a folder you create for caching. Thus it doesn't run anew every time a visitor hits the page, instead it'll draw from the cache.\n\nSo there ya go. A super easy way to extend the content you're writing in your blogs (the getting more bang for your buck part). I know there's SimplePie modules for Drupal too by the way if that's how you get down.\n\nAnd one more footnote, shortly after deciding to write this I read this <a href=\"http://simplepie.org/blog/2009/09/26/simplepie-is-ceasing-development/\" target=\"_blank\">note</a>. Not very cool. But hey, it has all the functionality I really care to have at this point so it serves me well even if it were never further developed.\n\nAnd I'll throw this in as an extra treat for anyone who actually read this whole article: <a href=\"http://www.feedmyinbox.com/\" target=\"_blank\">FeedMyInbox</a>. This is the solution for all those folks who are afraid of RSS aggregators - it turns every post into a new email from a given feed. You can even setup a custom form for your feed on your website (e.g. <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/prtm/news/emailfeed.php\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>).","createdDate":"2009-11-10T13:10:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-11T00:43:08.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10079","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Zend_Feed will do that as well, and it does a great job. We are using it to deliver RSS for the twitter.ncsu.edu site. It is really easy to do, you just have to pass it an array and it generates the feed for you.","createdDate":"2009-11-11T00:43:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10077","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Parsing and consuming an RSS feed is all well and good (and Jason/Garrison may have some things to tell you about Zend_Feed), but I haven't seen much in the way of libraries for producing RSS/Atom feeds. Has anyone out there seen a good tool to take care of the other end of the spectrum?","createdDate":"2009-11-10T17:23:47.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9998","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Link Checking","description":"Anyone out there use a link checking software? Basically something that runs through a site's pages and finds any broken links (especially external links) and gives you a report. I know DW has this functionality, though I find it to be not so great.. and I've had others recommend <a href=\"http://www.link-checker-pro.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Link Checker Pro</a>, but wondering what you all use and how you stay on top of the dreaded broken links.\n\nthanks.","createdDate":"2009-11-05T19:41:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2012-03-26T20:55:02.227Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:13628","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<p>In case anyone cares, here's a great FF plugin I've been using to visually show on a page where the broken links are: <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-us/firefox/addon/linkchecker/\" target=\"_blank\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-us/firefox/addon/linkchecker/</a></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>None of the other tools I've seen do a good job of explaining where a broken link is on a page, most just tell you the broken link href and the page where it's located.. maybe the line of code too.</p>","createdDate":"2011-02-11T16:15:47.753Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12739","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"<p>Two other approaches to the problem:</p>\n<p>1 use Curl, either as a stand-alone command-line program or in PHP,\u00a0like this:\u00a0http://w-shadow.com/blog/2007/08/02/how-to-check-if-page-exists-with-curl/</p>\n<p>2) use Greasemonkey to inject a link checker script that uses AJAX calls to detect broken links and then highlights and list them, like this:\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.xs4all.nl/~jlpoutre/BoT/Javascript/Linkchecker/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.xs4all.nl/~jlpoutre/BoT/Javascript/Linkchecker/</a></p>","createdDate":"2010-12-13T16:08:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12715","contributorName":"1l40ba7jekp4d","description":"Charlie,\n\nI've been using Xenu Link Sleuth for several years now and I would highly recommend it. I especially like the option to pick up redirects, which will become dead links eventually, in the broken link reports so I can go ahead and repair those as well. Have fun with it...\n\n--Brandon","createdDate":"2010-11-23T18:41:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12711","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"That seems odd. The site looks fine to me. You can disable Trend Micro for the time being and re-enable it afterward. There aren't any malicious JavaScript or otherwise on that site. The only reason that I would expect a blocker to have it blocked is that he has an anti-scientology page. That is what gives the tool its name, but the tool itself it simply useful and not a marketing/political item.","createdDate":"2010-11-22T20:06:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12708","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"So, I just went to download the Xenu product, and Trend Micro flags it as a high risk-level site and won't let me get to the URL. Anyone else experience this?","createdDate":"2010-11-22T17:11:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10076","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm always wary of putting the HTTP version in the header. It seems like it would be cleaner to let PHP handle it:\n\nheader(TRUE, TRUE, 404);\n\nIn this way it is similar to SEO friendly, application-generated, permanent redirects like:\n\nheader('Location: /new/page/location.php', TRUE, 301);\n\n@Charlie: It sounds like Mike has already explained what I meant by using a 404 page. I'm not sure why the 404 header isn't being automatically generated for Mike, though I have had issues if I tried to prepend the domain name in the ErrorDocument command (it was causing erroneous 200 response codes, which may be what he is seeing). I'm glad that those tools matched that for which you were looking.","createdDate":"2009-11-10T14:21:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10048","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"one last thing I forgot. If you are using your own PHP page to process 404 errors and still want to report the error to Apache, put this line in your PHP file...\n\nheader(\"HTTP/1.0 404 Not Found\");","createdDate":"2009-11-09T21:34:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10047","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"neat... I just went ahead and implemented this to carry the basic function of tracking the URI, the REFERER and the timestamp. oh and I used the new hostpilot, nice to have a little sandbox like that. thanks Mike.","createdDate":"2009-11-09T19:43:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10045","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Using the following line in your .htaccess file (as Jonathan points out) will funnel all errant requests for documents to a page in the root of your site called 404.php\n\nErrorDocument 404 /404.php\n\nInside 404.php you can determine what file was requested by accessing this var...\n$_SERVER['REQUEST_URI']\n\nFrom this point you can do an assortment of things...\n\nEven though Apache and your web analytics software may also automatically log the request for this missing document, those logs can often times be a burden to comb through... I second Jonathan in recommending you also shove a note of this request into your own MySQL database.\n\nAside from simply logging the missing request you can also get creative and recommend some pages that might be similar to the missing file that was requested. You can do this using your own database of related pages or you can copy google and break the requested url into pieces, and then use Google's Search API to query for those terms.\n\nHere's what happened in Chrome when I requested a missing file from the <a href=\"http://www.itecs\">www.itecs</a> vhost (and I didn't have a 404 error page specified). Notice that google extracted various words from the url and provided a few plausible alternatives...\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left; margin:20px 0;\"><img src=\"discussions/28-googleautosuggest.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-11-09T13:38:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10001","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<a href=\"http://home.snafu.de/tilman/xenulink.html\" target=\"_blank\">Xenu's Link Sleuth</a>\n<a href=\"http://validator.w3.org/checklink\" target=\"_blank\">W3C Link Checker</a>\n\nAlso:\nErrorDocument 404 /404.php\n\nInside of that file, shove the results into a database. Then a little tool displays an aggregate of that data to show you when, to where, from where, and by whom a missing page has been requested.","createdDate":"2009-11-06T13:17:32.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9985","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"NelNet Setup","description":"Hey campus web people! I'm trying to create a NelNet connection for the Campus Rec office. Running to a total lack of experience with NelNet. Is there anyone out there who has had experience setting up a connection to the NelNet interface that can talk me through some of the problems I'm having?\n\nAppreciate the help!","createdDate":"2009-11-03T21:31:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-04T13:41:48.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9991","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/accepting-payments-onthe-web\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/accepting-payments-onthe-web</a>","createdDate":"2009-11-04T13:41:48.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9984","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Meetup Survey","description":"I wondered if you all would take a second to fill out a survey about our meetups. This will help us determine who, what, when, and where we schedule our meetups and your feedback is very important.\n\nIf you fill out the survey, you will be entered in a drawing for a Google Wave and Google Voice invite.\n\n<a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dFZrMExWVGs1aE00NnNqc0tvZGVjZnc6MA\">http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dFZrMExWVGs1aE00NnNqc0tvZGVjZnc6MA</a>\n\nThanks for your help!","createdDate":"2009-11-03T20:05:18.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-03T20:05:18.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9982","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"Flex Training for ColdFusion Developers","description":"I posted an event, but I'm not sure how many folks check out the events on the main Ning landing page. I heard about this event from <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/thecrumb\" target=\"_blank\">@thecrumb</a> on Twitter (he's the head of the Triangle Area ColdFusion Users Group [<a href=\"http://www.tacfug.org/\" target=\"_blank\">TACFUG</a>] and the main reason <a href=\"http://www.cfinnc.com\" target=\"_blank\">CFinNC</a> happened):\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ce1.com/adobe/2009/flextrainingforcfdevelopers/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ce1.com/adobe/2009/flextrainingforcfdevelopers/</a>\n\nHow can you say no to an all day training session for $0?","createdDate":"2009-11-03T17:06:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-03T17:06:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9981","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"Web Data Leakage Policy","description":"The Web Data Leakage Policy Committee (WDLPC, yeah, it's a mouthful) is tasked with creating \"a University regulation to address the control of university webpage [sic] content and provide guidance to the university community to prevent leakage of sensitive data on web pages\". My bit of homework is to study other State agency/university policies for best practices. I have already begun a list of candidate sites to survey, but would like to extend an opportunity to NC State web developers to add to the list. Are there any sites out there that you'd recommend as an example of good data management policies as seen from the developers POV?","createdDate":"2009-11-03T17:01:29.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-04T13:38:48.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9989","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Other than the first, these might be more application specific, but I thought they might be useful for this community.\n\nRule #1: Minimize access to web enabled applications. If all your application needs to be able to do is read from a single database, that should be the only permission it should have.\nRule #2: Server side field validation is the only kind you can trust. Using JavaScript to do field validation is a user interface feature, not a security feature. Make sure whatever fields are coming in look exactly as you expect them to look (functions like intval() can help) before shoving them into the database or elsewhere. Additionally, use escaping functions (like mysql_real_escape_string()) or prepared statements to help avoid SQL injection vulnerabilities.\nRule #3: Beware of the LIKE keyword. Some people think that LIKE is the magical do everything keyword and use it for equality checking as well. This is very very bad. If someone puts in the percent character as their name, unity = '%' will return no results. unity LIKE '%' on the other hand will return the database to the screen.\nRule #4: Limiting your LIKE love. If at all possible, don't search for a string in the middle of a value (i.e. LIKE '%blah%'). If they leave it blank or put in a space, the full database comes out. Usually starts with (LIKE 'blah%') or ends with (LIKE '%blah') are more accurately what you are looking for. Additionally, starts with can leverage indexes.\nRule #5: Have some required fields. If a certain set of fields must not be empty (such as WRAP_USERID, SUBJECT, YEAR, SEMESTER) check them all and prevent the application from continuing if they are not provided or empty.\nRule #6: End execution after sending a Location header. header('Location: goaway.php'); should always be followed by your preferred variant of die() or exit(). Otherwise, execution continues.","createdDate":"2009-11-04T13:38:48.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9966","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: Ninite.com","description":"Ever had to wipe your PC and start from scratch? You know the drill....format....use Restore CD.....downgrade from Vista to XP.....install Firefox, Chrome, Skype, Pidgin, VLC....you know...all your favorite and indispensable Open Source apps. The hardest part of the process (other than the 5 minutes working in Vista before you downgrade), is remembering and downloading all of those apps.\n\nUnless you're almost done downloading your apps, stop what you're doing, and visit <a href=\"http://ninite.com\" target=\"_blank\">Ninite.com</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://ninite.com\" target=\"_blank\">Ninite.com</a> provides a way for you to build your own application installer, which includes all your favorite open source apps (and some trial versions) from one easy interface. They've categorized the applications into a few categories, so you can see and compare what options are available to you in say, the Instant Messaging area. I guess it could even help you try out something you didn't know existed.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/29-PickYourSoftware.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/30-PickYourSoftware.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"281\"/></a></p>\n\nAll you need to do is check the boxes for each application you want to install, and click the button at the bottom of the page.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/31-Save_Installer.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/32-Save_Installer.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"181\"/></a></p>\n\nSave the installer file, then run it, and it will download and install all of the applications you selected\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/33-downloadingSkype.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/34-downloadingSkype.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"76\"/></a></p>\n\nAfter the installer has finished, you just run the apps like you would normally.\n\nOne feature I didn't try out, but seems useful was \"Suggest an App\" where you can ask them to include something not already on their list.\n\nThere's not much to <a href=\"http://ninite.com\" target=\"_blank\">Ninite</a>, which is good, because it just works.\n\nNo signups, no login, just select, download and run. It's that simple, and that's why it's this week's Best Thing Ever.","createdDate":"2009-11-03T12:26:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-06T13:55:19.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10003","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Ubuntu support is nice. When it comes to an \"Apps Installer\" system, if <a href=\"http://www.allmyapps.com/app/ubuntu-9.10/frozen-bubble\" target=\"_blank\">Frozen Bubble</a> isn't an option, it's time to move on. ;)","createdDate":"2009-11-06T13:55:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9995","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Just found an alternative to ninite.com --- \"AllMyApps\"\n\n<a href=\"http://lifehacker.com/5396524/allmyapps-bulk+installs-your-favorite-apps-makes-system-rebuilding-less-painful\" target=\"_blank\">http://lifehacker.com/5396524/allmyapps-bulk+installs-your-favorite-apps-makes-system-rebuilding-less-painful</a>\n\nHaven't tested it yet, but seems to do the same thing.","createdDate":"2009-11-05T14:13:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9969","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Wow, that's a bit scary. I don't know that I'd trust them to play nice unless I could compile the installer from source. They seem like nice people, but until I can identify their revenue stream, I think I'll pass.","createdDate":"2009-11-03T14:32:44.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9941","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Group Bloggin'","description":"Hey Peeps,\n\nAny of you out there use Drupal for it's blogging feature? I want to start using it as a group blog - a single group blog with multiple authors. I've found a few things I've found online, but I'd rather use a method that someone on campus could endorse as a functional solution.\n\nThanks!","createdDate":"2009-10-30T13:16:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-09-20T15:03:31.381Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10009","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Cool thanks. Yeah, setting up a blog is built-in, real easy. It just starts getting complicated when you want to do something beyond the basic. I'll drop Matt a note though, thanks for the contact (and for thinking of my question at that conference, way cool!).","createdDate":"2009-11-06T18:31:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10007","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I happened to attend a local conference at ECU called a Think-In ( <a href=\"http://www.ecu.edu/academicoutreach/think-in.cfm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ecu.edu/academicoutreach/think-in.cfm</a> ). One of the people from Academic Outreach mentioned they use Drupal, so I perked up and asked if they've used the blogging feature (remembering your query here). The answer was \"yes\", and from the reaction of the person I was asking, setting it up is no big thang. The person I talked to was a student, and I can't remember his name. Let me give you a very social-media aware person over there that has his finger on the pulse of technolgies they're testing:\n\nMatt Long\nBlackboard Administrator\nSelf Help Ctr, Suite 304-D\n252-328-9074\n<a href=\"mailto:longm@ecu.edu\">longm@ecu.edu</a>\n\nTell him Tony sent you asking about experience with Drupal and blogging.","createdDate":"2009-11-06T16:30:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9997","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I was hoping there'd be a viable solution in Drupal because we drank the Drupal kool-aid long ago and I'd like that decision to pay off. But I'm starting to feel like this isn't a Drupal strength.\n\nMight just go with WolfBlogs and feed my Drupal site. Kinda reticent about adopting WordPress when there's already a perfectly fine centrally supported blogging tool on campus. And, fwiw, I do kinda love WordPress - it's so damn simple!\n\nRegardless thanks for ya'lls input!","createdDate":"2009-11-05T14:54:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9993","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"eh...i wouldn't call it (the OIT site) blog functionality per se....but i guess its all semantics.\n\nI mean....we have multiple content types, which i guess could be made to act like a blog. We have multiple authors who have different permissions for different content types though.\n\nI dunno.....Charlie -- if you're interested, i can show you how we set up the OIT site, and you can see if it matches what you're trying to do. I guess the question, rather than can Drupal be a multiple-author blog tool, is what you're trying to accomplish. If you give me an idea of that, i can tell you if Drupal would be a good fit for you.","createdDate":"2009-11-05T13:41:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9988","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"ha! I knew that at one point. I wonder if the main oit site is what he was looking for. It appears to have blog-like functionality with multiple authors.","createdDate":"2009-11-04T13:14:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9983","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"hmm.. alright, I'm going to throw this project on the back-burner for the time being, and when I get to it I'll post something back to this thread (on the off-chance anyone cares). thanks anyways tho.","createdDate":"2009-11-03T19:00:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9977","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Nope, that is wordpress. the main oit site is drupal though.","createdDate":"2009-11-03T16:56:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9967","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Isn't <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/</a> a Drupal multiple authors blog?","createdDate":"2009-11-03T14:20:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9961","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"nothin? really? :(","createdDate":"2009-11-02T21:09:24.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9926","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"NCSU Policies, Regulations, and Rules (PRR) Site Question","description":"Greetings from your sister school in Greenville!\n\nThe team I'm on has been tasked with recommending/implementing a system/website for policies, regulations, and rules. As a guideline, we've been pointed to the NCSU system at:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/policies/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/policies/</a>\n\nOther than it's written in PHP (my oh so clever deduction based on file extensions), I don't have much information.\n\nDoes anyone there know what team is responsible for the implementation and care and feeding of this site? We'd want the technical side, with thoughts on possibly asking for the codebase if that's possible.\n\nAny leads would be gratefully accepted.","createdDate":"2009-10-29T16:58:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-29T20:34:12.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9932","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Jen and I had a great phone conversation where she described the system in question. Thanks, Jen! It also seems that our timing is perfect, since she and her team are going to be revamping the workflows for getting the content available.\n\nWhat also came out of the conversation is the need for the ECU web folks (or other interested parties) to have a road trip to Raleigh so we can join one of your BoF sessions. I'll be talking to my boss and upward to see if we can arrange for a day in January to try and come visit.\n\nI'll post more once I've done some legwork on our end.\n\nRepeat after me: Collaboration is good! Collaboration is good!\n\nOh, and Jen, here's the contact information for my friend in the NCSU library <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/directory/moreinfo.php?username=trearl\" target=\"_blank\">Rusty Earl</a>\nI'm dead serious when I say, \"Tell him Tony sent you and you want to learn about document repositories and dSpace\".","createdDate":"2009-10-29T20:34:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9930","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Tony, this is actually a site that was built by Luis Chacon (who is on the Ning site) and then was taken over by myself and Nick Young after Luis moved on to another group on campus. Currently the \"care and feeding\" is done with Contribute updates by the PRR (Policies, Rules and Regulations) office and with assistance from us for navigation updates and... other help when things go wrong. Which they do pretty often. Sadly, the site is pretty complicated and changes in the PRR staff over the last few months has triggered a lot of help requests.\n\nOur office actually just met with the head of the Policies group last week. We're currently considering how we might redo the site. You're not the only one to comment favorably on the site organization-- we're not looking to mess with what's working. We are looking at how updates are made, how the navigation could be better managed and how to limit the complexity of the tasks our clients need to perform. At its heart it's a simple site: a lot of policies, with some past revisions, all listed categorically (with some overlap), so Nick and I are literally in the middle of deciding how the next iteration will work.\n\nWe'd love to hear your thoughts on how you might consider designing the site (technically speaking) and we'd be more than happy to have a phone call or meeting if you'd like to talk more about how it's working now. Feel free to contact me directly (919.513.7924; jen_riehle@ncsu.edu), or we can keep talking here if the masses our fascinated by our frustration! :)","createdDate":"2009-10-29T18:19:30.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9921","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","title":"Student Course Evaluation Systems","description":"For anyone: what software does NCSU use for on-line course evaluations? Is it mostly home-brew, reusing enterprise systems or open source off-the-shelf packages, some combination?","createdDate":"2009-10-29T13:11:16.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-29T13:11:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9901","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Any changes to our PHP version?","description":"Hi,\n\nI am wondering if there has been a PHP upgrade or configuration change. Suddenly the field validation on several of my forms isn't working, even though no changes have been made. I checked SysNews and did not see anything, but sometimes a major change happens and I am the last to know about it.\n\nElizabeth","createdDate":"2009-10-28T16:15:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-03T14:44:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9973","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Yes, the forms seem to be working fine with no changes. I suppose it was just coincidence that people were having problems with three different forms. It is our busy time of year, so perhaps the high volume of users included a few folks not completing all the fields as instructed. *sigh*","createdDate":"2009-11-03T14:44:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9971","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Any luck?","createdDate":"2009-11-03T14:34:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9924","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks, they were working last week. We did get submissions then. I will take a look at the code myself, just in case there were any changes made that I didn't know about. If I don't find anything, I will take you up on the offer of help. E.","createdDate":"2009-10-29T16:29:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9922","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"There were some minor security patches made back in September. Nothing that should have caused problems, but then again, that's php which is notorious for burying code changes in minor revisions. Email me with the url of one of your pages having problems and I'll help diagnose it.","createdDate":"2009-10-29T15:19:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9902","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"When was the last time you have checked that they were working? I don't know of anything lately that has changed.","createdDate":"2009-10-28T17:26:53.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9887","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  Mailplane","description":"I love GMail. I was an early adopter way back when you needed invitations to get an account. Over the years, I have started to depend on GMail for my everyday productivity.\n\nWhile GMail rocks the house, there was one part that always kinda bugged me about it...the lack of desktop notifications. As I was looking for a solution, I came across the <a href=\"http://toolbar.google.com/gmail-helper/notifier_mac.html\" target=\"_blank\">GMail notifier for OS X</a> and that did the trick! It would tell me when I had new messages, and even integrated with Google Calendar.\n\nThe notifier worked for me for a while, but then I started to collect extra GMail accounts. I am now up to 5 GMail accounts, so having 5 versions of the notifier running (which you have to hack in anyway) wasn't really a very good solution. It was also annoying that I had to have 5 browser tabs dedicated to GMail accounts in my web browser. This seemed to clutter up my workflow and really get in the way. That is when I discovered <a href=\"http://mailplaneapp.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Mailplane</a>.\n\n<p style=\"float: right;\"><img src=\"discussions/35-Mailplane.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>\nMailplane is OS X-based software that allows you to manage as many GMail accounts as you want in a desktop application-like setting. It has a few can't-miss features that I love.\n\n<b>Awesome Feature #1 - Integration with Growl</b>\n\nIf you are a mac user and don't use growl, you are missing out on an awesome product. Growl is a notification system that all my other apps integrate with nicely, and so does Mailplane. Whenever I get a new email in any of my GMail accounts, I get a growl notification. It is wonderful.\n<b>\nAwesome Feature #2 - Drag and Drop Attachments</b>\n\nYep, you can drag an attachment from your desktop, into Mailplane, and bam! Attached to an email. Saves a lot of time.\n<b>\nAwesome Feature #3 - More Notifications</b>\n\nMailplane comes with a GMail-Notifier-esque icon that is in your menu bar that will tell you how many unread messages you have. You have an option in the preferences to check every account or just the active one.\n\n<b>Awesome Feature #4 - Do Not Disturb mode</b>\n\nHave you ever been really concentrating on a project and you get a notification that you have new email? With Mailplane, you can turn on \"Do Not Disturb\" mode and you won't get any more notifications. Great for concentration.\n\nThere are more awesome features, but I will let you figure those out for yourself. Sorry Windows people, Mailplane is only for OS X. It does cost money after the 30 day free trial, but they give discounts for education, so the license only ends up costing about $18. I realize in a world of free software and other alternatives, that seems like a lot. But I have been using it for a few weeks and I will definitely be shelling out the money for Mailplane. It is that awesome...and that is why it is the best thing ever.\n\nFor more info on Mailplane, check out the 2 minute video on their <a href=\"http://mailplaneapp.com\" target=\"_blank\">homepage</a>.","createdDate":"2009-10-27T15:05:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-27T15:06:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9881","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Zend PHP Coference 2009","description":"I just got back from <a href=\"http://zendcon.com\" target=\"_blank\">ZendCon 2009</a> and thought I would share my experiences. The conference was great, and I blogged the whole way through, so if you are interested, check it out on our Outreach Technology blog.\n\nDay 1: <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/21/zendcon09-day-1/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/21/zendcon09-day-1/</a>\n\nDay 2: <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/22/zendcon09-day-2/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/22/zendcon09-day-2/</a>\n\nDay 3: <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/22/zendcon09-day-3/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/22/zendcon09-day-3/</a>\n\nWrap Up: <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/26/zendcon09-wrap-up/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/2009/10/26/zendcon09-wrap-up/</a>\n\nI'm thinking about doing a summary at the next meetup. Any thoughts on what you guys would like to hear about? I could talk for weeks about all the stuff I learned, but if there is something that a few people are interested in I can put something together.","createdDate":"2009-10-26T18:40:03.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-26T18:40:04.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9831","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Drop Everything and go get yourself Dropbox!","description":"We seem to have finally reached the point in our technological evolution where sharing files is no longer a question of \"if\", but \"how quickly and efficiently\". If you're still copying your files to a zip disk and walking them across town then my friend, you need a car. And a Dropbox download!\n\n<a href=\"http://www.getdropbox.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Dropbox</a> is a cross-platform application for sharing files. Create a (free!) account on the Dropbox website and a quick download later you've got a directory mapped to your machine ready to store up to 2GB of your files on the Dropbox secure servers! This is cloud computing on a bright, sunny day, folks. Your PC, Mac and Linux machines will share in ways Bill and Steve never dreamed. Naturally, you'll be so pleased that you'll rush about downloading Dropbox for your home machine, your laptop, mom's PC and on that machine across town. But wait! You can also manage your Dropbox files via the web and with their recently released iPhone app. Been frustrated with the challenges of managing your iPhone files? Weep no more, 'lil camper. The iPhone app will let you upload your images and view a wide, WIDE array of file types including images, music files, movies, PDF, document and presentation files. And more.\n\nIn case this isn't incentive enough you can also manage the sharing of your documents on Dropbox. Files in the \"Public\" space have a URL which can be shared with anyone. Other folders are private by default but can be shared with other Dropbox users. And in case you fear that all this yummy sharing might lead to editing conflicts or accidental deletions you can relax, Frankie. Dropbox keeps all your files, even the deleted ones, and has version controls in case multiple people are working on a file at once. And if you're the shy type, feel better knowing Dropbox uses SSL and AES-256 encryption for its file transfers.\n\n\"Jen, is there ANYTHING you don't LOVE about Dropbox?\" Well, yes. Yes there is. For one thing I can't seem to make good use of the Dropbox files on my phone. They're available in the Dropbox app, but difficult to get at otherwise. Making an image a Favorite doesn't put it in my \"Photos\". So unless I take a screenshot (press and hold the \"Home\" button at center bottom of the iPhone, then press and release the \"Sleep\" button on top right of the iPhone) I can't really play with my photo.\nI'm also bitterly and irrationally disappointed about the fact that my free account only give me 2GB of space. I'm really being silly here: it's free space and Dropbox gives ample opportunities to earn additional storage (up to 5GB with a free account) by simply using the application or signing up friends (Hey, friends! <a href=\"https://www.getdropbox.com/referrals/NTE4MDIzNDg5\" target=\"_blank\">Go sign up</a>!). There are also \"Pro\" options that allow you to bump up your Dropbox space significantly, but at $9.99 a month for the 50GB option ($19.99/ month for 100GB) it's a bit steep. That being said I use my Dropbox quite a bit and have only used 1.3% of my space.\n\nPlenty of folks have made good use of Dropbox for some more elaborate sharing. Symlink a profile or bookmark directory to Dropbox and enjoy an identical experience on your machines. Store a <a href=\"http://lifehacker.com/5133679/five-best-portable-applications\" target=\"_blank\">portable app</a> for use anywhere. Map your <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/boxee-tv-ouside-the-box\" target=\"_blank\">Boxee</a> to the Dropbox folder for quick access to shared media files (legal ones only, of course). The possibilities are fantastic.\n\nIf you'd like a Dropbox account go sign up now, preferably by <a href=\"https://www.getdropbox.com/referrals/NTE4MDIzNDg5\" target=\"_blank\">clicking here</a> and using me as a referral so I can get more Dropbox file space. Download it, share it, spread the word. This one is a no-brainer, my friends. It's totally the best thing ever. This week.\n\nLifehacker post: <i><a href=\"http://www.lifehacker.com.au/2009/09/use-dropbox-for-more-than-just-file-syncing/\" target=\"_blank\">Use Dropbox for More than Just File Syncing</a></i>\n\nFollow <a href=\"http://twitter.com/dropbox\" target=\"_blank\">Dropbox on Twitter</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-20T13:24:58.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-20T19:58:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9844","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Funny thing, I was going to update my <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/krtwkw\" target=\"_blank\">Dropbox vs Jungledisk facebook post</a> to submit as a BTE here. I guess Jen beat me to it. I'll just abbreviate my thoughts to this comment instead.\n\nIf you want:\n- unlimited storage (at a low price, roughly $0.15/gb + $2 per month)\n- easy support on linux, where dropbox's so-called linux-support is lacking\n- control of your own encryption keys\n- for your own files (not so much for sharing with public URLs)\n\nThen I recommend JungleDisk over Dropbox.","createdDate":"2009-10-20T19:58:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9842","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Just signed up!\n\nYou get an extra 250Mb if you use a referral from someone else...so.....literally everybody wins! So my brand new account has 2.25Gb instead of the regular 2gb. Pretty nifty.\n\nIf you prefer to give your referrals to australians instead of canadians, use <a href=\"https://www.getdropbox.com/referrals/NTI1OTc1MTM5\" target=\"_blank\">my referral code</a> ----- sorry if i start a commonwealth war :-)","createdDate":"2009-10-20T17:30:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9838","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Absolutely. The web interface (which I like a lot) has expanded options to the right and deleted files will allow you to permanently delete.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/36-dropbox.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nBy the way, deleted files don't count against your quota but the contents of shared folders do.\n\nRead more on the Dropbox Help... <a href=\"https://www.getdropbox.com/help\">https://www.getdropbox.com/help</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-20T13:54:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9835","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My question is: let's say I want to delete something permanently. Is that an option?","createdDate":"2009-10-20T13:45:50.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9814","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"got a phishing attempt this morning related to this board","description":"Got a phishing email that whose title was\n\n\"success added a comment to your page on NCSU Web Developers\"\n\nA few things set off my warning bells.. First was I got the email twice, second was that the URL looked way funky(lots of hex looking code tacked in the middle etc..), and third was that I didn't even know I had a \"page\" on the Web developers board..\n\nSo I went ahead and clicked on it ;-) Only kidding... I did a little investigating and went to a machine we have parked on the side for testing and got into my ning signon. Found out that I truly did have a page, and saw her note on my \"comments wall\". Looked at the page source and didn't see anything fishy (someone who got this might check behind me!), just a straight phishing attempt..\n\nGlenn","createdDate":"2009-10-20T11:31:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-20T20:40:48.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9846","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I also received this spam.\n\nThe email is not a phish... it's Ning sending you a note that you have a new comment. It would do that regardless of who posted the comment, or what its content was.\n\nThe comment is spam. The abuser simply posted to your comment page because s/he knew Ning would take care of sending the email for them.\n\nWhich brings up one shortfall on Ning compared to other social networks... it does not appear to have a \"report this user for abuse\" option. Best I could find was the option to simply deny all further messages from that user. I could not have it investigated as a spammer.","createdDate":"2009-10-20T20:40:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9824","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I deleted the entry and turned on Wall moderation. It not like each person is getting a flood of spam, so it probably doesn't make sense to disable any features that you expect you might use.","createdDate":"2009-10-20T12:50:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9815","contributorName":"31xmugq70vlv6","description":"Note on similar issue: I received email via a \"friends\" request through Ning from one of those \"Dearest, \" messages asking me to reply via email to a personal email address. Not sure I want to uncheck the setting for friends request in the configuration web page for Ning, but if this becomes a problem, I guess it's the only way to handle it. Any advice? I could not see a way to block a specific email address.\nKelley","createdDate":"2009-10-20T11:50:12.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9554","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"NC State GoLinks -- Need Beta Testers","description":"As part of my beta testing process, I am inviting the campus web developers community to test out a new application i've developed. The basic goal is to provide a URL shortening service for NC State.\n\n<a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu</a>\n\nThe application will allow you to create both random links AND links that you specify yourself. IE: <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/kriq7a\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu/kriq7a</a> OR <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/webdevelopers\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu/webdevelopers</a>\n\nI *think* i have it ready to be tested by other people :-) What i'd like to get is some input on any bugs you can find, any suggestions you think would benefit the project, and any criticisms as well (those can be the most important).\n\nNow to do some necessary thank you's to let you know how this project got to this stage.....Thanks to Jason Austin and Garrison Locke (<a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu\">http://ot.ncsu.edu</a>) for their patience and help throughout the development process. This application is built on their OT Framework, which is built on Zend Framework. This would not have happened without their help and leg work to provide a base on which to build this application.\n\nOnce i get feedback, make some changes/improvements, it will be publicized and made available to the entire campus (although all you need to do is WRAP in). Any non-NC State'rs --- i am going to open source the project, and will post the information after this initial testing is finished.\n\nSo....thanks in advance to anyone who can test the application for me. Hope you like it!","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:06:38.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-02-11T12:22:55.990Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10043","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Just a quick note to let all you early adopter/beta testers know.....\n\nI'm working on some new features and bringing the application in line with campus policies regarding domain names/locker names etc.\n\nAs a result, I've switched off the ability to create new links. All existing links will work while i complete the updates.\n\nI heard that some people who learned about the golinks site have taken it upon themselves to put their newly created links into print publications. I can't stress enough, that this service is in Beta, and the links you have created may be removed before it moves to production (Hence the title of this thread...\"Beta Testers\")\n\nOne of the things i'll be doing during this upgrade period is to ensure that all \"official\" links for the university are pointing to the correct locations. I think you'll all agree that it is not in the best interest of the university for \"go.ncsu.edu/athletics\" to point to some random club sport, just because that person got there first.\n\nRight now there are 252 user-specified links, and i'll be contacting the owners of any links that <i>might</i> be re-owned to an administrator (top level university links).\n\nIf you have any questions, please let me know either directly -- <a href=\"mailto:nick_young@ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">nick_young@ncsu.edu</a> or on this thread.","createdDate":"2009-11-09T12:38:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9822","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I will! Thank you! :)","createdDate":"2009-10-20T12:24:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9628","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Fixed. I was using empty(); instead of is_null().\n\nEnjoy your zero link.","createdDate":"2009-10-19T14:53:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9625","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Nope, '1' works just fine. You're probably doing something like:\nif(!$value) {\nheader('Location: <a href=\"http://golinks.ncsu.edu/\">http://golinks.ncsu.edu/</a>');\n}\n\nor:\n\nif(empty($value)) {\nheader('Location: <a href=\"http://golinks.ncsu.edu/\">http://golinks.ncsu.edu/</a>');\n}","createdDate":"2009-10-19T13:11:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9624","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'll check this out and see what i did to cause that. Originally there was going to be a way to request a \"numbered\" golink, which gave you an incremented number automatically, but i took that piece out. There must be something left over that's preventing a user-specified number from being used.","createdDate":"2009-10-19T12:42:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9623","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My remaining issue is that there appears to be an \"empty\" check which is disqualifying my perfectly valid <a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/0\">http://go.ncsu.edu/0</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-19T12:34:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9613","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I forgot to reply to your \"same target, two golinks\" issue too.\n\nYes, that is by design. It is logical to assume that multiple people may want to have their own link to the same destination, so that they can track different URLs if for no other reason. I found this to be most helpful for situations with bulk mailings where you wanted to put (for example) go.ncsu.edu/campaign1 on an email that went to one set of people, and go.ncsu.edu/campaign2 on an email that went to another set. Then you can very easily compare which mailing was most successful (for simple click-throughs), even though they end up at the same website.\n\nFYI: you can create your SMS:// links now....just added it in there.","createdDate":"2009-10-16T15:52:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9612","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"BTW -- if you're interested, the link target checker is just a regular expression that looks for prefixes. Now i just have to go back to the playbook to add in sms:// to the mix.\n\nreturn preg_match(\"/^(http(s?):\\/\\/|ftp:\\/\\/{1})/i\", $targetUrl);\n\n(regular expressions make me go crazy crosseyed sometimes....well...all the time)","createdDate":"2009-10-16T15:45:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9611","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The way the URL prefixing works, is that if the submitted target does <u>not</u> have http://, https://, or ftp:// at the beginning, it assumes you wanted it to be a regular http:// link. I think your request (if it was one) for sms:// to be allowed is not problematic, so i'll go ahead and add that as an allowed prefix.\n\nI have not built in a blacklist, but that's probably a really good idea. I dont know if that's something i can leverage from the OT framework, but i'll check with Jason and Garrison to see. If not, then i can build that in for sure.\n\nI'm not sure of blacklisting other redirection services, as that can be problematic to maintain. There's a million different services out there, and i cant be expected to keep up with all of them, just to prevent looping.\n\nThanks for the suggestions and testing...mucho mucho appreciated.","createdDate":"2009-10-16T15:42:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9608","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I've incorporated a lot of the suggestions/comments/bugs that have been mentioned here and via Twitter (@usaussie). Thanks for the interest, and quick testing that everyone has provided. I still have a few things i want to incorporate before \"going public\" but from what i can tell the base functionality of the application is running as expected.\n\nFYI --- there are now 143 golinks that have been created -- i'll be providing a way for stats and popular link information to be posted for viewing (probably with the ability for link owners to choose whether or not they want their links included in public listings).\n\nOne thing i did want to mention is that i cleaned up some of the links that were violating the new format guidelines ---- now you can only create links that have letters, numbers, periods, underscores and dashes. Sorry for cleaning them out, but you understand...right? :-)\n\nSo...next steps....keep on testing....we (the office i work in -- Design Education &amp; Outreach, OIT), are changing our processes for regular projects, and will soon have the this project posted to a <a href=\"http://www.redmine.org/\" target=\"_blank\">RedMine site</a> that will allow better bug tracking, involvement from the community, and downloads of the project.\n\nThanks again for your help so far...and please let me know if there's anything else that you'd like to see included. I'll post the RedMine site as soon as it's up and running.","createdDate":"2009-10-16T14:04:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9586","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"i definitely think this is a possibility.\n\nI am also collecting data on incorrectly attempted links (those that do not exist as a valid/active golink)....and i will be providing that information too. It proves useful to look at and compare what people are typing in, versus the actual link. This can help to proactively (or is it retroactively) insert incorrectly spelled golinks, so that when people make mistakes, they still get to where you want them to.\n\nI havent had any experience doing caching yet, so i'll see if my good buddies jason or garrison can enlighten me about that. The good thing is that im capturing the data though, and now it's just a case of how to best display it.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T16:15:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9585","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The kirby dance is eternal. I thank you for the opportunity to share it. Any chance you could put up a little statistics about how many GoLinks there are and perhaps how many total hits GoLinks have had? I don't really care if it caches for 15 minutes an hour or a day, but it would be neat to see usage statistics. :)","createdDate":"2009-10-15T15:49:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9584","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yeah yeah....i have fixed it in the dev instance to prevent any characters that aren't numbers, letters, periods, or dashes. So your best link ever will be short lived! Muhaahah.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T15:44:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9583","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Your link 'kriq7a' was seemingly created one second after my link 'kriq79'. Essentially, just because the link looks to be \"random\", it doesn't mean it wasn't crafted. Not a big deal, just trying things out. By the way, I stole the Epoch! Muahaha! Too bad it doesn't work because empty('0') returns true...\n\nBy the way: Best link ever:\n\n<a href=\"http://go.ncsu.edu/&amp;lt;(-%27.%27-&amp;lt;)&amp;nbsp;&amp;lt;(-%27.%27-)&amp;gt;&amp;nbsp;(&amp;gt;-%27.%27-)&amp;gt;\" target=\"_blank\">http://go.ncsu.edu/&lt;(-'.'-&lt;)\u00a0&lt;(-'.'-)&gt;\u00a0(&gt;-'.'-)&gt;</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-15T15:40:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9580","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"No -- i dont have limitations on which URLs can be shortened. I do have tracking on each link. It's a simple hit count for each link that is visible for administrators as well as the link owner.\n\nYes...you have pulled back the curtain on the creation of the random links. I'm wondering how/what you mean by users backdating entries though? Just trying to get inside the mind of someone trying to break my stuff :-) I'm pretty sure I've prevented people from injecting a timestamp to replace the random function, but i'd be interested to see if you can (better now than later).","createdDate":"2009-10-15T14:58:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9579","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"try now -- should let you WRAP in now.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T14:50:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9578","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"try wrapping in now --- my mistake -- made a couple of changes and forgot to push out the right one.\n\nyeah the pre-reservation thing was something i thought about. When this moves out of beta, i may get the input from our university communications folks (Tim, Luis --i'm looking at you) to help figure out which ones need to be created.\n\nURL best practices are a good idea for sure. Alternative short URLs are also a good idea.\n\nI don't how we can prevent link squatting, but it's something to figure out. There will be administrative abilities to produce reports on users, link counts etc, so it will be possible to retroactively moderate these things. However maybe there could be a limit on how many links you can create per hour or something? Just a thought.\n\nAll good suggestions ...keep em coming.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T14:49:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9576","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Same error for me...\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/37-error.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nI think this is an excellent idea.\n\nA few suggestions...\n<ul>\n<li>You may want to pre-reserve links that you think are going to be important to the university so they don't get farmed out to end-users, such as go.ncsu.edu/athletics.</li>\n<li>Consider providing a list of url best practices (I'm thinking in terms of SEO, etc)</li>\n<li>Provide other alternative short urls that are available when a user's desired url is already taken (similar to what domain registrars do)</li>\n<li>Is there any way to prevent a user from nabbing a ton of urls, pointing them to some place holder, and then editing them in the future? Sort of like domain squatting?</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2009-10-15T14:41:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9571","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"\"ERROR! You do not have access\nYou are not allowed to create an account. \"\n\nAww, but how am I going to test exploits. ;)\n\nDo you have limitations on which URLs can be shortened? Do you have any tracking associated with the redirects to identify high popularity items which may help in identifying misuse? What happens when you specify an existing link (or accidentally create a \"random\" one at the same time as someone else)?\n\nIn case you want to figure out when a \"random\" link was created (of course, beware of the tricky individuals who might \"backdate\" entries):\n\n&lt;?php\n$string = 'kriq7a';\n$string = str_split($string);\n\n$value = 0;\n$number_base = ord('0');\n$letter_base = ord('a') - 10;\n\nforeach ($string as $char) {\nif ($char &gt;= '0' &amp;&amp; $char &lt;= '9') {\n$base_value = $number_base;\n}\nelse {\n$base_value = $letter_base;\n}\n\n$value = $value * 36 + ord($char) - $base_value;\n}\n\nvar_dump(date('Y-m-d H:i:s', $value));","createdDate":"2009-10-15T12:49:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9570","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Without attempting to solve all problems at once, or simplify the issue, i see this service as 95% first-come-first-served. Now obviously we need to take into account that if someone creates \"go.ncsu.edu/athletics\" that it actually goes to the athletics page, and not some random website. I am still trying to figure out how to manage these issues, so any and all suggestions are welcome.\n\nI did think early on about including a 'spash page' that would display for 3 seconds before the redirect occurred. That way you could pause the redirect, read information about the link, the link owner, and submit a notice if the link is violating any real or perceived rules. I havent made my mind up on that one just yet, because that may get in the way of the speed of operation, but it's worth a thought.\n\nI figure a lot of the dispute resolution can be taken care of by existing processes. We store the user IDs of the link creator, so it will be pretty easy to provide contact information, should a dispute occur.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T11:54:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9566","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Webservers have been rebooted to clear the latest AFS caching problems. As Nick said, we'll be working out the OAuth/API stuff soon, and then sysnews will start tweeting its posts using these as article links.\n\nThis is not a problem with the AFS servers, but with the AFS clients (which are web servers) on RHEL5 machines. Basically the cache gets out of sync on the web server, and these large Zend file pushes get messed up in the cache, leading to the errors for some people and not others depending on which of the web servers you happened to get assigned to. We still don't have a good combo of AFS server and client versions that solves this problem, so the usual workaround is to do a rolling reboot of the webservers to clear their caches. We don't post these events in sysnews because the rolling reboot makes sure the service stays up while individual servers in the pool are offline.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T20:34:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9565","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I don't have any plan to deactivate links or recycle them. Im sure there will be policies that need to be developed, and because of that i have built in some things to the application (banned/preventable/bad-word links, distributed administration is possibile).\n\nRandom links are created based on the timestamp at which they were created (base10 conversion of php time()).\n\nAll links can have their targets edited, so that you can re-use the same golink for a new target (helpful to reduce the number updates needed for print materials, email templates etc).\n\nOne of the features i am going to build in, is to allow users to delegate ownership to another user, essentially creating the ability for groups to manage links instead of having them tied to a single person (helpful when people leave, graduate etc).","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:36:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9563","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Sounds nifty. Wish I could play with it right now... ;)\n\nHow long will the URLs be available before they get deactivated/recycled?","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:29:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9561","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Alan -- i believe this is the recurring problem with AFS &amp; the web servers --- depending on which web server in the pool you are accessing (1 of the 8), you might be getting a mixture of the application code before and after my last update. So i guess the long and short of it is wait for AFS to work itself out (8 hour refresh schedule if i remember correctly).\n\nAs for the API access....Yes....that is already built in. You can generate both random and specified short links via the API. I dont have the process documented just yet, but it is working. Charles Brabec is going to be using this exact thing for adding golinks to the sysnews posts.\n\nI should have waited 8 hours before i sent this out! Sorry :-(","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:25:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9557","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Seems to be broken right now - \"Fatal error: Class 'Zend_Auth' not found in /afs/unity.ncsu.edu/web/g/golinks/htdocs/public/themes/goncsu/views/scripts/auth.phtml on line 2\"\n\nThat said, I'm interested in whether or not you can/will provide an API to generating such URLs. I can think of a couple of scenarios where it could be handy to shorten URLs programatically.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:19:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9555","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"This is a good idea, I am constantly having to use the tinyurls to make manageable urls for professors articles, or even interviews that have long assed urls. Good job! This will help things tremendously.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:13:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9509","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Best Thing Ever: Google Wave","description":"URL: <a href=\"http://wave.google.com\" target=\"_blank\">wave.google.com</a>\n\nEveryone's heard of it...few have seen it. I'm here to tell you that it's pretty sweet. Will it eliminate the need for email? I don't think so. Is it a great way to collaborate on a conversation / document? Yes, yes it is!\n\nGoogle says that Wave is their idea of what would be created if email had been invented today. The idea is that you have one document / conversation (a docuversation?) that you can collaborate on in real time with the people participating in the wave (the recipients, essentially). So rather than have to create an email and send it to the various recipients and then rely on them to actually reply all appropriately, you can just use Wave to accomplish this task. This way you have one conversation rather than having to deal with a bunch of copies of emails. You can use Wave for organizing events, meeting notes, group reports, brainstorming, sharing photos,\n\nJason and I have been using it to collaborate and share files for some of our projects. It's convenient to be able to make notes and add files and have a conversation that's fully searchable all in one place.\n\nGoogle has added the ability to create widgets for Wave (similar to Gmail) so it's capabilities can be extended easily. There are various widgets already: voting &amp; polls, maps, trip planning, video conferencing, etc.\n\nThey also have a concept of robots that can be added to a Wave. For example, you can add a real-time language translation robot to Wave. If my language is French and Jason is in English, it will translate what I'm saying in French, in real time, to English for Jason to read.\n\nThere are a thousand videos and blog posts on Google Wave, so I'm not going to rehash all of that. I'll just link to a few informative resources:\n\n<a href=\"http://web.appstorm.net/roundups/communication-roundups/8-google-wave-resources-while-you-wait/\" target=\"_blank\">http://web.appstorm.net/roundups/communication-roundups/8-google-wave-resources-while-you-wait/</a>\n<a href=\"%20http://web.appstorm.net/roundups/communication-roundups/extend-your-wave-%E2%80%A6-eventually/\" target=\"_blank\">\n</a><a href=\"http://web.appstorm.net/roundups/communication-roundups/extend-your-wave-%E2%80%A6-eventually/\">http://web.appstorm.net/roundups/communication-roundups/extend-your-wave-%E2%80%A6-eventually/</a>\n\nI see a lot of potential in Google Wave, especially as more and more people get accounts :-) I'd venture to guess that they'll start opening it up pretty soon to a larger audience. Here are a couple of screenshots to make you totally jealous :-P\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/38-wave.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/39-wave.png\" alt=\"\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/40-waveall.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-10-13T13:22:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-13T18:41:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9529","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Wave, the protocol, encourages asynchronous communication. Wave, the Google client, does too, but the UI gives the appearance of threaded, interactive forums.\n\nWhat are the essential characteristics of email for the user? Asynchronous communication, message threading by id, filtering and sorting by headers and statuses, organization by folders and a primary folder \"inbox\", [store-and-forward (pop) or querying (imap)]=~ notification of new/unread messages. Wave handles threading, filtering, sorting, and folder organization; the inbox is there, and blips tell the Wave whether they are replying to one of my blips or not.\n\nThe protocol specs suggest to me that the bottleneck to making it behave like email is in the client UI and in the policies of the Wave service provider. Specifically, anyone expecting a simple email interface will be off-put by the apparent complexity of the Google client. So we can hope the client will improve, and I'd expect that something, perhaps Open Source, will spring up to fill the need for simplicity.\n\nBTW, there's a <a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/RDUWavelets/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Wave meetup</a> this month.","createdDate":"2009-10-13T18:41:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9526","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I definitely agree with you, and I'd vote for it. But unfortunately, it seems the traditional model for asynchronous communication is too-well established. If all the email clients slowly help the shift by bridging that Wave -&gt; non-Wave gap then maybe we could eventually get to this new paradigm as standard practice. There's definitely potential here though.","createdDate":"2009-10-13T15:34:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9524","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"I don't see why a particular kind of Wave client could not eliminate email, in theory and in practice.\n\nThat is, I'm sure email servers and clients won't just disappear. But other than legacy users I wonder what particular reasons there will be for SMTP services to remain a part of the IT infrastructure after Wave services are successfully deployed. The existing Wave client is just one way to access the server; other client interfaces could easily perform the same queuing and notification function that email performs.\n\nAfter using Wave, my impression is that after some acceptance period larger institutions may actually start requiring Wave in the name of governance. That's because the Wave represents the entire narrative of a communication, with all its edits and timings... stuff that will make the auditor types in all professions drool.","createdDate":"2009-10-13T14:42:30.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9497","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"How to Persuade Your Users, Boss or Clients","description":"I regularly read Smashing Magazine's articles and came across a gem this morning.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/10/11/how-to-persuade-your-users-boss-or-clients/\" target=\"_blank\">How to Persuade Your Users, Boss or Clients</a>\n\nFor anyone who ever does any kind of development, this article should be required reading. I can't tell you how many times I have dealt with developers who exhibit traits that are exactly opposite of the things mentioned in this article, and always with sour results.\n\nTo me, the best part of this article is the section on being personable. As developers, we sometimes like to retreat to a safe place where we know more than the user does and are not ashamed to let them know it. I have seen this happen more than once, and all it does is frustrate everyone involved. If everyone is frustrated, very little work gets done.\n\nAnother tactic that seems to work well for me is to be as informed as possible about your user/client's way of working. If you can put yourself in their shoes and step through their process, you can get a better perspective for where they are coming from. Perhaps that feature request that you think is asinine is actually really worthwhile. This is actually a really difficult task. Many times, even though your client may go through a certain workflow 10 times a day, they have never really sat down and written it out or explained it to someone. Sometimes this is frustrating for them, but this is where your experience, personality, and engagement is important. Help them through the process, understand where you may be able to help, and optimize any way you can.\n\nDo you guys have other tips and tricks?","createdDate":"2009-10-13T10:01:51.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-13T14:16:57.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9520","contributorName":"2clztbsxotepb","description":"Wow.... change a few words and this could relate to Tech Support as well. Nice article. Thank you for sharing... and pointing me to a new info source :-D","createdDate":"2009-10-13T14:16:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9505","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It will work out a whole let better for you if they appreciate your time as a developer. If someone thinks that they can boss your around because their money is paying for the project, you will not get any respect and the project will suffer (and the client won't realize why and will blame you more). If possible, don't accept projects for these project derailing users. Set a budget and stick to it, don't let the rest of your work suffer because of one user (unless it's your boss, in which case you should probably be looking for new employment).\n\nAkin to the article, I also find meeting with the user to follow their footsteps and experience the frustration firsthand. There are some things that we as developers can't do, but if it can be done, you'll be creating a stronger bond by doing so.","createdDate":"2009-10-13T13:07:26.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9467","contributorName":"0tsgrb8k0z34k","title":"Per Yesterday's Meeting","description":"I know I didn't speak up during the meeting yesterday but I think it would be nice to have the web developers meetings more frequently and during some of those meetings have sub-groups so people can get more into the nitty gritty of what they're working on or speak in groups on topics they are more interested in if the meeting is large enough. You can also invite people from Duke/UNC during those times as well.\n\nFor example have sub groups:\n\nDevelopers can talk about code or get into more technical detail about projects they are working on etc...\n\nCommunication/content people can get together to talk about how they are incorporating image galleries, news, calendars etc... and what they are doing to optimize those processes\n\nDesigners (visual and interaction) can get together to talk about usability, interface design, css, meeting branding guidelines etc...\n\nAnd at different meetings or if time allows at the same meeting people can intersperse themselves to a topic or area they are interested and change groups during the time as well (kind of like the birds of a feather presentation type format).\n\nThat might get more interaction during some of the meetings.\n\nJust a thought...","createdDate":"2009-10-09T12:47:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-27T00:32:13.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9885","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I am working on getting us a regular meeting space on a monthly basis so that we will have a set date and time to get together. Something like \"first Tuesday of the month\" or something like that. Regular spot, regular time, regular meetings, different topics. I got a few other good ideas from some folks at ZendCon who run PHP User Groups that I am trying to put together too. But having a regular date and time would make it easier to get people to come out (i would think).","createdDate":"2009-10-27T00:32:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9541","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"The MINDSET Project uses Joomla. I'm usually off-campus, but I've worked with other Joomla sites as well and would be happy to answer any questions.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T12:52:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9515","contributorName":"2clztbsxotepb","description":"Being stuck in the dredges of the Help Desk all day, it was nice to get out and see folks I've not seen in a while... or ever and while I'm not really a developer (Drupal just makes me think I am to help my self esteem), I did get a lot of ideas just from the conversation.\n\nKeeping things informal will help to string along dialogue. As far as a venue, I wonder what the library has for meeting spaces (plus there's coffee in the lobby), or during the warm months, just meet out at the creamery. There was a good bit of discussion post meeting too so it proves that we can do this just about anywhere and serve our purpose.\n\nFor our next meetup, I wonder if we can pick a focus or foci. It seems we hit the mobile point fairly well at our last, so how about something like a Drupal focus for the next. As we discussed, we can have multiple topics, then breakout into separate BOF's to chat. I personally would love to steal, I mean, hear some of your ideas regarding CMS's (anyone using Joomla for anything?).\n\nI do like the idea of increased frequency as it will help group cohesion if we are together more often. If nothing else, it's a good break from the mundane to network with university peers. Jason, if you want, i can help you look for venues and try to schedule the next event.","createdDate":"2009-10-13T14:13:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9495","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Just to clarify my position, I don't mind at all being a driver for the community. In fact I find it one of the most rewarding parts of my job. However, the whole idea of a \"community\" is for lots of people to participate. I saw this quote on twitter the other day from Fred Eaker which summed it up perfectly: \"The difference between an audience and a community is which direction the chairs are pointing.\" I'd like to foster the collaborative aspect of this community so that we can grow and be even more productive.\n\nIn other news, I am trying to find a better venue to hold our meetups so that they are less classroom-y and more group-y. Does anyone have any suggestions?","createdDate":"2009-10-13T09:36:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9470","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Grouping has it's benefits, for sure. I think the difficult part is identifying the groups.\n\n* I don't have a passion for mobile. (That said, I do think it offers a benefit and enjoyed both the presentation and discussion. Rather, it's not something I would pursue if I was given free reign.)\n* I don't have an eye for visual or interface design.\n* I do have a passion for best practices, future-proofing, APIs, collaboration and revision control.\n* I do enjoy conversations about PHP, MySQL, CSS, XML, HTML5 and SVN.\n\nYesterday, I was hoping to find out more information about how others are using SIS data and Drupal, how they manage 3rd party application updates and application database configurations, and the workload implications of the new branding guidelines (along with a small amount of @font-face discussion).\n\nIt was an ambitious expectation, though everything was at least touched on either in the full group discussions or in \"one-on-one\" style discussions. Success!\n\nI hope I didn't complicate things too much. I'm trying to explain my perspective, because I'm somewhat confident that each person represents a unique subset of the Venn diagram that is the interests of the individuals present yesterday.","createdDate":"2009-10-09T14:15:28.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9437","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Flash and the iPhone are BFF's now","description":"Adobe announced last week that they've updated Flash to be able to build applications for the iPhone (technically they've built a compiler that exports the Flash for the iPhone). The updates will be available with the beta version of CS5 available later this year and set for full production in April 2010.\n\nThere are a handful of games that have been developed with the new tool. Check out Chroma Circuit, Just Letters, Trading Stuff, Red Hood, Ficklebox and That Roach Game.\n\nWhile this is great for apps, Adobe also mentioned that they have not found a solution for a mobile browser (well, specifically for Safari) plug-in for Flash. Reading between the lines it doesn't look like this is coming anytime soon. There will be Flash Player updates coming that sound like they will work for Windows Mobile, Palm Android and other platforms.\n\nThe full FAQ from the Adobe announcement is linked below. Additional resources from Adobe and news outlets are also below.\n\nAdobe CS5 site - <a href=\"http://cs5.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://cs5.org/</a>\n\nInformation Week - <a href=\"http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=220301118\" target=\"_blank\">Adobe Flash CS5 Makes Native iPhone Apps</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-06T13:21:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-06T13:21:45.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255","fileAttachments":["discussions/41-NOTUSFAQ20091004.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9433","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: Google Trends","description":"<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profile/MikeVysocka\" target=\"_blank\">Mike Vysocka</a> contributed this week's Best Thing Ever..... Thanks Mike!\n\n----------------------\n\nIf you're responsible for the design, content, or marketing of your website you'll certainly appreciate what <a href=\"http://www.google.com/trends/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Trends</a> can offer you.\n\nGoogle Trends lets you compare how often certain keywords or phrases have been searched for (on Google) over time.\nWhy is this useful?\n\nSay you are having a dispute within your team about one of the navigation items on your new site. Several of your team members think the link should read \"<b>Current Students</b>\", while others are deadset on using \"<b>Prospective Students</b>\". Of course there's always the one guy who doesn't agree with anybody and wants the section to be called \"<b>New Students</b>\". So who's suggestion is the best?\n\nGoogle Trends can help settle the dispute with data.\n\nSimply enter your keywords (or phrases) into Google Trends, separating each with a comma (you may enter up to five items).\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/42-search.gif\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\n<b>The Results</b>\n\nThe graph can be a bit confusing and difficult to digest at first, but it's really delivering a pretty clear message. The results for this particular comparison shows us that for every Google search for \"<b>Current Students</b>\" there were approximately 5.4 Google searches for \"<b>New Students</b>\". The other charts on the results page will even tell you how the phrases rank against each other in different parts of the world (This can be particularly useful if your site is targeting international students). You'll also get a legend that outlines popular stories in the news over the past few years that may have contributed a spike in search volume. Each of those news items is flagged with\n\nSo Essentially\u2026\nNew Students &gt; Current Students &gt; Prospective Students\n\nThis makes perfect sense. Would you really expect high school seniors to be googling (or searching your site) for the term \"prospective students\", probably not. Knowing which terms or phrases resonate best with your users will help make your content richer in the long run and you'll start connecting with more users from search.\n<b>\nOther Practical Comparisons to Try</b>\n\n* <a href=\"http://google.com/trends?q=NCST,+NCSU,+NC+STATE&amp;ctab=0&amp;geo=all&amp;date=all&amp;sort=0\" target=\"_blank\">NCST, NCSU, NC STATE</a>\n* <a href=\"http://google.com/trends?q=international+study,+study+away,+study+abroad&amp;ctab=0&amp;geo=all&amp;date=all&amp;sort=0\" target=\"_blank\">international study, study away, study abroad</a>\n\n<b>What else can trends tell me?</b>\n\nBecause the keywords and phrases are graphed for their popularity over time, you can detect patterns. For instance, check out this comparison between \"march madness\" and \"super bowl\"\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/43-results2.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nAs you can see from the chart (over the past 5 years), the phrase 'super bowl' is googled more often than 'march madness' (6 times more to be precise). However, you should also note that both phrases are typically only googled during a specific time of year. Makes sense, doesn't it?\n\n<b>News correlates with Search Volume</b>\n\nWhether a big story just broke in the tabloids or your favorite team just won the championship game, you can bet that the attention the topic is getting in the news will have some impact on it's search volume on Google.\n\nTake a look at this comparison between \"obama\", \"palin\" and \"jackson\"\u2026\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/44-results3.png\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nThe small graph at the bottom (News Reference Volume) represents the number of occurences for each topic in Google News during that time period. As you can see, Sarah Palin wasn't appearing very much in the news until mid 2008.\n\nGoogle has also flagged (with letters) points in time when major news stories broke. Sometimes these headlines can explain a major spike in searches. For instance, when it was reported that Michael Jackson had died... searches for 'Michael Jackson' went through the roof (point F).\n\n<b>Have any burning questions?</b>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.google.com/intl/en/trends/about.html\" target=\"_blank\">Read more about Google Trends</a>\n\nWant to do some more advanced things with Google Trends? Try (the more robust) <a href=\"http://www.google.com/insights/search/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Insights for Search</a>.","createdDate":"2009-10-06T11:55:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2012-05-02T17:23:42.673Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9385","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Javascript in the body at the end of the page?","description":"I have seen a few sites recently that put the script tags for loading external javascript at the bottom of their HTML and not in the header where I always assumed it was supposed to be. This got me on the trail of trying to figure out why...\n\nThe first reason was because the browser has to load the external file when it gets to it, causing the page to slow down when it loads. Sounds like a good plan to speed up your page being shown, but it seems to fall apart when you have dynamic elements which javascript handles. If your page loads, and your JS takes some action on your page (like using jQuery to make sliders), your viewer is going to see your page without those dynamic elements, then once the script gets loaded...poof! Your site changes and the user doesn't really know what happened. That doesn't seem like a good idea to me, so I kept looking.\n\nThe second thing I found was this article (<a href=\"http://www.nczonline.net/blog/2009/07/28/the-best-way-to-load-external-javascript/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.nczonline.net/blog/2009/07/28/the-best-way-to-load-external-javascript/</a>) which stated the reason he loads his JS right before the ending body tag is so that all the DOM elements are loaded. I'm pretty sure I disagree with this reasoning as well, because every JS framework around has a method for on-page-load or on-dom-ready. It seems like writing your JS so that it executes before you know your object you need is in the DOM is a poor way to write your javascript.\n\nSo what gives? Are you guys doing your JS like this? Did I miss the good reason to do this?","createdDate":"2009-10-01T15:00:07.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-08T13:41:44.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9461","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Just came across this post\u2026\n\nNon-blocking Javascript Downloads\n<a href=\"http://www.yuiblog.com/blog/2008/07/22/non-blocking-scripts/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.yuiblog.com/blog/2008/07/22/non-blocking-scripts/</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-07T14:28:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9443","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Troy, we're doing a lot of javascript compression on the fly in Engineering. I'd be willing to share some of our code with you (or anyone else) if you are interested.\n\nBasically here's what we are doing...\n1) The header file for our template will check and see what javascript files are needed to render the page (any core modules, along with any page specific functions)...\n2) PHP will then grab the filemtime() for each of the requested components...\n3) If any of the files have been changed since we last made our compression, make a new one\n4) Serve out the compressed copy\n\nUsing a pretty url system, you can do this using just one script tag that points to your compress.php file...\nscript src=\"compress/jquery+slider+tablesorter+searchbox\"\n\nThis will tell compress.php it needs jquery.js, slider.js, etc.\n\nWe use a PHP version of JS Min to do the compression.\n<a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/jsmin-php/\" target=\"_blank\">http://code.google.com/p/jsmin-php/</a>\n\nBefore you write your compressed copy into a directory somewhere, you can also sprinkle in some PHP that will set expires headers (<a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/performance/rules.html#expires\" target=\"_blank\">why</a>), and gzip the output (<a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/performance/rules.html#gzip\" target=\"_blank\">why</a>).\n\n-Mike","createdDate":"2009-10-06T17:08:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9441","contributorName":"1y0cori2tk1a5","description":"Troy, the document.write() trick with scripts used to be a major cause of leaks and crashes in older Mozilla/Netscape browsers. I'm pretty sure it was because the code for creating document objects was not re-entrant. Thankfully the move to the gecko eliminated it. What you all are commenting about is a fundamental design flaw/feature of the browser as an application platform, to wit that timing issues in the execution flow frequently arise when you push the boundaries.\n\nBTW, iframes can also be used to load scripts immediately or lazily. Several years ago before httpRequest, we used that approach to lazily load plug-in card profiles for a browser-based product emulator. Don't downplay the JSON approach you are taking, it may have more practical application than you think.","createdDate":"2009-10-06T15:14:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9397","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"From Yahoo's Performance Best Practices (<a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/performance/rules.html#js_bottom\">http://developer.yahoo.com/performance/rules.html#js_bottom</a>):\n\nPut Scripts at the Bottom.","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:06:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9395","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I do it in the head where I think it makes the most sense and is most straightforward. I don't know that you can guarantee that the DOM has completely loaded just because the bottom of the page has been reached. That's exactly what DOM ready checks are for.\n\nBut aside from that, there is a difference in the two methodologies.\n\nJavascript in the body will be executed while the page loads, and javascript in the head will be executed when called.\n\nAdditionally, scripts in the head are ensured to be loaded before anyone can use it. So, if you have javascript that handles some click event, then you run the risk of having someone click the link or button before the javascript is loaded if you load the javascript at the end of the body.\n\nThat's all relatively straightforward, but not really relevant to the question if you assume you're going to initialize your javascript when the DOM is ready anyway.\n\nSo that brings up the question, if you're going to do it that way, is it any faster to put your JS at the bottom of the page?\n\nHere's what Google has to say about deferring the loading of javascript...which is essentially what we're talking about.\n\n---- From <a href=\"http://code.google.com/speed/page-speed/docs/payload.html#DeferLoadingJS\" target=\"_blank\">http://code.google.com/speed/page-speed/docs/payload.html#DeferLoadingJS</a> ------\n\nLike stylesheets, scripts must be downloaded, parsed, and executed before the browser can begin to render a web page. Again, even if a script is contained in an external file that is cached, processing of all elements below the script is blocked until the browser loads the code from disk and executes it. However, for some browsers, the situation is worse than for stylesheets: while JavaScript is being processed, the browser blocks all other resources from being downloaded. For AJAX-type applications that use many bytes of JavaScript code, this can add considerable latency.\n\nFor many script-intensive applications, the bulk of the JavaScript code handles user-initiated events, such as mouse-clicking and dragging, form entry and submission, hidden elements expansion, and so on. All of these user-triggered events occur after the page is loaded and the onload event is triggered. Therefore, much of the delay in the \"critical path\" (the time to load the main page at startup) could be avoided by deferring the loading of the JavaScript until it's actually needed. While this \"lazy\" method of loading doesn't reduce the total JS payload, it can significantly reduce the number of bytes needed to load the initial state of the page, and allows the remaining bytes to be loaded asynchronously in the background.\n\nTo use this technique, you should first identify all of the JavaScript functions that are not actually used by the document before the onload event. For any file containing more than 25 uncalled functions, move all of those functions to a separate, external JS file. This may require some refactoring of your code to work around dependencies between files. (For files containing fewer than 25 uncalled functions, it's not worth the effort of refactoring.)\n\n---------------------------------\n\nSo the short answer is: it might speed up your page a little bit, but in the end it really depends on the complexity of your code, the size of your code, and what exactly that code does. There is no catch-all 100% true all of the time rule. Some things will need to happen before the page is rendered, and others can wait. It's up to the specific application.\n\nBut the bottom line is that there's a trade off. It's not wrong to put them in the head or in the body and it won't make much of a difference unless you have a lot of javascript and can refactor it to defer the loading of functionality that you don't need until after the page has loaded.","createdDate":"2009-10-01T16:36:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9393","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The only reason i can think of, to put the javascript at the base of the page, is if the javascript has no effect on the initial rendering of the page. That way, it doesn't slow down the rendering of the page until a particular script/function is called.\n\nI still think the best method is to put the javascript at the very end of the HEAD tag (which is completely independent of good code....ie: making sure you aren't referencing an HTML element that may or may not be loaded yet.","createdDate":"2009-10-01T16:29:22.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9378","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"Yahoo YUI 3.0.0 Out Now","description":"Get it while it's fresh:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.yuiblog.com/blog/2009/09/29/yui-3-0-0/\">http://www.yuiblog.com/blog/2009/09/29/yui-3-0-0/</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-30T19:05:51.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-30T20:27:50.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9379","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"While breaking backward compatibility isn't all that surprising, it's a good thing YUI 2 and 3 can coexist. Would be nice if they would supply some \"transitioning from YUI 2 to YUI 3\" documentation.","createdDate":"2009-09-30T20:27:50.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9343","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  People with Ideas for future Best Thing Ever's","description":"Do you like reading the Best Thing Ever columns? If so, and you want to see more of them, help us out and give us some ideas. Because as of right now, we are out.\n\nMaybe it is time for the BTE series to come to an end. If so, your ideas about what should replace it would be great as well.","createdDate":"2009-09-29T15:42:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-06T12:32:58.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9434","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"I like it. Keep it going.","createdDate":"2009-10-06T12:32:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9382","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Next week's BTE should definitely be FailBlog. :D\n\nTony, I'm putting Sneakers on my Netflix queue, so it better be good! :)","createdDate":"2009-09-30T20:44:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9375","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Hackers was one of the few movies where I wanted my $1 back when I saw it at the (now sadly defunct) Astro III theater in Clemson, SC. Props for showing a real OpenSSH exploit in it, though. The movie you do want to see is <u>Sneakers</u>.\n\nI'm voting for 2x a month to lessen the obligation of the Ning editors, and expanding beyond toolkits/libraries/software to include blog/magazine.","createdDate":"2009-09-30T18:59:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9369","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Ok, what if we do BTE once or twice a month instead? Other suggestions for things you'd like to see up here? Departmental/people profiles? Highlight a good blog or magazine? Profile a good (or bad) mobile website? Movie reviews? (If you start with 'Hackers' it's kinda relevant... ok, no it's not).\n\nWe're open to suggestions - and volunteers!","createdDate":"2009-09-30T13:41:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9353","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Noooooo! BTE is my favorite column! I have ideas, I promise.","createdDate":"2009-09-30T02:25:10.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9338","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Chance to go to Adobe MAX conference","description":"Heads up folks! I got an email from our Adobe rep last week and she is offering NC State one free ticket to the <a href=\"http://max.adobe.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Adobe MAX conference</a>! If you're not familiar it's a pretty big show and does lots of training in addition to the regular conference sessions, which is nice.\n\nThe ticket is usually $995 so this is a pretty good deal. The downside is that it's in L.A. (the California kind) and it's next week: Oct. 4th-7th.\n\nIf anyone can muster up the time and money at such late notice give me a call (513-7924) or drop me an email (<a href=\"mailto:jen_riehle@ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">jen_riehle@ncsu.edu</a>) and I'll get you in touch with the Adobe folks right away. I'd love it if someone from NC State could go, though I know budgets being what they are this may not work for any one.\n\nMore about <a href=\"http://max.adobe.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Adobe MAX</a>:\nFrom October 4 to 7, more than 5,000 designers, developers, and decision-makers will gather in Los Angeles to learn new skills, discover emerging technologies, and connect with each other. MAX is about breaking new ground, networking and seeing what\u2019s being done at other educational institutions, and develop a vision for how you can adapt our curriculums. You\u2019ll also have the opportunity to explore innovative applications that facilitate the business side of education.\n\nMAX helps you become more competitive by providing the skills to pass on to your faculty members so they can begin incorporating cutting-edge tools into curriculums right away. MAX is packed with sessions that directly relate to the education material schools are using and teaching today and the material you want to teach next. Sessions cover teaching the Adobe Flash Platform in education, new uses for rich Internet applications (RIAs) in education, and much more.\n<a href=\"http://max.adobe.com/\">http://max.adobe.com/</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-28T13:03:54.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-28T13:03:55.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9274","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Next Webdev meetup","description":"Hey everyone, go take this poll and let us know what you wanna do for the next web dev meetup. We haven't had one in a while, so I figured we should.\n\n<a href=\"%20http://doodle.com/xub68kzigdiph3vr\" target=\"_blank\">\n<a href=\"http://doodle.com/xub68kzigdiph3vr\">http://doodle.com/xub68kzigdiph3vr</a></a>","createdDate":"2009-09-22T17:16:07.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-29T16:32:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9349","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Yay!","createdDate":"2009-09-29T16:32:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9341","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Sounds good to me!","createdDate":"2009-09-29T13:30:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9339","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"OK, so it looks like \"BOO WORK! Let's have a cookout!\" and \"Let's talk shop. Everyone give updates on stuff.\" is what everyone wants to do, so why not a combination of both? I will try to schedule our meetup at the end of the day, and then we can continue the party at a local food and beverage establishment. Would that be cool?","createdDate":"2009-09-28T13:55:24.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9262","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Video Compression Options with Flash and MPEG-4","description":"<i>This weeks Best Thing Ever is delivered courtesy of Hal Meeks, OIT's Multimedia Guru.</i>\n\nCompressing video is one of these thankless jobs that is only noticed when it doesn't work well. The quest is always for better quality given the limits of a broadband connection, while also offering the audience a transparent experience. Flash Video has become a dominant form of internet based video. However, concurrent with this, we have seen the rapid adoption of MPEG-4 as a de facto standard for tightly compressed video necessarily for both mobile devices and the web. The compression technology known as \"h264\" gave MPEG-4 a significant boost in the quality/size ratio, and is what is often used for video on mobile devices, and also as a compression format for consumer high definition video cameras (also known as AVCHD).\n\nAdobe's flash technology supports FLV as it's default video format. Like Quicktime, and MPEG-4, FLV is a container that can use a variety of compression technologies. In FLV's case, it is the ancient Sorenson compression technology or newer (but still not cutting edge) On2 compression.\n\nFlash 9 introduced support for MPEG-4/h264 as a playback technology. Many assumed that this meant that Flash's proprietary video container was updated to support these new compression technologies, but it goes much further than that. Flash Developers can use standard mpeg-4/h264 video in their projects with no modification. What this means is that you can create just one file that meets your needs for both web delivery and for other purposes, such as a podcast feed, and also benefit from h264's ability to offer better quality video.\n\nIt is important to note here that your compressed video must be \"real\" mpeg-4 files; Qucktime files using h264 compression (those that end with .mov) are not supported. Many tools exist that can create mpeg-4 content for you from your existing video; If there is more interest in this topic I will cover it in an upcoming article.\n\nSeveral options are available to use Flash to play back your mpeg-4 media. We will focus on two; using a custom player, and using an off-the-shelf Flash Video player combined with the \"embed\" tag. It is important to note here that while the \"embed\" tag has been deprecated in the latest HTML specifications, browsers have not completely moved to the alternative option, the \"video\" tag. Again, I can cover this in an additional article if there's interest.\n\nIf you have a smattering of knowledge of Actionscript (Flash's programming language), you can build a custom Flash player that will call mpeg-4 files. Essentially, this is a flash project that either points to the specific file itself, or perhaps an xml file that lists the files to be played. Building a custom flash player is useful because:\n\n- better user experience through a custom player interface\n- utilizes the same compression settings and flies that you can use for other venues, such as podcasting\n- obscures the mpeg-4 file, making it difficult for users to download (if that is your goal)\n\nFor more information, check out <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/devnet/flashplayer/articles/hd_video_flash_player.html\" target=\"_blank\">this article</a> on Adobe's site that goes into much more detail, and includes some source code examples that could be used as the basis for a custom player.\n\nThe good news is that you don't have to actually code a flash player to make use of Flash's playback of MPEG-4. JWPlayer is a pre-built flash media player that exists in a free and commercial version. The simplest way to use it is to create a piece of code that embeds the player and loads your file, such as:\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/45-code.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nThis was created with <a href=\"http://www.longtailvideo.com\" target=\"_blank\">Longtail Media</a>'s online code generator, which makes it super easy.\n\nNote in this example that it is playing back a 1024x768 frame size, just about right for those using presentation capture software (Camtasia, Relay, Apple's Quicktime X, etc).\n\nThere are two version of JWPlayer available; a free version and a commercial version. The free version displays a watermark that briefly shows up when your video begins to play; the commercial version removes that watermark, and is specifically for sites that are commercial (have ads, promote products, owned by corporations). It has a very extensive feature set, including support for captioning, streaming and skinning (custom user experience).\n\nFlash playback of MPEG-4 really bridges two worlds; the simplicity of Flash as a playback component for end users, and the quality and variety of frame sizes that mpeg4/h264 can provide, up to an online HD video experience. YouTube's HD playback uses MPEG-4 with a Flash player for this exact reason.\n\n<b>Resources:</b>\n\nExample of JW Player in Web Page\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/video/mediaplayer/test.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/it/multimedia/video/mediaplayer/test.html</a>\n\nJW Player\n<a href=\"http://www.longtailvideo.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.longtailvideo.com</a>\n\nJW Player Code Generator\n<a href=\"http://www.longtailvideo.com/support/jw-player-setup-wizard\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.longtailvideo.com/support/jw-player-setup-wizard</a>\n\nExcellent overview of Flash Playback of HD MPEG-4 (with Actionscript code examples)\n<a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/devnet/flashplayer/articles/hd_video_flash_player.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.adobe.com/devnet/flashplayer/articles/hd_video_flash_player.html</a>\n\nFlash 9 Video Support Overview\n<a href=\"http://labs.adobe.com/wiki/index.php/Flash_Player:9:Update:H.264\" target=\"_blank\">http://labs.adobe.com/wiki/index.php/Flash_Player:9:Update:H.264</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-22T13:08:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-22T15:56:08.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9272","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Sadly, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H.264/MPEG-4_AVC\" target=\"_blank\">H.264</a> is a patent encumbered video compression standard. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theora\" target=\"_blank\">Theora</a>, on the other hand, is a royalty-free, open video compression standard.\n\nSupport is available in Firefox 3.5 and Google Chrome. Opera is on the way, whereas Apple appears to be \"[refusing] to implement Ogg Theora in Quicktime by default (as used by Safari), citing lack of hardware support and an uncertain patent landscape.\"\n\nIt is worthwhile to note that Google Chrome does also include support for H.264 in their implementation (for performance reasons, which means they will likely default to H.264 for YouTube).","createdDate":"2009-09-22T15:56:08.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9246","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"NCSU is 33 in World University Rankings by Web Presence","description":"What do you folks think of this site? <a href=\"http://www.webometrics.info/\">http://www.webometrics.info/</a>\n\nSpecifically, NCSU's position as 33rd in the Top 6000 universities, with very high marks for \"Scholar\" (Google Scholar provides the number of papers and citations for each academic domain. These results from the Scholar database represent papers, reports and other academic items.). NCSU 42, UNC 192. Ha!\n\nRead the About the Ranking and Methodology. Certainly good advice in <a href=\"http://www.webometrics.info/best_practices.html\">http://www.webometrics.info/best_practices.html</a>\n\nI'm still processing it. Anyone familiar with this ranking?\n\nEllen","createdDate":"2009-09-21T20:13:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-21T20:13:04.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9228","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Operating Systems (as described by graphjam.com)","description":"<center><a href=\"http://graphjam.com\"><img src=\"http://graphjam.files.wordpress.com/2009/09/song-chart-memes-operating-systems.jpg\"/></a></center>","createdDate":"2009-09-18T22:57:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-12T20:43:50.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9241","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Is You Wish the upcoming release of Ubuntu? ;)","createdDate":"2009-09-21T12:57:54.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9226","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Update","description":"Just thought I would let you guys know that the web hosting pilot is moving forward fairly quickly and successfully. I haven't posted the meeting minutes for a while as we were trying to get organized, but all the meeting minutes can be found in our project wiki at <a href=\"http://ot.ncsu.edu/webhostingpilot/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ot.ncsu.edu/webhostingpilot/</a>.\n\nIf you guys have any questions, let me know. Just wanted to give an update and let you all know the project is alive and well.","createdDate":"2009-09-18T13:38:28.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-22T13:14:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9263","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Sadly, as a non-NCSU person, I couldn't see this information (understandably). I need to write up our experiences as well to share with the community. As of this fall, we've rolled out our home grown \"Pirate Panel\" software which lets you create your non-https space, create your https space, manage files, manage permissions, and create a blog. The blog creation is some glue code in Pirate Panel that runs scripts to create a new WordPress-MU blog for the user. Because we still have a big Active Directory infrastructure, we have Pirate Panel able to do user and group permissions based on AD.\n\nGood luck with your project!","createdDate":"2009-09-22T13:14:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9221","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"@font-face tips","description":"Saw this article and thought I'd share it:\n<a href=\"http://www.devlounge.net/design/five-tips-for-using-font-face\">http://www.devlounge.net/design/five-tips-for-using-font-face</a>\n\nexcerpt:\n\"Right now, users on Firefox 3.1+, Safari 3.1+, Opera 10 and IE4+ will see your @font-face fonts\"","createdDate":"2009-09-17T17:27:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-29T17:02:07.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:3593","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9351","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"been playing around with this to test it out, my fun lunch time activity:\n<a href=\"http://www4.ncsu.edu/~cdmorris/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www4.ncsu.edu/~cdmorris/</a>\n\nwithout any hacks, it renders right in IE8, and everything except the first font works fine in FF 3.5.3.\n\nI'm thinking of using Univers as a heading tag font style, I'd obviously have to build in the hack that the article recommends but it might be a nice little feature for a NCSU site.","createdDate":"2009-09-29T17:02:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9269","contributorName":"3f6w5e1hs2ifq","description":"Thanks for sharing this, Charlie! Good tip.","createdDate":"2009-09-22T14:14:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9224","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Notes:\n* Firefox 3.5 and Opera 10 are relatively recent releases.\n* IE4-8 only support a proprietary format for the font files. A CSS hack is possible.","createdDate":"2009-09-17T21:14:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9222","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Awesome tip, Charlie. Thanks! Naturally it sucks that IE screws it up but we're all used to that now.","createdDate":"2009-09-17T18:32:14.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9179","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Google Analytics","description":"Contribute doesn't play nicely with the tracking code that Google provides. This is another case of Contribute deciding to rewrite code in an uneditable region. If you are using Contribute and the most recent version of the tracking script from Google, this problem/solution is useful:\n<a href=\"http://groups.google.com/group/analytics-help-tracking/browse_thread/thread/c01cf664b327dfc2\" target=\"_blank\">\n<a href=\"http://groups.google.com/group/analytics-help-tracking/browse_thread/thread/c01cf664b327dfc2\">http://groups.google.com/group/analytics-help-tracking/browse_thread/thread/c01cf664b327dfc2</a></a>","createdDate":"2009-09-15T15:06:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-15T15:06:08.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9174","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Best Thing Ever: Memengo Wallet","description":"This week we're happy to have Tom Karches writing on why he thinks Memengo Wallet is the best thing ever.\n\n---\n\nAnyone that works in IT needs to keep track of passwords. Anyone that uses the internet needs to keep track of passwords. But how to do this in a secure and flexible way?\n\nThere are many password managers available, but most of them require that specific fields be set up for each password, and these fields have fixed lengths. If you need to save information that is more free-form, these solutions usually don't work.\n\nI used to keep my passwords on an encrypted disk image on a flash drive. Unfortunately, this requires access to a computer.\n\nThe best solution that I have found is Memengo (<a href=\"http://www.memengo.com\">http://www.memengo.com</a>). Memengo is a web based password manager that also has iPhone and Windows Mobile versions. The web site is free, and the iPhone app is $4.99.\n\nAfter creating an account on Memengo, you create a wallet, which contains your passwords. A encryption phrase/word is created, which secures the wallet. This password is different from the Memengo login password.\n\nA wallet contains pages which contain the actual password information. The pages can be grouped in a folder (personal, work, etc). When a page is created, a page type is selected. There are a number of different formats like \"Bank Account\", \"Credit Cards\", \"Phone Numbers\", but I like to use the \"Free-form Note\". The \"Free-form note\" is a plain text file with no formatting. To transfer my passwords, I cut and pasted my old password files into individual Memengo cards. I like to keep these cards relatively small to allow for faster and easier editing.\n\nI was initially concerned about storing my passwords on the internet, but the wallet is saved as an encrypted file on the Memengo site, and decrypted when the wallet password is entered. So the only data stored online is encrypted.\n\nThe Memengo Wallet iPhone/iPod Touch app ($4.99) syncs with the Memengo web site and caches a copy of the encrypted wallet. Since I generally have my iPod Touch with me, I always have access to my passwords. I find that it is generally easier to edit the password files on my desktop computer, but the password files are also editable on the iPod Touch.","createdDate":"2009-09-15T12:16:05.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-15T12:16:05.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:9102","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Best Thing Ever: JSBin.com","description":"<a href=\"http://jsbin.com\" target=\"_blank\">jsbin.com</a>\n\nI don't know about you, but I do a lot of Javascript development. As such, I often get questions about how to do things. For example, the other week someone asked me how to make a message box fade out a few seconds after the page loaded using jQuery.\n\nThis isn't a hard thing to do, but it can get tedious to explain exactly how to make it happen without either going to their desk and showing them, or sending them a fully-functioning example. But that can take a lot more time than it really should. So you usually just end up going over there and helping or wasting a lot of your time making an example, or giving them a snarky link to lmgtfy.com.\n\nBut with the help of jsbin.com you no longer have to choose one of those options!\n\nJS Bin is an invaluable tool for showing someone how to do something simple, or getting help on a bug you might be trying to fix. If you're familiar with the concept of collaborative debugging tools like paste bins (<a href=\"http://paste2.org\">http://paste2.org</a>, <a href=\"http://pastebin.com\">http://pastebin.com</a>), then this will be a tool you'll immediately appreciate.\n\nThey give you a simple way to write sample Javascript without having to write all the code to include the library you want to use and generate the html, etc. Just select the Javascript framework you want to use, then write your Javascript. It will automatically generate an html page that includes your selected library from a content distribution network (CDN) and lets you view the output in another tab.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/46-20090908_0927.png?width=500\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"318\"/></p>\n\nWhen you're finished tweaking your code, you can use the generated public link so you can send it to people and they can see the entire script in one page.\n\nJSBin.com has saved me a lots of time trying to debug complex Javascript and has enabled me to create examples for people in very little time.\n\nThat's why JSBin.com is this week's best thing ever!","createdDate":"2009-09-08T13:30:33.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-09T15:45:22.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9126","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Awesome, thanks.","createdDate":"2009-09-09T15:45:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9123","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"That is the default example built into jsbin.com...which you'll see every time you go there. I didn't write it.\n\nBut yeah, if you use jQuery, it's best practice to use $ and cache the result of that selector. There's no reason to run it twice. So if you're going to select anything that you're going to use again, just save it in a variable (i.e. - var controlPanel = $('#controlPanel'); )","createdDate":"2009-09-09T12:55:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9121","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Garrison,\n\nAre there any numbers related to the execution speed of document.getElementById() ? I would expect it to be indexed, but to have the speed scale with the number of nodes (likely in a btree or something similar). I tend to try and avoid doing the same lookup twice, so I'd turn your example into:\nvar helloNode = document.getElementById('hello');\nif (helloNode) {\nhelloNode.innerHTML = 'Hellow World - this was inserted using JavaScript';\n}\n\nWould this practice help the performance (particularly if the event triggered often) for larger applications? Also, because you mentioned jQuery, does the document.getElementById() shortcut $ offer a performance increase (or perhaps decrease?) or simply make the code size small (and in theory easier to read)?","createdDate":"2009-09-09T12:47:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9108","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"Good resource! Wish I had known about this earlier - thanks for getting the word out on it.","createdDate":"2009-09-08T14:50:21.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8824","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"HTML 5","description":"An article about the upcoming HTML5 specification at <a href=\"http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/08/090831080957.htm\">http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/08/090831080957.htm</a> is pretty interesting reading.","createdDate":"2009-09-03T14:05:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-08T14:45:12.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9106","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Does anyone at NCSU have any pages running new features of HTML 5 (like form validation without scripts, mathml, etc...)?","createdDate":"2009-09-08T14:45:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8831","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"Oops. Right link is\n<a href=\"http://www.ddj.com/architect/219401362\">http://www.ddj.com/architect/219401362</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-03T20:24:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8829","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Hmm, is this the right link? It took me to an article about an alternative keyboard helping those with autism.","createdDate":"2009-09-03T19:47:44.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8823","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Announcing the NC State Mobile Web","description":"After several months of preparation and planning, we're proud to announce the launch of the new NC State Mobile website.\n\nThe NC State mobile presence is a convenient place to find campus news and contacts while on the go. You can find the closest bus stop and watch a video on NCSU's mobile YouTube channel while you wait!\n\nThe new NC State mobile site supports any type of web enabled device from the most basic cell phone to the iPhone, Android, and Blackberry.\n\nNo matter where you are, you can get your NC State fix with ease.\n\nWe're already at work on improving your mobile NC State experience, too. Soon, we'll be adding features like maps, dining hall menu information, and sports scores.\n\nCheck it out now at <a href=\"http://m.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://m.ncsu.edu</a> from any mobile device!","createdDate":"2009-09-03T13:57:05.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-04T19:52:07.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8841","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Congratulations on getting this going. I tried it on my iPod Touch. Very spiffy!","createdDate":"2009-09-04T19:52:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8816","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","title":"PHP Accelerator for Windows","description":"All,\n\nI generally don't program anything web-related to run on a Windows server, but I thought this merited a post. Microsoft has released a beta Cache Extension for PHP.\n\nYou can read about it on the Windows Server Division Blog on TechNet: <a href=\"http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/09/01/download-the-new-windows-cache-extension-for-php-beta.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/09/01/download-the-new-windows-cache-extension-for-php-beta.aspx</a>\n\nOr you can go directly to the product page: <a href=\"http://www.iis.net/extensions/WinCacheForPHP\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.iis.net/extensions/WinCacheForPHP</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-02T13:54:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-03T12:53:00.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8821","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"For those who don't know, there's already an established PHP module which does opcode caching called <a href=\"http://us.php.net/apc\" target=\"_blank\">APC</a>.\n\nMy question would be if anyone has played with <a href=\"http://www.howtoforge.com/reducing-disk-io-by-mounting-partitions-with-noatime\" target=\"_blank\">Reducing Disk IO By Mounting Partitions With noatime</a>. After all, who really cares about atime unless you're looking for orphaned files?","createdDate":"2009-09-03T12:53:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8810","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Best Thing Ever: Mint.com","description":"So I don't know if you guys have noticed, but money is tight lately! Seems there's this \"recession\" thing and it's kind of a drag. I have big plans for a cruise in January but I'm finding that savings account a bit lacking of late. I guess it's time to check in with my Mint.com account.\n\nMint.com (<a href=\"http://mint.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://mint.com</a> for you literal folks) is a great site for managing all your money, bills, budgeting, etc. When you first hit the page and create an account you'll be prompted to enter your \"Accounts\". That means everything from your checking and savings account down at the good 'ole credit union (if you don't already have an account at the credit union, get down there!), to your credit cards, student loans, mortgage, car, money market, IRA's... you get the picture. You can choose to add as many, or as few of your accounts as you want. And if, like me, you're stressing a little at putting that much personal financial information into one place, <a href=\"http://www.mint.com/privacy/\" target=\"_blank\">Mint.com shares the ways they keep you and your information safe</a>.\n\nOnce your accounts are in there, Mint.com maintains a little balance sheet (left-hand column) so you know where you are overall (financially anyway). It also extracts the data to form pretty charts and graphs that tell you where your money is going over in the 'Trends' section. Naturally a mortgage/ car payment/ poor-retirement-planning can make this balance sheet look terrifyingly in the red, so keep a paper bag handy for the first time you take a good look at your finances in all their technicolor-GUI glory.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/47-mint.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></p>\n\nNow you're ready to start making Mint.com work for you. Check out the 'Emails &amp; Alerts' section to choose when you should get emails and/or text messages for things like low balance warnings, bill paying reminders, unusual spending and going over budget. Don't want to be harassed? Pull your information instead by downloading the FREE mint.com iPhone app. This gives you the latest balance information on all your accounts, warnings on balances and spending and will let you monitor your budget. I was less than pleased that the app doesn't have a lock or password feature (though it doesn't display your account information) but felt much better after a recent upgrade added a feature where you can deactivate the application via the Mint.com website.\n\nNot sold yet? One of my favorite things to do (in a masochistic, \"what-was-I-thinking\" sense) is going through my \"Transactions\". This is all the withdrawals and deposits to all my accounts and they're categorized to help with budgeting. You can also apply tags (the initial ones include \"Vacation\", \"Reimbursable\" and \"Tax Related\") to help you keep an eye on things that might be important later, or may be anomalies in the normal monthly bills. It's an eye-opener at the end of the month to see just where all your money is going (seriously?? On coffee!?) and really helps the next time you think about doing, say, a house renovation, for example. Once you realize how bad you are at managing your money you can use the budget tools in the \"Planning\" section to work out your fixed costs and budget the rest of your monthly paycheck. These features have recently been improved so I haven't played with them all but it's nice to know the Mint folks are keeping things fresh (pun intended).\n\nMint.com has a few ads, mostly in the financial sector, and occasionally they bug you with pop-ups about how you could be saving money by switching to this credit card at this rate, etc. I went down that rabbit hole once but never really got anything but a sales pitch. I also get frustrated with the Transactions being mis-categorized (which obviously can really do some weird stuff to your budgeting), but this happens surprisingly rarely. Mint.com knows Borders is 'Books', International Tile is 'Home Improvement' and it has learned that Reverie is my coffee shop.\n\nSo all in all this very easy, nicely pastel-ish, and completely free tool has made my finances much prettier (if not more significant). It's nice to know there's something keeping an eye on my money, even when I'm not. Stop reading right now and go sign up for Mint.com 'cause it's absolutely The Best Thing Ever (this week).","createdDate":"2009-09-01T14:02:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-14T20:06:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9166","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"170 million.. holy cow.","createdDate":"2009-09-14T20:06:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9164","contributorName":"0lqnwngbukofs","description":"Saw this article today about Mint being acquired:\n\n<a href=\"http://news.cnet.com/8301-17939_109-10351715-2.html\">http://news.cnet.com/8301-17939_109-10351715-2.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-14T17:17:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8805","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"CFinNC Conference","description":"Greetings, all. I added an event to the site that I just heard about on Twitter. It's a completely free ColdFusion conference right on the NCSU campus. See details:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.cfinnc.com/\">http://www.cfinnc.com/</a>","createdDate":"2009-09-01T12:16:23.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-10-19T15:17:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9629","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"To be honest I was a little scattered. A lot to keep up with (tons of good information). Only person I saw was Shaun, sorry I didn't look up you or anyone else :-( Me and a co-worker switched off and attended everything we could. We are both writing up notes to share with our group about what we saw","createdDate":"2009-10-19T15:17:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9626","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Glenn, didn't see you there, or notice you were there. Sorry! You should have hunted me down; I was there all weekend, and tweeting like a madman ( I'm @lightningwhelk ). Sorry I missed out talking to a local CF peep. It <u>was</u> a great conference, and all us .edu folks were totally stoked about it being free.","createdDate":"2009-10-19T14:28:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9621","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Attended this over the weekend. WOW it was well done. Kudos to Shaun Dunning and all of the users group folks for putting this one. Very informative, lots of good sessions and FREE!!","createdDate":"2009-10-19T12:07:22.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8781","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Contribute CS3 and PHP Includes","description":"So I think I've discovered a bug. I'm using a PHP include for a header region on a website (not the tag, a header div region). That in and of itself works great. The problem comes in when anyone tries to send for review. A user makes their edits then hits send for review and the page becomes blank. For some reason the page hits the PHP include snippet and stops rendering.\n\nThis is particularly odd because you can save as draft and publish just fine.\n\nAnyone experience this before? Probably not, but thought I'd give this group a try before trying to work with (terrible) Contribute support.","createdDate":"2009-08-31T14:26:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-15T13:29:27.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9178","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I guess it just needed more of a hint that it wasn't in an HTML context. Seems strange that it would rewrite PHP in a non-editable section in the first place. Ah well, at least it isn't as bad a hack as the underscore or asterisk CSS hacks.\n\nGrats :)","createdDate":"2009-09-15T13:29:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9177","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"This is insanity. So, whether using double quotes or single quotes or parenthesis it didn't matter - Contribute rewrites it as http..\n\nBUT! When I added this line\n\n$contribute = 1;\n\nContribute ignored the code and didn't rewrite anything. Problem solved.\n\nCharlie 1, Contribute 0\n\n;)","createdDate":"2009-09-15T13:00:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9176","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I tried parenthesis first, and it didn't like that.. I'll give single quotes a try.\n\nThis is the code (TownCrier) that works fine, Contribute doesn't touch it...\n&lt;?php\ninclude \"/afs/unity.ncsu.edu/web/c/cnr/htdocs/prtm/includes/display_events_tiny.inc.php\";\n$Seminar = new Seminars(158, \"Yes\");\n$Seminar-&gt;addSection(249);\n$Seminar-&gt;doQuery();\n?&gt;","createdDate":"2009-09-15T12:42:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9175","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Perhaps try using parentheses and/or single quotes?","createdDate":"2009-09-15T12:37:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9168","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"So Contribute in its infinite wisdom decided it's a super cool idea to change\n\n&lt;?php\ninclude \"/afs/unity.ncsu.edu/web/c/cnr/htdocs/prtm/includes/head.php\";\n?&gt;\n\nto\n\n&lt;?php\ninclude \"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/afs/unity.ncsu.edu/web/c/cnr/htdocs/prtm/includes/head.php\";\n?&gt;\n\nstill working on a solution, what's really weird is that I have other includes that are working fine - and I tried making the head and foot includes look like the working ones, and still it wants to re-write. I'll keep you all posted (I'm sure you are on the edge of your seats)","createdDate":"2009-09-14T20:40:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8807","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I think Mike is on the right track. This sounds like a PHP syntax error has been introduced. To confirm, you can try checking the error logs or doing a \"php -l filename.php\" on the actual file / files.\n\nThe situation where the PHP gets reduced to a single line may be due to differences between Unix and Windows / Mac line endings. Because the Windows / Mac users are unlikely to switch, it may be worthwhile to unix2dos the file before handing it to them. vim and its ilk will recognize what's going on and insert the line endings that the non-free OSs are expecting.","createdDate":"2009-09-01T12:18:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8783","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"We also use PHP to include a header and footer file in many of our pages. We've had some rare occasions where a user will make a change to the content and the page will suddenly stop rendering. When this happens, I usually open up the source of the page and find that all of the PHP has been condensed to a single line. In some cases, depending on how the PHP is formatted... there's little harm done. However if you use '#' or '//' to kick off your comments... PHP will ignore everything after that point once it's been reduced to a single line.\n\n<span style=\"color:green;\">\n&lt;?php //begin rendering template include('template.php'); //another comment $setSomeVar = 0; ?&gt;\n</span>\n\nNot sure if this is related, but it sounds similar.","createdDate":"2009-08-31T16:52:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8682","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Live CDs and Knoppix","description":"Today's BTE was written by Tony Miller, one of our colleagues from East Carolina University.....Thanks Tony!\n\nI've been a Linux user for 13 years. In that time, Linux has grown from being a plaything of hobbyists to becoming an enterprise-ready operating system capable of competing with the likes of AIX, HP-UX, Solaris, and Microsoft Windows. One way that early Linux promoters used to increase interest in Linux was to produce live CDs. A live CD is a CD that boots to an operating system that doesn't rely on any other storage to become a fully operational machine. The very first Linux distribution offered in Live CD form was Yggdrasil Linux, way back in 1992-1993. Think about using 1x CD drives on a 386dx running at 33Mhz trying to bring up a full GUI based desktop and you'll realize why those first forays into live CDs didn't take the world by storm. Fast forward ten years, to the halcyon days of 2003, when Knoppix was unleashed upon the world by Klaus Knopper [<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Live_cd\" target=\"_blank\">cite</a>].\n\nKnoppix was built from the ground up to not merely boot the operating system to a bare shell prompt, oh no. It was designed to poke and prod your hardware to do its darndest to be up, running, and fully available by the time you see a pretty graphical desktop environment. It's entertaining just to burn a CD or DVD image of the thing to watch how much stuff it finds on your machine to make use of. Hard drives are scanned and shown via icons (nothing is modified unless you do so, however), portable storage is shown, networking is started if possible, sound is auto-configured (and you know its working because the startup sound is a female voice saying \"Initiating startup procedure\"), and all of the things that nay-sayers whine about are simply done for you automagically. To steal a line from the Mac fanboys, \"It Just Works\".\n\nOK, you're still not convinced, why bother with Knoppix (or any other live CD)? Why download a 700Mb iso file for CD or 2+Gb iso file for DVD to get Linux? I'm glad you asked. Here are just a few reasons:\n\n<b>* Privacy.</b> Boot a CD, do anything you want, shut down, and all evidence of your actions are gone.\n<b>* With just an optical disc and a USB stick, every computer becomes \"your\" computer.</b> The latest versions of Knoppix let you save preferences and files to USB to retrieve once you've booted. Viruses? What viruses?\n<b>* Rescue mode.</b> Here's where you can be the hero of the hour. Boot Knoppix, make necessary fixes to a sick machine's hard drive, reboot, and you're gonna get some major love.\n<b>* Play mode.</b> You've heard about Linux, but don't want your highly tweaked main operating system to be destroyed. Boot Knoppix and see what everyone is raving about. Boot some other OS other than Linux. Return to your \"normal\" computer with a simple Ctrl-Alt-Delete.\n<b>* Appliance mode.</b> Besides Knoppix, there's tons of specialty live CDs that are tailored for audiences such as Tivo like video recorders, music and sound creation and editing, high end 3-d graphics, games, web publishing, and on and on. Let others do the hard work of combining operating systems, libraries, and applications. All you have to do is plop in a disc, fire up the machine, and start using.\n<b>* Test mode.</b> Booting a live CD gives you another operating system to run diagnostic tests on hardware, whether hard drive, memory, CPU, or something else. Your hardware vendor blames the OS? Tell 'em it's time to give you an RMA on that dead whatever.\n<b>* Cred mode.</b> When you get to that Monster/Dice/whoever job form and they ask what environments you're familiar with, do you wanna list only one? Of course you don't. Become a real Power User.\n\n\nTo give you an example of the power of the live CD, the Ubuntu folks decided that their install CD would actually be a live CD. That is, unlike RedHat, where you have to get a special live version, Ubuntu lets you use their single CD to boot immediately to a running OS. If you like it, you can perform an install from this running image. Reboot, and the same computing environment you were using from CD is now safely tucked onto your hard drive. How awesome is that? Try that with Windows 7 and see how far you get.\n\nFor those of you who can't escape the Windows world, there is an option: live CD building tools. One famous exampe is Bart PE. See, unlike the free software Linux world, you can't just download Windows live CDs (that would be what we in the tech world call \"Illegal\"). Rather, you download software that lets you build a live CD ISO file by using data from your own Windows install CD. I've had good luck with one called <a href=\"http://www.ubcd4win.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Ultimate Boot CD for Windows.</a>\n\nHave I used live CDs? You betcha. I've done Ubuntu installs, I've tried out other flavors of Linux, I've rescued a few Windows machines from the brink of death. In the last few months I've been using Knoppix to diagnose network configurations with blade servers my team is working with. Having a self-contained OS + complete set of diagnostic tools of all kinds makes it dead easy to figure out where things are Going South.\n\nSo, you've bought into my sales pitch, and you wanna get you some of that there live CD. Here's some resources to get you started:\n\n<b>Knoppix Home Page</b> - <a href=\"http://www.knoppix.net/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.knoppix.net/</a>\n\n<b>Knoppix DVD Image Torrent</b> - <a href=\"http://torrent.unix-ag.uni-kl.de:6969/\" target=\"_blank\">http://torrent.unix-ag.uni-kl.de:6969/</a>\n\n<b>Knoppix Official Mirrors</b> - <a href=\"http://knopper.net/knoppix-mirrors/index-en.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://knopper.net/knoppix-mirrors/index-en.html</a> (Pick a .edu for that sweet sweet high speed download action when on campus)\n\n<b>DistroWatch's Live CD List</b> - <a href=\"http://distrowatch.com/dwres.php?resource=cd\" target=\"_blank\">http://distrowatch.com/dwres.php?resource=cd</a> (A static list with background info)\n\n<b>The LiveCD List</b> - <a href=\"http://www.livecdlist.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.livecdlist.com/</a>\n\n(More distros than you can shake a stick at, with rankings to give you some hope of finding something you want)","createdDate":"2009-08-25T12:06:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-14T20:06:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8725","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Another non-booting Windows install!? Linux to the rescue! :)\n\nmemtest+ is a great tool indeed. It sure explained why my system a while back would crash when I started opening programs.","createdDate":"2009-08-26T13:04:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8703","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I use Ubuntu cds for this sort of thing since the install cd is also a live cd. Last week I helped a visiting researcher recover his data files from a non-booting Vista install. He got everything off the hard drive onto an external hard drive then wiped and reinstalled his laptop. There are other distros out there specifically for recovery of systems. SystemRescueCD, <a href=\"http://www.sysresccd.org/Main_Page\">http://www.sysresccd.org/Main_Page</a>, is one. I recommend memtest+ if you suspect memory problems. Ultimate Boot CD, <a href=\"http://www.ultimatebootcd.com/\">http://www.ultimatebootcd.com/</a>, is good.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T15:57:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8696","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Oh, and here's an something I just saw this morning via Digg. It covers some of the same ideas I did in my article: <a href=\"http://www.itwire.com/content/view/27176/1141/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.itwire.com/content/view/27176/1141/</a>","createdDate":"2009-08-25T14:15:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8694","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I can't recall if the CD has it, but the Knoppix DVD image has KDE (default), Fluxbox, Gnome, Icewm, LG3D, Larswm, Openbox, TWM, Windowmaker, XFCE, and XFCE4. So you can have a much lighter desktop. And, of course, you can boot to run level 3 and not worry about the graphics; the DVD image has tons of curses based tools.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T14:11:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8685","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Nice one Tony! Have to get them their first taste so they'll be hooked for life. ;)\n\nI think it is worth noting that if you give Knoppix a spin and don't like the graphics (I believe they are still using KDE), give a live CD with Gnome a spin. For those of you who are fervent minimalists, try out Fluxbox - you might be pleasantly surprised.\n\nI used Gnome for a very long time and it felt more like the \"work hard, play hard\" experience I was going for. When the overhead from using a bloated UI prevented me from playing resource hungry games under Wine, I found Fluxbox to be the lightweight workhorse for which I had been searching.\n\nAlso, for those of you with an always on internet connection who don't want to download a 600+ meg ISO and are interested in installing a Linux, you could always get a netinstall image ~120 meg.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T12:57:48.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8662","contributorName":"2fame7srqk6yk","title":"Prevent XML caching?","description":"Wondering if there is any standard way to prevent the browser from caching xml documents that are being used to bring information into flash.\n\nCurrently, I am just appending a fake argument (based off of the current time) when I request the xml in flash so as to fool the browser into thinking it is a unique file. However, this unnecessarily floods the user's cache with multiple copies of the file. It also doesn't seem like the most elegant way of going about it.\n\nAny thoughts on the matter would be greatly appreciated. Thanks everyone!","createdDate":"2009-08-24T20:34:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-25T13:37:31.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8690","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We end up having to do the same thing with some CSS and JS docs (appending a timestamp as a query string argument). Drupal does this as well.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T13:37:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8683","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Not sure if flash obeys standard cache control methods, but you could try setting the Expires header to a date in the past, or use the \"Cache-Control: no-cache\" header.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T12:18:01.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8642","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Connecting Billboard Users with Billboard Content","description":"<b>Often times we will build a web page like:</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/billboard.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/</a>\n\n<b>However, we may also want to deliver an eerily similar version of the same page for the large plasma displays driven by <a href=\"http://wolftech.ncsu.edu/billboard/\" target=\"_blank\">Billboard</a></b>:\n<a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/billboard.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/billboard.php</a>\n\nI'm wondering if we can create a standard way to link these pages together (sort of the way RSS feeds and fav icons are defined).\n\nFor instance, maybe on the labs page I could just add the following line:\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">&lt;link rel=\"billboard\" href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/billboard.php\"/&gt;</span>\n\nYour thoughts?...","createdDate":"2009-08-24T14:53:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-26T12:58:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8723","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Hmm, spidering is bad. Rather, if people want to be listed they should register with your service. A lot of people like to keep their events and such low profile so that they can get the individuals they are targeting and not the individuals looking for a free meal.","createdDate":"2009-08-26T12:58:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8710","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"looks like some of my post got truncated, weird. The last sentence should read...\n\n\"If the &lt;link rel=\"billboard... tag doesn't exist... the browser would simply load the default html content. Think of it sort of as a 'print' stylesheet, but only for billboard.\"","createdDate":"2009-08-25T18:59:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8707","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Ah, that makes sense. That seems like a nifty little idea. Kinda like how RSS feeds are handles, but with Billboard. That would be a great feature to add as a proposal to the project.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T18:41:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8701","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Sorry for the confusion. I'm proposing that the following tag would be placed on the <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/</a> page:\n\n\nThis would enable billboard to act in a similar fashion to something like ... say... Google Reader.\nWhen I want to add a new feed for Espn.com to google reader... I can just type in \"<b>espn.com</b>\"... where as the actual URL of the RSS feed is \"<b>http://sports-ak.espn.go.com/espn/rss/news</b>\" ... but Google knew what I meant (and where to look) because of the tag in ESPN's source. Something similar could happen with Billboard. Maybe I find a page that lists job opportunities in OIT, but I want to display it on billboard... I copy and paste the url for the OIT job opportunities page into Billboard... and billboard immediately picks up on the fact that they've designed a full size colorful ad for the positions advertised and it links there (instead of the regular html page). If the\nCould we also potentially spider all of the ncsu.edu domain for\n\nI hope I explained that a little better.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T14:59:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8697","contributorName":"1w0sf0zzlv8up","description":"Billboard's strength is that it simply delivers a list of urls. Not sure what is gained by the link rel here.\nIn the given example, the urls appear to end in the same page so I am confused about what purpose the linkage would serve?","createdDate":"2009-08-25T14:23:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8602","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Has anyone used X-SendFile?","description":"<span style=\"font:bold 15px Trebuchet MS; color:#a00;\">I'm curious to see if any of our Apache 2 users have implemented mod_xsendfile?</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://codeutopia.net/blog/2009/03/06/sending-files-better-apache-mod_xsendfile-and-php/\" target=\"_blank\">Read More About X-SendFile</a>","createdDate":"2009-08-20T14:54:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-24T12:27:09.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8813","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"This source dir for the service is not in AFS specifically for this reason.","createdDate":"2009-09-02T03:53:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8763","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Might be irrelevant, but we ran into this in older versions of AFS and their caching code.\nMAXINT(signed) = 2**31 = 2GB\nMAXINT(unsigned) = 2**32 = 4GB\nIf these browsers and/or PHP code are using 4 byte integers, you could be hitting these.\n\nCurrent versions of AFS still have a 4GB size limit for a single file. Keep that in mind if your source dir is in AFS.","createdDate":"2009-08-28T14:22:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8741","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"curl -v will show you the headers that are actually delivered. Essentially what I was saying is that the headers aren't sent to the client until output begins (at which point headers can no longer be set). Until then, most of them are treated similar to an associative array, being stuffed in with a key value pair that overwrites previous entries. So unless all three headers are showing up in the curl output, the browser will only receive one and doesn't get the opportunity to choose one that it likes.","createdDate":"2009-08-27T13:23:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8726","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Chrome and Safari both were tested and seem to work just fine, in fact Chrome is one of our suggested alternatives that we present for IE6/IE7 users.\n\n\"Doesn't setting the Content-Type multiple times only use the last one? You can probably delete those first two\"... &lt;- I've heard this before but couldn't confirm or deny that. I was under the impression that if a browser couldn't interpret a given content type (say IE for instance)... it would skip along to the first accepted Content-Type. I could be wrong and probably am.\n\nAlso, here's a link to the <a href=\"http://support.microsoft.com/kb/298618\" target=\"_blank\">IE6/7 file size limitations</a> bug described by Microsoft (I don't think it was linked anywhere in this post yet).","createdDate":"2009-08-26T15:09:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8722","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Doesn't setting the Content-Type multiple times only use the last one? You can probably delete those first two.","createdDate":"2009-08-26T12:53:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8721","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Along with Alan, I'm surprised that a couple browsers didn't make the list. I would fully expect both Chrome and Safari to be capable of handling a file that size. Rather than saying \"only these browsers work\", it would be diplomatic to say \"here are some suggested alternatives\". Too often I'm told by websites that my browser won't work because I'm not using the newest version of Netscape...\n\nRelated to the IE6/7 download limits, I'd be tempted to say that it is akin to a user using FAT16 or FAT32 (the maximum file size for these is one byte less than 4 GB). Similarly, individuals using Windows XP might fully expect that 4 GB of RAM would work correctly in their system, even though the hugely popular standard edition only supports up to 3.25 GB. (For the fans of trivia, Windows XP Starter Edition - a lower-cost version of Windows XP available mostly in South America and South East Asia - only supports 512 MB of main memory.)","createdDate":"2009-08-26T12:49:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8709","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"So I think we've nabbed the bug. It wasn't in the PHP headers.\n\nBecause our users were authenticating via Shibboleth right before their download, the browser was redirecting them back to our download script (after their successful authentication), and the script was immediately trying to serve a file... the sudden change of url and request for a file push out seemed to be triggering some sort of malware protection by Internet Explorer. We've created a work around to make IE happy (I know, how unusual).","createdDate":"2009-08-25T18:56:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8706","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"My gut instinct is that this has something to do with the headers we are passing to the browser with PHP. Here's the headers we are outputting... can anyone spot the culprit? Or does everything look okay?\n\nif Internet Explorer...{\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">\nheader(\"Cache-Control: maxage=1\"); //In seconds\nheader(\"Pragma: public\");\n</span>\n}\nelse{\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">\nheader('Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store, max-age=0, must-revalidate');\nheader('Expires: Mon, 26 Jul 1997 05:00:00 GMT'); // Date in the past\nheader('Pragma: no-cache');\n</span>\n}\n\n\n\n/* force download dialog */\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">\nheader('Content-Description: File Download');\nheader(\"Content-Type: application/force-download\");\nheader(\"Content-Type: application/download\");\nheader(\"Content-Type: application/octet-stream\");\n</span>\n\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">\nheader(\"Content-Length: \".$sizeOfFile);\n\nheader(\"Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\".$userFriendlyFilename.\";\");\n\nheader(\"Content-Transfer-Encoding: binary\");\n</span>","createdDate":"2009-08-25T16:47:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8705","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Daniel,\n\nI haven't noticed any particular problems from Velocity's users, but the average file size delivered by Velocity is well below the 2GB mark. That doesn't mean that it isn't on my radar, however - I see two options for going forward:\n\n1) Provide documentation for users instructing them to update their browser for files over a certain threshold. This isn't unreasonable, as IE6 and IE7 were built with certain expectations about Internet transfers in an age when an 8GB file download was simply a whimsical what-if scenario. Advising users to update to IE8 or later to perform actions that older browsers just can't handle is certainly the kind of thing that people have heard before. You could also advise them to use one of the alternate browsers if they absolutely do not want IE8 for some reason.\n\nSide thought: I'm surprised to see that Chrome isn't in that list. Was it simply not tested, or does it also have the 2/4 GB limit?\n\n2) Build an alternate download mechanism. As I've already built a Java program to get around the 2GB file upload limitation of modern browsers, building a related download program (or even better, integrate the two functions into one program) seemed only natural. However, in practice I have found that using the user's web browser for downloads is easy and reliable and fast enough that there hasn't been a reason to do the extra work for a simplistic file transfer solution.\n\nHowever, I've been working (albeit in a low priority mode) on a Java-based downloader in order to implement additional features - two very specific, widely-requested features, in fact: the ability to download multiple files in a single action, and the ability to transfer file and directory hierarchies. Currently, a rather poor workaround for this has been to zip several files (or directory structures) together, transfer the zip file, and have the user extract them. With a Java-based downloader, downloading several files at the same time and writing them into the correct directory hierarchy becomes very easy. Well, easy once the code is finished. Writing the code has turned out to be quite a fun experience. ;) On top of this, in order to maintain security and privacy expectations, such alternate downloads would have to occur via an encrypted format. When I was building the Java uploader, I looked into this and found such a rat's nest that I decided it was easier to just have a disclaimer that uploads done with that mechanism are done so insecurely. That works for one upload mechanism when there are other options for performing uploads, but expectations are such that any download is expected to be done so securely.\n\nSo, my alternate download solution to resolve a problem <i>easily solved on the user side</i> has now become tied into dependencies for three very nontrivial feature additions (multi-file download, directory hierarchy, and secure Java-based transfers). For this reason alone, I'd <b>strongly</b> recommend that you stay away from the concept of an alternate download mechanism, and instead simply post a notice on the site that files larger than [x] size will have to be downloaded via a browser in a supported list that you define.\n\nThat said, if you do end up writing it, I want the code. ;)","createdDate":"2009-08-25T16:26:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8692","contributorName":"35947pweiolu5","description":"Nice info here. All of this doesn't help with the IE6/7 download limits of 2 and 4 GB. Have you guys run into any issues with folks on older browsers and very large files? We found out yesterday morning that only IE8/Firefox/Opera can handle our Solidworks file at 7.7GB. I think we're going to have to offload to a java app for v2 (along with doing some RAID optimization) to ensure a wider user base.","createdDate":"2009-08-25T13:59:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8641","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Thanks for the heads up on mod_cband. Looks like a neat tool.","createdDate":"2009-08-24T12:16:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8628","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"To determine whether XSendFile even had potential to be the bread-winning solution I requested the file directly from Apache (after disabling some .htaccess restrictions). I felt like having Apache serve the file to me directly, without PHP doing the legwork would give me some indication of how XSendFile would perform (in comparison). Unfortunately, the improvements (especially on the user side) were slim. Now if you also take into account the loss of server-side scripting control (as Alan points out), the XSendFile solution becomes increasingly less viable.\n\nThanks for all of your valuable insights.","createdDate":"2009-08-21T15:54:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8627","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Having thought about this some more, the disadvantage to using something like X-SendFile is that you lose control over the transfer mechanism. For example, what if you want to perform some tasks after the client has received the file? In Velocity, I use that point to update some logs and statistics information. You couldn't do that with X-SendFile because the file only gets sent after your script stops running. And I'm not sure, but it doesn't look like there is a way to build support for resuming file downloads with this tool. Admittedly, I haven't done this in Velocity either, but it is something on the horizon.\n\nDon't get me wrong - I can see some reasons for wanting to use X-SendFile over custom PHP (or other language) code. The ease of use is a big one - being able to send a file to the client in one or two lines is very nice. So I can see where this would be well-suited for more simplistic systems.","createdDate":"2009-08-21T14:46:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8625","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"A few thoughts on running download.ncsu.edu as a similar service. Ours is CGI based rather than PHP, but has similar issues.\n\nIf you have to read the entire file into memory before sending it, you are doing it wrong. Alan mentioned fread and similar as a way to read a chunk and send it. That's a much better solution.\n\nExecution time limit is going to hit you based on the transfer rate of the client, not the server. If you happen to get someone with a 56k modem still in use, or perhaps even a slower broadband connection trying to get a huge file, you can expect that connection to be open a long time. If your time limit is based on CPU cycles used rather than wall-clock time, you'll probably not burn cpu doing a fread/print loop regardless of the client speed. (Excepting SSL overhead as Alan said.)\n\nHTTP/1.1 supports partial downloads. This is a good and bad thing. It's good for the client because they can do recovery from a disconnect. It's bad for our servers when so-called \"download accelerators\" make dozens if not hundreds of connections simultaneously for pieces of the same file. When your server only offers 150 connections before getting overloaded, having a single iPhone downloading 120 pieces of one file at once is a very bad thing. (Yes, this happened to wolfware earlier this week.) Back to the point, it's good if your software can be written to handle the HTTP/1.1 partial requests. That's one way to avoid the time limit. Unfortunately I've not written that into download.ncsu yet. There are other ways to handle overzealous accelerators, like mod_cband which is used on all of OIT's apache 2.2 servers.","createdDate":"2009-08-21T14:44:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8623","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Nice post! Thank you Alan.","createdDate":"2009-08-21T12:25:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8603","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"I haven't used this, though I find the reasons that the author cites as advantages over using a PHP script to be unfounded.\n\nHitting PHP's memory limit won't happen if you're using readfile() without output buffering, and reasonable values in fread() also generally work around this.\nMax execution time is easily changed in most configurations.\nPHP performance concerns are also easily addressed with proper tuning or using decent code.\n\nIn setting up and running the Velocity file transfer service for over a year and a half now, I haven't observed any of the above issues, even when the service is transferring several files simultaneously, or dealing with files &gt; 10GB in size. In fact, the only performance-related issue that the service faces comes from the CPU overhead of using HTTPS for transfers - something that x-sendfile will also have problems with.\n\nThe one advantage that I see it having over my PHP-based solution is that it automatically calculates the Content-Length headers. As you're already aware, PHP has issues with files larger than 2GB due to its use of integers in file-related data structures. To work around this, I've had to issue a call to the local system to determine the size of the file and treat the resulting output as a string that gets sent in the Content-Length header. The PHP Group certainly knows about this, and there've been patches submitted to work around this problem (see: <a href=\"http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=48886\">http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=48886</a> for an example for 5.3.0). My expectation is that we'll see one of these patches merged into the main distribution within the next few PHP releases.","createdDate":"2009-08-20T15:43:51.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8601","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Wireless device detection for apps","description":"Thought this may be useful for folks out there dealing with mobile content. As part of our work with the Mobile NCSU project, we had a need to be able to detect what device a user was looking at the site in so that we could optimize the view for their specific device. This means that iPhone users would get a nice, native looking iPhone interface to the site, while a smartphone user would get a slightly less graphical interface, but still nice.\n\nWe started using some python code written for the <a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/mit_to_open_source_mobile_web.php\" target=\"_blank\">MIT mobile site</a> (which we are basing the NCSU site off of) which implemented a <a href=\"http://wurfl.sourceforge.net/\" target=\"_blank\">WURFL service</a> to do this determination. The only problem was that it was aimed directly at the MIT app, meaning that no other apps could take advantage of it. As we struggled to get the code working, we decided to take a look at WURFL more closely and see if we could implement something that anyone (or any service) could use to do the device detection.\n\nWe found a WURFL PHP library and got that up and going in no time. In front of the PHP library, we created a REST server which will return XML. This means that any app can make a request to the WURFL service and get back information. So if you are working on a website and you want to switch it up for people looking at it on an iPhone, just use this service to help you out.\n\nThere is more documentation about arguments and options on the project page at <a href=\"http://code.ncsu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://code.ncsu.edu</a> (or more directly, <a href=\"http://jfaustin2.wolf.ncsu.edu:12001/projects/show/wurfl\" target=\"_blank\">http://jfaustin2.wolf.ncsu.edu:12001/projects/show/wurfl</a>)","createdDate":"2009-08-20T12:54:16.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-20T12:54:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8541","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Digsby WAS, the Best Thing Ever...","description":"Back in January, the <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/digsby-the-only-social\" target=\"_blank\">first Best Thing Ever</a> was about a new Social Networking client called 'Digsby.' It truly was the Best Thing Ever, as it aggregated your social networking services into one easy to use desktop client (for Windows). This week, we found out that Digsby turned towards the Dark Side, by slipping in a few extra features with their updates, and hiding some settings that you really should know about.\n\nFYI, I'm going to be rehashing what has already been said here: <a href=\"http://lifehacker.com/5336382/digsby-joins-the-dark-side-uses-your-pc-to-make-money\" target=\"_blank\">http://lifehacker.com/5336382/digsby-joins-the-dark-side-uses-your-pc-to-make-money</a>\n\nHere's the bottom line.\n\n1. They include 6, yes SIX, toolbars that you have to choose NOT to add when you first install Digsby. Yes this is bad, but at least they give you the option of not installing the toolbars (I've never had one install during an update, so this is just an annoyance really).\n\n2. But here's the really bad part. In layman's terms, Digsby uses your computer to make money. Yes...they do. Hidden inside the terms of service is a little blurb about allowing them to take advantage of unused resources on your computer to conduct research for them and their partners. Possibly the worst thing, is that to turn off this \"feature\" you have to go into the \"Support Digsby\" option on the Help menu, rather than in the preferences/settings area. Granted, you can turn off the client's ability to steal your resources, but it's still a crappy way to treat your users.\n\nTo be fair, they did announce/report it on their blog (<a href=\"http://blog.digsby.com/archives/68\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.digsby.com/archives/68</a>), and have engaged people on the Digsby forum, but they never sent out any kind of announcement to the users. You had to wait for the lifehacker article, or proactively go searching for them doing dispicable things in order to know about this practice.\n\nSo.....I am retracting the BTE title we gave Digsby back in January, and downgrading it to \"Best Features Ever, Except for The Stealing of Your Computer Resources.\"","createdDate":"2009-08-18T12:23:37.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-19T12:43:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8583","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I acknowledged the power consumption as \"additional electricity\". It delights me that I can use Firefox the way that I want to use it and they make money because of it. Google may mine the mail, but it is done automatically and that information (about who saw your add and why their e-mail triggered it) is not handed back to the advertisers.\n\nI agree wholeheartedly that it is how they make you aware of what is going on. The key is that people don't like it when something sneaky happens. If you click Next, Next, Next on an installation program, the unspoken agreement is that the program will be installed with the default options and won't install other programs or modify system settings. Anything else is an annoyance at best.","createdDate":"2009-08-19T12:43:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8561","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"Except that modern computers idle back on processor usage and resources when they're not using them. That in turn reduces power consumption, so they're still costing you something. Lots of \"free\" programs have features that earn them money. Mozilla makes money off of Google searches from the search bar. Google mines your mail to give you more targeted ads (which companies then pay more money for).\n\nIt's all about how they make you aware of what they're doing and then let you decide if the trade off is worth it.","createdDate":"2009-08-19T02:00:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8546","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm being slightly sardonic here. It is a huge betrayal when a program that you trust with your social \"life\" is sneaking around behind your back. This week's BTE is really a lot of fun though, because it breaks the mold while remaining true to form.","createdDate":"2009-08-18T14:36:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8544","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"While it is stealing, it is not a theft of computer resources. You weren't using them in the first place.\n\nI strongly disapprove of their practice of sneaking in \"features\" which earns them money. However, I find it highly amusing that they include a distributed computing client in their software. I was surprised to read about how well behaved it is - not using battery power and limiting itself to idle time.\n\nNow, I could see if you were already participating in distributed computing and they weren't playing nicely together, but other than the additional electricity used those computer resources were being wasted anyway.\n\nI'm not sure it's directly applicable to NCSU Web Dev, but Grid Computing is definitely a BTE.","createdDate":"2009-08-18T13:40:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8542","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Hi Nick. Thanks for this very timely update, since I'm doing an \"encore presentation\" of my Twitter: Personal Use and Professional Use Lunch &amp; Learn next week, in which I talk a little bit about Digsby. It'll be nice to have this info in my pocket when I do so.\n\n<a href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/event/twitter-basic-use-professional-use\" target=\"_blank\">More information and registration for the lunch and learn</a>.","createdDate":"2009-08-18T12:38:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8281","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  Getting Involved","description":"This week, our Best Thing Ever isn't about a product or service, but about an activity which has brought me an immense amount of value over the last week....getting involved in the tech stuff that is going on around Raleigh.\n\nI'm usually not one to make New Year's resolutions, but this year <a href=\"http://www.jasonawesome.com/2009/02/28/getting-involved/\" target=\"_blank\">I made an exception</a>. Part of my New Year's resolution was to get more involved in the tech community around Raleigh. I've been a part of the larger PHP community, and the Zend Framework community, and of course the NCSU Web Developers community. But I wanted to get out there and see what else was going on. When I started poking around, I found that we have quite an active tech community here in the Triangle! I was pleasantly surprised, but I wasn't sure how to get involved, so when I stumbled upon the <a href=\"http://barcamprdu.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\">BarCampRDU website</a> and found the organizer, I emailed him and the rest, as they say, is history.\n\nBarCampRDU was this past weekend and I got to meet a lot of really great folks. Most of the people I met were in the commercial side of life, but we all shared lots of commonalities. I even participated in the BarCamp process and gave a pitch about how to handle feedback. There were about 15 people in my session, and we had a great discussion about how to effectively handle feedback. I heard from a few friends that it was the talk with the best discussion surrounding it, so that made me feel good. I also got about 20 new followers on twitter, which is great for networking in the future.\n\n<a href=\"http://igniteraleigh.com/\" target=\"_blank\">#IgniteRaleigh</a> also went down this past week. I've <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/set-raleigh-on-fire\" target=\"_blank\">already posted my thoughts on it</a>, but I want to reiterate that it was AWESOME! Definitely less tech-oriented than BarCampRDU, but every entertaining. Both events have their own unique perspective, and both were really great.\n\nWhile #IgniteRaleigh and BarCampRDU are finished for this year, there are still lots of opportunities to interact with your tech community. There are tweetups about every month, where people from twitter meetup in real life and talk tech, have some drinks, and just have a good time. John Martin also told me about \"Startup Weekend\" where you get together, come up with an idea for a startup, and try to implement it, all in one weekend. That sounds totally awesome, and I am on board with that when it comes around again.\n\nThe point I am trying to make is that we have a very active tech community in the RDU area, and they can be an invaluable resource. But you have to make the first step and get involved. I think we have seen the impact that our NCSU Web Developers community has had on campus, so why not try to take that to the next level? You meet great people, share a free beer or two, and talk about tech stuff. For a geek like me, you can't beat that.","createdDate":"2009-08-11T13:19:40.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-11T13:19:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8245","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Billboard Followup","description":"First off, I want to say a HUGE \"thank you\" for anyone who filled out the Billboard survey that I sent out 2 weeks ago. We got a lot of great responses that helped us decide what to do next with Billboard.\n\nBased on your responses to the survey, emails that we have gotten, comments at conferences, and our own feelings about the product, we have come to the conclusion that Billboard has applicability to lots of people, inside and outside of NC State. Folks from all over the country are using Billboard to manage their digital signage, and we feel like that is important to the maturation of the product to keep it going. They have been able to take advantage of the Open Source BSD license that we released Billboard under and that has saved many thousands of dollars, at NCSU and beyond.\n\nWith that in mind, we have decided to embrace that diversity and run the Billboard development as a true open source project. This is a little different than just releasing the code as open source. We are going to be embracing the entire Open Source experience, inviting anyone and everyone to participate in the development of Billboard. That means we need people to help write code, formulate proposals, discuss ideas, and direct the project into being the great piece of software that we know it can be.\n\nI must note that we have the support of our management to run the project this way, which is a big shift in how we normally run projects. With that support also comes a dedication of Outreach Technology's time and resources to make the project successful. We have no illusions that this will always go smoothly, but it is an important process that we are dedicated to.\n\nOur hope is that other folks out there will get fired up about the prospects that this way of working can bring. If this strikes a chord with you, please join the project. For more information and how to get involved, we have posted a blog post on our website at <a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/ot/2009/08/06/announcing-billboard-community-edition/\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/ot/2009/08/06/announcing-billboard-community-edition/</a>","createdDate":"2009-08-06T18:10:24.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-07T15:23:14.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8204","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Best Thing Ever?  WRAP","description":"Today's Best Thing Ever article is brought to us by Dr. Charles Brabec. Thanks Charles!!\n\nWRAP - is it the Best Thing Ever?\n\nWell, no, no it's not. But it's pretty nice for what it does. So what does it do?\n\nWRAP is our campus-wide, web-based, single sign-on system. Users on any (Apache-based) web-server on campus can log in to WRAP, once, using their existing Unity ID and password, and they will be given a browser cookie that will identify them to other web-servers.\n\nWRAP is easy to configure: if your website is running on an existing OIT web-server, or many other servers on campus, WRAP may be already installed. You just need to setup an .htaccess file that looks very similar to BasicAuth:\n\nAuthType WRAP\nrequire affiliation ncsu.edu\nrequire user unityid1 unityid2 ...\n\nOnce configured, the Apache WRAP module automatically passes the authentication information to any scripts or pages that are running from the protected directory. PHP authors, for example, just need to look for the environment variable \"WRAP_USERID\" passed by the server, and the program can trust that is the current, authenticated, user.\n\nFolks who are setting up WRAP on their own servers will find it easy to install. We provide RHEL-based RPM packages for the current Apache modules. We also have source code which is pretty simple to build using standard libraries from Apache and OpenSSL. We offer a perl module as well. These downloads and some pages of documentation can be found at: <a href=\"https://webauth.ncsu.edu/wrap/\">https://webauth.ncsu.edu/wrap/</a> Note that we require users to register to download the software, but that registration is freely available to anyone with a Unity account.\n\nBy using WRAP, developers do not need to create their own login system. LDAPS is available, certainly. But that presents the users with \"yet another website asking for my password\". That - and good security practice - demands that your login system be SSL-enabled to protect the credentials on the wire between the browser and the servers. With WRAP, the users visit a single login page every time. That page is SSL-encrypted, so you don't have to worry about it as a developer. The cookie that WRAP uses is encrypted with 768-bit RSA, so it can be safely passed on a open connection.\n\nSo far so good, so what's wrong with WRAP? Why isn't it the Best Thing Ever?\n\n1) It only works on Apache servers. No IIS. No Java/Tomcat. OK, I take that last part back. The library has successfully written and deployed a Java-based WRAP module on their own servers. I'm no Java expert, so while I have a copy of their code I have never tried to use it, much less support it.\n\n2) It only works on ncsu.edu servers. The authentication token generated by WRAP is saved on the user's browser as a cookie. Standard cookie rules prevent passing that cookie, which is assigned to the ncsu.edu domain, to any server that does not have a name in our domain. A side effect of this that you may have run into: if you access your site by IP address, or by a shortened domain name like http://sysnews/, you will notice that WRAP will not work properly. The browser simply will not pass your cookie along.\n\n3) It doesn't play well with others. When it was first started, WRAP was written to use the same configuration options as BasicAuth. As a result, there is no way to tell Apache which \"require\" commands apply to WRAP, and which might apply to BasicAuth or something else. This becomes more of a problem because...\n\n4) It doesn't know about anyone who doesn't have a Unity ID. WRAP is great for Unity users. It's useless for guests. There's no easy way to extend the user-base.\n\n5) There is no way to handle idle-timeout. Once you login, you get a cookie that is good for the full time period that you requested (1 or 10 hours). If you walk away from a public computer, and do not destroy that cookie, then the next user has your credentials for the duration of the cookie.\n\n6) WRAP is an Authentication system: it tells you who the user is. It is not an Authorization system: it cannot tell you if the user has a permission, or is part of a group, or any other such attributes. The burden of determining which users have what permissions is still left to the code developer.\n\nWRAP sucks! What else have you got?\n\nShibboleth is coming down the pike. It's an open source SAML-based project that tries to solve a lot of these problems that are part of WRAP and common to other cookie-based SSO's. Specifically it improves upon these points:\n\n1) The Shibboleth service provider is available for Apache and IIS servers, and probably others.\n2) While it uses cookies, those cookies are specific to each client-server pair and do not need to be shared across domains\n3) Auth configuration is well separated from BasicAuth\n4) Your federation determines whose identity providers you can use. NCSU has three federation memberships, one for campus-only, one covering the entire UNC system of schools, and InCommon, which welcomes registration from almost any educational institution. We are also working with NC Trust, which is another state-wide collection of secondary schools and universities based in InCommon.\n5) It offers idle timeouts\n6) Shibboleth is an attribute-based system. By design, it sends information about the user without unnecessarily exposing the private identity of the user. In other words, it can tell your system that the user is a student at NC State, without giving you their name. It can also be configure to release few, some, or all attributes about a user per server that asks... so the same login can be used to visit iTunesU as an NC State student, and register for courses with the Student ID number.\n\nShibboleth is still in development on campus. We have a semi-production server <a href=\"https://shib.ncsu.edu/\">https://shib.ncsu.edu/</a> which is currently only seeing very light use. We are working on improving the horsepower to handle more traffic as new projects come on board. We are also still ironing out the details of our attribute release policies. Once these are done, we hope to open the service to general campus use, hopefully before the end of the year.\n\nHere's a sample of some current and future projects using Shibboleth:\n- VCL\n- UNC GA's cross-campus registration system\n- Engineering is working on a software deployment project for courses\n- Delta is working on Moodle\n- The campus portal project\n- Replace (or at least augment) WRAP as a general web-server authentication option\n- WebAssign already uses Shibboleth for other campuses\n- Google Apps / Gmail - can authenticate via SAML to a Shibboleth service\n\nLinks for more information:\n<a href=\"https://webauth.ncsu.edu/wrap/\" target=\"_blank\">https://webauth.ncsu.edu/wrap/</a>\n<a href=\"https://shib.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">https://shib.ncsu.edu/</a>","createdDate":"2009-08-04T12:44:29.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-10T19:19:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8233","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Ah! So eppn is short for eduPersonPrincipalName! That explains it. :)\n\nAlso worth noting: Applications (e.g. Moodle) with a flexible Shibboleth module expose the ability to map attributes to user fields rather than relying on you to have access to modify the server's Shibboleth attribute mapping.","createdDate":"2009-08-05T16:27:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8229","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I personally have no time, no plan, and no incentive from above to add OpenID to the mix of identities that we (OIT) provides. It's still on my mind, and would have been mentioned had I not been pushing the BTE deadline on this post.\n\nI hope that OpenID, where needed, can coexist with Shibboleth. VCL has done a fair bit with mixing ID providers on their service so they might be able to chime in with some advice.","createdDate":"2009-08-05T14:44:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8228","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Just to add... the owner of the shibd running on your server decides how the Shibboleth attributes are translated to the environment. You can map the Shibboleth eduPersonPrincipalName to WRAP_USERID if you like. It will still return the scoped unityid \"jqpublic@ncsu.edu\" rather than the expected plain unity id \"jqpublic\" as Jonathan mentioned.\n\nWe are still exploring the attributes that need to be provided, so providing an unscoped unity id in the appropriate field could probably be done, if there's a need. This would make it easy to make Shibboleth look like WRAP to the applications, but it would also return you to the limitation of WRAP where you have no awareness of the scope of the ID, and thus will have problems if you blindly accept IDs from other IdPs.","createdDate":"2009-08-05T14:34:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8223","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"2.1.2","createdDate":"2009-08-05T14:23:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8222","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Our setup is standard enough that it should work with any correctly written Shibboleth authentication module. Keep in mind that the shibd daemon needs to be accessible by the server which is serving up your Drupal site.\n\nWRAP_USERID is not populated by Shibboleth. The overlap field appears to be REMOTE_HOST. Keep in mind though that Shibboleth usernames are not the same as WRAP_USERID. Instead of 'rjhodson', Shibboleth provides 'rjhodson@ncsu.edu'. Fair warning: Do Not try to massage these to match existing WRAP_USERIDs for Shibboleth enabled applications. If you have Shibboleth enabled, then you should plan to use the Shibboleth IDs to avoid the myriad of issues that I ran into trying to make it match the WRAP_USERID.","createdDate":"2009-08-05T12:58:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8217","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"I'm curious if the setup of Shibboleth will allow it to work with the Drupal <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/shib_auth\" target=\"_blank\">Shibboleth authentication module</a>?\n\nAlso, will the old PHP superglobals (WRAP_USERID, etc.) be preserved to address backwards compatibility and will there be any new ones, like an array of the various attributes of a user?","createdDate":"2009-08-04T18:23:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8208","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"What version of Shib is the IDP running?","createdDate":"2009-08-04T14:41:25.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8182","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"Books about iPhone development","description":"At that get together where Apple did that overview of iPhone development there were a couple of books mentioned. Does anyone remember what they were and/or does anybody have any recommendations?","createdDate":"2009-08-03T16:27:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-09T01:20:23.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8192","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Thanks!","createdDate":"2009-08-03T17:44:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8190","contributorName":"2jt4yzjxvxgs7","description":"I think this is currently the best book on the subject:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Beginning-iPhone-Development-Exploring-SDK/dp/1430224592\">http://www.amazon.com/Beginning-iPhone-Development-Exploring-SDK/dp/1430224592</a>","createdDate":"2009-08-03T17:30:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8189","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Thanks for the comments. I definitely use online resources a lot also, and plan to in this case also. BUT.. I am looking for a book too..","createdDate":"2009-08-03T16:47:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8187","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Whats the name of it??","createdDate":"2009-08-03T16:46:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8185","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"If you want to borrow that book they gave me, you are more than welcome to come pick it up.","createdDate":"2009-08-03T16:44:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8145","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"BarCampRDU and IgniteRaleigh roll call!","description":"Hey everyone, just wanted to drop a line to remind you folks about some Raleigh area events coming up next week.\n\nFirst up is IgniteRaleigh (<a href=\"http://igniteraleigh.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://igniteraleigh.com/</a>) on Wednesday night at Lincoln Theatre. I'm not sure if tickets are still available, but our friends from Third Party Labs (the guys who did the Search Engine Optimization talk at one of the webdevelopers meetups) are a sponsor and are giving a talk too. The whole concept sounds awesome and I am really looking forward to going.\n\nThen next Friday night/Saturday is BarCampRDU (<a href=\"http://barcamprdu.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://barcamprdu.wordpress.com/</a>). Friday night, the pre-party will be at the Flying Saucer downtown at 7 (I think) and then the un-conference gets started Saturday morning at 8:30 over at Red Hat's headquarters. I am helping out with BarCamp this year so come by and say hi.\n\nBoth events require you to register in some way, but if you are planning on going post here and let me know so I can say hey.","createdDate":"2009-07-31T12:52:44.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-31T12:52:44.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8125","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"New software tools for iPhone app development","description":"Computerworld has an article on iPhone development that talks about tools other than Apple's Objective C. The url is <a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/nwyp4x\">http://tinyurl.com/nwyp4x</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-30T17:30:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-30T17:30:40.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8123","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Is your institution planning to roll out any--or add enhancements to existing--mobile phone apps?","description":"I've clipped the beginning of a discussion on the EDUCAUSE ITCOMM (IT communications) discussion board. It might be useful for benchmarking or contacts for experiences. If folks are interested, I can do another clip in a few days, assuming the dicussion progresses.","createdDate":"2009-07-30T17:04:44.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-30T17:04:45.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","fileAttachments":["discussions/48-ITCOMM_MobileAPP_discussion.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8032","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Trillian Astra","description":"Anyone use this? I'm thinking of ditching Pidgin and TweetDeck with just this all-in-one tool.. Seems similar to Digsby. It just won <a href=\"http://lifehacker.com/5322592/five-best-instant-messengers\" target=\"_blank\">the Hive Five on Lifehacker for best instant messenger</a>, that's why I'm taking a look at it. Looks like it can do mail too.. not sure if I'd be bold enough for that though.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T16:57:51.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-08-05T16:31:42.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8234","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"For those that don't know: Adium uses the Pidgin (nee Gaim) library for its services. For all intents and purposes, Adium is the Mac version and Pidgin is the Windows/Linux version. I'm not sure I've seen a Pidgin Mac version that doesn't require you to use Fink (the piece of software that makes it more like Linux).","createdDate":"2009-08-05T16:31:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8226","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"At the risk of throwing in an unwanted Mac comment I have been frustrated by Trillian's lack of support in that area. I too was a heavy Trillian user for years as a PC user but eventually backed off it in favor of various alternatives (if I recall correctly Trillian was a little slow to add Google to its supported services).\n\nI've been keeping an eye on Trillian Astra and I did signed up to be notified when they release Astra in a Mac version - but that was months ago. There's been no news on that front at all and I'd bet a nice shiny nickel that they haven't thought about that promised Mac version in a long while.\n\nAfter my switch to Mac I found <a href=\"http://adium.im/\" target=\"_blank\">Adium</a> and I haven't looked back. It's got all the connection services you can think of; I could even chat on Groupwise Messenger with Adium, if I was so inclined. On the downside it is Mac only and it doesn't integrate Twitter which I know some folks like.","createdDate":"2009-08-05T14:33:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8221","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"He's probably talking about:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/systems/site/pages/using-jabber\">http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/systems/site/pages/using-jabber</a>\n\nOf course, I think you need to request an account (which I keep forgetting to do).","createdDate":"2009-08-05T12:38:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8211","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I've been using Pidgin for a years now and it's a fine solution, and supports jabber just fine... but I was wondering about what you just wrote. Is there a directory of screennames of jabber people across campus or something? Not sure if Pidgin can do chat rooms either to be honest.. I know I've never done one. I typically use Elluminate for any web-meeting, but an ad-hoc little chat group session would be nice.","createdDate":"2009-08-04T15:29:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8210","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Digsby does support jabber, but i am not sure about the conference room thing. I know it doesnt seem to support chat rooms on AOL or Google Talk, so maybe it won't (yet) on jabber either. I still use it for everything though, and if there's a chatroom i need to join, i'll fire up that particular service's client individually.","createdDate":"2009-08-04T15:18:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8205","contributorName":"2vyz6lwayxwkk","description":"I've been a Trillian user for years. Recently swapped to alpha/beta testing Trillian Astra. Not bad. Though its definitely still in beta -- Jabber support works, but conference room bookmarks don't seem to yet -- ie, I have to rejoin conference rooms manually everytime I reboot.\n\nDoes Digsby support Jabber? Not finding any reference to that on its site. Without that, its a no go for me -- should be for everyone since we're trying to get all of the techies on a single Jabber IM/Conference system.","createdDate":"2009-08-04T14:30:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8037","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I was a long time Trillian user several years ago....moved away from it...i dont know why. I tried Trillian again about 2 or 3 months ago, and was completely disappointed. I much MUCH prefer digsby....but i do realize it is only on PC. Take it for what you will.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T18:54:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8033","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"itsatrap","createdDate":"2009-07-28T17:30:16.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8024","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","title":"Navigation menu using Dreamweaver CS3, CSS and IE problems","description":"Hey all,\nI have been having massive problems trying to get a navigational menu working for my redesign of the Plant Biology website. Even with tremendous help from Dan Underwood and Andy Click over with the DELTA people, we have been unable to fix the inherent problems with IE. The stupid menus have worked in the other browsers, only IE continues to refuse to coorperate.\n\nAfter talking with Luis Chacon over in Creative Services, he suggested that I incorporate the same kind of navigation that the NCSU main page uses. But I believe that involves php and I have no idea what that is or how to use it. I've tried again to use a navigation drop down menu from the dynamic drive people but it is not working properly in any browsers.\n\nThis redesign has brought me to tears at this point, I am not a programmer and I do rely fairly heavily on dreamweaver. I can read code well enough to \"tweak\" things when necessary and want to learn more, but I have hit a huge wall and can't go further.\n\nCan anybody out there help me? Either in getting the current nav menu to work properly or helping me impliment this php menu that NCSU main page uses.\nHere is my development site, <a href=\"http://www.cals.ncsu.edu/plantbiology/navigation/navtabularasa.html\">www.cals.ncsu.edu/plantbiology/navigation/navtabularasa.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-28T14:21:40.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-31T12:35:59.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/49-navtabularasa.html","discussions/50-pbstylesheetcss.css"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8141","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Added the menu from the previous post to the pbindex.html and pbstylesheetcss.css. Both files are attached.\n\nI hadn't planned on attending BAR Camp, but thank you for the offer! I have a feeling we'll be running around doing errands every weekend until the new year.","createdDate":"2009-07-31T12:35:58.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/51-pbindex.html","discussions/52-pbstylesheetcss.css"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8088","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"I'm trying to send this snippet from code, but it didn't take in my first reply\n\n<div id=\"header_photo\"><img src=\"New%20Folder%20(2)/flytrapbanner.gif\"/>\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<div style=\"width:auto; margin: auto; text-align:center;\">\n<div id=\"bodyArea\"><div id=\"left\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2009-07-29T19:47:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8085","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"OK i swear this will hopefully be the last time. I've reset my original design, but I can't seem to bring over the horizontal navigation menu change of what you did. It looked like it was working beautifully in all the browsers.\n\nHow do I slip that menu just underneath the header photo, above the two div left and div right?\n\n<div id=\"header_photo\"><img src=\"New%20Folder%20(2)/flytrapbanner.gif\"/>\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<div style=\"width:auto; margin: auto; text-align:center;\">\n<div id=\"bodyArea\">\n<div id=\"left\">\nI'm attaching my true new redesign index and CSS\n\nAre you going to the BAR Camp next week? I'll be buying some beers for all my helpers.</div>\n</div>\n</div>","createdDate":"2009-07-29T19:45:34.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/53-pbindex.html","discussions/54-pbstylesheetcss.css"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8062","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This is working for me. I haven't run it through the various versions of IE.","createdDate":"2009-07-29T13:16:15.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/55-navtabularasa.html","discussions/56-pbstylesheetcss.css"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8061","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Just realized that my post stripped out the html tags. What it's supposed to say is...\n\n\"The only HTML you'll need is some &lt; ul &gt; tags and &lt; li &gt; tags for your menu items.\"","createdDate":"2009-07-29T11:36:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8039","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"Thank you so much for this! Now that it is working properly, could it be switched fairly easily to a horizontal drop down menu? That was what my original design was going to be and I liked the way things looked with the horizontal menu option.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T19:57:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8035","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"If you want an alternative to look at......I'm a big fan of jQuery, and it just so happens that there's a jQuery plugin that would do exactly what you're trying to do...called \"Superfish.\"\n\n<a href=\"http://users.tpg.com.au/j_birch/plugins/superfish/#sample3\">http://users.tpg.com.au/j_birch/plugins/superfish/#sample3</a>\n\nSuperfish will do horizontal and vertical menus. Checkout the Examples link on that page i linked to, and then see the vertical style. All you do then is include the jquery files (js files, and some css), and then you're done. The only HTML you'll need then is some<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style: none\">and</li>\n<li>'s for your menu items. It can't get much simpler than that. We are actually using this for the OIT website in a horizontal layout, but it would be easy to change it over to vertical.\nOf course there's also the Accordion menu plugins for jQuery as well. <a href=\"http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex17/ddaccordionmenu.htm\">http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex17/ddaccordionmenu.htm</a>\n\nI like both of these options just because it doesn't require much to implement and maintain them.</li>\n</ul>","createdDate":"2009-07-28T17:52:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8028","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Here is the updated CSS file which should resolve the \"mousing over successive items in the sub menus causes the sub menu to hide\" issue.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T15:10:59.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/57-pbstylesheetcss.css"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:8025","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Here is the fixed html. Other than the W3C fixes, the child ULs were not inside of their parent LIs.\n\nOn a side note: &lt;style&gt; tags shouldn't be in the CSS file. It is already in the \"style\" context.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T14:44:00.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/58-navtabularasa.html"]}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:8021","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: VirtualBox","description":"I thought about it. I considered all the options. I consulted reviews, friends, my soul's reactions to TV commercials, and of course the all-knowing wikipedia (well maybe not). And after all of that, I still bought a Mac for my primary home machine. A nice shiny new 24\" iMac. I knew I'd have to change a few things as far as software choices, and I was worried about the impending hit to my wallet if I had to purchase Parallels. I know there are Mac alternatives to nearly any PC offering, but I recently found myself using a couple of programs that do not have a Mac version (yet). If you're an interested PC user, I'm referring mainly to <a href=\"http://www.artisteer.com\" target=\"_blank\">Artisteer</a> and <a href=\"http://www.digsby.com\" target=\"_blank\">Digsby</a>. Also, because my Mac will be used by other people less accustomed to the Apple way of doing things, I still needed a way to run Windows, as well as Windows programs.\n\nEnter....the wonderful, the magnificent, the totally awesomely free VirtualBox ( <a href=\"http://www.virtualbox.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.virtualbox.org</a> )\n\nFor the layperson, VirtualBox allows you to install multiple Virtual computers inside your existing operating system. For example, you could run Windows XP, Windows 2000, Ubuntu, SUSE and Fedora all at the same time in separate windows on your Mac. VirtualBox runs on Windows, Linux, Macintosh and OpenSolaris hosts and supports a whole bunch of operating systems....see here for the complete list: <a href=\"http://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Guest_OSes\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Guest_OSes</a>\n\nThe process is extremely simple. Download from the website, install, run the wizard to configure the virtual machine, install the OS, done! You'll be able to configure every little setting if you choose to, or you can go with the defaults for how much RAM to dedicate, hard drive space etc. I usually choose the defaults, because i can always go back and change the settings if needed. You can start and stop the machine as often as you want (there's no need to run it all the time). I use it for testing different browsers as well, which comes in very handy.\n\nSo, that's the basics of VirtualBox. It really is so simple, there's no reason not to give it a whirl. As an NCSU side note....I understand that it has become the de-facto solution for Mac users who need to run Groupwise. I guess the Mac version doesn't do some of the things the PC GW app does....\n\nSo...give it a try...i'm sure you'll think it's the Best Thing Ever...at least until next week.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T13:10:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-28T15:14:57.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:8030","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This is definitely a BTE among BTEs. Just remember to install the system integration software into the guest OS so that the mouse matches up with the host OS mouse.","createdDate":"2009-07-28T15:14:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7964","contributorName":"1f336f0y0zx2d","title":"cfselect and required = 'true'","description":"If you've ever tried to use this, you'll notice that it doesn't work by default. cfselect required=\"true\" is designed for multi-select statements.\n\nHowever... a LOT of the time I want a simple select to be required and leaving a blank value at the top to be ideal. I really don't want to have to write javascript each time to do this.\n\nThis solution alters the cfform.js to read \"if select statement is required, and value is blank... show message. I've yet to think of an example where I would encounter a bunch of blank value options unless my code or query was bad. Nor could I think of any good reason the displayed text would be blank in a well designed app.\n\nSolution: <a href=\"http://www.beetrootstreet.com/blog/index.cfm/2007/1/8/CFFORM-doesnt-catch-unselected-dropdown-lists-when-requiredtrue\">http://www.beetrootstreet.com/blog/index.cfm/2007/1/8/CFFORM-doesnt-catch-unselected-dropdown-lists-when-requiredtrue</a>\n\nPlease note that any coldfusion server that is caching templates will either need to have it's template cache cleared (click the button in the administrator: ) or you wait for until it times out and refreshes. I highly suggest you manually clearing the cache as to avoid any \"why isn't it working!\" moments.\n\nI cheated by (CTRL+f5) like 50 times.","createdDate":"2009-07-22T16:15:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-01-26T19:52:00.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:5089"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7963","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Billboard Survey","description":"Hey folks,\n\nI know we've said it before, but we have finally found some time to devote to Billboard and we need your help. We have been trying to figure out what features/enhancements/changes to make to the codebase, and we would like your input. If you have any interaction with Billboard, please fill out this short survey as soon as you can. We hope to start on this either later this week or first of next...\n\n<a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dDdobjg0aTlJQ2VTSWkzMlp3U25JRFE6MA\">http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dDdobjg0aTlJQ2VTSWkzMlp3U25JRFE6MA</a>..\n\nThanks in advance!","createdDate":"2009-07-22T14:14:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-22T14:14:42.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7942","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Best Thing Ever: Theme/Template Design Sites","description":"We're all familiar with the problem: gotta get a new site up quick but don't have time to worry about in-depth designing. Whether it's WordPress or Drupal or just a simple site hanging out in HTML Land, it's not always easy to come up with a nice, possibly professional, certainly snazzy site design.\n\nNow before we begin we're all probably aware that it's possible to find site designs and ready-made themes out on the web, however there are plenty of concerns with going this route. Most of these collections contain themes done by different designers so the quality of the themes vary more than Michael Jackson's nose (too soon?). Most of these websites do offer users a place to provide comments or rate the themes that are included but ultimately one really needs to be prepared to put some effort into at least testing these themes before going into production. Some of the sites I'm sharing here have done a good job of trying to manage this issue, but others haven't bothered to address the problem at all, so be aware.\n\nOh, and FYI I'm ignoring the theme sites associated with products (i.e. the Themes page in Drupal.org; the free themes directory on WordPress.org) since they're pretty much your first hit every time and often are more for tutorials and troubleshooting than displaying theme options.\n\n\n<b>Drupal Themes</b>\n<a href=\"http://drupal2u.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal2u.com/</a>\nThis site is a mix of the good, bad and ugly. On the plus side there are LOTS of themes here and unlike some other sites, it's all Drupal and all free. There's also a menu to jump to the category of designs you want, though I suggest considering the Drupal version (5.x, 6.x) category first. The bad is that there's no evaluation of the Drupal themes at all and also no larger preview or demo of the designs. And the \"ugly\" rears its head in the form of way too many ads that you have to scroll through before you can take a decent look at any of the themes.\n\n<b>WordPress Themes</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.themespreview.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.themespreview.com/</a>\nThis is a great site for a number of reasons. First of all you can search for themes based on the style, layout or appearance. They also offer support (a rare treat indeed) for any themes that they did and will facilitate contact with any other designers willing to take feedback or offer support. Finally, and best of all, they have a fantastic system for assigning points to their themes based on their XHTML and CSS W3C compliance, their compatibility with IE (6.0 or 7.0) and Firefox, their layout flexibility and other categories. And those designs that earn high scores are marked by a gold, silver or bronze seal that's easily identifiable.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.freethemelayouts.com/\">http://www.freethemelayouts.com/</a>\nThis site doesn't have a huge selection but all the designs are done by one group so there's less quality variation. These designs are a little more professional looking but still free and the site has a great pop-up preview of each design plus a full working demo.\n\n<b>Multi-platform Options</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.themza.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.themza.com</a>\nThese guys get a mention solely because they offer some decent, free Moodle themes, which are a little hard to come by. One of these with a few modifications might do good things for a NC State Moodle course at some point in the not too distant future... This site also has a handful of Joomla themes.\n\n<a href=\"http://themebot.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://themebot.com</a>\nIt's got an annoying advertise-y environment but there are free themes available for Drupal, Joomla, WordPress, XOOPS, PHPBB, Flash and some good, old-fashioned HTML. This site also lets you know up front how the theme/template validates, whether it's fixed width or fluid, if it's CSS or table-based and gives you a full-size demo. The designs are kind of hit or miss but there are enough options to give you something to work with if you put the time in to find it.\n\n<b>Design-only Sites</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.edustyle.net/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.edustyle.net/</a>\nMany of you have probably already found this site (I think it may have already been referenced on our Ning site somewhere...) but this is a good site to see what other schools are doing. And some schools are doing some really cool stuff. My favorite thing on this site is the \"Redesigned\" section in which you can compare Before and After shots of various sites. BTW, there are five NC State sites that have been submitted (there may be more, that's all I found); I'd love to see more but people are allowed to vote on your site (basically just plus or minus) so be aware of that going in...\n\n<a href=\"http://www.oswd.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.oswd.org/</a>\nThese are designs without a designated CMS so they are by nature a bit more flexible. This site kindly lets the user know if the design validates and also allows users to give it a rating so you have some idea of what you're getting into. There are a lot of simple, clean designs on here, some of which may look familiar to you and all of which are free, though they do have a \"premium\" section if you're shopping with a little money.\n\n---\n\nI'm sure there are other great sites out there so if you've got suggestions please post them! These kinds of things are always handy, even if it's just for inspiration or a jumping-off point. Best of luck, designers and happy browsing!","createdDate":"2009-07-21T13:41:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-21T14:40:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7947","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"Thanks jen - these are great resources.","createdDate":"2009-07-21T14:40:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7941","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Image-free CSS Tooltips","description":"This is a very very awesome article about how to create tooltips with CSS. These tips are 100% jQuery UI themeable too, so they will integrate seamlessly with your existing UI sites...\n\n<a href=\"http://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/image_free_css_tooltip_pointers_a_use_for_polygonal_css/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/image_free_css_tooltip_pointers_a_use_for_polygonal_css/</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-21T12:22:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-21T18:42:49.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7951","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The \"polygon using CSS\" might be very important for people to realize when using borders which are wider than one pixel and different colors than adjoining borders. They come together at a seam similar to the pieces of wood on a frame. The angle is determined by the width of the borders.","createdDate":"2009-07-21T18:42:49.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7881","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Adobe Support","description":"I've been unable to find any kind of support from Adobe for Contribute. We see a series of the same errors over and over and I'd really like to get feedback from Adobe about fixes. Anyone got an email address or better yet a phone number or person??","createdDate":"2009-07-17T14:50:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-17T17:30:45.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7884","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I'll give it a shot. If I hear back I'll post it here. Thanks Jen.","createdDate":"2009-07-17T17:30:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7882","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Charlie-- I'm not sure how much of a help this would be but our rep with Adobe is Molly Aiken (email: maiken@adobe.com). She should have some kind of information about who you could contact for help, though she's not always speedy with responses since she travels a lot.\nHope this helps!","createdDate":"2009-07-17T17:22:03.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7801","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"WRAP has turned extremely slow for us, anything going on?","description":"Out here at the Vet school we front end pretty much everything with WRAP authentication. Has worked fine forever. In the last week to week and a half we started getting complaints about \"why has the ........... program gotten so much slower\" (fill in with assorted program names). After digging into this we figured out it wasn't the program here they were complaining about, it was how long it was taking to get through WRAP. What used to be almost instantaneous(1-2 seconds max wait) now is between 10-20 seconds per log in. Has something changed in WRAP? Is there anything we need to do different? Is this just out at the Vet school (meaning no one else is having issues??)","createdDate":"2009-07-15T11:11:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-09T16:59:55.484Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7922","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"The certificate for webauth was changed to a GoDaddy cert today, Mon Jul 20. The lag problem should be resolved.","createdDate":"2009-07-20T20:13:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7847","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Jonathan, note that email you quoted is over 6 months old, and probably refers to a prior version of firefox. Even so, it's not good to see they have such a history.\n\nI have placed a support ticket with ipsCA to see what they can do about the problem. If they can fix the server that is down, then great. If not, I'll most likely get new certs for webauth and the upcoming renewal for webmail as well. Both of those have too high a volume to put up with this lag.","createdDate":"2009-07-16T14:20:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7846","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"That quote was from <a href=\"https://lists.dns-oarc.net/pipermail/dns-operations/2008-November/003354.html\" target=\"_blank\">a mailing list post</a>.\n\nHowever, it appears that the Authority Information Access entry in the certificate \"http://ocsp.ipsca.com/\" is simply timing out.","createdDate":"2009-07-16T13:21:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7845","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Thanks guys.. Interesting stuff. We'll have to decide what we are going to do on a global basis now that we have a fix, but at least we have one :-)","createdDate":"2009-07-16T13:03:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7844","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Yes, the CA chain will still be verified. I believe the OCSP service is supposed to give the browser information about revoked certificates and other such updates that are made after the certificate is created and installed. Personally, I have not turned this off in my firefoxes. I am willing to live with the lag for now.\n\nI'm going to have a chat with our security folks about whether or not this is a show-stopper for IPSca. If so, I'll get webauth and the others that I've converted moved back to a paid CA service.","createdDate":"2009-07-16T12:54:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7843","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It sounds like you'll get as much checking as any other browser. OCSP (from the Wikipedia link) appears to be an alternate way to identify revoked certificates (an optional security feature for faster revocation information).\n\nEven though it appears to be supported by the other popular browsers, it may not be enabled by default as in FF3.\n\n\"The OCSP service for ipsCA is broken in several ways. Firstly, it uses a\ncertificate that's not in any of the major x509 TA repositories (Firefox,\nOpera, OS X, Microsoft). Secondly, even if you explicitly import the\nmissing certificate, it's not authorised to validate the OCSP responses\nit was used to sign (!).\"","createdDate":"2009-07-16T12:54:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7841","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Charles.. thanks... your information was dead on.\n\nNow I have a question. I understand what certificates are, but I definitely don't understand all of the nuances of what this OCSP thing is. If I cut it off in Firefox, do certificates still get checked in general?","createdDate":"2009-07-16T12:24:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7825","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Found it...\n\nIPSca has an entry in their certificates for OCSP (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_Certificate_Status_Protocol\" target=\"_blank\">Online Certificate Status Protocol</a>) verification. That entry is (ocsp.ipsca.com has address 213.27.159.120) And that IP address is not responding. Firefox seems to be the only browser checking the OCSP credentials, so it takes an extra 10 seconds to timeout the attempt to contact that service.\n\nThe ideal fix would be to get ipsca to fix their OCSP service.\n\nA work-around is to disable OCSP in Firefox 3:\n- menu: Tools -&gt; Options (or Edit -&gt; Preferences)\n- Advanced section\n- Encryption tab\n- click the button named \"Validation\"\n- uncheck the first entry \"Use OCSP to confirm...\"\n- click OK\n\nNote that we are not the first to find this problem...\n<a href=\"https://spaces.umbc.edu/display/CIG/IPSCA+Certificates\" target=\"_blank\">https://spaces.umbc.edu/display/CIG/IPSCA+Certificates</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-15T21:36:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7823","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"This seems to be repeatable with Firefox, and not with other browsers. Here's the test:\n- start with a fresh browser instance\n- go to <a href=\"http://webauth.ncsu.edu/\">http://webauth.ncsu.edu/</a>\n- you should get redirected to the SSL-enabled login page\n- if that redirect takes a long time (around 10+secs) you have recreated the problem\n\nWe have tried:\n- Opera/linux = ok\n- wget/linux = ok\n- Chrome/win = ok\n- IE/win = ok\n- Safari/mac = ok\n- Firefox/mac = bad\n- Firefox/linux = bad\n- Firefox/win = bad\n\nIt appears to be something in the code where firefox verifies the SSL certificate chain. Note that repeated requests in the same browser session do not lag, suggesting that Firefox has cached the verification.\n\nNow, we recently (around 5 weeks ago) changed the SSL certificated on webauth from Thawte to IPSca. As IPSca is a chained certificate that requires more steps to verify, this may be part of the problem.\n\nMore info as I figure this out...","createdDate":"2009-07-15T20:20:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7804","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I thought it was just my computer acting up, but I have noticed that it was taking forever to pull up the page. I'm glad to know that it wasn't just me. :)","createdDate":"2009-07-15T12:24:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7802","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I've seen similar issues in general (on and off campus). Not sure what the deal is, but I will try to follow up with Charles about it.","createdDate":"2009-07-15T11:51:47.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7761","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  Cheat Sheets","description":"My mind is full of useless data. I remember the lyrics to most every Journey song, the phone number from the TV show \"Full House\" (555-2424...now I'm going to go hide), and random football stats from NCSU football history. Somewhere, way back in the shadowy depths of my brain, lies important information like /my/ phone number, where I live, where I work at, who I'm married to, where I grew up, and some more Journey lyrics.\n\nThe point is, my brain feels like it's full. This becomes a problem when things like...oh....work?...get in the way. Like I'll be working on a website and not remember the default CSS setting for \"overflow\". Is it \"auto\", or maybe it's \"default\", or maybe it's \"visible\"....crap. Where do I turn to get help? Probably 99% of us fire up the ol' Google and search \"css overflow\". One \"I'm Feeling Lucky\" click away, and you have the w3schools website that tells you all about the \"overflow\" property. That wasn't too hard, but I'm here to tell you about another way that may help....cheat sheets.\n\nCheat sheets provide a great \"crutch\" to help you through those momentary brain lapses. <a href=\"http://www.addedbytes.com/cheat-sheets/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.addedbytes.com/cheat-sheets/</a> provides a great set of cheat sheets for just about anything: PHP, CSS, Python, HTML, Javascript, MySQL, Apache, Subversion, World of Warcraft (wait, what? why? really?). And if they don't have something, just do a search for \"jQuery cheat sheet\" and, spladow! You have a cheat sheet for jQuery.\n\nThese cheat sheets can be invaluable if you are just getting started with learning a particular technology. And they provide a good reference for those more experienced to jog your memory. They will never be as good or inclusive as searching, but maybe they will help you save some time.","createdDate":"2009-07-14T12:55:48.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-17T19:02:20.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7886","contributorName":"3herub2xatqwz","description":"Thanks for posting this. I've already found a couple that I think will be helpful.","createdDate":"2009-07-17T19:02:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7781","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Yepper, this is one great site. I've been here before a few times. I've always had a huge fondness for cheat sheets, ever since I found my first Emacs cheat sheet in PostScript (hey, does that date me? (and did I mention that [X]emacs is the One True Editor?)). Despite my love for them, I mostly collect URLs and Delicious links to them, for some reason I just do the Google thang rather than looking at the cheat sheet.\n\nOn the other hand, there's some \"live\" cheat sheets out there that I do use a lot: <a href=\"http://api.jquery.com\" target=\"_blank\">jQuery API</a> and <a href=\"http://reference.sitepoint.com/css\">SitePoint CSS/JavaScript/HTML Reference</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-15T01:30:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7765","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"There is a ton of great information at <a href=\"http://www.zvon.org\" target=\"_blank\">zvon.org</a>, even if the latest news listing on their site is from 2007. They have terrific <a href=\"http://www.zvon.org/xxl/css1Reference/Output/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">CSS1</a> and <a href=\"http://www.zvon.org/xxl/CSS2Reference/Output/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">CSS2</a> references with examples that I've used personally. They also have XML, RSS, SVG, DOM, MathML, SOAP, and so many more <a href=\"http://www.zvon.org/index.php?nav_id=references&amp;mime=html\" target=\"_blank\">reference libraries</a> as well. Check them out when you get the opportunity. I've known about this particular site for at least five years, and I'm <i>still</i> finding things to learn there after all this time.","createdDate":"2009-07-14T18:03:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7762","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"/moo is definitely the BTE.","createdDate":"2009-07-14T13:13:49.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7702","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"SlickMap CSS - Site Maps with CSS","description":"This looks pretty interesting for those out there that have to do a site map:\n\n<a href=\"http://astuteo.com/slickmap/\" target=\"_blank\">http://astuteo.com/slickmap/</a>\n\nIt is straight CSS and HTML. Basically, it turns an ordered list into that pretty chart. Probably has other applications as well beyond a sitemap.","createdDate":"2009-07-09T12:44:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-09T21:24:50.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7709","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Neat! I'm a little surprised they didn't notice/resolve that small bug in the second column.","createdDate":"2009-07-09T21:24:50.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7621","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  Coding Standards","description":"Let me set the scene for you. One of the groups we do work for gives me a call and they are having a problem with an old, legacy-style app that they are using. The app is critical to their business practice, but nobody really supports it. It's been around for about 5 or 6 years, with minimal to no updates. And now it's broke, and they don't know why. So, here I go. I start trying to figure out the application, but the code is horrendous. No comments. Variables are named $myVar. Functions are called makeOutput(). There's one file with 50+ functions in it, and none of them documented. I think to myself, \"Who is the moron that wrote this garbage?\"....then I look at the ONE comment in the ONE include file. // Jason Austin - 2001. Crap. I'm the moron!\n\nIf you have been a programmer for more than 5 minutes, this has probably happened to you. You look back at old code and think \"What was I thinking when I did that?\". The good news is, that means that you have (hopefully) grown as a programmer. The bad news is that you still have to do something with this crappy code.\n\nTo try to \"future proof\" your code, there are some things current-you can do to help future-you not pull your hair out when looking at it. Perhaps the easiest and most productive thing to do is adopt a coding standard. Notice is said <b>ADOPT</b>...not <b>CREATE</b>. There are quite a few coding standards out there for whatever language you are working in, so there is absolutely no need for you to create your own. In fact, I would discourage it. Just use something that someone else has already put many hours of thought and reasoning into. This will be a big help when other people look at or edit your code.\n\nSo what do coding standards entail? Most of them have guidelines for the formatting of code, naming of variables and methods, naming of files, organization of code, etc. The goal is to make your code look no different than my code. That way when you go to edit something that I wrote, you can follow what is going on easily. One of the other main focuses of a coding standard is documentation. This is something that we all struggle with. It's just not something that comes naturally to programmers. Most of us are naive enough to think that when we come back to this code in 2 years, we will always remember what is going on. I'm here to tell you that that is 100% false. Documenting your code is essential to its long life, so like Nike, \"Just Do It\".\n\nTo better illustrate the difference between code with no adherence to a coding standard and code that does, let's look at an example:\n\n<code>&lt;?$my_var=array(1,2,3);\n$myOther_var=2;\nfor($i=0;$i\nfunction my_var($i,$l){ return str_pad($i,$l,'0',STR_PAD_LEFT); }\n?&gt;\n</code>\n\nOuch, my eyes hurt from just looking at that. What language is it? Looks like PHP, but I'm not sure. Could be perl... Why are there no spaces...anywhere??? What is $my_var and $myOther_Var representing? Why are we looping through them, and why is there a method and a variable called my_var? Now lets look at the same code, following the Zend Framework coding standards:\n\n\n<code>&lt;?php\n// Numbers from source\n$source = array(1, 2, 3);\n\n// length of return string\n$returnStringLength = 2;\n\n// Loop through source, echo result from padWithZero() method\nfor ($i = 0; $i &lt; count($source); $i++) {\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0echo padWithZero($source[$i], $returnStringLength);\n}\n\n/**\n* Pads a number on the left with 0's.\n* IE: padWithZero(2,4) would return '0002'\n*\n* @param $number Number to pad\n* @param $padLength length of the string to return\n* @return string padded with 0's\n*/\nfunction padWithZero($number, $padLength)\n{\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0return str_pad($number, $padLength, '0', STR_PAD_LEFT);\n}\n\n</code>\nNow this makes much more sense. Now we see what the point of the code is, what the variables mean, and what the method does. Both pieces of code accomplish the same task, but example #2 is preferable. This example seems really simple to follow, and it is. But imagine if you had thousands of lines of the first example code? You'd be lost real quick. With a well documented, well formatted piece of code, you (or anyone else looking at your code) will be able to follow what is going on.\n\nSo if you haven't already, I would encourage you to adopt a coding standard for whatever language you are working in. PHP is working on a coding standard for the whole language, but for now you can adopt ones from PEAR or Zend. Adobe has coding standards for Cold Fusion. Google has an Objective-C style guide. My point is that every language has at least one, so find it and adopt it. Future-you will thank present-you.","createdDate":"2009-07-07T14:29:32.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-03T15:36:45.802Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7806","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Oh, no, no offense meant. I've been around UNIX and the 'Net long enough to not take any religious wars seriously at all. And, yes, I've seen that XKCD, it's one of my favorites (that, and the totally classic <a href=\"http://xkcd.com/327/\">Little Bobby Tables</a> one).\n\nI actually use Xemacs less these days than I used to, relying on a mix of Dreamweaver (for the edit and site management, not design view), Eclipse, and Notepad++.","createdDate":"2009-07-15T13:11:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7742","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":":)\n\nDon't worry, just having fun in \"The One True Editor\" vein. I used emacs for a while and it was good. I only switched to vim because a lot of the servers I work with do not come with emacs (and I didn't have permissions to install it).\n\nIf you haven't seen <a href=\"http://xkcd.com/378/\" target=\"_blank\">the XKCD rendition of \"The One True Editor\"</a>, you're missing out.","createdDate":"2009-07-13T19:36:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7741","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"There's always the nox option for Xemacs. And comparing Xemacs to Gedit is Just Wrong. Can Gedit actually be set to be your login shell? I didn't think so.","createdDate":"2009-07-13T14:02:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7705","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"They could say: \"Don't use array_map.\" Or they could have a set of tips: \"By the way, if you have any calls to split(), you're probably doing something wrong.\"\n\nIt seems like a good place as any to have a \"Tips and Tricks to Avoid Burning Yourself\" page.\n\n@Jason, I was worried that their guidelines preferred the for loop. Sorry if it seemed like I was nitpicking.","createdDate":"2009-07-09T17:38:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7703","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"If there are any other perl programmers left out there, I highly recommend the O'Reilly book: <u>Perl Best Practices</u>, by Damian Conway. One of the few perl books I've actually read front to back, rather than just used as a reference. There's a ton of good advice on style and standardizing for perl code.","createdDate":"2009-07-09T16:39:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7663","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"While you are 100% right about foreach loops, the point of the code was to show the difference in styles, not show optimized, production code. It was just a simple example to show how code formatting is important to readability, which obviously it is readable, otherwise you wouldn't have pointed out the lack of optimization :)\n\nAlso, it is important to point out that most coding standards I have read (PEAR and Zend Framework I am sure) do not suggest using one type of control statement/looping method over another. Their goal is to give you a guideline to create readable, easy to interpret code...not to ensure it is 100% optimized.","createdDate":"2009-07-08T14:32:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7661","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Why would you use a for loop on an array like that? Rather than recalculating the size of the source array at every iteration and fiddling with an iterator variable, it seems like the use of foreach would be preferable and far more readable.\n\n@Tony: Xemacs? Really? :P The One True Editor shall not require xlibs to be installed. That's almost as bad as saying that gedit is The One True Editor (even if it is beautiful in its own way). ;)","createdDate":"2009-07-08T12:15:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7645","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Ahhh, coding standards. Developers probably have had as many arguments over code standards as over The One True Editor (Xemacs, BTW). The C/C++ folks especially have fought over K&amp;R vs. ANSI style. That being said, your advice is sound, and the recommendation to not make your own standard is about the best thing you could have said.","createdDate":"2009-07-07T20:13:29.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7525","contributorName":"2zcnsukt2voqj","title":"Accessibility lawsuits / complaints against universities for deploying inaccessible technology","description":"Saroj forwarded a <a href=\"http://www.readingrights.org/458\" target=\"_blank\">news release</a> about six universities either being sued or having complaints lodged against them because of their plans for large-scale deployment of Kindle DXs.\n\n\"The National Federation of the Blind (NFB) and the American Council of the Blind (ACB) filed suit today against Arizona State University (ASU) to prevent the university from deploying Amazon\u2019s Kindle DX electronic reading device as a means of distributing electronic textbooks to its students because the device cannot be used by blind students.\"\n[...]\n\"The NFB and ACB have also filed complaints with the Office for Civil Rights of the U.S. Department of Education and the Civil Rights Division of the U.S. Department of Justice, asking for investigations of these five institutions, which are: Case Western Reserve University, the Darden School of Business at the University of Virginia, Pace University, Princeton University, and Reed College.\"\n\n<a href=\"http://www.readingrights.org/458\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.readingrights.org/458</a>","createdDate":"2009-07-01T22:40:58.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-01T22:42:40.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1102"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7509","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"PHPJS, awesome functions for JavaScript Developers","description":"You've done PHP development in the past/present, you know the name of the function, and you totally wish you had access to that in JavaScript.\n\n<a href=\"http://phpjs.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Wish no more</a>\n\nYou can get a giant all-in-one mega distro, or grab just the function code you need.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:33:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-01T15:33:10.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:4062"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7508","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"ColdFusion 6 (MX) to 8 Gotchas?","description":"We've got a production server with user generated scripts of all kinds we are finally moving from CF6 to CF8. As far as our team can tell, 8 is a superset of 6 and won't break anything that people are using. If anyone has tips on specific things to look for so we can give our script writers additional heads-up, that would be greatly appreciated.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:30:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-06T14:43:28.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:5089","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7601","contributorName":"1f336f0y0zx2d","description":"CF9 would be well worth the wait AND you can go ahead and download 8 for development purposes to move forward with the conversion. A typical set of apps that is 1500 pages can take upwards of 2 months depending on the code for a complete conversion to production cycle.\n\nYou'll have to MANUALLY re-ad all datasources registered in your ColdFusion Administrator.\n\nAnd no... you don't have to go 6-7-8. We went straight from 5 to 8. The only problems we had was a few reports using an exploit that no longer worked. Those reports had to be all re-written.\n\nColdfusion 8 supports all correctly used tags from as far back as 5.0. It still supports cfupdate and cfinsert (BAD MOJO DONT USE THESE).\n\nFeel free to email me with any questions or gimme a call.\nChad_Stinner@ncsu.edu\n919-513-1527","createdDate":"2009-07-06T14:43:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7522","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I know, I know that CF9 is coming out, but we got the go-ahead and the license now, and in these uncertain budgetary times, you get while the getting is good. Plus, because of the central nature of these machines, we could only do the upgrade during a summer or winter break.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T18:13:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7521","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"One question..why are you going to CF8 when CF9 is right around the corner? I would wait for 9 if you could and skip another upgrade that you have to make at some point..","createdDate":"2009-07-01T17:39:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7519","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"I do remember when going from 6-7 that there were issues with the DSNs moving over correctly. I make screenshots and good notes of what it looks like inside the CfAdministrator whenever I do an upgrade. I also noticed that some of my databases (MSSQL) that used the text type needed to be changed to ntext for anything to show up on the page...weird I know :-)","createdDate":"2009-07-01T17:38:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7515","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Much appreciated! Also, to pass along to our tech doing the actual install, can you jump directly from 6-8, or do you have to go 6-7-8?","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:42:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7512","contributorName":"1f336f0y0zx2d","description":"Hey Tony,\n\nYes... definitely. I've done four transitions now. 5-7, 5-8, 6-7, 6-8. The worst is 5.0 to 8.0. The conversion you are doing shouldn't have too many problems HOWEVER... if there is any \"sketch\" code, or arrays doing things they shouldn't be you'll run into problems. If your app is simply coded you'll be fine.\n\n8.0 is extremely forgiving unless something was done in the code that was more of an exploit than coding.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:35:47.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7506","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"For all the designers out there...","description":"So you've got a PSD file, and you want a client to see the results without having to export to blahblahblah.\n\nCheck out the blog post someone Tweeted: <a href=\"http://www.catswhocode.com/blog/php-display-adobe-psd-files-on-a-web-page\" target=\"_blank\">PHP: Display Adobe PSD files on a web page</a>.\n\nI <a href=\"http://www.phpclasses.org/browse/download/1/file/17603/name/classPhpPsdReader.php\" target=\"_blank\">downloaded the code</a> and tried this out. I had a dumb-simple psd that rendered on my Dell 620 work laptop running XAMPP likety-split. The 12M complex drawing of weather images I grabbed from somewhere took quite a bit longer. Test your files before inflicting long waits on someone.\n\nAll in all, though, a fantastic quick-preview for pre-production stuff!","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:28:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-09T01:20:23.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7510","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"that is pretty cool for previewing PSDs.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:33:39.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7505","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"WordPress 2.8 is out...","description":"Well, WordPress 2.8 is out and about, and my install is telling me to \"Upgrade Now!\". I'm waiting for further kinks to be ironed out. Anyone here already upgraded? Good/bad experience stories welcome!","createdDate":"2009-07-01T15:23:16.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-02T12:12:41.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7542","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I upgraded a few of the wordpress sites i run when it first came out. Im not doing anything crazy with those sites -- just a few plugins here and there...simple themes etc. But i haven't had any problems at all with the upgrade. Everything is still chugging along nicely. So i guess that adds 1 to the good experience column for you.","createdDate":"2009-07-02T12:12:41.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7445","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  Google Charts API","description":"Everybody loves charts. See, I made a chart that shows how everybody loves charts:\n\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=v&amp;chs=300x200&amp;chd=t:75,50,0,50,50,0,0&amp;chdl=Everyones+Love|Charts&amp;chtt=Everyones+Love+Of+Charts\"/></p>\n\nYou're probably asking yourself, \"Self, how was Jason able to ninja up some fly charts like that?\" Well, I'll tell you how...it's the <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/chart/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Charts API</a>!\n\nIn it's no-doubt infinite wisdom, Google has come through yet again with a useful time saver. The Google Charts API lets you make all kinds of fun charts and graphs. Bar graphs, line graphs,Venn diagrams, crazy charts I've never heard of nor know what they mean...even barcodes and maps! The API also lets you add labels, gradients, grid lines, titles, legends. Anything you can think of needing in a chart or graph, Google hooks you up.\n\nNow if you have ever used a standard software graphing package, you may be thinking \"Yeah, great, but this is going to take me forever to figure out how to use it\". That's just wrong. In fact it is so wrong, that I made a chart to tell you how wrong you are:\n\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chs=200x100&amp;cht=gom&amp;chd=t:12&amp;chtt=Scale+of+Wrongness&amp;chl=You\"/></p>\n\nIt's as easy as making a URL. All you have to do is know Google's black-magic ways and poof! You have a chart that does exactly what you want! And Google is nice enough to lay all the directions and documentation out at the Google Chart API site. Want to know how any of the charts seen here are created? Just right click on the image and click \"View Image\". This will show you the URL that was created to form the chart.\n\nSo the next time you think to yourself, \"Self, a chart would be awesome right here!\", you can just call up your old buddy Google Charts, and BAM! You'll be showing people how awesome your charting skillz are. And on that note, I leave you with this link: <a href=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=p3&amp;chs=500x200&amp;chd=s:Hellob&amp;chdl=give+you+up|let+you+down|run+around+and+desert+you|make+you+cry|say+goodbye|tell+a+lie+and+hurt+you&amp;chco=CC0000|00CC00|0000CC|CCCC00|CC00CC|00CCCC&amp;chtt=Rick+Rolled+Chart+Style|Rick+Astley+Would+Never...\" target=\"_blank\">Most Awesome Google Chart EVAR!</a>\n\nSo a challenge is now being made to all of you who have read this article. Can you make a chart more awesome than any of my awesome charts? I don't think so, but if you do, post them up in the comments and maybe we will see how creative you folks are.","createdDate":"2009-06-30T13:34:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-03-03T20:21:58.340Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7706","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Definitely not in the alt tag, it should describe the purpose of the image. In this case it might be \"Groupwise Availability Pie Chart\". I believe longdesc is the preferred attribute for the explanation of the data. My understanding is that the screen reader would say \"An image of Groupwise Availability Pie Chart.\" The person then asks for more information and it reads the longdesc. If anyone knows a bit more about this or can repair the damage I might be doing, please let us know.","createdDate":"2009-07-09T19:50:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7701","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"considering that the charts API generates an image, i would imagine the accessibility issue would center on providing the charted information separately. There would be only so much you could include in an alt tag so-to-speak, so i would think the appropriate accessibility solution would be to give the chart data in a separate but accessible way . IE: Display the API-generated chart image, but clicking on it or a captioned link could take you to a page that lists the data as text. You could use jQuery (or ) to have a link switch the image div with the chart data as text div too. Maybe that would be a good method considering usability too, and thinking that all the data to display would be in the URL of the image, it wouldn't be too hard to grab and format.\n\nAnyone else know if that's the correct (and legal) way to think about this?","createdDate":"2009-07-09T12:12:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7665","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"Anyone want to comment on accessibility? Best use cases with accessibility in mind?","createdDate":"2009-07-08T20:19:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7503","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"++ On Google Charts API being one of the Best Things Ever. We're using the pie chart for our Google Map showing the <a href=\"http://www.ecu.edu/campusmaps/itcs/\" target=\"_blank\">ITCS computer labs</a>. Expand one of the map points and click on the 'Availability' link for an example.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T14:35:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7501","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=bvg&amp;chs=300x175&amp;chbh=20,5,5&amp;chco=058fcd&amp;chd=t:20,40,60,80&amp;chds=-20,100&amp;chtt=More+Bars+In|Unncessary+Places&amp;chma=25,25,25,25\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-07-01T13:43:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7488","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I'm afraid to ask what football cream is.\n\nReally, i DO NOT want to know.","createdDate":"2009-07-01T01:52:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7486","contributorName":"2nzrrfshzfg2m","description":"Hah, fantastic! :) These charts rock!","createdDate":"2009-07-01T01:49:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7484","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"holy crap that is awesome. I've never seen that stuff before. I gotta use that one something now...","createdDate":"2009-07-01T00:56:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7482","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I love the Google Charts API - but even more - I love the <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/visualization/\">Google Visualization API</a> - I'm using it in one of our applications - and <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/jasonadamyoung/google-visualization-api\">did a presentation on it for this year's ACE/NETC conference</a> (<a href=\"http://share.extension.org/public/extensionstaff/acenetc2009/googlevisualizationapi/\">sourcefiles for the presentation</a>).\n\nThe nice thing about the Visualizations is that they are interactive. I mean, you can take something like this:\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/59-MozillaFirefox.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"729\" height=\"501\"/></p>\n\nBut if you <a href=\"http://rambleon.org/other/examplechart.html\">load the example in a web browser</a> (view source for the data) - you get some interactivity with tooltips, highlights of pie pieces if you click in the legend, and can even process javascript events as folks interact with your visualization.\n\nGoogle even <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/ajax/playground/?type=visualization#pie_chart\">has a nice \"playground\"</a> application for exploring the API and using it.","createdDate":"2009-06-30T21:10:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7475","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"It's been brought to my attention no one gets this. It's from '<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w91-GMc3j7I\" target=\"_blank\">Ghostbusters</a>', though I realize if I have to explain it, it doesn't work. :(\n\nPS- hawt generator, Charlie! Good find!","createdDate":"2009-06-30T16:10:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7463","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<img border=\"0\" alt=\"Google Chart\" src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chxt=x,y&amp;chtt=World%20Series%20Championships%20Since%202001&amp;chts=CC0000,12&amp;cht=bvg&amp;chdl=Red%20Sox|Yankees&amp;chxt=x,y&amp;chxl=0:||45|1:|0|1|2&amp;chs=500x200&amp;chd=s:8,A&amp;chco=CC0000,0000FF&amp;chbh=150&amp;chf=c,s,FFFFFF\"/>\n\nI'm lazy, so I used this <a href=\"http://www.jonwinstanley.com/charts/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.jonwinstanley.com/charts/</a>","createdDate":"2009-06-30T15:47:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7461","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=p&amp;chtt=Percentage%20of%20Google%20Chart%20Which%20Resembles%20Pac-man&amp;chs=550x250&amp;chd=t:10,80,10&amp;chco=FAFAFA,FFFF00,FAFAFA&amp;chl=Does%20not%20resemble%20Pac-man|Resembles%20Pac-man\"/></p>\n\nPretty much the only things that I dislike about the Google Charts API is that you're limited to a total size of 300K pixels (it sounds like a lot, but you hit that barrier really quickly) and that occasionally AdBlock will block a chart (depending on what you're graphing).","createdDate":"2009-06-30T15:42:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7459","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"lol","createdDate":"2009-06-30T15:14:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7456","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/60-chart.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"160\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-06-30T14:39:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7454","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=v&amp;chs=400x200&amp;chd=t:0.05,50,0&amp;chdl=Groupwise+Mac+Features|Groupwise+Features&amp;chtt=Groupwise+Features+That+Are|In+The+Mac+Client&amp;chco=177F1C,3B699F\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-06-30T14:33:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7450","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chtt=Break+Me+Off+A+Piece+Of+That&amp;chts=000000,20&amp;chs=400x400&amp;chf=bg,s,DEDEDE&amp;cht=p3&amp;chd=t:0.00,0.00,0.00,100.00&amp;chdl=Applesauce|Chrysler+Car|Football+Cream|Kit+Kat+Bar&amp;chco=8B00CF,0FAE50,0A74AF,FF9322\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-06-30T14:21:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7448","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"challenge accepted.\n\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chtt=Things+Meatloaf+would+do+for+love&amp;chts=000000,20&amp;chs=400x400&amp;chf=bg,s,ffffff&amp;cht=p3&amp;chd=t:0.00,100.00&amp;chdl=That|Anything&amp;chco=0000ff,ff0000\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-06-30T13:58:18.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7421","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","title":"Ning RSS Broken, JSON support","description":"Not sure who else has noticed, but the Ning Latest Activity RSS feed is broken in the sense that the title links now go to a nonsense address. This is difficult for those of us using live bookmarks because the only link available is the title link.\n\nA quick search did yield this somewhat interesting piece of information: the possible values for \"fmt\" are rss and json.\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/activity/log/list?fmt=rss\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/activity/log/list?fmt=rss</a>\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/activity/log/list?fmt=json\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/activity/log/list?fmt=json</a>","createdDate":"2009-06-29T13:03:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-29T14:10:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7426","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Ning has been on the open social kick for a while. They got rid of their API's in favor of adopting the open social standards, which i was bummed about. I haven't noticed the RSS problem, but i dont use that feed, i use the individual blog and forum feeds and those seem to be fine (the twitter feed uses these as well and it's still fine). May just be a bug?","createdDate":"2009-06-29T14:10:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7424","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Jonathan,\n\nI hadn't noticed this, as I use a full RSS reader application (FeedDemon on Windows, NetNewsWire on OS X). I went back and reviewed the archives I have, and it appears that this problem first started between the 23rd and 26th of June.\n\nSpecifically, the problem is that the title links have been changed to http://<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com</a> rather than the URL for the action in question (such as <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/xn/detail/2486881:Comment:7316\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/xn/detail/2486881:Comment:7316</a> ).\n\nI'll look around on the admin side of things, and if I can't make that work, I'll try and get in touch with Ning support staff.\n\n--Alan","createdDate":"2009-06-29T13:47:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7422","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"On a side note, it appears that the death knell of Ning Development has rung. After killing off REST, silencing WebDAV, and quieting concerns with FAQ entries, those FAQ entries are now only available via Google cache with the live site proclaiming \"Permission denied\". There appears to be a rally behind some \"OpenSocial\" banner, but I'm not sure if this is a new era of Ning or a bait and switch. It would be interesting to find out who forked over the 60 million dollars but decided to keep their involvement with the project hush hush. My guess is that it isn't someone with a passion for transparency.","createdDate":"2009-06-29T13:29:28.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7394","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"CSS Grid Systems","description":"One of the major sections in the <a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/06/25/35-css-lifesavers-for-efficient-web-design/\" target=\"_blank\">Smashing Mag 35 CSS Lifesavers</a> is grid systems and grid layout creators. I've gone so far as to download some of the grid system packages (960, a couple of others).\n\nHave any of you tried any of the systems, and if so, what did you think?","createdDate":"2009-06-26T15:07:23.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-26T15:20:03.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:3593","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7397","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Oh, yes, that's right. I read your posting (I read <b>all</b> of the Best Thing Ever posts), and went to try some of them out. I even went to the grid builder Yahoo! has. Great stuff. I might give it a shot when we do some of the cleanup on our main pages.","createdDate":"2009-06-26T15:20:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7395","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"We use the YUI Grids system. We love it. I actually wrote a best thing ever about YUI's CSS tools a while back. Check it out here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/yui-library-css-tools\" target=\"_blank\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/yui-library-css-tools</a>","createdDate":"2009-06-26T15:13:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7387","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"List of CSS tools","description":"I ran across this on Digg today. It's a list of 35 CSS tools. Most I've never heard of much less used. There may or may not be some good stuff out there.\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/06/25/35-css-lifesavers-for-efficient-web-design/\">http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/06/25/35-css-lifesavers-for-efficient-web-design/</a>\nglenn","createdDate":"2009-06-26T14:53:49.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-26T15:05:27.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:3593","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7392","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I follow them via RSS and Twitter. Almost too much to keep up with.","createdDate":"2009-06-26T15:05:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7390","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I love smashing. They always have great resources and tutorials and free stuff. Definitely a blog worth adding to your RSS reader","createdDate":"2009-06-26T14:58:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7388","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Smashing Mag puts out SO MUCH content. Holy cow. Thanks for sharing, looks like some useful little apps here.","createdDate":"2009-06-26T14:57:10.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7361","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Accessibility features on iPhone","description":"FYI\n\n<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pj-1fULN8wI&amp;feature=haxa_popt1cus02\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pj-1fULN8wI&amp;feature=haxa_popt1cus02</a>","createdDate":"2009-06-25T13:53:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-25T13:53:27.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1102"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7318","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: SQLite","description":"Pop Quiz hot shot......you need a database, but you don't have a database server. You have a database server available to you, but you don't have any money? What do you do? What do you do?\n\nIf you answered \"get in a bus and drive away really fast,\" then....well....that's just plain wierd. But if you answered \"I'd use <a href=\"http://www.sqlite.org/\">SQLite</a>,\" ..... kudos to you my friend.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.sqlite.org/\">SQLite</a> gives you nearly all the functionality of a MySQL database, but in a nicely packaged flat file. That means you can use SQLite anywhere, without the need for a database server. You just need SQLite enabled on your web server, which means if you're using AFS on campus, it's already done for you.\n\nThe hardest things about SQLite (for me), was setting up the database to begin with, and then adding fields to existing tables (poor planning on my part). That's to say it was difficult until i found a very helpful firefox extension called \"<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5817\">SQLite Manager</a>.\" This extension lets you create and manage a SQLite database from your browser. If you're familiar with MySQL datatypes and the general commands, this will be an easy transition for you.\n\n2 weeks ago i had no idea SQLite existed. Now i've started to rethink how i can build websites and applications using it instead of having to require a MySQL database. A lot of mobile apps use SQLite for their databases, because it has a small footprint. I'm sure someone else can elaborate on that too.\n\nI know it won't meet all my needs, but for small, compact projects, it's a perfect fit. It's the best thing ever.","createdDate":"2009-06-23T13:05:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-09T01:20:23.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7383","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Just trying to figure out what the down side of SQLite and I found <a href=\"http://discuss.joelonsoftware.com/default.asp?design.4.281660.5\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>:\n\n\"(1) No data types -- everything is just a generic field (think varchar)\n(2) No security except for native filesystem security on the data file\"\n\n\"SQLite is best for single-user use (one user accessing the database at a time). MySQL is best for multi-user use. \"\n\nAnd as you mentioned too...\"For low load websites, SQLite has worked great in our projects\"\n\nThanks Nick, nice post.","createdDate":"2009-06-26T14:06:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7381","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"Firefox does indeed us SQLite for this. I got to meet the creator of SQLite at the <a href=\"http://www.southeastlinuxfest.org\" target=\"_blank\">Southeast Linux Fest</a>. His talk was called \"The Great fsync() Bug\". He was an excellent speaker, and once the videos are up I'll post a link. There was professional videographers at SELF, and all the video is going to be made available to the 'Net.","createdDate":"2009-06-26T13:55:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7335","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yeah -- i think i remember someone saying that a lot of iPhone apps use it as well.","createdDate":"2009-06-23T19:44:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7330","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I believe Firefox uses SQLite for a number of internal storage items.","createdDate":"2009-06-23T16:15:32.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7301","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Meetup for 6/23/2009 canceled","description":"We are going to have to cancel the meetup for today. Because of the wolfwise migration this past weekend, a training session for campus support staff was scheduled and it overlaps with our meetup. Knowing quite a few of you are the support people for your departments, and in light of having people choose one over the other, we are going to reschedule our meetup to sometime in July. I will let you all know a time and a location as soon as we reschedule.\n\nThanks for your understanding.","createdDate":"2009-06-23T12:05:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-23T12:05:46.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7262","contributorName":"0ssw8trg4zllt","title":"Searching AFS files","description":"I have been trying to perform a recursive grep search of my web server (/afs/eos/engrwww/mse/) without much success. I am able to access the files using ssh and perform a search such as\negrep astring /afs/eos/engrwww/mse/*\n\nbut I cannot get it to search recursively. I've seen references to a \"-r\" option, but it doesn't appear to work on our system.\n\nI also tried mounting the volume, but I don't appear to be able to search the mounted volume at all.\n\nDoes anyone know a way I can do this?\n\nThanks,\nRebecca","createdDate":"2009-06-22T14:43:58.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-23T12:43:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7310","contributorName":"0ssw8trg4zllt","description":"I get...\neos% grep -E -r \"aregexp\" /afs/eos/engrwww/mse/\ngrep: illegal option -- E\ngrep: illegal option -- r\nUsage: grep -hblcnsviw pattern file . . .","createdDate":"2009-06-23T12:43:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7305","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Does the following not work?\n\ngrep -E -r \"aregexp\" /afs/eos/engrwww/mse/","createdDate":"2009-06-23T12:34:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7281","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"Engineering will be keeping remote.eos.ncsu.edu and remote-linux.eos.ncsu.edu, which serve basically the same purpose, but are COE-only.","createdDate":"2009-06-23T02:42:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7272","contributorName":"0ssw8trg4zllt","description":"So, what I got to work was...\nfind . -name [FOLDERTOPRUNE] -prune -o [repeat \"-name [FOLDERTOPRUNE2etc] -prune -o \" as needed] \\( -name \"*.php\" -o -name \"*.htm\" -o -name \"*.html\" \\) -exec egrep STRTOFIND {} \\; -print\n\nHaving figured this out, I now notice the notice stating that \"On Tuesday, June 30th, OIT will deprovision the public remote access servers known as \"login.ncsu.edu\" or \"ssh.ncsu.edu.\"(<a href=\"http://sysnews.ncsu.edu/news/4a29151c\">http://sysnews.ncsu.edu/news/4a29151c</a>)\n\nDoes that mean I will no longer have a place to run these commands from? (Doh!)","createdDate":"2009-06-22T19:38:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7264","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"Some of the builtin tools get a little funky with respect to whether or not to cross volume mount points.\n\nI think this will do it (or something very similar, as I'm not testing this as I write it):\nfind . -type d -exec egrep astring {} \\;\n\nThat should recursively go through all of the directories and run a grep at each one. Not very pretty, but should work.","createdDate":"2009-06-22T15:22:44.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7200","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"Testing for WRAP cookie with javascript","description":"I could use another set of eyes to look over some code and poke holes in this idea if they are there. We have a true \"external\" public page that has a list of links down one side pointing to assorted places. What I'd like to do is if it was an \"internal\" person who had already \"wrapped\" through be able to see a link that was hidden from the general public. I've already tested this and it does what I needed, but since I'm not really up on the internals of Wrap I wanted some second opinions on this. OTHER then the user having javascript turned off, does anyone see any issues in using this sort of code/structure...Thanks for any and all advice!\n\noops.. I guess I can't put html code inline.. see attachment","createdDate":"2009-06-17T18:26:50.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-18T14:48:55.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","fileAttachments":["discussions/61-testjava.html"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7254","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Let's see if this CF statement makes more sense:\n\n&lt;cfif isdefined('cookie.WRAP_UserID')&gt;Do This&lt;cfelse&gt;Do That&lt;/cfif&gt;","createdDate":"2009-06-18T14:48:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7251","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Many thanks to all for the informative replies. Very appreciated.\n\nA little more detail to answer the questions posed in the replies.\n1.We run Coldfusion over here for internal stuff, and I could do this easily in that. But since this is a page on the campus servers that wasn't an option. We could have done it in PHP, but due to the nature of where the links were that I wanted to manage, it would have been more hassle then it was worth to shoehorn PHP code into. Javascript was just an easier fix.\n2. It's understood about Javascript not being a really secure fix to this issue. Actually this all started from an internal conversation with us wondering if \"could you do something like this\". So this would be more of a casual \"security by obscurity\" kind of thing. Even if someone took the time to look deep into the code the back end is secured down pretty well even if someone found the link.\n3. The WRAP options are definitely worth exploring. Didn't know it could work like that!\n4. The confusion factor about the link showing sometimes to internal users and not showing other times(depending on their WRAP state) actually didn't occur to me. Seems strange since that was the goal but I was too focused on the \"external\" people. But you are right of course.. I'll have to ponder that for a while! ;-)\n\nAgain many thanks!","createdDate":"2009-06-18T14:02:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7245","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Definitely if you have access to some server side processing, that is a much better method, because then you don't need to worry about if they have JavaScript enabled.\n\nIn PHP, you would then just check:\nif (!empty($_SERVER['WRAP_USERID'])) { echo 'authenticated links go here'; } else { echo 'public links go here';}","createdDate":"2009-06-18T13:37:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7242","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Glenn:\n\nI'm not sure why you'd want to use JavaScript when WRAP has \"optional\" as an internal state. I don't do ColdFusion, but one of my evil minions does. He says something like this:\n\nDo ThisDo this\n\nshould work. You would also need to write an .htaccess file in the directory where your page lives with the following lines:\n\nAuthType WRAPOptional\nrequire nothing\n\nThis flavor of WRAP tells the server to go ahead and show the page even if a non-WRAPped request is made. So you put the html for the \"internal\" list of links in place of \"Do This\" and the html for the \"external\" list of links in place of \"Do That\".\n\nJust one aside. Whatever method you use, it's always a good idea to stick some sort of \"authenticate here\" link on the \"external\" page to make it easy for your \"internal\" audience to flip over to the hidden extras.","createdDate":"2009-06-18T13:22:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7239","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"not sure if this will work but can't you wrap the content you want hidden from general public in a sub directory using htaccess then include that file either via ajax or php on the main page. This way the content will only display for people who have wrapped in but will be invisible to 'outsiders'. Only catch is how will internal people know they are missing content if their wrap session has expired.","createdDate":"2009-06-18T13:06:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7236","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"First, on that script tag, you should set: type=\"text/javascript\"\n\nSecond, because you're using JavaScript, you won't be able to hide what the code is doing so that third link that only wrapped people are supposed to be able to see shouldn't be treated as \"secret\" in the sense that if they click it that web page shouldn't assume that they are automatically authenticated. In fact, it is very easy to set a custom cookie with that field set to some gibberish. Sorry if you already knew this part, but it's worth mentioning.\n\nFinally, if you're just using it to hide a link to a page that people from public couldn't access because it has \"AuthType WRAP\" set, then sure that will save the public some confusion (but will cause internal people who haven't \"wrapped\" that day a little confusion about where the link went).","createdDate":"2009-06-18T12:55:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7123","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: WhatTheFont.com & DaFont.com","description":"Ever found yourself yelling (out loud or in your head) '<b>WHAT THE FONT!</b>' --- well maybe that's a stretch, but I'm sure you've wondered what font was being used in an image you found online. Enter '<a href=\"http://www.whatthefont.com\">WhatTheFont.com</a>'...the answers to all your questions and concerns....at least about mystery fonts.\n\nIt's a pretty simple process:\n\n1. Go to <a href=\"http://www.whatthefont.com\">WhatTheFont.com</a>\n2. Upload an image where the font is used, and clearly identified\n3. Submit and see the suggestions about which font it is, or some that closely match.\n\nJust remember, if one of the suggestions/matches is Comic Sans, just say no. It's not worth it.\n\nKnowing the font is only half the battle. You've got to have the font to use it. Here's where a few good font resources would come in handy.....\n\n<b><a href=\"http://dafont.com\">dafont.com</a></b>\n\nThere are probably hundreds of font sites out there but I keep coming back to this one-- <a href=\"http://dafont.com\">dafont.com</a>.\n\n<a href=\"http://dafont.com\">dafont.com</a> is nicely organized into clear, if somewhat subjective categories: fancy, foreign-look, techno, gothic, basic, script, holiday and a huge selection of dingbats. They're also sub-categorized but no matter how desperate I am to fill space I will not copy those lists here.\n\nThe really nice thing is that while the categories might help if you're not sure what you're looking for, you can still use the search tool to hunt down something specific. And all searches also give you a list of commercial fonts from other sites that might meet your description. Of course, those fonts typically cost at least $35, while all fonts on dafont are free. Makes me happy just to say it so I'm gonna say it again: <b>FREE.</b>\n\nIf in your searches you find a great font but aren't sure if it will work for your purposes, test it out! Each font has an area where you can type in the text you want to use, select a font size (tiny, small, medium, large) and then preview. Very handy for finding out what works and what doesn't before you download.\n\nSo the next time you're looking for a nice touch on a banner or a symbol that you just can't find in Photoshop remember your fonts and go browse dafont. I promise you won't be disappointed!","createdDate":"2009-06-16T12:55:09.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-16T12:55:09.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7027","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"doodle.com: A simple, elegant solution to a complex, messy problem!","description":"I love it when a simple, elegant solution solves what is often a complicated messy problem. <i>And I love it even more when you don't have to get a userid and password to use it!</i>\n\n<b>Picture it</b>: You want to have a gathering of a large group of people. You want to offer as many possible meeting times and dates as possible to increase the odds of finding an available time and date that accommodates the greatest number of people.\n\nForget collecting all those email responses. Forget that little piece of paper (or spreadsheet!) tallying all of the dates and times. Forget collating the yeses to see which date has the most response.\n\nJust do it all on <a href=\"http://doodle.com/\">doodle.com</a>, which has a very intuitive interface. I walked through my first schedule creation without incident.\n\nThe three-step approach to create a schedule:\n\n<b>Step 1</b> \u2013 Enter title and description of the event, and enter your name and (optionally your email address). I usually include these two sentences in the description, since no directions appear when the user comes to fill out the poll:\n\n\"Select the check box under the dates/times you can make. Leave the check box clear under the dates/times you can't.\"\n\n<b>Step 2</b> \u2013 Select the dates that you\u2019d like to include as potential days for the event. This is done through a nice calendar interface. Just click on the dates on the calendar that you\u2019d like to include as options.\n\n<b>Step 3</b> \u2013 Select the time or times you\u2019d like to offer up as options. Five different time entry slots are provided, but you can always click to add more. I use military time, but it takes other formats as well. (Examples are given.)\n\nThen you click <i>Options</i> (I just take all the defaults on this page), and then <i>Finish</i>. It gives you two URLs: one for the participants, which is what you send to the people you're inviting to your event, and the other for you as the administrator to go back and make any changes.\n\nAnd in the end, you get a very nice visual representation of the date/time available for everyone who participated in the poll. Just like <a href=\"http://www.doodle.com/hkhga7eitp2b7p9q\">the one for our Habitat For Humanity event</a>. It's very easy to see in that one that June 12th is the best date!\n\nEnjoy!","createdDate":"2009-06-09T15:48:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-17T12:53:58.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7161","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Cool. Thanks!","createdDate":"2009-06-17T12:53:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7141","contributorName":"i643tt9ut0ty","description":"I really like this tool, also. In addition to using it for scheduling activities, you can also use it for a sign-up sheet or a poll by inserting your own column headings instead of dates. You could limit the number of people who select any one column to a maximum number. Likewise, you can limit the number of columns that are checked by any one person. Try it.\nDede","createdDate":"2009-06-17T03:06:52.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7026","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Need Volunteers to write BTE's","description":"Hey yall,\n\nWe would really like to have some volunteer \"guest bloggers\" to write some features for the \"Best Thing Ever\" articles. They don't have to be long, and can really be about anything you care to write about. We have done articles on services, products, non-profits, etc.\n\nIf you would like to write something, please go here and fill out this form:\n\n<a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=cjVidzVxLWllMlhyWXV4M3pwVDNzeXc6MA\">http://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=cjVidzVxLWllMlhyWXV4M3pwVDNzeXc6MA</a>..\n\nThanks a bunch!","createdDate":"2009-06-09T15:06:36.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-09T15:06:37.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:7024","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Social Media Summit TODAY at 1pm","description":"I meant to post this sooner, but I didn't get around to it until now. I received the following note from the University Web Developers group and thought some of you might be interested:\n\n=========================\nI\u2019d like to extend an invitation to join me at a virtual summit as we explore the challenges and opportunities of social media in higher education.\n\nSocial Media Summit\nTuesday, June 9, 2009\n1:00 pm - 3:00 PM (Eastern)\n\nOriginating from the 2009 Penn State Web Conference\n\nHashTag #smsummit\n\nThe format will be much different than a typical workshop. Following the principles of an unconference, we will leverage the wisdom of the crowd in an open environment where everyone\u2019s participation is encouraged.\n\nIn addition to those attending in person, we will be using Adobe Connect to stream the event live and allow our virtual attendees to participate in the proceedings. The URL for the summit is <a href=\"http://breeze.psu.edu/psuwebsms\">http://breeze.psu.edu/psuwebsms</a>. (Please note the login will be required during the summit.)\n\nWe will also be utilizing social media to create a backchannel to let people from across the globe participate virtually. For those of you who want to participate on Twitter, delicious, Flickr, etc., the hashtag for the event is #smsummit\n\nDiscussion topics will be chosen by participants. To facilitate conversation both before and after the summit, I have created the following group on our site: <a href=\"http://cuwebd.ning.com/group/socialmediasummit\">http://cuwebd.ning.com/group/socialmediasummit</a> . I have started the conversation with a couple of potential topics for the summit. I encourage everyone to take a look at the topic list prior to the event and add additional items for discussion.\n\nI look forward to an interesting afternoon. Hope to see you there.\n\nThanks \u2013\n\nMark Greenfield\n=========================\n\nI found out after that email that you will need to create a \"friends of Penn State\" id, so instructions are available from the main Social Media Summit page at <a href=\"https://breeze.psu.edu/psuwebsms\">https://breeze.psu.edu/psuwebsms</a>\n\nIf anyone in the hillsborough building wants to watch/participate, we have a projector and sound setup in our office in 214 HLB. Drop me a line if you want to come over and watch it with us.","createdDate":"2009-06-09T12:54:36.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-09T12:54:51.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6983","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Auto Rotation of Images plus Captions and ALT tags","description":"Hey web dev community, I could use your collective help/input for a project I'm working on.\n\nDoes anyone know of a way to automatically rotate through images that are aligned with corresponding captions and ALT tags? The rotation can be via page refresh or by a timer, not picky there.\n\nI know this is possible through some lightweight PHP, or whatever scripting you use, development, but I was thinking that this would be a common enough request that someone has made it already. Alas I have only found auto-rotate scripts, nothing that ties in ALT + caption. Any ideas or thing you could point me to?","createdDate":"2009-06-08T14:02:49.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-08T19:30:22.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6996","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"sounds like you've already figured it out....but just in case you hadn't seen this, i figured i'd send it along:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex4/frogjs/index.htm\">http://www.dynamicdrive.com/dynamicindex4/frogjs/index.htm</a>\n\nBasically a image slideshow / rotator, but you may be able to wedge it into what you need, especially seeing that it seems to just use the image and the alt text, instead of a database.\n\n<a href=\"http://DynamicDrive.com\">DynamicDrive.com</a> has some others too, but i'll let you browse through them to figure out if they may be what you need.","createdDate":"2009-06-08T19:30:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6994","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Thanks for the advice Jason, but I actually was looking to just hit one image with an alt and a caption at random from a set of about 20 or so. I went with the DB method, which I figured was the answer, but the laziness (spelling?) inside me told me someone else might have made some sort of open source PHP package for this (which would probably be overkill, it's not that complicated). So I spent a little bit of time and coded up something along the lines of Mike's first suggestion. Works like a dream, only problem is that now only I can edit what's inside the DB, though... that's not such a bad thing actually.\n\nPS. Love the webdevelopers community! Helps me look good :)","createdDate":"2009-06-08T18:34:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6991","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think you should be able to do it with jQuery pretty easy if they are already in your webpage. If I understand your problem correctly, you have a set of 10 images and 4 of them have similar alt or caption tags? So you want to select all the images with the same alt and caption tags?\n\nIf so, you can do something like this:\n\n$('img').filter(function() {\nreturn this.alt.match(/yourtag/);\n}).each(\n//show or hide images accordingly\n);\n\nBut that may not be what you were looking for since i just read mike's response.","createdDate":"2009-06-08T15:55:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6988","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"thanks for the suggestions!","createdDate":"2009-06-08T15:13:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6985","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"There are two options I would suggest...\n\n1) Use a database to store the path to the image, the alt text and caption (you could even go so far as to store a frequency variable, if you wanted some images to appear more often than others)\n\n2) You could simply create a directory for your images and captions, save your images in there and save your captions with the same base file name but as text files...\n\nExample contents of the directory 'rotating-images/'\nvysocka.jpg\nvysocka.txt\nmorris.jpg\nmorris.txt\ngoogle.jpg\ngoogle.txt\n\nYou can instruct PHP to choose a random jpg photo from the directory, then look for a text file with the same base file name and use the contents of the text file as your alt text.","createdDate":"2009-06-08T14:54:51.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6853","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"ZF 1.8 Webinar Tomorrow","description":"Hey guys,\n\nJust got a note from the ZF mailing list that Matthew Weier O'Phinney (project lead for ZF) will be doing a webinar on the new features in ZF 1.8\n\n<a href=\"http://www.zend.com/en/company/news/event/webinar-unveiling-zend-framework\">\n<a href=\"http://www.zend.com/en/company/news/event/webinar-unveiling-zend-framework\">http://www.zend.com/en/company/news/event/webinar-unveiling-zend-framework</a></a>","createdDate":"2009-06-02T16:26:31.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-02T16:26:31.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:220"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6844","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: Kiva.org","description":"With the upcoming Habitat for Humanity event for the NCSU Web Developers Community (<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer\">click here for the thread about it</a>), I figured it might be time to talk about something that I really do think is the best thing ever. Want to contribute to a worthwhile project but wondered where your money was going? Do you like to have a little more stake in what your money is being used for? Do you get the overwhelming feeling that your small gift doesn't really help any individual in particular? Enter...<a href=\"http://www.kiva.org\">Kiva.org</a>...loans that change lives.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.kiva.org\">Kiva.org</a> is a microfinance organization. Simply put, Kiva allows individuals to make small loans to people all over the globe. You can make a loan as small as $25, or as large as the amount being asked for.\n\n<b>Here's the way it works:</b>\n\n1. A person or group has a project that needs funding, so Kiva and a local agency help that person get their project posted to kiva.org\n2. Many people make loans to that project until it is fully funded\n3. The loan funding is dispersed to the project owner\n4. They make payments back to you over the course of the loan period.\n\nHere's some of the reasons I really like Kiva (other than the feeling of actually making a difference in an individual's life):\n\n<b>1. You can lend as part of a team</b>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/62-kiva_team_page.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/63-kiva_team_page.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\"/></a></p>\n\nI have setup the NCSU Web Developer's team on Kiva, so if anyone wants to join, please do: <a href=\"http://www.kiva.org/team/ncsuwebdev\">http://www.kiva.org/team/ncsuwebdev</a>. Teams can more easily meet the asking amounts of certain projects, and therefore more quickly help a project get off the ground. Maybe there are projects on Kiva that suit our web developer's community, like <a href=\"http://www.kiva.org/app.php?page=businesses&amp;action=about&amp;id=105142\">Internet Cafes</a> or other web related businesses.\n\n<b>2. Get your research &amp; statistics fix:</b>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/64-kiva_stats.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/65-kiva_stats.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"147\"/></a></p>\n\nYou can research the risk factors for loaning to different parts of the world. For example, you can choose whether to loan based on a star rating system, or amount of delinquent loans, or number of loans defaulted.\n\n<b>3. Kiva.org is built on Zend Framework</b>\nWell...not really a good reason, but it's interesting to know.\n\n<b>4. You get paid back or you can re-invest.</b>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/66-kiva_stats2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/67-kiva_stats2.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"138\"/></a></p>\n\nYou don't earn interest on your loans, so don't expect to be making money off Mr Azizov in Tajikistan who farms livestock. I like the idea of being able to pull my money out, if i ever get into a situation where i need some funds. With Kiva, loan payments made by the project owners are put into my Kiva account. I can either choose to re-lend the money to another project, or withdraw it into my own bank account. I am yet to withdraw anything yet, so i can't tell you about that process with any individual experience.\n\nSo check out Kiva when you get a chance. Kiva is also on twitter (<a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/kiva\">@kiva</a>) and there's a <a href=\"http://kiva.ourtoolbar.com/\">firefox toolbar</a> that lets you keep a trained eye on your loans...if you like having a little closer look at how your money is doing.\n\nI've been using Kiva since April 9th, 2008, and have since <a href=\"http://www.kiva.org/lender/usaussie\">made 15 loans</a>. I expect to make many more, and hope that those of you who may be able to, join the NCSU Web Developer's team on Kiva with me.","createdDate":"2009-06-02T12:05:46.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-02T12:15:06.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6808","contributorName":"2vklsif9jjgh1","title":"Free WAP/WML emulators","description":"Hi Folks,\n\nI was looking for a free WAP/WML emulator for Windows XP a couple weeks ago to demo the mobile web interface for <a href=\"http://gwweb.ncsu.edu\">http://gwweb.ncsu.edu</a>. We had plans to use an Elmo anyhow, so not a huge deal, but I'm wondering how you web dev folks handle this. I found a couple freebies, but none of them properly displayed the page. I don't see any money available to buy even a modest package, and this is more of a desire than a need. Any suggestions? I suppose we could use the Windows Mobile emulator package from MS. Maybe that's the best route, but it's a bit cumbersome to install and flaky to run.\n\nThanks,\n\nBarry","createdDate":"2009-05-28T23:18:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-28T23:19:00.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6781","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"mobile stylesheet","description":"FYI\n\nSubject:\nRe: Mobile Version\nFrom:\"Donald St. Martin\"\nDate:Wed, 27 May 2009 11:21:15 -0500\n\nI am starting the research on the best way to create a mobile version of our\nsite. One site that I came across that wasn't on your list is\n<a href=\"http://www.rhomobile.com\">http://www.rhomobile.com</a>\n\nDonald St. Martin\nWeb Designer\nTexas A&amp;M Engineering Communications\n3134 TAMU\nCollege Station, Texas 77843-3126\n(979) 845-8439\ndstmartin@tamu.edu\n<a href=\"http://engineering.tamu.edu\">http://engineering.tamu.edu</a>\n\nSubject:\nRe: Mobile Version\nFrom:David Mulder\nDate:Wed, 27 May 2009 13:43:12 -0400\n\nThere are a few approaches to mobile sites\n\n1. Do nothing (No effort)\nMobile technology is getting better and will eventually offer a similar experience as you'd get on a desktop. Besides, mobile visitors are used to their devices rendering screen-based webpages in a different format. The websites that Robert pointed to are supporting this approach (let the technology catch up).\n\n2. Use a mobile stylesheet (A little effort)\nCreate a mobile-specific stylesheet that is activated on mobile devices. You can make the experience a little more friendly for those visitors by making link targets bigger and reducing the amount of small text.\n\n3. Sign up for a mobile transcoding service (A little effort + money)\nAn increasingly popular option. The service automatically creates a stripped-down version of your website and a few key content sections (you don't have to maintain it separately). One advantage is that data presented is optimized for specific devices (they use device detection). A popular service is Usablenet Mobile (<a href=\"http://www.usablenet.com/usablenet_mobile.html\">http://www.usablenet.com/usablenet_mobile.html</a>).\n\n4. Create an independent mobile version of your website (A lot of effort)\nIt is very important to consider the geographical context of mobile users. The things they do and the functionality they need is dependent on where they are, not necessarily who they are. A student on campus may be wondering where the nearest computer lab is or what the bus schedule looks like. Visitors may want to know what events are going on, where they can eat, and how they can get from one point to another. Essentially, you create a mental model that is completely independent of what you used to build your homepage, and then go from there. Obviously, there's a substantial effort behind this approach, but it's the best if you want to create a rewarding and motivating mobile experience.\n\nIn case you're wondering, my university is currently using approach #2, but is looking to shift toward approach #3 or #4 in the next year or so.\n\n\nAlso see:\n<a href=\"http://www.alistapart.com/articles/return-of-the-mobile-stylesheet\">http://www.alistapart.com/articles/return-of-the-mobile-stylesheet</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-28T11:29:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-16T20:47:57.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7865","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"#1 is probably the best plan in the sense that if you can design it using standards, the mobile devices will be able to interpret it in the way that makes the most sense.\n\n#2 has the advantage of trying to cut down on the \"they've got a huge screen to enjoy my artwork on\" mindset, and appears to be targeted on <a href=\"http://delta.ncsu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">the DELTA website</a> with the media=\"handheld\" option. The guy who wrote it is gone now, but it probably worked back then. The problem that you run into is that once you are unable to test on a platform, that platform's support can degrade. It's another thing to maintain and you may end up breaking something on one mobile platform when you fix something on another. The key would be to keep it simple, turning off the flashing lights and focus on delivering the content and navigation.","createdDate":"2009-07-16T20:47:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7862","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"Has anyone at NCSU used any of the above to produce a mobile version of their website? I've had friends use <a href=\"http://www.wirenode.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.wirenode.com/</a> but I like the idea of using a mobile CSS file.","createdDate":"2009-07-16T18:58:10.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6742","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  twitterfeed","description":"Twitter really is an awesome tool for communication. There are millions of people on there, and there is always something interesting to read or look at. Perhaps one of the best benefits of twitter is its ability to reach out to an audience you normally wouldn't be able to reach out to. Because of this, lots of blogging software packages have integrating the ability to post to twitter when you create a new blog post. But what if your blogging software doesn't support that? Well, that is why <a href=\"http://www.twitterfeed.com\">twitterfeed</a> may be the best thing ever.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/68-twitterfeed.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"120\"/></p>\n\ntwitterfeed allows you to take a simple RSS feed from any site and post it to your twitter account as a tweet. twitterfeed checks the RSS feed on a periodic basis (from once a day to once every 30 minutes) and posts anything new that shows up on the feed. So now, as long as your blog or message board or whatever supports RSS feeds, you can post updates to twitter automatically.\n\nSignup is easy. All you need to do is authenticate with your OpenID (if you don't know what OpenID is, check out <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/best-thing-ever-openid\">last week's Best Thing Ever</a>). Once authenticated, you can setup any number of feeds to go to any number of twitter accounts. All you need to do is authenticate with your desired account through twitter (don't worry, twitterfeed never keeps your twitter username and password because they use OAuth to authenticate you. You will be seeing a Best Thing Ever on Oauth soon ;). Once you have authenticated to twitter, you tell twitterfeed what RSS feed to read, how often to check it, and what info to put in the tweet. It is that easy!\n\nIn case you were wondering, twitterfeed powers our <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/ncsuwebdev\">@ncsuwebdev</a> bot that posts new events, forum postings, and blog posts.\n\nSo if you use any sites like blogger.com or livejournal.com, checkout twitterfeed to automatically share your blog posts with your twitter friends!","createdDate":"2009-05-26T13:12:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-02T16:42:02.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6857","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Something like this is especially useful for an organization or some kind of news source. I personally probably wouldn't turn my delicious feed into tweets because I pick and choose, but I may end up using this for our college's new News blog. The author of our blog hasn't ever used twitter, but with this I could easily create an account for her that automatically posts to Twitter... nice!","createdDate":"2009-06-02T16:42:02.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6606","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"University-wide iPhone Developer License","description":"Just wanted to let everyone know that we are working on securing a University-wide iPhone Developer License. Right now, the funds have been approved (at least they were) and Bill Coker, our software licensing guru, is trying to work with university legal and Apple to get the contract signed. Once this happens, we should be good to go to create and distribute apps through the App store for iPhones and iPods.\n\nI'll update this post as I know more, but we are moving in the right direction!","createdDate":"2009-05-19T20:13:38.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-09T01:20:23.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:9606","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Damian and Mike - hold on there for a moment. There's two sides to this. I've had delays on both the personal side - and for the non-profit organization associated with our grant, and I'm all for complaining about Apple and this App Store process.\n\nBut I fail to see how this is completely on Apple and for that matter, all that much \"bad form.\" Our beloved University is as culpable on this process as anything. Our software contracts process is insane. If I'm sitting in Apple's shoes - and I'm faced with the expense of rewriting my agreement and pulling in my expensive silicon valley lawyers every single time some organization's legal rep says \"hold on there buckaroo, we need you, Apple, to fly *here* we we sue you, or we get sued and drag you into it\" - I'd probably fire the customer too.\n\nWrite the blog post, but write the companion blog post about how our contracts process is holding up the ability of the University to move forward in areas like this.","createdDate":"2009-10-16T13:30:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9604","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I hate to be the one who brings the <a href=\"http://tintee.files.wordpress.com/2009/05/supersoaker50.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">super-soaker</a> to the water pistol fight... but I really think Apple's handling of this situation deserves a blog post (somewhere public). It might even get picked up by slashdot or HN actually. Sometimes a little bad PR can get a company's attention and inspire them to cooperate...","createdDate":"2009-10-16T12:52:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9602","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"This is really bad form by Apple. I was talking with Mike V. and we both agree this whole situation and apples inflexibility should be broadcasted in a more public venue.\n\nJason, as you are closes to all of this, if you were to write a blog somewhere, and we went viral getting it out via twitter and our own blogs it'd be interesting to see what sort of response we got.\n\n--\n\nFrom a solutions standpoint, has anyone looked into if other schools (Ohio State, MIT, Georgia Tech, Virginia Tech) have been able to successfully negotiate a contract.\n\nPerhaps a solution is to just create a network of developers across the state university system? I know that's way easier said than done, but still an idea","createdDate":"2009-10-16T12:43:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9581","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Hey everyone. Got some bad news on the iPhone license. Bill Coker, our University Software Licensing guru has been working on this for us for a while and it doesn't appear to be possible. I asked him to write up his findings so that I could post them accurately. Here they are:\n\n======\n\nIt was the goal of the Office of Information Technology to establish an iPhone Developers Program with Apple. After having separate discussions with Apple and our attorney, OIT has determined that it can no longer pursue this program. Apple is making the process far too difficult for a state supported higher education institution to join.\n\nApple has two requirements for an institution to enter the program. First, the individual who enrolls the university into this program must a) be an iPhone Developer who can sponsor the university and b) have legal binding authority on behalf of the university. Even if we were able to find someone who could meet these requirements, the university does not permit an individual to accept personal liability on behalf of the university.\n\nFurther, Apple has indicated that the Agreement is \u201cas-is\u201d and that even if we are able to cite North Carolina statutes that prevent us from accepting certain terms, there is still the excellent chance that Apple will refuse our requests for modifications. We were told by the manager of the iPhone Development Program that they have never seen Apple modify terms under these circumstances. The university will not and cannot be asked to sign anything that is viewed by North Carolina law as illegal, and based upon our discussions, we feel the opportunity to successfully enter into this program is minimal. We have looked to see if other public higher education institutions in North Carolina have been able to join this program, but we have discovered none.\n\nWe also asked whether other groups on campus can enter into the program on behalf of their college, division or department. We were told that this was not permitted and the agreement would have to be completed on the university level.\n\n=====\n\nSo it looks like we are out of luck with developing anything for native iPhone apps. I am actively trying to find ways around this, so if anyone has any ideas, I would be more than happy to entertain them.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T15:09:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7230","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Let me be clear that OIT is not brokering this on behalf of OIT. The license won't be NCSU OIT's license, but NCSU's license, so OIT would have just as much access to funds generated from it as anyone else, if funds were generated from it. Also, I am just speculating on what may be the \"rules\" for releasing something under the general NCSU license. We have lots to hammer out with it right now, so don't take any of it as \"gospel\" just yet.","createdDate":"2009-06-18T12:34:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7227","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My guess is that if you wanted to use the University license from the deal they would work out that it would require that all apps written using that license to be free. I don't imagine that anything is stopping you from acquiring your own license for \"for-profit\" ventures. Then again they may be nice enough to allow us a freedom to set that as an option.\n\nI imagine the stumbling block becomes: if there is one license, who gets the money? After all if you only have one \"account key\", who is the \"owner\" of the account? If it is set up in this way, then all the revenue may end up in OIT's hands instead of the department who posted the non-free app. Then again, it may be that you can have an unlimited number of accounts even though you only have the one developer license. Of course they could always have multiple developer licenses for the University, but I have no idea how they would generate them or if it would just be a pool that gets handed out.\n\nThanks Jason for keeping us updated. I see how complicated this matter can be, especially if we're a special case.","createdDate":"2009-06-18T12:25:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7127","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"I would hope they are not going to require that all apps written by NCSU are by nature free. There are lots of extension related materials that may have a cost associated with them.","createdDate":"2009-06-16T13:18:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7033","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I would guess that everything distributed under the NCSU license would be free, but that designation hasn't been made at this point. And at this point, I have no idea whatsoever about what our legal and apple legal are hung up on.\n\nIf you are interested, we'd really like to have you contribute to the mobile web group we are getting together. We are in the process to try to get more funding for these kind of projects and would welcome any expertise that you would have. I'll be posting about any upcoming meetings so you may want to check it out.","createdDate":"2009-06-09T16:57:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7021","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Just wanted to give a quick update. The campus legal department has modified the Apple Developer contract and has sent the modified version back to Apple. We are in a wait-and-see pattern to find out if Apple accepts the contract or what. I will let everyone know something as soon as I do.","createdDate":"2009-06-09T12:48:42.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6601","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","title":"Drupal - authenticated RSS feeds","description":"I've been looking for a fix for this problem for a while. Since I finally found one, I figured I'd share it...\n\nThe problem:\n\nSay you have a Drupal site, and that site has content that is not public. The Drupal engine only displays the articles that are available to you as an authenticated user. This includes the built-in RSS syndication tools. You can download and preview an RSS feed as an authenticated user, but the feed that you will get from a standard reader that is not authenticated will be missing most of the content.\n\nThe solution:\n\n<a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/tokenauth\">Token Authentication</a> - a drupal module that lets you add a unique, secret token to any drupal URL, and the Drupal engine will render the content as if the token's owner is the authenticated user.\n\nUsage:\n* As the site administrator, download, install, and enable the Token Authentication module.\n* You can configure a few settings for the module, like token length and which pages are permitted to have token access. By default, the module is configured to allow token access only on RSS/feed pages.\n* Remember to visit your permissions page and grant tokenauth access to your registered users.\n\nAs a user:\n* Login to the site, and go to your My Account page.\n* Click on the \"Token authentication\" tab.\n* The module will present you with your unique token, some basic usage instructions, and two example links: one for the front page feed, and the other for the blog posts feed.\n* If you just want the front page feed, you can easily right click the example link and \"copy link location\" and then paste the URL into your favorite RSS reader.\n\nWarnings:\n\nThis module exposes content that is meant to have limited access. Do not share your token with other users, and please do not publish a token-ized feed URL in email or on public web sites.","createdDate":"2009-05-19T19:20:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-19T19:30:42.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6603","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Awesome! Does something like this exist for phpBB3?","createdDate":"2009-05-19T19:30:41.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6595","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"Could use some help with \"hiding\" URL's","description":"This is one of those things I thought should be easy but has turned out to not to be. I've inherited an application that the end product of is a \"general public\" facing link. I keep an eye on our server logs and I've been noticing that we are occasionally getting hit on the links in question with \"them\" trying to figure out a way to get in to our servers. I'm pretty sure these are just script kiddies sniffing around, and we have the back end secured down pretty well. So it's more an annoyance then anything serious (at least so far). To make this a little worse, it's a fairly complex application which I really don't have the time or manpower to straighten out properly.\n\nThe CVM \"news\" function ends up on the public pages with a link that is formed like\n\n<a href=\"http://webapps.cvm.ncsu.edu/news/view.cfm?id=1686\">http://webapps.cvm.ncsu.edu/news/view.cfm?id=1686</a>\n\nThe \"http://webapps....\" is our Coldfusion server, view.cfm is the application in question, the part I'm trying to hide is the \"?id=1686\" ie.. the part that passes via URL the id number of the story to pull up. I've tried assorted Coldfusion approaches without any luck. I've looked into Apache approaches (rewriting the URL's? any of you have any experience with this???).\n\nI realize short of rewriting the application there won't be an ultra \"secure\" solution. Right now I'm just looking for a way to make it a little less convenient for the hacker community.\n\nAny thoughts, comments, etc.. are appreciated!","createdDate":"2009-05-19T14:39:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-21T17:55:32.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6701","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It probably just has an .htaccess like list of users it will let in.","createdDate":"2009-05-21T17:55:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6685","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Many thanks for the ideas. The mod rewrite approach seemed to work the best, and played well with the application as it is today. I like the idea of rewriting it to send it through a file handler approach also, and will probably go this approach \"long term\", but that's down the road a piece. Thanks again to all!","createdDate":"2009-05-21T11:19:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6683","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"I'm not sure why exactly that page is forcing people to wrap in... Maybe I shouldn't leave a 5 year old homegrown/dead CMS laying around.\n\nAnyways, the important piece was that after turning on Options Multiviews (see: <a href=\"http://httpd.apache.org/docs/1.3/content-negotiation.html\">http://httpd.apache.org/docs/1.3/content-negotiation.html</a>) you can turn:\n\nhttp://yourhost/entry.php?entryid=1234567&amp;section=php&amp;style=screen\ninto:\nhttp://yourhost/entry/php/1234567\n\nusing something like:\n\n$pathInfoVars = explode(\"/\",$_SERVER['PATH_INFO']);\n//index 0 should be blank\nif(isset($pathInfoVars[1])) {\n//do stuff\n}\n\nYou can do basically the same thing as the mod_rewite piece above, but some people have mod_rewrite disabled.\n\nAgain, I'm not the programmer. Jason Y. wrote it up. I can send it to you if you want, though I don't know why the very deprecated site is not liking people.","createdDate":"2009-05-21T05:08:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6632","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Not sure what kind of access you have to the webapp, but you need to hide the id#, you could do two different things:\n* Rewrite non-existing files to a file handler which attempts to lookup the pages in a database.\n* Have the CVM spit out flat files that include the view.cfm file with the correct id.\n\nMike's idea of adding words to the link from the article title is what I'm talking about here, just without the id # specified.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T14:00:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6627","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"It's probably not a bad idea from an SEO standpoint and a web log standpoint to also append the first five or six words of the article title to the link, that way you can have some idea of what that link maps to without having to open it...\n\n<u>Example:</u>\n<b>http://webapps.cvm.ncsu.edu/news/article/1686/my-article-headline-here/</b>\n\nYou can write your RewriteRule or cfm script to ignore the hyphenated words. I just prefer to actually see the article title (or part of it) appear in our analytics data.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T13:01:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6624","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"You may want to give me a more public link.. it didn't like me (Forbidden etc...)","createdDate":"2009-05-20T11:02:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6621","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"You can do the same thing with Options Multiviews. <a href=\"http://sysadm.eos.ncsu.edu/site/pages/-7e440e1b09d11b2f4f5be23440fe70af\">Something Jason Y. wrote a while back and we haven't killed off yet.</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-20T06:08:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6597","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Apache rewrites would be the way to go. You could rewrite the url so it went to something like <a href=\"http://webapps.cvm.ncsu.edu/news/article/1686/\">http://webapps.cvm.ncsu.edu/news/article/1686/</a> and then use mod_rewrite to direct it to news/view.cfm?id=1686\n\nThat is a fairly straight forward rewrite and would obscure your URL a little bit, but people will always be able to go to view.cfm?id=1686 so just make sure you filter input and escape output and you should be fine.\n\nThe rewrite rule may look something like\n\nRewriteEngine on\nRewriteRule ^news/article/(.*) news/view.cfm?id=$1 [NC]\n\nNot sure if that would 100% work as I kinda did it off the top of my head, but you get the idea.","createdDate":"2009-05-19T14:46:21.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6582","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  OpenID","description":"I have a boatload of online accounts. It seems that every site I visit these days, I need to make a new account and provide my name and email and a password. It's becoming a pain to keep up with where I have accounts, and what those accounts are, and then what the passwords to those accounts are. That's why OpenID may quite possibly be the best thing ever.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/69-openid.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"253\" height=\"71\"/></p>\n\nOpenID \"eliminates the need for multiple usernames across different websites, simplifying your online experience.\" Basically, it is a single-signon tool that anyone can implement. You have one OpenID and one password, and you can use that username/password for a multitude of sites that support signon with OpenID.\n\nSo how exactly does that work? The first thing you have to do is create an OpenID with a provider. Some services, such as wordpress.com, blogger.com and flickr.com, provide you with an OpenID already. All you have to do is know where to look and how to access it. If you want to have a more generic OpenID that is not affiliated with one of those services, you can register with a host of other providers. My personal OpenID is registered with <a href=\"www.MyOpenId.com\">MyOpenId.com</a> and it has worked out really well.\n\nOnce you have registered your OpenID, you are ready to go. When you visit a site that supports authentication with OpenID, you will enter in your OpenID (which usually looks like a URL). You will get redirected to your provider's website where you will enter in your OpenID password. Once you authenticate, you will get sent back to the application and you are now authenticated! No need to create a new account, with a new username and password. Everything is handled by OpenID.\n\nFor us developers, this is a really intriguing option. No more messing with account provisioning! No more storage and retrieval of passwords! And implementation is pretty easy. Most PHP frameworks have built-in support for OpenID (I know CakePHP and Zend Framework do), so integration into existing applications is a snap.\n\nIf you would like to learn more about OpenID, check out <a href=\"http://www.openid.net\">http://www.openid.net</a>.","createdDate":"2009-05-19T12:48:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-19T12:48:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6405","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"The NC State Branding Bar","description":"University Communication (Public Affairs) at NC State has been tasked with developing a brand book for the university in an effort to improve consistency in communications and marketing. As part of this process, Web Communication has been tasked with finalizing and delivering the NC State Branding Bar (what is commonly called the \u201cstrip\u201d) that will be included as part of the resulting university web requirements and guidelines.\n\nTo help us finalize the first iteration of the \u201cstrip\u201d we\u2019re offering a few versions to the university web developers first for testing and feedback. Currently, we have a very slimmed-down version of the strip, consisting of the NC State brick and a search box, as well as a version of the strip that includes a handful of university-wide \u201cutility\u201d links. We\u2019re interested in your feedback regarding which version you feel is most appropriate for this university-wide strip. Bear in mind that, in the interest of consistency, any links included in the strip would not be optional, edited or expandable outside of approved university-wide changes. (For instance, a department or unit could not add its own collection of links, remove unwanted links, change the wording of links, or change the destination of the links).\n\nAlso, what we\u2019re hoping to deliver in the near future is simply the first iteration of the strip. The hope is that eventually, we will be able to identify a manageable solution that allows the strip itself to be maintained centrally, so any changes, modifications or adjustments could be pushed out across the board.\n\nThat said, take it for a spin and let us know what you think. Let us know if there are technologies needed we don\u2019t have represented or if you have suggestions for improving the code, etc. Send your feedback to <a href=\"mailto:web_feedback@ncsu.edu\">web_feedback@ncsu.edu</a>. We\u2019re hoping to move quickly, so if you can get us your thoughts in the next few weeks, that would be most helpful. We\u2019ll try our best to monitor any feedback we receive here on Ning as well but your best bet is the email above (<a href=\"mailto:web_feedback@ncsu.edu\">web_feedback@ncsu.edu</a>)\n\nI\u2019ve included a draft (below) of the language that might accompany the strip in the upcoming Brand Book, as well as links to the currently-available versions.\n\n\n<b>Branding Bar</b>\n\nThe NC State Branding Bar is a small but effective element. A simple\u2014and consistent\u2014way to let users know where they are in the World Wide Web, regardless of how or where they enter the site.\n\nAs approved by its Executive Officers, NC State University requires the Branding Bar to be placed at the top of all official NC State University websites and pages.\nThe bar attempts to provide some consistency across the thousands of NC State web pages under decentralized control. The branding bar is available in various color combinations consistent with the University color palette and is available for download via the university brand website.\n\nImplementation:\n\u2022 The university branding bar must appear at the top of each official university web page. No content of any kind may appear above this bar.\n\n\u2022 The bar may NOT be edited or altered in any way outside of the options presented when downloading (color options, local search, etc.)\n\n\u2022 The bar may be centered or left aligned\n\n\n<b>Versions:\n</b>\n<b><i>Branding Bar with Links:</i></b>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/html/\">HTML</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/iframe/config/\">iFrame Configuration Tool</a></li>\n<li style=\"list-style: none\">* Add the iframe code right after the body tag or inside your wrapper div</li>\n</ul>\n<b><i>Branding Bar, Search Only:</i></b>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/iframe-v2/html/\">HTML</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/iframe-v2/config/\">iFrame Configuration Tool</a></li>\n<li style=\"list-style: none\">* Add the iframe code right after the body tag or inside your wrapper div</li>\n</ul>\n\nPlease send your feedback to <a href=\"mailto:web_feedback@ncsu.edu\">web_feedback@ncsu.edu</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-13T14:59:36.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-23T15:02:25.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10126","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Came across this resource today that lists <a href=\"http://webfonts.info/wiki/index.php?title=Fonts_available_for_%40font-face_embedding\" target=\"_blank\">fonts available for use with @font-face</a>\n\nPerhaps as the university pursues a more structured communications strategy(see State COMM on our <a href=\"http://www.hiceschool.com\" target=\"_blank\">CCO's blog</a>), we can introduce the font discussion again. Seems like the right time to do it.","createdDate":"2009-11-23T15:02:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9573","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Awesome, thanks Luis. The only remaining concern is a complicated one. The \"link\" tag is only valid within the \"head\" tag, whereas the \"iframe\" tag is only valid within the \"body\" tag. As such, it is not simply the copy-paste that it seems. I'm not sure what the best UI choice would be, but it might be worthwhile to explain this in the instructions. The people who already know what's going on probably don't read them currently, so we're trying to target the individuals who have a web role, but may not know about the allowed tag structure defined by the relevant DTD.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T13:05:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9564","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I was on the original committee that designed the brick, which was supposed to be a web button, not the end-all be-all of university graphic identity. It was designed to be minimalist and understated, not writ large as a building sign or on print pubs (it's too small).\n\nThe choice of a proprietary font was unfortunate, but the logo was already vetted and approved, so no one saw fit to reverse-font it. The result has been many poor imitation bricks that have taken people's time and resources to recreate, usually badly. I apologize for my part in not seeing that coming. Personally, I am tired of the brick and look forward to the day when we have a few more than one graphic identifier to choose from as appropriate for the deliverable, whether building sign or branding bar.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:34:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9548","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"thanks for suggesting htmlspecialchars - I should have thought about that when we discussed generating valid code. let me know if you have any problems with the form: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-14T18:16:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9463","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"7. \u201cPersonal or Internal Business Use\u201d shall mean Use of the Font Software for your customary personal or internal business purposes and shall not mean any distribution whatsoever of the Font Software or any component or Derivative Work thereof. \u201cPersonal or Internal Business Use\u201d shall not include any Use of the Font Software by persons that are not members of your immediate household, your authorized employees, or your authorized agents.\n\n\nEssentially: because you are providing the font for download, you are being disqualified on both the \"distribution\" and \"use by persons outside your organization\" exclusions.","createdDate":"2009-10-08T12:33:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9446","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Except that the rub with @font-face is that it potentially provides a direct path to the entire font file, which would constitute \"distribution\" of it. Potentially bad (very bad). EOT works similarly but honors flags, etc. so that the font can't be \"downloaded\" so to speak.","createdDate":"2009-10-06T19:39:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9445","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"So according to <a href=\"http://www.fonts.com/Legal/MI-EULA.htm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.fonts.com/Legal/MI-EULA.htm</a> we can't use the licensed font we bought for commercial use. But it looks like anything else is fair game, including @font-face.\n\n\"you may electronically distribute Font Software embedded in a \u201cPersonal or Internal Business Use\u201d document (that is, a document other than a \u201cCommercial Product\u201d as defined herein) only when the Font Software embedded in such document (i) is in a static graphic image (for example, a \u201cgif\u201d) or an embedded electronic document, and (ii) is distributed in a secure format that permits only the viewing and printing (and not the editing, altering, enhancing, or modifying) of such static graphic image or embedded document.\"\n\nPS. I hate legalese.","createdDate":"2009-10-06T17:42:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9440","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Here's the best info I can find on @font-face with Univers (and other Linotype fonts). Still very cloudy, but it might be that purchasing the extended license/new EULA will allow embedded fonts in EOT (doesn't help no IE people really, but....)\n\n<a href=\"http://www.linotype.com/5926/eotfonts.html\">http://www.linotype.com/5926/eotfonts.html</a>\n\nAnother resource that declares @font-face illegal with purchased fonts: <a href=\"http://blog.themeforest.net/general/font-licensing-for-the-web/\">http://blog.themeforest.net/general/font-licensing-for-the-web/</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-06T15:00:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9429","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"<a href=\"http://www.myfonts.com/WhatTheFont/\" target=\"_blank\">What The Font</a> finds a couple similar options (looking to match the Univers Light Condensed), but both are also licensed:\n- Europa Grotesk No. 2 SB Light Condensed\n- Folio Light Condensed\nnot much help there.","createdDate":"2009-10-05T20:21:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9428","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Fonts are like software in that you need to buy some of them to be able to use them legally. If you do purchase the license, you can use them to create whatever you want. Hell, you can even use it in for-profit collateral and not have to pay additional royalties. The question is more about the terms of the license and whether using it in the @font-face context challenges the terms/intent of the license. Still a little unclear on that particular legal consideration, but looking in to it.\n\nI'm thinking about it in the sense that buying a copy of windows doesn't necessarily entitle you to install it on every computer you own, but with Adobe products, you are entitled to install a software product on a desktop and a laptop within the terms of the license. Just need to figure out the limits of the font license. But, \"we\" are legally allowed to use the font as long as \"we\" paid for it.\n\nFor font use on the web in the context of the brand book, check out: <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/web/web-guideline/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/web/web-guideline/</a>","createdDate":"2009-10-05T19:47:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9424","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"Oh Jesus...this is the funniest thing I've seen in months.\n\nSo I gather that we are now being forced/encouraged to use Univers font on all the web sites, but we don't have the legal use of the font?\n\nGood god...","createdDate":"2009-10-05T18:20:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9423","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"At the least it would be great if we could negotiate as a campus for a campus-wide license for the Univers fonts. We at CNR just bought 15 and I think it cost around 400 bucks. So does this mean I can use Univers where ever I want on any webpage? I would think so, including @font-face.\n\nTim if you could post back on what you hear about whether or not the @font-face use of Univers is legal that would be great. By the way, I gave it a whirl a little bit ago\n<a href=\"http://www4.ncsu.edu/~cdmorris/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www4.ncsu.edu/~cdmorris/</a>\n\nLogically you'd think that if we had it on every single web-page already (in logos/banners), on physical signs, brochures, etc then effectively we should own a license to this font. To the point: if I can't go anywhere on campus without looking at Univers, why can't I make it my font default for headings on any NCSU webpage.","createdDate":"2009-10-05T17:47:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9422","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Since at least July, 1997, in fact...\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><img src=\"http://greenman.webhop.org/images/970717.png\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-10-05T17:34:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9421","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Here's hoping we can find a free web font which has similar characteristics. There appears to be a lot of good ones available now under GPL, OFL, and Apache licenses.","createdDate":"2009-10-05T13:21:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9404","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Not sure if the licensing for Univers works with @font-face. Interesting question. I'll poke around and see what I can come up with.\n\nThere have been a handful of complaints about the cost of Univers, which I totally understand. We've provided \"alternative\" fonts that are approved for use, but I still do understand the concern. The thing is, the University has been using Univers as its official typface since at least 1998 when the first \"communications manual\" was approved. The Brick's been around forever as well. Changing those would be an enormous undertaking (building signs alone...wow) but certainly could and might happen at some point.","createdDate":"2009-10-02T14:42:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9403","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Get the code the way you want it, then htmlspecialchars().","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:53:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9402","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It's really disappointing that our official typeface isn't a free web font. It makes me wonder if the licensing on the purchased fonts is even compatible with @font-face usage. Anyone know?","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:51:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9401","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"I'd bet the code being sent to the browser is correct, but the browser interprets the &amp; code to be the ampersand and only displays that. They would need to convert the ampersand character in the code twice. Which would probably break something else (i.e. the less than/greater than signs)... Perhaps the best solution would be to put a paragraph of text with instructions to change the ampersand characters to &amp; when using in places like blogger.","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:38:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9400","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Yeah, we've had trouble with this. I'm speaking outside of my personal expertise here, so I'll try not to embarrass myself, but the ampersands are definitely the issue, and they start out correct then get changed back to ampersands somewhere in the generation process. Any workarounds/ideas/suggestions on this are welcome. The easy fix is, as Jason points out, just changing the ampersands to the correct character codes.","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:22:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9399","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Would be nice if the code generated was valid. ;)","createdDate":"2009-10-02T13:14:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9392","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"BRILLIANT!!! I should have realized that :(\n\nThat worked.\n\nThanks!","createdDate":"2009-10-01T16:09:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9391","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"change all the ampersands to the correct HTML character code: <a href=\"http://rabbit.eng.miami.edu/info/htmlchars.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://rabbit.eng.miami.edu/info/htmlchars.html</a>\n\nMaybe that will work.","createdDate":"2009-10-01T15:59:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9390","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"That's what I tried and expected it to work. :(\nOn the Blogger hosted site, when I edit the template and put the iframe code, I get the following error:\n\nYour template could not be parsed as it is not well-formed. Please make sure all XML elements are closed properly.\nXML error message: The reference to entity \"inurl\" must end with the ';' delimiter.","createdDate":"2009-10-01T15:45:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9389","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Are you talking about the hosted blogger and wordpress sites? Like from blogger.com and wordpress.com?\n\nI'm pretty sure with both of those services that you can edit the HTML, so what you would have to do is copy the code from here (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/utility-bar/iframe/config/</a>) and put it in the template you use.\n\nIf it is your own install, just go into the template you are using and paste the HTML in there.","createdDate":"2009-10-01T15:35:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9386","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"Does anyone know how to put the NC State Branding Bar in a Blogger or WordPress template so the branding bar could be used on blogs that are on those sites?\n\nThanks,\nJohn","createdDate":"2009-10-01T15:16:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7950","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Sorry about the delayed response. I've been on vacation for a good long while.\n\nFirst, let me again thank all of you for the great feedback you've provided. It's helped shape (and will continue to shape) the direction for NC State's identity standards.\n\nThe first iteration the brand book was released to the campus communicators on July 1 and is available for consumption at <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ncsu.edu/brand/</a> Check with your college/department communicators first if you have specific questions.\n\nIn the coming months, University Communications will be formalizing identity standards via the university's policy/rule/regulation process. As that process moves forward, we'll do our best to keep this group informed and most certainly keep everyone here on the hook to provide feedback and guidance.","createdDate":"2009-07-21T18:01:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7708","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Anyone have updated information about this?","createdDate":"2009-07-09T20:03:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6921","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Dede,\n\nI do wonder if the LMS where the strip may not be practical within the course content would not already have the strip applied LMS-wide. It seems likely that the branding plan is that any HTML content that is used for NCSU activities where a &lt;body&gt; tag exists will have the branding bar included. The exception would likely be for content frames in framesets (where there is another frame which includes it). As such, content within an LMS likely does not need an additional strip because the LMS wrapper itself is the owner of the topmost &lt;body&gt; tag (though WolfWare courses would likely be expected to include the strip assuming that it lacks an LMS wrapper).\n\nHowever, this is all just brainstorming and guesses. I'd be interested in seeing the finalized guidelines/regulations.","createdDate":"2009-06-04T15:10:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6901","contributorName":"i643tt9ut0ty","description":"Can you clarify what counts as \"official university web pages\"? As an instructional designer for several DE programs my development is primarily course content.\n\nIs the \"brick\" image with NC State University in the rectangular block with an outline no longer acceptable? I am thinking of content development within an LMS where the strip may not be practical, but a brick could easily be tucked in a footer or course banner.\n\nThanks\nDede","createdDate":"2009-06-04T03:44:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6882","contributorName":"2s8kx2bywa1qa","description":"Quick comment on the \"Libraries\" controversy--from a totally biased source (I'm the comms director for the group). Did a quick, random check of SE schools. Duke, Vandy, UVA, Clemson, UNC-G, ECU all have \"libraries\" on the homepage (though some don't have consistent branding bars). UNC, no--go figure!","createdDate":"2009-06-03T13:18:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6855","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Nice idea Mike! I'm betting the wheels of motion are too far along for this to be considered, but I think it is a modern and elegant solution worthy of discussion at least.","createdDate":"2009-06-02T16:38:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6806","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"If you should use Mike's suggestion, could we choose between the brick and the full name of the university? While Engineering has an international focus and would prefer the full name, an extension group might be aiming at local audiences and prefer the brick.","createdDate":"2009-05-28T20:38:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6804","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"I think spelling out the full name of the university is a good idea too. I would like to be able to have the different color options available that are approved and I still like the grey option best. But a black lettering on white would work ok too.","createdDate":"2009-05-28T20:28:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6801","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I like this idea a lot, too, and I also like the use of the FULL NAME OF THE UNIVERSITY.\n\nTim and others, please remember that we are speaking to the nation and the world and need NC written out, as you have on the current home page. That is a better branding bar than the one you are proposing now because it does not start every page of our university web site with an abbreviation that is never defined. We need to clearly identify who we are to the whole international community, not just to locals.\n\nFor example, if we change <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/\">http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/</a> to use your new branding bar, we will not have NC written out until the footer, which is not a standard element used on all pages.\n\nEveryone has pushed the brick, but no one has adequately pushed institutional identification.","createdDate":"2009-05-28T20:14:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6761","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"I have been fiddling around with this branding bar trying to see how this will compliment our department's new website design. I'm very sorry that you are going to take away the possible grey background because frankly, that one compliments the page best, it doesn't overpower the overall look of the page and yet it is still visible and easy to see. The black and even the red really over power the page and probably will over power all the pages it is used with. I didn't think that the branding bar was going to be \"the\" most important thing on the page, but they way it is now, it is potentially going to stand out like a sore thumb. I don't understand why we can't all just impliment a red, white or black brick at the top left, or right of the page which then links to the main NCSU web site where all that other stuff can be easily accessed. Putting that branding bar at the top is not going to eliminate or even make consistent some of the god awful websites that exist out there in the NCSU web, it will be a little bit like putting lipstick on pig! Yea, I'm quoting Obama...\n\nI like Mike's idea a lot, it is so much less overpowering.","createdDate":"2009-05-27T16:17:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6750","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I'm wondering from a usability (&amp; consistency) standpoint, if we could avoid a lot of this confusion over controversial links like 'Giving', 'News', 'Calendar' etc if we retained all of these links, but folded all of them into a collapsible container/overlay. Essentially we would have some sort of box (or bar) appear when the user moused over the NC State University brick. With this arrangement, the branding bar links aren't pushed out in the users face, but they are there if they need them) and they won't (or shouldn't) be as easily confused with the residential site navigation.\n\nThe closest example of what I'm envisioning is exhibited by the 'myESPN' link on upper right hand corner of <a href=\"http://espn.go.com/\">http://espn.go.com/</a>.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left; margin:20px;\"><img src=\"discussions/70-bardropdown.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"270\" height=\"28\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-05-26T15:25:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6746","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Awesome feedback everyone. Exactly why this group is so important. I\u2019ll do my best to answer some of the questions contained in the feedback. Keep in mind this is just me answering questions, and specifics can and probably will change.\n\nFirst, the questions of authority and enforcement. University Communications ( Public Affairs\u2026 the name change is official July 1) was commissioned to create the Brand Book in response to the PACE(President\u2019s Advisory committee on Efficiency and Effectiveness) on Marketing, Communications, and Public Relations activities at NC State for the purpose of making recommendations for increased effectiveness and efficiency. This study was done at the request of the UNC System President. That study produced several recommendations, many of which the Chancellor approved and asked be implemented. Among those was recommendation #10 \u201cCodify authority for visual identity in university policy.\u201d University Communications, as the central marketing, communications and public relations unit on campus, was charged with this task, which falls neatly within the work we\u2019ve been doing for the past two years with the marketing and awareness campaign (Red Means Go).\n\nAs for enforcement, we\u2019re working on a PRR (the regulation one) to answer those questions. That will, as all do, go through EO\u2019s and University Council and should provide clarity.\n\nIt\u2019s worth noting again that the concept of the Branding Strip was approved during the NCSU redesign process by the university\u2019s Executive Officers.\n\nThat said, the goal here is to provide in early June, a publicly available branding strip as the first step toward providing some consistency across university web sites. We\u2019re working toward that \u201csilver bullet\u201d solution, but the intricacies of the university\u2019s web presence make this a pretty significant undertaking. As such, we\u2019re working now with a few options to get people comfortable with the concept. At this point, I think we\u2019ll offer an iFrame, javascript and HTML download version of the strip. Possibly a PHP and/or ASP include as well, until we can work out a single centrally managed solution.\n\nOne of the reasons we\u2019re after a central solution is this question of specific links in the bar. We\u2019ve already removed news, calendar and giving from the strip, realizing that those are problematic for a significant number of sites. The remaining links, we think, do a decent job of pointing to university resources and offering visitors, both new and repeat, and easy way to get to those things. It\u2019s obvious that not every site will reap a huge benefit by having the \u201cMyPack Portal\u201d or \u201cLibraries\u201d or \u201cCampus Map\u201d or \u201cCampus Directory\u201d or \u201cSearch\u201d but it seems like the inclusion of those links won\u2019t cause massive usability issues or significant conflict inside a site the same way news and calendar would have. If we can identify a central solution or set of solutions, we\u2019ll be able to adjust the links in the strip as push them out if we find that something is particularly problematic.\n\nColors: The university\u2019s official colors are red, white and black. Those are the colors the strip will be available in. That\u2019s it. No other colors, no freedom to change the colors, etc. The gray option that was available earlier will not be part of the public release, nor will it be included in the Brand Book as an accepted version. There will be a black type on white background option that isn\u2019t represented currently.\n\nThe search feature (toggle with radio button for local global) is customizable as part of the configuration for the iframe version.\n\nWidth is customizable; we just didn\u2019t detail it in this test release. No worries there.\n\nWe\u2019ll make the strip validate before it\u2019s public.\n\nAs for placement in the code, not really concerned with that at this point. It can go where it needs to go for now, as long as it appears, visually, at the top of the page. This does work against the consistency concept in some ways, but like I mentioned already, this is the first iteration, and we\u2019ll be fine tuning things in months to come. I\u2019d be interested in more discussion about this particular topic in regards to SEO, as the association with NCSU undoubtedly adds credibility to any content contained within a page (though I do realize the drawbacks, which is why we\u2019re not pursuing anything other than visual placement for the time being). The H1 tag, also, isn\u2019t particular problematic I don\u2019t think, but something worth discussing also. Great topic for discussion.\n\nSo what\u2019s next? The first edition of the Brand Book will be available in early June, as approved, reviewed, etc. by the Brand Advisory committee. The web portion will be detailed therein, as well as contained on a as-yet-to-be-launched website that will also house some \u201cbest practice\u201d recommendations (not requirements, just recommendations.\u201d That particular part will benefit from the expertise contained in this group, and we\u2019d love to have you all sending suggestions, examples, writeups, etc. for that portion of the site. It will also link to here (NING).\n\nThe other web-specific requirements stated in the Brand Book will include things like the official university color palette, approved HTML fonts and some minor content requirements. Nothing too dramatic. The goal is to encourage designers and developers to attempt some level of consistency and bear in mind that everything needs to represent NC State in a clear, consistent, professional way.\n\nHope this helps. Feel free to email me with additional questions, either at web_feedback@ncsu.edu or directly.\n\nTim","createdDate":"2009-05-26T13:47:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6663","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Sorry I haven't responded yet everyone. I'll do my best to answer some questions in the next day or two.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T16:56:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6630","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Christine,\n\nThey have a <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/iframe/config/\">simple tool for generating the html</a>. If you give that a spin and feel it doesn't make sense or is difficult to use then that feedback is one they would be delighted to have.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T13:49:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6590","contributorName":"2be0f401lba3h","description":"I agree with this as I am one of those people, although I would like to consider myself a real web designer. I am not a computer programmer and I am running around like a chicken without a head anyway trying to keep up with the changes that I can, like resdesigning my department site using CSS in the first place. i don't know how to write a javascript, but I can plug one into my site if necessary. I don't know waht iFrame is let alone how to configure it.\n\nMake this thing as simple and easy as possible to implement without a lot of configurations or be prepared to send a little geek squad out to every department to sit and hand hold us through the process. Have the directions be written in the lowest common web language possible so that we can pop it into our existing sites or redesign around it with relative easy. And definately, make it so that if there is a major change, it can be done from one spot on campus to spread out to every web site. Sort of like the swine flu...;-)","createdDate":"2009-05-19T13:26:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6561","contributorName":"211tgo999ov7e","description":"The earlier revisions of the bar all had News/Events type links, which causes an issue for non-university level groups, since we have our own News/Events pages. Having two links labeled \"News\" that go to two separate places doesn't work for us. It's confusing to users and non-intuitive.","createdDate":"2009-05-18T13:22:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6491","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I believe it separates the robots from the rest of the data. The robots breakdown for that same time period should be accessible from the interface for comparison.","createdDate":"2009-05-15T15:08:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6489","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm not against the use of JavaScript as an option, but the noscript example should at least use the iframe instead of merely a link to the NCSU home page.\n\nI don't imagine that having multiple options is a bad thing unless it becomes too much of a hassle to maintain (though the current number of options + a JavaScript interface would most likely be reasonable).\n\nMy main concern is that JavaScript should not be the only option or even the default (read: lowest common denominator) option. It's great for fancy things, but I believe that unless we make the conscious, open decision to require JavaScript for a given site/application/use, that we should strive to have every functional element (access to information, submit forms, enter data, request information) function in the absence of JavaScript.","createdDate":"2009-05-15T15:04:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6487","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Plus all the standard attributes listed below that chart. As that page indicates, they intend for you to use CSS for all of the sizing and alignment options.","createdDate":"2009-05-15T14:00:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6485","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Interesting... only the 'src' attribute will be supported for iframes in HTML 5.\n<a href=\"http://www.w3schools.com/tags/html5_iframe.asp\">http://www.w3schools.com/tags/html5_iframe.asp</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-15T13:54:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6483","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"For January 2009:\n\n3,480 of 36,017 visitors to the COE Homepage had javascript disabled. (~9%)\n\nWe are tracking web traffic with AWstats and Google Analytics. GA is completely JS dependent, so essentially the number of visits reported by AWstats minus the number of visits reported by GA gives us a pretty good estimation of how many visits were void of javascript.\n\nNow, keep in mind that it's very likely a LARGE chunk of those 3,480 visits were paid by search bots (and we don't really care if they have JS disabled or not).\n\nThe reason I looked at January '09 was because it had the most traffic out of the Spring Semester months.","createdDate":"2009-05-15T13:51:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6481","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I would like to see some stats surrounding users who have javascript enabled/disabled on university sites, just to see what we're dealing with. If 10% of the people coming to ncsu.edu domains have JS disabled, then I'd say it is not an option. I would suspect that number to be much much lower, but I have no facts to back that up.\n\nNowhere in section 508 or NCSU's guidelines does it say not to use javascript. As long as you provide an alternative where a user using a screen reader can get an equivalent experience (IE access to the information), there is no problem.\n\nI'm not married to the idea. I just thought of it as an alternative which would work no matter the language of the page in which it was hosted. The iFrame option would certainly work as well.","createdDate":"2009-05-15T12:50:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6479","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"JavaScript may be ubiquitous for 90% of people, but that doesn't mean we don't have to abide by <a href=\"http://ncsu.edu/it/access/standards/508.php\">the law</a> and its <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/policies/campus_environ/non-discrimination/REG04.25.5.php\">intent</a>. If the ruling on accessibility is that JavaScript is free game for functional elements, I'd be delighted to know. I keep hearing that it isn't all there yet, so I'd like to be on the safe side.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T20:54:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6477","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I don't know of a way to hijack someone's browser to submit a malicious POST other than through JavaScript.\n\nThe point is not that we write bad JavaScript. The point is that JavaScript can do very malicious things and at multiple times users at large have been encouraged to disable JavaScript entirely until the threat is resolved. I know intelligent users that disable JavaScript for sites by default with addons such as NoScript. It doesn't make sense to use a client side script to pull in data if you can just inject the data directly into your page, particularly with the iframe option. Additionally, if a PHP include is available, you could use that. You could even insert the contents directly after pulling it from the branding server with your server side script. Then you could cache it to help the branding server cut down on traffic. Lots of better options.\n\nAlso, try throttling your processor a bit, and you'll see the page jumping I'm talking about. I imagine the iPhone does a lot of funny things when the DOM is built from scratch like that.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T20:40:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6475","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Although I hate iframes, I still think that's a better solution. Self contained, centralized, static.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T20:31:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6471","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"And indeed, while the test bar works, it gives a \"partially encrypted\" warning when viewed under SSL.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T14:48:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6468","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"A technical plea that I made early on in this process...\n\nDistribute this bar under SSL. The latest generation of browsers gets so whiny when it tries to mix a non-SSL element like an outside toolbar on an SSL-encrypted page. The reverse is not a problem (that is, SSL elements load just fine on an unsecured base page). So, either make sure the code is functional from both an SSL server and <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">www.ncsu.edu</a>, or only offer the SSL option to everyone.\n\nTo that end, I've added a mount for webcomm to ssl.ncsu.edu, effective after 10:40a today (Thurs 5/14). The test url will be <a href=\"https://ssl.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/html/\">https://ssl.ncsu.edu/webcomm/utility-bar/html/</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-14T14:23:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6465","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"I will write more as I continue to collect my thoughts. In the meantime, my concern will be the department that doesn't have a web developer/designer. I would want to make sure that whatever solution we come up with includes the least common denominator. The administrative assistant that has to update the website, is not going to understand iFrame Configurations, js files, or anthing that causes him/her to have to config the bar. They are probably not going care or have the time or energy to do it.\n\nMy early $1.00 - $0.98","createdDate":"2009-05-14T13:53:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6462","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Just a few things I noticed that haven't really been mentioned here yet.\n\nJust a few aimless thoughts and rambles on the latest iterations of the university branding bar...\n\n1. I'm wondering what kind of arguments you'll receive semantically against making North Carolina State University the 'h1' across all pages, and placing it at the top of the source code.\n\nTypically, we place the branding bar code at the very bottom of the source code for the page (and use CSS to bring it to the top) because it's typically the least relevant content for the user once they've arrived at our location. We also want search engines to discover 'our' content before anything else, so order in the source code is important.\n\nWe typically also consider 'North Carolina State University' a second level heading (&lt;h2&gt;).\nAn example page structure might be:\n\n&lt;h1&gt;Department of Operations Research&lt;/h1&gt;\n\n&lt;h2&gt;Admissions &lt;/h2&gt;\n&lt;h3&gt;Sub Topic A &lt;/h3&gt;\n&lt;h3&gt;Sub Topic B &lt;/h3&gt;\n\n&lt;h2&gt;North Carolina State University&lt;/h2&gt;\n\nSee: <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/soc/\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/soc/</a> for a live example.\n\n2. You'll want to consider prepending some sort of string to your class names and id's in the source code. A class name like 'logo' is sure to conflict with a user's local css.\n\n3. If you're going to serve out these branding bars and images from a central location (which is the goal of an iframe), consider how many hits/bandwith you'll be dealing with.... essentially every single webpage that exists within the university will be pinging your files (scary thought). Right now, the branding bar uses 1 JS file, 1 CSS file and 5 images... there's 7 HTTP Requests (cache ignored).\n\n4. The iframe code generated by your tool does not validate...\n<a href=\"http://validator.w3.org/check?verbose=1&amp;uri=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.itecs.ncsu.edu%2Fbrandingbar.php\">http://validator.w3.org/check?verbose=1&amp;uri=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.it...</a>\n\n5. For some of these more common links like 'Directory', it may be better to say 'Campus Directory'.\n\n6. I firmly believe that users should have the freedom to integrate 'Search' into their design in different ways. Some projects will require that 'Search' be a much more prominent feature. Other sites may not want to leverage an engine like Google, they may want to search their own backend database/CMS. Also the link for search reads 'Search NCSU', but after clicking the link you realize you also have the option to 'Search This Site'.\n\n6b. For search, the magnifying glass and the red 'x' buttons are equally weighted in the overall visual heirarchy. However, one is clearly a primary action and the other is a secondary action... should they be equal?\n\n6c. The two search buttons and the NC State University brick could be combined into one image sprite to optimize load time. The 'white lines' don't really require an additional graphic, you could just use css' border-left. The background-image used on the search input box could probably also get cut.\n\n7. How do you intend to punish sites which don't comply with using the 'strip'?","createdDate":"2009-05-14T13:29:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6460","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I agree that the Javascript solution is the right way to go. There are way too many benefits to ignore.\n\nI'm going to have to completely disagree with Jonathan too. I've never seen an onload script make the page jump around and this is the basis for core functionality in all of our applications. I've never had a problem with it.\n\nAlso, JavaScript does not form the basis for browser exploits and session stealing attacks. Poorly written Javascript might, but Javascript does not. I know our Javascript (should we choose to go this route) would be correctly implemented and be secure.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T13:23:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6455","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I don't really agree with that at all. At this point, javascript is as ubiquitous as CSS, and it is as much a part of the user experience to most websites as well. Also, I've never seen a page jump around from an onload event and we use them all the time, but I'm sure it could happen if there was network lag or whatever. I honestly don't see how people function on the web with javascript disabled, or really why you would think it improves your experience to do that.\n\nMy point is that it gets you more than you give away: one version of the truth. If you distribute HTML code with all those links hardcoded in, you are stuck with those. That means if you want to make a change to what those links are, you have to touch every single webpage that implements those. Inevitably, you are going to have things out of date all over the place with people unwilling (or unavailable) to make the needed changes to stay in compliance.\n\nI'm not saying the JS idea is the only way to go. Only that part of the consideration has to be future-proofing as much as possible. Heck, you could embed a flash object too. The point is, centralizing this stuff makes more sense than distributing the HTML, and if I were going to do that, Javascript &gt; Flash &gt; other things I can't think of.\n\nIf you went the JS route and people have JS disabled, put in a [noscript] tag that points you to ncsu.edu and you're done.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T13:08:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6447","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"We should treat JavaScript like the Premium Subscription to a service in the sense that if people don't have JavaScript, they still get all of the basic functionality, just not all the silly toys. Also, onload JavaScript object injection makes the page jump around and do funny things while the user is sitting there bewildered by the annoying dance.\n\nSure this sounds a bit \"Get off my lawn!\", but it's a real concern. JavaScript forms the basis for a series of browser exploits and session stealing attacks. A number of people won't be running your JavaScript whether they are blocking it or for accessibility purposes. In fact, I wouldn't be surprised if the Web 2.0 backlash happens soon and JavaScript starts disabled and you whitelist websites you trust.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T12:45:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6444","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I can email these too, but I wanted to share my thoughts here right quick.\n\nThe things people mentioned about what links are and are not included on the branding bar are important, but my concern is more implementation rather than substance.\n\nI'd like to look at the possibility of a totally javascript driven solution. A single, centrally managed include file that injects into the DOM all the \"pieces\" of the branding bar, into whatever target is specified. That javascript file would load the CSS as well, so as a developer, your job is simple. Include a JS file, set some configuration options, and boom...your bar is there.\n\nThis gets you a lot of benefit like:\n- Change one of the links in one place, it gets propogated throughout every site that implements the bar.\n- Developer ease-of-use. You include a single JS file, and call an initialize method when the page loads with configuration options.\n- No-one mucking with the links on the bar. You give people HTML, they are going to mess with it. Inject it into the DOM and it's a bit harder for people to mess around with stuff.\n- Emergency Notifications. If there is an emergency on campus, it would be super simple to replace the nav bar with an alert that is big, flashy, and gets your attention. Having it centrally located would allow you to do that.\n\nJust a quick idea of implementation, here's what it would look like:\n[script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://someurl.ncsu.edu/navbar.js\"][/script]\n[script]\nvar options = new Array();\noptions['color'] = 'red';\noptions['align'] = 'left';\noptions['sitename'] = 'My Site Name';\noptions['googlesearch'] = true;\noptions['target'] = 'myContainerDiv';\n\nfunction init() {\nshowNcsuNavBar(options);\n}\n\nwindow.onload = init;\n[/script]\n\nClearly define the options and the implementation, then it doesn't matter what kind of site people are running (PHP, Cold Fusion, ASP, static HTML), they can implement this and it is the same for all users.\n\nRight quick, there are some cons:\n- Centrally managed means a single point of failure. But if you put it on <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">www.ncsu.edu</a> and it goes down, there are bigger problems.\n- JS compatibility with browsers. You'd just have to make sure it all works in a variety of browsers, including (gasp) ie6\n\nAnyway, that is my $0.02 worth. I think the idea of a branding bar has lots of merit. I'd just like to see the implementation change.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T12:03:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6418","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"You\u2019d have to be on crack to not see the value in using a consistent \u201clogo\u201d on every University web page. The design developed by Web Communication is simple and unassuming. Varying the colors makes it flexible enough to use with most local color palettes (though I\u2019m curious why there\u2019s no \u201csearch box only\u201d bar in gray.)\n\nNix the strip with logo and search box entirely or change the box back to \u201cSearch NCSU\u201d text. At the college and departmental levels we\u2019re going to want to put a local search box in about the same horizontal position under the strip. I\u2019m concerned that two search boxes will be confusing and since your Google search doesn\u2019t index pages in all subdomains we have little choice but to offer a local one. I like what you did with the \u201cSearch NCSU\u201d text link on the other strip; the radio button choice of \u201cNCSU\u201d or \u201cYour Site\u201d works nicely provided we could personalize the \u201cYour Site\u201d text. Hey, we\u2019re the autobahn of innovation! Let\u2019s figure out a way to make the search box smart enough to figure out the name of the subdomain it\u2019s on.\n\nNext the strip with \u201cutility\u201d links:\n\n--Thanks for making the directory say \u201cDirectory\u201d! The link definitely deserves to be on the strip but I\u2019m concerned that the information in it is stale. A good portion of our faculty and staff do not understand that they need to change their listing here as well as in the MyPack Portal. Isn\u2019t it time we single-sourced contact info? Icing would be an API that all developers on campus can use.\n\n--Sentimentally I agree with Charlie that \u201cLibraries\u201d should stay, but trends at other big tech schools disagree. Only one of the US News top ten in engineering has libraries on their equivalent of our utility bar and that one looks like they copied their bar from ours.\n\n--I also agree with Charlie on dumping \u201cNews\u201d, \u201cCalendar\u201d and \u201cGiving\u201d. We have a long way to go before those pages serve the college and departmental levels as well as they do the university.\n\n--If any page on our main site deserves an upgrade, it\u2019s the \u201cCampus Map\u201d. With GPS, Google maps and the Ares system, we could make some really slick improvements here. Please see <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/maps/\">http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/maps/</a> as a place to start. We\u2019re NC State and there should be an app for that!\n\nI have to ditto Jason\u2019s suggestion that you create centered options based on standard widths and I\u2019d even expand that to say both centered and left-justified deserve this customization. Also would you please post the answers to Charlie\u2019s questions on the Ning site? I\u2019m sure more than just Charlie and I would like to hear them.\n\nOpinions. Mine, mine, mine!","createdDate":"2009-05-13T21:41:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6415","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Interesting, I note that this is only part of the upcoming guidelines, any idea when we can expect to go see that and give feedback on it? My feedback might be different given that context.\n\nAs for the strip, I actually think Libraries is important to have there and I think that Calendar/News is too decentralized to unify like that right now, kind of the same feeling towards Giving too, which different colleges handle differently.\n\nOne other addition, what about color? Are we relegated to these colors or can we keep the font and font treatment and add in our own background color that makes sense with the rest of our website?\n\nAlso, who tasked University Communication to develop the brand book in the first place? Just curious.","createdDate":"2009-05-13T19:33:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6411","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"(i've emailed this as requested)\n\nMy thought on the branding bar would be to make it have links that would apply to visitors to any website in the ncsu.edu domain. With that said.... here's a couple of thoughts, with varying degrees of difficulty...\n\n1. Why Libraries? I'm assuming political....but to me, a more appropriate replacement would be either Academic Programs or some general link to academics at ncsu. Also, i think it would be more appropriate to have News and/or Calendar/Events.\n\n2. I think you should have several centered options, based on standard widths. Right now, it looks like the centered version is based on a 600px wide layout, which would make it look just fine. I don't think it looks as good when you use it in a 750, 950 or 974px layout. It just looks kind of crunched together. I don't have an exact solution just yet, but if you look at it on a larger display, when combined with a site template underneath it, it appears very scrunched together.\n\n3. I think that rather than provide the HTML directly to people to use (and abuse), you could provide methods for them to include a centrally managed strip. IE: provide strips for each common languages used on campus. IFrames can work for the HTML pages people create, but a simple PHP/CF/Perl/other 'include' code snippet would be useful i think. This way, if (and when) the strip has links added or removed, you can do it at a university level, rather than having to wait several months for each web developer to update their own pages and templates (like you're going to have to wait during this current re-branding exercise).\n\n4. I'm not sure of the purpose of the search box only version. I think if you are going for consistency, you would attempt 100% consistency, rather than two versions. I think when people see the strip at the top, they will expect to see the utility links on the bar. If you allow people to just use a search box only with the brick, i think that detracts from the original purpose of providing brand and site consistency.\n\nMy $0.02.","createdDate":"2009-05-13T16:54:19.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6381","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Requirements for a system to share code/projects/etc.","description":"In case you missed the other thread, I have registered code.ncsu.edu and started trying to find a way to make it benefit all of us by giving a central resource to share projects and code.\n\nWhen the webdev group first met last November, there was a lot of interest in figuring out a way to share stuff across units and departments. Subversion with WebSVN was mentioned, as well as a simple database of what is out there, who did it, etc. In researching some code hosting places, I have found some cool tools that will let us do alot, but my requirements may not match what everyone else wants, so I pose the question here: What would the requirements for a code/project sharing system be?\n\nTo get us started, here is what my initial requirements list was:\n\n- Multiple project support (with account provisioning based on the project)\n- Searchable\n- Repository access, specifically SVN\n- Able to manage code releases\n- Source for some documentation about installation, project requirements, etc.\n- Issue tracking. If you are sharing your project with other people, you need to be able to get feedback on it\n- Collaborative/Community approach\n- Open source and FREE!\n- Something that can be hosted on campus\n\nNow this approach was geared towards developers and not really towards \"end users\". In my mind, it would become part of our workflow, and a way to allow other folks to \"watch\" our projects to contribute if they'd like. End-users would be able to go to the page and search for things they care about, and download them as well, but it wouldn't be as much about PR as it would about functionality.\n\nIs this the right path? Should we have a simpler, less involved approach that caters more towards general end users? Damian Hall and I were having this discussion off-list and figured it would be good to bring it here and see what people thought.\n\nDo you even think it is a good idea to have something centralized like this? I'd hate to have people spending lots of time on this if you guys don't find it useful.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T14:27:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-19T13:42:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6593","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"That's a good point. And I suppose it would allow collaboration if someone wanted to add or recommend an addition.\n\nIf it does that as well then, with the addition of the aforementioned \"PR\" piece, then it seems this cover a pretty broad spectrum of releasables. To make up a word.","createdDate":"2009-05-19T13:42:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6587","contributorName":"342r1a4s0h1s3","description":"If you want to control deployment and code dissemination, perhaps you could restrict access to that particular Redmine project, so only people participating in the development of the application could see the issues, code repository, developer documentation, etc.","createdDate":"2009-05-19T13:06:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6450","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Possibly even a sugar coated unified diff. :)","createdDate":"2009-05-14T12:48:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6409","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I think the beauty of this type of service would be to allow people to make the choice if they want to create their own product, or use an existing one. I mean, if they come and use your product, and it's everything they need, then my guess is they'll use what you built. If they don't like it though, they can build their own. Either way, you'll get good feedback from them that you can use to improve what you built.","createdDate":"2009-05-13T15:57:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6407","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"As I think about it this is really sounding like a great idea for sharing code and that sort of thing.\n\nBut what about applications for which you are trying to increase usership(for lack of an existing word)? If you create an application or tool and you are hoping for people to be able to use your version, and not use your code to make their own version, how does that sort of project fit into the proposed system?","createdDate":"2009-05-13T15:31:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6402","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'm all for this type of thing. I think its important to remember that we have a very diverse range of skills and experience in the NCSU web developer community, and this type of thing can help make people a little more autonomous. The way I'm looking at this type of service is that it will be beneficial to use for larger projects with complex ingredients, as well as small code snippets for doing very specific things.\n\nIt seems that there are already resources posted on different sites for ncsu.edu, but there's no central repository. I'm thinking about common processes like the best way to query ldap through PHP, and things like that.\n\nIt would also seem that once we have the site populated with a lot of projects, it will be easier to see what things people are working on. That may foster more collaboration, and less re-invention of the wheel. If someone has already done parts of the project I'm working on, I'd sure like to save myself some time and use the collective experience of the community.\n\nSo yeah....this is a good idea....let's do it.","createdDate":"2009-05-13T11:49:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6394","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"This Redmine stuff I was playing with is pretty cool, and it has lots of ATOM feeds coming out of it. If you guys want to try it, go here (<a href=\"http://jfaustin2.wolf.ncsu.edu:12001/\">http://jfaustin2.wolf.ncsu.edu:12001/</a>) and request an account. I will be more than happy to setup a project for you to mess around with.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T17:06:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6391","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"I agree that something of this variety is quite useful. And if it does all that, then it may not be too hard to build a PR side, so to speak, that is a little easier for non technical users to navigate. Giving more information about what it is/does and a little less about how it was made.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T17:03:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6386","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"I think it would be useful also. I can see it being a real good testing system to help developers figure out bugs. I guess ( since I join late ) would this be kind of like a NC State SourceForge.net system?","createdDate":"2009-05-12T15:39:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6383","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I think it would be very useful and is exactly the right way to go. We've run into issues in the past where we have a project that we want people to be able to download or something and have no good way to share it. Having this kind of a system would give us a straightforward way to distribute projects to people other than a random blog posting or something with a zip file attached that might not persist. If I was a person wanting a project from NC State, I'd like to have a central place to see it.\n\nThere's a lot of cool applications people have created that I'm sure a good number of people would love to take advantage of.\n\nA system like this would also be a great place to get ideas about how to do some task you might have to tackle or even avoid reinventing the wheel when faced with the challenge of inventing some kind of campus-specific wheel. Chances are, someone else has had to do it before, so if people know about that it'll save everyone a lot of time.\n\nFurthermore, if someone finds a bug or desires a feature, you might not know who to email or you might have the same feature request or bug that eleven other people already reported. But with an issue tracking system, you can avoid duplication of issues to some extent.\n\nThere's a lot to gain from us having this kind of a system. I say let's do it!","createdDate":"2009-05-12T14:38:29.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6365","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Best Thing Ever:  BarCampRDU","description":"I'd like to let you all in on a little secret. BarCampRDU.\n\nWhat is BarCampRDU? I'll give you a quote straight from their website:\n\n<i>BarCamp is an ad-hoc gathering born from the desire for people to share and learn in an open environment. It is an intense event with discussions, demos, and interaction from participants who are the main actors of the event.</i>\n\nBarCampRDU is our local version, held yearly at RedHat's headquarters on our own Centennial Campus. It is only one day (Saturday, August 8th from 8:30 - 5:30), so you are not committing to a lot. There is also a pre-party the night before...usually at a bar (hence the name <b>BAR</b>camp). And the most important thing is, it will cost you exactly $0. That's right folks, it is free.\n\n<p style=\"float: right;\"><img src=\"discussions/71-331592803.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\"/></p>\n\nBarCampRDU isn't your typical conference. There is no set schedule. There is no call for proposals, or scheduled speakers. It is an Un-conference conference. If you aren't familiar with un-conferences, it basically means there is a big white board that has slots available, and at the beginning of the day, it is empty. Everyone (and yeah, I mean everyone) pitches ideas for talks, and they get scheduled on the board. From the BarCampRDU website, \"<i>everyone is expected to teach, to talk, to participate</i>\". What happens is an intense learning experience where everyone is involved. It is less lecture, more collaboration, which is right down my alley :)\n\nSo if you aren't busy that weekend, you should really check out BarCampRDU. It is an opportunity to get some free training, network with people and companies, and have a good time with your fellow techies. And it may be the only chance to go to a conference this year for us State Employees.\n\nTo sign up, head over to our EventBrite page at <a href=\"http://barcamprdu2009.eventbrite.com/\">http://barcamprdu2009.eventbrite.com/</a>. The original allotment of tickets sold out, but we opened up another 50, so be sure to select the ticket type \"BarCamp RDU - additional space\". Here are some other links of interest:\n\nBarCampRDU Wiki: <a href=\"http://barcamp.org/BarCampRDU\">http://barcamp.org/BarCampRDU</a>\nBarCampRDU on twitter: <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/barcamprdu\">http://www.twitter.com/barcamprdu</a>\nBarCampRDU Blog: <a href=\"http://www.barcamprdu.org\">http://www.barcamprdu.org</a>\n\nIf you post things about BarCampRDU on twitter or flickr or wherever, make sure you tag your post with #BarCampRDU so they can be found easily.\n\nIf you have any questions, feel free to ask. I am volunteering this year, so I can try to answer your questions or pass them on to other people who can.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T12:38:53.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-12T12:39:46.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6328","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Essentials@NC State content is moving to OIT Web site","description":"Important Note:\n\nOn July 1, 2009, the contents of Essentials@NC State (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/essentials\">http://www.ncsu.edu/it/essentials</a>) will be moving to the OIT Web site (<a href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu\">http://oit.ncsu.edu</a>).\n\nPlease update any links and bookmarks to the new site.\n\nIf you have any questions or encounter any problems, contact us at OIT_PUBS@remedy.ncsu.edu (mailto:OIT_PUBS@remedy.ncsu.edu).\n\nIf you cannot find the information you are looking for, try the following:\n\nSearch OIT (<a href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/search\">http://oit.ncsu.edu/search</a>)\n\nSearch NC State (<a href=\"http://search.ncsu.edu\">http://search.ncsu.edu</a>)\n\nIt is already happening. Some of the content has already been moved, and other content is in the works. We plan to have it completed by late June. Keep checking if you need to update your links or bookmarks. On July 1, all Essentials@NC State content will be redirected and no further maintenance will be conducted.\n\n*******************************************************************************************************************","createdDate":"2009-05-11T15:07:55.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-11T17:14:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6333","contributorName":"26qxx7r2w8cpk","description":"Hi Don,\n\nPreferred email address for Remedy workgroups is:\n\nworkgroup@help.ncsu.edu\n\nThe @remedy.ncsu.edu will work, just trying to be consistent on what we communicate to customers.\n\nThanks.\nLarry","createdDate":"2009-05-11T17:14:39.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6261","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Code Hosting","description":"One of the things that has continually been bounced around is that we all need a way to share code between us. I've been trying to find a good solution, but haven't really found anything good.\n\nWhat I'd like to see is something like Google Code or Sourceforge that we could install and run locally.\n\nI would say lets all just go to Google Code, but that has a few issues. #1, you only get 10 projects and we would fill that up mad fast. #2, everything has to be licensed open source, which means any project we put up there to share has to go through the office of technology transfer, which can take a LOOOOOOOOOONG time.\n\nAnyone out there know of a hosted solution that is similar to Google Code? I know that <a href=\"http://trac.edgewall.org/\">Trac</a> does most of this and supports multiple projects, but it is python based and we have had issues getting that up and running. And I'd like an all-inclusive solution so that we can do searches and such. Help?","createdDate":"2009-05-07T12:38:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-07-21T15:24:30.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:7949","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm open to anything. The redmine stuff has been working well for us, but I am willing to look at anything. Perhaps a requirements document is in order?","createdDate":"2009-07-21T15:24:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:7945","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"Now that <a href=\"https://launchpad.net/\" target=\"_blank\">Launchpad</a> has been released as open source, perhaps it is time to revisit this discussion?","createdDate":"2009-07-21T14:21:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6378","contributorName":"342r1a4s0h1s3","description":"Are you thinking exclusively of something project oriented like Google Code and SVN or something more ad hoc for sharing snippets? Maybe you could host your own <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pastebin\">pastebin</a>. There is a link to the source for pastebin.com on their <a href=\"http://pastebin.com/pastebin.php?help=1\">help site</a>. I've used it but not hosted it myself.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T13:43:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6374","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Damian,\n\nI am working on something similar, hosted at <a href=\"http://code.ncsu.edu\">http://code.ncsu.edu</a>. It is a continuance of what we were talking about in our first ever web meeting about a place to share code both within and beyond campus. Right now I have a test project management system running (Redmine, it is a Rails app) in my dev space. I am working on figuring out how to provision accounts to the thing without having to manually do it, but I think it will be a great resource.\n\nIf anyone would like an account, head over to <a href=\"http://code.ncsu.edu\">http://code.ncsu.edu</a> and click on the Projects header. That will take you into Redmine where you should be able to register. Send me an email and I can create a project for you to play with. Check it out, see what you think. This will be open to anyone and everyone on campus, not just web projects, but it is early in the process right now.\n\nFor more about redmine, checkout <a href=\"http://www.redmine.org/\">http://www.redmine.org/</a>. It has version control support, so we are planning on linking it in with our SVN repos, but it also supports Git, CVS, and a few others.","createdDate":"2009-05-12T13:25:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6369","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"On a similar note we, ITECS, are currently looking to re-purpose our webtools vhost. We are thinking of making it a sort of repository for available applications and packages/code snippets.\n\nWe aren't talking about hosting all the code, but would be willing for packages/snippets, but rather having somewhere that developers and potential users can use as a \"one-stop shop\" for available applications around the university.\n\nI think it could also potentially help some of us not have to invent a wheel that someone else already has! Speaking of which, has someone already created something like this for their own projects that could be expounded into a university wide system?","createdDate":"2009-05-12T13:18:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6361","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Subversion and Websvn do all of that, you just need someone to manage the permissions (or a cron on a web service if you feel the need to \"automate\" a process that still requires manual intervention)","createdDate":"2009-05-12T12:15:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6215","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"SimpleViewer","description":"There are a plethora of ways that you can post images to the web and an equal amount of ways that you can display photos. I don\u2019t know if I can say that <a href=\"http://www.airtightinteractive.com/simpleviewer/\">SimpleViewer</a> galleries from Airtight Interactive are \u201cthe best (photo display) thing ever\u201d, but I can say that it has been quite useful and a fan favorite of folks over here in the College of Natural Resources.\n\nThis all started, simply enough, with a request I get a lot, namely: \u201cHow do I post my cool pictures on the Web, web guy?\u201d To which I used to respond: \u201cUhhh, well, there a few different ways to do this..\u201d No longer is that my reply. I have found a solution which satisfies a few criteria as far as a recommendable method. Those criteria are as follows:\n\n1. Has to be something that non-Web people can do\n2. Has to be small in file size\n3. The less complex the better\n4. Must be low on the server-side technical requirements\n5. Must look nice\n6. Free\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/tourismextension/gallery/02/\"><img width=\"250\" style=\"float:right;\" src=\"http://content.screencast.com/users/charlie_morris/folders/Jing/media/83f84710-a252-4eee-95ec-2ceaf8ddae3d/2009-05-05_1054.png\"/></a>This is where SimpleViewer comes in. Essentially SimpleViewer is a free extensible Flash-based photo gallery template for which users can add and create as many albums as they desire. And when I say \u201cextensible,\u201d <a href=\"http://www.airtightinteractive.com/simpleviewer/instruct.html\">I mean it</a>. It has a number of options for how you want to set things up, both on the backend configuration side and on the gallery display side. For our purposes at CNR, we actually don\u2019t use any server backend for it. Instead we can rely on handy desktop software to organize the photo albums, specifically <a href=\"http://picasa.google.com/\">Picasa</a> (free, of course). As a user, you just have to download Picasa and then add a template file for SimpleViewer and then your off to the races (handy instructions <a href=\"http://www.airtightinteractive.com/simpleviewer/auto_desktop_instruct.html\">here</a>, as well as other desktop software). The rest of the workflow involves exporting from Picasa to an HTML templated version of your album (built-in process) and then sending that album to your local Webmaster (me) who in turn adds it to a Web directory and creates a link to it. Done. And in short time you could have something like <a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/ppf/gallery/\">this</a>. Or, to see an embedded gallery, something like <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/tourismextension/gallery/02/\">this</a> (pictured above). There are actually many ways you can have a gallery display in your site including changing the background.\n\nThus I\u2019ve met all my requirements. I\u2019ve got a free and easy-to-use product that can create slick looking galleries without any intensive programming involved and Picasa does all the compression for a user too, so file sizes stay down. As advertised, it\u2019s a \u201cSimple\u201d viewer.\n\nLastly, SimpleViewer is not the only gallery template available. You can also choose from <a href=\"http://www.airtightinteractive.com/viewers/\">any of these</a> and work with them in the same fashion (Picasa template).\n\nOk, one more thing. I don't view this solution as the be-all-end-all. Ideally I'd love to have a kind of repository, almost like a locally hosted <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/\">Flickr</a> (or maybe just paying into a commercial Flickr account). But, for ad-hoc photo galleries, this is what I'm turning too.","createdDate":"2009-05-05T14:59:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-11T19:17:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6339","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Yeah, like I mentioned, it may just be easier/better to buy a shared Flickr account. The slideshows that it can produce and embed are very nice. But I always get push back from people whenever something is externally hosted.\n\nAnyway, SlideShow Pro is indeed slick, thanks for sharing!","createdDate":"2009-05-11T19:17:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6336","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"I just downloaded the Photoshop CS3 script for SimpleViewer and it is indeed nice.\n\nI use Slideshow Pro to build slide shows. It is definitely not for everyone. It is a flash based image viewer. I like it because the user interface is extremely customizable (not that SimpleView isn't) and it has exporters for iPhoto and Photoshop.\n\nEssentially, you write some XML, or use one of the exporters I just mentioned to write it for you, then you build a simple flash project with your dimensions (or just use their example one), add the Slideshow Pro component, and point it at your XML file. No backend scripting, and it is just pointing to a folder of images. I can add and delete fairly easily. Oh -- and it will play back video.\n\n<a href=\"http://slideshowpro.net/examples/video_gallery_auto\">http://slideshowpro.net/examples/video_gallery_auto</a>\n\nI understand though -- this is more than most people may want. I use flickr for the dumb stuff, slideshow pro for the portfolio stuff where I want to impress someone. I have tried a couple of different gallery apps on my hosted server -- they were more than I needed -- I do not need an asset manager -- I have Aperture for that. This is simple, flexible and looks slick.","createdDate":"2009-05-11T18:00:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6241","contributorName":"2nzrrfshzfg2m","description":"I've used SimpleViewer and have been very happy with it over many of the more complicated galleries (<a href=\"http://gallery.menalto.com/\">PHP Gallery</a> is probably the best of the more complicated ones available). You may also want to look at <a href=\"http://smugmug.com\">smugmug</a> as they are in my opinion the best externally hosted photo gallery site.","createdDate":"2009-05-06T12:55:37.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6163","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"New @ncsuwebdev twitter account","description":"Hey folks,\n\nI know there are lots of us on twitter, so I setup a ncsuwebdev account. I have the account setup to automatically post new threads and new blog posts, so it is an alternative to getting the Ning emails.\n\nIf you want, follow @ncsuwebdev :) Also, if you post something about ncsuwebdev, lets use the hash tag \"#ncsuwebdev\".\n\n<a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/ncsuwebdev/\">http://www.twitter.com/ncsuwebdev/</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-04T13:02:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-04T13:02:56.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6161","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Why aren't there RSS feeds on ncsu.edu and news.ncsu.edu?","description":"I noticed the other week that both ncsu.edu and news.ncsu.edu don't have RSS feeds. Why not? Even if the one on ncsu.edu linked to the news.ncsu.edu feed, that'd be fine, but I think we should have feeds people can subscribe to.","createdDate":"2009-05-04T12:32:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-14T12:51:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6453","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Awesome! Thanks Tim! I look forward to a simpler, consistent future for NCSU News. :)","createdDate":"2009-05-14T12:51:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6421","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Just catching up on Ning. I could attempt to \"explain\" why RSS has been an issue, but I'll just say that, at least for the news site, it'll probably be fixed in the near future (think a couple weeks). Ah well, here's a brief explanation. The news site currently runs through a CMS that uses a static publishing model (and has some issues with automated workflows....long story), so the feeds that are generated have to be manually published whenever new content is created and added. To web people, it's a simple step, but one often overlooked by those only concerned with posting the story itself. While those web pros among us might gasp at the thought of this, it's just one of the things that happens. But it'll be fixed soon as the news site is moved away from the static publishing model and into a more dynamic environment. Again, soon.\n\nAs for the feature content on the homepage, different but related issue. That stuff will be syndicated soon as well.","createdDate":"2009-05-14T00:41:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6190","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Goto <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">ncsu.edu</a>\nClick 'More News'\nClick 'News Archive',\nClick '2007',\nChange url to include '2009'\nScroll to the bottom of the page, click 'RSS'\n\nAnd you finally get here: <a href=\"http://news.ncsu.edu/news-indexes/2009/main-categories/news-index.rss\">http://news.ncsu.edu/news-indexes/2009/main-categories/news-index.rss</a>\n\nI wish I could explain how I discovered this, but I'm not really sure. It was an accident.","createdDate":"2009-05-04T18:26:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6170","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The news.ncsu.edu one is a little frustrating because it breaks (discontinuity occurs) whenever we cross from December into January. Any student that subscribes in their traditional first semester would not be getting updates until they figure out the issue or give up on it. It would sure solve the issue I mentioned if we could use a combined feed, like the one hinted at on <a href=\"http://news.ncsu.edu/news-indexes/\">http://news.ncsu.edu/news-indexes/</a> However, it appears to be displaying a blank rss feed. <a href=\"http://news.ncsu.edu/brights/pyro-man.php\">oops</a>, I guess I should stop clicking links.\n\nI'm hoping that while they are in there adding the simple link tag that follows that the 5 validation errors can be resolved as well (selected=\"selected\", extraneous span in block1 (double), superfluous 'text' tag in newsbody, and type=\"text/javascript\"):\n&lt;link rel=\"alternate\" href=\"http://news.ncsu.edu/news-indexes/&lt;?php echo date('Y'); ?&gt;/main-categories/news-index.rss\" type=\"application/rss+xml\" title=\"NCSU News\" /&gt;\n\nIt looks like someone has been playing with the <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/site-map/index.php\">site map</a> (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/featured-stories/embracing-diversity/jan-2008/index.php\">date mismatch</a>, <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/featured-stories/outside-the-classroom/test/Test.php\">test content,</a> <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/featured-stories/provost-statement.php\">placeholder content</a>).","createdDate":"2009-05-04T14:04:03.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6136","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"NCSU OIT's Use of Twitter for IT Communication","description":"I recently attended a teleconference, during which two schools (University of Oklahoma and University of Texas-San Antonio) shared what they've been doing with both Twitter and Facebook in terms of IT Communication.\n\nThat has prompted me to share what we're doing here in the Office of Information Technology (OIT) at NC State University with Twitter. We started using Twitter in the second half of September 2008. We're not using Facebook at this point, at least not from an overall OIT perspective. We had a \"Student Email Initiative\" going on for a while, and we did use a Facebook group in that effort.\n\nOur Twitter address is: <a href=\"http://twitter.com/ncsu_oit\">@ncsu_oit</a>.\n\n<a href=\"mailto:john_martin@ncsu.edu\">John Martin</a> (that's me) devises the content for this twitter account, and we have three communicative purposes for our @ncsu_oit tweets:\n<ol>\n<li>Advertising (workshops,seminars, services, events). Examples of a few of these tweets:<ul>\n<li>WolfWise Demonstration for Campus (Mac/Linux), WED, 05/06, 14:00-15:30, DH Hill Auditorium. More info/sign-up: <a href=\"http://idek.net/8tr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/8tr</a></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">Introduction to Excel 2007 Part 3 (formulas, macros, drop down lists) 04/22, 1:30-4:00, 6 seats left, More info/sign-up: <a href=\"http://idek.net/7U8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/7U8</a></span></span></li>\n<li>Conference call services: Station-controlled, Operator-assisted, Meet-me. Complete information: <a href=\"http://idek.net/6wa\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/6wa</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Announcements (outages, change management, security incidences, etc.). Examples of a few of these tweets:<ul>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">OIT staff continue to work with Research In Motion in trying to determine the cause of BlackBerry issues. More info: <a href=\"http://idek.net/93j\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/93j</a></span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">WolfPrint Quota Online Purchasing currently unavailable. Quota can b purchased in person@DH Hill Copy Center. More info: <a href=\"http://idek.net/8Gg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/8Gg</a></span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\"><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\"><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">Tiny URLs can be big security risk! (And you know Twitter uses them extensively.) <a href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/news-releases/tiny-urls-can-be-big-security-risks\">http://oit.ncsu.edu/news-releases/tiny-urls-can-be-big-security-risks</a><a href=\"http://idek.net/817\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>News (IT, education, social media,\u00a0IT in education, social media in IT, social media in education). Examples of a few of these tweets:<ul>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">RT: @<a href=\"http://twitter.com/SteinCom\">SteinCom</a> New blog entry: Seven tips on search engine optimization for edu sites <a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/dlt68q\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://tinyurl.com/dlt68q</a></span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">RT: @<a href=\"http://twitter.com/hfrankm3\">hfrankm3</a> NCSU's library lends all kinds of cool equipment... Including iPods &amp; Kindles. [ &amp; MUCH MORE! see <a href=\"http://idek.net/6F1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://idek.net/6F1</a> ]</span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\"><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">Retweet: @<a href=\"http://twitter.com/nyt_tech\">nyt_tech</a> Gadgetwise: Wireless Electricity, Not So Far Off <a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/cm6r34\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://tinyurl.com/cm6r34</a></span></span></span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\"><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\"><span class=\"status-body\"><span class=\"entry-content\">RT: @<a href=\"http://twitter.com/highereduSTATS\">higheredu</a> STATS: U.S.A. Social Networking Rankings: <a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/9bply5\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://tinyurl.com/9bply5</a> (Twitter in 17th [Hitwise] &amp; 9th [Nielson] place resptvly)</span></span></span></span></span></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\nAs of this writing, we have 157 followers and we're following 124 accounts. We've made a total of 467 tweets since September. This is what the growth of the number of accounts following us looks like, starting from February at which time we began tracking:\n<br/>\n<center><img alt=\"Graph showing Twitter followers count going from around 70 in February 2009 to about 155 on May 1, 2009\" src=\"http://www.nematome.info/TwitterGrowth.JPG\" border=\"0\"/></center>\n\nIn April, we made a survey available to our followers, asking these seven questions:\n\n<ol>\n<li>I have been subscribed to @ncsu_oit: Less than a month, Between 1 and 3 months, Between 4 and 6 months, Other.</li>\n<li>@ncsu_oit tweets the kind of information I expect to see from an information technology support organization: Yes, consistently; Yes, for the most part; No, sometimes it does not; No, consistently it does not; Other.</li>\n<li>The frequency of tweets from @ncsu_oit is: About right, Too often, Too seldom, Other.</li>\n<li>I found out about, or began following, @ncsu_oit after: Noticing a retweet from it, Attending UNC CAUSE '08, Seeing it in search results, Seeing an OIT news or information item, After an OIT class I took about it, Don't remember, Other.</li>\n<li>I would attend a \"Tweet-up\" if @ncsu_oit had one: Definitely would; Might, depends on time/date/location; Probably wouldn't; Defintiely would not; Other.</li>\n<li>@ncsu_oit tweets in three main categories: OIT classes/workshops/events, OIT service/support announcement, and IT/Education/Technology industry items of interest. Do those \"work\" for you? Any other areas you'd like to see us tweet about?</li>\n<li>Use this space to convey any other information you'd like to about the @ncsu_oit Twitter service.</li>\n</ol>\nHere are <a href=\"http://ceres.cals.ncsu.edu/surveybuilder/ViewTestResults.cfm?testid=7862\">the results of the survey</a>, to which 9 people responded. Light response rate, but helpful, enlightening comments.\n\nOne other thing that we've done with regards to Twitter is that I presented a Lunch &amp; Learn called, \"Twitter: Basic Use &amp; Professional Use,\" which filled up 25 seats in a matter of a couple of days. An interesting aside is that the first time I scheduled the class, I called it, \"The Glitter of Twitter,\" and we had to cancel the class because we had less than five people sign up for it.\n\nAmong the things I shared in terms of how we're using Twitter in business and how it can be used in business in general (in addition to the specific ways we're using to communicate with it) were:\n\n<ol>\n<li>Colleagues tweeting what we're doing during the day, using the hashtag #ncsu_oit. This gives us an awareness of what each other is working on, has spawned serendipitous helping/learning, \"Hey, I've done that before, if you get stuck or need some help on it, give me a yell,\" or \"Hey, I want to learn how to do that, can I come and observe you working?\" Also, just joining this organization in September, Twitter was invaluable in acculturating me to academia (I came from IBM), quickly made me feel like a valued member of the team, <i>and</i> I made some fast friends.</li>\n<li>To keep up with your industry\u2014who's doing what, where, why. Say you're interested in these areas of IT: Computer Operations, or Security and Compliance, or Enterprise Resource Planning, you can use something like \"TweetGrid\" (which searches the public timeline of tweets for tweets that match your search argument) to see what the global conversation is about them: <a href=\"http://tweetgrid.com/grid?l=2&amp;q1=computer+AND+operations&amp;q2=security+AND+compliance&amp;q3=ERP+OR+(enterprise+AND+resource+AND+planning)\">http://tweetgrid.com/grid?l=2&amp;q1=computer+AND+operations&amp;q2=security+AND+compliance&amp;q3=ERP+OR+(enterprise+AND+resource+AND+planning)</a></li>\n<li>To get customer feedback and \"the buzz\" about products you might support or sell. For instance, a Microsoft salesman who sells Office, might use this TweetGrid search argument to see what's being said: <a href=\"http://tweetgrid.com/grid?l=4&amp;q1=word+AND+microsoft&amp;q2=powerpoint+AND+microsoft&amp;q3=excel+AND+microsoft&amp;q4=outlook+AND+microsoft\">http://tweetgrid.com/grid?l=4&amp;q1=word+AND+microsoft&amp;q2=powerpoint+AND+microsoft&amp;q3=excel+AND+microsoft&amp;q4=outlook+AND+microsoft</a></li>\n</ol>\n\nSome of the challenges we've had and some things we still want to do include:\n\n<ol>\n<li>Determining whom to follow or follow back.<ul>\n<li>Some decisions are easy: students, faculty, staff from our own university are a no-brainer. What's hard about it is knowing that they are at times. Unless it's specifically stated in their profile, it's too time consuming to try and find out.</li>\n<li>Other Twitter accounts of organization at NCSU are usually good candidates; for example, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/NCStateNews\">@NCStateNews</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/NCStatePR\">@NCStatePR</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/NCSUEngLibrary\">@NCSUEngLibrary</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/ncsuweb\">@ncsuweb</a>, and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/ncsu_oit_ot\">@ncsu_oit_ot</a>.</li>\n<li>We try to follow accounts from which we might glean some content to retweet, so accounts such as <a href=\"http://twitter.com/higheredu\">@higheredu</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/techboard\">@techboard</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/nyt_tech\">@nyt_tech</a>, and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/chronicle\">@chronicle</a>.</li>\n<li>When someone follows @ncsu_oit, we usually take a gander at their profile, how often they generally tweet, and do a quick scan of the kind of content they tweet before following back. I know there is a philosophy out there that you should follow back every single person who follows you. As of now, I've not yet bought into that philosophy.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>We'd like to do analysis of who is following us to \"know our audience,\" as that's one of the three key elements of any type of communication (along with the purpose and context of the communication).</li>\n<li>We'd like to investigate the possibility of enhancing our class/workshop application to automatically tweet if there are still some open seats, say, two days before a class or workshop.</li>\n</ol>\n\nOkay, that's enough for now. That got long, but I guess we've been on a steady exploration of this new communicative device for over six months now, and we've learned a lot. I welcome questions, suggestions, or observations by anyone. Again, my email address is <a href=\"mailto:john_martin@ncsu.edu\">john_martin@ncsu.edu</a>.","createdDate":"2009-05-01T23:46:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-18T14:26:13.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1241","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6167","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"John, this is an awesome amount of information- I'm impressed!\n\nI for one try to post something about what I'm doing to #ncsu_oit at least once a week. I agree that there is no need to follow everyone following you- some of those followers are becoming the spam of Twitter, imho. I love the idea of posting class openings to Twitter, although at some point it may be worthwhile to split out ncsu_oit purposes so we can make sure the appropriate audiences are following the appropriate account. Also, thanks to Jason we now have @ncsuwebdev, so you might want to following up on those posts as well (if you aren't already).\n\nI hear all the time that Twitter is a vain and worthless pursuit so I really like to see it justified with some numbers and an explanation for how it really can benefit the workplace. Thanks, again!","createdDate":"2009-05-04T13:44:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6123","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Accepting payments onthe web","description":"Hi,\n\nI am looking for a payment processing app available here at NC State. We will be registering participants in a national conference hosted here next fall. We will be delighted to accept their payments online, once we figure out how. We have an inquiry in at McKimmon, but I believe they charge quite a bit for the service.\n\nAnyone have experience doing this?\n\nThanks!\nElizabeth","createdDate":"2009-05-01T15:54:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-08T18:56:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6288","contributorName":"3herub2xatqwz","description":"We accept online payments for a variety of things. We used Yahoo Storefront for a couple of conference registrations and it worked fine; it just wasn't flexible enough for the other things we needed to use it for. We switched to NelNet and have been very pleased. Cindy Hutchins and others at EADS have been great to work with.\n\nFeel free to contact me if you need additional information. 5-8657","createdDate":"2009-05-08T18:56:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6211","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Also, please keep me in the loop as to when the PHP classes you are creating might be ready to share. Our event will be held in November, so we will be setting up over the next few months. Thanks again for your help.","createdDate":"2009-05-05T14:19:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6208","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks very much. As far as security, does SSL take care of that? We do have our registration forms on an SSL server.","createdDate":"2009-05-05T13:55:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6193","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"The University's page on credit card processing starts here:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.fis.ncsu.edu/controller/cash_receipts/credit_card.asp\">http://www.fis.ncsu.edu/controller/cash_receipts/credit_card.asp</a>\n\nYour online options are a Yahoo Storefront or the NelNet gateway. I'm guessing you already have some software to do the registration bits (if you don't let's talk about the conference CMS we're setting up) so toss Yahoo and you'll end up where we did--with NelNet. We've coded and tested a pair of PHP classes for the NelNet system that facilitate the information passes between your site and the gateway. Right now we're packaging the classes, the XML config file and the instructions so we can distribute it.\n\nOnce you have your merchant account established, you can either code your own \"pre-payment\" and \"thank you\" pages or you can farm it out to the group that Cindy Hutchins manages in Applications Development and Emerging Technologies. Even if you do your own pages, Cindy (or someone from her group) will be the folks that help you \"complete the set up process\" as described in Step 5 of the \"How to:\" in the URL above.\n\nHrm, that's about it without getting into the technical details. Check out the price tags on NelNet (at the above URL). Cindy Hutchins can probably give you the pricing details on the set-up. She's at 3-7748.","createdDate":"2009-05-04T19:12:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6173","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"NelNet has been mentioned in the past in multiple threads. <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/phpdevelopers/forum/topics/credit-cards-nelnet-object\">Margaret</a> may be able to provide feedback regarding her experience with it over the past two months.","createdDate":"2009-05-04T14:10:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6105","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Mobile Web Computing and NCSU","description":"Last week, a few of us went over to Duke to check out what they were doing with their mobile suite of applications, including their new iPhone app. Along with us and, of course, Duke, UNC also had a presence there, as well as a few industry types. The guy who managed the mobile project for Duke (an NCSU grad...represent!) did a great talk on their mobile suite, which also includes WAP access to the same data that is on their iPhone app.\n\nAnyway, it got us thinking that we, NCSU, need to get our collective rear-ends in gear and start not only thinking about, but doing something about NCSU's mobile (or lack thereof) situation. There is no reason why we should be getting passed by in this arena, and I think with a little combined effort, we can make something happen quickly.\n\nI know that everyone is crazy busy right now, myself included. I don't know if it is a realistic goal to \"combine forces\" and get a project done, but I think this group probably has some of the best potential on campus.\n\nSome initial things to think about:\n- How do we get buy-in from the higher ups for dedicating already tight resources to this?\n- How much money/time/etc. would it take to pull something off?\n- Is outsourcing an option?\n- Where do we get the data for the mobile apps from?\n- How is it supported after its out there?\n\nI propose getting together in the next few weeks and just talking some logistics. I'll be glad to schedule the meeting, but I would like to know how many people are interested in possibly helping out.","createdDate":"2009-04-30T15:01:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-04T14:16:12.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6180","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I have scheduled the ETSS conference room (basement of the hillsborough building) for Tuesday, May 12th from 2 - 4pm to have a get together. I know not everyone will be able to make it, but I would like to get a count of who is coming.\n\nPlease RSVP here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/mobile-web-group-meeting\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/mobile-web-group-meeting</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-04T14:16:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6131","contributorName":"2nzrrfshzfg2m","description":"I'm in! Thanks Jason! :)","createdDate":"2009-05-01T19:07:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6128","contributorName":"1m6icsp2xqxcd","description":"I'm also writing from the libraries, and I would love to help out with putting together some collaborative opportunities for mobile development. I think even a casual semi-regular meeting to discuss development hurdles would be really helpful.","createdDate":"2009-05-01T16:58:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6125","contributorName":"2jt4yzjxvxgs7","description":"At least a couple of us in the Libraries would be interested in contributing ideas and possibly developer time to a shared initiative. We have some experience in this area. Please include me in your initial planning meetings.\n\nBy the way, I know that there is an unofficial UNC Chapel Hill class that started up last week that is going to follow the archived video lectures from the Computer Science iPhone class at Stanford:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.stanford.edu/class/cs193p/cgi-bin/index.php\">http://www.stanford.edu/class/cs193p/cgi-bin/index.php</a>\n\nSo yes, we are behind.\n\nTito","createdDate":"2009-05-01T15:59:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6113","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Fully supportive. I've started preaching mobile up the ladder a bit, and there is significant interest. We can talk about that when we get together. There is a great interest in several corners of the university landscape in making existing data feeds more readily available. Mobile is just one of the places, but if we want to use this project as the first visible output of those, that's a great place to start.","createdDate":"2009-04-30T18:00:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6110","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I'm interested in helping out, and I'm sure other folks in my unit would will be willing to jump on board.","createdDate":"2009-04-30T16:54:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6107","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Would love to get a project like this going and I agree it's overdue. Schedule away and I'll be there!","createdDate":"2009-04-30T15:25:54.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6041","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"Twitter Usage?","description":"Several of our team are using Twitter for professional development. A couple of us heavy into web apps follow design type users for HTMl/CSS/JavaScript inspiration. Our SharePoint guy gets lots of great feedback from a big community of SharePoint gurus on Twitter.\n\nWe've also got a couple of \"RSS to Twitter\" type of scripts running. One is for our campus safety alerts, one is for IT outages, and we have a couple that include general events and sports information.\n\nHow about there?","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:41:12.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-28T15:53:00.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1241","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6061","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I almost forgot, we have a non-ECU community springing up here in Greenville: <a href=\"http://www.greenvilletweets.com\">http://www.greenvilletweets.com</a> which is based on the idea of a Tweetup, where people in Twitterspace meet \"for real\". The founder of Greenville Tweets got inspiration from the Triangle Tweetup group. In fact, we have a big bunch of people heading to the Triangle Tweetup on April 30.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:50:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6052","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm sorry to say that we, at a university level, are way freaking behind in anything having to do with \"social media\". We just can't seem to get going at a university level with twitter, or facebook, or even RSS in a lot of places. That is not to say that people in our colleges and departments aren't utilizing it in a great way.\n\nWe have a twitter account for our group that we post updates out to (@ncsu_oit_ot), and OIT posts some to @ncsu_oit. I know the libraries have a twitter account here or there, as well as the bookstores, but I have found them less than informative and actually stopped following them. The sports folks are doing their own thing.\n\nI posted recently on my personal blog about my value with twitter. <a href=\"http://www.jasonawesome.com/?p=65\">http://www.jasonawesome.com/?p=65</a>. I find it invaluable on so many levels, and there has been alot of discussion here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/main/search/search?q=twitter\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/main/search/search?q=twitter</a>.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:48:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6029","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"Favorite JavaScript library / framework?","description":"Our team at ECU has become big fans of jQuery, along with some of the associated plugins for this and that. We haven't started using the Yahoo library, jQuery UI, MooTools, or anything else. What do people there in Raleigh choose?","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:36:05.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-28T14:50:19.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:4062","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6046","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"We use exclusively jQuery and jQueryUI along with the YUI CSS tools. We used to use all MooTools, but moved everything to jQuery a few months ago. jQuery seems to be more organized and supported. I wrote a couple articles on jQueryUI and the YUI CSS stuff if you haven't seen 'em:\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/yui-library-css-tools\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/yui-library-css-tools</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/jquery-ui\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/jquery-ui</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:45:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6035","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"In ITECS we are mostly using jQuery and it's plugins. But we have some projects that use Prototype as well. We don't really have a standard as to which framework to use. Some of our student employees prefer to still to it by hand rather than use a framework.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:39:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:6018","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Zend Server CE","description":"<a href=\"http://zend.com\">Zend</a> is a pretty awesome company. Not only are they the corporate force behind PHP, but they make an awesome Framework for PHP development, and a pretty decent IDE as well with Zend Studio. Those two products were typically where I stopped with Zend. I knew they had some other things out there for security purposes, as well as a Server product, but those really weren't important to me, and they cost like a hojillion dollars.\n\nBecause of my other involvement in Zend products, I am on their mailing list. A few months ago, they sent an announcement that they were releasing a free version of their Server product for personal and development use. I thought, \"cool, but I don't really need that right now\". At work, we develop directly in AFS, and use a central MySQL server, so there was no need to have a development environment on my local machine.\n\nWell, lately I have been having LOTS of issues with working with AFS from off campus, so I decided that I wanted to install something locally on my Mac to do development. OS X comes with Apache and PHP ready to go, but I wanted a seamless solution. One install to rule them all. I had installed MAMP a while back, so I decided to try that. Well, it was totally busted when I went back to try to use it, and I spent a few hours trying to figure out what was wrong with no luck. I decided I needed to try something new, so I decided to give <a href=\"http://www.zend.com/community/zend-server-ce\">Zend Server CE</a> a shot. I figured, what the heck, its free. And if it stinks, I could just delete it and give MAMP another shot.\n\nI downloaded the installer from Zend's website and had it installed in seconds. Complete with a management console, PHP 5.2.9, Zend Framework 1.7.8, phpMyAdmin and Apache 2, I was ready to go.\n\nTheir management console is really nice. It will let you search through the php.ini file and change any settings you need to (no more scouring the file system for php.ini, then changing it there).\n\n<p style=\"float: right;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/72-ZSCEmgmt.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/73-ZSCEmgmt.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"181\"/></a></p>\n\nIt also provides multiple technologies for improving your applications. Code acceleration, full page caching and data caching are included to improve response times and minimize resource utilization.\n\nThe only real downside I found was the lack of documentation. I guess because it is a very \"new\" product, that was grown from an existing product, so some of the documentation is incorrect. Like the docs said that my htdocs directory was in my Applications/ folder. It's not, it is in /usr/local/zend/apache2/htdocs. And it never told me what my initial password was for MySQL (btw, it is username: zend password: (blank)). Also, there was some quirks getting MySQL to run as localhost on the Mac. But a few quick searches on the internet led me to the answers.\n\nPerhaps one of the nicest things is that it bundled Zend Framework with the product, so it is one less thing I have to keep in my local directories. And since almost every single one of my projects is ZF powered, that was really nice.\n\nZend Server CE is available for Mac, Windows and Linux. Give it a shot. I know that lots of people use WAMP in the windows world, but this install seemed much better.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T13:54:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6055","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I doubt we ever deploy Zend Server on our main web servers, but the CE version is HAWT for local development. I like its all-in-one nature and that it is crazy fast. Of course that is probably because it doesn't have to do network transfers, but still. It is great.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:49:26.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5986","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Some Inspiring Internet Happiness","description":"We, as a society, always make such a big deal over stuff when things go wrong. We celebrate Bill Gates' blue-screen-of-death while he was demoing windows, we harp endlessly about how twitter is always down, we love hearing about how some celebrity is messed up on drugs and did something stupid. Well, in the last 2 days, I have read some truly inspiring articles that celebrate the goodness of the internet, so I thought I would share them.\n\nThe first is from readwriteweb, whom I enjoy reading alot of stuff from. The situation that they are talking about is the recent troubles with the OAuth security protocol (some of you may check out right now and think \"BORING\", but seriously, read the article). The message is that the big boys of silicon valley (Google, Yahoo, twitter) helped out one-man startups to avoid some serious security issues relating to an OAuth security hole. It really was inspiring to hear the story of how the situation unfolded, and how businesses put aside profitability and competition, in favor of collaboration and camaraderie.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/how_the_oauth_security_battle_was_won_open_web_sty.php\">http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/how_the_oauth_security_battle_was_won_open_web_sty.php</a>\n\nFor those that didn't want to read about security protocols, here is another, much less techy article that is talking about Zappos, the online shoe company. The title of the article is \"18 things you can learn from Zappos\". Basically, this company sounds awesome! IMO, they totally \"get it\". Relaxed, creative environment. Equality. Accountability. They seem to be one of those truly unique companies that people love, not just need because of the paycheck. Anyway, here is that article:\n\n<a href=\"http://blog.mrtweet.net/18-things-you-can-learn-from-zappos-what-other-companys-should-we-be-learning-from\">http://blog.mrtweet.net/18-things-you-can-learn-from-zappos-what-other-companys-should-we-be-learning-from</a>\n\n\nThat's it for now. I hope you guys enjoyed those articles. I think there is much to be learned from both of them.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T02:30:07.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-28T13:34:00.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6007","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"On a related note, is this something we have implemented?\n\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Session_fixation#Solution:_Store_session_identifiers_in_HTTP_cookies\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Session_fixation#Solution:_Store_session_identifiers_in_HTTP_cookies</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-28T13:34:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6004","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I like it when Twitter is down, because of the beautiful artistry that is the fail whale. Though, even with all the \"always down\" comments, I have yet to see it in person (on the live site).","createdDate":"2009-04-28T12:21:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5921","contributorName":"0u80tuq8uoubg","title":"Contribute - Does it Suck? And if so, for Whom?","description":"In Student Affairs, we're currently evaluating different tools for site content updates. One of the ones we're considering is Adobe Contribute.\n\nThose of you who are using Contribute, how did you choose it? What were your other contenders? What problems did Contribute solve for you?\n\nDo users of Contribute like it? What do they like about it? Administrators, do you expect your users to self-help if they need assistance?\n\nDo administrators of Contribute like it, or is it a support burden, and why? What is supporting Contribute like?\n\nIf administrators need help with Contribute, whom do they ask for help?\n\nAdministrators, how did you train your users to use Contribute? How long did it take to teach your users how to use Contribute?\n\nHave you been to a class on Contribute on campus? What is the learning curve like? Administrators, do you find that you need to explain concepts in Contribute over and over again, or do you explain once and users are able to figure it out from there?\n\nHow did your department or unit purchase licenses for Contribute, and what were the approximate costs?\n\nHow large is your department? How many licenses for Contribute do you have?","createdDate":"2009-04-23T21:59:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-30T13:49:24.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6101","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Jessie,\n\nI'll respond soon.\n\nIDon","createdDate":"2009-04-30T13:49:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6071","contributorName":"i643tt9ut0ty","description":"I've used it with several out-of-state adjunct faculty members and have been able to help them install Contribute and set up access to their course sites over the phone. I'd say that to add text or edit existing pages it's wonderful. It can get a little trickier when you want to create new pages and make sure that you have the proper navigation back and forth. Also, to keep a consistent look and feel it is very important to have intuitive CSS set up and make sure that users understand which styles they should apply to headers, which to body content etc. -Dede","createdDate":"2009-04-28T16:17:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6020","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"At the College of Ed we use Contribute so that all departments can update their own info.\n\nMy biggest issue with Contribute is that I have to give my users full access to the entire website, not just their section in order for it to work properly. Because we use CSS to drive our design all of that is at a higher level of access and without them having privileges to the whole site they see it as a stripped text only version.\n\nSo my choices are to give them access to just their area in afs and when they edit their webpages it doesn't make sense. Or give them full access in afs and control it via the Contribute Key and pray they don't know how to ftp outside of contribute &amp; blow up my website. Neither of these options I like.\n\nOtherwise, I really like Contribute of DW. My biggest issue with DW in the past was the whole local/remote concept. Contribute makes that easy. I will say that the thing I have had to keep on top of is the use of documents. For some reason everyone wants to put up a word document to be downloaded rather than having it in a web page. Then everytime they upload a new document it doesn't replace the one of the server, it just adds to it. Since they can't see the remote file structure I end up with a lot of unused documents on the server that eat up space.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:13:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6001","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"I can't add too much to the discussion and the resources posted in the other messages. We have had a long term project here at the Vet School of straightening out our web \"presence\" and trying to get the users to keep content up to date. We converted over from users using Dreamweaver to Contribute and couldn't have been happier with the results. The learning curve has been negligible for both the established users and for new ones. Training = Don Schmidt = on campus resources has worked very well (Don continues to be my hero where training is concerned). Are there problems .. sure.. are there support needs..sure... But the end result which we were aiming for has been achieved, of a consistent web look and feel along with relatively up to date content.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T12:05:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5983","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"We run Contribute in engineering, still at version 3 since there has not been much call to upgrade. It's just so simple --open page, edit page, publish page-- and that is all our users (about 30) try to do with it. It has eliminated the bottleneck of getting sites updated. We do not have to write and enter content for people. The only alternative would be to put Dreamweaver around and that is overkill. There is no other browser-based editor that does what Contribute does. I was hoping there would be by now (we have been running Contribute for 5 years or so) but there isn't, AFAIK. Contribute requires some IT support, but it is pretty minor compared to doing site updating for people.","createdDate":"2009-04-27T20:52:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5961","contributorName":"0u80tuq8uoubg","description":"Thanks for a thoughtful and helpful response, Dave. This kind of information will be invaluable to us as we go through the research process.\n\nCould you say more about what \"non-ADA compliant\" means, within the context of Contribute. I am aware of the fact that ADA-standards exist and that and am not looking for a definition of the term WRT the web as a whole--but more am talking about what it is that Contribute does specifically that make its code non-ADA compliant. There are a couple scenarios I can think of, but depending on how much work they'd create for the \"web-type person\" to fix, those may or may not be dealbreakers for us.\n\nOn \"admins go for help\" I was more looking to get a sense of whether or not there is a Contribute support infrastructure on campus, or if there needed to be one. But it sounds more like individual departments purchase their own software and take care of their own support.\n\nThanks for your offer to be available as a training resource. I have a handout that I used to train some folks on Contribute 3 long ago, but as we move forward with this project and that needs refreshing, I'd definitely like to touch base with you about how you're training.\n\nThanks again.","createdDate":"2009-04-27T12:47:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5943","contributorName":"17rwrtv3zxd13","description":"A lot of fac/staff in CHASS use Contribute. It's very user friendly in my opinion and the learning curve isn't bad at all. However, my understanding is that the code it puts out is not ADA compliant. We're actually looking at moving away from it for this reason. Aside from that, I'm not aware of any problems that are really worth mentioning.\n\nUsers typically like it and find it easy to use. People accustomed to being able to edit code, occasionally comment on not being able to do that with contribute. But, they don't typically have any real reason to touch the code anyhow.\n\nWe usually help them if they have problems or direct them to our tutorials. Supporting contribute usually consists of training up front or reminding a user of how to do something every now and then. Occasionally we have to deal with a lock file preventing a user from editing a page. There are times in which a user is having a problem or wants something done that's easier for us to just edit the code for them. If they're strictly updating content, i don't think that would come up much.\n\nTraining is not bad. We mostly do one-on-one training with folks when they first start using it, and that usually goes off without a hitch and people retain info. just fine. The time that takes typically depends on what the user wants to be able to do, and how computer savvy they are. I would say usually 30-60 minutes (less for some users). If you want more details about how I personally go about training users, feel free to shoot me an email or call.\n\nWe also do a class occasionally, but sometimes we get the same folks coming back for that or some of those people have trouble later. But that could be a problem with the current instructional model we're using, the specific people attending, and their motivation for taking the class. We also have tutorials available online for users - <a href=\"http://it.chass.ncsu.edu/training\">http://it.chass.ncsu.edu/training</a>.\n\nI'm not sure how to best answer your question regarding where admins go for help. I can't think of any problems we've run into that weren't pretty straightforward (there's not much to Contribute). I will say that I've used the Adobe forums extensively for other products (Captivate and Flash) at an old job and typically received help that was both good and timely.","createdDate":"2009-04-24T17:02:24.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5890","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Powerpoint from SEO Presentation","description":"Thanks to Rob Ruchte of ThirdParty Labs and Jon Williams of Shovemedia for taking the time to talk through all the various facets of Search Engine Optimization. It was nice to have some folks come speak at the Web Developers meeting, and we hope to do more presentations in the future. I've posted the link to the PowerPoint from today's presentation. If you have questions for Rob or Job, take advantage of the comments section...they're more than willing to follow up.\n\n<a href=\"http://karoshiethos.com/2009/04/22/seo-presentation-for-ncsu-web-developer-group/\">http://karoshiethos.com/2009/04/22/seo-presentation-for-ncsu-web-developer-group/</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-23T00:40:03.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-23T00:40:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5888","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Thanks to Web Comm for the Meetup on SEO","description":"I just wanted to say a special thanks to Tim Jones and the Web Communications group for sponsoring the meetup today with the SEO experts. In a time where budgets are extremely tight, it is awesome to get some free training. I thought the talk was pretty interesting, and I learned some stuff along the way. My main takeaway was \"safe = boring = death\"....I liked that alot :)\n\nAs I mentioned in the meetup today, if anyone has ideas for the next meetup (Sometime in June I would guess), let me know.","createdDate":"2009-04-23T00:27:15.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-23T00:27:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5887","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Clay Shirky: Institutions vs. collaboration","description":"The SEO presenters mentioned (and showed a clip from)the TED talks. This one is very, very interesting. It's just under 21 minutes long, so grab an adult beverage and some popcorn, perhaps. :-)\n\nIn this prescient 2005 talk, Clay Shirky shows how closed groups and companies will give way to looser networks where small contributors have big roles and fluid cooperation replaces rigid planning.\nCategory: Science &amp; Tech\n\n<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sPQViNNOAkw\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sPQViNNOAkw</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-22T21:51:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-22T21:51:08.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5818","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Round 2 of Web Apps vs. Web Sites:  Design","description":"So we have had a good discussion over the differences and similarities of webapps vs. web sites, so now comes a followup....round 2 :)\n\nMy question is how design relates to the two. When I am talking about design, I'm referring to the look and feel of the project, not how it functions on a \"code\" level.\n\nDo you take different things into account when designing a webapp vs. a website?\n\nShould webapps follow the same design \"norms\" as websites?","createdDate":"2009-04-21T15:14:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-20T14:33:54.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5842","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I agree wholeheartedly with Glenn on this one. They're really all trying to \"achieve their purpose\". I do see a possible distinction in that you want to make \"tasks\" (things that people need to do) simple, while making sure that the \"experience\" is fun / different / exciting. A flashy, stylish website may make a strong artistic impression, but simple and clear layouts make performing tasks easier. Likely it depends more on \"what you are selling\" to determine whether simplistic or artistic is more beneficial for either a website or a webapp.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T19:55:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5834","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Coming in a little late to this discussion having just read the other discussion. I don't design a web app any different then I would a website. Basically either is designed for a \"purpose\" and I have a goal of satisfying that purpose. The lines (IMHO) between \"app\" and \"site\" are so blurred these days with all the stuff you can hang off of a site, who knows what to call them anymore :-)\n\nThe \"norms\" I design to are probably geared more from a developer perspective versus a designer. I aim for a simple interface for my apps (fewest things to click or fill in as possible), and also a simple design that presents information clearly without a lot of baggage for a website.Past that it just depends on the purpose of the task.. Everything else is just eye candy!","createdDate":"2009-04-21T17:50:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5823","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I think generally with webapps you have a desired end-goal for the user. It's important that your design clearly communicates that goal to the user. Whether it's simply filling in an entire form, or dragging and dropping pictures into an album. Either way, action is usually required from the user.\n\nWith a website, I think it's more difficult to predict the user's goal. So instead you should focus more on how you can guide the user into making an informed decision. You should give more emphasis to creating a visual hierarchy of the information you are presenting, work on improving the readability of the information and how it's organized.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T15:41:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5810","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"Feedback Wanted: New Student Owned Computing Website Launched","description":"<strong>ITECS Student Owned Computing team has just redesigned their website</strong> and we want your feedback. Feel free to comment, critique, or discuss the usability, accessibility, design, and/or code right here on Ning. Let us have it!\n\n<a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/soc/\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/soc/</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-21T13:29:53.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-05-20T14:55:09.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5839","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Looks great! Even if I do feel a bit slighted by the secondary treatment OpenOffice receives, I'm glad that it is mentioned. :)\n\nIt might make sense to include something like the following on the main page at least:\n&lt;link rel=\"alternate\" href=\"/soc/rss/blog/\" type=\"application/rss+xml\" title=\"SOC-Blog RSS News Feed\" /&gt;\n\nSome standards issues:\n* The flash content is using the non-standard embed tag. See <a href=\"http://www.alistapart.com/stories/flashsatay\">http://www.alistapart.com/stories/flashsatay</a>\n* The \"Learn More\" button should probably have alt text\n* Laptops in the classroom has some unclosed tags\n* RSS Feed has some <a href=\"http://validator.w3.org/feed/check.cgi?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.eos.ncsu.edu%2Fsoc%2Frss%2Fblog%2F\">validation errors</a> (for the date one, you can let PHP format it for you using \"date(DATE_RSS, $time)\")\n\nWith so few changes, this is a glowing recommendation from me. Even though I'm not the content / grammar police, the structure looks great from the initial run through.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T19:47:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5820","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Firefox on XP: the drop down menus are semi-transparent, which seems to make it more difficult to differentiate between the menu link and the text on the page underneath. Sure its not very transparent at all, but it just seems unnecessary. I wonder if color blind users would have more trouble with this?\n\nI would think that you could make it completely opaque, and not lose any usability or graphical impact of the menu.\n\nJust a thought...other than that, the site looks pretty nice. Good job :-)","createdDate":"2009-04-21T15:32:13.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5815","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I only saw one little graphical thing. In the search box, it looks like the text element has a border, but the icon doesn't have the border, so it looks kinda like it is an error. I'd either remove the border from the text box or add it to the button.\n\nLooks good otherwise :)\n\nPS: That was on FF and Safari on OSX","createdDate":"2009-04-21T14:59:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5802","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Best Thing Ever: Web Developer Toolbar","description":"How do you know something? Well, you either discovered it yourself, or someone else showed it to you. Now...if you don't have colleagues showing you new things, and you're too busy to discover things for yourself, then you're going to have a hard time knowing about certain tools...certain tools with a few neat features even.\n\nIf only there was a tool that so clearly was linked to a profession...say.....Web Development. And just to make it easier for those people without helpful colleagues, the tool was named exactly the same as the profession. Enter, the \"Web Developer Toolbar (an extension for Firefox).\"\n\n<b><a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/60\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/60</a></b>\n\nI put the Web Developer Toolbar, into the category of \"if you know about it...you can't understand why anyone wouldn't know about it, and if you don't know about it, don't admit it, lest you be looked at like you have 3 heads.\" For many of you, you probably fall into the first group...the people who get to look incredulously at non-users who haven't heard of it yet. And so, this edition of Best Thing Ever is targeted at the second group...let's call them to \"Uninformed Unfortunates.\"\n\nThe Web Developer does many things, and there is too much to fit into one article, or at least too much for me to write about. So I'm going to focus on the few things that I use every day. Go ahead, install the extension, and you'll see where all this stuff is located... seriously ...I'll wait.\n\n<b>1. CSS -&gt;View Style Information (shortcut == Apple+SHIFT+Y)</b>\n\nThis allows you to hover your mouse over the pieces of the currently displayed website, and view the layout elements, as well as any style information. In the top of your window, you'll see the code that is applied to whichever element you are hovering over, and you'll get a red border around the element so you can be sure of what you're seeing.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/74-screenshot1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/75-screenshot1.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"38\"/></a></p>\n\nThis allows you see very easily what may be wrong with a page you're developing, or better yet, what may be right on someone else's site. You'll be able to see the beauty of css only layouts, and experience horrifying bewilderment as you move over nested tables.\n\n<b>2. CSS -&gt; Edit CSS (shortcut == Apple+SHIFT+E)</b>\n\nWhen you're wondering where you went wrong (I'm talking about an error with css, not where you went wrong in life), you would previously have to edit your css file, save, then return to the browser and refresh, repeating that loop until you've fixed the problem (or started thinking about where you went wrong in life).\n\nWith the web developer toolbar, you can edit the css of a page directly in the browser. This way, you can mess with it all you want during the troubleshooting phase, and then only commit the real solution to your css file. It will open up a tab (not a firefox tab) for every single css file that is referenced by the page, giving the option to augment any or all of the pages, making it easy to copy paste changes to your real css file. This is also interestingly useful when looking at other people's websites, because it gives you the ability to play a little \"what if\" game with their site. What if you turned off the menu....what if you changed the color of the links....what if you changed the banner graphic to something else, then took a screenshot of it, making it look like you developed a whole new site just like theirs....the possibilities are endless.\n\n<b>3. CSS -&gt; Disable Styles</b>\n\nSometimes you'll be working on a site with multiple stylesheets, and you won't know what's causing a problem. Maybe you have redundant styles that are preventing a new class from applying? With this option, you can turn off individual stylesheets, or all of them. This is most powerful when you have multiple stylesheets for separate purposes, like one for layout, one for text styles, one for table styles, one for form styles....I don't know why you'd do that, but its possible, and I've seen it done before.\n\n<b>Use what you use...forget the rest...</b>\n\nThere are many many many many other neat features to the toolbar...and I won't pretend to use all of them, or even know about half of them. The good thing is that you can use what you need, and forget the rest...until someone looks at you with those critical eyes, like their saying \"what?...you don't use the Display Stack Levels option....and you call yourself a Web Developer?\" I'm actually hoping that people will comment on this article and add their favorite toolbar hidden options.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T11:56:20.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-21T19:26:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5837","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Richard,\n\nFirebug will let you use hierarchical navigation and watch in real time as your JavaScript modifies the DOM.\n\nThe HTML Validator Addon will give display the Page Validation (without having to load it from a remote site) and clicking on its icon will show you the source with the full list of problems as well as highlighting where in the code each problem is occurring.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T19:26:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5812","contributorName":"1eracb58xe19h","description":"One of my favorite features of the Web Developer Toolbar is the <b>Images-&gt;View Image Information</b> option, which will generate a listing of all images on a page, whether they're in image tags or there by CSS. The listing will open up in a separate tab and give link, height, width, alt and file size information for each of the images on the page. I find it very handy for when you have images layered over one another.\n\n<b>Miscellaneous-&gt;Display Line Guides</b> comes in very handy for quick measurement between items on a page when setting up a layout - my only complaint about this feature is the vertical line guide doesn't extend down past the screen height.\n\n<b>View Source-&gt;View Generated Source</b> is very helpful for viewing code when you're doing a lot of javascript DOM generation., since it will give you the source of the page at the instant you click the option instead of the standard View Source, which will only give you the source of the page on initial load.\n\n<b>Tools-&gt;Display Page Validation</b> gives you a handy toolbar telling you how many validation errors your page currently has - it updates on page refresh or tab change too. It's helpful to have up while you track down validation bugs. Clicking on the error count will also send you to the W3C validatior, which is handy.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T13:31:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5807","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"My particular favorites are the 'Outline' tools and I occasionally use the 'Information' menu to show me how the styles are laying out the page or what divs are nested where. This is, of course, in addition to the ones mentioned above. I'll also mention the keyboard shortcuts are fantastic, especially when you're trying to work out some odd CSS layout and not generally a terribly patient person anyway.","createdDate":"2009-04-21T13:22:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5804","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"As far as the three items you mentioned, I feel like Firebug does a better job (while realizing that it is in part which look and feel you are comfortable with). Click Inspect then click on the element that you want to look at. It will show you all the styles that are being applied to that element, in descending priority order (so you know which one is overriding which other one) and allowing you to temporarily disable or add/edit/delete individual lines of the styles.\n\nHere are the things for which I still use Web Developer (albeit rarely):\n\nWhen something appears to be caching incorrectly:\n* Miscellaneous -&gt; Clear Private Data -&gt; Cache\n* Disable -&gt; Disable Cache\n\nWhen you just want to see what the fresh or not trusting visitor sees:\n* Cookies -&gt; View Cookie Information\n* Disable -&gt; Disable JavaScript -&gt; All JavaScript\n\nWhen you want to enlighten people about form input validation (e.g. Little Bobby Tables):\n* Forms -&gt; Display Form Details\n* Forms -&gt; Convert Select Elements To Text Inputs","createdDate":"2009-04-21T13:05:12.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5784","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Search Engine Optimization Presentation, April 22","description":"Just a reminder that we'll be having the regular meeting of the NC State Web Developers on Wednesday, April 22 at 2 p.m. in McKimmon Center. Room is still to be determined, but should be clearly labeled the day of the event. Plenty of parking as well.\n\nAlso, below is an outline of the SEO presentation and bios of the presenters.\n\n\nINTRO\n\nHOW PAGE RANK WORKS\n\nCONTENT STRATEGY\n- Content is, was, and will always be, *king*.\n- Be Remarkable.\n- Sprinkle keywords (lightly!) across a variety of semantic tags.\n- Quality over quantity.\n- Quality *outgoing* links count too\n- \"On-page Optimization\"\n\nDESIGN STRATEGY\n- Typography\n- Why whitespace matters\n- In support of minimalism\n- Generic vs Specific? Not \"Either Or\". Both And.\n\nTECHNOLOGY STRATEGY\n- Semantics\n- Syndication\n- Aggregation\n- Strategies for Multimedia\n\n\nSOCIAL STRATEGIES\n- Communication Philosophy\n- Build, deploy, promote (in that order)\n- Serenity - Things you can change vs those you can't.\n\nPITFALLS\n\nQ&amp;A\n\n\nBios:\nRob Ruchte/Thirdparty Labs\nThirdparty Labs is a Raleigh-based web development shop specializing\nin custom content management solutions. Thirdparty Labs provides\ntechnical services to the advertising and PR industry, as well as a\nnumber of Triangle area universities. Founder Rob Ruchte has been\ndeveloping dynamic web sites since 1997, and has been involved in the\ndevelopment of applications for fortune 500 firms including FirstUnion/\nWachovia, Cable &amp; Wireless, DuPont, and GlaxoSmithKline.\n\nJon Williams/Shovemedia\nShovemedia is a boutique interactive development studio specializing\nin Flash / Actionscript. Founded in 2005 by Raleigh designer,\nprogrammer, and entraprenuer Jon Williams, shovemedia boasts a large,\ncomprehensive portfolio of work done for clients all over the world.\nJon has been published online and in print, conducted workshops at\narea schools, and has been a featured speaker at numerous interactive\nconferences across the country. His work has been recognized by\nrespected online publications such as Communication Arts, How Design\nand the Remedi Project. In 2001, Jon's work helped ioResearch win the\ntechnical merit award at the Flash Forward Film Festival in New York\nCity.","createdDate":"2009-04-20T20:59:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-20T20:59:57.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5721","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"What is the difference between a web application and a web site?","description":"\"What is the difference between a website and a web application?\" That question has been posed to me several times, and I thought I would bring it here to see what your opinions are on the matter. To me, they couldn't be more clearly different, but I am a programmer so my definition may vary.\n\nTo me, a web application is a functional piece of software, driven by dynamic, interactive content. A website is more static and informative in nature. When I think of a web application, I think of gmail. When I think of a website, I think of ncsu.edu. Do the lines blur sometimes? Sure. But they are inherently different.\n\nTo me, from a design perspective, web applications serve different purposes, and therefore need to be designed differently than websites. Websites primary role is to inform. Webapps primary role is to do something. When the primary target of something you work on is different, the final result is going to be different.\n\nSo what do you think? What <i>are</i> the differences between a web application and a website, or are there any?","createdDate":"2009-04-16T12:15:44.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-04-06T12:05:28.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5741","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I'm not sure I can really can draw any kind of line here, or break out the \"web site\" vs. \"web app\" buckets or sets. On a vaguely humorous note, my first thought when I read two classifications here was \"well, is this a european swallow, or an african swallow?\"\n\nI mean, really, <a href=\"http://www.style.org/unladenswallow/\">what <i>is</i> the airspeed velocity of a unladen swallow?</a>\n\nSo there's both a design, and a technology question here. On the technology level - the lines blur pretty quickly. The ubiquitous \"they\" has to manage and configure the web server process(es), manage the language environment(s) available (perl, python, ruby, php, etc.), and the connections between those language environments and the web server. Is it a site or an app? Both require an implementation and maintenance cost of varying levels - depending on experience with the environments/servers, vendor support, architecture, etc. While you might can draw a line between Apache opening an html file itself and sending it back out to browser and Apache handing off a file to the PHP module to interpret the PHP code in the file - it gets a bit harder to really draw solid lines between a simple php script that reads a text field out of mysql and prints it back out. or a guestbook form. Or mediawiki. Or drupal. All of the latter are a \"codebase\" - an app if you will - that has a lifetime, a maintenance need, an ongoing resource cost, etc. That simple PHP script is quite likely going to need a change when PHP 6, 7, 8 comes out. (We've had a lot of issues with this where folks are very willing to \"write an application\" or usually faculty very willing to volunteer us or request \"a web site\" or a \"web application\" - they almost always say 'site' - without considering the ongoing resource costs of implementation - and particularly maintenance).\n\nAt the design level, it seems impossible to draw a line, it's really a continuum. A single static page is different than a whole interconnected \"site\". A blog is different than a wiki, A wiki is different from Google Knol, Google Knol is different than twitter, twitter is different than gmail. Gmail is different than, well, everything else. All of which have different design considerations based on audience, content, the interactivity, and the technologies chosen to deliver it.\n\nSo I don't think you can draw a line here, either based on static vs. 'dynamic' or 'interactive' or not. Static html blogs are often WAY more 'dynamic' than most of our CMS-produced \"sites\" - but that CMS very, very has an ongoing management/maintenance costs. A very simple forum we spend two days on could generate WAY more interactivity than that conference application we spent hundreds of person-hours developing. And all of them could have vastly different design, traffic, maintenance, resource, technology, etc. needs and costs.\n\nI love my bukkits (the compartmentalization of these things) - but I don't think that site and application are the right bukkits here. It's very much a venn diagram of different characteristics and factors involved - or a gradient, or pick a favorite \"shades of grey\" metaphor.","createdDate":"2009-04-17T01:52:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5735","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I think that we begin to cross the bridge from website to web application the minute the user has the ability to interact with the content.","createdDate":"2009-04-16T17:20:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5732","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"All good ways to look at the question. I think what's interesting is that there are, in fact, different ways to understand, interpret and explain the distinction between a web site and a web application. Imagine how the less-than-savvy end users feel...or more importantly, how little they care. If a users visits a website to \"do\" something, then he/she should be able to, well, do that. Doesn't matter if the \"something\" is complex or simple, or simply a matter of retrieving some bit of information. Just needs to work.\n\nIn my mind, the website is the place on the Internet where the stuff lives. Some of that stuff might be static, some of it might be fancy-pants web apps that do all kinds of neat tricks. The site itself is responsible for delivering that stuff, should it be the result of some complicated, intricate actions, a simple database fetch, or a some high quality copy/paste work.\n\nA few things I suspect most users won't ever think: If a web app isn't on the web, can it be a web app? Or, if a desktop app talks to the web, is it a web app or desktop app?\n\nTo put it all in another way, that, I hope, will be interpreted as what it's intended to be (a joke), maybe the difference is really in who creates it. Geeks build websites. Web apps are built by a different kind of geek.","createdDate":"2009-04-16T15:52:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5729","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"In the most general terms any URL is technically a website. So, reader.google.com is a website. However, reader.google.com is more accurately called a webapp. To me the distinction is that any site that uses the \"web as platform\" is a webapp, it's a site that is also a service. I agree with DaManLovett... webapps \"do stuff.\" One easy way to tell if something is a webapp or not is if it can replace a piece of software on your machine it is certainly a webapp. That's not the only test of course, but its one of the simplest measurements I can think of.\n\nAlso, a dynamically driven site, say a CMS-powered site, is not necessarily a webapp.","createdDate":"2009-04-16T13:54:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5726","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"A web application is a website in the same way that a square is a rectangle.\n\nThe application part is the model-controller combo. The web part (the view) is why it qualifies as a website.\n\nSomething that is only a website and not a web application is simply missing the dynamic aspect.\n\nOf course, it can be difficult to decide on how much server-side processing is required to qualify it as a web application. Probably when it has a data store.\n\nThus, you have the primary role of webapps confused. A website's primary role is to inform. A web app's primary role is to inform using dynamic content (the do something part).","createdDate":"2009-04-16T12:50:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5723","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"I agree with Jason completely with a little twist. I don't think a web site has to be static to be considered a web site by definition. I believe there are several sites that are dynamic but still fall under a \"web site\" definition.\n\nMy perspective comes to me because I started out as a web designer and moved to a web developer. I believe the basic fundamental difference is that webapps can be stand-alone objects. If you could wave a magic wand over it and it could turn into software or desktop application, thus it is web app. In turn, the significants could be redefined and still be useful.\n\nWeb apps ROCK, cause they do \"stuff\". That' my .02 cents.","createdDate":"2009-04-16T12:24:45.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5683","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","title":"Rands - The Best Site Ever","description":"I'm either missing something, or the forum categories have a roles/permissions system attached to them and \"The Best Thing Ever!\" is reserved for a far more responsible crowd (The Best Thing Ever! where this really belongs, although it's about a person, and not a thing, so maybe the reading room is a fair substitute).\n\nAnyway, I digress as I've been wont to do, a time or two. Or eleventy-billion.\n\nDo you manage? Do you want to manage? Have you managed and don't really desire to do so again for a while? Do you never want to in the first place, but want to have a glimpse into tech management? Do you manage at the University and want to have a glimpse into the world \"out there\"?\n\nYes or no to any of those questions, well it doesn't really matter. You should be reading <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/\">Rands in Repose</a> anyway - I haven't drunk all the koolaid and <a href=\"http://managinghumans.com/pitch.html\">bought his book</a> (reading books? I'm not sure what that is anymore) - but the blog is awesome and the posts JasonYoung-esque-length (but far, far, far better written)\n\nBest Blog Ever (until I post something else a few weeks from now). I'm reminded of this by his latest: <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/2009/04/15/the_pond.html\">\"The Pond\"</a> - but browsing <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/cat_best_of.html\">the best of</a> category is highly recommended.\n\nWay Two Thumbs Up! Five Star Rated! 10 Tomatoes or something like that.\n\n(This site not sponsored or endorsed or provided on behalf of my alma matter, contents may settle, void where prohibited, express of the MLB required for rebroadcast or retransmission, etc. etc. yadda yadda yadda)","createdDate":"2009-04-15T02:54:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-15T13:15:14.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5701","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It was nice to see his openness to those who leave the Pond. My previous experience had a lot of resistance on that front. I find that the Pond - with all of its ripples - is a turbulent place that makes creating a house of cards a difficult venture. Rather, to fight this, we have to build up walls on the Pond itself (on a regular basis) in an attempt to minimize the ongoing turbulence. Likely I'm just one of those who thrive whether or not I'm away from the Pond. The only real benefit to being on the Pond for me are the superfluous interactions (which have a value all their own) and the proximity to assist the faint cries for help from a drowning compatriot. Plus, I enjoy the delicious bandwidth.\n\nOn a side note, management who aren't on the Pond (particularly those who fashion themselves as a lifeguard) will be ineffective at communicating with the leaf nodes. Some can't afford to be on the Pond, but those that aren't need to rely on the Pond's middle management instead of attempting to shake the leaves directly.\n\nThese comments are not approved by the FDA and may contain false SEC filings.","createdDate":"2009-04-15T13:15:14.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5662","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"Zend with multiple controllers","description":"I'm starting a new project using Zend. It's a new version of the software we've been running in our chemistry stockroom for 20 years (it's dBase and won't run under vista). The project naturally breaks down into sections: Inventory, Customers, Sales, etc. My idea was to use multiple controllers for each section so I created the usual Index Controller and a InvenController in application/controllers and application/views/scripts/index and application/views/scripts/inven directories to hold the code. The main index page loads just fine but I haven't been able to figure out how to get the inven part to work. When I try to load <a href=\"http://site.ncsu.edu/inven\">http://site.ncsu.edu/inven</a> I get a 404 Page not found error. Obviously I'm missing something but google hasn't been much help to me. Any suggestions on what I'm missing?","createdDate":"2009-04-14T17:55:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-14T18:12:09.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5664","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I would almost guarantee your htaccess file is the culprit. Do any actions other than index load in your main index controller? IE, does <a href=\"http://site.ncsu.edu/index/details\">http://site.ncsu.edu/index/details</a> load? If not, I can bet it is an htaccess file. If so, it is probably something else with either your directory structure or the naming of your controller. This has some info on the htaccess file guidelines: <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.controller.html#zend.controller.quickstart.go.rewrite\">http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.controller.html#zend.controller.quickstart.go.rewrite</a>\n\nHope that helps.","createdDate":"2009-04-14T18:12:09.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5647","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Dashcode:  The Best Thing Ever for iPhone Web Development","description":"I've never hidden the fact that I am an Apple fanboy. I have a Macbook, iPhone, iPod Nano, a Time Capsule, and some other miscellaneous accessories. I fell off the Windows bandwagon about 2.5 years ago, and have never looked back.\n\nWhile I have always loved Apple's hardware, the true beauty of Apple lies in their software. OSX is amazing, as is the iPhone platform. It was only recently that I was introduced to Apple's development tools: <a href=\"http://developer.apple.com/technology/tools.html\">Xcode</a>, <a href=\"http://developer.apple.com/technology/tools.html\">Interface Builder</a>, and <a href=\"http://developer.apple.com/tools/dashcode/\">Dashcode</a>. (Note: These tools are only available on OSX...sorry Winders users)\n\nI have recently gotten into iPhone development (both native and web-based apps). The tools Apple provides for development make programming for iPhone super easy. Xcode and Interface Builder provide the foundation for building native applications, while Dashcode provides tools for creating web-based applications optimized for iPhone. My focus so far has been on web-based applications, so I can say with 1000% certainty that if you are going to develop an iPhone friendly web-based application, Dashcode is the best thing ever.\n\n<img src=\"discussions/76-Picture1.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"270\" style=\"float: right;\"/>Dashcode was originally introduced to give developers an easy way to create widgets for OS X's Dashboard. However, when the iPhone development kit was released, Dashcode got an upgrade to include iPhone web application support.\n\nDashcode gives you a nice interface to get you started. You can obviously start with a blank project, but Apple has helped you save some time by creating some commonly used templates like browsers, utilities, and an RSS reader.\n\nOnce you get your project started, you get a boatload of UI Parts you can drag and drop into your interface. Here is the real value in Dashcode. It has all the UI elements that you expect to see in an iPhone application, ready to drap and drop into your interface. This gives your web app a \"native\" look and feel, even though it is running through a browser.\n\nDashcode also provides alot of pre-written javascript code to help with things like processing AJAX requests and getting elements from your interface. You can also write your own javascript fragments and save those in the code library. So if you are constantly writing the same code over and over again, you can save yourself some time!\n\nWhen you are done with your project, Dashcode makes it easy to deploy the project to any WebDAV enabled account. You just setup your account, tell Dashcode where to put your application, and it handles uploading all the javascript, css, images, and HTML. Before you know it, you have a full-featured, iPhone optimized web applicaiton up and running!\n\nMy first little project in Dashcode was an app that did AJAX calls to a JSON script that pulled version information from some of our applications. It was a pretty simple project, and only took me an hour or so to put together. Without Dashcode, I would have had to spend lots of time worrying about formatting of the common iPhone interface elements like buttons, lists, and headers. Instead, I got to get straight to work on the point of the project, which saved a lot of time.\n\nSo if you are going to write some kind of web app for iPhone, and you want to save yourself a lot of time and energy, checkout Dashcode. You will quickly understand why it is the best thing ever.","createdDate":"2009-04-14T12:28:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-07-27T18:30:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5659","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"That sounds cool. I dunno if we have the time right now, but it sounds like a great idea and we can certainly talk about it. One of the things on my (very long) list of things to do is better organize some iphone development on campus, so this is right down that alley.","createdDate":"2009-04-14T16:16:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5651","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"Hey Jason. We have a grant to create some content for iphones/ipods and I was wondering if anyone on campus had expertise creating apps for these platforms. Do you think you/your group would be able to work with us on this? The project is developing videos, pictures, and text that law enforcement can load onto their iphone and take onto a crime scene. They would then follow a step by step process on how to approach the scene to preserve the integrity of the evidence, etc.","createdDate":"2009-04-14T15:19:53.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5584","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Drupal Themes - Artisteer & Theme Starter 1.0 Demo","description":"I wanted to post about a couple of Drupal timesavers that i've found in the past couple of weeks:\n\nArtisteer (<a href=\"http://www.artisteer.com\">http://www.artisteer.com</a>)\n\nand then just today, i found this:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1JA1VK1YpQ\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1JA1VK1YpQ</a>\n\n<b>First...Artisteer</b>\n\nI found Artisteer through one of those nice web links at the top of my gmail account. I thought i would check it out, thinking that there's no way a theme builder could actually work and be customizable enough for my needs. Well....it doesn't hit all the points i want, but what it does do, is save me a whole lot of time getting started with a custom theme.\n\nArtisteer is a theme builder, with predefined \"suggestions\" for anything from the whole site template, to the individual colors of links and text. The best part is that you can keep clicking any of the \"suggest\" buttons, and cycle through a bunch of different options...OR... you can just use the parts you want, then customize to heart's content. I usually start with a basic layout for the template (2 or 3 columns, menu location, width and background stuff)...then go in and tweak the styles of the blocks, block headings, articles and text/links too. After a while you'll get used to what it can and cannot do....and then you can figure out how much post-artisteer work you'll have to accomplish.\n\nThat's a quick look at the pros...now the cons....it doesnt have as many layout options as i would like. It is basically restricted to a 1, 2 or 3 column layout, with one main content area. The only thing i would add in there at the moment, is the ability to split the content area into two (or more) rows. That way it can be possible to put blocks in above your content once you create pages in drupal. Check it out though....the trial version will give you all the functionality you want....but you cant export Drupal templates. You'll have to shell out some $$$ for that. I think its just barely over $100. But i can say its already paid for itself by the amount of time it has saved me. Oh yeah...it also does Joomla, HTML, and Wordpress templates/themes too, and its all CSS.\n\n<b>Now, Drupal Theme Starter 1.0</b>\nIt is a video about Drupal Theme Starter 1.0, which is a GUI tool for developing your Drupal theme. It basically gets everything setup for you, including the *.info file. This won't get you a full colorized imagified spectacularized theme, but it will get you the framework to build upon.\n\nThe download for the tool is at the end of the video, but here's the direct link for those that want to skip ahead: <a href=\"http://xtnd.us\">http://xtnd.us</a>\n\nI havent used this one yet, but i think i will definitely be investigating it. It has the benefit of being free, and the flexibility of letting me layout the regions in any way i want. It doesnt go as far as Artisteer does, but it does not pretend to. This is going to very helpful to develop sites that have a more unique layout requirement.\n\nThat's all for now...check em out. I'll be interested to see people's opinions about the theme builder, as i havent used it much yet.","createdDate":"2009-04-10T12:31:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-10T12:31:10.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5563","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","title":"Can't Understand Error","description":"Can anyone help me figure out what I'm doing wrong. Thanks in advance\n\n\nHTTP/1.1 404 Not Found\n\nThe following error occurred:\nexception 'Zend_Controller_Dispatcher_Exception' with message 'Invalid controller specified (quickstart2)' in C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\library\\Zend\\Controller\\Dispatcher\\Standard.php:249 Stack trace: #0 C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\library\\Zend\\Controller\\Front.php(914): Zend_Controller_Dispatcher_Standard-&gt;dispatch(Object(Zend_Controller_Request_Http), Object(Zend_Controller_Response_Http)) #1 C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\application\\bootstrap.php(23): Zend_Controller_Front-&gt;dispatch() #2 C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\public\\index.php(28): require('C:\\wamp\\www\\qui...') #3 {main}\n\n\nFatal error: Uncaught exception 'Zend_Controller_Dispatcher_Exception' with message 'Invalid controller specified (quickstart2)' in C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\library\\Zend\\Controller\\Dispatcher\\Standard.php:249 Stack trace: #0 C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\library\\Zend\\Controller\\Front.php(914): Zend_Controller_Dispatcher_Standard-&gt;dispatch(Object(Zend_Controller_Request_Http), Object(Zend_Controller_Response_Http)) #1 C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\public\\index.php(48): Zend_Controller_Front-&gt;dispatch() #2 {main} thrown in C:\\wamp\\www\\quickstart2\\library\\Zend\\Controller\\Dispatcher\\Standard.php on line 249","createdDate":"2009-04-10T01:44:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-10T18:49:29.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:220","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5602","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"Thanks Garrison","createdDate":"2009-04-10T18:49:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5599","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"Thanks Troy, I'm about to fire up WAMP and see if I can find the problem.","createdDate":"2009-04-10T18:49:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5581","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"It's hard to tell exactly without seeing your bootstrap or the controller in question, but it looks like it looking at www as the root of your app instead of quickstart2.","createdDate":"2009-04-10T12:26:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5546","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"Calendar functions (CF, Javascript etc..) and accessibility","description":"We do a lot of applications over here that involve entering dates (beginning date..ending date etc..). Then we do searches based on the ranges entered. Currently we use simple text boxes to allow for the entry. We also work very hard to insure that all of our pages are as fully \"accessible\" as possible.\n\nRealizing how primitive that is, and how prone to error it can be :-) we are looking at ways to simplify date entries using calendar functions. ColdFusion has a neat one built in(but it's Flash based), there are tons of Javascript ones out there, so implementing a method isn't the issue. What I'm curious about is how accessible these sorts of functions are? Is anyone using one of these sort of functions that has actually looked into this (ie.. actually ran it through some sort of accessibility checker etc..)","createdDate":"2009-04-09T13:37:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-13T12:25:14.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5624","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Just keep in mind that even with the variety of formats, some people still can't provide good dates.\n\n\"Returns a timestamp on success, FALSE otherwise. Previous to PHP 5.1.0, this function would return -1 on failure.\"\n\nSo for anyone using a supported version of PHP, check to make sure that if the strtotime === false that you ask them to put in a good date before continuing.","createdDate":"2009-04-13T12:25:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5621","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","description":"Thanks for the replies.. Need an opinion from the masses. I've fooled around a bit (based on Jonathan's comments) with this and have created a text box like the current method. I have a Javascript calendar input beside it, which if used,fills in the text box. But entry can also be made directly into the text field if desired. I'm thinking from an \"accessibility\" point of view that should be acceptable, shouldn't it?","createdDate":"2009-04-13T12:22:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5592","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"PHP has a nifty little function called <a href=\"http://us2.php.net/strtotime\">strtotime()</a> that will take a date the user has inputted (in a variety of formats) and convert it into a unix timestamp (which you can then transform back into a date with the format you for liking).\n\n$userSubmittedDate = $_POST[date];\n$dateWithPreferredFormat = date(\"m/d/Y\",strtotime($userSubmittedDate));\n\nThis should help catch most date formatting mistakes made by your users. I am not sure if ColdFusion has an equivlanet function.","createdDate":"2009-04-10T14:28:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5586","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"If any of them are going to be good, I would imagine that the <a href=\"http://jqueryui.com/demos/datepicker/#date-formats\">jQuery UI calendar</a> one would be good (making sure to set the format using a type=\"hidden\" input or format utility function of course). Flash rarely is accessible, and given that JavaScript creates the same kind of DOM Nodes as the rest of the website, it just requires a screen reader which works like Firebug and watches the DOM for changes (not that I imagine any of them are good enough to do that, sadly). Really, you'll probably want to leave the entry method as is, but for people with JavaScript and sight, displaying the optional calendar magic is a nice extra. It's not that it doesn't work for the blind, but unless you display the Calendar inline using server side processing, I don't know how you'll be able to make it work for them.","createdDate":"2009-04-10T12:49:24.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5490","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"jQuery UI","description":"<b>jQuery UI - <a href=\"http://ui.jquery.com\">http://ui.jquery.com</a></b>\n\nRaise your hand if you help make the internet. Keep your hand up if you use jQuery. Now keep your hand up if you use jQuery UI to make your user interface a fully theme-able, cross-browser compatible land of magic, wonder, and happiness. A land filled with unicorns, and after every April shower, the sky is adorned with sublime quadruple-rainbows at the end of which are pools filled with the ambrosial nectar of the sweetest honeysuckle. The slight breeze echoes mellifluous through the moss-covered forest...\n\nBut I digress.\n\nWhy am I the only person with their hand still raised?\n\nGood thing I'm here to show you the way the veritable Brigadoon that is jQuery UI.\n\n<img src=\"discussions/77-BrigODoon.jpg?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\"/><br/>\n\nEver needed an accordion menu? How about a calendar? Tabs? Sortable lists? Dialog windows?\n\nI'm going to assume you said yes to all of those. Now, have you ever wished all of those widgets would look the same everywhere without having to do any work?\n\nIf you said yes to all of that, then jQuery UI is the answer. Since you said you already use jQuery, all you need to do is download the jQuery UI library and include it and an accompanying theme and you're good to go. jQuery UI is a widget and interaction library built on top of the jQuery JavaScript Library that you can use to build highly interactive web applications.\n\nWith jQuery UI, the developers have completely separated the look and feel of all the widgets from the functionality using a powerful CSS framework that you can even harness outside the scope of the widgets they give you.\n\nWant all of your table headers to be tied to the theme? Just assign the tr the ui-widget-header class and you're done. Now, no matter what theme you use, your tables will always be styled with your theme.\n\nDon't like the available themes?\n\nMake your own with their themeroller tool: <a href=\"http://jqueryui.com/themeroller/\">http://jqueryui.com/themeroller/</a>\nYou can easily download the theme and unzip it to your themes directory, change your stylesheet path and BAM! you've got a brand new theme.\n\nDo you always have to go peruse the internet for an icon set for your apps? jQuery UI does this for you too. Surprised? They provide a nice set of 173 icons for your use. They're all in one image too, so you don't have to download dozens of resources. And each image is referred to by a simple css naming convention. Want a plus button? Just use the class ui-icon and ui-icon-plus. Done and done!\n\nYou can also have themed alert and warning boxes. This helps keep the messages in your app consistent and themeable.\n\nThis might not be the 100% most appropriate thing if you're not making web applications, but jQueryUI has saved us boat-loads of time. Making the decision to standardize all of our widgets and buttons has made our applications 93% more cohesive and structured. For us, it also helps make the line between our the underlying base application framework and the custom parts of the application nearly seamless.\n\nIf you write applications, already use jQuery, and want all kinds of neat features like themes, calendars, accordions, tabs, and dialog windows, then jQuery UI will change your life.\n\nGo here to get started with jQuery UI today! <a href=\"http://jqueryui.com/docs/Getting_Started\">http://jqueryui.com/docs/Getting_Started</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-07T12:42:49.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-09T12:27:08.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5541","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The wonderful part of using the Google loader thing is that if you always want to be using the latest and greatest (trusting Google not to host something broken - which they have been pretty good about) or want to allow minor updates to be included, you have a wide range of version specificity to choose from. This helps when you have 50 different sites and you don't want to or can't roll out 50 minor changes (one to each site's template).","createdDate":"2009-04-09T12:27:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5524","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"that caching argument is compelling enough on its own. thanks for the tip!\n\nalso, thanks for sharing Garrison, I think I'm going to get nice and cozy jquery ui.","createdDate":"2009-04-08T21:06:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5508","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Indeed! So is jQuery and YUI! We stopped hosting those three things ourselves for those exact reasons. Although, we don't use the Google loader thing. We just reference them directly like you did up there.","createdDate":"2009-04-08T13:07:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5505","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Good news, the JQuery UI is available in Google's Ajax Library which means you don't have to host the file yourself.\n\n<a href=\"http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jqueryui/1.7.1/jquery-ui.min.js\">http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jqueryui/1.7.1/jquery-ui.min.js</a>\n\nHere are <a href=\"http://www.ajaxlines.com/ajax/stuff/article/_reasons_why_you_should_let_google_host_jquery_for_you.php\">three reasons you should let Google host JQuery for you</a>.","createdDate":"2009-04-08T13:01:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5501","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Article: Top 10 jQuery Plugins and Resources\"-- <a href=\"http://logicpool.com/archives/123\">http://logicpool.com/archives/123</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-08T12:25:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5384","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"10 skills developers will need in the next 5 years","description":"I found this article extremely interesting and spot-on:\n\n<a href=\"http://blogs.techrepublic.com.com/10things/?p=643\">http://blogs.techrepublic.com.com/10things/?p=643</a>\n\nI love how PHP has made it to one of the \"big three\" wrt programming languages on the web. When I started using PHP3, it was a niche language that most people didn't know nor care about. I am glad to see it getting a little love.\n\n#5 \"Soft Skills\" is definitely something that will be new for a lot of developers, but I think it is very very important. I find myself doing alot more interaction with \"people\" than \"code\". It seems to be a natural progression, as much of what we are doing has a people element to it. Social networking, collaborative tools, etc. To write a good people-driven application, I believe you need good people skills.\n\nRight now, our group is working on #4 (Web Services) and #10 (Mobile Development). I think personally I should work on #6 (Dynamic/Functional Programming) as I have no Python or Ruby skillz. The rest I feel like I have a good understanding on.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T12:11:45.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-09T13:57:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5548","contributorName":"2wyc015nbv7q4","description":"RIAs are here to stay and Adobe has a big push on getting Flex mobilized. The Flash/Flex product lineups are positioned as development IDEs that can compete with the MS platform, check out there Flex in a week online tutorials here: <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/devnet/flex/videotraining/\">http://www.adobe.com/devnet/flex/videotraining/</a>\n\nAll I've heard in the forum groups and the design/tech conference wrapup sessions is mobile, mobile, mobile... so maybe picking up some Apple/Objective C and Android Java SDK is finally in order.\n\nI am surprised MS still pushes VB.net... it is easier to follow implement but I'm not sure how C# couldn't just be the only implementation needed. The .NET development system does a great job of creating the different walls between Design/GUI, Development, DB and backend however you do seem to need to invest in a lot of MS software/implementation. With MS it's easy to believe they'll always be around, but that was the same thinking within Coldfusion back in the day...\n\nThe big issue on retirement, turn-overs and lay offs only compound things in the work and development environment so it's needed to develop good code standards, legacy documentation and version control. These are a definite must... including data archiving and backups.\n\nThis list is great and all but if your company/corporation doesn't support training and professional development it's pretty pointless. You will definitely need to be proactive and take it on yourself to beef up and maintain your skills which can be difficult...","createdDate":"2009-04-09T13:57:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5495","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"That makes a lot more sense than the line in the documentation:\n\n\"NOTE: Pass-by-reference is the only parameter passing mechanism permitted in a method declaration.\"\n\nTo me that means: \"Pass-by-value (another parameter passing mechanism) is not permitted in a method declaration.\" Because I don't trust people not to mess up variables when I pass them into a function, I'm glad to see that I misunderstood and things aren't done that way.","createdDate":"2009-04-07T13:04:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5488","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"No, what it is saying that if you are going to pass something by reference, you have to declare it in the method declaration, and not when you call the method. IE:\n\n// NOT ALLOWED\npublic function doit($frank) {}\n\n$this-&gt;doit(&amp;$somevar);\n\n// ALLOWED\npublic function doit(&amp;$frank){}\n\n$this-&gt;doit($somevar);","createdDate":"2009-04-07T12:42:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5485","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Ah, in my experience it's rare that everyone shares a common IDE, and often I have seen people use something more like a text editor than an IDE for development.\n\nAlso, do you really <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/coding-standard.coding-style.html#coding-standard.coding-style.functions-and-methods.declaration\">declare all method parameters as pass by reference</a>? Or am I misunderstanding the standard?","createdDate":"2009-04-07T12:35:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5483","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Everyone in our group uses Zend Studio (based on Eclipse) to do development, and it allows you to specify line endings. Most every IDE will allow you to do that, regardless of platform you are working on.","createdDate":"2009-04-07T12:28:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5481","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"How do you ensure that everyone is using the <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/coding-standard.php-file-formatting.html#coding-standard.php-file-formatting.line-termination\">correct line endings</a>? I imagine it might be difficult if your programmers are not using Linux or non-Mac BSD.","createdDate":"2009-04-07T12:25:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5444","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"And back on topic, we are using SVN for every project we work on. We definitely don't use all the features, but we tag releases, branch when we need to, etc. We try to do a good job of documenting our commits, but that doesn't always happen as well as I would like it. When we were researching versioning systems, I wrote a few pre-commit scripts for SVN that would compare submitted files with <a href=\"http://pear.php.net/package/PHP_CodeSniffer\">PHP Codesniffer</a>, which worked OK but not great. In the end we just decided on a coding standard and trusted our programmers to do it correctly. We've had no problems with that decision to date.\n\nSince we have recently hired a part-time programmer, having a versioning system in place has been wonderful. They can check out code, make changes, and we can review the changes before being committed in. It is really a great thing to have around. FYI, SVN access is one of the features the web hosting pilot group is looking at wrt integration with cPanel.","createdDate":"2009-04-06T13:29:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5441","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm going to get off on a tangent here, but coding standards, IMO, is one of the FIRST things any programming team/community/project/whatever should agree on. I am a BIG evangelist of coding standards (anyone who has taken any of the PHP classes Garrison and I have taught can tell you that I talk about them at length). I think it is one of the easiest, most beneficial things you can do for your project.\n\nAnd also, when I say coding standard, I'm not talking about the \"Jason-coding-standard\". There is absolutely no reason what-so-ever that one should create their own coding \"standard\". There are plenty to choose from. With PHP, abiding by either the Zend coding standard or the PEAR coding standard would be my recommendation, but it is up to your team. Just decide on one and stick with it.\n\nSome may argue that this is not needed if you are not doing team-based projects. It is my strong opinion that EVERY project should abide by a consistent coding standard from within your group, even if you are the only one who will be messing with the code. Odds are that one day, you won't be there anymore to fix a bug, add a feature, whatever...and someone else is going to have to do it. Knowing you were abiding by a standard will help them out greatly.\n\nOur group abides by the <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/coding-standard.html\">Zend Framework Coding Standard</a>. At this point, I can't look at a piece of code and tell you who wrote it, which IMO is the way it should be. Anyway, my point is that adopting a coding standard is an easy thing to implement that will give you rewards way down the line.","createdDate":"2009-04-06T13:21:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5424","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"He takes it quite a bit further in #9, <b>*assuming*</b> version control is in place (and saying that is not enough). Honestly, he sounds like an Agile zealot, but I agree that in \"group project\" environments that healthy communication and self documenting and well documented code is valuable. However, I'm still of the opinion that not everything is a \"group project\" and pretending it is (by forcing communication) means that you can't trust individuals to do the trivial stuff. Doing #9 \"well\" seems arbitrary particularly because what works \"well\" for some will likely not work \"well\" for others. Large open source projects handle this by laying down the rules in a document like this:\n\n<a href=\"http://drupal.org/coding-standards\">http://drupal.org/coding-standards</a>\n\nI've been slowly incorporating a number of these, because they have some recommendations that I had been on the fence about. I still can't get over the curly brace on the same line style, because it makes it so hard to read. Also, two spaces isn't enough of an indent to differentiate easily (and it takes less time to press the tab button).\n\nSide note: Using whitespace to determine indent level (Python) is a horror story that even Comedy Central won't air after 10 pm.","createdDate":"2009-04-03T13:03:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5409","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"I'd be interested to know how many people on campus are actually doing #9 well. Version control, especially if it enforces code standards and has useful check-in comments can let a new person understand someone else's code/app and not have to rewrite everything.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T15:51:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5401","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"I was just getting read to post this very article.\n\nPersonally I need to work on #4, #6, and #10. Our group is doing a bit of #10. We've got a great lab stats app that looks very clean and condensed on an iPhone or CrackBerry.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T15:36:15.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5358","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Announcing- Drupal UE","description":"FYI\n<a href=\"http://www.lullabot.com/blog/announcing-drupal-ue-usability-edition\">http://www.lullabot.com/blog/announcing-drupal-ue-usability-edition</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-01T22:43:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-12T14:39:57.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5386","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I couldn't find the file upload field. Clearly this isn't going to work for developers. I say we fork it and add some more complex functionality for people who aren't so simple minded.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T12:24:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5381","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"this actually had me going until i clicked on the link at the bottom. Being April 2nd now, i had dropped my defenses, and returned to a state of blissful naivete.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T11:23:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5360","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We should start the campus migration now! Quick, to the Bat Cave!","createdDate":"2009-04-02T01:35:32.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5328","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Internet Radio","description":"Initially I was planning on writing this article on the wonders of last.fm, but instead of limiting ourselves to just one fantastic online free music service, I thought I\u2019d expand in to the general world of Internet Radio. I\u2019m sure there are a veritable plethora of these kinds of services out there, but for the sake of this piece I\u2019ll focus on <a href=\"http://www.last.fm\">last.fm</a>, <a href=\"http://www.pandora.com/\">Pandora</a>, <a href=\"http://pandorafm.real-ity.com\">PandoraFM</a> and <a href=\"http://somafm.com\">somafm</a>. All together these services have my iTunes app growing a very thick layer of dust. And my apologies for veering off of the web developers utilities topic, but hey, this stuff helps web developers stay sane and productive!\n\n<b>Pandora</b>\n\nSo the one name in there that I imagine everyone and their mothers have heard of is <a href=\"http://www.pandora.com/\">Pandora</a>, \u201cthe music genome project\u201d as it was called. Pandora was introduced to me back in 2005 or 2004, and I thought to myself: \u201chow can this be free?\u201d. A website that I can access anywhere, any time that plays a radio station centered on Del tha Funkee Homosapien? Keep in mind that at this period of time services like Napster, Kazaa and Limewire were dead or unreliable or of low quality and most importantly, illegal. Pandora filled the void of free music for the world. I won\u2019t go into the details of how Pandora works or where to find it, because that is how sure I am that everyone has used it. I will offer this tidbit though, for those of you who have smart phones, definitely get a Pandora app setup on your phone/iPod tocuh immediately.\n\n<b>last.fm\n</b> <img style=\"float:right;\" src=\"http://content.screencast.com/users/charlie_morris/folders/Jing/media/fec8b324-9090-4987-8e41-258e1e95b9cb/2009-03-31_1330.png\"/>\nSince being exposed to Pandora I have been introduced to <a href=\"http://www.last.fm\">last.fm</a>, which is a kind of blending of Pandora and Facebook \u2013 a social networking music service (not to be confused with MySpace). The basic way that it works is this: sign up for an account and then listen to music. Sounds familiar I know, but the magic happens when you actually listen to music, last.fm pays attention. Last.fm makes a record of every time you listen to a song; this is called \u201cscrobbling.\u201d You can scrobble from their website, from the last.fm player or your iPod. Over time as you listen to more and more music, last.fm will develop radio stations for you and give you recommendations. There\u2019s a bunch of other stuff that this site can do, such as\u2026\n\n\u2022 tell you how musically compatible you are with your friends.\n\u2022 let you tag your music\n\u2022 give you charts of what you\u2019ve listened to in x amount of time (see below for my overall top listened to artists)\n\u2022 create mix lists\n\n<table class=\"lfmWidgetchart_d81c23a03b0e1cf57d81a2c59401df2d\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:184px;\">\n<tr class=\"lfmHead\"><td><a title=\"cdmorris: Overall Top Artists\" href=\"http://www.last.fm/user/cdmorris/charts?charttype=overall&amp;subtype=artist\" target=\"_blank\"></a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"lfmEmbed\"><td><object type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" data=\"http://cdn.last.fm/widgets/chart/19.swf\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=7,0,0,0\" id=\"lfmEmbed_1779358061\" width=\"184\" height=\"140\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://cdn.last.fm/widgets/chart/19.swf\"></param><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\"type=topartists&amp;user=cdmorris&amp;theme=red&amp;lang=en&amp;widget_id=chart_d81c23a03b0e1cf57d81a2c59401df2d\"></param><param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"never\"></param><param name=\"allowNetworking\" value=\"all\"></param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"quality\" value=\"high\"></param><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"d01f3c\"></param><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"transparent\"></param><param name=\"menu\" value=\"true\"></param></object>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"lfmFoot\"><td><table cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:184px;\">\n<tr><td class=\"lfmConfig\"><a href=\"http://www.last.fm/widgets/?colour=red&amp;chartType=topartists&amp;user=cdmorris&amp;chartFriends=1&amp;from=code&amp;widget=chart\" title=\"Get your own widget\" target=\"_blank\"></a></td>\n<td class=\"lfmView\" style=\"width:74px;\"><a href=\"http://www.last.fm/user/cdmorris\" title=\"View cdmorris's profile\" target=\"_blank\"></a></td>\n<td class=\"lfmPopup\" style=\"width:25px;\"><a href=\"http://www.last.fm/widgets/popup/?colour=red&amp;chartType=topartists&amp;user=cdmorris&amp;chartFriends=1&amp;from=code&amp;widget=chart&amp;resize=1\" title=\"Load this chart in a pop up\" target=\"_blank\"></a></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n\n<b>PandoraFM</b><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/78-20090331_1332.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/79-20090331_1332.png?width=250\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"247\" style=\"float: right;\"/></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://pandorafm.real-ity.com\">PandoraFM</a> is a creation by some group known as Real-ity that combines these two forces (Pandora and LastFM) into one website. You can login and easily switch between Pandora and last.fm, and what\u2019s really nice is that it can scrobble music you\u2019re listening to in Pandora. This is especially nice for me as I\u2019ve slowly become more and more obsessed with scrobbling. In the back of my mind when I\u2019m listening to music, I\u2019m always thinking \u2013 this should be scrobbled! Yes I know, it\u2019s a sickness.\n\n<b>SomaFM</b>\n\nFinally, when I\u2019m bored with Pandora/last.fm, I turn to <a href=\"http://somafm.com\">soma fm</a>, which is truer \u201cInternet radio.\u201d Soma merely has live streaming feeds of music pumping out 24-7. I\u2019m not a fan of all of their channels, but one in particular is great background music for work, it\u2019s called \u201cGroove Salad.\u201d A former co-worker introduced this to me as he would always play it right before a workshop as participants were getting settled into their computers.\n\nSo there you go, a small selection of Internet radio services that make my life a little easier. Do you have anything you'd like to recommend?","createdDate":"2009-03-31T18:06:20.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-03T13:09:07.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5427","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"San Jose has pretty nice weather. The San Francisco Bay Area is an enjoyable place to live if you can afford it.","createdDate":"2009-04-03T13:09:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5415","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"<a href=\"http://www.publicradiofan.com/\">Public Radio Fan</a>\n\nI catch my NPR fix in the evening while working on homework, due to 3 hour west coast delay. It is nice to hear what the weather is like in San Jose. Many of the stations broadcast via shoutcast so I don't have to install more software. I have my favorite streams bookmarked on my iPhone via Tuner.","createdDate":"2009-04-02T18:46:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5351","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I think you're right, I should be donating to Pandora. I will say that I do actually buy music through links that Pandora provides for songs/artists I discover. I wonder if they get any of that action? Also, that Squeezebox device looks slick!","createdDate":"2009-04-01T17:28:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5348","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Pay Pandora if you like them. $3/month is a pretty trivial amount to support a music option whose business model is under constant attack by the RIAA and their legal manipulation to collect broadcast fees from all music everywhere.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.slimdevices.com/pi_boom.html\">http://www.slimdevices.com/pi_boom.html</a> - Squeezebox Boom - internet appliance that lets you stream your internet radio or even your local music files to a portable device in your house. Easy to setup on 802.11 wireless, and once configured, can be controlled from the squeezecenter website from any browser. I leave mine in the living room and control it from my office computer to provide music to the whole house. Speaks Pandora and Last.fm among other formats.","createdDate":"2009-04-01T16:37:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5341","contributorName":"342r1a4s0h1s3","description":"<a href=\"http://kexp.org/\">KEXP</a>","createdDate":"2009-04-01T13:53:18.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5284","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Photoshop Feeds","description":"Just thought i would share some of my favorite photoshop-related feeds, that i have in Google Reader:\n\n<a href=\"http://psdlearning.com/\">http://psdlearning.com/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://pshero.com/\">http://pshero.com/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://photoshopdisasters.blogspot.com/\">http://photoshopdisasters.blogspot.com/</a>\n\nenjoy. and post your own if you have other favorites.","createdDate":"2009-03-30T14:38:52.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-30T14:38:53.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5261","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"CSS forms","description":"FYI\n\n<a href=\"http://www.sitepoint.com/forums/forumdisplay.php?f=53\">http://www.sitepoint.com/forums/forumdisplay.php?f=53</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.sitepoint.com/forums/showthread.php?threadid=604643\">http://www.sitepoint.com/forums/showthread.php?threadid=604643</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-29T22:48:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-31T12:16:23.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:3593","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5306","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It's amusing that the \"Firefox\" bullet looks nothing like the bullet rendered for the \"standard\" list.\n\nAlso, it appears that there is a style (with specificity 1,3) that is overriding the list-style-type: none; for the \"heart\" and \"button\" lists (which have a specificity of 1,1).\n\n#abm ul li, #abm ol ul li {\nlist-style-type:disc;\n}\n\nI imagine that the article predates the site's current look-and-feel.","createdDate":"2009-03-31T12:16:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5301","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Getting Lists to Look the Same in IE and Firefox and Other List Options:\n\n<a href=\"http://webdesign.about.com/od/examples/l/bl_listscss.htm#standard\">http://webdesign.about.com/od/examples/l/bl_listscss.htm#standard</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-31T10:54:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5293","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"1. The point of CSS is to separate the view from the content.\n2. External style sheets improve the performance of page #2 (this is also why Google's AJAX Libraries API is so attractive - because it provides page #2 performance on page #1 for heavy JavaScript libraries).\n3. Not every website is a top 100 website. In fact, most sites have a less than complete build process, so minimizing the number of files that need to be modified makes the web maintainer's life easier (which is still better than saying - sorry the website is down for an hour, I have to rebuild it).\n\nI don't understand these anti-\"CSS Evangelism\" people. It's a best practice for reason #1. This person even acknowledges that it is a best practice (and does the layout of his own blog using it). I can only imagine that they are a troll or trying to play devil's advocate in order to get more page views / street cred. There are some valid points in there about how things should be done to avoid problems, but the rest is a misguided rant about perceived criticisms of table based layouts (I've never even heard of the spacer image one and I've done table based layouts - with CSS encouragement - before). Of course, this is all without mentioning the how tables don't have effective bounding boxes (a single long string of characters will run your entire page off the end of the screen).\n\nEDIT: Ah, it looks like the folks in that thread reached similar conclusions.","createdDate":"2009-03-30T17:05:25.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5192","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"100 Cheat Sheets for Web Development","description":"Ran across this list of cheat sheets...some of which i've seen before, but some i haven't.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.webdesignschoolsguide.com/uncategorized/100-terrific-web-design-cheat-sheets-that-will-save-you-time-money-and-mistakes.html\">http://www.webdesignschoolsguide.com/uncategorized/100-terrific-web-design-cheat-sheets-that-will-save-you-time-money-and-mistakes.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-26T17:51:23.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-26T17:51:23.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5132","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Questions for Search Engine Optimization Presentation","description":"One of the suggestions that came up for our upcoming meeting on <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/web-developers-meeting-search\">April 22 at McKimmon Center (2p.m. to 4 p.m.)</a> and the search engine optimization presentation we'll have is to offer some related questions here to pass along to the presenters to answer. I think it's a great idea, and I would encourage you all to take some time and post some possible questions for the guys at <a href=\"http://thirdpartylabs.com/\">Third Party Labs</a>. We'll pass them along maybe a week or two out from the presentation.\n\nSo, have at it.","createdDate":"2009-03-25T16:30:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5281","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"What limitiations are available for each of the search engine robots to prevent them from using 50% or more of your site bandwidth when they spider your site? We frequently find that Yahoo and Googlebot are particularly bad about re-spidering the same files multiple times in any given week and thus run up our bandwidth usage.","createdDate":"2009-03-30T12:19:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5196","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This cheat sheet (thanks Nick!) appears to answer the title tag question:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.seomoz.org/blog/the-web-developers-seo-cheat-sheet\">http://www.seomoz.org/blog/the-web-developers-seo-cheat-sheet</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-26T19:57:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5183","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"<b>1.</b> I pay quite a bit of attention (in most cases) to my document outline or nested order of h1..h6 tags within my pages, I'm wondering (aside from accessibility) does it make a difference to search bots?\n\n<b>2.</b> It's my understanding that Google (&amp; other search engines) will truncate your html page title in their search results, (displaying as little as 67 characters sometimes) which causes NC State to show up as...\n\"North Carolina State University :: Welcome to North Carolina State...\" . Do search engines completely disregard information in the page title after x-number of characters? Should we be aiming to keep all title tags within a certain length?\n\n<b>3.</b> Should news on a departmental homepage be listed as -h2- News -h2- with all of the headlines that follow as -h3- tags or should it be an unordered list? Is there an advantage to either?","createdDate":"2009-03-26T13:04:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5137","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Why should we trust your information about SEO? (What makes you an expert? For which keywords do you rank well?)","createdDate":"2009-03-25T16:49:04.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5037","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"50 Top and most popular drupal modules (projects)","description":"<a href=\"http://mydrupal.com/50_top_and_most_popular_drupal_modules_projects\">http://mydrupal.com/50_top_and_most_popular_drupal_modules_projects</a>\n\nThought some people might be interested in this post.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T17:01:09.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-24T17:01:09.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5035","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Student Email Task Force Recommends Google Apps for Education","description":"The full report can be found here: <a href=\"http://oit.ncsu.edu/student-email-initiative/report\">http://oit.ncsu.edu/student-email-initiative/report</a>\n\n\nFor those lazy individuals who won't click through, the executive summary is as follows:\n\n<b>Task Force Charge</b>\n\u2022 Evaluate current student email services\n\u2022 Determine best path for supporting current and future student needs\n\u2022 Consider closely-related IT services and possible improvements\n\u2022 Identify ways to reduce costs and improve services\n<b>Options Evaluated</b>\n\u2022 Enhancement of existing Cyrus system\n\u2022 Forward-only service\n\u2022 Outsourcing to Zimbra (a Yahoo company)\n\u2022 Outsourcing to Microsoft\n\u2022 Outsourcing to Google\n<b>Recommendations</b>\n\u2022 Migrate student email services to Google Apps Education Edition.\no Email services would be improved\no Cost savings of at least $60,800 per year are anticipated if student email is hosted offsite by Google. Additional savings could eventually be achieved if campus reduced www4 file space and had students use Google Sites.\no Additional tools would be available to students with little if any additional support needed\no Support from the vendor of the service would be acceptable\no Some administrative/support functionality (like detailed logs and multiple tools) would be lost, but is acceptable\n\u2022 Create an implementation team to continue working on the initiative that includes key OIT staff and significant representation from the current task force.\no More extensive piloting is needed.\no There are many policy and process issues needing further consideration as part of an implementation process.\no Continuing the communication with students and other campus stakeholders is critical.\no Extension of a migration to Google Apps Education Edition to the faculty/staff population should be considered and would result in significant cost savings.\n\n\nI was a member of the task force, and fully believe that our recommendation to move to Google Apps for Education is not only the right move for financial reasons, but also logistical and technical reasons too. I am just putting this out to broaden the announcement, and also find out what people think about the report, the recommendation or anything in between.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T16:49:51.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-24T17:20:30.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5039","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I think it's brilliant and the best thing we could do. Now if only faculty and staff we're on Google Apps too, then we'd be on top of it.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T17:20:30.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5033","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"NCSU Majors Page, 3 Years Since Last Update","description":"I was trying to find a 3 letter curriculum code for a student today and I didn't know what it was off the top of my head, so I decided to Google for it.\n\n<span style=\"color:#a00;\">My google search for \"ncsu majors\" brought me to this page:</span>\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/majors-careers/\">NC State Majors and Careers</a> (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/majors-careers/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/majors-careers/</a>)\n\nThe site actually spells out what each of the University's Majors are, the degree concentrations, minors, career paths, estimated salaries etc. But the footer on each of these pages claims <b>the site was last updated in June 2006</b>. :-( I wonder if this is just an oversight (maybe someone has just forgotten to change the footer)? Or worse... our old outdated pages aren't being cleaned up and search engines are delivering our users to answers that may not be accurate anymore.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T16:29:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-09T13:21:06.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5656","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I got this back from <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/oasis/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/oasis/</a>, when I inquired:\n\nDr. McDaniel,\nI have been asked to let you know that the dates on the Majors pages (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/majors-careers/do_with_major_in/searchresults.php?type=college&amp;id=4\">http://www.ncsu.edu/majors-careers/do_with_major_in/searchresults.p...</a>) have been changed to reflect when they were last changed/modified--some of them like the front page hasn't changed so the date remains. If any of the content for the College of Engineering individual majors needs to be changed please let me know and I will correct it. Otherwise I will contact the Coordinators of Advising in late May/early June to request that they review their majors to make certain that the information is accurate.\n\nRegards,\nMartha Wicker\nAcademic Adviser\nOASIS","createdDate":"2009-04-14T16:15:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5296","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Something like the following?\n\nRedirectMatch 301 /majors-careers/(.*) <a href=\"http://admissions.ncsu.edu/have-major/\">http://admissions.ncsu.edu/have-major/</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-30T17:11:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5286","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"You missed one possibility: no changes in majors, concentrations or minors have occurred in the last three years. Consider this:\n\n--only after we've been through three rounds of budget cuts did the <a href=\"http://www.news14.com/content/local_news/charlotte/606621/unc-system-stops-select-degree-programs/Default.aspx?RegionCookie=30\">Board of Governors decide to cut 70 \"low productivity\" degree programs</a>\n--the <a href=\"http://www.ssme.ncsu.edu/\">Service Science, Management and Engineering</a> program has been trying to get off the ground here since before their website went up in October 2006\n\nIt should be easy to see that it can be difficult to both start and stop degree programs. However, in this case, your second assertion is correct. The page you saw has not been cleaned up since the launch of the new NCSU web design. We should hope the search engines would deliver for this info is the new \"<a href=\"http://admissions.ncsu.edu/have-major/\">Do You Have My Major?</a>\" page. Which brings me to my own pertinent question--why don't we clean up old sites with proper redirects and user-oriented explanations of changes?","createdDate":"2009-03-30T15:40:26.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5024","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Twitter: Best Thing Ever (or at least it can be)","description":"<a href=\"http://www.twitter.com\">Twitter</a> is your customized tour of the Web led by friends, colleagues, thought leaders, marketers and others. All in 140 characters or less.\n\n140 on the nose. Score.\n\nMore specifically, Twitter is a web service that facilitates \"microblogging,\" or communicating through 140-character posts or \"tweets.\" Users create short posts as frequently as they like, often embdding links, usually by taking advantage of any one of a dozen or so URL shortening tools (<a href=\"http://is.gd\">is.gd</a>, <a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/\">tinyurl</a>, etc.) to keep the overall character count low. Posts then appear as a timeline, or list of updates, with the most recent first. Twitter users can choose to \"follow\" other tweeters and view the progressive collection of all their updates in a \"friends\" timeline. Tweets can be protected from view and only viewable to those to whom you grant permission, or wide open to the world allowing anyone to follow you or view your tweets. Users can essentially talk back and forth via twitter using the simple @username (the username is, well, the username of the individual to whom you wish to reply) to direct tweets at others. Twitter keeps track of all the tweets directed at you in the \"@replies\" timeline. Twitter also allows users to create channels or trends on the fly using the # character (#besthingever). The result is millions of short snippets of content in every conceivable direction and on every conceivable topic. Each user can aggregate a customized timeline of Twitter conent however he or she likes by choosing carefully (or indiscriminately) who to follow.\n\nMy friends timeline, which updates every three minutes in footer of my Firefox window courtesy of the <a href=\"http://twitterfox.net/\">TwitterFox plugin</a>, is currently full of tweets from co-workers at this and previous jobs, industry personalities and thought leaders, people I've met at conferences, news updates, Amazon Goldbox Deals, video game journalists and a handful of random people who often tweet about stuff I like. On any given day, the tweets from this collection of people will provide me breaking news in the industries of my choosing, new book recommendations, pithy music and movie reviews, web development tips and tricks, meeting, lecture and event summaries as they happen, great online bargains, links to new web development technologies and techniques, hilarious photos and YouTube videos, design or development advice, recommendations on just about anything, and, sadly, a daily account of what a few people I know eat for lunch and/or dinner and an account of the precise moment they arrive at and leave from work. You know who you are.\n\nLike most social networking and social media technologies, the value of Twitter is in the application of the application. At first I didn't get it. Twitter, at least for many, boils down to constant status updates. Really? Why would anyone assume I'm interested in their perpetual whereabouts, uninteresting cuisine choices and other inane commentary (LOLZ OMG 4REELZ @article). On the surface, there might not seem to be much more than the absurdly narcissistic Twitter employed by the overly-zealous, do-it-cause-everyone-else-is-doing-it, I-heart-everything-in-my-Web-2.0-tag-cloud-even-if-I-can't-figure-out-where-the-value-lies-but-who-cares-at-least-I-can-say-I-do-it Twitter.\n\nBut then I tried it and discovered that, in the right context and with the right application, Twitter might be the Best Thing Ever.\n\nConceptually, Twitter is much like an RSS feed, but Twitter feeds are personal, editorial, and often independent of any specific site or content source. More and more content-rich sites leverage Twitter to tease and link to their own content, providing yet another entry point for users. It works like word of mouth for the Internet.\n\nMuch like blogging, sifting through the mass of inane, uselss Twitter chatter is critical for the application to have any value. Fortunately, search.twitter.com makes this easier, as do any number of Twitter search tools and Twitter feed collection sites (like <a href=\"http://cursebird.com/\">cursebird</a>, a site that displays all the Tweets that contain curse words). Another invaluable way to build a robust list of Tweeters to follow is through the \"Following\" lists on each users page. Often you'll find users with similar interests worthy of adding to your twitter timeline. Much like the value of any particular blog, the value of a particular Twitter user's contributions stem from the content creators' authority, expertise and personality.\n\nThe web-based Twitter interface couldn't be much more simple. An empty text block in response to the perpetual question \"What are you doing right now\" paired with the remaining character counter sit atop the list of recent posts from everyone you choose to follow. Pages can be customized in look and feel to some extent, though utility reigns supreme on Twitter.com.\n\nTwitter offers a great way to keep your finger on the pulse of the Web, as parsed by your own, personally-assembled Internet editorial board. For all the meaningless proclamations of \"grilled chicken for dinner then bed,\" there are a handful of valuable, relevant, interesting and erudite tweets. And the resulting collection of content is profound.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T15:45:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-14T20:06:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5681","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Hmmmmm... Someone should tell Marc he should probably follow at least one person, so his followed/follower ratio would be better than <a href=\"http://twitter.com/THE_REAL_SHAQ\">Shaq's</a> 1,304 to 1 (as of this posting) might be incredibly asymmetric - but that #DIVIDE BY ZERO! exception that keeps getting thrown is symbolic to me (and yes I read the interview where he spoke to this, and didn't agree with it anymore then than I do now).","createdDate":"2009-04-15T02:26:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5641","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Is it only \"add your name\"? I don't Twitter, but I'm surprised our new head of OIT is not listed.","createdDate":"2009-04-14T12:12:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5626","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"It might be good if we had a list on NCSU based twitterers. Not sure if anyone has done that - so I created a page on Wolf Wikis @ <a href=\"http://wikis.lib.ncsu.edu/index.php/Twitter_%40_NCSU\">http://wikis.lib.ncsu.edu/index.php/Twitter_%40_NCSU</a>\n\nAdd your name so we can get a good list going - or if you know of another one let me know.","createdDate":"2009-04-13T14:22:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5152","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I think my all-time favorite day in twitter was the day we <a href=\"http://rambleon.org/2008/11/19/because-meat-loaf-and-twitter-are-like-peas-and-carrots/\">group-tweeted a bunch of geek re-titles of MeatLoaf songs</a>.\n\nYou probably had to be there though :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-25T22:13:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5145","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Nothing new here. Twitter == ways for me to keep up with different technologies, tech-people, as well as family and friends.\n\n@usaussie == me\n\n@nprnews == NPR News...duh\n@ricksanchezcnn == one of the most avid and collaborative twitterers in the media, even if you dont like CNN\n@movie_recipes == if you like movies and awesome writing ;-)\n@drupalcon == Drupal Conference...dont know what will happen now that DC is over, but they were very good about keeping people up to date about what was happening at the conference. I expect this to continue at future DrupalCons\n@KevinRuddPM == Prime Minister of Australia...its required for me to follow him :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-25T17:17:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5134","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"something im curious about is how does twitter make money? i've read a few articles that talk about the fact that no one is real interested in buying Twitter (Google, MS, Yahoo, etc) because there is no way of profiting (yet) from Twitter, no revenue stream. at some point I'm betting that ads will become a necessary evil of Twitter, maybe at worst.. an hourly message from Coca-Cola or Wal-Mart... Or maybe there will be a paid versus unpaid account on Twitter (like Flickr).\n\nAnyways, I also am using TweetDeck now, it's pretty nice, I like it more than Twirhl, mainly because I can now group my Twitter buddies into separate groups and when I'm notified of new Tweets I can find out from what group it comes from before going to look at it.\n\n@cdmo = me\n\n<a href=\"http://www.viralvideochart.com/dailymotion/quottwouble_with_twitterquot_soustitreacute?id=x8puil\">some of us may need to step away from the Twitter every once in a while...</a> just a bit of humor re:the twitterverse :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-25T16:36:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5129","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"While I am a Twitter-er I can understand the point of view that Twitter is useless ramblings from people who have too much to say to people who are out there not paying attention anyway (for a humorous expansion on this idea check out the \"Twouble with Twitter\": <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PN2HAroA12w\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PN2HAroA12w</a>).\n\nThat being said, everyday I find benefit in Twitter. It may be a new website or tool I didn't know about. Maybe it's hearing from friends of family far away. I enjoy (some of) the ramblings of friends and the minor celebrities I follow and I'm fascinated by how a simple statement by one person can become a national (and perhaps eventually global) conversation.\n\nPeople I follow:\n<b>michaelian black</b> : Michael Ian Black (sometimes a little too verbose, but funny)\n<b>twitterFon</b>: Twitter updates for the iPhone app of the same name (there are a number of iPhone Twitter apps but TwitterFon is my favorite)\n<b>macrumors</b>: <a href=\"http://www.macrumors.com/\">http://www.macrumors.com/</a>\n<b>boxee</b>: Updates about the social networking media center application, <a href=\"http://www.boxee.tv/\">http://www.boxee.tv/</a>\n<b>raleighnews</b>: Raleigh News\n<b>dhstatus</b>: If you have sites on Dreamhost servers this posts when one of their servers are having issues. I wish more webhosts would do this actually.\n\nAnd me: @ncsumarit","createdDate":"2009-03-25T14:37:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5112","contributorName":"bethanyvsmith","description":"I have to say that Twitter has totally changed the way I \"do business\" and the way I keep up with other tech people in education. There are a few tools that have helped me build my PLN in Twitter.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.tweetdeck.com/beta/\">Tweet Deck</a> is great for keeping track of Twitter on your machine.\n\n<a href=\"http://mrtweet.com/\">Mr. Tweet</a> is great for finding who you should follow based on your current list of friends\n\nHere is a list of the <a href=\"http://www.thewebpitch.com/twitter/top-100-twitter-tools/\">Top 100 tools</a> for using Twitter.\n\nHappy Tweeting!\n@bethanyvsmith","createdDate":"2009-03-25T13:24:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5055","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"@rainnwilson - Dwight from The Office\n@THE_REAL_SHAQ - Shaq...cause hes funny\n@jason_austin - By far the most awesome twitterer around!","createdDate":"2009-03-24T19:11:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5042","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Be sure to leave some suggestions for great Twitterers to follow if you have them. I'll go first:\n\nzeldman (Jeffery Zeldman)\nRaleighNews (self explanatory)\nmeyerweb (Eric Meyer)\n\nor, search at wefollow.com","createdDate":"2009-03-24T17:20:58.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5022","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"OIT Budget Reduction Strategies","description":"This has been talked about a lot on TWW, in AITD, and within OIT. I know most of the people on here are not in OIT, so I would like to see what people are thinking about the possible cost reduction strategies that Dr. Hoit is exploring. Also, we have great discussions on here that are usually well put together and thought out, so I was curious of your thoughts.\n\n======================================\n\n1) Move all faculty and staff e-mail to a single centralized\nsystem. This involves discontinuing all other campus email systems. It\nalso assumes that Cyrus is discontinued and student email is moved to an\noutsourced platform. The final step is to determine the future best\nplatform for faculty and staff email including possible outsourcing.\n\n2) Require/expect students to have laptop computers and then\ndecommission at least 50% of the computer lab seats campus wide. This\nchange assumes that many of the required services can be provided\nthrough application delivery tools, license servers, student installed\nsoftware, open source and many other options. Specialized computer labs\nthat are still required for software or activities that cannot be\ndelivered through the above mechanisms would still remain.\n\n3) Unify web hosting and related services with a migration to\ncontent managed systems. This would move many/most of the websites to a\ncontent managed environment. Special websites that cannot be moved\ncould have an exemption. Web hosting for these environments at\ncompetitive pricing would be used. There is already a pilot going on to\nlook at environments that might allow this type of service.\n\n4) Move all staff and lab computer systems to a managed desktop\nenvironment \u2013 and move the appropriate staff systems to a virtual\ndesktop environment. Some of the colleges already use a managed desktop\nin which most of the functions are automated and it has reduced support\ncalls by 80%. This type of improvement needs to be shared throughout\nthe campus. In addition, many of the current desktops do not need the\ncomputational power of a standalone machine and desktop virtualization\ncan potentially save even more.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T15:42:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-10T15:42:59.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5597","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"One last point about laptop initiatives.\n\nThe assumption is that students will carry their laptops with them all day, eliminating the need for labs.\n\nThis is an incorrect assumption. There is plenty of data to support this. In fact, some faculty do not want students using their laptops in class.\n\n--hal","createdDate":"2009-04-10T15:42:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5346","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"I think you have some good points about the issue of whether a laptop requirement is needed, particularly regarding the issue of support.\n\nAs we've talked internally within CHASS about the possibility of eliminating labs, we realize that we would likely have to cut some instructional labs as part of the lab reduction process. If we do that, some faculty feel that a student laptop requirement is necessary because it would be the only way we could be assured of students actually having a laptop, which would be required as part of the instruction of the course. As an example, we had a couple of student-owned computing pilot sections of courses this semester that listed a laptop requirement as part of enrollment in the course. On the first day, we found over a dozen students who didn't own a laptop and so had to be relocated to other sections of the course.","createdDate":"2009-04-01T16:21:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5344","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"I have been told that we pay as much as $32.00 a month, but that number may be incorrect. It is certainly much more than $18.00 a month. I picked the number $25.00 out of thin air -- if we made it $20.00 a month, that is $12.00 less, and at $20.00, my voice plan gets bumped to a plan that I feel will easily cover the amount of phone traffic that I get. And on top of that, I get nation-wide calling -- no additional long-distance fees that OIT has to pay.\n\nBut it is not just the month-to-month costs. Not only do we pay for voice mail, there is a recurring cost that OIT pays for the voice mail system itself that everyone uses. There is the phone service itself -- part of the money goes to our operation of our campus phone system, part of it goes to the phone company, so there is savings there immediately.\n\nThere is equipment costs. The phone in your office. The infrastructure to run a phone system (equipment and people). The ongoing expense of maintaining and expanding this system to support more customers. Migration to VOIP. Do we want to spend money migrating to another wired phone service when the trend outside the university (unless you are in a dorm) is to \"cut the cord\" and do away with land lines? It is time for us to leapfrog.\n\nWe pay for people to have a Blackberry for messaging. Many of these people own another smart phone (iphone, PocketPC) that is capable of this. It is crazy for us to pay for a device that does the same thing that the user already has. Plus, it is just one more thing to carry.\n\nThe biggest issue with my scenario is segregation of phone numbers. We do not want clients calling on our \"real\" cell number. They should call our office number, which gets routed to our cell. This is to protect our privacy and downtime, but also to make sure that we are able to separate phone calls that are work related from those that are personal. One potential reason for this is that our work voice calls (and voice mail) may be considered public record.\n\nWe can re-route phone calls with our existing system, so it is not entirely necessary for us to migrate to Google Voice, but obviously it has features our existing voice mail system does not have -- but further than that -- it immediately saves us money, even for those that choose to keep their office phone.\n\nI don't think anyone has to lose their job. There are plenty of other opportunities for us to pursue. Off the top of my head, I would pick \"rich telephony\" -- video/web conferencing with phone/skype etc linkage as a cost-recovery service. Instead of leasing phones, we can lease things like Polycom units, multiple participant conferences (video and phone), etc. I expect demand for these services to increase as travel budgets evaporate. Many other campuses have offered these services for a while now. There is a working group on campus (which I am a member of) that is looking at these issues right now. We can route some of our cost savings into these new services, and recoup our costs. Instead of a department buying a Polycom that sits idle, they can can lease one for the time that they need it. It saves the university money, and provides a needed service.","createdDate":"2009-04-01T14:47:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5326","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'm new around here, so maybe I'm not getting the cost savings of the cell phone idea. Do we pay outside of the institution for phones now? I mean...i love the idea of getting a stipend for a cell phone instead, but I'm trying to figure out the cost savings. Please mister...can I have some more information..\n\nIf we are paying out of the institution more than $25 per month for a basic land line, that seems a little nuts. In little ol' Banner Elk, a place with one-telephony provider, the cost of a landline was $18, and that included all the bells and whistles (voicemail, caller id, call waiting, call forwarding etc). You're saying that NCSU doesn't get a better bulk rate than that? Surely i'm missing something.","createdDate":"2009-03-31T17:47:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5324","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I love the idea of getting rid of office phones. Mine only rings when someone is looking for someone who previously had my number.","createdDate":"2009-03-31T17:28:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5321","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"#2: Requiring all students to own laptops is like requiring all students to breathe air. Our own data shows that laptop ownership is on a sharp incline. We don't need to require students to do something that they are already doing. It is unlikely to save us much money, and may actually cost us money. UNC-Chapel Hill stopped their Carolina Computing Initiative for several reasons -- one key one is that cost of support went up. They are simply part of a trend; many schools that had laptop initiatives have abandoned them. If we make laptop ownership a requirement, it is assumed then that we are going to support those laptops. Maybe we can get the money from ETF, or perhaps we can just outsource support and make students pay for it. I can see the ed piece in the Technician now.\n\nClosing some Unity labs and substituting it with a laptop initiative has no dependency -- one does not imply the other. If we are going to close labs, the only savings will come from closing ALL Unity labs and relying on Colleges own computing facilities, and even then, the cost savings will take 2-3 years to filter through (replacement cycle for lab machines being the key).\n\nOne suggestion I have is allowing people to get rid of their office phone, give them a stipend for their cell phone ($25.00 a month, still cheaper than having a land line in their office). It saves equipment, resources, people and defers the need for expansion. We may not need to transition to VOIP at all. The other part of this proposal is to move to Google Voice, which allows us to replace our existing voice mail system, and to re-route calls to our cell phone without having to give clients our cell number.\n\n--hal","createdDate":"2009-03-31T17:15:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5232","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"The original #3, where we look into cpanel and outsourcing as ways to provide better web services, is not my idea. Credit where it is due, I first heard this idea from the Jason/Garrison/Everette group on campus, and we've all been working together to explore the options. In my humble opinion, it is NOT a cost saving option. The cheapest thing we could do is continue to offer a minimum of PHP service and let people explore the various add-on packages at their leisure. That is not good customer service on our part (as per the very vocal comments on TWW to that effect) and so we need to explore new options to get back into the program, far far more than we need to do this to save money.\n\nCost savings will come to play if/when campus adopts us as a hosting provider instead of making their own way. That will not happen is we cannot offer the specific packages that each and every department wants to use. Cpanel is a big step in that direction, in that is covers and simplifies most major PHP applications. It completely ignores the Cold Fusion users, and the ASP/IIS users. Much as I'd love to tell those folks they're doing it wrong (*grin*) that's not my call to make.\n\nWhat TWW fails to grasp is any sense of scale. It is no more efficient or cost-effective for us (OIT) to run 25 different one-off systems, than it is for 25 departments to run their own one-off systems. We can only develop an efficiency by getting people into the same system and figuring out how to support what they do within that system. Cpanel itself is easy. 25 different CMS-like packages within cpanel... is going to mean 25 different ways of running your websites. It is our hope that we can find a way to make this happen, but we know very well that support for the individual packages is going to be problematic. If you as departments still need to keep your FTE's worth of web support to maintain your packages with minimal help from us, then there's less cost savings there than the 50ft view seems to suggest. Sure, we can consolidate the hardware and keep it off your balance sheets, but you'll still be paying experts to maintain the sites on that hardware. Since I'm speaking mostly to those people employed in that capacity, I imagine this is good news. :-)\n\nAs for the ipsCA certificates... yes, lets move forward. It will take us the better part of a year to roll through all the certs as they expire. The bigger concern is to make sure the keepers of the Thawte contract are also planning for this move, so that it doesn't get purchased again when the contract renewal is due.\n\nEmail for faculty... this is my semi-informed opinion: Groupwise is going to fail. I cannot elaborate without mudslinging, so I'll just leave it at that. We need to stop NOW and go ahead and move all of campus, not just the students, to gmail. Cyrus mail can continue to support all of campus, as it has for many years. But in that regard, it's just like our web services... a minimum of service that no longer meets everyone's needs. I have 2 personal gmail accounts now and they work very well. I tried the student email pilot on gmail and msmail, and recommended to the committee that gmail was the clearly superior solution. As for cost savings... back at the time GW was the chosen solution, the proposal was expected to cost on the order of $1Mil plus maintenance. Envelope calculations in our suite put the gmail cost for faculty around $80,000, which is the amount needed to cover state-mandated backups. That's a 90% savings. There's still an overhead for campus-run relays that may or may not factor into both sides of the argument.\n\nOne last pot-shot... Boise State was one of the poster children for the Groupwise solution back when it was proposed. They have already seen the light and started their migration to gmail/Google Apps. <a href=\"http://helpdesk.boisestate.edu/email/groupwise/index.shtml\">http://helpdesk.boisestate.edu/email/groupwise/index.shtml</a>. I say we need to skip the middle step and move ahead to the conclusion without inflicting the GW environment on everyone in between. <a href=\"http://helpdesk.boisestate.edu/email/googleapps/\">http://helpdesk.boisestate.edu/email/googleapps/</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-27T15:42:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5226","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"This is my personal philosophy, and by no means a slight or judgment on anyone's ability to manage a service effectively.\n\nAs far as the email strategy goes, the way i think about it is this.... it's a utility. It is as necessary to the operations of this campus as electricity. In my mind, we should not be spending exorbitant amounts of money and time just to keep the email system running. It takes a lot of resources to just have it running effectively, including the life-cycling of equipment, the creation, maintenance and checking of day-to-day processes, support, and any other activities related to just keeping the email system switched on.\n\nWe are not in the business of creating our own electricity, because it is not cost-effective to do so. We take the electricity provided to us, and build efficient operations based on that platform. Email, to me, can now work on the same principle. We should leverage the ability of a provider (in this case, Google), to supply the base utility to us for a lower price than what we can provide in-house. What that allows us to do, is build upon that platform to better meet the needs of current and future projects.\n\nThe thing that disappoints me about the outsourcing of faculty and staff discussion, is that it is always framed in terms of money saved. The part that is lost or overlooked, and to me is the most important, is the improved set of tools Google can offer, over what we can provide in-house. Yes, money can be saved, and yes, that is very important in the current climate. But money is just one factor.\n\nEven if outsourcing only saved a relatively small amount of money going out the door per year (ie: licensing costs), it would save much more in intangible funds &amp; time, because we could have our best people working on adding services to what google offers, rather than just trying to keep the service switched on. If we want to become a leader and a demonstrator of innovation, then we need to allow our people the time to innovate. The great fact though, is that it does save a tremendous amount of money, as long as you consider ALL costs associated with it (licensing, hardware, software, backups, related-salaries, dedicated support personnel, related committee time, help desk support calls, customer satisfaction, , etc, etc, etc). If anyone can prove that keeping email in-house is as cost-effective as outsourcing to a competent provider and building on top their product, I'd love to see those numbers.\n\nHow about we trust somebody else keep the lights on for us? We can develop some pretty nice things when we're not running to the power meter and every light switch every waking moment, just to make sure it's still working.","createdDate":"2009-03-27T13:33:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5224","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"\"People look at me like I'm stupid when I tell them I don't use MS Office products any more (at all).\"\n\nThat still scares me a little. I remember trying to explain Linux at a club expo, and I ended up having to say \"You know Microsoft Windows? I use Linux instead.\", to try and get the idea across.\n\nI haven't used a commercial Microsoft product (other than for cross-application testing) in six years (which is why I cringed when you said ASP and ColdFusion -- yes I know ColdFusion isn't a Microsoft product, but it's not any better). I feel that we are already in a free software capable world, and that the perceived gaps in functionality are related to either bloated silliness or a lack of widespread adoption (which is a chicken-or-egg problem).","createdDate":"2009-03-27T12:29:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5181","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I don't find that my ideas are ignored, but that may be because I've only been here since August. I think that in an organization as large as we are (both as OIT and NCSU as a whole), it just takes a little more patience before things take root and grow. To me, the downfall of a large organization is that there are just a few more hoops to jump through, and bridges to build before you can implement new ideas. The benefit however, is that if your idea is a good one..IF......then there will undoubtedly be more people that support the idea and can get behind it. I can hear you saying that there are also more people to go against it...and that's true...but that's where leadership can step in and get everyone moving in a common direction.\n\nThe key to all of this is good decision making. If you have a good decision or solution, then its easy to get people to support it. If you make a bad decision, then its vitally important to the organization that you address it head on. Whether that is to explain why it was a necessary evil, or whether it is to quit throwing good resources after bad ones already spent.\n\nSo..no..i don't feel like good ideas meet resistance...I feel like we have to be aware of a process that works:\n\n1. come up with an idea\n2. vet the idea amongst colleagues, both supportive and not\n3. vet the idea with dissimilar audiences..ie: kids will say the darndest things\n4. gather support from key stakeholders\n5. present the idea to decision makers\n6. work hard to make sure the idea is given the best chance to succeed AND be willing to accept that your idea may not be a good one.\n7. implement, or move on to the next idea","createdDate":"2009-03-26T11:49:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5167","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"To be honest, I have no idea. But I'd be perfectly willing to give figuring it out a try rather than continue on with the same broken setup forever.","createdDate":"2009-03-26T04:17:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5165","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Lest I be remiss - this kind of stuff is the seed for innovation. (I'm not saying that these are innovative necessarily, but smart, common sense, strategies that cut against the grain of \"it's the way it's always been done\" certainly is a seed for innovation. #2 might go in combination with procurement practices that encourages or mandates purchases equipment - and operating systems - that conform to more stringent energy saver standards. Good luck with seeing much progress on #3 - but I'd love to be pleasantly surprised ;-)\n\nLet me guess, y'all find that some of your ideas meet a fair amount of resistance don't you? Get ignored a fair amount? (don't answer that :-).","createdDate":"2009-03-26T03:44:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5163","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I am thoroughly anti-consolidation mainly along the continued observation that large organizations - run as large bureaucratic organizations - are \"where innovation goes to die\" and the line item cost savings are not worth - not in Education/Research settings - the opportunity cost impact to innovation. I won't deny that there are cost savings associated with \"economies of scale\" - but I'd offer they only exist in well-defined and constrained commodity service areas (networking, storage, most procurement, given good/smart/out-of-the-box thinkers and negotiators in procurement, and business computing) - but not within support, not within educational+technology initiatives, not within research - those don't really fit well with commodity/scale solutions - they benefit more from open access, open collaboration among diverse parties. Or sometimes just the sheer genius and sweat of one or two dedicated, hard-working, drivers working directly on individualized problems. There are certainly innovative teams in large organizations, but they usually operative in spite of, not because of, the organizational structure.\n\nHere's an alternative idea - split any \"organization\" larger than say, I don't know, 8 people. Remove any hierarchical reporting structures beyond that. Identify some connectors - which aren't necessarily, and I'd argue, shouldn't be, the managers, of those 8 people, to bridge those teams and make sure they rotate out now and then. Fan the teams out into departments to solve local departmental problems. Utilize every third-party social networking tool known to us to connect the various teams - and let them both compete and collaborate - and provide opportunities for team members to move among teams. Give some teams dominion over a very few common infrastructure items (like the network we have today) - data centers (where you open the data centers to all these teams) - provide some common procurement services - but push the rest of those teams down into departments across campus. The model will be flawed, certainly, and I can make all kinds of arguments about service duplication, service inconsistency, etc. But I'll bet you that the decentralized, small team-without-hiearchical-organization model will be cheaper, more innovative, and far more efficient than \"consolidation\" and creating the management hierarchies \"necessary\" (and I quote that with the most sarcastically pantomimed air quotes that I possibly can) in larger organizations.","createdDate":"2009-03-26T02:54:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5160","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I, for one, would find it highly entertaining if you would elaborate on \"done right\" :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-26T02:25:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5158","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"I'm not sure that I think these four possibilities encompass all of what college and departmental level units do. Within CHASS, we focus on some discipline specific computing and technology needs, and being able to do a bit more of that has been one of the drivers for trying to consolidate some of our infrastructure in to what's provided elsewhere (e.g. migrating our email system in to whatever is provided centrally, making use of AFS for file storage rather than running our own file servers, etc.).","createdDate":"2009-03-26T01:16:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5155","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"Let me ask a stupid question (I know, nothing ever stopped me before):\n\nIf there are proposals to consolidate web services, email, research computing, lab/staff environments, remote access to applications, and storage.... What exactly would be left for college/departmental IT staff to do? Desktop support? And exactly where is OIT gonna get the fleet of people to do all this stuff \"centrally\" in addition to the Strategic Operations Plan initiatives?\n\nIf on the budget proposals you choose d) All of the above, you are talking about consolidating alot of IT on campus. Not just servers and services, but people too. I personally don't have a problem with that. I'm solidly in the pro-consolidation camp, assuming its done right and not like the OIT reorg. But IF consolidation at that scale is a goal, it needs to be stated openly and discussed.","createdDate":"2009-03-26T00:57:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5148","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"There was also a fifth strategy of consolidating all research computing clusters that exist around campus in to the OIT-HPC unit supported clusters.","createdDate":"2009-03-25T17:18:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5140","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Yesterday, a few of us in OIT sent some suggestions to Dr Hoit detailing some budget saving strategies. I figured i would post them here to see what other people think. For some of them, we dont need to wait for a top-down directive...we can implement them ourselves while we wait to see what the overall vision will be. It's never too early to start saving money.\n\nHere is the bulk of the email sent to Dr Hoit\n\n<b>1. Convert all SSL certificates (where possible) to ipsCA free Educational SSL Certificates</b>\n<b>Suggested by:</b> Nick Young, nick_young@ncsu.edu\n<b>Potential Implementation Cost:</b> $0 (Time for systems administrators to install new certificates, but this is equal to the time they would be taking to renew existing paid certificates)\n<b>Potential Savings:</b> Estimated $10K-$20K per year\n<b>Implementation time-line:</b> Immediately, or as soon as existing certificates expire\n<b>Description:</b> ipsCA provides free SSL certificates for educational domains (*.edu) on a two year basis. At the end of each two year period, the certificates must be renewed. The renewal is free as well, providing a method of securing websites for free in perpetuity. There are currently around 100-200 certificates using Thawte certificates that cost approximately $100 per certificate year. Charles Brabec has tested the ipsCA certificates and posted his findings to the NCSU Web Developers Ning Website (<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/free-ssl-certificates-for-edu\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/free-ssl-certificates-for-edu</a>). His conclusion was that the ipsCA certificates are a viable alternative for securing websites, and can be implemented immediately. There are some policy issues that would need to be worked out, such as who the domain contacts would be for certificate approvals (the setup process requires a domain administrator to verify the request is valid), but other than that this could be implemented as each Thawte certificate comes up for renewal.\n\n<b>2. Power Saving Settings on Lab &amp; Office Machines</b>\n<b>Suggested by:</b> Nick Young, nick_young@ncsu.edu, Jen Riehle, jen_riehle@ncsu.edu\n<b>Potential Implementation Cost:</b> $0 (Time to decide upon a power saving utility, and implementation schedule)\n<b>Potential Savings:</b> 56% reduction of power use per computer, depending on a policy of configured power settings\n<b>Implementation time-line:</b> Immediately, or as soon as software can be approved and pushed out\n<b>Description:</b> For many employees there is no need to leave their computers on at the end of the day. The only reasons to leave machines on at night would be for scheduled processes to occur, or for telecommuting purposes.\n\nScheduled Processes: If scheduled processes (antivirus, spyware scans, backups) are the sole reason for leaving machines on, then there needs to be a standardization of when these processes will occur. This could be done on a campus-wide basis, or an individual building solution. For example, all full antivirus scans could be scheduled to run on Mondays and Thursdays. Every other night, the machine could be switched off. This should not affect the real-time scanning of the computers, and so should not increase risk of infection. In a typical work week (8-5) an employee may leave their machine on every day, every night, and on the weekends. This means their machine would run for 168 hours. By having them turn their machines off on tuesday, wednesday, and friday afternoons, they would only have their machines on for 75 hours per week. This means that 93 hours of savings would be realized or a 56% reduction.\n\nTelecommuting Employees: Where possible, wake-on-lan network cards should be installed, so that telecommuting employees can still remote desktop to the office computer. This would mean that they could also participate in the schedule mentioned above, where they could turn their machines off on several days per week, and not affect their ability to work from off-site locations.\n\nPower Saving Utilities: Although all computers come standard with power saving settings, many people either don't use them, or don't use them effectively. In concert with the scheduled process changes above, if there was a centrally approved/recommended power saving utility, more people may configure their settings properly. Verdiem (<a href=\"http://www.verdiem.com/edison.aspx\">http://www.verdiem.com/edison.aspx</a>) has a utility which will tell the user exactly how much power has been saved, and when the computer is most used. These details can empower employees to make better choices about when they leave their computer on and when they shut it down completely. There are many utilities available, and maybe it can be a decision made by individual departments/offices, but in any case, there is potential to combine the efforts of many people to achieve better power savings through a simple software install.\n\nPublic Relations: If we consider a utility that can record power usage per computer, per building, then it will be possible to communicate the efforts to the rest of campus as well as external constituencies. This is beneficial from a public relations standpoint, and showing that we are not only interested in saving money, but doing our part for the planet as well. This is a particularly timely article that i found after the email was sent to Dr Hoit: <a href=\"http://www.usatoday.com/tech/science/environment/2009-03-25-pc-power-company-costs_N.htm\">http://www.usatoday.com/tech/science/environment/2009-03-25-pc-power-company-costs_N.htm</a>\n\n<b>3. Move all faculty &amp; staff to Google Apps for Education immediately.</b>\n<b>Suggested by:</b> Nick Young, nick_young@ncsu.edu, Garrison Locke, gplocke@ncsu.edu, Jason Austin, jfaustin@ncsu.edu, Jen Riehle, jen_riehle@ncsu.edu\n<b>Potential Implementation Cost:</b> Faculty &amp; Staff will require archiving / document retention services as per state guidelines. $8.50 per user for Postini services, but it may be possible to repurpose existing servers to provide archiving tools. Time to develop policies and procedures for implementation\n<b>Potential Savings:</b> Eventual 100% elimination of licensing costs for GroupWise &amp; other on campus email services\nElimination of all college/departmental email servers. Elimination or re-purposing of central servers that provide Groupwise and/or Cyrus\n<b>Implementation Timeline:</b> Immediately, or as soon as policies can be created and approved to deal with an outsourced model.\n<b>Description:</b> If a \"move everyone at once\" policy is not possible, rather than spend the next 2 years moving everyone on campus to a centralized GroupWise system, we could move each pocket of campus gradually to Google (starting with OIT). The benefit of this would be reduction in licensing costs over the next 2 years for those users who would have been moved to GroupWise, as well as being able to decommission hardware in colleges that provide their own email services. Archiving for faculty and staff would need to be addressed, but this could be outsourced through Google's partnership with Postini, or provided in house by continuing to use OIT's central email servers as mail relays, essentially capturing everything that passes through before relaying onto Google.\n\nOne of the main reasons why the student email task force eliminated Microsoft's offering, was due to cross-platform, cross-browser issues. GroupWise, even in the latest release, has the same issue of providing a different user experience to different platforms. It does not support open calendar protocols (ie: CalDAV), therefore forcing every user to use either the GroupWise fat client, or the GroupWise web client.\n\nIt is difficult to find anyone who believes that GroupWise is the final solution for email and calendar services on campus. Supporters of GroupWise give it a lifespan of a few years at best, before we move to an outsourced solution. Why not save money right now, and rather than move people to a temporary solution, move them to something that at least has the chance of being a permanent solution.\n\n\n----- That's all....good ideas? bad ideas? any other ideas that people are implementing in small ways that maybe the rest of us can benefit from?","createdDate":"2009-03-25T16:49:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5081","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Agreed. In my former life i was a Director of IT at a smaller private institution, and these kinds of discussions were a regular occurrence. In fact, i was able to pull my own budget efficiency strategies that i submitted at that college, and suggest some of them to Dr Hoit.\n\nIt seems that larger institutions are a little more insulated to these kinds of 'efficiency' discussions, simply because the funding spigot is always on, even if its a low-flow model. At the smaller private institutions, you're worry is not about some people losing their jobs...its whether the whole institution will go under.\n\nI hope this crisis is a seed for making people realize how interconnected we are. We should not regress to grudges of the past (easy for me to say..I'm new here), but rather take this as an opportunity to collaborate to make things operate more efficiently AND effectively. Clinging to things because 'that's the way we've always done it' is not an effective way to operate. Efficiency and effectiveness strategies are not a one-time deal that you address when the CIO sends an email. It should be something we attempt to address in an intentional manner, and on a regular basis (if not daily).","createdDate":"2009-03-25T11:27:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5060","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"DISCLAIMER: I have no inside info on any of this stuff. I got the email that was posted above this morning, so all I know is what is written there. I don't want to speak on behalf of OIT. I can only give you my interpretations and opinions regarding these things.\n\nWith that out of the way, I don't think #3 will be possible unless our web hosting initiative succeeds. By changing our web hosting model, we will be able to move in a direction of a centrally managed and maintained CMS. If we keep our current model, that would be (IMHO) impossible.\n\nI think the main idea being expressed would be to move all content-driven sites into a centrally run CMS, thus eliminating webservers that are run by anyone outside of OIT, which is where the cost savings are. At least that is what I extrapolate from that.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T19:23:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5052","contributorName":"2v65x9nrx3otc","description":"this sounds like stuff that should be happening regardless of a \"budget crisis\"","createdDate":"2009-03-24T19:09:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5045","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This seems to be what Charles is investigating with CPanel etc. Though, I might be wrong.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T18:11:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5026","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Per #3 - Could someone elaborate?","createdDate":"2009-03-24T15:53:51.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:5015","contributorName":"2jt4yzjxvxgs7","title":"iPhone app Omnigraffle stencils","description":"There are some nice Omnigraffle stencils here to help you mockup or wireframe your iPhone apps:\n\n<a href=\"http://graffletopia.com/search/iphone\">http://graffletopia.com/search/iphone</a>\n\nIf you are not familiar with Omnigraffle, it is a fantastic diagramming tool (like Visio for Windows, but better). Omnigraffle is a Mac-only application that costs $99. You can download free custom stencils from Graffletopia.com, or create your own stencils. I use Omnigraffle for wireframing, ERD diagrams, flowcharts and technical architecture diagrams. There are stencils available for network diagrams, space planning, and org charts.\n\nAttached are examples of a few wireframes I created for an iPhone app project I am working on in case you are curious.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T14:31:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-24T15:41:47.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","fileAttachments":["discussions/80-listview.pdf","discussions/81-siteview.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5019","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"thats awesome. I need that...","createdDate":"2009-03-24T15:41:47.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4983","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"NCSU Web Dev Habitat For Humanity Day","description":"I was wondering if anyone had any interest in participating in a NCSU Web Dev <a href=\"http://www.habitat.org/\">Habitat for Humanity</a> day?\n\nWe've done this within OIT before, and it was a whole lot of fun for a good cause. The last time I went I learned how to hang vinyl siding, which was cool.\n\nIf you are not aware, <a href=\"http://www.fis.ncsu.edu/hr/hrim/comm_srvc.asp\">NCSU provides you with 24 hours of leave per year</a> for doing service work, and this definitely applies. Why not take a day off and spend some time with your colleagues while helping out Habitat? It will get us all out of the office and away from our computers, phones and clients for a day :)\n\nBasically, I am just gathering interest right now. Once I am sure we have a group of interested people, I will get up with Habitat and make the arrangements.\n\n++++++++++++UPDATE+++++++++++++\nPossible Dates are: 6/10, 6/12, 6/24, 6/26\n\nFill in your availability here: <a href=\"http://www.doodle.com/hkhga7eitp2b7p9q\">http://www.doodle.com/hkhga7eitp2b7p9q</a> - Thanks John Martin :)\n\n++++++++++++UPDATE #2++++++++++++\nJune 12th is our date. Please RSVP here:\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-24T12:18:13.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-06-05T12:28:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6941","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I need a final headcount of who is going to be doing the Habitat day by next Wednesday (6/10). Please head over to the event page (<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer</a>) and RSVP if you are planning to go. I have also updated that page with all the relevant info that the Habitat folks sent me, so make sure you read over the details.","createdDate":"2009-06-05T12:28:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6824","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"FYI, we have a date now. The Habitat people will be in touch with me later this week to work out details. Please go to the event and RSVP so we know exactly how many people to expect.\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/events/habitat-for-humanity-volunteer</a>","createdDate":"2009-06-01T14:18:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6666","contributorName":"048o8i00t8d9v","description":"I'm in.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T19:16:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6661","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Jason, can we use this tool to tally?\n\n<a href=\"http://www.doodle.com/hkhga7eitp2b7p9q\">http://www.doodle.com/hkhga7eitp2b7p9q</a>","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:24:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6659","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"I'm okay on all but the 24th with a preference for Fridays.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:23:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6656","contributorName":"2zcnsukt2voqj","description":"I'm interested in going again. The 12th would work for me.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:23:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6653","contributorName":"25f2wpbzy4qg8","description":"Keep me in mind. I've done a stint with habitat through our church several times before.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:12:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6650","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Any of those dates are good for me too.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:10:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6647","contributorName":"0ptauxo4xohrb","description":"Let me know when the day is","createdDate":"2009-05-20T15:06:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6641","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Horray! they finally got back to me with some possible dates. What do you guys think about the following:\n\n6/10\n6/12\n6/24\n6/26\n\nI can do any of these dates.","createdDate":"2009-05-20T14:58:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5120","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Me three.","createdDate":"2009-03-25T14:09:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5115","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"I'm game.","createdDate":"2009-03-25T13:25:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5108","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Me! Me! Pick me!","createdDate":"2009-03-25T13:20:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5105","contributorName":"22d8ohcn3r426","description":"I'm in!","createdDate":"2009-03-25T13:16:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5006","contributorName":"2clztbsxotepb","description":"I'm in. When and where?","createdDate":"2009-03-24T14:07:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5003","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"i'm interested.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T13:52:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4988","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I'm definitely interested in that! It was good stuff when we did it last time.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T12:42:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4985","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I'm interested","createdDate":"2009-03-24T12:21:27.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4961","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Apple unveils new iPhone features","description":"FYI\n\nSome of the 100 new features included in the update replicate those already offered by other smartphones.\n<a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/7949557.stm\">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/7949557.stm</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-23T11:19:40.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-23T11:19:41.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4921","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Implementing OAuth into a web app?","description":"We are in the process of creating some API support (XML, JSON and SOAP) for our base application framework which all our apps live in. We currently have SOAP support which is using an API key that we generate in the app to handle authentication, but it has a certain \"hackish\" quality to it. In our refactoring of the API support, we ran across <a href=\"http://oauth.net/\">OAuth</a> and was wondering if anyone else on campus is looking into this?\n\nI know twitter is rolling out a beta-version of OAuth support for their API, and a few other web services. It seems like a great concept, so we were going to work on implementing it for our OTFramework. Just curious if anyone out there has implemented this with success, or perhaps something different/better for authentication for an API?","createdDate":"2009-03-21T20:38:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-26T17:06:38.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5189","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"FYI to anyone interested, we did get an OAuth server/client implementation working with PHP in a ZF app. We had found a proposal for a Zend_Oauth component that was in the ZF incubator, but it was way buggy and really not ready for ....well....anything.\n\nWe ended up taking the sample code provided on the OAuth website for PHP and changing a good bit of it around, formatting it, correcting some errors, and polishing how it worked. We have a decent code base now, which we are working on documenting. We will be posting some tutorials/writeups about it later, but we did get it figured out. And it is a pretty awesome technology...","createdDate":"2009-03-26T17:06:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4923","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I can only answer the \"looking into it part.\" I keep telling myself I will implement a provider eventually. Even created <a href=\"http://justcode.extension.org/issues/show/338\">an issue for it last November</a>. That's as far as I've gotten. We have some data transfer needs and I'd rather use OAuth than the security-by-obscurity that we are using now (e.g. using hidden methods - sometimes with an \"api key\" - except ours isn't SOAP, it's just flat-out GETs ).\n\nWhile you're at it - feel free to whip a rails controller for me if you like. SVN commit access is quite easily arranged :-D","createdDate":"2009-03-21T21:23:35.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4801","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"Breadcrumbs for web pages","description":"I ran across this link,\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/03/17/breadcrumbs-in-web-design-examples-and-best-practices-2/\">http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/03/17/breadcrumbs-in-web-design-examples-and-best-practices-2/</a>\non the use of breadcrumbs in web design. It's a good read.\nglenn","createdDate":"2009-03-18T12:20:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-19T16:37:31.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4823","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"An interesting article from User Interface Engineering that somewhat downplays the effectiveness and use of breadcrumbs.\n\n\"We're recommending that when teams see users needing breadcrumbs, they look for other holistic design solutions. They'll need to watch users and see the circumstances leading up to how the need arises. In almost all cases, they'll find a better way to solve the problem than traditional breadcrumbs.\n\nFor example, in the instance where the user wants to explore a topic in more depth, there's probably a better way to indicate the \"next topic\" than a simple, overarching heading of the topic area. Perhaps a suggestion list of specific follow-on topics will serve their need better? Understanding the user's need will easily spawn some great ideas.\n\nBreadcrumbs aren't evil. Users won't collapse in their chairs\"\n\n<a href=\"http://www.uie.com/articles/breadcrumbs/\">Read the Full Article: Design Copy-out #2: Breadcrumbs</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-19T16:37:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4809","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Neat article. Breadcrumbs (hierarchies or often recursion in general) can be a nightmare from an application design point of view. You have to choose between selecting the entire table, or making multiple selects. Likely the best bet is to create a cache so that it isn't affecting response time, but if you choose to do partial caching you have to be very careful to refresh anything this might be affected. With custom attributes, you have to decide if caching makes sense or if it's going to work with the refresh implementation.\n\nIt would have been nice to find out what the accessibility recommendations are for Breadcrumbs, such as which tags to use to denote the hierarchical nature of the information. I imagine that it's nested ULs, but I would presume that the styling associate with that to have it appear as most pages do would be a daunting proposition.","createdDate":"2009-03-18T18:40:22.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4749","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Firefox Extensions 2.0","description":"Ok, kids... it's time for Firefox Extensions, Part Deux (The Reckoning).\n\nI wouldn't necessarily say these are my favorite Firefox extensions (for one thing Nick nabbed Colorzilla and MeasureIt) but most of these I use everyday and the rest are still awesome. If you don't see your favorites here stay tuned for more next week. And the personal suggestions and favorites you guys have contributed have been fantastic so keep it up!\n\nI'm not as nice as Nick so there are no screen shots but let me know if you have any questions about any of these tools.\n\n<b>Firefox Accessibility Extension</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5809\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5809</a>\nThis is just a good idea. Built by the folks at University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, this tool works for users with disabilities and for web developers testing pages. This Add-on is unique in that it adds a menu button (which I prefer to the also-available toolbar). From there you can run reports, preview navigation and scripts from an accessibility POV and use any number of available tools and validators. And before you say \"Hey, the Web Developers toolbar does that too!\" let me say that this Add-On has much better (and more strict) testing standards for its pages. I honestly think that the UI site's Functional Accessibility Evaluator (<a href=\"http://fae.cita.uiuc.edu/\">http://fae.cita.uiuc.edu/</a> ) is the standard we should all be aiming for.\n\n\n<b>FlashBlock</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/433\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/433</a>\nI don't know about you guys but it seems to me that Firefox sometimes runs REALLY slow. It could be that I always have at least two Firefox windows open with ten to twelve tabs or it could be my snoozy Intel Pentium processor but regardless, it's a pain. I did a fair bit of research on how to speed things up (or more accurately, make Firefox use less of my processing power) and this was one of the suggestions. Just start her up and all the Flash on your page will be replaced with a little Flash icon that you can choose to click on if the Flash is Flash you want. And you'll be surprised at just how much Flash is out there slowing you down. Think about some of those obnoxious, flashy, bouncy ads out there... you won't miss 'em.\n\n\n<b>Fast Dial</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5721\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5721</a>\nThis is one I use every day. I don't know how I found it but it's definitely a favorite. This will give you a new home screen when you open a tab. The screen will give you 4, 6, 9... however many windows you choose and fill them with the screenshots, links to pages you choose, typically your most-visited pages. Simple, but infinitely useful.\nI will mention that some reviewers have given Fast Dial some negative reviews. For some reason the developers seem to have removed some functionality in their latest version; I'm hoping they see the error of their ways. I've also been frustrated with the tools for setting up my Fast Dial links. Look for those tools in the Add-Ons menu &gt; Fast Dial &gt; Preferences. Or try hovering your mouse on the top right-hand corner of the screenshot windows to make changes.\nIt's still awesome, though.\n\n\n<b>Foxmarks</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/2410\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/2410</a>\nI think this is one of the staples for anyone who uses Firefox: automatic syncing of your bookmarks on all your machines. Set up an account with Foxmarks at <a href=\"http://www.foxmarks.com/\">http://www.foxmarks.com/</a> . Then follow the very simple instructions to have Foxmarks back-up your bookmarks. Install Foxmarks on all your other machines and login with your account ID and password to sync the bookmarks on a new machine. Update your bookmarks by clicking on the little icon in the lower right-hand corner of your Firefox browser. Very easy.\nFoxmarks will do some other stuff as well, such as storing your passwords and securing them with a PIN. I haven't tried this (paranoid and not yet brain-dead) but it will also let you do all your syncing and password-saving to your own server if you want to provide one.\n\n\n<b>FireFTP</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/684\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/684</a>\nOh, look! Another extension that starts with \"F\"! How original! This is one I don't use that often but when I remember it I'm very happy. FireFTP will open an FTP client in a Firefox tab. It's pretty fully-featured and very intuitive (you've seen one FTP client you've seen 'em all) and although it does work on Windows, Mac and Linux some additional downloads may be required. The FireFTP launcher is in the \"Tools\" menu so don't forget about it; there's actually another Add-On to put a FireFTP button on your toolbar.\n\n\n<b>Twitterfox</b> - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5081\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5081</a>\nTwitterfox is an Add-On that will let you connect to your Twitter account(s) and view/update your Twitter feed from within Firefox.\nOh, wait, I forgot... we haven't really talked about Twitter on here. If you're a person who doesn't use Twitter, doesn't \"get\" Twitter or doesn't know what Twitter is, stay tuned. We'll have a Twitter \"Best Thing Ever\" in the coming weeks.\nIn the mean time, those of you already on Twitter might want to consider consolidating your open applications by managing your tweets in Firefox. A little icon in the lower right-hand corner let's you know when new posts arrive and you can expand the view to see all recent tweets and add your own.\nI feel the need to qualify this recommendation by saying I don't actually use this Add-On. I don't really like the Twitterfox interface, so although I think it's a cool Add-On, I still use Twhirl. I am optimistic that they'll improve the interface, however, and the developers have been doing regular updates every 2-3 weeks or more so it's definetely kept-up.","createdDate":"2009-03-17T12:16:38.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-04T19:34:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5142","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"There is a page I ran across on Digg today. Their 10 Best are largely the same as picked here.\n<a href=\"http://www.firefoxfacts.com/2009/03/24/10-popular-web-designer-tools-for-firefox/\">http://www.firefoxfacts.com/2009/03/24/10-popular-web-designer-tools-for-firefox/</a>\nglenn","createdDate":"2009-03-25T17:05:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4757","contributorName":"0qxi8q3568pcg","description":"I use the delicious social bookmarking site with the Delicious Bookmarks extension :\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/3615\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/3615</a>\n\nI have the extension installed on every computer I use, both at home and at work.","createdDate":"2009-03-17T13:00:58.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4732","contributorName":"halmeeks","title":"YouTube Captioning WebApp","description":"Check this out:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.youtubecc.com/\">http://www.youtubecc.com/</a>\n\nand coming up soon:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.capscribe.ca/\">http://www.capscribe.ca/</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-17T01:11:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-17T11:12:29.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:4173","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4741","contributorName":"0tsgrb8k0z34k","description":"Cool, thanks! Hopefully we can use these tools for some videos for Design. :)","createdDate":"2009-03-17T11:12:29.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4687","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Author Information for NCSU Websites","description":"On a fairly frequent basis, I (and Jen Riehle) have to help resolve random website issues for sites hosted on campus. Generally, the remedy ticket comes in, we check it out, and try to resolve the issue as quickly as possible. Sometimes it is very quick, but sometimes it takes a little longer because we were not the people who originally developed the website. It would be helpful if we could easily find the original developers, so either they could resolve the issue, or at least help point us in the right direction. This becomes quite necessary when dealing with graphics that need to be altered, or navigation that doesn't immediately make sense.\n\nSo, what I'm asking is for ideas on the best way to store this information. I'll pose this as the starter idea:\n\nIn the .htaccess file at the root of any ncsu website, add the following information as a commented section:\n\n# Begin Author Information\n# Date: (site launch date)\n# Lead Author's Name (or multiple author names)\n# Department:\n# Email Address:\n# End Author Information\n\nThis way, it can be replicated on any website developed on campus, and can be found in the same place for any website at all. If you don't have an .htaccess file in the website you're developing because you're not creating any permissions or custom rules, then you can still put this information in there, and nothing else.\n\nAnyway, there's a start. I'm open to new ideas, because at the end of the day, I'd like to have something standardized that all web developers on campus can follow without too much effort. Ideally, I don't want us to get bogged down with implementation issues or buy-in questions before we develop the template or method itself.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T12:49:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:11857","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"no -- no more further information on this. It got pushed down on the priority list (as things usually do). I still have plans to revive the discussion, but need to find the time and also take into account some new developments like the web hosting initiative, AFS locker renewals, branding initiatives and whatnot.\n\nThe long and short of it is, that there are a wide array of needs and requirements that surround this topic, and we want to be sure that anything we implement doesn't get in the way of future projects/plans.\n\nThe best thing you can do until there is a central/standard solution, is to retain good records about your sites. If you keep a central spreadsheet, or a readme file in the web site locker itself....either way, as long as there is discoverable information available, that is a good first step.","createdDate":"2010-05-04T13:24:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11854","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"Have the parameters for this info file been finalized? I see there was a meeting last fall but no further information after that. I'm ready to start adding this information to some newly redesigned sites. Thanks!","createdDate":"2010-05-04T10:47:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9856","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'll be out of town.\n\nJust remember: simplicity! :)","createdDate":"2009-10-22T12:47:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9851","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"From the feedback on the Doodle Poll, I have scheduled a meeting for us on Monday, October 26th from 10-11am in the Hillsborough Building. If you didnt get the email (sent via Groupwise), let me know and i'll resend it. Right now i have Mike Vysocka, Tim Jones, Margaret Hudacko, Ellen McDaniel and Troy Hurteau on the list of attendees, but anyone else is welcome to show up (just let me know ahead of time, as i'll need to let you into the stairwell or elevator to get to the meeting (no security personnel in HLB anymore).","createdDate":"2009-10-21T17:37:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9630","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Ok --- i've created a Doodle Poll so we can figure out who would like to meet, and when we can get together to talk about this issue.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.doodle.com/q2yzxp6km3fxi4ap\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.doodle.com/q2yzxp6km3fxi4ap</a>\n\nWe'll have to figure out a meeting place after we get a time penciled in, but I'm sure we can work something out.","createdDate":"2009-10-19T18:31:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9574","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"This is one of those things that I have an interest in, but am wary of. It seems like the kind of meeting where we decide to consolidate on Groupwise - I'd like to know about my fate, but am unsure about whether I want to participate in the ... death march is probably too strong of a word.\n\nPlease keep us informed about when it is, but if I am unable to attend, I would really appreciate if someone advocated simplicity. Minimizing overhead is very important any time, but especially in these budget strapped times.","createdDate":"2009-10-15T13:17:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9552","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"I'd be interested in discussing as well.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T19:00:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9547","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Yes, still interested and Mike Vysocka and I would come to a mtg.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T15:21:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9545","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Don --- i agree that the author information should be easily found and accessible, but the difference of opinion comes in when we consider who the information is primarily targeted at. We will obviously have more discussion when the small group of us meet about this topic, but here's a few of my thoughts.\n\nIf you centralize the information into a .htaccess file, then it is more easily kept up to date, rather than having to manage meta data on every single page on the website. Not all developers use templates, and those using a CMS may not be able to implement (easily) a solution that requires meta data to be posted to multiple pages.\n\nThe information i originally intended to store, was centered around developers. What kind of information does a developer need when inheriting or maintaining a website. This was the original problem that we tried to solve. With that in mind, the htaccess solution may meet those needs, as the developers will have access to that file.\n\nI cannot really think of a reason why regular visitors to the website need to be given information about the inner organization of the staff of created the site, or where it lives in AFS, or what symlinks are working for that particular site. If a regular visitor to the site needs to know who authored the site, they can look at the actual content of the site, the contact us page, or do a AFS locker lookup in sysnews to figure out where it lives in the server structure.\n\nHaving said all that, it is quite possible that a hybrid solution may be the way to go. Maybe a simple set of metadata, but then a more complete set of information stored in .htaccess (or some other hidden file?).\n\nI'm waiting to get some more input or interest from the community before trying to organize a meeting, so whoever is interested, please let us know.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T13:35:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9544","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Nick,\n\nWe've been waiting for a resolution to this issue ever since I've been here (9+ years).\nThis idea is an option - However, the Owner/Author information needs to be easily found and accessed by anyone - including the Web page visitor. The use of .htaccess or some other restrictive method may not be as useful other as other options such as Author Meta tags, links in the Footer or some other way.\nLets keep the discussion going until we come up with something that will allow everyone to easily find out the Owner/Author of published Web pages. Luis Chacon has given this a lot of thought. And I think he may have posted something (somewhere) earlier.","createdDate":"2009-10-14T13:04:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:9468","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"In our meeting yesterday, I mentioned that I would attempt to revive this discussion and see if we can get some motivated people together to produce a solution.\n\nSo....if you're interested in this topic of Author Information for NC State websites, please reply to the thread and we can get something going.\n\nIt appears that a face-to-face meeting may be the best way to get this off the ground, and then we can continue online.\n\nBut i'm open to other suggestions for how to move this forward.","createdDate":"2009-10-09T13:25:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5499","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"That would be great, Troy. Maybe in another week or so, I can set up a f2f mtg for all of us to get together and hammer something out, or at least get a clearer vision of what might work.","createdDate":"2009-04-07T14:25:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5221","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I think that your template is the best idea i've seen so far. I think this is a good method. I'm not completely up on the ZF solution you describe, but then again, i can rely on Jason Austin or Garrison to fill me in on the details -- they're just down the hall.\n\nI for one, don't really care about the revision date. But this may be tied to my responsibilities (contracted work for clients on campus). However i can see how that may be a benefit to the developers within officers/departments, as they could use it as a scheduler for which site gets updated next. So i think we're on the right track with mandatory and optional fields, and your example template is a good one to start from, for sure.\n\nI think that having a \"full\" metadata file in the root of each site may be necessary, just so people don't have to drill up through directories to find the full compliment of information. If you have a folder that houses multiple websites, then you'll just need multiple metadata files inside each root.\n\nI'm trying to be conscious, as i think we all are in this thread, to make sure we have a solution that provides useful data, but does not become a disproportionate burden on the developer to maintain. I think we're on the right track.","createdDate":"2009-03-27T11:45:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5127","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"good idea -- i like that idea a lot actually.\n\nObviously we can quibble over the sections included, but i think this could work, and be relatively easy to implement. With this type of structure, it would be relatively easy to have an online tool that produced the file for you. That way, it could insert the information into the central db at the same time as producing the file for placement in the directory.","createdDate":"2009-03-25T14:28:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5123","contributorName":"1l94q89y956k5","description":"Good idea. Could #2 be leveraged to create and maintain #1? Such as, some tool would scan the host directories for the info file (I'm partial to \"site.info\", so it'll stand out from a regular .txt) and parse the information to the database? That way developers only need maintain one set of data. If you use a basic .ini file structure, it should be easy enough to parse and extend (see attached file for example).","createdDate":"2009-03-25T14:14:47.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/82-site.info"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4979","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"ok -- so i dont want to let this go too long without moving us incrementally forward (or sideways as the case may be). I'm not sure what the next step should be though.\n\nIt seems that the solutions we are talking about are:\n\n1. Centralized database of website information (a full compliment of info about the site), which is updated by the developer upon launch, and then by the party who is maintaining the site as time moves on.\n\n2. Decentralized method of storing simple details about the website. Probably not in an .htaccess file, but something that can be placed in any NCSU directory. An equivalent of robots.txt was mentioned.\n\n\nAs mentioned before, it might be helpful to start with a narrow scope (ie: #2 above), and then branch out from there. How about a file called something like \"siteinfo.txt\" and it contains the following:\n\n-- Developed/Designer Information (Name, Dept, Unity ID's, Email)\n-- Last major version/launch date\n-- \"Supported by\" information, if different than the developer information. (Name, Dept, Unity IDs, Email)\n\nIn order to help people learn or remember that the siteinfo.txt is there, would it be helpful to put a comment line into the htaccess file that refers to it? At least then, when a permitted person does see the htaccess file, they'll remember to check the siteinfo.txt for full information.\n\nAnyway -- there's a start. What does everyone think? By no means does this have to be the solution, but i figured if i posted something, we can say yes or no to it, and keep this moving till we get something that everyone can agree on.","createdDate":"2009-03-23T19:52:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4745","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Im not familiar with Dublin core, but i like the idea of using an existing standard. I dont think we need to reinvent the wheel if someone has already built it for us.\n\nI guess the htaccess file may not be the best idea, for the permissions reason you mention. The reason i thought this may be the easiest solution, is because i was only considering it for use when developers are needing to update the site. If they are updating the site, then they'll have permissions to the htaccess file, and if they arent supposed to update the site, then there'll be no need for them to see the metadata we are talking about. I guess there will be times when you may need to see the metadata, in order to direct a troubleshooting request to the proper person, so that puts a vote in the column for a non-htaccess solution.\n\nJohn -- could you explain a little how you are using the dublin core standard for the library? you mentioned the level of maintenance varies....how so?\n\nI wonder if we can keep our scope fairly narrow to begin with, or maybe specify a smaller set of 'mandatory' information, and then if people want to include extra, they can choose that on a site by site basis. I was thinking that we could just store those few things i mentioned in the first post ( site launch date, Lead Author's Name (or multiple author names), department, Email Address). although i think that the 'refresh dates' may be helpful to the department itself (and its own developer), i'm not sure its valuable information for the purpose i had with this topic. But maybe that's my narrow-minded approach to this singular issue.\n\nI'm trying to think how we move this forward, as it seems that we agree that this is an important issue to address. Do we need to develop and agree on a standard set of data first, and then a secondary set of data that is more of the optional type? Or should we decide on a method of storage first, and then figure out the data later? I guess we could tackle them at the same time too. I'm hoping we can have some kind of idea to talk about at the next web developer's meet-up, so we can have an idea from the whole community (in case they aren't checking these forums). I'm not sure on the date right now, but this doesn't seem too insurmountable does it? I like to be able to present an idea that those of us interested in it have agreed on, and then see what's left standing when we show it to the whole community. Does that sound feasible?","createdDate":"2009-03-17T11:44:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4724","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"I like the Dublin Core idea (all this time I thought it was Dublin, Ireland, not Dublin, Ohio. Who knew?). See 2.3. Metadata Storage and Maintenance Issues of <a href=\"http://dublincore.org/documents/usageguide/\">http://dublincore.org/documents/usageguide/</a> and <a href=\"http://www.ukoln.ac.uk/metadata/dcdot/\">http://www.ukoln.ac.uk/metadata/dcdot/</a>. I think we could work with a subset of the standard in any case.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T20:27:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4719","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"A a good idea.\nBut, I do have one follow up question.\nIf it's in a .htacces file, and we do not have PTS permissions to get access the the web site's files, how could we get to it to look at it?\nIt needs to be somewhere where there is unrestricted access (header, footer, META, About this Site, etc.)\nIt would also be nice for it to NOT be dependent on what tool is used to develop the site (Dreamweaver Templates, Cascade, Drupal, etc.) Some generic way of doing it.\n\nMy $0.02 worth.\nDon","createdDate":"2009-03-16T16:23:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4714","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"i thought about a centralized database of site information that could be easily searchable...but... having that information separated from the site itself may pose problems with keeping things up to date. At least with an htaccess-type solution, there's no need to remember to go to a separate website, login, and update site information.\n\nI do like the idea of a website registration system though, and think that would be very nice to have that information handy. I wonder if we could have a hybrid solution? An htaccess file with the most basic information in it, and then the registration system that has a more fully compiled list of websites and their characteristics/metadata etc.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T14:42:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4707","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"As Mike says (he and I work together), we have been talking about an \"About this Site\" tool that could be written for each site that is housed in one of our web lockers.\n\nAs our sites multiply, we need to keep some record about the who, what, where, when and how of their development. I have been thinking of a db that might generate a custom \"About this Site\" page with such content as:\n\nWho is responsible for it/authorization\nWho designed it\nWho supports it\nCompliances\nAnalytics/stats\nRefresh dates\nTechnologies/versions used\netc.\n\nMost sites have some kind of \"About Us\" which is about the people and content of the site. But few have good accounting/reporting about the site as a web resource. I think we need something driven from the vhost level or even across vhosts, if possible.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T14:20:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4704","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I would hope that all sites developed and housed on NCSU servers would have this information stored. I don't know that we could ever mandate or enforce this kind of thing. Its more of a good practice, so that people who follow in your footsteps, or people who have to fix/update things on websites you've designed can easily find who the original developer was.\n\nSo, i guess to answer your question directly...(in my opinion): all sites. all afs paths.\n\nThis is all just discussion at the moment --- there's no mandate or push coming from any higher-ups (AFAIK), so this is something that we campus web developers could decide upon for ourselves, for the betterment of our own community.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T14:12:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4701","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Which sites / AFS paths will be affected by this policy?","createdDate":"2009-03-16T14:04:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4693","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Nick, excellent suggestion! This is something we've recently been pondering in Engineering, especially for all of our Student Organization websites which experience ownership turnover just about every other semester.\n\nUsing the .htaccess file to store this information could be a bit cumbersome for us. Most of our .htaccess files are actually auto-generated by WolfTech's <a href=\"http://www.wolftech.ncsu.edu/guarddog\">GuardDog</a> tool. While GuardDog does allow you to add custom code to the auto-generated file, you would still have to maintain this information via GuardDog and not the file system. Any users that have read/write perms on a particular locker but don't have access to GuardDog would be unable to get to it.","createdDate":"2009-03-16T13:10:50.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4535","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","title":"NKOTB Zend Studio Question","description":"I'm having trouble understanding how to use Zend Studio for Eclipse. I want to be able to work on the file locally and then upload them to the server. I am able to connect a remote systems on my desktop but not my laptop, which makes no sense.\n\n1. Can I FTP through Zend Studio\n2. Can I export my remote systems settings so they can work on my laptop?\n3. Is phpunit really important for testing.\n4. Well I ever figure Zend out or will I die trying.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T21:05:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-26T16:20:50.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:220","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5048","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"Troy,\n\nI thought I fixed the problem, but I realize that the linux worked on one computer, but not the one I had the problem earlier. You mentioned it might be the firewall, is there a way to check to see if this is it?","createdDate":"2009-03-24T18:34:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4685","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"No worries Troy, my response wasn't directed at you (otherwise it would have been a reply).\n\nFor basic highlighting, I use vim or gedit. So when I'm trying to compare an application plugin like Zend Studio for Eclipse, I try to think in terms of \"What does it do well that I don't know how to use vim to do?\", which results in that short list of function completion, visual conflict resolution, and syntax warnings (even if false positives abound).","createdDate":"2009-03-16T12:38:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4563","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The best features when using Eclipse with a PHP Plugin (Zend or otherwise) are:\n* function completion with types (requires @param lines, which also make your code more readable)\n* visual SVN integration (to show modified files and resolve conflicts)\n* syntax error checking (saves a php -l)\n\nHowever, I still believe that if you are using SVN that you shouldn't be editing the files directly with Zend. Either you're editing production files directly, which is just asking for trouble, or you are editing development files, which means that there is probably no separation between the development and production branches.","createdDate":"2009-03-12T12:33:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4549","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"Jason,\n\nThe remote worked I used the Linux section and that did the trick. And I'm going to take your advice about keeping Zend Studio simple. Thanks for the help.","createdDate":"2009-03-12T00:50:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4546","contributorName":"38n6ifg2h285w","description":"John thanks. I am able to connect I tried SSH and then linux and the linux connection worked. I really appreciate the help","createdDate":"2009-03-12T00:48:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4540","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I agree with everything Troy said. Here are my extra notes:\n\n1) Yes, I have done it. You do it through the remote system and you edit the files directly on the server.\n\n2) I dunno\n\n3) PHPUnit is great if you have things that /really/ need unit tests. Unit testing is something that is more typically done with programming languages like Java and C and not with web-based languages. That doesn't mean that you shouldn't do unit tests, but you certainly don't have to. We have used PHPUnit some, but we found it to be fairly cumbersome. But that was a few years ago, so I don't know what they have done with integration with Zend Studio, so maybe it is easier now.\n\n4) Just like Troy said, Zend Studio is intimidating if you try to use ALL the features. Just use what you need and let the rest go. We don't use nearly all the features and we get by OK. It is still better than any other PHP IDE I have tried.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T23:37:56.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4527","contributorName":"2jt4yzjxvxgs7","title":"iPhone Developer University","description":"I wonder if any academic administrators in the College of Engineering are aware of this program:\n\n<a href=\"http://developer.apple.com/iphone/program/university.html\">http://developer.apple.com/iphone/program/university.html</a>\n\nThis certainly would provide a boost for iPhone development on this campus.\n\nPlease note that the program states \"This Program is designed for instructional purposes.\" so I assume staff would not be able to tap into the Developer University distribution license. Staff would probably need to get their own \"Standard\" or \"Enterprise\" program license.\n\nTito","createdDate":"2009-03-11T19:28:13.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-12T18:28:39.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4579","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Maybe it was the guys in IntelliMedia? Does the name James Lester ring a bell? They have a site at research.csc.ncsu.edu.","createdDate":"2009-03-12T18:28:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4543","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think our class next week will generate a lot of interest. We have some plans in the works as well to generate some more interest in iPhone development. I'd love to see it as a real, for-credit class (which is what the iPhone University Program requires). I know I'd take it.\n\nHal, if you remember who it was, I'd be glad to reach out to them and see how we could help get a real class together.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T23:40:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4532","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"I was contacted by someone in the Computer Science department about a year ago who was looking for affinity groups on campus for this exact program. I just spent a couple of minutes trying to dig up their email but no dice.\n\nThe Art+Design program has done some development work with Unity (a 3d game engine), which now supports the iPhone as a development platform, so the potential exists that they could do game development on the iPhone -- but the iPhone Unity dev environment is not particularly cheap, and the budget....well you know.....\n\n<a href=\"http://unity3d.com/unity/features/iphone-publishing.html\">http://unity3d.com/unity/features/iphone-publishing.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-11T19:51:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4443","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"CMS for Conferences","description":"There's a pretty open source nice conference CMS:\n\n<a href=\"http://pkp.sfu.ca/?q=ocs\">http://pkp.sfu.ca/?q=ocs</a>\n\nbut of course it doesn't work out of the box in our engineering web environment because of open_basedir restrictions (the bane of my existence). When I was in WolfTech Dan Green had an instance going for a little while over in OIT web space but it got back-burnered.\n\nSo after reviving the project over here in ITECS, we're nearing completion of open_basedir adaptation and are now considering what hooks (if any) to add so that the package authentication module would be WRAP-friendly. Anyone out there written an object for this or have any opinions on WRAP adaptation of open source software?","createdDate":"2009-03-10T14:27:33.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-10T14:34:15.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4445","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Dan and I have differing opinions on how WRAP should be used for authentication... at least with regards to our respective Drupal modules. When I wrote mine, I took an existing module for pub_cookie and adapted it to recognize WRAP cookies instead. WRAP and pub_cookie are very similar in mechanism, so that's a great shortcut if you can find code for it.\n\nOn the other hand, if your conferences will involve non-NCSU people, I'd suggest looking for an alternate login mechanism. OpenID, or *shudder* Shibboleth come to mind.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T14:34:15.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4412","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","title":"Credit Cards, NelNet Object","description":"We're very close to testing a PHP NelNet object for the Engineering Career Fair. It suddenly seems like various Engineering admin groups wanting the ability to take credit cards are coming out of the woodwork. Is any other unit/college offering a \"packaged\" solution out there for the university's NelNet gateway? Does anyone else care? :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:17:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-10T13:17:17.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4405","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Firefox Extensions Part I","description":"While trying to figure out what to post for this week's Best Thing Ever!, I realized that the things I use each day within Firefox are pretty awesome. They may not warrant an entire article about each individual extension (we'd have enough articles for the rest of the year if we did that), but collectively they form a nice collection of development tools.\n\nThis is by no means an exhaustive list. Look for Part II next week by Jen Riehle as she profiles her favorite extensions.\n\n<b>ieTab</b>\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/1419\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/1419</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/83-ieTab1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/84-ieTab1.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"86\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/85-ieTab2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/86-ieTab2.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"94\"/></a></p>\nSo...you know you have to test your websites in all browsers, but you really don't want to open Internet Explorer even for a second. You're heart is telling you never to double-click on that little blue 'e' but your head is saying you have to. Wait...you could send the link to a friend with Internet Explorer and let them tell you if \"it looks right.\" But then you're risking infecting your friend with continued exposure to a sub-standard browser. Enter \"ieTab\" to save your day (and your friend's day too). ieTab allows you to view web pages within Firefox as if you are running Internet Explorer. It's so simple. Add the extension, then just click on the icon in the bottom right corner to switch the rendered view. Click it again to switch back to render in firefox.\n\n<b>ColorZilla</b>\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/271\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/271</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/87-colorzilla1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/88-colorzilla1.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"144\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/89-colorzilla2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/90-colorzilla2.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"144\"/></a></p>\nIf it's got zilla in the name, it must be a monster of an extension. Not really. This is just about the smallest addon you'll find, but can save you a bunch of time. If you want to know exactly what color a website is using, don't take a screenshot, open in photoshop, use the color picker, then look at the hex values. Install 'ColorZilla' and use your new built-in color picker within Firefox. It appears as a eye dropper in the bottom left corner. Simply click on it, and then click on the website somewhere to get the exact color being used. There's even a preview as you scroll across the page so you know exactly which one you'll be choosing (very helpful when it comes to striped background tiles). This is a good companion to the Web Developer Toolbar's \"View Color Information\" option, which will give you a list of all the colors being used on a site. That is particularly useful for viewing a site's entire palette.\n\n<b>MeasureIt</b>\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/539\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/539</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/91-measureit1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/92-measureit1.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"155\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/93-measureit2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/94-measureit2.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"155\"/></a></p>\nHate guessing the size of an image, or the distance between div elements? Need to bump an image a little closer to something else? You could make a change to your css, return to the browser, refresh, make another change to the css, return to the browser, refresh...rinse and repeat-style...OR...you could use 'MeasureIt' to get a pixel-perfect measurement of anything on the page you're viewing. It appears as a small ruler in the bottom left corner of your window. Click once on it to get a draggable marquee, which tells you the height and width as you drag across the screen.\n\n<b>Lorem Ipsum Generator</b>\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/198\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/198</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/95-loremipsum1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/96-loremipsum1.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"136\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/97-loremipsum2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/98-loremipsum2.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"136\"/></a></p>\nDeveloping a template for a website and need to fill in some dummy text? Need to see how the site stretches and conforms to small and large amount of text? Old method: go to lipsum.com, click some options, select the generated text, copy, return to your template, paste. There is a quicker way. The LoremIpsum generator sits in Firefox and will let you generate as much dummy text as you would ever want or need. It will generate any number of characters, words or paragraphs in Lorem Ipsum, Epsum Factorial, Li Europan, or Ma Quande (whatever those last 3 are). Dummy text is dummy text, but i guess if Latin is not your thing, you could use one of the others provided. A \"copy to clipboard\" button in the extension is a neat feature whcih saves at least a couple of clicks.\n\n<b>FEBE (Firefox Environment Backup Extension)</b>\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/2109\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/2109</a>\nWorried about the safety of those around you if Firefox ever lost all your extensions that you've spent an epic amount of time configuring? FEBE allows you to backup and restore all of your installed Firefox extensions and themes. It actually creates individual installable .xpi (or .jar for themes) files that you can put on CD, Flash Drive or floppy (do they still make those?) and install on another computer. You could also backup your extensions before installing an extension upgrade. This way you could always go back if the upgrade doesn't work for you. The best part is you can schedule it to run automatically, so you never have to worry about forgetting to look after your prized configuration in the event of an unexpected crash. After all, aren't they all unexpected crashes? It's not like you get up in the morning and say \"yep...today is the day i'm going to crash Firefox and lose all my stuff.\"\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/99-FEBE1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/100-FEBE1.png?width=274\" alt=\"\" width=\"274\" height=\"300\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/101-FEBE2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/102-FEBE2.png?width=274\" alt=\"\" width=\"274\" height=\"300\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/103-FEBE3.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/104-FEBE3.png?width=274\" alt=\"\" width=\"274\" height=\"300\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/105-FEBE4.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/106-FEBE4.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"182\"/></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/107-FEBE5.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/108-FEBE5.png?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"79\"/></a></p>","createdDate":"2009-03-10T12:54:57.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-16T12:28:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4683","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The best theme I've seen is the Linux default theme which I'm guessing (based on the logo) is called \"Tango!\".","createdDate":"2009-03-16T12:28:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4644","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"VERY happy to learn about measureit, useful it will be (channeling yoda).\n\nMy FF add-ons:\n-Firebug\n-Webdeveloper (a must)\n-GSpace (for my personal computer, this takes advantage of all that free space google gives out)\n-delicious (also a must)\n-colorzilla\n-download status bar\n\nAnd also, I use the theme called \"Whitehart.\"\n\nGreat post!","createdDate":"2009-03-14T14:45:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4616","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I love tabs. Well...love is a strong term..but i find myself having more tabs than my screen width will display...so im very interested in these. Thanks for posting...i'll be checking them out as soon as i can get through the tabs i already have open :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-13T13:28:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4613","contributorName":"Drew3D","description":"<b>Tree Style Tab</b> - shows tabs vertically on the side of the window. Absolute must-have for tab addicts. Also lets you create hierarchical trees of tabs that you can expand/collapse.\n\n<b>Tab Mix Plus</b> - Lots more tab features, works great with Tree Style Tab.","createdDate":"2009-03-13T13:18:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4503","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I use Adblock at home. At work, I try to make sure that I get whatever a normal user would get.\n\nWith Greasemonkey, I've mostly just used it to delete elements from the DOM to remove advertising divs and useless menu bars or obtrusive headers.\n\nI've been considering instead using user stylesheets, but until today had not known that WebDeveloper supports it. I don't know what kinds of controls it gives you on applying them, but then I could just \"#advert { display: none;}\" my troubles away.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T12:45:05.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4501","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"FireBug is good for more than just Javascript. Actually, because it is so useful for editing CSS (by showing applied styles in descending specificity) and modifying the DOM, it almost makes Web Developer obsolete. The only thing that I still use Web Developer for is two click selective cache clear, cookie view/modification and cache disabling.\n\nNice call on the HTML Validator. I was delighted to discover that both the Linux 32 and 64 bit flavors were available and have been using it for several months now.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T12:37:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4457","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I'll be talking about Foxmarks, TwitterFox and possibly GreaseMonkey next week. And I think we decided not to bother with the Web Developer toolbar since it's kind of assumed to be on any web developers toolbar... but maybe we should do a quick highlight of it for next week...","createdDate":"2009-03-10T16:49:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4448","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"My favorites... google for the links if you are curious:\n\nAdblock Plus - block content from ad sites, by personal list or use one of their subscription lists\n\nDownload Statusbar - get rid of the download popup window and just put progress bars at the bottom of the browser window\n\nFoxmarks - sync bookmarks (and passwords if you dare) between browsers on multiple computers\n\nGreasemonkey - scripting language, I use it exclusively to add features to Flickr\n\nTwitterFox - adds a twitter tracker to the bottom bar\n\nWebDeveloper - tons of tools for tearing apart and analyzing HTML/CSS/layout/etc","createdDate":"2009-03-10T14:39:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4427","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"sorry about that --- i should have specified the compatibility of the extensions i was writing about. In the interest of full disclosure, my setup is Windows XP, Firefox 3.07.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:36:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4424","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I also find HTML validator at\n<a href=\"http://users.skynet.be/mgueury/mozilla/\">http://users.skynet.be/mgueury/mozilla/</a>\nto be quite useful for flagging invalid code on web pages. The Mozilla site doesn't include the Linux or OS X versions but the authors site does. And Web developer from\n<a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/60\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/60</a>\nand of course FireBug if you're doing javascript/AJAX.\nglenn","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:35:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4421","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My favorite feature: \"IE Tab is not available for Linux.\" ;)\n\nBeing serious though, thank you for the neat addons. I'm looking forward to the next iteration.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:32:13.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4379","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Figuring out the \"How\" for collaboration and transparency","description":"We had an all-hands OIT staff meeting today. In that meeting, Dr. Hoit laid out his plans for OIT, as well as touching on some projects and budget issues, but one thing from the SOP stood out to me: he wants collaboration and transparency...and he wants it everywhere.\n\nAssuming you have read just about anything that I have posted on this site, you know that I am a big fan of both collaboration and transparency. While both are the ultimate of buzzwords, they can have real meaning and value behind them, but you have to work at it.\n\nMake no mistake. I appreciate so very much a directive to be transparent and to collaborate. But one glaring omission in Dr. Hoit's presentation was the \"how\". We've gone years and years without any directive <i>to</i> collaborate and be transparent. Well, now we have a directive, but I'm not sure OIT is really ready for it. Are we willing? Sure. But I don't know if we are trained in the ancient ninja art of collaboration and transparency. SOOOOO I bring this to you guys....a few simple questions so I can help myself and my colleagues:\n\nHow do you do business transparently, and do it effectively?\n\nHave you determined your costs regarding time, resources, etc. to being \"transparent\"? If so, what are those costs? Did you have a tipping point that said \"it's worth it here, but not here because it would take too much (whatever resource we currently don't have)\".\n\nAre there certain tools you use to aid in your transparency and collaborative efforts? What did you try that worked and that didn't?\n\nWhat direct benefits have you gained from being \"pervasively transparent\"? How did you measure your success?\n\nHow can good cooperation across division, college, department, etc. be facilitated? Is it going to have to be a grassroots effort or should it come from the top?\n\n\nI'm hoping someone will come back with a \"magic pill\" which will instantly make us good stewards of collaboration and transparency, but somehow I doubt that is the case. And yes, before anyone points out the obvious, I know the tool/technique depends on the situation, but I want to know what has worked for you. Plz 2 halp? kthxbai....","createdDate":"2009-03-10T01:23:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-10T11:55:46.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4383","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I'm usually a person who tries to find the most simple solutions before trying the complex ones. Transparency, for me is no different. Transparency, at its root just means that information is being exposed for people to discover. The key here, is that the information needs to be usable once it is discovered. Transparency for transparency's sake is a waste of time.\n\nSo here's my ideas for simple things we can do immediately to achieve more effective transparency:\n\n1 - mandatory (and enforced) posting of meeting agendas and minutes to a central location, that has RSS feeds available for each committee. Even the most interested and motivated people won't go out of their way to find all the different committee minutes that reside all over the web.\n\n2 - website that aggregates all the committee feeds into one location, so that when a new committee is formed, you can get a notification about it. Then you can subscribe if you wish, or ignore and move on with your life.\n\n3 - common template for meeting minutes that promotes interest and discussion <u>outside</u> of the committee itself. This <u>MUST</u> include an overview of the minutes...a table of contents if you will. IE: at the top of each set of minutes, just a quick bullet list of the items that will are included below. If the meeting minutes are brief, there may be no need for this. This becomes important when feeds are available, so that people can very quickly see what the topics of discussion were, and not have to drill down into layers of text to find what was actually talked about.\n\n4 - transparency cannot be the sole target. <u>Effective</u> transparency must be the goal. At each small step of the process, the people communicating must take a few seconds to ensure that what they are divulging is both understandable and a benefit to their audience. Eventually this becomes second nature. It does not benefit anyone to have boat-loads of information thrown at them in the name of transparency, if you get buried under the weight of the content. This does not mean that information is removed from the record for being too wordy or full of jargon. It simply means that there may need to be that list that simplifies the document down to its key topics.\n\n5 - Grassroots movements are generally, in my experience more effective than individually led top-down directives. For me, its a numbers game. If you have 50 people on lower levels all working for the same thing, its better than having 1 upper level administrator pushing an agenda that has no grounding with the peons below. The best process IMO, is to find your supporters first. Find out who supports your idea or your project. If you don't find anyone that agrees with you, maybe you need to focus elsewhere. If you find people have a stake in what you are doing, then you can grow from there. The people that have a stake might often be the lower level people (there's your grassroots peeps), but ideally you'll want to identify an upper level person who shares your vision. While you're working on getting the idea off the ground, you can have that upper level person making sure the ceiling isn't so low you're going to bump your head as soon as you all stand up.\n\nMaybe I'm naive (but in my experience i dont think so) :-) .... but i think that the most simple solutions are often the best. Once you solve the small issues, you can take on the larger ones. If we make it easy for people to post information AND we make it easy for people for find and digest that same information, we've taken a big step towards effective transparency.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T11:55:46.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4287","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","title":"SIS Feeds","description":"Mike Vysocka and I were talking today about the new SIS feeds coming out of People Soft. We were debating if we had all of the necessary information we might want. He pointed out that there is no view for faculty/staff. Is that something other developers might want also? Should we consider asking for that addition?","createdDate":"2009-03-06T17:02:52.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-11T13:01:26.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4507","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Actual date fields. Check STU_BIO for the DOB. Initially, when I pulled the data, it determined that everyone had died on January 1st 2001 (01-01-01). The data still thinks they died on January 1st 1901, but I'm reasonably confident that not many people will have that as their birth or death date (so it can be more safely ignored) and understand that it is filler for \"empty\".","createdDate":"2009-03-11T13:01:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4505","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I don't care about field order, because they are indexed by field name and really there is no useful reason (other than looking pretty, and that should have been considered when the table was initially created) for fields to be reordered in a database structure without adding or removing fields. If I have extra fields they just won't be used until the next day after a \"heads up\" e-mail lets me know that the remote schema has changed.\n\nYour point makes sense though and I'll ensure that we're not relying on field order or having a certain number of fields.","createdDate":"2009-03-11T12:51:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4465","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Send an email request to Connie Reitfort (connie_reitfort@ncsu.edu).","createdDate":"2009-03-10T19:35:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4418","contributorName":"211tgo999ov7e","description":"Which tables are you looking at that only have two digits of the year? Almost every non-timestamp field I've seen that handles dates is formatted CYYS.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:27:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4414","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"Yes, because if they add a field, or reorder the fields, then your program breaks. In the first case, you have an extra field that your program doesn't know where to put. In the second, everything could get shifted over and even if the program doesn't break because of data type mismatches, your data is corrupt because you can't call it properly.\n\nIn the case where you own the database, using SELECT * in your programs then prevents you from making these changes to the tables for the same reason.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:22:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4408","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Even if you want all of the fields?","createdDate":"2009-03-10T13:01:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4374","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"You're going to need to look for a different source for faculty/staff, by definition you're not going to get that from SIS.\n\nFor Engineering's pulls we're using to_char() on date field types from Oracle. SELECT * is bad.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T21:41:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4365","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"You're probably going to have to be very specific about what information you're requesting from them if an outside contractor is going to have any sort of access to SIS related data.\n\nYou can get more general information on the new <a href=\"http://www.fis.ncsu.edu/sis/\">SIS website</a> and use their feedback form to get in touch with the appropriate people.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T17:02:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4355","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"My guess is that only the Oracle functions are available on Oracle. They do have a TO_CHAR() function, but I'm not interested in specifying individual fields. With the session variable set, doing a \"SELECT *\" is a viable and clean option while still returning well formed datetimes.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T13:08:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4350","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"We actually hadn't gotten to that issue yet as we were just handed the table dumps mid last week and were just doing a review of available information.\n\nBut would't it be possible to use MySQL's Date_Format() function when you are pulling a date? Like I said we haven't actually implemented anything yet, but that would be my first thought, though it is a bit of a pain to have to do that.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T12:41:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4344","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"Does anyone know who to contact to request a SIS feed? We're going to need a feed for a project being done by an outside contractor.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T12:33:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4341","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Damian or Mike: How did you go about resolving the dates that were coming out?\n\nInitially it was impossible for me to tell the difference between 1900 and 2000 because it was returning only two digits for the year. I ended up having to set a session variable with the following (MySQL friendly) command:\n\nALTER SESSION SET NLS_DATE_FORMAT = 'YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS'","createdDate":"2009-03-09T12:27:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4292","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"The latter. Though I do believe they are Oracle Views. They are already in place, you should be able to request access? I dunno the process, it was taken care of for me.","createdDate":"2009-03-06T19:02:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4289","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Definitely. We want as much info out of that thing as possible. Any idea how the feeds are going to be structured yet? XML of some sorts? Or will it be like the old sybase \"feeds\" which were really just views?","createdDate":"2009-03-06T18:07:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4281","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Mozilla Focusing on Mobile Web Technologies","description":"An Interview with Mozilla chairwoman Mitchell Baker about Mozilla's plans for 2009. An updated Firefox and Thunderbird and a lot of work for mobile browsers!\n\n<a href=\"http://www.newsweek.com/id/187745\">http://www.newsweek.com/id/187745</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-06T13:38:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-09T12:34:52.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4347","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Fennec is nice (and scores well on the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acid3\">Acid 3 test</a>).\n\nHowever, I'm still more excited about TraceMonkey (Mozilla's make-javascript-faster offering), which they're intending to ship with Shiretoko (Firefox 3.1). Of course, because TraceMonkey isn't just some minor feature, they're <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/devnews/index.php/2009/03/06/shiretoko-to-be-named-firefox-35/\">renaming the Shiretoko release to Firefox 3.5</a>.","createdDate":"2009-03-09T12:34:52.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4264","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Polls (Advanced or Basic)","description":"Has anyone implemented the Poll or Advanced Poll module on their Drupal 6 site? I know its still in beta (the module), but it seems to integrate with views/blocks. What im trying to do is manipulate the views that come out of the box, so i can change a few settings.","createdDate":"2009-03-05T20:52:30.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-05T20:52:31.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4194","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"NCSU office seeking web developer","description":"Hi,\n\nI am a web designer in the Office for Equal Opportunity. We are looking for a web developer to carry out a new design for our office website (currently at <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/equal_op\">www.ncsu.edu/equal_op</a>). The site was implemented way back in 2004 and is comprised of somewhere 100-150 pages that use a single Dreamweaver template. We also have a website at <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/dso\">www.ncsu.edu/dso</a> that is an affiliated office with a newer website. We would like the two websites to look more similar so that people know we are part of the same organization, but the DSO site does not necessarily need to be updated at this time (although we may be open to it). Unfortunately, the code for the DSO site is not standardized on a template and could use some cleaning up on the back-end. This site is also probably about 100-150 pages.\n\nIf you or your group are able to take on this project (or know of someone who can), please let me know. As designer, I would present sketches, requirements, and ideas and answer questions. I would need an estimate of hours/billing and some samples of your work.\n\nThanks!","createdDate":"2009-03-03T17:45:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-04T02:25:43.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4220","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"I should clarify that this is not a position for hire, just a short-term project. Thanks!","createdDate":"2009-03-04T02:25:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4180","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","title":"Drupal updated to 6.10","description":"The OIT-hosted drupal sites have all been updated to use Drupal 6.10. This security patch was released on Feb 25th.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T16:09:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-03T19:25:16.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4202","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Actually, this one was slow. Tim posted a bugtrack warning about 6.9 to me about 2-3 weeks before 6.10 finally came out. Ah well.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T19:25:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4199","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"is it just me or does a new release of drupal come out every morning? grrr.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T18:48:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4196","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"thanks Charles --- you rock.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T18:31:27.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4178","contributorName":"halmeeks","title":"Joomla vs. WordPress Article","description":"I found this article interesting in comparing two tools that outwardly are not very similar, but do share a bit of common functionality. From my purely liteweight perspective, I found WordPress much easier to comprehend for my limited needs. But I think the bigger message is the question of who are developers writing for: is it other programmers or for content creators? I realize the line here is blurred, but it is something I encounter a lot.\n\nAnyway, here's the article:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.playingwithwire.com/2009/03/open-source-and-usability-joomla-vs-wordpress/\">http://www.playingwithwire.com/2009/03/open-source-and-usability-joomla-vs-wordpress/</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-03T15:56:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-11T19:45:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4529","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Considering that the article was exploring usability it's no surprise they left Drupal out. When it comes to Drupal and content creators (if I may paraphrase Monty Python), \"This is not a CMS for installing, this is a CMS for lying down and avoiding.\"\n\nYou assert that usability is not the equal of \"core design\". To quote another famous comedian, \"I find your lack of faith disturbing.\" ;-) But that's not really the point, is it? Your comments juxtaposed against Hal's clearly show that CMS value is derived from from end user--you on the \"programmer\" end of Hal's scale with your preference for Drupal and he on the \"content creator\" end where usability is at least as important as good code.\n\nBut we do aim to satisfy around here so if you want Drupal in the mix, check out:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.goodwebpractices.com/other/wordpress-vs-joomla-vs-drupal.html\">Wordpress vs Joomla vs Drupal</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-11T19:45:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4241","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I saw this article and was disappointed that they didn't choose to evaluate Drupal. When it comes to a strong core design, Drupal is the clear winner. Usability is the fancy song and dance that you dress up a powerful software tool with to reach a wide audience. Fixing the usability issues is like styling a website. Fixing core functionality in lesser products such as Joomla is like starting the website over from scratch.\n\nUltimately, comparing a simple tool like WordPress to a multi-featured Joomla installation is like comparing a bicycle (which is quite effective and has a simple design) to a Walmart vacuum cleaner (it might do what you want with its plurality of connectors... in a wasteful though diverse sort of way). Of course, when you want to do much other than \"riding a bike\", you'll need a Wordpress technician to modify your bike into some mangled human-powered vacuum. Mixed metaphors sure are fun.","createdDate":"2009-03-04T13:49:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4149","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Google Reader","description":"Application: Google Reader\n\nURL: <a href=\"http://reader.google.com\">http://reader.google.com</a>\n\nWhat is it? An RSS feed aggregator\n\nI love me some news. I scour the internet looking for new things to read, new blogs to follow. It is an obsession really. So much so, that I was using a complicated system of bookmarks and good ole fashioned memory to remember all the sites I wanted to go to. That's all well and good when you have 3 or 4 sites you go to, but when you try to check 40 - 50 sites a day, it gets VERY time consuming.\n\nHere is where an RSS feed aggregator comes in to play. For a while, I tried to use Thunderbird's built-in RSS reader. It did most of what I needed it to do, but it relied on Thunderbird, which is not a web-based application. That means that when I read a feed from home, it wouldn't mark it as read on my work computer. This is a pain because I am a multi-machine type of dude. It's just how I roll :) Also, the main reason I switched away from Thunderbird is that I couldn't read the alt tag on XKCD, which meant I missed half the joke. That just made me angry.\n\nHere is where Google sweeps in and saves the day. Most people, it seems, have at least heard of Google Reader, but a lot of people haven't ever given it a go. Since it is Google, it is online, which means that no matter where I read my feeds, they are consistently marked as read...even if I read them on my iPhone.\n\nGoogle reader also has some nice features that you don't get in other feed aggregators. One of my favorites is that it marks items as read as you scroll through them. This is a feature you can disable, but it prevents me from having to \"mark as read\" everything I read.\n\nIt also has the ability to star certain posts, so that you can refer back to them easily. This is helpful if I am reading something at home, but I want to make note of it so I can do something with it at work.\n\nGoogle Reader also allows you to share stories. It's sorta like syndicating your own aggregations. You can mark any story as \"shared\" and instantly, it will be added to a custom Google Reader page for your account. It is a cool way to share interesting stories through RSS.\n\nA few other features that are important to highlight that might convince you of Google Reader's superiority:\n\n* It's simple to import your feeds from the feed reader you may already use\n* Easily export your subscriptions as an OPML file\n* Easily add a subscription to Google Reader from any webpage via a convenient bookmark\n* Available in over 20 languages (even Australian English!)\n* Keep your subscriptions organized in folders\n\nThere are lots of other cool features in Google Reader, so I would encourage you to check it out; you've got nothing to lose. I can't tell you how much time it has saved me. Check out the Google Reader Team blog for more info (<a href=\"http://googlereader.blogspot.com\">http://googlereader.blogspot.com</a>).\n\nHappy RSSificating!","createdDate":"2009-03-03T14:29:48.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-03T15:21:45.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4161","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"i am also a big fan of Google Reader, for many of the same reasons. Although i am now subscribed to about 3 times as many feeds as i used to be, i find that i spend less time reading them. Now that their all centralized, and categorized into folders, i can focus on what's important, and leave the unimportant ones till i get home (or during lunch at my desk). It helps that i've categorized them into a few personalized folders named: NCSU Feeds, Design Tutorials, Inspirations, News, Friends, and Time Wasters (displayed all the way at the base, so as not to pull me in).","createdDate":"2009-03-03T14:43:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4151","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Ditto.\n\nAnd I mean that in the most excellent use of the word ditto - <a href=\"http://comic.conversationswithplasticdinosaurs.com/2007/03/features.html\">not the dinosaur-esque use</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-03T14:39:39.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4121","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Do's and Dont's of Higher Ed Web Strategy","description":"I thought this was extremely interesting:\n\n<a href=\"http://blog.dojo-web.com/\">http://blog.dojo-web.com/</a>\n\nHow many of the \"dont's\" and \"do's\" do we do?","createdDate":"2009-03-02T15:27:46.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-09T17:35:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4156","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I'm going to invent some:\n* Do pay attention to your Y-Slow score. Many people don't have fast connections, so the half megabyte we serve up can mean a two minute wait.\n* Do make your site useful. The people who already use your website regularly will thank you and it will probably translate somewhat to the new users as well.\n* Don't have pictures of \"person\". If there is just one person in your pictures of campus, it will make it feel lonely. The joke I keep hearing about Pembroke's \"Where learning gets personal\" relates directly to the belief that there is only one student attending the school.\n* Do make it easy to get funding. Whether it is from application fees, tuition, grants or donations, making it easy for people to give you money means they'll have less time or incentive to second guess their decision. Afterwards, thank and inspire them (get them excited about their involvement) to minimize the \"buyer's remorse\".\n* Do validate your pages. ... ok, that's something I want to see, but it's a bit silly that most websites have a blaring red X in the bottom right hand corner. To me, website validation indicates a dedication to standards, quality, and shows that you care about what other people think of your site.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T14:41:17.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:4023","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Part 5: My Interview With NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"The last installment of my interview with NCSU CIO Dr. Marc Hoit gets a little more personal as Dr. Hoit talks about what he is reading, what is playing on his MP3 player, and what he was most proud of during his time as interim CIO at the University of Florida.\n\nBefore getting to the interview, a big thanks to Dr. Hoit for allowing us to interview him. Also big thanks to OIT's <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profile/JohnMartin\">John Martin</a>, <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profile/JenRiehle\">Jen Riehle</a> and <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profile/GarrisonLocke\">Garrison Locke</a> for helping with the edits of the interview.\n\nIn case you missed it, here is <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-1-my-interview-with-ncsu\">part 1</a>, <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-2-my-interview-with-ncsu\">part 2</a>, <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-3-my-interview-with-ncsu\">part 3</a> and <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-4-my-interview-with-ncsu\">part 4</a> of the interview.\n\n========================================================\n\n<b>What accomplishments were you most proud of at the University of Florida?</b>\n\nI would say it was consolidating some of the IT functions there. I took all of the student systems that ran under the registrar and brought them together. I found out that just after I left, two major things I was trying to consolidate were completed, and they also announced a permanent CIO that reported to the correct place. I helped them move to a structure that will help them function better in the future.\n\nAnother accomplishment was with regards to a campus-wide email system, similar to the Groupwise Email Initiative work that\u2019s going on here. I got people to buy into an idea, and then got 60% of campus into a central system.\n\n\n<b>Anything you wish you could have done differently?</b>\n\nI wish they\u2019d had the foresight to make changes more rapidly instead of having me in an interim position for four years. It would have been better to make the changes to the CIO\u2019s office, have everyone report to the proper place, and give them the authority to do things\u2014like they\u2019ve done here. It would have been better for the institution. I think this university has made some outstanding decisions in that respect, and of course I got the job, and I like it! I think the direction that NCSU is heading in will be the direction for IT in universities in the future.\n\n\n<b>How important is it for campus to be a proponent of open standards and protocols?</b>\n\nI'm a big believer in having standards and following them. But like everything else, you have to balance the productivity, the cost, the gains, and so on. For example, many email systems contain elements that aren\u2019t standard. Microsoft Exchange, for example, has some nonstandard SMTP and internal exchange for accounts. There are some huge benefits to that, but some of the email doesn\u2019t meet the standards set forth for transfers.\n\nThe Internet Explorer (IE) browser is another example. There was some nonstandard functionality in it, though I think the newer versions have gotten better. The point is that you have to consider what you\u2019re willing to sacrifice to follow standards.\n\nIt\u2019s the same thing with cost and scale. You have to look at its benefits in the bigger picture. My challenge is to get the job done efficiently and effectively . There are people who say, \u201cOpen standards solve everyone's problems.\u201d In reality, they solve a lot of problems, but there are still a lot of open standards that don\u2019t yet solve problems at the enterprise level. They\u2019re getting there, and whenever we can use them in a way that doesn\u2019t hinder us, I\u2019m all for it.\n\n\n<b>Favorite Book?</b>\n\nRight now I'm reading The HERetic\u2019s Daughter, about a girl growing up in Salem, Massachusetts, where the girl\u2019s grandmother saw her mother go through the Salem Witch Trials. I\u2019m also reading about business process change, and how to manage everything associated with it, but that\u2019s not as exciting.\n\n\n<b>What\u2019s on your MP3 player?</b>\n\nI\u2019m a 50s, 60s, 70s and 80s guy, although my daughter tries to keep me a little more current and every once in a while turns me on to a new band. One of the more interesting ones she pointed me to was \u201cGirl Talk.\u201d It\u2019s a guy that does mashups of a bunch of different styles. It\u2019s pretty cool stuff.\n\n\n<b>What RSS feeds do you subscribe to?</b>\n\nI don\u2019t really subscribe to feeds, because my inbox is just too full, and I'm not willing to pull more into it. Nothing is consistent enough that I always want to see it. I still read Slashdot and CNET to see some of the more popular stuff. And I read the Technician and the News &amp; Observer every day to keep current on what\u2019s going on locally.\n\n\n<b>You\u2019re a Blackberry user. Is there a mobile app that you can\u2019t live without?</b>\n\nTwitterberry is really cool. And I'm only a Blackberry user because that\u2019s what gives me the best functionality in our email environment. It\u2019s not perfect, but none of them are. In the past I had a Windows mobile device\u2014a Motorola Q. It had some things I liked better than the Blackberry and some I didn't. The Blackberry is a productivity tool for me; its integration is really nice. I didn\u2019t buy it for its coolness. Lots of folks like the iPhone, but we don\u2019t have the syncing at the level here that I need. I looked at the touchscreen Blackberry and it just isn\u2019t there yet.\n\n\n<b>Coke or Pepsi?</b>\n\nWhichever one is on tap, but I\u2019m not a soda drinker. I\u2019ll drink water. But, I like espresso more than soda.\n\n========================================================\n\nThats it! Hope you all enjoyed it!","createdDate":"2009-02-27T13:40:07.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-02T20:06:43.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3969","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Part 4: My Interview With NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"Part 4 of my interview with NCSU CIO Dr. Marc Hoit explored his views of social networking and Twitter. <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-1-my-interview-with-ncsu\">Part 1</a>, <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-2-my-interview-with-ncsu\">Part 2</a> and <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-3-my-interview-with-ncsu\">Part 3</a> of my interview are also available.\n\n===============================================\n\n<b>How do you see the future of OIT being shaped by social networking, or do you?</b>\n\nI am very interested in looking at social networking tools as a way to enhance collaboration. Most of the social networking activity I have read says that social networking is not the way to form communities; it\u2019s a way to enhance an existing community\u2019s collaboration. I am fully in favor of using social networking.\n\nI\u2019d like to see how we can use social networks to research activities not only within our campus, but outside of our campus. To see how we can we work with the rest of the UNC system, the Research Triangle area, universities, to collaborate. They are probably looking at the same issues we are with regards to Web hosting, email, ERP systems and student systems. If social networking tools can help these groups communicate to collaborate, then great.\n\nOne thing we have to remember is that a tool is only as good as its application in the right instance. You can\u2019t force social networking activity just because you have a tool. You have to instill social networking into the culture, and then use the tool to help you carry it out.\n\n\n<b>We have members from ECU and UNC-Charlotte on our NCSU Web Developers social network who have helped a lot in our discussions about Web hosting.</b>\n\nThat is the perfect use of a social network. If you have an environment where people are willing to share, it\u2019s great. Higher Education is one of those places where we\u2019re allowed to do that. We don't have trade secrets really. When we open source and share things, we\u2019re not going to make money, but we get better results and oftern more in return. We have open sourced the Virtual Computer Lab (VCL).\n\n<b>Twitter is pretty popular with some of us. You are on it and generally post on your way to meetings. I notice you didn\u2019t join until you came to NCSU. What inspired you to use Twitter, and what have you gotten out of it?</b>\n\nThere were a couple of things I was looking at doing before I left Florida. I wanted to start a blog, and I\u2019d heard about Twitter, which I was interested in, and to me, is just a micro-blogging service. It\u2019s faster turnaround communication vehicle for doing a lot of the same things as blogs. And as I understand it, blogs are dying and Twitter is taking over\u2014at least in the media I\u2019ve been reading.\n\nThese two things were in the back of my mind as potential ways\u2014as one of the leaders of IT\u2014to communicate some of the things going on. For instance, if I tweet that I\u2019m going to a meeting with NetApp or EMC, it can get people following me to think about possibilities and ideas to improve IT on campus. So, I use it as a communication tool to keep people informed about what I\u2019m doing and what I think people in OIT will be interested in.\n\nTwitter can be used as a two-way communication tool, but I'm not using it that way. I could \u201cfollow\u201d people, which I\u2019m not currently doing, and I could look for responses to my tweets, but quite honestly I just don\u2019t have the bandwidth to operate that way. I\u2019m going to use the governance structure and other methods to solicit responses.\n\nMy interest\u2026 I love that stuff, I mean\u2026 I\u2019m a technology fan. If anybody remembers the little HP-100\u2014the first portable clamshell computer with MSDOS, about the size of a calculator\u2014I had one of those, and I had the Palm when it first came out. I love the stuff if it can help, but all too often I\u2019ve found that a technology is \u201cnot quite there\u201d yet, and because it can\u2019t meet my needs, it sits in my drawer. For that reason, I\u2019ve backed off a little when it comes to jumping into things that are fun, things that I\u2019d like to play with, but can\u2019t get the value out of because my time is too crunched. I\u2019m being a little more selective about what I pick up.\n\n\n<b>So, you\u2019re using Twitter to get information out. Staff are using it as a two-way communication vehicle to keep up with what immediate colleagues are doing, as well as groups across campus, the UNC system, and the industry. Do you think that\u2019s a positive thing?</b>\n\nAnything that can get staff to communicate and figure out what\u2019s going on is beneficial. You all have to figure out what works for you. I figured out what works for me based on my style and needs. If all of a sudden you are following 10000 people on Twitter and spending most of your time looking at Twitter without it helping to get your work done, then no, that is not a positive thing.\n\nOn the other hand, if you have Twitter set up such that the people you are connected to are providing value to what you\u2019re doing, or how you\u2019re operating, then I\u2019m all for it. And that goes for a lot of things\u2014daily phone calls, blog postings, focus groups, whatever communication vehicle that doesn\u2019t waste time. I hate information and meetings that are a waste of time. I just don't have that much time, and I want to use it effectively.\n\n===============================================\n\nCheck back tomorrow for the last part of my interview, where Dr. Hoit speaks about his most proud accomplishment from his time at University of Florida, his views on open standards, and what is playing on his MP3 player right now!","createdDate":"2009-02-26T16:05:28.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-02T20:07:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4031","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I don't see twitter killing blogging. If anything, it has enhanced my blog entries. Perhaps they are not as frequent, because the short stuff I just tweet about and am done with it. But I think my blog entries have actually benefited from it.","createdDate":"2009-02-27T15:16:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4025","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"\"And as I understand it, blogs are dying and Twitter is taking over\u2014at least in the media I\u2019ve been reading.\"\n\nYeah, that's what my Twitter News feed is saying... ;)\n\nActually, I don't use Twitter, because I didn't see any value in it (insert obligatory Luddite or new fangled technology quote here). However, now I see how it could be useful assuming that the people that I follow or read responses from have a high 'meaningful post' ratio.\n\nIf you haven't already modded this Insightful or Funny: CowboyNeal, story, andnothingofvaluewaslost, netcraftconfirmsit.","createdDate":"2009-02-27T13:48:17.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3941","contributorName":"1l94q89y956k5","title":"Drupal Help - Preserving Changes between Test/Development & Live Sites","description":"First, a point of etiquette -- am I in the right place? (this may be more of a MySQL / phpMyAdmin question, or should be under 'Web Programming'...or even drupal.org)\n\nSecond -- if I am building / updating stuff on an offline test site/db, and I want to integrate my changes into the live site, is there any really easy way to preserve whatever has occurred on the live site? At the moment I'm mainly concerned with the information from the Statistics module -- I don't have any users messing with content (like creating / editing nodes), but I would like to preserve the access statistics so that my \"What's Popular\" boxes are still relevant, as well as the 'top referers' and other semi-useful info.\n\nI suppose you could boil it down to this: (1) what are the tables used by the Statistics module / access logs, and what's the best way to merge them with another site? (2) ditto for merging all of the tables, but preserving newer content?","createdDate":"2009-02-25T20:06:12.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-26T13:40:44.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3964","contributorName":"1l94q89y956k5","description":"Oh I know about that stuff you both mentioned. In my situation, it's more like I'm working on the site for a day or several days, and then I want to merge my changes with whatever has gone on with the site -- so while I've been developing or moving stuff around, someone could have written a news article or modified a page. Even if I issue the content freeze, I'd still lose the page hits / access logs. So, the problem would work both ways -- I can copy the live site every day to the dev site, but then I'd lose my changes, or when I upload the dev site to the live site, I'd lose the user changes.\n\nI think for now I'll probably just ditch the access logs, since I think WebStats shows the same stuff already, and I can probably \"manually\" add the page counters in node_counters. For newer content, the Admin / Content Management should order the content list by most recently updated, so I can compare that list. Provided people aren't very active, this could work for a little while, but if anybody can suggest something more elegant and \"Drupalish\" I'd love to know.","createdDate":"2009-02-26T13:40:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3961","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Drupal has a maintenance mode that you can activate that is extremely helpful for things like that.","createdDate":"2009-02-26T12:56:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3943","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"It's usually a good idea to initiate a content freeze, copy the live database to the test environment, make the appropriate changes, copy back the modified tables, and then release the content freeze. I don't know if Drupal provides a button for this functionality, but the old fashioned informational e-mail saying \"Don't edit the site after 5pm today or your content will be lost.\" is typically effective.","createdDate":"2009-02-25T21:37:23.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3926","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Part 3: My Interview With NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"Part 3 of my interview with Dr. Marc Hoit, CIO of NCSU, explored OIT's role in bringing IT across campus together. <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-1-my-interview-with-ncsu\">Part 1</a> and <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-2-my-interview-with-ncsu\">Part 2</a> of my interview are also available.\n\n==============================================\n\n<b>Because IT at NC State has traditionally been decentralized, we have a lot of groups in a lot of places doing the same kind of work. What do you think about this structure, and do you want to change it?</b>\n\nThe reason I have developed the Strategic Operations Plan is to change that culture. You\u2019ll notice that I am involving external people in all of my committees. If you look at the Identity and Access Management team, for example, it\u2019s has people from the colleges, from departments, and people from OIT on it. This is specifically to uncover duplicated or overlapping work. It\u2019s a chance to brainstorm, \u201cYou need Identity Management. We need Identity Management. In most cases, 80% of what we\u2019re doing is common and 20% of what we\u2019re doing is unique. So, let OIT do what\u2019s common and you can have the freedom to customize your 20%.\n\nSo, to generalize this, when there is a product or service that can benifit from scale, we centralize the portion that makes sense for OIT to do, and we collaborate with the partners to build their portion into the product or service. This works best when addressing a campus-wide product or service.\n\nIn situations where only two or three departments or colleges have need for something, things are probably not going to scale. Take collaboration tools for instance. They are not at the level that they are used pervasively on campus. In this type of situation, we want to set up a committee to determine a \u201cstandard for collaboration tools\u201d so we do not grow into a tower of babel. The approach would be for OIT to bring the disparate groups together, find a cost structure that helps them, and perhaps make a collaborative purchase. And then, stay involved as the service grows to see if it gets large enough (pervasive), and if we can identify commonalities that might lead to a standard OIT service.\n\n<b>Do you see OIT being the catalyst to bringing people together?</b>\n\nAbsolutely. My governance view is that some things need to come from the top down and other things thrive with a grassroots approach.\n\nThere are things that I will notice or that will be brought to my attention from a General Administration (GA) or campus wide perspective. These are the top-down things. Typically, I will announce these as initiatives or imperatives and create task forces or bring to committees through which to engage stakeholders in coming up with a proposal for the best solution. These proposals will return for potential changes and then final approval through the appropriate channels.\n\nAnd then there\u2019s the grassroots approach. An example of this is what Engineering is doing with an idea for video sharing. They\u2019ve implemented some great solutions, and other people are now interested in the solution. I hope the collaboration gets to the point where everyone starts telling other people, until it gets to the point that OIT can say, \u201cWe\u2019re ready to offer this as an OIT solution or service.\u201d\n\nI expect both the top-down and the grassroots approaches to be based on trust and collaboration. We need to move forward efficiently with the appropriate approach for the given situation.\n\n<b>How do you see centralizing efforts affecting departmental budgets?</b>\n\nMy hope is that it will save departments money. But as I mentioned earlier, some of that freed up capital still has to go towards the departmental function\u2014that idea of, \u201cYou\u2019re doing something for $100, you give me $60 to do that for you, which I can do at that price due to economies of scale, and you keep the $40 to redirect as you see fit to accomplish your mission. Again, it\u2019s that idea of, \u201cIt\u2019s voluntary. I have a great service; you want to purchase my service because it\u2019s good, and cheaper. You benefit. I benefit.\u201d\n\n<b>Currently, the Nelnet campus credit card interface costs the departments a lot of money\u2014thousands of dollars up front. What do you think about making that service free to campus, with perhaps OIT covering the initial cost and the departments covering the transactional fees?</b>\n\nI can\u2019t answer this question completely, as I\u2019m not yet at the level of understanding about it that I\u2019d like to be. However, I can tell you that we\u2019re doing a complete rate review of every service we offer. In the future, we\u2019re all, including our customers, going to be able to see why a particular rate is what it is.\n\nMy understanding is that part of the Nelnet service works statewide, as part of a General Administration (GA) solution, I believe. There is a monthly connector fee for using credit card transactions in general, as well as a per transaction fee like every credit card service in the industry.\n\nSo, if there is a $50 per month fee per connector, then each connector needs to have a fairly high number of transactions in order to keep the overall cost to an effective level because of the overhead. I know groups on campus are using other services, too, so we need to ask ourselves, \u201cIs the Nelnet service for everybody? Should we be hosting Nelnet-like service ourselves? Maybe we have one $50 fee that is spread across everybody using it. Maybe we do a second service for people who need less volume.\u201d\n\nWe need to understand what it would take to develop such an interface. I expect OIT to be able to say to our customers, \u201cWe charge x dollars an hour to develop Web pages, so we could develop an interface for y dollars. If you can do it yourself, you\u2019re more than welcome to do that. We\u2019ll answer simple questions for you, but beyond that, you\u2019re on your own.\u201d We have to find that balance. I expect us to make the rate available, in support of our transparency goal, so that both we and our customers can make informed, consistent decisions.\n\n==============================================\n\nWant to hear more? Check in tomorrow when Dr. Hoit answers questions about how social networking will affect OIT in the future, and how Twitter has impacted his time here at NCSU.","createdDate":"2009-02-25T15:13:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-02T20:07:36.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3845","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Jing: Capturing Your Screenz","description":"Application: Jing\n\nWebsite: <a href=\"http://www.jingproject.com\">http://www.jingproject.com</a>\n\nWhat it is: Image and video capturing and sharing tool.\n\nHow many times have you been trying to help someone or show someone something, and you need them to send you a screen shot or you want to send them a screen shot? Probably 54,000. At least that's my current count.\n\nIf your unfortunate to have to run Windows, then you know how tedious it can be to print screen and then crop the part of the image you want. If you have a Mac at least you can <img src=\"discussions/109-dhbndf9q_2fpmbphcr_b.jpg?width=243\" alt=\"\" width=\"243\" height=\"250\" style=\"float: left; padding: 7px 7px 7px 0;\"/>skip the cropping part with a handy Apple+Shift+4. But you're still left with the task of either emailing or instant messaging the picture, or posting it to some web space somewhere where they can view it. That's too many steps...\n\nWouldn't it be nice if there was a FREE way that you could just click three times and have your image or a video available for viewing anywhere by anyone? Well now you can! (If you think I'm sounding like the Sham Wow guy, just picture me with an unnecessary headset on.)\n\nJing is a tiny app (for Mac OS X and Windows) that allows you to easily take a screen shot (or video!) of part or all of your desktop and then easily upload it to Screencast.com, save it, or copy it. It also lets you do things like highlight a part of your image, add text, or put an arrow pointing to something. It also saves a history of your captures so you can get to them later if you need to resend something.\n\nIf you have your own server, you can configure it to use FTP or upload to Flickr or YouTube.\n\n<img src=\"discussions/110-dhbndf9q_3dhh8xbcf_b.gif?width=164\" alt=\"\" width=\"164\" height=\"250\" style=\"float: left; padding: 7px 7px 7px 0;\"/>This has saved me bunches of time already, and has become a very valuable tool around our office.\n\nBut don't take my word for it...just watch the video for yourself:\n\n<a href=\"http://video.techsmith.com/jing/latest/demo/jing_overview_video/jing_overview_video.html\">http://video.techsmith.com/jing/latest/demo/jing_overview_video/jing_overview_video.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-24T13:07:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-24T13:14:52.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3841","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Part 2: My Interview With NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"Part 2 of my interview with Dr. Marc Hoit, CIO of NCSU, got a little deeper into how he sees OIT running under his oversight. In case you missed it, you can <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/part-1-my-interview-with-ncsu\">read Part 1 here</a>.\n\n============================================================\n\n<b>Regarding funding, what is your cost recovery approach?</b>\n\nThere are two very different funding approaches in an organization: collecting up front for services, or charging back for services.\n\nCollecting up front can give the illusion of a no-cost option, but nothing is free\u2014somebody has to pay for it. It\u2019s just that in this approach, central funding covers the cost of services that are shared out as required by your customers. In most cases you have to place limits on the services with this approach.\n\nThe opposite approach is to charge back for services rendered. This approach also requires operating in a cost-effective way; closest to scale; and reducing costs over time, which increases trust in your service; and in a way that customers use their funds to pay per use for a service they are happy with. A couple of examples of this are telephones and networking. We have telephone system infrastructure costs, and we do our best to keep those costs very reasonable for what you get. Compared to Time Warner\u2019s Road Runner services, our networking costs are cheap, providing 100M to the desktop and up to 1G in some places. So for the services we\u2019re offering, the prices are really good. I think we\u2019re very efficient at that and we are at scale.\n\nAnother service that we provide using the up-front approach is our Enterprise Resource Planning service. Everyone gets access to the ERP systems and they pay that centrally. We build the system, and they use it as much as they need to, since it\u2019s a universal and critical business operation.\n\nDepending on the use of the service and the cost, you can work in between these two extreme approaches.\n\nA model that I\u2019ve used in the past and that has worked well works like this, using email at the University of Florida as an example. We\u2019re moving to the GroupWise system and it costs a certain amount to get built, which we\u2019ll do as cost-efficiently as possible. Once it\u2019s built, we\u2019ll be able to calculate what the cost is per user. As the user base grows, that cost will come down, approaching some very reasonable cost when scaled to our entire campus.\n\nThen, we can go to departments and say, \"Look, you\u2019re running a mail server that costs you $3000, which every three years or so you have to replace or upgrade and buy software and antivirus protection for. You also have to have someone manage it for you, which costs x dollars, and you might only have 500 users on it. Looking at your cost per user, you\u2019re spending the same, or up to five times what we\u2019ll spend, and our service is enterprise-wide with redundant systems, backup, 24x7 service and professionally managed. So let\u2019s make a deal\u2014save some of your money by giving us 60% of your budget for this service and the remaining 40% you can put to use in producing your core work or services; and we\u2019ll provide your email service.\u201d So, it\u2019s a trade where we get the resources to offer the service at reasonable costs, and they get a return of some of their support dollars to use toward other needs\u2014and everybody wins. The key is that we can scale the service and they can\u2019t, because there is no way a service scaled at a college or department level can compete with one scaled at a campus level.\n\nIn order for this model to work, the system has to be opt-in. We can\u2019t force people to join. They need to join in because they see value in it\u2014value at an equivalent or reduced cost for the same service they currently have. Another requirement for the success of this model is that our service be excellent. It has to be outstanding and at or above a performance level that they are expecting.\n\n<b>A quoted question from one of our members: \"My local team is finding incredible success with the idea of \"radical transparency\": that is, our meeting notes, our project planning, our team's activity stream, source code, and so on, are completely in the open\u2014open either to the world or to the thousands of account holders we have across the land-grant system. There's a historical fear in Higher Education IT\u2014I\u2019ve held the fear myself\u2014that being open with your work and processes will lead to a breakdown in expectation management, that people will misread your work as an \"official, coming project,\" for instance, or that such openness will lead to too much questioning by people about your work. We've found the complete opposite to be true. It has increased our productivity dramatically. Would this type of model work for the NC State IT community and OIT? Do you see a benefit in this model? What can we do as a campus to put more of our activity, work, and planning in the open in real-time?\"</b>\n\nIf you look at our Strategic Operations Plan, we\u2019ve used the words \u201cpervasive transparency.\u201d One of our goals is to do exactly what you\u2019re talking about, with some caveats. I believe transparency is critical\u2014that people need to get support, collaborate with each other, and take advantage of the benefit that having visibility to each other\u2019s work can bring. I have asked all of OIT to make our meeting notes and cost structures available on the Web.\n\nI haven\u2019t given thought yet to going as far as making interim source code available to people, but I\u2019ll certainly include that in my thought process going forward. Making that kind of work available is critical, particularly in areas such as Extension, because they need to know what\u2019s going on in order to feel like part of the team. We can do this with web conferencing, and it\u2019ll probably have to be video web conferencing, especially with our ongoing travel and budget restraints.\n\nThe idea of \u201cradical transparency\u201d is kind of interesting. I would be willing to try that on a project to see how it affects it. There are some things that I'm hesitant to do that with because of security concerns. Web hosting, I would have no concerns over. But doing that with our Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) process, for instance, I\u2019d be a little more hesitant about. However, I am not hesitant about putting a diverse group of people on a team to collaborate more, and making minutes and milestones related to their work available on the Web.\n\nTransparency is one of our goals. I\u2019m not sure I\u2019m ready to take it to the extent described in the question, but I\u2019m certainly willing to pilot it on a sample project.\n\n============================================================\n\nPart 3 of my interview will be posted tomorrow. See what Dr. Hoit has to say about centralizing IT efforts on campus, and how services, such as NelNet, will be evaluated in the future.","createdDate":"2009-02-24T12:45:21.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-02T20:07:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4167","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Just for the record, my example of WRAP was poorly written - and is somewhat of an obscure reference. Sorry about that.\n\nThere was a period of time in the last few years, where every set of meeting notes I wanted to look at (those few that actually showed up available to campus) was stuck behind WRAP. I'm trying to find an example, but can't at the moment (I thought the <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/it/uitc/\">UITC work</a> was once behind an authentication wall, but my memory appears flawed). Maybe it's not a problem anymore, and all of that information is slowly swinging back into the open again).\n\nThat actually has nothing to do with WRAP - and I should have written \"restricted to University account holders only\" - WRAP is just easier to say that (but, hey, not that I've ever shirked away from verbosity before, why start now? :-)\n\nMy point was mainly that it's absurd to stick most meeting notes and announcements behind an University-account only authentication wall like that. It's an impediment to producing and getting feeds of content updates (protected feeds have never really worked and usually boil down to just using some kind of unique hashkey in the url) and it just throws up an unnecessary roadblock to getting information.\n\nIf there's a real need for auth wall protections, split the data output, Sysnews is a decent model of information splitting here, it's a combination open+authenticated information feed, which is fine, I can understand some of the technical details staying behind an auth wall, but it's very useful to have a feed of the public details of that.\n\nSorry, I was pretty unclear.\n\nHowever, since you mention it, WRAP could probably be opened just fine. (I have no opinion of whether it should or shouldn't, however, it probably will never be, because there's a truckload of University Intellectual Property history that comes along with it)\n\nThe core of WRAP is cryptographically strong public/private key protection. I don't think I ever looked at the code that closely, but the people that created it here on campus and continue to maintain it are some of the most conscientious developers I've met. So I'm sure it could withstand public scrutiny. It's certainly a whole lot better than most of the auth protocols used in off-the-shelf open source software - and I bet very serious money it's better than many of the proprietary authentication buried in some the of the commercial software we get.\n\nKerberos is open source (and open protocol). Shibboleth is open source (and open protocol). OpenID (not a paradigm of high security, but good enough for most of the web) is open source and open protocol. So I don't buy your perfect example. And what would be vulnerable? OMG we might release what? Some departmental memos? Please.\n\nDo we have data that needs protecting at this university? Yes, but nowhere near what we do. And that's a continuing conversation that I'll have to reserve for a later verbose posting :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-03T15:07:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4141","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"When we do talk about actual security, a whitelist of allowed users is much better than a blacklist of \"problem IPs\". With the \"opportunities\" of cross-site scripting, SQL injection and arbitrary code execution, complex applications are open to a much higher level of scrutiny (that of those who enjoy stealing University quality Internet connections). By whitelisting users (through the use of WRAP), you limit the attack vector to a known quantity. Additionally, if it is open for all, it might be considered a \"University website\" with all the rights and restrictions granted thereunto. This could mean a lot of work making something accessible even though the actual users of the system do not have the associated accessibility needs.\n\nI'll admit that I'm playing devil's advocate in this last point, but these can be legitimate concerns for individuals who are trying to do their job without running afoul of University guidelines or malicious users.\n\nThe point is that while I value open access to information, there is always some risk involved. Whether that risk is worth the openness (open standards for encryption) or just means you'll get burned (broken hashing / encryption algorithms) all depends on the quality of the design.\n\nYou brought up the example of WRAP, and I think that is perfect. Last I checked, not everyone (in the world) can download WRAP. However, it has a lot of value that the world could benefit from. If it were open, how long do you think it would stay secure? If it did not stay secure, how many applications might become vulnerable? Would they need to be shut down? How long would they stay disabled? How difficult would it be to design a new solution which maintains the functionality but resolves the security issue that was being exploited? How do we ensure that there isn't still a way to exploit the new design? How much does this all cost? How long are we going to be unable to do our job while this process is going on?\n\nThe core infrastructure has a lot of dependent pieces. We saw with the global DNS exploit how even SSL is insecure and it still isn't completely resolved. However, the value of openness is ever present, though it can be an expensive and risky proposition. The definition of a noble cause indeed.","createdDate":"2009-03-03T14:13:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4073","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Exactly why is \"Transparency on the entire scope of operations planning\" - \"entirely another\"?\n\nLet me quote the President, if I may - while the President is talking about the <a href=\"http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/FreedomofInformationAct/\">Freedom of Information Act</a> specifically, I think it has bearing here:\n\n<blockquote>\"In the face of doubt, openness prevails. The Government should not keep information confidential merely because public officials might be embarrassed by disclosure, because errors and failures might be revealed, or because of speculative or abstract fears. Nondisclosure should never be based on an effort to protect the personal interests of Government officials at the expense of those they are supposed to serve.\"</blockquote>\n\nThat's not the way this campus operates today. We banter around the word \"security\" when we put things behind WRAP, or fail to share with our colleagues. And security is most often just a phrase for \"speculative or abstract fears\" I don't buy it.\n\nWhy on earth can't we be open first? And closed second? Instead of the current practice of \"closed information first, open when somebody complains about it\"?\n\nPeople can filter. But why not let me have that option rather than the information holder deciding that for me?","createdDate":"2009-02-27T21:54:30.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3808","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","title":"Need help identifying graphic tool","description":"Hi everyone,\n\nI will be doing some work on an existing website that uses a font/graphic that looks like this:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/dso/images/home/Disability-Services-Office.jpg\">http://www.ncsu.edu/dso/images/home/Disability-Services-Office.jpg</a>\n\nDoes anyone recognize the tool from which this might have been generated? The person who worked on it has left the university.\n\nI have Fireworks, Illustrator, and PhotoShop. I will play around with those and see if I can match it, but if anyone sees what is is right off the bat, please help! That would save me a lot of time.\n\nThanks,\nElizabeth","createdDate":"2009-02-23T16:31:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-08-11T02:17:25.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4905","contributorName":"2kureeaenviny","description":"Photoshop:\n\nInner and outer glow, drop shadow, gradient overlay with the right two colors, and the right font. Looks like a slight bevel too. Instead of an inner glow, it might be just a white outline.\n\nEdit: someone already answered.","createdDate":"2009-03-20T20:25:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3888","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Oh my goodness, thank you so much. I am very rusty at PhotoShop and was just now trying to get through this. I owe you some brownies.","createdDate":"2009-02-24T17:43:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3886","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Web 2.0 shiny ftw! Nice tutorial hal!","createdDate":"2009-02-24T16:22:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3883","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"I would bet Photoshop. I don't recognize the font, but I think I can approximate the effect.\n\nCreate a new document with a white background.\nOpen original document in new window.\nClick on Text Tool\nUse eyedropper to match font color to original document, then pick a shade lighter.\nControl-Click (or right-click) on text layer.\n\nSelect Blending Options\nCheck Drop Shadow, Bevel Emboss/Contour, Gradient Overlay, Satin and Stroke\nAdjust drop shadow opacity.\nDouble Click on Satin and drag selection until it matches original document.\nDouble-Click on Stroke and change stroke color to white. Adjust stroke thickness.\nMost options will default to black, you may want to experiment changing them to a shade of blue.\n\nThe main trick is to use a gradient that has a very limited range. See images below.\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/111-Picture11.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"594\" height=\"454\"/></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"discussions/112-Picture12.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"243\" height=\"79\"/></p>","createdDate":"2009-02-24T16:06:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3831","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks, I did not know about this type of digital signature -- good to know for future use. For now, I'll just try to match close enough to look OK.","createdDate":"2009-02-23T20:00:17.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3828","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Whatever program it was, it did not create an EXIF entry to identify itself. A quick test of Photoshop CS3 shows it would have left a lot of data in the EXIF, so that probably rules it out.\nSorry.","createdDate":"2009-02-23T19:48:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3816","contributorName":"1emnywagsa7hr","description":"Thanks, both of you. Although the automated tool did not find a good match, someone in the forum posted immediately and came up with Adobe Optima Bold, as well as letting me know that there was a vertical stretch, overlaid blend, emboss, drop shadow, and white outline as far as what effects were added. They also indicated that it was probably done with PhotoShop or Gimp. Wow. I don't have that Adobe font but will get a hold of it ASAP.","createdDate":"2009-02-23T17:00:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3813","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"That could be easily created in any graphics program, but what I'm guessing you're really looking for is the font. I'd give <a href=\"http://new.myfonts.com/WhatTheFont/\">http://new.myfonts.com/WhatTheFont/</a> a try, but you'll probably need to clean up the image a bit (remove the drop shadows, etc.) to make it more accurate. If that doesn't work out, try their forums to see if anyone there can identify it. If all else fails, just pick something close ;-P","createdDate":"2009-02-23T16:45:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3810","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I know you can do it with Photoshop. If you need the font, there are some awesome services out there that will help you find the fonts in an image like this one: <a href=\"http://new.myfonts.com/WhatTheFont/\">http://new.myfonts.com/WhatTheFont/</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-23T16:35:12.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3803","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Part 1:  My Interview With NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"On behalf of you, our campus web developers, I sat down with Dr. Marc Hoit, the Chief Information Officer of NCSU, for a conversation ranging from budgets to social networking to sodas. The interview will be split into several posts. I will be posting additional parts of the interview throughout the week, so make sure you check back to continue the interview.\n\n\nPart 1 of My Interview with NCSU CIO, Dr. Marc Hoit\n========================================================\n\n<b>We've elected a new president and he is evaluated on his first 100 days in office. I\u2019m curious as to how you think your first 100 days have gone.</b>\n\nI'm really happy with them. As an organization, we devised a Strategic Operations Plan (SOP) and there is already feedback coming in from campus that they are happy with the interactions, collaborations and directions of OIT. So my goals for the first 100 days have worked out well.\n\n<b>And the next 100 days?</b>\n\nIn the next 100 days, I want to turn the SOP into actions, making sure everyone operates according to that plan and truly internalizes the goals and strategies, using them as the way to do business. A perfect example of this is OIT\u2019s Web Hosting Committee, which has set up communication channels to involve everyone using our Web hosting services in telling us how we can help them do what they need to do. This is what I\u2019d like to see all of OIT do.\n\nMy plan for the next 12 months will be focused on governance. Our Governance structure should help address two common frustrations in large organizations: 1) communication issues and 2) a process to solicit and encourage input\u2014both toward how decisions are made in the organization, and creating and improving the processes in which the organization works. Again, the Web Hosting Committee is a good example of what we need to do. It\u2019s not enough to have ideas of what we should do or what industry is doing. We need to take the required step, as web did, to make sure that it fits the needs of our University. They did this by bringing together interested parties on campus to devise a proposal that considers: what the interested parties\u2014such as other central units on campus\u2014need, what OIT can efficiently and cost-effectively provide, and the strategic future direction of the industry. This resulted in a jointly-developed proposal on how to do Web Hosting at N.C. State, along with an opportunity to improve the plan and make a recommendation as to who should approve it.\n\nThat is just one of a hundred things we need to be doing. So, governance is a critical part of helping us to operate as an organization with shared goals\u2014so people know where to bring their questions and how to get projects done and work together.\n\n<b>Speaking of Web hosting, currently students are allotted www4 space. How is the Web Hosting Services Pilot going to affect that?</b>\n\nI don't know. I am hoping that an evaluation of the Web Hosting Services Pilot will give us that answer. Concurrently, our Student Email Initiative is evaluating products that come with Web space. At one extreme, we could have a student Web space (for personal home pages, for instance) solution that is externally operated and managed.\n\n<b>Similar to Google sites?</b>\n\nExactly. In addition to Google Apps Education Edition, we\u2019re considering Microsoft Live@edu/Exchange Labs for a student email solution, and it, too, includes Web space in its package. Yahoo\u2019s Zimbra includes an option to get a MySite at yahoo.com. And you get to brand these however you\u2019d like to. So that is one extreme of the possibility, one which would incorporate some hosting space within our student email solution.\n\nThe other extreme involves internally building a hosting solution, offering it at very good rate, and somehow finding a mechanism to pay for it. In building the solution, we\u2019d have to consider storage requirements, what we currently offer, and what new requirements the students might have. Then, as an example of finding a way to fund it, we might approach a department or college to say, \u201cStudents get this percentage of the service automatically, and maybe student government or student fees could fund the rest.\u201d\n\nIn reality, we would probably end up somewhere between those extremes. Student organizations are using the OrgSync product, which includes Web hosting. Others are already using Google sites and have their own presence. Student organizations do have some funding, and there may be some interest by Student Affairs in subsidizing their Web space to have sites that better fit campus needs. So, that\u2019s why we might end up somewhere in between those extreme options.\n\nOne of my biggest concerns is about the cost constraints under which we\u2019re working. As you look across industry, Web hosting services are offering unlimited storage and bandwidth for $5.95 a month. You can drop a Drupal instance or a Wordpress instance in there, use a C-panel interface and have a hosting environment for $60 per year. However, you do have to be knowledgeable enough to manage the environment and update the software. The other extreme is that for around $2.35 per month, you can get a limited number of pages in a truly content-managed site, pick a template, type your information into forms, and have 20 or 30 static pages and build a site very easily\u2014without having to manage anything. This type of offering is possible for Web hosting services companies because they can operate at scale. They have thousands of sites and people to set up the automated software and they do all the virtual hosting\u2014and because of that, they can do it at a cost that is pretty inexpensive.\n\nIf OIT were going to host, we would need a comparable approach, which doesn\u2019t necessarily mean the same cost. While they supposedly serve at unlimited access speeds, we\u2019d be doing it at 1-gig access speeds and providing enterprise-level storage and backup. We may end up offering a system that would be comparable to industry\u2019s $100 per month package, so we need to be careful with what we compare. We need to start our offering at a cost that is reasonable, and one for which we have the resources to support, while providing value that is evident to our customers.\n\nWe have some important things to consider. For example, we have to protect most student data, so hosting it ourselves may be the only answer. Or it might turn out that we can achieve that security with a hosted rack that a vendor provides more cheaply, because they can operate at scale and we can\u2019t. Email systems are another example of where scaling is a factor. It takes about 15,000 users to be able to cover all of the up-front costs of hardware and software needed to install a system. You have to consider all of these things in your decisions to see what\u2019s sensible\u2014in the case of Web hosting as well as student email, and that\u2019s what we\u2019re doing in our Web Hosting Services Pilot and our Student Email Initiative.\n\n========================================================\n\nCheck back tomorrow for Part 2 of the interview, where I speak with Dr. Hoit about Cost Recovery and the idea of \"Radical Transparency\".","createdDate":"2009-02-23T13:49:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-02-02T20:06:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3825","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I think it'd be a great idea to give students the option to manage their own Wordpress instance as their personal space. WP is a really easy-to-use blog/cms, more so than Drupal, and so many colleges/departments either require or would really like their students to have their own Web portfolio space and WP could facilitate that very nicely. And after they graduate I imagine that they could port out their own individual WP instance fairly easily and do with it what they wanted... Nice to see everyone thinking about these ideas.","createdDate":"2009-02-23T19:47:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3752","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","title":"Feb 20th - what the heck happened?","description":"This is one of my big problems with AFS. It's too big. When something that \"shouldn't ever happen\" does happen, it shuts down way too many services.\n\nSometime around 12:30 am this morning, AFS stopped working. I was paged in to check on the courses websites at 1:45, when they started showing signs that something was amiss.\n\nA quick lesson in basic AFS: The AFS directory structure is a collection of volumes. Each volume is a piece of the file system, it usually contains a top level directory, some sub directories, and some mount points for other volumes. The volumes are stored on the various AFS file servers. The VLDB (volume location database) is maintained on a set of database servers. This database contains all the points that map the volume names/ids to the locate the volume data on the file servers.\n\nA simple command like \"cd /afs/unity/users/b/brabec\" results in a long list of lookups behind the scenes:\n- VLDB lookup /afs/unity\n- retrieve the root volume for unity from a fileserver\n- look inside, find that the users directory is a mount for the users volume\n- VLDB lookup for the user volume\n- retrieve the users volume from a fileserver\n- look inside, find that the b directory is another volume mount\n- and so on...\n\nSo the \"Very Bad Thing\" that happened in the wee hours of this morning, was the three database servers somehow fumbled the VLDB between them, and corrupted it beyond recovery. We're not sure what happened to do this. Theories include problems with mixing v1.2 DB servers with v1.4 fileservers, and possible network interruptions that were evident while trying to fix the problem. Regardless of the cause, once the VLDB was trashed, none of our AFS unity volumes could be located on the file servers. The only thing that saved us for a time was the cached copies of a lot of those lookups did not expire very quickly. But anytime a server or client tried to find something that was not saved in cache, it could not proceed.\n\nThe fix was to erase the VLDB and then survey all of the unity file servers to find all of the volumes and get their entries back into the database. That took a lot of time, on the order of 6 hours even with 3-4 servers being polled in parallel for most of the time.\n\nMeanwhile, the cache that saved us on some servers, also made the problem worse on others. Servers that didn't know where to find volumes would do a lookup, the VLDB would tell them the volume didn't exist, and they'd cache that result. Once the VLDB was rebuilt we had to reboot all of our Solaris based web servers to make sure they weren't saving these bad results.\n\nUnfortunately, this is the second time this particular \"Very Bad Thing\" has happened to us in recent months. The last time the database was corrupted but recoverable, but systems still had to spend a lot of time tracking down and restoring missing/bad entries. It would be naive of us to assume it won't happen again.\n\nSome fixes are in the works:\n- upgrade the database servers and other remaining AFS servers to the 1.4.x software\n- keep a 7 day history of the VLDB database file, to provide checkpoints that may be used for faster recovery in the event of another corruption.\n- and of course, give serious consideration to splitting web things off of AFS where it is no longer needed.","createdDate":"2009-02-21T00:01:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-25T15:08:36.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:859","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3924","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Jason Edgecombe at UNCC contacted me and passed this problem along to Derrick Brashear at openafs.org. I gather Derrick and Tim had a good chat session yesterday and sorted out what they hope is the answer to most of the problems that we've been having of late.\n\nYour best bet would be to talk to Tim directly about the solutions they found. The short answer I heard from Tim was.. 1.4.7 fixes most of our problems. 1.4.9 will fix them better, when it is available. We also understand something of what is wrong with the AFS caching on our RHEL5 webservers, and that it's directly related to having multiple network interfaces on the machine.","createdDate":"2009-02-25T15:08:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3901","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"Thanks for the update Charles. When OIT has an outage of a service that we also run, we're intently curious about what happened to know if it's something we could bump into and if there are actions we can take to prevent it. Many times we don't hear anything so we really appreciate you doing this.\n\nSo how are things looking since upgrading the afsdb servers to 1.4.7? Did you find something definitive about the 1.4 server/1.2 db mix or just pushed this out to see if it resolved? That would obviously have implications for the eos cell.","createdDate":"2009-02-25T06:03:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3835","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"This didn't personally affect me at all. But I know if had, I would have appreciated this description greatly. This was a great breakdown of what happened, and a model I think, to our colleagues on campus for things like this. Thanks very much for posting this Charles!","createdDate":"2009-02-23T23:15:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3822","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Yes. The cpanel solution that we are looking at would use its own standard unix filesystem. Obviously if we go with reselling a private hosting provider they would not be using AFS either.\n\nWe're not going to make any changes out from under the existing hosting that we do. We hope to offer a better solution that people can migrate to if they choose. <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">www.ncsu.edu</a> on the other hand, is not likely to move soon, if ever.","createdDate":"2009-02-23T19:43:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3819","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Ditto on what Jen said.\n\nAre you referring to your group's proposed webhosting solutions as a \"splitting web things off of AFS\"?","createdDate":"2009-02-23T19:40:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3763","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I really appreciate the information on what happened. Thanks for putting all this out here, Charles.","createdDate":"2009-02-21T17:36:28.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3738","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"A conversation with entrepreneur and software engineer Marc Andreessen","description":"I came across this interview via a Tweet (from @kbodnar32)that said: \"If you care about technology, the Internet and innovation than you must watch this absolutely no excuses.\"\n\nA conversation with Marc Andreessen, co-founder and chairman of Ning and an investor in several startups including Digg, Plazes, and Twitter. Best known as co-author of Mosaic, and founder of Netscape. He is on the Board of Directors of Facebook and eBay.\n\nJason pointed out to me that this would be much more accessible if the link to it were included. Sorry about that! Here it is:\n<a href=\"http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/10093\">http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/10093</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-20T19:15:34.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-20T20:50:46.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3710","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Is this just devevelopers.","description":"Is this group just for developing web services for mobile devices ?\nOr is it for exchanging information about using the devices.\nI have questions about iPhone applications and using them.\nIs this the right place.\nIf not - should I start an iPhone/gPhone group?\n\nDon","createdDate":"2009-02-20T14:14:48.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-20T17:24:00.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:2651","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3733","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think this group would be a fine place to ask those questions. I dont think it is just for mobile development, but mobile environments in general.","createdDate":"2009-02-20T17:24:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3645","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"How do you run things?","description":"For those of you who don't know me, my name is Charlie Morris and part of my job is the task of coordinating the College of Natural Resources' websites. I know how I run things over here, but I'm curious as to how other colleges and bigger units manage their websites. Please add to this forum with a description of how things work for your shop.\n\n<ul>\n<li>At CNR we use a series of OIT project lockers (max size of each = 2GB). We have 2 principal lockers for departmental and college-level activities. Then there are a series of about 8 or so other project lockers that various sub-units of CNR use, these include extension folks, special research projects, etc.</li>\n<li>We use Adobe Contribute (CS3 version) as our means for updating content. In the college we have many \"contributers\" - probably around 40-50.</li>\n<li>We also rely on managing PTS groups for decreasing the risk associated with giving so many people write access to all pages on our sites. This is necessary because there is the potential that a \"contributer\" could mistakenly open up Dreamweaver and connect and cause some problems, or even worse, open up the J drive to one of our sites and cause havoc.</li>\n<li>Each major department or unit has a kind of content master - a person who oversees all content and ensures that pages are being updated and that content is correct and of good quality.</li>\n<li>We are in the beginning stages of experimenting with the open source CMS known as Drupal. Right now it is internal to just the IT group at CNR. So far, I have my concerns about it and don't see it replacing our Contribute model anytime in the near future - though Drupal does have a lot of compelling features that Contribute doesn't.</li>\n</ul>\n\nSo, I'm especially interested in learning what other colleges do for hosting and for content updating. Also, do any of you have specific graphical/visual/communication strategies across all sites and pages in your college? Anything else you'd like to add?","createdDate":"2009-02-19T14:11:25.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-01-26T16:46:26.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4976","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"CHASS' setup is very similar to that of Engineering.\n\nWe run our own web servers and files are hosted in AFS. We use the COE AFS servers as well as their locker portal system (which is an extremely handy tool) to request lockers, set permissions, etc.\n\nUsers in the departments are also using Contribute 3 for content updates.\n\nAfter we finish a few more projects, our plan is to look more closely at Drupal.","createdDate":"2009-03-23T18:51:06.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4974","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Wow, I had no idea about any of this, very informative and interesting.\n\nI know there are talks regarding a possible changing of how web-hosting is provided, as in possibly replacing AFS with something else, but I did not know that web-hosting was only a small chunk of AFS.\n\nAnyway, thanks a lot for taking a minute to spell all this out.","createdDate":"2009-03-23T18:11:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4941","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"AFS was designed to be a worldwide filesystem. At one point on our lab machines if you looked in the root you would see AFS cells for CMU, MIT, UMICH, and other universities as well as some companies. But over time there was little use of that sort of thing so it was phased out on our standard environments. Nowadays it makes things much slower for little benefit.\n\nThe \"root\" of AFS (/afs on *nix or J:\\ on Windows) is constructed in different ways, like using a config file (CellServDB) that simply lists all of the AFS cells (or just some of them), or it can be pulled from DNS or a combination of the 2, or it can be handed out as a volume by your \"home cell\". It better to almost think of it as a shared set of bookmarks for AFS cells. Authentication/authorization only happens once you enter one of the cells.\n\nOddly enough, we aren't listed anymore on the public CellServDB:\n<a href=\"http://dl.central.org/dl/cellservdb/CellServDB\">http://dl.central.org/dl/cellservdb/CellServDB</a>\n\nAnd as for the 3 cells:\nunity.ncsu.edu - Home volumes, lockers, and other stuff provided by OIT\nbp.ncsu.edu - Back-end volumes that make the \"realm\" environments work, space provided by OIT, but some of the data is from the colleges\neos.ncsu.edu - This is the \"mostly not-OIT\" cell. Used by Engineering/PAMS/DELTA/CHASS. There's still some legacy OIT stuff in there. This was the first of the cells.\n\nThe VLDB's (Volume Location DataBase servers) for all 3 cells are run by OIT. The VLDB's handle telling the clients how to find the almost 200,000 volumes across the 3 cells.\n\nPlease also note that providing a filestore for web services is just a small chunk of what AFS is used for on campus. AFS pre-dates the web.","createdDate":"2009-03-22T20:59:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4901","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Obviously I'm no webhost specialist ;-). So even though I can go from afs to afs/unity or afs/eos - they are two totally different web servers. Getting sort of technical, but does that mean that the root afs is some kind of main server that connects the two (as well as \"bp\" whatever that is)? If this is documented somewhere already, please feel free to send that on.\n\nThanks!","createdDate":"2009-03-20T19:21:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4812","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Actually, engineering runs its own AFS cell (as well as its own webservers). :-) OIT = Unity. Engineering = Eos.","createdDate":"2009-03-18T20:48:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4784","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Thank you for sharing! Looks like you all have a pretty sophisticated system over there. So, is it the case that Engineering essentially runs their own Web servers - and uses the same AFS file system as OIT? Or is there some kind of special sharing of servers going on between you and OIT? This makes sense considering the computer engineering background of the college.","createdDate":"2009-03-17T21:00:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4779","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"In the College of Engineering, we have web lockers in AFS and a tool for requesting them (2GB max per volume, can have multiple volumes) and MySQL databases by vhost webmasters. We also have a locker portal that locker owners and admins can use to set access to PTS groups, request quota, etc. Most of how we do things is described at <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/</a>. We also support .org sites, <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/orgsites\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/orgsites</a>.\n\nStaff on our supported Windows desktop run Contribute 3 (if we have money, we will upgrade to CS4 this year). About 30 of the 150 staff we support are routine Contribute users and maintain our college-level sites pretty well. Everyone else pretty much uses Dreamweaver.\n\nOur departments and centers all have their own vhosts, see <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/domains\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/domains</a>. Not all have a dedicated webmaster, but between the IT staff and web-savvy content people in the unit, they get it done. We also have a testing server for staging sites (which will display their php errors), see <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/testingstaging\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/testingstaging</a>\n\nITECS runs one Drupal site at <a href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/helpdesk\">http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu/helpdesk</a> for internal documentation. But ECE has several sites, including research sites, running it. We have a stable and powerful web infrastructure in COE that works well to distribute control to our many web developers. However, our security measures, particularly open base dir restrictions (<a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/security\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/web/security</a>), sometimes makes it hard to run a lot of free software and CMSes out of the box, but Drupal installs pretty easily, see <a href=\"http://www.wolftech.ncsu.edu/support/support/Drupal_Installation\">http://www.wolftech.ncsu.edu/support/support/Drupal_Installation</a>","createdDate":"2009-03-17T19:54:04.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3597","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Meeting Minutes from 2/2 and 2/17","description":"Meeting minutes from our last two Web Hosting meetings. Sorry for the delay.\n\nAs Jason mentioned in the webdev meet-up, please let us know if there are additional applications or technologies you'd like us to look into offering. Now's the time!","createdDate":"2009-02-18T21:18:55.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-18T21:20:35.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/113-Web_Hosting_Meeting_2_2.pdf","discussions/114-Web_Hosting_Mtg_2_17.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3498","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"LimeSurvey is the best thing ever!","description":"<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/115-limesurveylogo.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/116-limesurveylogo.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"61\"/></a></p>\n<b>1. Enter name of The Best Thing Ever!</b> LimeSurvey\n\n<b>2. Does it have a website (choose one):</b> Yes No\n\n<b>2a. If Yes, what is the URL?</b> <a href=\"http://www.limesurvey.org\">http://www.limesurvey.org</a>\n\n<b>3. What is the environment?</b> Web (PHP)\n\n<b>4. How many surveys have you hand-coded? (choose one)</b>\n\nA. Zero\nB. 1-10\nC. 11-20\nD. Too Many to count\nE. Arghh the numbers are too large, they make my brain hurt.\n\n<b>5. How satisfied are you with online survey tools that limit the number of questions, or make you pay for them? (choose one)</b>\n\nA. Very Satisfied\nB. Satisfied\nC. Neutral\nD. Somewhat Unsatisfied\nE. Very Unsatisfied\nF. Sweet mercy....I hate limited applications\n\nIf you answered anything except A on questions 4 and 5, you should take the time to look at using LimeSurvey. If you answered A on both then that makes you a lucky individual. I envy your innocence.\n\nLimeSurvey is a 6 year old open source project that provides a way for multiple users to administer their own surveys. How many of you are tired of having to develop your own survey form, create and connect a database, develop permissions for people to access the survey, and then format the results? I'm guessing there's a whole lot of you who fit into that category. If i wanted to know for sure though, it would be a good bet that I'd use Limesurvey to poll you.\n\n<b>So why LimeSurvey?</b>\nIt just works. It makes sense. There's barely any learning curve, unless you have never heard of a radio button list (select one), or check box list (select many).\n\nYou can find the full list of features on the LimeSurvey site, but a few of my favorites are:\n\n* Unlimited number of surveys open at the same time\n* Unlimited number of questions in a survey (only limited by your database)\n* Unlimited number of participants to a survey\n* User-Management\n* 20 different question types with more to come\n* WYSIWYG HTML Editor\n* Integration of pictures and movies into a survey\n* Creation of a printable survey version\n* Conditions for questions depending on earlier answers (Skip Logic / Branching)\n* Re-usable editable answer sets\n* Ready-made importable questions\n* Survey expiry dates for automation\n* Enhanced import and export functions to text, CSV, PDF, SPSS, queXML and MS Excel format\n* Basic statistical and graphical analysis with export facility\n\n\nThe conditional question feature is possibly my favorite, just because its such a time saver. IE: If you answered A,B, or D in question 1, then display question 2, otherwise, skip question 2 and go to question 3. It really is as simple as point and click survey creation.\n\nThe more complex features may take a little while longer to become accustomed to, like using tokens for sending survey invitations via email merge. This is so you can track who has responded (and what they answered), and who has not responded yet.\n\nWhile setting up the survey can take a significant amount of time, you usually will spend longer on the analysis of the data collected. LimeSurvey does a fantastic job of making it both easy to get quick stats on the data, or exporting it for use in another program (SPSS anyone?).\n\nI could go on forever about much time it has saved me, but that would just waste more of the time you need to create your old fashioned surveys. So quit reading this, and go start using LimeSurvey. Your first survey can be to ask your users how much they like the ability to create their own surveys, and not have to rely on a break in your schedule.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/117-questions1.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/118-questions1.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"177\"/></a></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/119-questions2.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/120-questions2.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"140\"/></a></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/121-questions3.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/122-questions3.png?width=200\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"74\"/></a></p>","createdDate":"2009-02-17T14:46:03.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-18T20:11:57.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3589","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I have not used surveybuilder before --- i'll defer to the group for more information on that comparison.","createdDate":"2009-02-18T20:11:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3584","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"We've used it on a client by client basis. It's very flexible, easy to deploy, not bad to customize look and feel, and does a good job collecting data.\n\nNot sure about it being centrally hosted...could be part of the package deal with hosted service.","createdDate":"2009-02-18T18:55:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3581","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"interesting.. is this better than surveybuilder? any thoughts of hosting a central version of this for all ncsu to use? too ambitious? not a good fit for that?","createdDate":"2009-02-18T18:41:46.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3402","contributorName":"35cq68t8q2xge","title":"Document Management - Purchased or Open Source","description":"Wondering if anyone out here is using or knows of anyone using on campus a \"true\" document management system. Needs to be friendly to users, and pretty robust. Vet School uses LOTS of paper that needs to be managed (ie.. medical records for the critters they treat). We are ramping up an effort to go totally electronic with the medical records(we have the software for that), but need something to manage the years worth of existing paper we already have. Any thoughts or leads are appreciated!","createdDate":"2009-02-13T15:04:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-13T15:04:01.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3391","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","title":"PHP Functions Written in JavaScript","description":"For all those times when you thought to yourself \"I need blah I've used in PHP, and I know it wouldn't take long to code up in JS, but I don't have time to debug it\":\n\n<a href=\"http://kevin.vanzonneveld.net/techblog/article/phpjs_licensing/\">http://kevin.vanzonneveld.net/techblog/article/phpjs_licensing/</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-13T02:27:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-13T02:27:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3381","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Article:  My Boss is an #%*&#@&$*@!!","description":"No, I'm not talking about <i>my</i> boss :)\n\nI ran across this interesting post, sent via twitter from one of my followers and thought it was incredibly relevant and interesting regarding social networking and how what you post on twitter/facebook/myspace etc. affects you \"long term\".\n\n<a href=\"http://theantipimp.com/?p=317\">http://theantipimp.com/?p=317</a>\n\nI'm very \"aware\" of what gets tweeded or posted on facebook by me. I have followers/friends in higher places which makes me more conscience of what I post. I never really thought about making hiring decisions based on what was on someones facebook page though.\n\nAnyone ever looked through social networking sites of potential hires? Ever made a decision, one way or another, based on what you found?","createdDate":"2009-02-12T13:11:16.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-12T13:11:16.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3362","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Collecting Data Feeds for Campus","description":"I mentioned this in a response for my blog post about collaboration, but I wanted to start a discussion here and see what you guys thought.\n\nI basically had an idea of a collaborative project to collect as many data feeds from NCSU sources as we can. Off the top of my head, I'd think the following would be important:\n\n- Type of feed (DB, XML service, other, etc)\n- Who owns the data\n- What kind of data is contained/available via the feed\n- Who can access the feed\n- Any steps to gaining access to the feed\n- How to access the feed\n- Contact info for the maintainer of the feed\n\nMy guess is that we would have to use some sort of searchable, community-maintained database to store all this data. The benefits, IMHO, would be enormous to campus. Think of all the possibilities of mashups (yay web 3.0!!!111one).\n\nAny concerns that folks would have? Privacy, etc? I would think that even private feeds would be worth documenting, even if there is only x number of people who can access them. Just knowing who owns the data and that it can be gotten at would be a awesome step.\n\nThoughts? Ideas? Concerns?","createdDate":"2009-02-11T23:24:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-11T23:24:10.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3355","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"iPhone Development Workshop Possibilities","description":"I had posted something a while back about interest in an iPhone development class. Well, I have us 2 possibilities, but nothing set in stone yet.\n\nI am working with our campus Apple rep to get Steve Hayman, the CE of Mobility, to come give us an overview of iPhone development, combined with some how-to's. Right now, we are still working out logistics, but it looks like it will take place on March 19th here on campus. The workshop will be in conjunction with some folks from UNC and Duke, so we are trying to work out how it will work. What it looks like now is that we will do a half-day session for NCSU people, then the UNC and Duke people will do the other half-day session. We haven't determined if we are going to do it in the morning or afternoon yet, but I wanted to let you folks know so you could get it on your calendar.\n\nThe second option is a little different. Everette Allen was contacted by a commercial training unit that does iPhone development classes for a fee. They have a 5 day iPhone dev workshop that costs about $3000/person for the standard rate. They offered to come here to teach what would amount to the first day of that 5 day class for &lt; $100 per person. We are trying to work with them to see if they will give us a discount off the rest of the $3000 to continue the class, because frankly $3k for an iPhone class is out of reach for pretty much everyone on campus. In fact, the $100 may be out of reach, but that is the point of this. They would like an estimate of who would participate in the workshop if they did it, so would anyone be interested? I know our group would still likely do the $100 class, but beyond that who knows. I'm not asking anyone to commit to it, just post if you are interested. We do not have a date for this yet, but it would likely be a few weeks after the free on-campus iPhone class...so late March early April.\n\nEither way, I am working on ways to get us some exposure to iPhone development classes, including looking at licensing for the University for iPhone development.","createdDate":"2009-02-11T17:42:49.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-11T18:05:56.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3357","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I'm definitely interested!","createdDate":"2009-02-11T18:05:56.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3308","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Boxee: TV Ouside the Box","description":"<b>Best Thing Ever! (this week): Boxee</b>\nWebsite: <a href=\"http://boxee.tv/\">http://boxee.tv/</a>, <a href=\"http://blog.boxee.tv/\">http://blog.boxee.tv/</a>\n\n<b>See the Video Demo here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/video/boxeedemo-1\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/video/boxeedemo-1</a></b>\n\n\nBoxee is cross-platform media center software. Similar in many ways to the open source X-Box media center XBMC (Boxee is actually built off it) this software will allow you to organize all your media in one place and makes it easily accessible. But don't think that Boxee is just a rip-off of XBMC; it's marketed as the \"first ever social media center\" since among its other fantastic features is the ability for users to have \"friends\". Use their website to find or invite your friends and their information will appear when you login. You can follow what they've watched recently, their likes, dislikes and recommendations through the Boxee interface.\n\nBoxee also scores big with its network options. It connects with IMDB (Internet Movie Database) and TVDB (figure it out) to give you thumbnails and reviews of videos and AMG for album art. It comes with a built-in BitTorrent client and can stream your video with Windows File-Sharing and XBMSP (X-Box protocol). It can also export a users activity to Twitter and other social networking tools, though it doesn't yet pull those feeds back into the Boxee interface. Boxee is built primarily in C++ but a Python plug-in system allows content \"channels\" from the web (one of Boxee's best features). Boxee uses XMBC's reputably easy-to-use GUI toolkit for designing themes so look for lots of skinning options to be available.\n\n\nStart up Boxee and you'll be asked to login. Initial set-up is super-easy: start on their website and create an account to get going, then just follow the instructions. Once you're logged in Boxee pretty much takes over. It will look on recognized drives, in designated folders for video, music and pictures.\n\n<b>Music</b>\nFor the music segments, Boxee will find any cover art available, and organizes by album and artist. If you don't see CD you expected, use the \"Browse' section to wander through any of your networked machines, connected devices, etc. Finally, if you want to expand your horizons you can use the \"Internet\" section to browse free music and Podcasts available online through sites like BBC, NPR, last.fm and a few others.\n\n<b>Pictures</b>\nAs with your music, Boxee will go looking in the obvious places for pictures. Anything in your \"Pictures\" folder should show up, and the folder structure remains which makes it a little easier to navigate. Again, if you're missing something use the \"Browse\" section to go looking for your shots. Is your best stuff online? Connect to Flicker, Picasa or \"The Big Picture\" to find your shots, and anything your friends have available as well. I admit to having some troubles getting to online pictures, but this thing is in Alpha so I'll let it go...\n\n<b>Video</b>\nThe Video options are by far the most impressive section on Boxee. As with Music and Photos, Boxee will find anything you've got to start with but the \"Browse\" options will let you seek out additional files or those added later. Boxee separates video files into \"Movies\" and \"TV Shows\". It also has an 'Internet' section and here is where the fun begins. Connections are available to 18 \"channels\" including CBS, Comedy Central, BBC, CNN, MTV and best of all, Joost and Hulu. Dozens of shows and movies are at your fingertips here, which is especially exciting for those who haven't caught up on their 'Remington Steele' and 'Doogie Howser M.D.' episodes (you know you're excited!).\nThe 'Internet' section also includes a connection to Netflix. If you're a member (and really, who isn't?) you can login and view your queue. If you've got anything in your Instant Queue you can watch it through Boxee, though it's only as good as your network connection. Rumor has it that the Netflix options are unavailable on Apple TV and Linux for the time being.\n\n<b>More</b>\nBoxee will let you interface with your profile and see what your friends are up to and whether or not they're online. Boxee also has some exceptionally flexible options to play with in the 'Settings' including your region (for weather info from weather.com) your background, screen saver, navigation sounds, controls, etc. Finally there is a \"Download\" section which apparently includes a built-in BitTorrent client. Can't give accurate info on this since all my attempts to play (and by \"play\" I mean download only completely legal files) have caused Boxee to crash for me.\n\nSo you want it, right? Currently Boxee is in Alpha. It was released for the Mac (Leopard, Tiger), Apple TV and Linux machines with Intel processors in June of 2008. An Alpha version for Windows was released in January of 2009 but is currently invitation-only. Rumor has it that they plan to release a Boxee box sometime this year. Keep an eye on their blog (<a href=\"http://blog.boxee.tv/\">http://blog.boxee.tv/</a>): its updated regularly and they're very good about soliciting feedback and talking to their audience. If the blog is too much work for you follow them on Twitter: <a href=\"http://twitter.com/boxee\">http://twitter.com/boxee</a>.\n\nSee the video demo: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/video/boxeedemo-1\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/video/boxeedemo-1</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-10T20:18:24.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-10T21:05:04.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3301","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","title":"What are you working on right now? Put your spoke on the wheel.","description":"<p style=\"font:bold 1.3em Georgia\">I'd like for us to try (once a month or so) to share/list the various projects we are all working on or planning for the near future. I think this will help prevent the infamous reinvented wheel scenario. So anyways, I'll start with what we have going on over in <a href=\"http://www.itecs.ncsu.edu\">ITECS</a> at the College of Engineering.</p>\n\nOur webteam is currently working on redesigning the following sites. They are all in various stages of development, but most have made it into a fully CSS'd template (they are just awaiting internal review).\n\n<ul>\n<li>www.imse.ncsu.edu (<a href=\"http://www.imse.ncsu.edu\">view the original site</a>)</li>\n<li>students.engr.ncsu.edu (<a href=\"http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/\">view the original site</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://students.engr.ncsu.edu/careerfair/\">students.engr.ncsu.edu/careerfair/</a> (redesign just launched! 2.9.09)</li>\n<li>www.eos.ncsu.edu (will be revamped in the near future)</li>\n<li>a handful of other miscellaneous site redesigns are ongoing</li>\n</ul>\n\nWe are still actively working on the <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/maps/beta/revamp/\">Campus Google Map</a>, but haven't had much time to devote to the project in 2009 so far. We are waiting to see what GIS information is made available from the University's Architect's Office when they go live with their new API this spring.\n\nWe are currently monitoring the real-time availability of computers in each of our 18 Eos Computing Labs and reporting it to this public page for students to see: <a href=\"http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/\">http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/labs/</a> . Eventually we plan to integrate it with OIT/Wolftech's Billboard software and project it around campus. We've also developed an entire back-end to statistically summarize traffic in the lab, which will help us better determine what resources are needed where (and when).\n\nWe plan to make several improvements to <a href=\"http://www.webtools.ncsu.edu/publicat/\">Publicat</a>, a tool which provides you with an embeddable list of all the publications (listed in the library) for your department.\n\nI may have overlooked a few projects, but I'll be sure to post them here as soon as they come to me.","createdDate":"2009-02-10T14:56:02.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-16T13:15:26.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:4696","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Great sharing idea, Mike. Here's some potential synergy to come out of it. For Jason, regarding classmate, I recently taught a class and at the end of it, it would have been nice to have been able to manipulate the feedback data/graphs. Caveat: I may have missed how to do this, if it functionality already exists. 1) At the very least, I would have liked to have been able to print all of the feedback graphs to a PDF. It seems to me that all you can do right now is look at them one at a time. 2) The ultimate would have been to have had the ability to copy the graph's data into an excel spreadsheet to further manipulate (like make my scores look much better than they were--just kidding).\n\nThanks for any consideration you can give to these \"customer requirements\" in the next go-round. :-)","createdDate":"2009-03-16T13:15:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4468","contributorName":"11j9b5inrnbhl","description":"Adding on to Mike's list of stuff in ITECS... we're currently writing a couple of PHP objects that will handle the interface with the NC State NelNet gateway (one of three university options for processing credit cards). We'll be testing it next week with the folks who run the Engineering Career Fair. If all goes well, we have Engineering Summer Programs next in line for customization.\n\nWe're nearly done installing an open source academic conference CMS. It's a bit of a trick over hear since we usually have to go back and make open source code work in an open_basedir restricted environment. Just a bit more skinning and we'll be ready for testing.\n\nWe've been working on a tool to calculate faculty release time and you wouldn't *believe* how many \"isolated cases\" have cropped up since we started testing it. As soon as we get an additional feed from HR, we'll be expanding the tool for use in the College of Textiles.\n\nWe're entering our second year and third phase of a program assessment tool project (mostly using ABET guildelines). Right now we're retrofitting it with live data feeds from the SIS for access control.\n\nLastly, we're assessing PayDay, a bi-weekly timesheet generator, for a scale-up in users.","createdDate":"2009-03-10T20:12:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3746","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Hey Mike! Well now that the RSS feed for eos is in a happy place *wink*, I'm working on mapping the new SIS data (now that it's been moved off Sybase) to support existing applications, such as the various LMS offerings and their integration tools.","createdDate":"2009-02-20T21:03:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3600","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I'm working on several client projects including site redesigns for New Student Orientation and Finance &amp; Business I've also got the finishing touches for two or three other client sites: GIST, Plant Virology and CWSP. And I'm working on updates for a few of our on-going clients: the Shelton Leadership website, Provost website and several sites internal to OIT.\nIn non-web-related news I'm working on plans for OIT's Orientation involvement and the beginnings of plans for UNC CAUSE 2009, coming up in October in New Bern.","createdDate":"2009-02-18T21:28:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3507","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"Cleaning up iTunes U for (hopefully) imminent inclusion in the main Apple Store\nClassroom Capture Task Force @ MCNC\nWriting some documentation for Podcast Producer, Quicktime streaming\nAnd of course, midterm animation project for ADN 560 Animation Studio YAY!","createdDate":"2009-02-17T15:03:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3441","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Right now im working on...\n\n** Drupal instance for the OIT website. We are working on the inner workings of that to fine tune our deployment. This is the same point as Jason, so i figured i'd steal his description of it...seeing as though we're collaborating FTW.\n\n** NCSU client website redesigns (that;s my main job with Jen Riehle)\n\n** Student Email Task Force is looking at feasibility of outsourcing student email to either Google or Microsoft.\n\n** I'm working on an app to manage quick/short web links for NCSU. Kinda like TinyURL, but more readable and usable for marketing without needing to request new DNS entries all the time.\n\nThere's other incidental things that arrive on my desk randomly, but there are the major ones i thought i would mention.","createdDate":"2009-02-16T13:29:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3386","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"We have a bunch of incremental projects in the queue. The one that's most in front of me right now is a RubyonRails based activity application. Including workstreaming of logins, edits, and publishing events for our content creation tools. And then summarizing that data in numbers for the week/month/etc. It's using the Google Visualization API to do graphs. And for \"public data\" (e.g. nothing that's an individual graph, unless they say ok - just aggregate group or site-wide numbers) - the json data table can be used anywhere - e.g. iGoogle gadgets.\n\nI also want to get a live view of the data flowing in - ala <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=ncsu\">twitter's real time search view</a> (example is NCSU) - or FriendFeed's live view. Right now, \"live\" is a misnomer - it's a 5-minute cronjob doing cross-database joins to import data. But I plan on playing some memcache games to either do data exchange or fake \"live\"\n\nI am also still working on the interface to Mailman that we built in to our People directory. Mailman's web interface, like every other web interface to mailing list packages caused \"support issues\" - so we manage mailing lists using group tools in our directory application. I still need to get the moderation queue into the People app.","createdDate":"2009-02-12T20:53:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3348","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Charles... I've used Host Gator to host some of my own personal sites in the past and although I don't have too many terrible things to say about them... I think they have a terrible administrative UI. I've recently switched over to <a href=\"http://mediatemple.net/\">Media Temple</a>, who I have been VERY satisfied with (they are also cheaper [for what im doing])... and if you haven't given them a look I would seriously consider it.","createdDate":"2009-02-11T13:47:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3345","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Shibboleth central authentication - as discussed at length on the mailing list.\n\nWeb hosting project - evaluating Host Gator as a possible reseller, and cpanel/fantastico as a hosting service on our own hardware.\n\nThose are the big ones right now.","createdDate":"2009-02-11T13:35:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3343","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We haven't started yet, but the plan is to get anyone who is interested to participate. Not only in planning, but development as well. We (Outreach Tech) don't exactly have all the time in the world to work on it (not as much as we would like anyway) so if it is going to be done, it will definitely have to be a collaborative effort.\n\nRight now, Billboard is in the \"planning on planning\" stage, meaning we haven't done anything to it other than realize that we need to do something to it. Hopefully by the first of next month you will see things moving on it.","createdDate":"2009-02-11T13:04:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3320","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","description":"What is the deal with Billboard? Are OIT and ECE working together on the rewrite?\n\nOr has collaboration already FAIL?\n\n:)","createdDate":"2009-02-10T22:30:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3303","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Awesome idea Mike! Here is our list of current projects for Outreach Technology in OIT (this goes for Me and Garrison)\n\nCurrently we are redesigning and re-architecturing ClassMate, which is what our education group uses to manage their workshops. (<a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate</a>) ClassMate is being put into our standard OT application framework. We are also working on getting ClassMate to do some cool stuff with calendaring. Trying to integrate it so that it is a subscribable feed through calendar systems like iCal and Google Calendar.\n\nRegarding out OT Application Framework, we just finished working on that. What it is is a base application framework built off of Zend Framework to allow us to quickly get started on projects. The base framework includes all needed modules for authentication, authorization, email queueing, application trigger support, customization of app variables, navigation control, internationalization, etc. Basically, everything you have to do for every application you write, we abstracted out into a framework. We've been doing that for the last 2 months.\n\nWe also just finished up the Standing Committee survey application for the provosts office.\n\nNext things to work on are re-architecturing Billboard, upgrading Aerial (our classtech management system), and finishing LifeCycle (our project management system).\n\nAll our projects that are active can be found at <a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/lifecycle/\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/lifecycle/</a>\n\nOther things we are working on:\n- Drupal instance for the OIT website. We are working on the inner workings of that to fine tune our deployment.\n- Getting more of our projects pushed through to the Office of Technology Transfer so that we can open source them\n\nI'm sure I missed something, but that is the general idea for now. Oh yeah, and doing a whole lotta stuff for this site re: content.","createdDate":"2009-02-10T15:50:11.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3221","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","title":"Don't reinvent the wheel, unless you planning on learning about wheels","description":"I thought that <a href=\"http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001145.html\">this post from Jeff Atwood</a> was interesting, and echoes one of the rambly points I was making on Jason Austin's <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/profiles/blogs/collaborate-together-or-get\">great blog post on collaboration</a>.\n\n<blockquote>Indeed. If anything, \"Don't Reinvent The Wheel\" should be used as a call to arms for deeply educating yourself about all the existing solutions -- not as a bludgeoning tool to undermine those who legitimately want to build something better or improve on what's already out there. In my experience, sadly, it's much more the latter than the former.</blockquote>","createdDate":"2009-02-08T13:49:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-08T13:49:19.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3152","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Meeting Minutes (all)","description":"Im just going to start putting the meeting minutes in a single thread, because its dumb to create one for every meeting.","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:12:55.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-03-24T19:16:10.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/123-webhosting_pilotproposal.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:5058","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think a change is imminent, although the medium we choose to achieve that change is still up in the air. There are significant technical hurdles we are trying to get over right now, and giving you a time frame would really be a shot in the dark. Also I don't wanna do keep pushing some mythical deadline back. Expect to see an interim report in the next few weeks, but I don't think any dates will be in that. As soon as we know, you all will know.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T19:16:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5029","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"So my follow up question - is this new web hosting system imminent? How many months out do you think it will take before we can start working with it?","createdDate":"2009-03-24T16:00:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5011","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Photo album software is included with Fantastico, which we are looking at deploying with a CPanel environment. They include 4Images Gallery, Gallery, and Coppermine.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T14:11:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5009","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Part of what we are looking at is going to \"bare-metal\" servers, meaning outsourced OS and hardware, but we install whatever we need on it, so CF becomes an option then. I don't think this is part of HostGator, but that that is just one place. The company they buy space from (The Planet, I think) would offer bare-metal access, so that is an option we are looking at too.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T14:08:32.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4998","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"Sounds like CPanel is a nightmare and the license restrictions are a mess.\n\nI didn't see Cold Fusion on the HostGator site, but of course I have no idea if the package we'd be considering would even be displayed on their website.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T13:44:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4991","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"thanks for posting these Jason. out of curiosity I have a specific question, on the order of smaller details, will the new web hosting option have a built-in photo library utility? I've been thinking of setting up Coppermine or something else, but won't waste my time if it or something like it will be included in this new webhosting environment.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T13:16:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4981","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Minutes from our meeting on 3/11\n\n======================================================\n\nSarah Noell, Carrie Brown, Tom Karches, Dolores Leonard, Jen Riehle, HMN, Charles Brabec, Richard, Jason Austin, Everette Allen.\n\nCharles has been working on cpanel. we cannot install cpanel on top of realm linux - no way. working on trimming down a stripped out rhel5 and he has begun experimenting with it. so far, no success. he is working on getting this even more stripped down.\n\nproblems: vm part - cpanel can take 10-70 minutes to install, his experience has been &gt; 200mins. Tom will look at profile and see what is going on. It is currently bootloading with more stripped down rhel.\n\ncpanel expects to login into whm with machine root account. there seems to be no other way to do this. he cannot create account, account create program just seems to spin and do nothing.\n\nEverette - there is a different cpanel for vm's and bare metal machines. are we getting the right version?\n\nTom will identify a standalone box today for Charles and Charles will test install there.\n\nThere is a billing manager in whm. They have standard plug-ins (paypal, etc). Have 2 separate API's. In order to use the API's, you need to have a bare metal account. Neither of our current payment systems (suntrust or nelnet) are in the std plugin suite. If we can get our own up, we'll be in a much better position to know what we need ask about if we host off-site. S&amp;C requires us, because of our current vendor and how they do billing, requires us to use bare metal.\n\nCan we evaluate cold-fusion based services in addition to php? CALS, CVM, TX are big users. Jason - we should get an environment up and get deliver it will...our question right now is whether or not oursourcing is a valid question. We need to consider whether or not we should use hostgator as our service environment.\n\nCpanel has no troubleshooting documentation...charles feels that outsourcing it is a better option.\n\nIf we are going to decide to outsource, then should charles waste any more time working on in sourcing. Charles will have answer by Friday morning.\n\nSarah needs to develop an interim report by end of March.","createdDate":"2009-03-24T12:10:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3165","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Meeting minutes from 2/2","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:16:37.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/124-Web_Hosting_Meeting_2_2.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3162","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Meeting minutes from 1/22","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:16:21.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/125-webhosting_jan22.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3159","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Meeting Minutes from 1/15","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:16:07.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/126-Web_Hosting_Mtg_1_15.pdf"]},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3155","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Meeting minutes from 1/9","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:15:50.000Z","fileAttachments":["discussions/127-Web_Hosting_Meeting_1_9_2009.pdf"]}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3030","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"del.icio.us is the best thing ever.","description":"<a href=\"http://delicious.com\">http://delicious.com</a> (regrettably this is the new URL post-Yahoo takeover)\nEnvironment: Web\nIntended audience: Anyone who wants to bring order to their virtual Web lives\n\nOh, I was going to start this post with a link to an important and illustrative example for a specific point I was trying to make. Hmm.. uhh.. can\u2019t seem to find it. Oh well, gone forever it is. Or is it? With Delicious you\u2019ll never lose anything ever again. Here\u2019s that link: <a href=\"http://lib.rario.us/\">http://lib.rario.us/</a> (one of my first bookmarks I ever saved, back in 2006).\n\nOkay, so the link itself is not the point I\u2019m trying to make, it\u2019s the fact that I have it and that I can retrieve it quickly. Delicious is an online service that is typically billed as social bookmarking and it is only one example of this kind of service (see <a href=\"http://www.google.com/bookmarks/\">Google Bookmarks</a>, <a href=\"http://www.stumbleupon.com/\">StumbleUpon</a>, <a href=\"http://www.furl.net/\">Furl</a>, and <a href=\"http://digg.com/\">Digg</a>). And maybe Delicious isn't the very newest or sexiest service out there, but very few things on the Web have stuck with me like Delicious has. There are a plethora of Web 2.0 apps/services out there, and I find it refreshing to have one that does one thing very well. The only thing that would make it better is if more people used it, just like any Web 2.0 app. Hence, this posting :-).\n\nThe way it works is pretty simple, just watch <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x66lV7GOcNU\">this simplistic little demonstration</a>. Thank you <a href=\"http://www.commoncraft.com/\">Common Craft</a> for yet another fantastic and simple tutorial! (aside: talk about \u201cbest thing ever\u201d that could easily be applied to Lee LeFever\u2019s Plain English series). So, you get the idea: go to a Web page, tag it using the Firefox browser plugin, have it forever, automatically share it with everyone, etc. Now that you know how this works, here\u2019s what I really love about it.\n\n<b>My Internet Library</b>\n<a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/128-20090203_1407.png\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/129-20090203_1407.png?width=250\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"207\" style=\"float: right;\"/></a>\n\nThe greatest thing about Delicious is universal access to my folksonomically organized bookmarks. Might sound like a mouthful, but it's all a little too easy and obvious. So, instead of being restricted to folders on a single browser for organizing my bookmarks, I can choose to associate any Web page with as many \"keywords\" (called tags) as I want, after all nothing ever fits neatly into one and only one category does it? Plus, there's no having to deal with the hassle of exporting/importing bookmarks from browser to browser, it's all right there at <a href=\"http://delicious.com/cdmorris\">http://delicious.com/cdmorris</a> (insert your username at cdmorris). At the time of writing this posting, I've made 821 bookmarks. Can you imagine storing that all in a browser? No way. If you could imagine that though, could you imagine finding anything? With Delicious you can start searching for something by looking through your tags. So your thought process might go something like this.. \"Ok I know I found a great web design resource the other day, some kind of background generator tool.. hmm\" and then you'd look through your tags for \"design\" and \"tools\" and <a href=\"http://delicious.com/cdmorris/design+tools\">find it there</a>.\n\nFor me, the real useful tools are the ones that save me time in my everyday life. I want tools that save me steps and shave seconds off of any task. I can't stand having to go back through the dark recesses of my mind to try and figure out the correct Google search string that brought me to the page I found the other day. So, whenever I find something I find useful, I tag it with Delicious and add it to my ever-growing personal Internet library.\n\n<b>My Network</b>\n\nI've established that Delicious makes my life easier by providing me with a catalog of organized links, but the real value definitely is the social aspect - enter \"your network.\" As any of you are familiar, with any social website, you can add friends - or \"fans\" as they are technically called in Delicious. For me, I'm fans of some of my old co-workers, teachers I've had in the past and industry experts. Via RSS I recieve a stream of all new bookmarks that each one of them makes (I use Google Reader here). And now I can get the very latest on what other people are finding interesting or valuable. This helps me stay up-to-date professionally in some cases and in other cases its good for a laugh.\n\n<b>Nice little tool, but...</b>\n\nDon't get me wrong. I know the title of this blog/discussion forum is \"Best Thing Ever\" and I really do love Delicious, but.. there are so many other services out there that decrease it's potential. For example, there's Digg, which is like a specialized version of Delicious focusing on news and articles. Then there's Twitter which some users employ to send out links to each other (ephemeral though they may be). And there's also Google Reader, which has it's Share function. My gripe here is that there are too many options, too many ways to do the same thing, which means we're all missing out on the full potential of the Web.\n\nMy next post on this forum might be regarding a convergence tool like <a href=\"http://friendfeed.com\">FriendFeed</a>, <a href=\"http://www.noovo.com\">NooVo</a> or <a href=\"http://zannel.com\">Zannel</a>, after all <a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/10_ways_social_media_will_change_in_2009.php\">I hear that is one the ways social media will change this year...</a>\n\nps. if you are on Delicious already my username is cdmorris, feel free to follow me or to let me know your account and I can grow my network!","createdDate":"2009-02-03T20:29:37.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-12-14T20:06:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3351","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Fascinating, delicious bookmarking of emails.... that could be useful. Not sure what you are referring to when you say \"Quicksilver file tags\" though - care to talk a bit more about that?","createdDate":"2009-02-11T16:14:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3326","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Only that some things probably aren't worth keeping, but are worth sharing. (e.g. I probably won't care about a Lonely Island video a year from now, but it's fun to share now). del.icio.us is fantastic for things I want to keep.\n\nFriendFeed and the Facebook link sharing are probably more oriented to that \"for a moment\" kind of sharing - and certainly for have the potential of conversation around those links - in fact, I started using FriendFeed for the distinct purpose of wanting to comment on links that colleagues were sharing - usually originally in del.icio.us - or ma.gnolia before the ma.gnolia service failed).","createdDate":"2009-02-11T02:13:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3323","contributorName":"1te7rr9vxnf1i","description":"Also, Gmail emails have stable URLs, so you can bookmark and tag your emails in Delicious (with Do Not Share chosen, of course). And with that, and Quicksilver file tags, I am only a local aggregator away from world domination :&gt;","createdDate":"2009-02-11T01:04:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3315","contributorName":"ew4jprn7fbe5","description":"I love both FriendFeed and delicious (I'm jdorner on both). If I tag a page in delicous, isn't it shared via my FriendFeed where others can comment on it? This way it is both places.\n\nWhat's the advantage of sharing via FriendFeed's post a link feature?","createdDate":"2009-02-10T22:03:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3123","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"yep - and I actually have done this in the past, everything I tagged \"distanceed\" went to my portfolio page. Also, think of the applications in a class: have 30 students and 1 teacher all tagging their class tag, let's say ece101fa09. Students and the teacher could all post interesting things related to the class and see what each other was tagging - and this could be facilitated through a tag-specific RSS feed onto a course web page!! If you can't tell, I &lt;3 delicious.","createdDate":"2009-02-05T20:24:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3063","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"One of the most powerful features of Delicious is it's ability to share your bookmarks via RSS. Not only can you access the master feed of your bookmarks, but you can also pull -tag- specific feeds. For instance, I tend to tag a lot of web articles for <b>design</b>... and I can extract that list out with <a href=\"http://feeds.delicious.com/v2/rss/mjvysock/design?count=15\">this feed</a>.\n\nNow most people tend to create and populate delicious accounts with their personal bookmarks, but imagine for a second if you had an account that served the sole purpose of pushing content to your website and supplementing the user experience. You could bookmark articles specifically for your site, tag them accordingly, and then using the various feeds you could pull links that were related to particular page directly into a sidebar (or footer) for your users to access.","createdDate":"2009-02-04T13:59:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3041","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I, for one, welcome my <a href=\"http://friendfeed.com/jasonadamyoung\">FriendFeed Overlords</a>. FF for me, right now, is the best thing ever for social sharing of links and having a conversation surrounding them. I still have my 'reference library' in del.icio.us - the things I go back to time and again based on tags, but the social part is all FriendFeed now.","createdDate":"2009-02-04T04:16:40.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:3023","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"$500K for NCSU College of Management...for Second Life","description":"Just saw this come across the twitter wire...\n\n<a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/stories/2009/02/02/daily20.html?ana=from_rss\">http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/stories/2009/02/02/daily20.html?ana=from_rss</a>\n\nBasically, Ernst &amp; Young are giving $500K to the COM to develop a presence in SecondLife.\n\nI'm not sure I like the message this will send in the current climate of budget cuts, but i guess getting grant money is better than getting no grant money. I only wonder if COM had a choice in what they spent the funding on.\n\nHas anyone else out there developed for SecondLife already? Im trying to figure out how far $500K would go in development. Does one Linden dollar equal a real dollar?","createdDate":"2009-02-03T17:43:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-05T20:30:55.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3126","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Actually this goes only to the Accounting department within COM. This is huge! I don't know what they plan on developing, but my guess is they will use the money to buy a big piece of real estate in SL (aka - server space) and then start doing the boring stuff that everyone else out there does with Second Life (aka - recreate physical buildings). Hopefully they'll amp up the imagination and do something interesting, but I'm having trouble thinking of accounting scenarios that could really benefit from this - this trouble is either a result of not enough caffeine for me or the fact that accounting makes me think of spreadsheets and numbers. Thanks for posting this though, I'll be curious to see what they come up with.","createdDate":"2009-02-05T20:30:55.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2762","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Interest in an iPhone development class?","description":"This is just a \"feeler\" to see if any of you guys would be interested in attending an iPhone development class. It's something that I have wanted to look into for a long time, but have never had the opportunity. I was going to try to make some calls and see about getting some who knew what was up to do like a one day tutorial or something like that. However, I don't wanna go through all that if no-one else is interested. Would that be something you guys would wanna do?","createdDate":"2009-01-27T21:01:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-11-18T13:08:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10118","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Another resource:\n<a href=\"http://digitalmedia.oreilly.com/iphone/?CMP=ILC-orm_sponsor_footer_links&amp;ATT=iphone\" target=\"_blank\">http://digitalmedia.oreilly.com/iphone/?CMP=ILC-orm_sponsor_footer_links&amp;ATT=iphone</a>","createdDate":"2009-11-18T13:08:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:10117","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"FYI\nHere are some resources:\n<a href=\"http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596155452/\" target=\"_blank\">http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596155452/</a>","createdDate":"2009-11-18T12:16:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4248","contributorName":"2nzrrfshzfg2m","description":"Hey Jason, I'll bring my own macbook :)","createdDate":"2009-03-04T15:47:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4244","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Thanks for everyone for signing up. The class is full now, but there is a waitlist available for 10 people. We think we may be able to get some more people in if they bring their own machines. You can sign up for the waitlist at <a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate/workshop/index/details/?workshopId=94\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/classmate/workshop/index/details/?workshopId=94</a>.\n\nFor those of you who emailed me, make sure you sign into classmate and confirm I have your info correct. Everyone who emailed me is now in the class. If for some reason you can't make it, please go to classmate and cancel your reservation. We've had lots of interest in this class, and I wouldn't want someone on the waitlist to miss out.\n\nThanks!","createdDate":"2009-03-04T14:38:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4123","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Hey everyone, I finally have approval for an iPhone class, but I want to make sure anyone on the web developers group gets first crack at it. We are going to be doing signup via classmate, but if you email me your info, I will add you to the role before we open it up to the general public. I am going to open the class up on wednesday, so email (jason_austin at ncsu dot edu) me your info before wednesday morning for early signup. After that, you will be on your own to fight out the remaining spots :)\n\nThe class will be March 19th from 9 - 12 in the Jordan Mac Lab.","createdDate":"2009-03-02T19:47:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3864","contributorName":"1l94q89y956k5","description":"i would also like to learn more about iphone, and mobile development in general.\n\n(probably way late, but i've been lurking instead of joining ning)","createdDate":"2009-02-24T15:05:14.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2957","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Count me in. RE: Mike's reply. We have 3-4 student developers in ITECS.","createdDate":"2009-01-30T21:33:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2949","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Came across a post this morning for iPhone Development...\n<a href=\"http://hiddenpixels.com/designer-and-developer-resources/iphone-web-development-resources-tools-tutorials/\">http://hiddenpixels.com/designer-and-developer-resources/iphone-web-development-resources-tools-tutorials/</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-30T17:08:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2894","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Heck, yes. I'm in.","createdDate":"2009-01-29T20:47:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2878","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"rock on...how many folks is that?","createdDate":"2009-01-29T19:11:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2875","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"I'm interested and would probably mandate that all of our student developers in ITECS attend as well.","createdDate":"2009-01-29T19:11:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2763","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I'd be very interested in doing something like that!","createdDate":"2009-01-27T21:12:23.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2758","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Meeting Minutes from 1/15/2009","description":"See attached notes. Things are moving ahead. I wasn't at the last meeting so I am in search of meeting minutes for that meeting.","createdDate":"2009-01-27T20:52:48.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-06T20:17:45.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/130-Web_Hosting_Mtg_1_15.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3170","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"consolidating to a single thread.","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:17:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2745","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Contribute CS4 installation - Administrator","description":"Here is my latest experience with installing Contribute CS4:\n\nI work at OIT. Part of my responsibilities is to be the Contribute Administrator of for the (AFS based) Web sites that OIT-OCC-DEO supports (quite a few of them). Some large(30+ users), others smaller and a lot with only one or two users.\n\nNow that Contribute CS4 is available, and some of the clients either installing it or will soon be ordering it, I wanted to install it on my computer (PC).\n\nTo begin with, I provide instructions to clients on how to obtain and install Contribute.\nSo, this looked like a good time to update those procedures.\n\nI updated the procedures and began to test them.\n\nThe download (of Contribute CS4) went great.\n\nThe install started smoothly. However, during the download, a pop up asked me if I wanted to allow earlier versions of Contribute to be used. I checked the Yes box. The remainder of the install continued to a successful conclusion. I closed Contreibute CS4. Happy that my instruction worked.\n\nA little while later, I received a message form a client saying that she was trying to use Contribute (CS3) to update some web pages, but got a message (on the yellow message bar) that said the the connection was no longer valid.\n\nI started up my Contribute CS3 and found out that my key based connections were also no longer valid.\n\nLater that day (and continuing), more calls came in form other users that also were getting the message that the the same message - their connections were no longer valid.\n\nAfter conducting some research, we found out that other people had reported the same problem and that an apparent solution was to: 1) disable all administrative functions in Contribute CS4 (I did and I also removed CS4 from my computer), and 2) have clients re-install their connection keys.\n\nUsing Contribute CS3, I sent clients connection keys along with instructions on how to install them. That worked.\n\nNow, I have to make sure that all of my remaining clients re-install their connection keys.\n\nAs the tee shirts say - \"Life is good\".\n\n\nToday, I received the following additional information:\n\nIts from:\n<a href=\"http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba3730-7c33.html\">http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba3730-7c33.html</a>\n\nAnd says:\nEnable compatibility with older versions of Contribute\n\nComments (0)\nContribute offers administrators two compatibility options\u2014one that allows users with earlier versions to work on the website, and one that does not:\n\nTransition mode\nIn this mode, users of earlier versions of Contribute can continue working on the website, along with Contribute 4.0 and later users. This lets you evaluate the new version and set up new roles and permissions without disrupting users with earlier versions of Contribute.\nCompatibility mode\nIn this mode, all users must use Contribute 4.0 or later. Users with earlier versions cannot work on the website.\nContribute 4.0 or later starts in Transition mode by default when you migrate from an earlier version of Contribute. Use this mode temporarily; when you\u2019re ready, transition all users to Contribute 4.0 or later and enable Compatibility Mode.\n\nIn Contribute 4.0 or later, select Edit &gt; Administer Websites, and then select a website.\nThe Administer Website dialog box appears.\nSelect Compatibility from the category list on the left.\nThe Compatibility options appear in the Administer Website dialog box.\nSelect Compatibility, and then click Close.\nAfter you enable Compatibility Mode, all users connected to the website must use Contribute 4.0 or later.","createdDate":"2009-01-27T16:31:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-30T21:37:45.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2960","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","description":"Sounds scary, in print and on the phone when you told me! We are looking at upgrading our admin users from Contribute 3 to CS4. Will be cautious. Thanks for passing this on!","createdDate":"2009-01-30T21:37:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2861","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Additional Adobe Contribute CS4 resource at:\n<a href=\"http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba180d-7fff.html\">http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba180d-7fff.html</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-29T12:51:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2766","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","description":"Follow up to this posting:\n\nAdobe Contribute CS3 is actually Contribute 4.1\nAdobe Contribute CS4 is actually Contribute 5.0\n\nSo, I do not know if the information at the following link may apply:\n<a href=\"http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba3730-7c33.html\">http://help.adobe.com/en_US/Contribute/5.0_Using/WS5b3ccc516d4fbf351e63e3d1180fba3730-7c33.html</a>\n\nDon Schmidt","createdDate":"2009-01-27T21:13:31.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2722","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Nuevasync!","description":"Best Thing Ever! - Neuvasync\n<a href=\"https://www.nuevasync.com/\">https://www.nuevasync.com/</a>\nEnvironment: Web/Cell Phones\nIntended Audience: Cell Phone (notably iPhone) / Google Calendar Users\n\nThis story starts with me in my dentist's office. After my (painful) visit, I am trying to schedule an appointment for 6 months away. The lady behind the counter picks a day, and my first thought it \"Wait, lemme check my calendar to make sure I don't have anything scheduled\". So I whip out my fancy schmancy, brand spankin' new iPhone, and click on the calendar icon. March -&gt; 12 -&gt; 2009. Nothing on there, must be free! \"Sign me up,\" I say. So I put my appointment on my calendar on my iPhone, get home, sync up my phone, and whaddaya know? I have a meeting on that day, and therefore can't go to the dentist. A rousing story of phone tag and reschedule attempts followed, but you get the gist of the story.\n\nIf you have been using iPhone without Neuvasync, this story probably sounds familiar.\n\nBy default, iPhone can't do over-the-air syncing with a calendar (whether its on iCal on your computer, or GCal) unless you have it setup with an Exchange server, unless you want to pay for MobileMe. Since I don't have access to an Exchange server, and I didn't want to drop $99/year for MobileMe, I was stuck with syncing my calendars whenever I synced my phone with my computer. That is until i discovered Neuvasync.\n\n<img src=\"discussions/131-ipod_cal.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"350\" height=\"510\" style=\"float: right;\"/>\nNeuvasync allows you to masquerade your Google Calendar as a Microsoft Exchange server. So what does that mean exactly? It means that if you create an appointment on your phone, it will automatically push that appointment to your Google Calendar. It also means that if you put an appointment on Google Calendar, it will push back to your phone.\n\nInstantly, your calendar application on your iPhone becomes useful without MobileMe or Exchange! No more waiting to sync when you get home. No more scheduling meetings over one another. It's really the best thing for the iPhone since...well...the iPhone.\n\nNeuvasync also added a new feature in the last week or so that supports colors for calendars, meaning if you have more than one Google calendar setup for your account, they show up in different colors on your iPhone!\n\nDon't have an iPhone? Neuvasync works with a variety of other devices, including some Windows Mobile devices!\n\nAs far as setup is concerned, it was easy as pie. Neuvasync provides detailed instructions on granting access to your Google Calendar, then getting it setup on your phone. The only caveat was that when setting up your phone to use an Exchange server, it will delete all your existing appointments that are currently on your phone. That's an Apple thing, not a Neuvasync thing, so other phones may have different results.\n\nNeuvasync really has changed the way I use my mobile phone. Even though this isn't a \"web development\" related service, it sure has made me more efficient, which carries over into other parts of my life. So check out Neuvasync if you haven't already. Your dentist receptionist will thank you later :)","createdDate":"2009-01-27T12:56:54.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-27T12:57:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2648","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Help!  Tiered Development and Databases","description":"We have a conundrum...\n\nWe have a tiered development structure, where we have AFS space for development, staging, and production. All of our projects live in SVN repos which we all commit into for development. When we are ready for a release, we export from SVN into our production space. Right now, we do this without changing any code or config vars or anything. We do this by (embarrassingly) using the production DB when we are working in dev or stage.\n\nProblem is, we just haven't figured out a good way to do it any differently. I really don't want to touch production code, even just changing a config variable, but we are to the point where this model just doesn't work anymore.\n\nHow are the rest of you handling this? There's gotta be a better way...","createdDate":"2009-01-23T20:08:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-27T13:21:40.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2728","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Thanks for your suggestions Jason. I think we are gonna go with the server variable bit. I was thinking about making it contextually aware based on the requesting domain (ie, webapps.ncsu.edu would go to production branch, webapps-dev.ncsu.edu would go to dev branch), but a server var seems like a better approach.\n\nI think, in the end, we are going to have to have more development on local machines as opposed to in AFS. The only issue with that I see is keeping consistent configurations, and not using something which works on local machines that doesn't in the AFS environment. Of course this all will be a bit easier to manage if we can get our web hosting stuff situated to a point that will allow us to have separate vhosts for dev and production code.\n\nAnyone else out there tackling these issues?","createdDate":"2009-01-27T13:21:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2661","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Sheesh. Man do I wrote [sic.] poorly when I'm writing fast.\n\nIn my only defense, English <i>is</i> my second language though.\n\nAfter Southern.","createdDate":"2009-01-24T13:24:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2656","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"You have to go with a per vhost (or per environment) configuration in some way. You could probably get away with defining something based on $_SERVER['SERVER_NAME'] in the request somewhere before you setup your db connection - but if I remember right there's some possible conditions under which SERVER_NAME can be affected by the requested host in the HTTP headers.\n\nThe Rails framework does what it does by using a database configuration file and ruby process is launched under either ENV[\"RAILS_ENV\"] == 'production' or ENV[\"RAILS_ENV\"] == 'development' (or test). However that affects more things, like debugging settings, object persistence, and the rest. What we do is leave this configuration file out of subversion (svn:ignore property) and put the config file on each execution environment - development mode locally, and the demo database config in production mode on the demo server and the production db config on the production server. The server config file is outsided the deployment directory and symlink'd in our case.\n\nWe do similar with other configurations - we'll have per server settings in a configuration file, and leave the configuration file out of subversion, and have conditional code blocks based on the configuration settings (like sending exception emails with different subject lines so we can tell the different between errors that matter and those that don't so much).\n\nOut of all of the things I experimented with over the years, I still keep coming back to the per-server configuration settings, and leaving that out of subversion.","createdDate":"2009-01-24T02:04:59.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2626","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Why we use Firefox","description":"The folks over at New City Media have a good post about using Firefox for web development, in spite of the majority using other, more ridiculous browsers. And I'll take this opp to mention that New City Media does some really nice work sharing their \"agency\" thinking with the masses through their blog. It's uncommon transparency, particularly in the sense that their ideas are a commodity, but they are willing to share to make the Web a better place.\n\nAnyhow, here's the link.\n\n<a href=\"http://is.gd/gTW6\">http://is.gd/gTW6</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-23T01:23:23.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-31T17:45:24.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2990","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/video/design-coding-rap\">\"checkin' all browsers, I do it directly..\"</a>\n\noh i cant help sharing this again and again","createdDate":"2009-01-31T17:45:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2901","contributorName":"211tgo999ov7e","description":"I'm probably one of the few web people who still use IE regularly and as my primary browser. At the same time, I also seem to be among the few who still test IE6 and make sure to get most of my web tools working for it.\n\nThe reasons are two-fold: First, on my own public facing website, my browser report over the past month comes out to:\nInternet Explorer - 61.17%\nFirefox - 25.97%\nOpera - 7.35%\nSafari - 2.41%\nChrome - 2.36%\n\nOf that 61% IE traffic, 33% is still IE6; so basically, around 20% IE6 users. Considering that is barely lower than my Firefox percentage, and almost double the combination of the other 3 browsers, it's a hard demographic to ignore.\n\nOn the ECE homepage (a much, much smaller sample which I think is heavily skewed by all the testing we do on the page), we get:\nInternet Explorer 46.32%\nFirefox 41.62%\nChrome 4.96%\nSafari 4.01%\n\nWith 27% of the IE traffic being IE6, so 12% total viewership by my math. At the end of the day, I don't see how you can say \"let me cater to Chrome and Safari, instead of IE6, when both are much less popular\". That's just my point of view; and I don't expect many to share it. I'm still jaded against non-IE browsers after the hell that was Netscape 4.7.\n\nThe second reason is that primarily when I develop, I start doing so in IE6. IE6 is almost a common ancestor to every modern browser in that when each of these newer browsers came out they HAD to render the pages that IE6 could, otherwise they never would've gained any marketshare. So if you start all your pages there, it tends to make it easier to branch it out to Firefox and IE7, rather than going from Firefox to IE7 then trying to work in IE6. You'll still be able to make your pages compliant and validate, but I generally find myself using CSS hacks and tricks a lot less.\n\nThen again, I've been developing in IE6 for about 10 years now, so I'm sort of used to all it's little idiosyncrasies.","createdDate":"2009-01-29T21:20:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2801","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We have a similar mantra....we only support current browser versions, and that aint IE6. If you are using IE6 at this point, you are a full release behind, and soon will be 2 full releases behind. I see no redeeming value in IE6, nor IE in general (of course, like Jason, I am a bit bitter).\n\nWe also use standards, as well as the adoption of things like <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/yui-library-css-tools\">Yahoo's YUI CSS tools</a>. By using those, we are predominantly sure that our app will not look like a Picasso painting in IE6. We base all our JS on jQuery or MooTools, which takes a lot of the guess work out of browser compatibility, but honestly we just ignore IE6 as much as possible. Firefox...check. Safari/WebKit....check. IE7....sorta check.","createdDate":"2009-01-28T13:15:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2781","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I'm not sure that I'd give the campus community any credit for being smarter. However, I'm a bitter and jaded old man. Okay, I've always been bitter and jaded - so that needs a grain of salt.\n\nI do think that NC State in particular has a history of Microsoft alternatives in general and that may have some influence. And we have a fairly large group of folks doing web development, and that have suffered dearly doing IE 6 development support and maybe we have some influence. I have lost good and valuable months of my life that I'll never get back because of IE and javascript.\n\nI will say with those numbers, we don't care so much anymore about IE (okay IE 6) Our UI architect will, much to my chagrin, test in IE 6. But I've personally written IE 6 off - and only do cursory testing in IE 7. (though, see part about bitter and jaded, lather-rinse-repeat). Thankfully, most of what I do is standard, and standard frameworks, and IE at least pretends to work most of the time.\n\nWhat gets me is the people that *like* IE 6. The COMPUTING PEOPLE that like IE 6. That boggles the mind - and that's not even bitter and jaded talking.","createdDate":"2009-01-28T03:20:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2739","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Funny you should bring this up since I remember reading this recently:\n\n<a href=\"http://news.cnet.com/8301-13505_3-10130301-16.html\">http://news.cnet.com/8301-13505_3-10130301-16.html</a>\n\nI find it appalling that almost 70% of users are still browsing with IE and even worse that 20% of that number are still using IE 6.0. I don't know about you guys but I'm not even testing in IE6 (IE 7.0 uninstalled it on the way in).\n\nI'd like to think campus is a smarter group, hence the higher percentage of non-IE users. That being said I overheard someone complaining about people browsing with \"Foxfire\" a few weeks ago. It hurt me.","createdDate":"2009-01-27T14:59:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2701","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"The College of Engineering (<a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu\">http://www.engr.ncsu.edu</a>) visitors are 59% IE (20% of that bunch still use IE6) and about 35% using Firefox. Overall, VERY similar to Charlie's breakdown.","createdDate":"2009-01-26T15:35:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2683","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Yeah, I think it's still accurate where the general public is using your site(s) (particularly via search).\n\nHere are two of our sites for the last month where the traffic is coming in predominately via search and that are geared toward to the general public - with <i>vastly</i> different traffic profiles, but with similar browser numbers:\n\nOur <a href=\"http://www.extension.org\">Public Site</a>:\n<img src=\"http://share.extension.org/public/engineering/ga/public_site.jpg\"/>\n\nOur very little used <a href=\"http://news.extension.org\">\"News\" aggregation site</a> :\n<img src=\"http://share.extension.org/public/engineering/ga/news.jpg\"/>\n\nVery similar browser profiles.\n\nNow, thankfully there's hope, our internal sites, targeted at faculty/staff , with a lot more referrer/direct traffic:\n\nA balanced referrer/direct/search site at <a href=\"http://about.extension.org\">about.extension.org</a>:\n<img src=\"http://share.extension.org/public/engineering/ga/about.jpg\"/>\n\nTwo of our content creation tools:\n\n<a href=\"http://about.extension.org\">faq.extension.org</a>:\n<img src=\"http://share.extension.org/public/engineering/ga/faq.jpg\"/>\n\n<a href=\"http://about.extension.org\">copwiki.extension.org</a>:\n<img src=\"http://share.extension.org/public/engineering/ga/copwiki.jpg\"/>\n\nThis is a least a snapshot of what we are seeing with some of our sites.","createdDate":"2009-01-26T01:17:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2641","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I don't think 70-80% is accurate anymore for IE users.. check out one of CNR's most-visited sites <a href=\"http://screencast.com/t/ZbKbu8ttXQH\">stats</a>\n\nIE = 58%\nFF = ~31% (both Mac and PC)\nSafari = 6%\nChrome (ugh) = 2%\n\nI wonder what other stats people around here are getting for browsers of visitors.","createdDate":"2009-01-23T14:06:20.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2583","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"50 Useful PHP Tools","description":"found this article in my wanderings, and thought i would ask the group if they've used any of these tools before. And by continuing that thought, is this list any good at all?\n\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/01/20/50-extremely-useful-php-tools/\">http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/01/20/50-extremely-useful-php-tools/</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-21T13:31:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-28T14:46:30.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1790","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6049","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"I've used dBug ( <a href=\"http://dbug.ospinto.com/\">http://dbug.ospinto.com/</a> ). If you've ever seen the ColdFusion cfdump tag and its nifty tables/JavaScript output, you'll love this one. One include, one new, and you can view almost any huge nested object/structure/resource in your browser. Highly recommended!","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:46:30.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:5421","contributorName":"1m89sv3p0ar0c","description":"I found a condensed version with just 5\n\n<a href=\"http://query7.com/top-5-php-resource-websites/\">http://query7.com/top-5-php-resource-websites/</a>\n\nHeavy on tutorials I plan on looking into it more.","createdDate":"2009-04-03T12:06:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2569","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"YUI Library CSS Tools","description":"<b>YUI Library CSS Tools</b>\nURL - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/</a>\nEnvironment - Web\nIntended Audience - Web developers\n\nHow many times have you been asked to create a website or application only to begin by doing something you've done a hojillion times, create a layout? I know I certainly have, and it's a pain to run into the same layout problems over and over again and to address repeatedly the cross browser nuances that inevitably plague us all. I needed a solution or I was going to end up tearing my hair out, driving to Redmond, and bestowing my pent up rage and hatred for Internet Explorer upon some unsuspecting Microsoft peon. Enter Yahoo! to save the day!\n\nYahoo!, in what I can only imagine as a feat of clairvoyance, realized how livid I was regarding this exact subject and came up with the Yahoo User Interface Library CSS Tools, for which I am eternally grateful. There are four main pieces to the CSS tools \u2013 fonts, base, reset, and grids \u2013 each one more awe-inspiring than the last. The basic goal of the entire YUI CSS Tools suite is to normalize your look and feel across all A-grade browsers (as of this writing, Firefox 3 is the only A-grade browser across all operating systems).\n\n<b>Fonts, Reset, and Base</b>\n\nFonts is intended to normalize the font size and line height across all browsers. This means that all your font sizes will be consistent whether or not you look at your page in IE, Safari, or Firefox. Rather than have to add CSS hacks and such nonsense to make it look right in IE, just include this file and all your fonts will look the same with no extra effort on your part.\n\nReset is the core of the three styling tools, and is probably the most useful. It \"removes and neutralizes the inconsistent default styling of HTML elements, creating a level playing field across A-grade browsers and providing a sound foundation upon which you can explicitly declare your intentions.\" The key thing there is \"explicitly declare your intentions.\" This means no unexpected padding or margin issues where IE gives a default margin to an element and another browser does not. Reset takes care of that by making every element look exactly the same in all browsers unless you specify otherwise.\n\nBase, in some ways, is the opposite of reset. \"While Reset removes and neutralizes the inconsistent default styling of HTML elements, Base applies a consistent style foundation for common HTML elements across A-grade browsers. It's certainly optional, but saves you a decent amount of work in having to assign default styles to all the elements. If you want something different than they provide for several, then it's easier to just override those specific tags than have to deal with all of them.\n\n<b>Grids and Grids Builder</b>\n\nLastly, the piece I think is the best thing since Italo Marchioni patented the ice cream cone in 1903. \"Grids offers four preset page widths, six preset templates, and the ability to stack and nest subdivided regions of two, three, or four columns. The 4kb file provides over 1000 page layout combination.\" What does this mean? This means that you no longer need to worry about laying out your CSS divs, containers, leftColumn, and rightColumn nonsense. This takes care of all of that for you. You can even build your layout with their handy grids builder (<a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/builder/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/builder/</a>) so there's no guessing or trial-and-error involved.\n\nAdditionally, the result of using Grids has more profound theoretical implications. Being able to keep the structure of the layout (the grid, essentially) separate from the feel of the layout (colors, background-images, etc.) is an often unrealized pipe dream (at least it was for me). But now, that dream has become reality, and how the app feels is separate from how its layout is constructed and all of that is separate from how it behaves. Its helps one obtain a level of abstraction and organization heretofore only achieved by Buddhist monks living in remote Himalayan monasteries.\n\nThanks Yahoo! for helping keep me centered and calm, bringing me that much closer to CSS Nirvana.\n\nFonts - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/fonts/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/fonts/</a>\nReset - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/reset/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/reset/</a>\nBase - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/base/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/base/</a>\nGrids - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/</a>\nGrids Builder - <a href=\"http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/builder/\">http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/grids/builder/</a>\n\nSubmitted by Garrison Locke (gplocke)","createdDate":"2009-01-20T18:38:27.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-23T01:13:51.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2623","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'll second Garrison's blatant fanboyism. We have been using YUI's css libraries for the last 2 years and it has really REALLY helped speed up cross-browser testing. We no longer have to worry about a 3 column layout looking completely busted in IE when it looks spectacular in FF and Safari.\n\nAnd if any of you are concerned about converting an existing layout to grids, have no fear. It is actually really easy. We end up doing this a good bit, and have integrated wordpress and drupal templates using grids. It's good stuff, and there is no use in re-inventing the wheel by creating your own structural CSS.\n\nTime-saver scale: 9.4/10","createdDate":"2009-01-23T01:13:51.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2409","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"How to run a meeting like Google","description":"Just saw this on one of my Google reader subscriptions, and it rings true on several points. I thought some (or a lot) of web developers may run meetings, so i figure this might spark some ideas on how to run them better.\n\nWithout going into too much detail, my favorite points were \"Micro-meetings\" and \"Discourage politics, use data\"\n\nAnyway, here's the link: <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/smallbiz/content/sep2006/sb20060927_259688.htm\">http://www.businessweek.com/smallbiz/content/sep2006/sb20060927_259688.htm</a>\n\nenjoy :-)","createdDate":"2009-01-15T18:04:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-15T21:34:52.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2421","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"Good post. Some good pointers in there. Micro meetings are critical, as well as keeping politics out of the discussion (even if that is totally impossible at NC State).","createdDate":"2009-01-15T21:34:52.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2331","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Do you know of something that can do this ____ ?","description":"I'm looking for some kind of webapp or script that can read a directory on a server and write the contents of that directory onto, let's say, an unordered list in HTML. Would really like it if anyone knew a technique here, especially if it is using Javascript. Anybody have an idea?","createdDate":"2009-01-14T14:17:00.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-15T21:37:15.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2424","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"You know, this forum question is actually ripe for a regular forum section. Any takers?","createdDate":"2009-01-15T21:37:15.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2401","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"That makes sense. By the way, I was able to get it to work with PHP on some of my <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/project/cnr/dev/index.htm\">test space</a>. It's pretty cool! Only downside is that clicking on a file only tells you the location, it doesn't download it, but I'm sure that the code could be re-written so that it does.","createdDate":"2009-01-15T13:09:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2383","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I dont think you are gonna be able to find anything that will read through directories without server-side scripting. Javascript just won't do it because it won't have the server access. I have no idea what the capabilities of WolfWare are...maybe CGI/Perl?","createdDate":"2009-01-15T02:00:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2365","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Cool, thanks Jason, would be even better if no server-side scripting was needed period. I'm looking to use this for WolfWare (/afs/eos/courses/*), which as you may or may not know is not PHP-enabled. It might have other server-side options though - do you know if it does?","createdDate":"2009-01-14T20:29:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2337","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"<a href=\"http://abeautifulsite.net/notebook/58\">http://abeautifulsite.net/notebook/58</a>\n\njQuery ftw! Ive never used this thing, but it look hawt!","createdDate":"2009-01-14T14:30:45.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2310","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"i18n with Zend_Translate and MVC Architecture?","description":"We are working on version 2 of our application framework and are trying to figure out the i18n support with Zend_Translate with regards to ZF's MVC architecture.\n\nHere is the scenario:\n\nWe want to add the ability for our apps to seamlessly support multiple languages, and by languages I don't just mean english vs. russian vs. spanish. By language I mean anything different than the default text that we ship with the application, IE the text on the page says \"hello world\" and the application admin wants that to say \"howdy people\" without contacting us.\n\nZend_Translate allows you to do this pretty easy. In your view, you simply can say $this-&gt;translate('hello world') and it will go to your language file and find any entry for \"hello world\" and replace it with whatever is there, in this case \"howdy people\". This is all well and good until you change the default from \"hello world\" to \"whats up world\". Then the translation (which is keyed off of \"hello world\") is broken. So they provide an option, basically defining a key for each place you wanna put text in the app. So instead of $this-&gt;translate(\"Hello World\"), you'd say $this-&gt;translate('default-index-header'). Then you'd provide a default language that maps 'default-index-header' to \"Hello World\", and any new language would map 'default-index-header' to whatever (\"howdy people\") and it would still work, even if you changed the default to \"whats up world\".\n\nThe problem to this solution is that if there is no translation for 'defalul-index-header', it will print \"default-index-header\" to the browser, which means any and all translations have to be complete. Any thoughts on a preferred way to do this?\n\nThis is only really the tip of the iceberg when it comes in i18n, but were working towards a solution. Anyone out there had any experience in designing apps for multiple language support?","createdDate":"2009-01-13T20:51:35.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-13T20:51:35.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2305","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","title":"Netvibes : Personalized Internet Content Buffet","description":"<p><strong>Netvibes</strong> (<a href=\"http://www.netvibes.com\">www.netvibes.com</a>) is an up-to-the-minute summary of your personal, customizable Web. It's the online tool that lets you scan headlines from 30 or 40 hand-picked websites (or 100 if you're into that kind of thing) in a matter minutes on the very same page you check email, Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, YouTube, del.icio.us, etc. It's an all-you-can-eat, Internet content buffet with no rules on plate sharing.</p>\n<p><strong>Why is this the Best Thing Ever?</strong><br/></p>\n<div style=\"width:280px; float:right; margin-left:10px; margin-bottom:10px; padding:3px; border:1px solid black;\"><p><strong>Name of App / Service</strong><br/> Netvibes</p>\n<p><strong>URL</strong><br/> <a>http://www.netvibes.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>Environment</strong><br/> (online) widget-based ajax desktop</p>\n<p><strong>Operating System</strong><br/> web based</p>\n<p><strong>Intended Audience</strong><br/> Anyone looking for a single site to aggregate a huge variety of content (rss, social networking, web clips, email etc.)</p>\n<p><strong>Screenshot</strong><br/> <a href=\"http://www.webcommdev.com/tim/images/netvibes-screen.jpg\"><img border=\"0\" src=\"http://www.webcommdev.com/tim/images/netvibes-thumb.jpg\" alt=\"Netvibes Screenshot Thumbnail\"/></a></p>\n<p><strong>Submitted by</strong><br/> Tim Jones (ukalimbe) and Luis Chacon (lrchacon)</p>\n</div>\nThe essential concept of Netvibes is a personalized website that aggregates virtually any kind of content you want from across the far reaches of the Internet. Although it shares some similarities as a portal, I hesitate to call it one because Netvibes doesn't simply \"lead\" to other sites \u2013 rather, it brings content in. A subtle difference, but a compelling one \u2013 particularly in regards to RSS (more on that later).<p></p>\n<p>What sets Netvibes apart from other online widget-based desktops (iGoogle, myYahoo, Microsft Live, Pageflakes) is, in a word, flexibility. High-quality themes, infinitely-editable color schemes and a huge variety of mix-and-match configurations for one-, two-, three- and four-column layouts make it easy to create a customized grid on which to dump as much stuff as you possibly can. Netvibes allows you to create several pages full of widgetized content, and displays them in a familiar tabbed interface. On top of that, each tab can have a different layout of its own.</p>\n<p>Netvibes offers all of the expected widgets \u2013 weather, email, RSS feeds, Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, Flickr, Google search, along with hundreds of obscure \u2013 but no doubt, useful \u2013 widgets, accessible through a useful search. Search for a widget, click \"Add to my Page\" and there you have it.</p>\n<p>Where Netvibes really shines is with RSS feeds. Adding a feed is as simple as pasting a URL into a text block. Coupled with Netvibes' tabbing and AJAX-ified drag-and-drop, organizing and recording feeds is quick and easy. I have a few RSS tabs, each dedicated to a particular topic, like \"marketing,\" \"technology,\" \"sports,\" \"higher ed\" and \"lolCats,\" making it easy to scan a bunch of content very quickly with some structure. Feeds display cleanly once on the page. Mousing over headlines in a feed displays the first snippet of the content, which is particularly useful for high-speed news scanning. Nothing worse than a pithy headline that, after clicking on it and waiting for the destination site to load, turns out to be a crap story.</p>\n<p>Netvibes also offers a couple options for reading syndicated content as well. You can 1) use the \"feed view\" that \u2013 depending on the particular feed's setup \u2013 will show you a teaser or the full content and the link from Netvibes to the actual content, or 2) the \"show website\" view that sucks in the page containing the content into the Netvibes reader window. And, you can toggle between the two options on the fly. Very handy.</p>\n<p>Social networking sites \u2013 everybody's favorite \u2013 are also easy to integrate into Netvibes. The Facebook widget is very user-friendly, showing your profile summary (inbox, friend requests, invites, status, etc.), a status-update tool and your friends list. Again, clever use of the mouseover, which shows your friends' status updates from the thumbnail view, makes this widget useful for impatient, hurried web browsers like myself. Twitter integration, too, is very well done.</p>\n<p>One of my favorite uses for Netvibes (I do work in public affairs after all) is the monitoring capability provided by pre-populated searches of news, blog, video and photo sites. Every time I log in to Netvibes, I see the most recent results for \"NC State\" or \"NCSU\" on Technorati, YouTube and Flickr, among others.</p>\n<p>Another well-done feature is what I term web clips \u2013 basically iframed web pages. For those sites that do not provide content-syndication options, you can clip an actual page and skim it right in Netvibes. Since Netvibes allows flexibility with different tabs having custom layouts, I set up a web clip on a 2-column page \u2013 the web clip taking 75% of the real estate \u2013 and related RSS feeds in the narrower column. So I have 'dub dub dub' as my main web clip on my NCSU tab and sysnews, ning, and a few other NCSU-specific feeds set up for quick and easy skimming.</p>\n<p>In the spirit of Web 2.0 (are we really still talking about that?), Netvibes gives you the option of setting up a \"public\" page to share your favorite content with the world. Admittedly I haven't taken advantage of this offering, but it's cool to know that it's there if I want to, or others demand that I share my undeniably profound collection of content.</p>","createdDate":"2009-01-13T17:01:19.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-14T14:40:44.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2340","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"\"Web 3.0\" is already being used, and anyone that uses it should be immediately regarded with suspicion because they clearly have no idea what they are talking about.\n\nMy favorite early last year were the <a href=\"http://rambleon.org/2008/03/18/just-fyi/\">fools using \"Web 1.5\"</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-14T14:40:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2307","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I'm tired of \"Web 2.0\" as a phrase too, and the first person who says \"Web 3.0\" gets punched or at least ridiculed. ;)\n\nYeah, I use iGoogle and have used Netvibes in the past, but I've gotten in the habit of using Google Reader for everything. While Google Reader is a similar animal it's got a major difference in how content that is pulled in is displayed.\n\nAnyway, nice post! Anytime you can mention <a href=\"http://icanhascheezburger.com/2009/01/09/funny-pictures-needs-iz-a-crazy-laydee/\">lolcats</a> you've done a good job I think.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T17:55:00.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2245","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Meeting Minutes from 1/9/2009","description":"Here are our meeting minutes from our last web hosting pilot meeting. Lots of things got put in motion, but no big decisions were made. Our next meeting will be on Jan 16th.","createdDate":"2009-01-12T19:58:32.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/132-Web_Hosting_Meeting_1_9_2009.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3168","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"consolidating these to a single thread and closing this one....","createdDate":"2009-02-06T20:17:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2769","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I just posted these <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/web-hosting-pilot-meeting-1\">here</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-27T22:40:05.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2198","contributorName":"2svjysi3vj2qk","title":"What next?","description":"There has been some discussion that maybe AFS isn't the right filesystem to use to back web services. While I certainly don't believe AFS is the right FS for home directories or research data, it has done pretty well for our (meaning COE) web infrastructure. That being said:\n\n1. What other FS's have people looked at for web services? We've very cursorily talked about CIFS, ZFS, or Lustre, but none really impress me too much. Any ideas?\n\n2. Do people believe that IF the university starts using different web services models side-by-side (like a pool of standard LAMP boxes + some vhost w/ drupal via cPanel + linux box with apache and sysadmin can install whatever) that they would all even need to use the same back-end filesystem?","createdDate":"2009-01-09T21:48:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-13T18:22:35.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:859","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3406","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"If cpanel is the way we go, then we're looking at using the native file system and providing remote access to it via WebDAV. That's all built into the cpanel and seems to work to some degree. (Works nicely on my Windows PC, not so nicely on my RHEL5 machine, but RHEL5 doesn't have native FUSE support which is required.)","createdDate":"2009-02-13T18:22:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3395","contributorName":"07qv4q0ev7rkm","description":"CHASS moved into AFS fairly recently, still not entirely done with the transition. Previously the primary web servers ran on DFS, and some web stuff and all home directories/research data on novell. While there have been some rocky parts during the transition I find AFS to be a great improvement. It has been much easier to manage the web sites and spaces, and the users seem to have an easier time as well. Granted, our previous setup wasn't all that it could be, and using the ITECS locker model helps a bit too (thanks guys!).","createdDate":"2009-02-13T03:33:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2237","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I cant talk about the first point because I really don't know, but I would like to share my thoughs on #2.\n\nI'm really torn on the idea of \"do we need a shared file system\". In some ways, it makes our deployment of web applications a lot easier, because we have a singular code base for shared libraries and don't have to worry about duplicating those all over the place. That is both a convenience and a liability at the same time. It means if you upgrade a library, you upgrade it in all places, which sounds good on the surface, but in reality you end up missing a lot of incompatibilities if you aren't incredibly thorough.\n\nOn the other hand, I think it is simply a \"nice to have\" feature, but its certainly not business-critical. I do a lot of stuff from traditional ISP's that require you to FTP things and most IDE's work fine with that, so you can't really tell that the files are on a remote system. Using shared libraries can be tough if you are using different domains, but if you keep everything you need to share under a single domain, theres no problem.\n\nJust my $0.02.","createdDate":"2009-01-12T18:44:58.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2143","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"iPhone Application Programming Resource","description":"Here's a good resource I was pointed to for iPhone application development. It's all the lectures and examples and things from a class on the subject that Stanford is now teaching.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.stanford.edu/class/cs193p/cgi-bin/index.php\">http://www.stanford.edu/class/cs193p/cgi-bin/index.php</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-08T14:21:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-08T14:21:56.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2122","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Web Hosting Pilot Proposal Approved!","description":"Over the past few months, a group of us in OIT have been working on drafting a proposal to change the way we deliver web services to campus. We have met with all of you, met with our sister institutions at UNC Cause, and done a lot of research online to figure out what is out there and what (and how) we can offer it to all of you.\n\nWe drafted a proposal and sent it to Dr. Hoit for his approval. On Monday, he approved our proposal and agreed to give us funding to try out a few things. Our proposal has been attached to this post, so if you are interested, read over it and let us know what you think.\n\nI'd like to get some ideas from you all about what software packages work well for you all, what you think about the idea in general, how you think you would like to see the process go, etc. Also, if anyone out there is interested in helping out, that would be cool too...just let us know.\n\nWe are meeting on Friday to figure out some \"next steps\", so let me know what you think!","createdDate":"2009-01-07T21:00:24.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/133-webhosting_pilotproposal.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2441","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"I think I would recommend starting a new thread/topic for that discussion.\n\nI'll stick with my suggestion of a Google Sites type of solution where users have the ability to easily throw together some very basic pages without the need for any additional software or web development knowledge -- the more easy to use and slimmed down the solution, the better.","createdDate":"2009-01-16T04:12:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2427","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"Believe me, the weaknesses of www4 and the inability of a general user to create a web site are things that have been mentioned. These problems can't be solved with this project, but they can be addressed.\nOne of our goals is to consider the user experience with each of the solutions - can a general user make their way through the request process and what do they do once they have their website? What kind of training or support is available to them? What tools can we affordably and reliably make available to campus?\nI'm very curious to hear more about what people would like to see in this area, although we're still at the costing out and setting up stage so that's getting a bit ahead of ourselves right now...","createdDate":"2009-01-15T22:10:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2389","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"For <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu\">www.engr.ncsu.edu</a> our php config has open_basedir=./ and a number of disabled functions. Mostly types of things that exec out system calls and such. For Apache we AllowOverride AuthConfig FileInfo Limit and Options MultiViews. We specifically don't allow FollowSymLinks. Since this is all stored in AFS, with symlinks it's very easy to link a non web locker into a web locker and inadvertently make the locker served out to the world. This had been a problem in the past so we disallow it now. As a side note, even with this disabled, Apache itself can follow symlinks, it just won't serve out files that are symlinked. This narrow case lead our ECE department to develop and application called GuardDog for central management of .htaccess files. The .htaccess files are generated, stored in a single location, and then you can symlink to them in the directories they are needed.\n\nWe refer to subsites as site lockers. Each site locker has 3 pts groups that belong to it, an admin group, write group, and read group. The read group is obvious, the write and admin groups both have full write access but the admin group is used to also control membership of the other groups. Individual logins are all afs ids. Group membership is managed through a web app that puts the information in a database and a perl cron job picks up the changes every 10 minutes. If additional pts groups are needed, they can be created as being owned by the admin group and the tools will pick up these groups and allow them to be managed through the same portal. That's a feature that isn't really used much for the web lockers.\n\nSite lockers can also have a mysql database associated with them by request. Each database has 3 logins, a read id which only has select, a write id that has select, update, delete, and insert, and an admin id which can create, alter, and drop tables etc. We haven't really let anyone do things with views or stored procedures so far but only people in our own group have asked about them.\n\nSite lockers are requested on a web page, we then approve them and run a perl script that handles the creation of the volume, pts groups, database and database ids. It also mounts the volume. Site lockers are triple mounted in various paths to facilitate file based access for both the servers and the users.\n\nIt looks like <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu\">www.engr.ncsu.edu</a> currently has 77 site lockers. That may be partially inflated due to the fact that if you want a separate database, then you need a separate site locker. While <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu\">www.engr.ncsu.edu</a> is probably our biggest shared vhost like this, all of our 70ish vhosts have these capabilities. Additionally we handle the lockers for 35 vhosts for CHASS but they run their own web and database servers.\n\nWow this ended up long winded. /makes note to make shorter posts in the future","createdDate":"2009-01-15T05:12:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2350","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"No, I didn't at all. I wanted to provide a little more color(*) to the background of why the initial decisions were what they were. That's missing in a lot of decisions that any group makes - and it's missing in a lot of discussions. And as a body we don't look back on prior decisions and do any kind of \"after action review\" - We'll either dismiss them as \"what was that fool thinking\" or we'll take them as \"well, it's the way it was always done, so we better keep doing that way\"\n\nI'm not sure if it served the 90% case or not honestly. The whole thing was ridiculously overengineered. But you do what you can with the information you have at the time, and you hope that you have enough flexibility (and chutzpah) to revisit the decision again as new information comes available.\n\nThe actual benefits of it probably turned out to be as much, if not more, for the staff implementing and working directly with it. e.g. the skills developed in doing it led to the VCL project in ITECS as one example.\n\n(* speaking of, like \"why the heck is that Crayola crayon called 'burnt umber' anyway ;-)","createdDate":"2009-01-14T16:01:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2348","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I hope you didn't translate my post in that I think the way it was implemented is bad, just that it crippled some aspects of the environment. You guys did what you had to do at the time, and it worked well for 90% of the people needing to do things. I think there are better options now, which as you pointed out, were not available a few years ago. It's our job now to find what those options are and what problems they solve (and which new ones they introduce).","createdDate":"2009-01-14T15:33:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2343","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"<blockquote>(which I know our engineering colleagues have solved, at the expense of crippling parts of their environment)</blockquote>\n\nAs the original architect for the 'Locker Model' that crippling was actually intentional - beyond even the security aspects.\n\nLet's rewind 7 years. (which is when the genesis of this locker model thing began). Actually we don't have to rewind really because the situation hasn't changed much for the target audience, but it's good to realize that we are talking about the state of PHP and Web applications 7 years ago.\n\nEngineering had all these podunk exceptions around on the engineering webservers, unused or half-used perl-based forms, server side includes - where somebody *had* to have something - and because they *had* to have something, they put pressure on my predecessors to \"make it work\" and my predecessors either thought that was fine (or didn't have much choice) - and the exception was long forgotten - and every so often, some script kiddie would come along and use the form to spam the hell out of somebody. Or we'd change something and it'd break, and something that somebody used once a year wouldn't work and we'd get screamed at.\n\nOh, and let's not think about all the web accessible directories that had student files in them with social security numbers.\n\nSo knowing we needed to have something that we knew worked, and having needs for PHP ourselves, we wanted to replace all that scripted crap with a scripting model that could be available everywhere.\n\nBut available everywhere has a price - because what we had (have) is a whole bunch of faculty/graduate students/staff that get the brilliant idea to download \"some code\" off the net, and run it on a webserver without the foggiest idea what that code does, how it works, and the I/O points in it. It's treated like some application you download for the desktop. Only it's not your desktop anymore where you only screw yourself up when you install Bob's Great Application - it's a shared web server.\n\nSo, not only did open_basedir provide a block for a PHP applications from reading ../../../somebodyelse'swebaccessibledirectory (which honestly - while a concern, the real odds of somebody doing that are pretty low - we weren't providing smart, bored, students access, it was smart, but clueless-about-web-programming and too busy faculty, their grad students, and overworked staff) - it also threw up a roadblock for Bob to download PHP-app-that-he-knows-nothing-about and install it without understanding it. If Bob had to take some time and fix the application so that it would be self contained - well he'd become a little more edumacated about the application that he was taken on responsibility for. At least for that semester until their TA funds ran out.\n\nThat was the theory anyway. It probably turned out to mainly just annoy the heck out of those groups that were taking responsibility for their applications, like ITECS itself, ECE, etc. But some of those applications that needed to be run (like the drupals and the wordpresses, and the mediawikis) should have been pulled out of AFS web environments and put on their own servers. At the time though, that was a struggle because exception handling is hard to manage. And there's the \"eat your own dog food\" principle. And VMWare still wasn't viable even 4 years ago.\n\nTo this day, I remain a little surprised about how many off-the-shelf apps an open_basedir restriction broke. In the framework world, it's a little different. But this was PHP pre-viable frameworks.\n\n6-7 years later, the world has changed more than a bit. But Jay's Law of Computing is that \"Everything is permanent in Higher Education Applications\" And inertia is hard to overcome.","createdDate":"2009-01-14T15:21:18.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2335","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"heh....as soon as we create it :) We are working on it now, so it'll be out as soon as we get it together, although I'd love to hear what people think the constraints and requirement should be.","createdDate":"2009-01-14T14:28:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2323","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I see your point about passing the outsourced costs on, but there is no such thing as having no overhead, even if a service is just resold. There are lots of other things to consider that are apparent on the surface, such as network changes, help desk support, monitoring, end-user training, etc. Alot of times, the reason that the charge for service doesn't equal the actual cost is that all of this stuff is figured in as well (I am only speculating, but that is what I would guess). Whenever we resell any kind of service, we have to take on the responsibility of all these other things, adding cost one way or another.\n\nI'm not saying that it will not be possible to absorb these costs as part of doing business, I am just pointing out that just because a reseller may charge us $5/account/month (or whatever), that doesn't mean that there are no other costs to provide the service.","createdDate":"2009-01-14T13:29:56.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2321","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I don't think the idea of the pilot is to see what \"wins\" and what \"loses\". The idea is to explore how we can deliver the services people are asking for in a better way. Does this mean a single solution implemented for every problem? I doubt it very seriously. We are looking at this as an opportunity to see what else is out there and how we can deliver them in an efficient and scalable manner.\n\nThe problem is that we don't truly know if there is ANY solution out there that will work given the constraints of our environment. The reason we don't know is that we have never really tried it before, so we are trying it now. There is a laundry list of requirements we have to put together including domain management, DNS routing, backup, storage, allocation, etc. All of these are questions we will have to answer with this project, and we will have to answer them for every service we evaluate.","createdDate":"2009-01-14T13:24:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2312","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"So is this being evaluated more from a \"single solution that wins\" perspective or what these different solutions provide? The early part of the proposal seems to allude to multiple solutions for different situations which I firmly agree with. I think many times single solution leads to a lot of compromise and least common denominator solutions that don't meet anyone's needs. The Engineering web infrastructure has these issues too. The open_basedir=./ restriction is needed for large shared vhosts such as <a href=\"http://www.engr.ncsu.edu\">www.engr.ncsu.edu</a> however smaller single owner vhosts could get by with something different. It adds to the support, maintenance, and configuration complexity though. I think that largely the idea of groups running their own webservers as a point of pride or because it's cool has past. Now I think people do it because what is currently offered for some reason isn't palatable to them due to features, restrictions, cost, etc.\n\nI think there should probably be a couple of more focused solutions for campus. Something like the single click deployable webapps that are regularly patched and updated would be great for a number of students, faculty, and even groups and centers. Other groups would need spaces that they could develop themselves that included things like databases, commonly used frameworks (that are patched), and separate development/testing and live areas. Some of these options could be outsourced/resold while the others maintained in house.\n\nAs for AFS, I certainly agree that it doesn't work for all situations. As Charles mentioned, ISOs and other large files are limited. Total site size (beyond 2 GB) isn't necessarily an issue as it can be solved with multiple volumes but sometimes on media heavy sites this can get unwieldy. I've seen that mostly with gallery installs. The issue with AFS server failures while real (as shown last night) but even after everything I went through last night, I don't consider show stoppers and could be designed around. If you're talking about a push to publish or push from dev to live style solution, that could easily incorporate read only servers and the push handling the volume releases. Plus, quite frankly, we haven't had a huge number of afs server issues. Half of our AFS servers have been running since they were patched for the time zone change 2 years ago. I think there's another discussion about storage and file systems so I'll just save further comments for there. I know I'm probably coming off sounding like an AFS fan boy but I'm not. I fully believe we should move away from AFS for certain solutions and data storage needs. I just don't think AFS should be automatically discounted.","createdDate":"2009-01-14T00:57:31.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2303","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"I think making it available to everyone, yet not forcing it is a good plan.\n\nWith respect to the www4 service, what I would like to see is the ability to replace that with something like Google Sites (or a similar solution). We often come across faculty and students who want to create a very basic website in a way that requires the least knowledge possible. We often teach them how to use Adobe Contribute, but that's not always a great solution either because of licensing requirements and sometimes the functionality of the product (particularly for folks who use a wireless connection). So having a very simple offering that folks who just want the very basics in web design would be a advantageous. Then other users who want or need additional services beyond that could make use of whatever solution is derived from this pilot project.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T16:57:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2299","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I think just the fact that we are admitting up front that it doesn't have to scale immediately is a step in the right direction. It all comes down to cost vs. value added. If the cost to scale outweigh the value added, we should investigate other ways to provide the service at a more appropriate cost-to-value ratio.\n\nI believe that it is always a better move to think about scaling from the beginning of the project as opposed to the end though. Alot of times it costs less to scale a project from the beginning than to go back and retrofit it to scale later. All I am saying is that it is much easier from an implementation standpoint to scale early than late, which is why we are talking about this during the planning stages :)","createdDate":"2009-01-13T15:47:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2297","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I did not take it that way. Sorry if I gave that impression. I very much appreciate you sharing your experiences.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T15:36:50.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2293","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"Thanks for the responses. Regarding item 3 -- I definitely agree that it is the sort of thing that should be available to anyone within the university.\n\nThis seems like a very useful and worthwhile project and my only concern is that I would hate to see the end result crippled by folks worrying about scaling it to \"everyone\" when that's simply not realistic usage pattern.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T14:29:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2291","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"Good questions -- I'm not sure I think it would be OK for OIT to charge if it's outsourced, but personally, I would find that more understandable (palatable?) simply because you're acting as a reseller and passing along the actual costs (with hopefully no overhead) that you're being charged. In that setup, it's not something that's attempting to scale to unused levels -- it's merely the case that whoever wants it can pay for it, and if only two individuals want it, the university as a whole hasn't put resources in to something designed for 1,000 users. To me, that's more of a true cost recovery.\n\nI think that too often many of the \"charged\" for services don't represent actual cost recovery, and in that case, many (most?) of the pricing structures quickly become inconsistent with what one could find outside the organization. This leads to less cohesiveness in the federated IT structure that exists within NCSU because folks go out and develop their own solutions or implementations at a cheaper cost than buying in to the OIT-provided model. Overall, it's a waste for the entire university.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T14:24:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2289","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I think the idea is to make it available to everyone, but not to force it upon anyone. We'll be looking into how we can use this sort of system to redeploy www4 for example. That's about as \"everyone\" as it gets. Then again, <a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu\">www.ncsu.edu</a> is not moving anytime soon. There's too much from too many there to force a move.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T14:13:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2287","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I abhor any system that passes my password in the clear. That is just a given. Central authentication is nebulous at this time. If we go with 3rd party, we'll most likely use local accounts/passwords as provided by their software. If we go with the cpanel solution, it's going to depend on what we can improve, and whether or not we have the time to devote to changing the default and maintaining a non-standard modification. From my perspective, we're looking for a solution that we can add value to, but still let handle the basic details on its own.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T14:03:51.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2285","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"Just a personal soapbox here...\n\nMoney doesn't come from nowhere, unless you are the federal treasury I guess. If the ISP's are charging $10/month, and we do it ourselves, you can bet our expenses are going to be roughly the same as theirs. Why is it OK to charge if we pay someone else for you, but not if we pony up the money for servers and resources ourselves?\n\nThat said, the party line is hoping to be that we plan to cover the costs on the behalf of the university, regardless of which solution.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T14:00:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2281","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Great questions...here is my personal opinion, meaning take this for what its worth.\n\nItem 1: The $5000 in the proposal is an estimate we put together for the pilot project only. These include acquiring the software licenses for an on-campus solution, acquiring a 3rd party solution (or multiple ones), and receiving support for all things involved.\n\nItem 2: It is my hope that the service will just be part of what we offer, with no additional cost to the user/college/organization. If you are NCSU, you get it. This is my hope no matter what our solution is, internal or out-sourced. Of course this totally depends on the cost to OIT, and also if we still do have the funding that you are talking about from the University. If we did take on a pay-for-service model, I would guarantee that it will be more inline with what ISP's are offering as opposed to our current $300/year (or whatever it is) cost for MySQL DB only.\n\nItem 3: This is an interesting question. The fact is that not everyone on campus is interested in a service like this. And yes, scaling to a magnitude of a possible 60,000 users could hinder our ability to be agile with the process. However, I believe this should be a service that is available to anyone on campus regardless of your primary role at the University. I think it is totally possible for us to design a system that could handle 60,000 accounts IF it needed to, without sacrificing the goals of the project. Does that mean we are going to create a system for 60K accounts up front? Probably not. But if we design it saying \"only <i>x</i> amount of people will want to use this\", when <i>x</i> + 1 people want the service, we have painted ourselves into a corner.\n\nWe are having another meeting today to start on our project plan, which will more clearly lay out some goals and strategies for moving forward. I really appreciate everyone's responses and questions...it can only make the process better by having everyone in the loop.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T13:30:24.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2269","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"Just a couple of questions:\n\n- Are the costs listed in this proposal the costs which need to be covered by the $5,000 for the pilot project?\n\n- Is the idea that whatever service is ultimately developed/derived from this pilot project would be something that OIT will charge for? If it is an in-house solution, I would strongly urge against that because, regardless of the price, you minimize the ultimate impact and continue the likelihood that other units/colleges will simply continue to do their own thing. The whole cost recovery model process (which is a complete misnomer in most instances that it's used) is something that needs to be revisited and reconsidered within OIT as I see it -- I believe the university provides resources to the organization to provide services for it. Using those resources to provide something that is then a charge-for service seems a bit wrong. A charge-for service would be more understandable/reasonable if it's the case that OIT is simply a reseller of an out-sourced solution.\n\n- Is the idea that this will be scaled to \"everyone\" ultimately? I ask because I think the need to scale to everyone in some cases can minimize the effectiveness of a solution -- particularly when scaling to everyone is unneeded.","createdDate":"2009-01-13T04:02:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2263","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I haven't explored this much. It's going to depend on what we see from the hosts that we test, and what the cpanel provides. I expect it will be a publishing model rather than a live-to-filesys model. SFTP, possibly with WebDAV if available.","createdDate":"2009-01-12T21:59:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2261","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"Excellent information Charles! Thank you! I was wondering what your thoughts on an alternative are? In other words, what would you do instead of using AFS? How would folk who need to edit their space get to it? Are you looking at something like an all WebDAV based setup? Or maybe a separate-from-AFS network file system of some sort?","createdDate":"2009-01-12T21:30:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2256","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","description":"I don't want to use AFS for the new web servers.\n\n95% of our current outages stem from shared servers reading all of their content out of AFS space. When any single AFS file server goes south, the volumes on that server timeout... on the order of 5 minutes per request. That stalls out the one child process in apache, waiting 5 minutes for a reply. As more requests come in, more children get stall out. eventually you hit the 250 child limit, and the entire web server (80 hosts) is no longer functions... from a single point of failure on an AFS file server.\n\nSecond, there's no compelling reason to have web files available everywhere. They need to be available on the web server. Not on any and every campus client in the world. In some ways, this has proven to be a security problem (remember what happens when someone embeds a password in a script that is world readable in AFS).\n\nThirdly, AFS does not handle standard user/group permissions models. In many ways, the PTS system is superior. In this, it is not. Commercial web hosting assigns a userid and expects the file system to obey the files by the userid. AFS can only control access by server IP. Or, you have to find some convoluted way to get tickets/tokens for the user, and make sure those only apply to the right connection and not to the other connections concurrently on the machine. It is far, far easier to throw away the AFS model and use Unix perms that work, than to fix AFS/PTS to work the wat that we need it to.\n\n2GB volume limit... Is still an artificial limit that we impose operationally. It started with that being the limit on the size we could comfortably backup. Now that number is closer to 4GB I think, or even unlimited. Keep in mind that no matter what size, the volume is locked out when a backup is in progress; the larger the volume, the longer the lockout. The other hard limit I know of is a single file cannot be larger than 4GB on our AFS. (may be fixed in a version newer than what we run). This means no ISO-dumps of DVDs. In practice, many of our file servers are still running AFS 1.2 which has a lovely bug in caching whenever the size of a single file exceeds maxint (2.1GB).","createdDate":"2009-01-12T20:51:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2247","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"*grin* Fair enough! I'll keep an eye out for your meeting notes! Thanks for the info!","createdDate":"2009-01-12T20:00:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2242","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm really not sure where the 2gig limit comes in at, but I know it is a downfall of our current way of doing things (either in the locker system, AFS, how our backups are handles, or whatever).\n\nI don't want to speak for Harry, Charles, and Everette, since they are the technical people involved in the project, but I think we are looking at ways to utilize network storage to be the data store. Again, we aren't very far in the process, so I don't know exactly what the hardware plan looks like. However we need to do it, our \"pilot\" execution may not be what we implement that will scale, so its a lot of speculation at this point.\n\nI'll be posting meeting notes as we go through the process on here, so that'll be the place to look for some of the more technical questions. I'll try to bring as much back as I can, but I am no sys admin, hardware guru, or network infrastructure wizard :)","createdDate":"2009-01-12T19:55:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2240","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"Perhaps I misunderstood but I could have sworn I had heard that the 2gb limit was due to:\n- server hosts not being able to handle &gt; 2gb file, which would be fixed by running on something \"better\"\n- clients not understanding files larger than 2gb\n\nAny idea how much truth or untruth there is to that? The \"internet\" seems to be mixed in it's feelings on that.\n\nSo is what you are looking at, at least for this PHP solution, something local to the machines themselves? or perhaps some sort of network file system that's not in a shared space? or even something more basic like your app mounts X network file share, that only your app has access to?\n\nI personally have never run into the per-file access permissions actually being a real issue, just something to think about when laying things out. Does that mean others don't have that issue? of course not. =) Just never run into it myself.","createdDate":"2009-01-12T19:43:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2235","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"While the file-level access permissions is a big one, the most common problem that I have heard is the 2gig limit on locker space. A lot of sites are just bigger than that, and so it makes management of such things next to impossible.\n\nAlso, security is an issue for PHP webservers (which I know our engineering colleagues have solved, at the expense of crippling parts of their environment). I'm not sure that is limited to AFS, but it is a downside of a huge shared file system.\n\nI'm sure there are other things out there, but those are the 2 that I am personally aware of.","createdDate":"2009-01-12T18:31:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2223","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"Howdy! I'm curious about the comment about file storage considerations. I've heard some chatter here and there about AFS being considered incapable of handling a lot of scenarios that come up nowadays. Would you mind talking a bit about what you consider \"wrong\" with AFS? The primary thing I can think of is that it does not allow for file level access permissions, which generally is easy to work around. That said, I'm certainly no AFS zealot. hehe At some level I'd like to hear what you are thinking about so that I can do some more research on it myself. =)\n\nBasically the only chatter I've heard has focused on just saying \"AFS doesn't cut it\" but without any actual details as to what it doesn't cut. ;D I'd love to hear more!","createdDate":"2009-01-12T16:16:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2187","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Thanks a lot for sharing this. We are about to go into our meeting to lay out an initial plan for deployment, so I am sure there will be more questions.\n\nCollaboration FTW!","createdDate":"2009-01-09T14:24:09.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:2014","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Top 20 Twitter Posts of 2008","description":"20. Twitter in Plain English\n19. Why You Need to be Looking at Twitter\n18. Top 10 Uses of Twitter\n17. 15 Twittery Things for Your Holiday Enjoyment\n16. Three Ways to Maximize Your Twitter Time for Networking, Marketing and Fun\n15. How Twitter Made my Website Better\n14. Using Twitter for Customer Service\n13. Should Analysts use Twitter?\n12. Corporate Twitter Accounts and Online Reputation\n11. 16 Examples of Huge Brands Using Twitter for Business\n10. How Twitter Can Help at Work\n9. Newbies Guide to Twitter\n8. Twitter and personal branding: The BIG mistake I see people make every single day\n7. The Role of Twitter in Brand Management\n6. [Missing in the article!]\n5. How ReTweets Spread\n4. The Five Stages of Twitter Acceptance\n3. The Elevator Pitch Hits Twitter\n2. How to Use Twitter as a Tool\n1. 50 Ideas on Using Twitter for Business\n\nThe artcle, with the links to all of those is here: <a href=\"http://www.searchenginejournal.com/top-20-twitter-posts-of-2008/8221/\">http://www.searchenginejournal.com/top-20-twitter-posts-of-2008/8221/</a>","createdDate":"2009-01-06T15:57:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-06T19:32:22.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1241"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1998","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Twitter Clients","description":"Given Nick's post about Digsby, it got me thinking of the variety of twitter clients out there, so I was wondering what people are using.\n\nFor desktop, I use Twhirl.\nFor iPhone, I use Twinkle.\n\nTwhirl isn't really flashy, but it does what I need it to do. It'll also let you do multiple accounts and it uses Adobe Air, so its available cross platform.\n\nTwinkle is flat out awesome as an iPhone client. First off, its free. Second, it uses the GPS in the iPhone 3G to tag where you are, then you can see other people who have posted around you. Pretty cool stuff.\n\nSo, what are you guys using?","createdDate":"2009-01-06T14:13:08.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-04-28T14:40:11.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:1241","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:6038","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Yeah, i switched to TwitterFon on iPhone too, and I love that thing. Much better than Twinkle, and it doesn't lose my tweets all the time.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:40:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:6032","contributorName":"3eskgaralqbpn","description":"TweetDeck on desktop, TwitterFon on iPhone.","createdDate":"2009-04-28T14:38:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2029","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Oh yeah, I <i>do</i> have the TwitterFox plugin on my work browser. Forgot about that. And I like it.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T19:30:19.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2022","contributorName":"1x58sgozterf4","description":"I find I use the <a href=\"http://is.gd/aZ9\">TwitterFox plugin</a> most of the time since I usually keep a browser open. I've tried all the others, but like many things, it's just easier to use an interface that's part of something else I'm already using. For the iphone, I use TwitterFon. Simple, quick, lightweight, free and not ad supported. After reading this, I'll probably check out Twinkle again and see if I like it.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T16:38:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2016","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I use Twhirl and Twinkle as well. Twinkle is awesome! I like Twhirl simply because it's simple and doesn't try to do much more than is it needed.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T16:15:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2011","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Call me old-fashioned, but I use the web client: <a href=\"http://twitter.com\">http://twitter.com</a> on my PC, my laptop, and on my iTouch. With that said, I'm an ESFJ in Myers-Briggs, and we are people who like \"routines.\" It's amazing in itself that I keep up with technology, since I like the routine, predictable, and institutionalization if totally left alone. :-)\n\nI'm on the verge of configuring (have installed it) digsby though, so maybe my answer will be different next week. :-)","createdDate":"2009-01-06T15:49:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2003","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I use Twhirl (<a href=\"http://www.twhirl.org/\">http://www.twhirl.org/</a>) on both my desktop PC and my Mac laptop (here's to multi-platform apps!).\n\nI use TwitterFon on my iPhone and I'm going to impeach Jason on his \"Twinkle is flat out awesome\" statement. I had a problem getting updates on Twinkle. I would only get updates from a handful on my Twitter peeps and sporadically at best. The location feature on Twinkle is neat but it wasn't worth the hassles to me so I switched to TwitterFon.\n\nI like the simple interface on TwitterFon. It's easy to see the people referenced in other peoples @ messages, access profiles, send direct messages and distinguish between new messages, old messages, messages that refer to you etc. Posting pictures is simple and I've never had a problem getting updates. I have to say, this is one of the most heavily-used apps on my phone.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T15:23:41.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1985","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Digsby: The Only Social Networking Client You'll Need","description":"<b>Name of App / Service</b>\nDigsby\n\n<b>URL</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.digsby.com\">http://www.digsby.com</a>\n\n<b>Environment</b>\nDesktop\n\n<b>Operating System</b>\nWindows\nLinux and Mac versions are in planning: <a href=\"http://www.digsby.com/signup/maclinux\">http://www.digsby.com/signup/maclinux</a>\n\n<b>Intended Audience</b>\n\n* Social Networking Addicts\n* Email'ers\n* Twitter'ers\n* Facebook'ers\n* LinkedInn'ers\n* Instant Messenger'ers\n\n\n<b>Screenshot</b>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/134-ScreenHunter_01Jan.0607.35.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/135-ScreenHunter_01Jan.0607.35.jpg?width=66\" alt=\"\" width=\"66\" height=\"150\"/></a></p>\n\n<b>Submitted by</b>\nNick Young (usaussie)\n\n\n<b>Why is this an App of the Week?</b>\n\nIn simple terms, Digsby is a desktop-application-un-clutterer, for people who participate in several chat, email, and social networking circles.\n\nFor example, before Digsby came along, my system tray was home to the following apps, either all at the same time, or in different combinations:\n\n* AOL Instant Messenger\n* Yahoo Messenger\n* MSN Messenger\n* Google Chat\n* Gmail Notifier\n* Twhirl (for Twitter)\n* Pidgin (for Jabber and other IM stuff)\n\n\n...and i would also have a browser open to inform me of any new postings to Facebook, LinkedIn, and my Gmail account. Yes, i did consolidate some of the IM stuff into Pidgin, but that wasn't overnight either.\n\nNow my system tray holds the following apps:\n\n* Digsby\n\nThat's awesome.\n\nWhen you fire up Digsby, you add your different accounts and passwords, and then sit back and watch the notifications roll in.\n\nThis is all configurable, with themes, options for what to show and what not to show, so this is just how i have it set up. It looks like a regular buddy list window, just with different sections for the different accounts.\n\nIn the main window area, it lists all the chat buddies from all of your accounts. It aggregates them into a single list, so you don't have to worry about which protocol/service the buddy is on.\n\nAt the base of the list, it shows the 3 (currently) supported social networking services (Facebook, Twitter, and LinkedIn). You can write to each service directly from the Digsby panel too, so you don't have to open a browser to do anything. You can connect and manage as many twitter accounts, Facebook accounts or whatever you want. This makes it easy to send tweets out for both a personal and professional account, without having to open a browser, or run multiple applications.\n\nBeneath that, it shows any email accounts you have configured to connect to. Currently, it supports:\n\n* Gmail\n* Yahoo Mail\n* Hotmail\n* Any IMAP Account\n* Any POP account\n* AOL/IM Mail\n\n\nIMO, the good thing about Digsby is the notifications. The notifications can come as a sound, a popup, a prompt, a nice web 2.0'ish gradient box that fades in and out somewhere on your screen...its all pretty flexible. Turn on the options you want, and turn off the others. I like the fading notifications in a certain area of my dual monitor setup, so they don't get in the way, but so I still notice them.\n\nThe only drawback I've found in the last 3 weeks of using Digsby, is that it does not support AOL chat rooms.\n\nThe last neat feature of Digsby, is that the settings are kept out there in the cloud. So I don't need to worry about keeping several configurations and settings up to date on my office desktop PC, laptop, and home pc. I just sign up for Digsby, install it wherever I want, and all my settings are loaded exactly the same at each location. Even if you forget to close it at home, and then open it at work, it still plays nice. You just get some nice little messages from your ol' AOL System buddy, telling you that your account has been signed into at multiple locations.\n\nBottom line...the concept of Digsby rocks....and the actual application does too.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T12:38:10.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-06T12:38:10.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Best Thing Ever!"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1944","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Questions for Dr. Marc Hoit","description":"Our first interviewee is Dr. Marc Hoit, the not-so-new-anymore CIO here at NCSU. Please submit any questions you'd like me to ask him, and I will!\n\nPS. The interview will be sometime in early February, so get your questions in soon!\n\n======================================\n\n<b>UPDATE!</b> The interview will be for Feb 4th, so we will keep this discussion open until the end of the day on Feb 2nd. Thanks to everyone for the great questions!","createdDate":"2009-01-05T19:00:47.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-02-03T17:46:47.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Spotlight","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:3025","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I am closing this discussion as my interview with Dr. Hoit is tomorrow.","createdDate":"2009-02-03T17:46:41.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2737","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"1) How important is to you for campus to be a proponent of open standards and protocols (iCal, RSS, CalDav, IMAP, etc.) given that, by definition, they provide and facilitate important requirements such as transparency, relevance, openness, impartiality, availability, and maintenance? And to what extent will you strive to make open technologies available to our campus (faculty, staff, and students)?\n\n2) What is your favorite book?\n\n3) Coke or Pepsi?","createdDate":"2009-01-27T14:36:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2731","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"The interview is next week, so if you guys have any more questions to Dr. Hoit, submit them soon.\n\nAs I said in an earlier post, I am not going to make anyone do the video idea. It will be just a straight-up question/answer type interview. So get me those questions!","createdDate":"2009-01-27T13:24:28.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2567","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"<blockquote>PS, if anyone knows a good speech to text interpreter, that'd be something I'd be interested in.</blockquote>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.mturk.com/mturk/welcome\">Mechanical Turk</a> :-)\n\nOr heck, just post it - and let the transcript happen (NCSUWebDev Turk). You don't need to take that on. We can organize around that and make it happen. Though converting it to swedish chef might be in order.","createdDate":"2009-01-20T15:50:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2561","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Aight, I think the easiest way to do this is me take all of your questions to Dr. Hoit and do the interview. I will record the audio and attempt to transcribe it. I think that is the most effective way and I don't want to leave anyone (or their questions) out. FYI, I am no professional interviewer. I'll do the best I can, but I am certainly no Peter Jennings :)\n\nPS, if anyone knows a good speech to text interpreter, that'd be something I'd be interested in.","createdDate":"2009-01-20T14:30:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2523","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"Hrm. Well, I remain against the video. I would not watch a video of an interview with much of anyone. Find them boring and I prefer text. And like Richard said, they're searchable. If you must do a video interview, then at least provide a transcript in text format. And you might as well ignore my questions because I'm not going to record myself asking them. =)","createdDate":"2009-01-18T21:31:02.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2521","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"I agree that Dr Hoit is probably too busy to follow the forum posts and at that point, it really is an ongoing discussion and not really an interview. The advantage of the written interview is that it can be searched, scanned and skipped through if a particular question isn't of interest to you. If the questions are going to be recorded I'd be afraid that those would be the only questions asked. I think a good interview should have some back and forth between the interviewer and interviewee. There should be follow up based on the responses. As I said, it can still be done with the recorded questions as long as it isn't forgotten.","createdDate":"2009-01-18T20:53:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2473","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I think the video idea is a better one for several reasons other than the ones that have already been mentioned.\n\n1) It's much more interesting to watch that rather than read someone's responses to written or transcribed questions.\n\n2) It's incredibly presumptuous to assume that Marc has the time and/or is willing to troll a forum responding to and asking questions to about 100 people. It's a time consuming task...I don't even have time to keep up with all the traffic here and there's not that much of it.\n\n3) Having a video interview style allows us to have something that's technologically up-to-date that we can also use in the spirit of campus collaboration with the NCSU You Tube site.\n\n4) While the main focus of the interview comes from the NCSU Web Dev group here, I think it would be beneficial for the rest of the campus IT staff to have an opportunity to view the interview. If it's not a one-on-one formal interview (either video, text, or audio) then there's no way for OIT as a group, or campus for that matter, to get the results in a compact fashion that is coherent and useful unless someone here goes through and coalesces the relevant interview related data and produces a written report, email, etc.\n\nSo, I vote for a video interview style, and would be happy to record a video question for the interview.","createdDate":"2009-01-16T16:13:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2468","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"I tend to agree a bit with Daniel on this in that I think it would be a bit easier for someone to quickly go through a forum setup and answer (and provide follow-up questions, which I think is very valuable) than it would be to watch a bunch of videos and record answers to each one. I think the YouTube/video interview is an interesting one and a format that worked well in the presidential debates, but primarily because the responses to the questions were being broadcast out to network television allowing the candidates to quickly/easily reply. Also, I think Marc showed his willingness to view/respond to forums when he was eliciting feedback for the SOP document.","createdDate":"2009-01-16T15:14:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2403","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"i am not opposed to the type of format you suggest, but i think it has a large amount to do with the person being interviewed. I know i wouldn't have a problem answering questions for a week or two (although i dont think i'm interesting enough to captivate people for that long), but im unsure as to how much time a CIO could devote to this. I guess you can always ask. Maybe for the (dare i say) \"lower profile\" featured people, this could work.\n\nMaybe for the less available people, it could be in the form of an online chat forum (real time) that lasts for an hour or two. Or maybe for an hour each week for one month? maybe not that frequent, but something along those lines. Just thinking out loud.","createdDate":"2009-01-15T14:41:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2387","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"Hrm. I uh.. am not recording video questions. =P I'm not really videophobic or anything (hell I have a podcast out there on an open source site that I did). But I do believe having to record a video of your question would deter a lot of people from asking.\n\nHonestly, I'd -rather- see this work like this:\n- For the month of January we are interviewing Dr. Hoit this means that every week (or more if he wants) he pops on here, looks at what was posted, and replies to everything he can/is reasonable.\n- For the month of February you switch to someone else who does the same type of thing.\n\nBasically a \"live\" discussion via forums. The \"interview\" aspect of it really just means that this person will agree to talk with us via the forums. If you don't think the person in question would be willing to go through the entire discussion, maybe you could cull together the questions brought up in the forum and post them as a \"new reply\" or something right before the interviewee checks so they could have a quick list of things to reply to. Frankly I'd -prefer- it just be \"reply amongst the discussion\", but hey.\n\nIf a month is too long, maybe make it a week long interview period that the person should check every day.\n\nI think the fact that we have a forum here provides a good interface for bouncing questions off each other. Would even give the interviewee an opportunity to ask some questions back at the interviewers.","createdDate":"2009-01-15T03:32:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2385","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"that was just a straight-up weird video... :-)","createdDate":"2009-01-15T02:02:35.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2381","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"I'm not sure about the video thing - but a I triple-dog dare you to <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-lt3vVA-4I\">do yours with a ukulele</a>. :-D","createdDate":"2009-01-15T01:47:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2363","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"We've been working on that and have a few ideas. I have the interview time setup with him, and the general idea is that I will take your questions and interview him and bring back the results. How that happens is up in the air right now.\n\nMy current \"best\" idea would be to get people who have submitted questions to do a video of themselves asking the question. Basically it would be a \"This is Jason Austin from OIT and my question is...\". If any of you saw the primary debates where they used YouTube to ask the candidates questions, it'd be similar to that. I'd play these for Dr. Hoit and video tape his responses. Then I'd put it all together.\n\nA couple things this would accomplish:\n\n1) Dr. Hoit could start putting some names with some faces. He's already done this a good bit, but it may help.\n\n2) I wouldn't have to worry about not asking one of your questions the way it was intended. Much is lost when you go from thought to internet message board to someone else on a message board to asking a question in person.\n\n3) We'd have a video worth watching that is hopefully interesting to watch and not just me asking questions and Dr. Hoit answering them.\n\nThoughts or concerns? I figure not everyone is going to want to make a video of themselves, but take one for the team :) I'm definitely not awesome on camera and I'm gonna do it. If someone doesn't have access to a webcam, I've got a MacBook and will travel!","createdDate":"2009-01-14T18:52:12.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2361","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"What's the format of the interview? That is -- is he simply going to read through these posts and reply as needed, or will it be a collection of questions which he will reply to (voice or through email)?","createdDate":"2009-01-14T18:42:01.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2329","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"It does, thanks! =)","createdDate":"2009-01-14T13:58:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2327","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Anything goes as far as I'm concerned. With the first interview, being that it is our CIO, I figured there would be more technical questions like \"what are your plans about x service\" or whatever. These interviews will probably morph a bit into a \"get to know your fellow developers\" type thing, but with the first one being Dr. Hoit, it may be a little different than all the rest.\n\nhope this helps...","createdDate":"2009-01-14T13:49:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2325","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"So, it occurred to me that it's possible I misinterpreted what \"kind\" of interview this was going to be. Is this supposed to be a \"get to know Dr. Hoit\" type of thing, or is it intended to be a forum for asking questions that affect IT at the university? Little of both? I guess another way of phrasing it is .. is this supposed to be formal questions or informal questions? There's certainly a significant difference between stuff like \"how do you envision the future of central IT help desk support\" and \"do you think twitter is cool\". =) (sorry John, I picked that one because it's the last post in this thread, not implying it's a bad question, just makes ya wonder what -kind- of questions are supposed to be asked here) So what do you think Jason? Are we going for literally a mishmash of any type of question one can come up with? Or is it meant to be more lighthearted? If there -is- an expected \"type\" of questions an interview should include, maybe we can come up with some sort of type tag for future ones. [Technical] [Fun] whatever. =)","createdDate":"2009-01-14T13:31:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2192","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"For Marc:\n\nI know that you use Twitter and that you use it primarily to tweet meetings (and events) that you're off to. I'm interested in your thoughts about it in these areas:\n<ol>\n<li>What value, if any, have you realized from the (albeit small amount of) time you put into it? Any?</li>\n<li>Why do you choose not to follow any other tweeters? What do you think the perception is of a person who follows no one else on Twitter?</li>\n<li>Would you attend a Tweetup of NCSU tweeters if we had one?</li>\n</ol>","createdDate":"2009-01-09T16:21:08.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2161","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"I'm still thinking over some questions for Dr Hoit, but I wanted to respond to some of the discussion about personal webspace. The College of Engineering offers locker space upon request to students, faculty, and staff that are part of the College. One of the options for this space is to have a section on a php web server. For the past 18 months, we've also offered the choice of a mysql database with it. In the past 18 months 166 of these lockers have been requested with 95 of them selecting the web option and 70 of those requested a database. Additionally 13 people that already had a locker have requested databases for a total of 83 databases. However only 29 of those databases have any tables in them of which at least 1/3 belong to staff. I'm citing these numbers to show that such a campus wide service wouldn't have to be designed for 50,000 people because if it's made an opt in service, not everyone on campus will.\n\nNow this could just be commentary on how difficult it is to get the word out to students, but we've advertised this service in the E115 class that incoming freshman engineers are required to take.","createdDate":"2009-01-09T02:43:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2150","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Some quick-fire filler questions, maybe to start out, or at least to let us know him a little better: Favorite Movie, Favorite TV show, what's on your mp3 player right now, favorite techie website, favorite non-techie website, what application/applications can you not do without?","createdDate":"2009-01-08T16:34:25.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2145","contributorName":"1g0vgtzqw7h6n","description":"To follow up on what Daniel mentions. I think that there is some value in having a service like www4, but I think that overall, we could do a better job of providing this type of service to folks. I think there are essentially two categories of folks who need a service enabling them to create their own web pages:\n\n- users who want something basic where having the ability to set something up easily (in a Google Sites type of way) is a tremendous advantage over what we have because it gives them the ability to throw something together very quickly. There are many faculty (and quite likely many students) who need/want to throw up some basic information without having to know anything about web development -- and \"just use DreamWeaver or Contribute\" aren't acceptable solutions.\n\n- users who want or need to have the ability to develop their own websites in the traditional sense, have the ability to create data-driven components, or write other applications (essentially having access to a PHP and MySQL environment).\n\nI would guess this second group of users would be a smaller percentage of users than the first group, and given that, I think that the service provided for them wouldn't necessarily need to be \"scaled\" so that the entire campus could use it -- in fact, it may be better if it's not scaled to that degree since that often seems to create limitations which could make the end-result less useful than was originally intended.\n\nWe have a couple of classes within the technical writing discipline within CHASS that focuses on teaching students how to create dynamic, data-driven websites using PHP/MySQL. Typically we run a separate server for these classes to provide them access to the tools that they need to do their course work. I'm sure there are other courses in other disciplines in other colleges which have similar needs requiring their college units to provide similar access. It seems as though it would be far more efficient if there was a centrally provided service that could meet these various needs, while also giving access to the self-motivated computer science/computer engineering/etc. student who would like to experiment with and learn about this type of software development.\n\nIn addition, I thought I would expand upon the definition of exorbitant as it relates to NelNet. Recently, CHASS looked in to the possibility of switching our college giving site over to having a NelNet back-end. The cost we received from OIT to provide this was $4,000. However, if we wanted to do some of the work ourselves, the cost WENT UP to $7,000. Given Daniel's previous experiences with NelNet and my own experiences with assisting in the development of donation sites using credit cards, these labor costs seem extremely high. There are multiple groups within my college (and likely within units across campus) that sell items online (books, DVDs, other merchandise) and would love to have an easy way to tie in to a centrally managed (and consistent) back-end to accept credit card purchases. But when you consider a ~$50 a month charge for having a NelNet account, plus the up-front development costs, they would have to generate a massive amount of business in order to simply break even. I'm not sure if this issue is in the scope of what was originally intended, but I think e-commerce is certainly something that is within this vein.\n\nFinally, I would encourage the folks that are organizing the interview to send the link to this page over to Marc so that he can possibly reply directly himself to questions, ask follow-ups, etc. as I think that would be a more engaging and fruitful interview method.","createdDate":"2009-01-08T15:23:33.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2115","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I get the gist of what you are asking. I, just this morning actually, had a conversation with Nick Young about how we can be more transparent with the things we are working on. I'd like to think we are making improvements at a small group level (our group of 3, Outreach Technology, has very much the same creed as your group does, Jason), but I don't think we are there yet as an organization.\n\nI don't think your question is <i>too</i> leading...but maybe just enough to hopefully get the response you are looking for :)","createdDate":"2009-01-07T16:25:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2110","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Hmmm... Okay, that's what I'm trying to get at with a question - but I honestly can't think of a way of wording it that does not present it as a \"setup\" or put it in terms where it's a \"defensive\" question\n\nMy local team is finding incredible success with the idea of \"radical transparency\" - that is, our meeting notes, our project planning, our team's activity stream, sourcecode, etc - is completely and totally in the open. Either open to the world, or open to the thousands of account holders we have across the land-grant system. There's a historical fear in Higher Education IT (I've held that fear myself) that being open with your work and processes will lead to a breakdown in expectation management (people misread your work as an \"official, coming project\") - or lead to all kinds of \"cooks in the kitchen\" questioning work. We've found the complete opposite to be true. It's increased productivity dramatically.\n\nI'm seeking some way of trying to get at that without presenting it in a way that makes it leading in a way. Something along the lines of:\n\n\"Many IT and Engineering organizations are moving toward \"real-time\" openness, a flattening of organizational hierarchies, buoyed by the technological changes in social networking services. Higher Education seems to be struggling with this change. Where do you see these models working for the NC State IT community and OIT? What can we do as a campus to put more of our activity, and work, and planning in the open in real-time?\"\n\nMaybe the group here can help me wordsmith that?","createdDate":"2009-01-07T16:08:26.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2105","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I will certainly bring this up to Marc, but I wanted to just let everyone know that we (OIT) are working on this exact problem right now. More info (and requests for feedback) will be coming in the next few weeks about it.","createdDate":"2009-01-07T15:36:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2102","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","description":"I totally concur with the www4 service question, but I place a slightly different spin on it: is it worth the cost of maintaining the www4 service for the limited featureset that it possesses? Daniel is correct: Google and others can provide web serving capabilities for a much lower cost. Personally, I have no doubt that the www4 service is useful to the campus community, so the argument that it should exist is easy to make.\n\nSo, assuming that the powers that be want to keep that service running, how can the University (read: OIT) enhance the www4 service to give it a featureset that is post-1997? Nowadays, students are looking for more than a static HTML web server. They want dynamic pages. They want databases. They want more space. The list goes on and on... What can be done to enhance the quality of the service to bring it to a more modern featureset?","createdDate":"2009-01-07T15:07:10.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2081","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"What are your thoughts on possibly discontinuing the www4 service as it exists, as the common use of those services can be gotten elsewhere for free (like google sites and such)?\nA side question to that, instead of the existing www4 service, what about an easy to sign up for free campus php/mysql service that students could use to learn from?\n\nCurrently the campus credit card interface (to Nelnet) costs colleges/departments a significant chunk of money to make use of ... thousands of dollars up front. Want do you think about the possibility of making that available to campus as a free service? Note, can understand the small monthly cost to cover transaction fees, but the up front huge chunk, especially if someone is writing the code themselves, is exorbitant.","createdDate":"2009-01-07T13:15:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2046","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"How do you see open source offerings affecting our decision making for enterprise applications in the future?","createdDate":"2009-01-06T20:45:48.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2019","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"What web applications, projects , and new sites are on the \"university's\" priority list for 2009?","createdDate":"2009-01-06T16:23:11.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:2006","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"What service or technology do you think is the most important to get to students?","createdDate":"2009-01-06T15:24:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1991","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I updated the original post. No real date set yet, but it will be in early Feb.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T13:39:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1962","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"When is the interview?","createdDate":"2009-01-06T00:36:40.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1863","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Contribute CS4","description":"Has anyone tried out CS4 yet? I've got it in my possession and am intrigued by some of the new features (in-context editing and shelf-life especially). However, I'm leery to jump right in. Will it play nice with CS3? I mean, can the two coexist harmoniously? Would it be worth it to buy a license for everyone in my college?\n\nWhat are you all doing out there?","createdDate":"2008-12-23T13:41:29.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-23T13:45:12.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:416","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1865","contributorName":"24454py9jn5di","description":"We have CS4 at the CVM, but I am currently the only person who has it on their computer. It plays fine with CS3, in that they coexist without any complaints (so far). It seems a bit smoother than CS3, but I've yet to delve in too deeply.","createdDate":"2008-12-23T13:45:12.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1861","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","title":"Free PHP Hosting","description":"Has anyone heard of any of these 5 free hosting services or better yet, ever used one?\n\n<a href=\"http://woork.blogspot.com/2008/12/5-awesome-free-web-hosting-services.html\">http://woork.blogspot.com/2008/12/5-awesome-free-web-hosting-services.html</a>\n\nThey offer very limited space, but still... it's free! This isn't so much for work related purposes (obviously).","createdDate":"2008-12-23T13:37:03.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-23T13:37:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1778","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","title":"Navigation Editor Question","description":"So, I've got a question I don't know if anyone else has ever encountered or attempted. I've done this in our existing framework using mootools, but I'm moving everything to jQuery and this nav editor is the last thing, and I'm wondering if anyone has any thoughts or ideas.\n\nFirst of all, our navigation is stored in an xml file and we allow our application administrators to rearrange, add, edit, and remove items from their navigation structure via a drag and drop interface. This is all great and works very well...but in attempting to convert it from mootools to jQuery I'm wondering if there's not a better way to handle this task.\n\nI'm curious how do you guys do this, if you even provide this functionality?","createdDate":"2008-12-18T14:20:40.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-18T14:21:18.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1741","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"A Single, Unified Mailing List for NCSU web devlopers","description":"I posted this to the new list, but wanted to post it here too. I have combined the webdevelopers@lists and webdesign@lists mailing lists into a single list, with the address of webdevelopers@lists.ncsu.edu.\n\nNow you only have to subscribe to a single list to get all your web development goodness. We decided to use webdevelopers as our list name because it better encompassed the entire process of doing development on the web. Planning, designing, publishing, promoting, implementing, etc.\n\nWe now have 196 people on the one list, so that is a good chunk of folks on campus!","createdDate":"2008-12-17T21:14:53.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-17T21:14:53.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1722","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"University Color Palette","description":"This was not the easiest thing to track down, so I figured I would share this here. It contains the official university colors with their Hex values, helpful for doing university-affiliated things.","createdDate":"2008-12-17T19:48:13.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-01-06T12:32:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/136-NCSTATEPALETTE.pdf"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1981","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"holy crap --- i never knew that existed either --- like Jason, i use Colorzilla, but i think that may get uninstalled pretty soon, now that i know about this little gem of a feature.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T12:32:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1968","contributorName":"halmeeks","description":"and I am a graphic weener that always has photoshop open, so i use the round about screengrab (command shift 4)/eyedropper ninja punch to deconstruct pages.","createdDate":"2009-01-06T00:42:55.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1796","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"that is nifty. didn't know that existed. I have always used the colorzilla FF extension to grab colors on the page.","createdDate":"2008-12-18T16:28:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1766","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"For those of you that may not be aware of this, the <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/60\">Web Developer Toolbar</a> for Firefox has a useful feature which can be used to extract all of hexadecimal values tied to a particular page.\n\nGoto '<b>Information</b>' -&gt; '<b>View Color Information</b>'.\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"noborder\" href=\"discussions/137-viewcolorinformation.gif\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"discussions/138-viewcolorinformation.gif?width=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"243\"/></a></p>","createdDate":"2008-12-18T14:02:59.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1754","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"FYI, the color palette has been on the internets for a little while now (although I have to admit I didn't know about it until after I sent Jason the pdf he posted)\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/graphicID/\">http://www.ncsu.edu/graphicID/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/graphicID/NCSUColorUpdate.pdf\">http://www.ncsu.edu/graphicID/NCSUColorUpdate.pdf</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-18T02:46:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1730","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"useful! thanks :)","createdDate":"2008-12-17T20:25:22.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1702","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","title":"Notes from Delivering Web Services BOF @ UNC CAUSE '08","description":"The idea of holding this session at CAUSE was as a result of a \"Delivering Web Services\" campus-wide meeting that was held at NCSU on 11/07/08. The notes from that meeting are also in this discussion group, with the title, \"Notes from the Delivering Web Services Meeting.\"\n\nThe BOF meeting at CAUSE was an attempt to broaden the scope to other universities to understand what they might be doing in this area. Representatives from NCSU, ECU, and UNC-C attended the BOF. The meeting notes are attached. Attendees, please feel free to comment here to make additions/corrections/clarifications.","createdDate":"2008-12-17T18:39:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","fileAttachments":["discussions/139-WebServicesBOF.doc"],"comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2034","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"Scott,\n\nThanks for your time and energy in providing this update!\n\nBest,\nJohn","createdDate":"2009-01-06T20:11:16.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1727","contributorName":"gbxjo1hblmvi","description":"Thanks to you and the other guys at NCSU for doing this.","createdDate":"2008-12-17T20:03:25.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1621","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Drupal Beginner Basics - 20+ Videos","description":"I've just found these two resources, but they've already filled in some gaps in my understanding of a few Drupalisms.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.drupaldude.com\">http://www.drupaldude.com</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://mydrupal.com/drupal-beginner-videos-basics\">http://mydrupal.com/drupal-beginner-videos-basics</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-16T13:23:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-16T13:23:26.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1521","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Ning Webinars","description":"On one of the mailing lists i am on (uwebd), a message just came across about using Ning in Higher Ed. Here's the post if anyone is interested:\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nHello uwebd members,\n\nIn these tough budget times, the free platform NING might be a very\ngood candidate for your next online community/social networking\ninitiative.\n\nJust a quick announcement about an upcoming webinar series featuring 2\nsessions presented by higher ed Ning community managers:\nSocial Networks MBA (Jan 13-15) - 3 webinars for $300\n<a href=\"http://higheredexperts.com/socialnetworksmba\">http://higheredexperts.com/socialnetworksmba</a>\n\nMark Greenfield from the University at Buffalo has become a sort of\nNing evangelist in higher ed. Beyond his work on the uwebd social\nnetworking website - powered by Ning - Mark has also created several\nNing websites for his institution and several associations.\n\nMike Caulfield launched the alum community of Keene State College\npowered by Ning last April. Mike has also been a very active political\nonline community organizer.\n\nHere's the complete description:\n\nSocial Networks MBA\" is a 3-webinar series that will help you decide\nif your institution should launch its own private niche social\nnetworking website. After this series, you will know why and how to\nnurture and develop a thriving online community around your own social\nnetworking website.\n\nJanuary 13, 2009 1PM-2PM ET \u2013 Rain date: January 20, 2009 1PM-2PM ET 1PM-2PM ET\nBesides and Beyond Facebook: Do's and Don't's for your niche social network\nMark Greenfield, director of Web Services at UB, will help you figure\nout if a niche social network is what your institution needs to\ncommunicate with all or some of its constituents. Mark will share best\npractices and lessons learned in launching and maintaining a few niche\nsocial networks including a private site targeted to current students\nand a public site for higher ed web professionals.\n\nJanuary 14, 2009 1PM-2PM ET \u2013 Rain date: January 21, 2009 1PM-2PM ET\nROI-Oriented Social Network in a Box: Why and how to buy an integrated\nsocial network\nAdam Stahr, Assistant Director for Special Communication at UNL\nAdmissions Office, will explain why and how his institution launched\nClub Red, a private social networking website targeted to admitted\nstudents. Adam will also help you understand what it takes to run a\nsocial network that delivers results and great return on investment.\n\nJanuary 15, 2009 1PM-2PM ET \u2013 Rain date: January 22, 2009 1PM-2PM ET\nAdd-Member Social Network Mix : Why and how to host your free online\ncommunity on Ning\nMike Caulfield, director of Web communications at Keene State College,\nwill explain why and how his institution launched \"About Keene and\nAfter,\" a private social networking website targeted to alums, in\nalmost no time and no cost by leveraging the Ning platform. Mike will\nalso share good tips and practical advice to jump start and nurture a\ncommunity.\n\nFor more info and to register (before Dec 19), just go to\n<a href=\"http://www.higheredexperts.com/socialnetworksmba\">www.higheredexperts.com/socialnetworksmba</a>\n\nQuestions? Just reply to this email.\n--\nKarine JOLY\n<a href=\"http://higheredexperts.com\">http://higheredexperts.com</a>\n<a href=\"http://collegewebeditor.com\">http://collegewebeditor.com</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-11T13:16:36.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-11T13:16:36.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1484","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Testing of Web Apps","description":"One of the things that we could afford to do better is with testing our apps. We had really good intentions to unit test all the apps that we write, but actually we don't do much (if any) of that. We met Sebastian Bergman, author of PHPUnit, at ZendCon and he has developed a nice way to run unit tests on PHP apps. There is even a Zend_Test suite. They have made it easy, but we just can't seem to carve the time to write unit tests as effectively as we'd like.\n\nWe have been known to use the \"F5 Methodology of Testing\", also know as the \"Ctrl-R Testing Suite\" :)....but that really isn't a good way of testing.\n\nOur development cycle forces us into allowing the end user to test, but I'd rather our end user not be our test subject if possible. We've looked at using <a href=\"http://seleniumhq.org/\">Selenium</a> but have never really gone past looking. Anyone out there used that ever? Good, bad, indifferent?\n\nI guess that leads me to my real question, how are you guys out there testing your applications?","createdDate":"2008-12-10T21:20:54.000Z","updatedDate":"2011-01-26T17:39:33.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:2107","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"Like everyone else I'm sure we don't do anywhere near enough of the usability and user testing that we probably should do. Thankfully we have a really good UI and design person out of those four that when we let him near a given product, the usability improves - but we still have some apps (or some functions in some of the apps) that are a complete mess (not Ben's fault at all - it's mainly the apps that we care about less) I'm not completely sure about his testing methodology, I know it's a lot of cross-browser testing and starting with a foundation of semantic markup - we usually don't have a lot of actual UI bugs - unless it involves things like standard javascript and css and [expletives removed] Internet Explorer version 6.\n\nOn the functional side, our development model helps mitigate a lot of formal QA and testing. Every developer has a full-stack development environment locally, that comes pretty close to what's running in production. Some of us will continually download a copy of the production db for that application and use it in local development to make sure that we are developing against real data.\n\nIn theory - and sometimes practice - we are continually deploying to a [site].demo.extension.org vhost - which has the same configuration as production, and a close-to-current copy of the production data on it for more \"open\" testing.\n\nAnd also, In theory, those interested (or that have complained before) in production releases for that application are invited to demo the application (depending on which of the applications it is) - and are invited to put the demo app through their usage paces - which in practice they <b>never</b> do. So we try to release often to production to watch it get real world use.\n\nOne thing that's nice about our development and deployment environment is that exceptions triggered in the application will generate emails to a mailing list for us. On more than one occasion, I've had some code path I forgot about - and it was executed with somebody doing something I didn't test for, it would generate an exception, which I'd see, and often, I'd have the problem fixed and redeployed before the person that had the error would get around to notifying us there was a problem.\n\nAdditionally, our whole team gets checkin notifications for all the applications we develop (using a subversion post-commit hook to send email, but our source is also open, so there are open feeds too). That gives us a chance to do at least ad-hoc code reviews. We don't have anything formally, or even habitually in place, in doing that, but we can see if something really out of the ordinary is coming as a group. Being open with everything also goes a long way to helping with the QA.\n\nAs far as unit testing, three of us have been doing some kind of development - web development at that - for 10+ years. None of us have come up in the age of \"unit testing\" and so we got used to not doing it - and while we want to believe in it - every - and I mean every (okay, we had one that didn't) contractor we've had that had the unit testing religion has turned in miserable results when it came to real world use. It's like somehow \"it passed all the test\" came along and substituted for a modicum of \"did you actually try anything an application user would do?\" So that's cast a bit of a dim view on the utility of unit testing. I imagine if we were writing more \"API-oriented\" applications - where other developers were implementing services that depended on queries and results we'd change our minds\n\nSo basically, our testing strategy boils down to: 1) make sure we develop against real data, 2) cross-browser walkthroughs, 3) as-close-to-standards, clean, semantic, output that we can get 4) exception notifications, 5) event logging, 6) release early and often and 7) using experience (or wild-arse guessing) to differentiate between real problems and um, er, \"training opportunities\"","createdDate":"2009-01-07T15:51:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1623","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"One of my favorite tests is the <b><a href=\"http://www.uie.com/articles/five_second_test/\">5 second usability test</a></b>, yes it's really only 5 seconds.\n\n<i>Most content pages have a distinct primary purpose. In the case of RedCross.org's Donation content page, the primary purpose was to communicate to users all of their contribution options. This is a high-risk page for the Red Cross. If it fails, they risked losing hundreds of thousands of dollars of essential contributions.\n\nAs we often do in other types of usability tests, we start by giving users a focused task. For the Donation page, we gave users a simple task:\n\n\"You're ready to donate to the Red Cross organization. But you're unsure of what kind of donation to make. What are your donation options?\"\n\nNext, before we show the user our page, we tell them we'll only display it for 5 seconds. We ask them to try to remember everything they see in this short period.\n\nOnce the user views the entire page for 5 seconds, we remove it by either covering it up or switching to another window. Then, we ask them to write down everything they remember about the page. When they finish jotting down their recollections, we ask two useful questions to assess whether users accomplished the task. For the Donations page, we'd ask, \"What is the most important information on this page?\" and \"How would you go about donating to the Red Cross?\"</i>\n\nIts interesting to hear what users remember about your page and what they thought the primary purpose of the page was with only 5 seconds to review it. Often times, the message or goal you were trying to communicate to the user was not as clear as you thought it was.\n\nSo why just 5 seconds? Several studies have found that a user will make a decision about the relevance of your page in less than 5 seconds, and if they didn't feel it was relevant (trustworthy, engaging, etc), they'll leave. We have all done it before,... paging aimless through Google search results... how many times have you clicked a search result link, gone to the page and then said \"This isnt what I want, [back button!]\". Sometimes I find myself moving fast enough to rule out 8 to 10 pages in less than a minute, so those first five seconds are very important.\n\nI'd be more than willing to regularly test and give feedback to any of your pages, applications on campus. Just drop me an email (<b>mjvysock</b> <i>at</i> ncsu <i>dot</i> edu).","createdDate":"2008-12-16T13:59:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1544","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I suppose general testing. For example, an app works, you add a feature, does the rest of the app still work. Basically what unit testing encompasses.\n\nIt'd be interesting to see how people do usability testing as well. Security testing isn't so important to me, as we use so many standard framework pieces that take care of most of the security issues (filtering input, escaping out, etc).","createdDate":"2008-12-12T17:45:49.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1541","contributorName":"2k7vvpf9lb3q6","description":"Jason, to me the word \"Testing\" can encompass quite a lot of things. Are you interested more in Usability testing, Application Security, or both?","createdDate":"2008-12-12T14:03:54.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1421","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Adobe is coming to campus!","description":"Adobe representatives will be on campus <b>Friday, January 16th</b> for an all-day demo of the new CS4 Suite of products!\nWe'll be in the BTEC Building located on Centennial Campus (<a href=\"http://www.ncsu.edu/campus_map/centennial.htm\">http://www.ncsu.edu/campus_map/centennial.htm</a> - Building 762A); parking information is below. We'll be in room 135 which has a capacity for ~100 people. There is also room to relax and mingle in the lobby common area outside the room.\n\nMore details to come- please check back!\n\nParking Information: There is parking for C permits in the Partners Parking Deck across the street (Partners Way) from BTEC. Those without a