Finder: <a href=\"http://drupalmodules.com/module-finder\">http://drupalmodules.com/module-finder</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-05T18:28:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-05T18:28:26.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1201","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Google Friend Connect","description":"<a href=\"http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2008/12/google-friend-connect-now-available.html\">http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2008/12/google-friend-connect-now-available.html</a>\n\nThis looks pretty awesome, but then again, a lot of what Google does is pretty awesome.","createdDate":"2008-12-04T23:49:56.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-05T17:54:53.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1269","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"minority report. They had retinal scans. RFID is so last year :)","createdDate":"2008-12-05T17:54:52.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:1229","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"yeah --- it gets me wondering how much longer Google can keep its mission of \"Do No Evil\" above its abilities to transform how people find and use information.\n\nIts one of those things that I'm okay with, as long as its not used for \"evil\" purposes. Kinda of like a real time scanning of data, and then no storage. I'd hate to be in court for a parking ticket and have them bring up evidence that i browsed a 'how to beat radar detection' article on the web a month ago.\n\nI can't remember the movie -- may have been Idiocracy, or maybe Minority Report -- where you walk around and ads on billboards and LCD panels target you individually, much like google ads do when you're reading your email. I guess its only time before i have an RFID chip in my arm, and a billboard reminds me that i need to buy milk, go to the dentist, and that i'm late for the football game that i blogged about :-)","createdDate":"2008-12-05T13:30:20.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:1174","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"The Future of Form Building in Drupal (it's here!)","description":"Thought this would be of interest to this group.....\n\n<b><i>(posted from Lullabot)</i></b>\n\nThe Future of Form Building in Drupal (it's here!)\n\nToday Lullabot released an exciting new project into the Drupal community. It's the Form builder module: an AJAX, Drag and Drop interface for constructing forms in Drupal. We hope that it will become the defacto standard in building forms in Drupal, replacing our inconsistent form-building tools that are spread across CCK, Webform, Profile, and other modules.\n\n\n\nDrag and drop and AJAXy, but degrades too! No need for JavaScript required.\n\n\nOverview\nThe Form builder project reads and modifies Forms API arrays. Using a well-known data-structure that most Drupal developers are familiar with should make for low barrier to entry for utilizing the new module.\n\nThe project uses a AJAX-based interface for updating form elements. As you modify properties such as \"Title\" or \"Description\", Form builder makes requests in the background to update the element through Drupal's internal FAPI system. The user gets a live preview of their changes without saving the form. This approach means that no additional JavaScript needs to be written by implementing modules, since the rendering is done in PHP and then sent to the client as needed.\n\nDemo\nEnough talk, go try out the demo and see it in action.\n\nImplementing Form Builder\n\n\nRead it here:\n<a href=\"http://www.lullabot.com/blog/drupals-form-building-future\">http://www.lullabot.com/blog/drupals-form-building-future</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-04T14:30:22.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-04T14:30:22.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:824","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"Twitter Status Design Tutorials, Icons and WP Plugins","description":"I know there's a growing community of NCSU Twitterers, so here's a link to some resources about how to extend your twittering past the defaults...enjoy:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.noupe.com/tutorial/20-twitter-status-design-tutorials-icons-wp-plugins.html\">http://www.noupe.com/tutorial/20-twitter-status-design-tutorials-icons-wp-plugins.html</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-21T02:56:40.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-21T04:25:18.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:834","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"FYI, Zend Framework has accepted a proposal for a Zend_Service_Twitter to be put in the incubator immediately. In the mean time, we have implemented this library:\n\n<a href=\"http://github.com/sidhighwind/phly_twitter/tree/master\">http://github.com/sidhighwind/phly_twitter/tree/master</a>\n\nwhich is the incubator version of the new Zend lib. We use it to post to twitter for our Lifecycle product. It is really really slick and easy, and if you are already using ZF, it is simple to install and go.","createdDate":"2008-11-21T04:25:18.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:800","contributorName":"1u69204dqxgz6","title":"Getting started with Zend Framework","description":"If you are trying to get started with Zend Framework there are some pretty good screencasts and some sample code to look on <a href=\"http://lebensold.net/category/video-tutorials\">Jon Lebensold's blog post</a>. Of course there is always the Quickstart example and documentation at <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/docs/quickstart\">Zend Quickstart</a>. Anyone else have some good resources?","createdDate":"2008-11-20T19:49:18.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-03T17:46:38.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:220","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1111","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"Akrabat's getting started tutorial is fantastic: <a href=\"http://akrabat.com/zend-framework-tutorial/\">http://akrabat.com/zend-framework-tutorial/</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-03T17:46:38.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:771","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","title":"O'Reilly Books Drupal Webinar","description":"O'Reilly Books Online Webinar about Drupal on December 5th....limited spaces, so register soon. <a href=\"http://oreilly.com/emails/drupal-5books.html\">http://oreilly.com/emails/drupal-5books.html</a>\n\nFull Information Here:\nEverything You Wanted to Know about Drupal but were Afraid to Ask Presented by Jeff Eaton and James Walker, authors of \"Using Drupal\"\n\nIn this live, online event, Drupal developers Jeff Eaton and James Walker will guide newcomers through the nuts and bolts of Drupal's content management system, content management framework, and community.\nThey'll cover the evolution of CMSes and how Drupal fits in, discuss some of Drupal's philosophies towards concepts such as content management and software architecture, and explain some of the fundamentals about Drupal's extensible APIs. Finally, they will muse about Drupal's thriving community and how best to leverage and participate within it.\n\nAttendance is limited, so register now. <a href=\"http://oreilly.com/go/drupal\">http://oreilly.com/go/drupal</a> We'll send you a reminder before the webcast. And please feel free to share this invitation with others.\n\nDate: December 5th at 10 am PT (1:00pm NCSU Time)\nPrice: Free\nDuration: Approximately one hour\nMeeting link: <a href=\"http://oreilly.com/go/drupal\">http://oreilly.com/go/drupal</a>\nAudience: Developers and site-builders interested in learning more about the Drupal CMS and its capabilities.\nQuestions? Please send email to <a href=\"mailto:webcast@oreilly.com\">webcast@oreilly.com</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-20T14:22:52.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-20T18:20:20.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:793","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I've corrected this in the text above -- i didnt notice the difference until i saw the confirmation email sent to me, and where it showed up on my calendar. Thanks Jonathan for catching that :-)","createdDate":"2008-11-20T18:20:20.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:785","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"I like how it has \"December 3rd\" on the first page linked, and then in the sidebar says \"Wednesday, December 5th\", and then has the actual \"Friday, December 5th\" on the registration page.","createdDate":"2008-11-20T16:05:43.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:745","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Oh Noes!  http://giveupandusetables.com/","description":"<a href=\"http://giveupandusetables.com/\">http://giveupandusetables.com/</a>\n\nLet's hope people don't <i>really</i> do this!","createdDate":"2008-11-19T23:21:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-19T23:21:41.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:724","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","title":"15 Helpful In-Browser Web Development Tools","description":"This article lists 15 different plugins for browser (mostly for FireFox but some for IE) to help in debugging javascript, seeing how much data is downloaded and how many requests are made for a particular page, plus others. Pretty good summary.\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2008/11/18/15-helpful-in-browser-web-development-tools/\">http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2008/11/18/15-helpful-in-browser-web-development-tools/</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-19T16:12:14.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-20T14:03:48.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:766","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"The only new one i use is ColorZilla (a simple color picker for firefox), but i can't take credit for it....Jen told me about it. My list is short and sweet for Firefox:\n\nWeb Developer Toolbar\nAccessibility Toolbar\nMeasureIt\nColorZilla","createdDate":"2008-11-20T14:03:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:741","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I personally use Firebug, Web Developer toolbar and colorzilla. Firebug is pretty much the best thing to happen to web development EVAR! ;)\n\nAnother nifty thing I found was <a href=\"http://www.kevinfreitas.net/extensions/measureit/\">MeasureIt</a>. It is really helpful when trying to figure out how large an image is or needs to be or things like that.\n\nWhat other in-browser tools are people using?","createdDate":"2008-11-19T21:10:38.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:729","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I forgot the link\n<a href=\"http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2008/11/18/15-helpful-in-browser-web-development-tools/\">http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2008/11/18/15-helpful-in-browser-web-development-tools/</a>\nglenn","createdDate":"2008-11-19T16:37:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:726","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"hey glenn, I think the link failed to get posted...","createdDate":"2008-11-19T16:27:35.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:721","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Using the Web to Organize Your Life and Get Things Done","description":"Wanted to share a presentation with you all from UNC Cause 2008. It was all about using online tools to get things done.\n\n<a href=\"%20http://www.edutechie.com/2008/11/using-the-power-of-the-web-to-organize-your-life-and-get-things-done/\">http://www.edutechie.com/2008/11/using-the-power-of-the-web-to-organize-your-life-and-get-things-done/</a>\n\nWhat kind of tools and such do you guys use to stay organized?","createdDate":"2008-11-19T13:17:17.000Z","updatedDate":"2009-09-09T13:21:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1041","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"RTM is the bomb. Plus it has an iPhone app that's pretty nice. I too am big on Google Reader (and just about everything Google).\n\nI've gotta plug <a href=\"http://delicious.com\">delicious</a>. I've been using this for about 2 years now and have a collection of almost a thousand links - it's my personal Internet library.","createdDate":"2008-11-26T17:39:09.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:803","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I was also in the session and found it very useful. Lead me to look for some of these tools in Firefox/ Thunderbird (I too like all my stuff in one place whenever possible). A couple of these are still in development so add at your own risk.\n\nIntegrated Gmail - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/9457\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/9457</a>\nName is modest. Allows you to view all your Google stuff in one page with collapsible sections.\n\nTwitterfox - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5081\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/5081</a>\nShows your tweets and let's you post with a pop-up interface in the lower right-hand corner of your Firefox browser.\n\nRemember the Milk - <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/thunderbird/addon/7125\">https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/thunderbird/addon/7125</a>\nA tool that (theoretically) will sync my Thunderbird Lightning with RTM. This is in alpha-- I'll let you know how it goes...\n\nI also added the Google notebook plugin but it's a Google tool so don't look for it on the Mozilla site.\n\nI'll post more later if these are really awesome or super-sucky.","createdDate":"2008-11-20T20:35:34.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:763","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"I was in the same sessions, and although i don't feel that I use tools to 'stay organized,' i do use things to facilitate my daily life. Mainly its Google, just because i can make most, if not all of the things I'm interested in show up on my iGoogle home page. One stop shopping is definitely a good thing in my book, and i have just started redirecting any feeds that i subscribe to into Google Reader. Formerly i had a mashup of having them display on my personal site, or in Outlook, or in other places i've long forgotten.\n\nI guess the tools on my utility belt are:\n\nEmail + Calendar + Tasks: Google (Personal), Outlook 2007 (Work)\nDocument Management: Google Docs\nRSS Feeds: Google Reader\nImages: FlickR Pro Account\nTV: Tivo with 400 hours of Best Quality recording time.\n\nI put the TV thing in there, because if i had to watch TV live, i wouldn't get anything else done...ever :-)\n\nI didn't know there was a theory behind \"zero-inbox\" but i always try to answer or file emails as soon as they come in. I hate a page full of emails in my inbox. I convert emails to tasks in Google Calendar, or do the same in Outlook for work.\n\nI also make sure that Google calendar sends me a daily schedule, and also reminders of appointments, which helps job my memory, even if its to say \"there are no appointments scheduled for today.\"","createdDate":"2008-11-20T13:56:37.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:558","contributorName":"3vjvd1dywteau","title":"A web developers take on Moodle & open source C/LMS","description":"Hi folks, it seems appropriate to start a discussion here to ask for your input on Moodle as a tool to consider using as a partial solution to our campus course/learning management system needs [I say partial because I think that WolfWare is part of this equation]. What do you think of Moodle as a tool from the developer's perspective? Any thoughts (if you have experience) from the perspective of why Moodle rather than Sakai? As a web developer community, what are some of the issues, concerns, and exciting possibilities in this area? :-)","createdDate":"2008-11-13T21:39:39.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-18T16:06:07.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:310","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1793","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"The benefits of having an Open Source system for managing your teaching needs include (but are not limited to): community support, a low barrier for entry, standards compliance, and extensibility. Assuming the community is led by people who understand the needs and wants of their community and the world at large, you can move forward - making amendments as needed a la the U.S. Constitution. Also, should the leaders choose a different path which defies their user base, a coup (fork) is quite simple as they can't take away the code which was developed under the Open Source license. By having an active community, it is best not to modify the core code so that the upgrade path is a simple one. Plugins and a modular infrastructure make customizations simple and portable. The dedication to standards compliance is usually related to the desire for a high quality example of an application using Open Source practices.\n\nThe experience I do have with Sakai isn't Sakai specific, but comes down to its implementation. Sakai vs. Moodle is to me the battle between Java and PHP. The LAMP stack (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP) is a top to bottom Open Source environment. Java on the other hand has a long history of proprietary software implementation. Although it has made large strides recently, my experience with the setup, maintenance, development, and implementation of Java-based web applications is wrought with the patented \"frowny face\". Java is the 300 pound gorilla of resource usage. PHP may make it easy to do the wrong thing, but Java (especially for the web) makes it hard to do the right thing.","createdDate":"2008-12-18T16:06:07.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:549","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Zend Framework 1.7","description":"A little birdie told me that ZF 1.7 will be released on Monday.\n\nHere is a link to the preview release. I assume 1.7 full release will have all this stuff and probably more. I know, I know....I'm a fanboy :)\n\n<a href=\"http://devzone.zend.com/article/3962-Zend-Framework-1.7-Preview-Release-now-available\">http://devzone.zend.com/article/3962-Zend-Framework-1.7-Preview-Release-now-available</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-13T20:26:11.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T20:26:11.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:544","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"DrupalCon","description":"Anyone going to DrupalCon in DC in March? <a href=\"http://dc2009.drupalcon.org/\">http://dc2009.drupalcon.org/</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-13T19:54:04.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T19:54:04.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:225"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:538","contributorName":"1ofqn8jwi6fza","title":"Local Conferences for Web Developers","description":"Most of us are looking at budget cuts, and travel to conferences is one of the first things to go. What local conferences are in the RTP area and within commuting distance? Here are a couple I know of. Please add.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.aboveandbeyondlearning.com/xmlconference.html\">http://www.aboveandbeyondlearning.com/xmlconference.html</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.aboveandbeyondlearning.com/ditaconference.html\">http://www.aboveandbeyondlearning.com/ditaconference.html</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-13T19:39:29.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T19:39:29.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:526","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","title":"Tutorial: Use Adobe Illustrator to Create a Clean Website Layout","description":"Useful in the design phase, this tutorial walks you through the steps of creating a mock-up of a site design in Adobe Illustrator.\n\n<a href=\"http://vectortuts.com/tutorials/web-design/use-adobe-illustrator-to-create-a-clean-website-layout/\">Link to Tutorial</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-13T16:47:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T16:47:26.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:517","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","title":"Reference: Zend Framework - PHP MVC Framework","description":"Zend Framework (which has its <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/zendframework\">own group</a> here on Ning) is a web application framework for PHP 5. It presents libraries for a number of useful functions for PHP programmers, from LDAP to access control lists to a templating engine.\n\nThere is a well-documented reference in the <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/\">Zend Framework Manual</a>, as well as a <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/docs/quickstart\">quick start tutorial</a> on the <a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/\">Zend Framework home page</a>.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T16:28:58.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T18:21:57.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:532","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Just wanted to share some more ZF links:\n\n<a href=\"http://akrabat.com/zend-framework-tutorial/\">http://akrabat.com/zend-framework-tutorial/</a>\nThis is one of the better ZF MVC tutorials out there.\n\n<a href=\"http://zftutorials.com/\">http://zftutorials.com/</a>\nLots of tutorials, but not incredibly up-to-date. Still has some good resources.\n\n<a href=\"http://devzone.zend.com/\">http://devzone.zend.com/</a>\nDevZone is ZF's developer area, but there are lot of other good articles that get posted as well. Their Auth example is a good one.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T18:21:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:509","contributorName":"2dd57fufhen4q","title":"Resource: A List Apart - Web Standards and Best Practices","description":"A List Apart delves into the world of web standards and best practices for those standards - covering everything from programming (\"Progressive Enhancement with CSS\") to web accessibility (\"Deafness and the User Experience\") to design (\"Zebra Striping: Does it Really Help?\").\n\n<a href=\"http://www.alistapart.com\">A List Apart</a> - a great resource for broadening your web design skills.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T16:18:41.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T16:18:41.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"The Reading Room"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:468","contributorName":"0qsx0ul0q1hyu","title":"Form elements","description":"I also found out that Drupal/TinyMCE will change the specified width in multiline text input fields.\nI recently developed a form where the the multiline input text field was specified to be 60 characters.\nIt displayed properly from \"Preview in Browser\" in Dreamweaver (both Firefox and IE). It also displayed properly when opened by a browser directly from the file space.\nWhen I copied and pasted the HTML code into Drupal's TinyMCE editor. When I the previewed or saved it, the multiline text fields were much shorter.\nNick Young suggested that I insert a inline CSS style for width. I did. It worked.\nBut, I don't think this should be an accepted solution. We should avoid using inline style specifications. Especially in Drupal as it already uses over a dozen linked style sheets already.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T12:09:01.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-13T13:00:34.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:470","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I'm not sure that has anything to do with Drupal. As part of the OIT template, we use Yahoo's YUI base and font reset css libraries to make sure all elements display the same in all browsers. It fixes a whole lot of cross-browser compatibility issues, but also sets default sizes for things like form fields. Inline styles is one way to fix that, but you can also create some common css classes that we could add to the template and you could apply. Also, the \"size\" attribute is deprecated in XHTML 1.0, so the css route is the better approach anyway.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T13:00:34.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:403","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"WRAP module for Wordpress","description":"We developed this a while back. Figured I would share it here. It comes with no guarantees, other than it worked for us :)\n\n<a href=\"http://webapps.ncsu.edu/ot/2008/08/08/wrap-module-for-wordpress/\">http://webapps.ncsu.edu/ot/2008/08/08/wrap-module-for-wordpress/</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-12T19:35:26.000Z","updatedDate":"2012-02-13T15:50:39.725Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:400","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:30766","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>That's correct. This functions the same way as wrapping a directory, except you can limit it to specific file(s). I haven't tested it with Virtual files/folders, but given that the &lt;Directory&gt; or &lt;Location&gt; directives seem to allow some Virtual behavior, that would be worth investigating.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If that doesn't work and they are instead they're trying to control an intangible \"page\" within Wordpress, they'll probably just enable WRAPOptional (perhaps indicate that they should login for access) and then set access permissions within Wordpress to require a user to be in a group and make sure to assign users to groups (such as member@ncsu.edu).</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:50:39.773Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30852","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>I think Leslie was referring to wrap protecting a single wordpress page......correct Leslie?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Jonathan -- your solution would just protect a php file outside of the wordpress site. Unless i misunderstood it?</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:29:58.738Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31131","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"<p>In your .htaccess:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>&lt;Files my_secure_file.php&gt;</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 AuthType WRAP<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 require affiliation ncsu.edu<br/>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 require user ladare<br/>&lt;/Files&gt;</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-13T15:15:57.397Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:31065","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"<p>wordpress site, or just any single page (html/php etc) ?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>I don't know of a way....except to put the file in a folder by itself and wrap protect that folder.</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-03T13:28:34.642Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:30843","contributorName":"13bkpxt4h8ige","description":"<p>Anyone know of a way to WRAP just a single page within a domain.ncsu.edu website?</p>","createdDate":"2012-02-02T16:15:36.882Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12037","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Gave it a whack but I'm getting 500 errors when I add that snippet to the root htaccess file.","createdDate":"2010-06-08T14:08:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:12031","contributorName":"0uxf6aiu6dkz6","description":"I know this is a bit old and I should have seen this post earlier but I'm familiar with your looping problem with the plugin. See my answer below.\n\n@jasonaustin, it used to work that all we had to do is place an htaccess file in the wp-admin but something changed and now I also add the following code to the root htaccess file:\n\n\n&lt; Files wp-login.php &gt;\nAuthType WRAP\nrequire affiliation ncsu.edu\nrequire valid-user\n&lt; / Files &gt;\n\n\n\nTo be clear, I add this to the one that lives at the top of your wordpress root, the one that gets the permalink rewrite code.","createdDate":"2010-06-04T19:40:36.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11913","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Keep in mind that this module was written almost 2 years ago for an older version of wordpress. We have since stopped using it in favor of wordpress's own authentication, so I have no clue if it works with current iterations or not.","createdDate":"2010-05-11T13:13:43.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11912","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"for what it's worth...i couldn't get the module working on our oitdesign.ncsu.edu wordpress blog (on the web hosting service). It was a while back that i tried....and considering that it's just me and Jen accessing it, i didn't try all that much.\n\nBut...i do remember that the conventional wrap wisdom from AFS didn't help me. It is possible that it wouldn't work for me because it was on the web hosting service with all it's intricacies and whatnot, or that i tried it on the external service instead of internal.\n\nNot much help i know...but that was my experience with it.","createdDate":"2010-05-11T13:08:58.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11910","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Is that in the /wp-admin folder or in the root install?","createdDate":"2010-05-11T12:51:00.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11909","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I didn't at first. I had..\n\nAuthType WRAP\nrequire affiliation ncsu.edu\nrequire cdmorris\n\nAnd after changing it to...\n\nAuthType WRAPOptional\nrequire nothing\n\nStill looping. Hmm.","createdDate":"2010-05-11T12:47:54.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11908","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Do you have an htaccess file in there with WRAP Optional turned on? If not, you will need that.","createdDate":"2010-05-11T12:39:21.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:11906","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"Hey Jason, I'm trying to implement this plugin, I know you have no guarantees that it will work for us - but I was wondering if you all still have it working for you. The behavior I'm seeing right now is a loop. 1. Install plugin according to directions, 2. Create a user ( cdmorris) 3.Log out 4. Login. Here at step 4 it just loops over and over. I login, then login again.. and again.. and so on.\n\nIf you know what's up here that'd be cool. The blog lives on Extension's server btw at <a href=\"http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/wou/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/forestry/wou/</a>\n\nThanks","createdDate":"2010-05-11T12:37:39.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:390","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","title":"Code Repository - what do we want?","description":"Do people have a web-based code repository package that they are particularly fond of using? OIT currently runs a vanilla subversion server internally, and I'd be happy to extend that to the web developers community on campus. If there is an SVN front-end that would make it more user friendly, I'm open to suggestions. If there's something other than svn that you would prefer, I can look into that as well.\n\n<a href=\"https://svn.unity.ncsu.edu/svn/webservices/\">https://svn.unity.ncsu.edu/svn/webservices/</a> is the current repo for the code that I have to share with the campus. Note that the site is using a self-signed SSL cert, so Firefox and others may whine about it.","createdDate":"2008-11-12T18:50:09.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-03T01:12:39.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1090","contributorName":"206i00d0xpofs","description":"The weak point we've always run into when looking at some sort of svn front in is the ability to have delegated privilege administration. Without that piece, and given that we've only ever gotten a lukewarm response when we asked people in Engineering if they wanted/would use it, it got back burnered.","createdDate":"2008-12-03T01:12:39.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:490","contributorName":"2rf1k1zw8yycr","description":"After quite a bit of looking and developing a strong aversion to Java web apps, I went with the <a href=\"http://websvn.tigris.org/source/browse/websvn/branches/2.0/\">WebSVN 2.0 Branch</a>. It's quite attractive and effective at providing the version history that is the point of replacing (and main missing feature of) the default SVN web browse feature. I find it easier to stay up to date by using the `svn update` command rather than reinstalling and reconfiguring the entire package.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T14:45:46.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:444","contributorName":"1u69204dqxgz6","description":"EIT has been using subversion with websvn. However we would be open to working whatever is deemed appropriate.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T02:20:07.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:426","contributorName":"1ou9m4evpyyeo","description":"We were using (<a href=\"https://sourcecode.extension.org\">and are still using</a> - same warning about self-signed certs) <a href=\"http://websvn.tigris.org/\">Websvn</a> for the longest time.\n\nLately, I'm happier with the repository view of the <a href=\"http://www.redmine.org/\">Redmine</a> issue tracker. (e.g. <a href=\"http://justcode.extension.org/repositories/show/identity\">the repository</a> for our <a href=\"http://justcode.extension.org/projects/show/identity\">\"Identity\" project</a>).\n\nThe latter probably isn't very applicable to OIT given that it's a Rails app - but it fit in with our core team knowledge and delivery environment.\n\nI looked at <a href=\"http://insurrection.tigris.org/\">Insurrection</a> at one time too - at the very least to provide feeds for the svn repo - it was sometime around the time that websvn had some vulnerability in it, I think I came away not wanting to edit xslt and decided to not mess with it.\n\nWe use a post-commit hook to email an open mailing list of commits too, for all repositories - in addition to the websvn and Redmine views.","createdDate":"2008-11-12T22:22:29.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:397","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I found a list of tools here:\n\n<a href=\"http://subversion.tigris.org/links.html#high-level-tools\">http://subversion.tigris.org/links.html#high-level-tools</a>\n\nI have looked over trac before, but never actually used it to roll anything out. It also has lots of requirements, like python, that we aren't setup for. But there are other things in that list that may be appropriate too. Anyone ever used any of those?","createdDate":"2008-11-12T19:28:57.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:394","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"A guy on the Zend Framework list started working on a plugin repo for ZF plugins and helpers using DocuWiki. Here is his site.\n\n<a href=\"http://zfhelpers.com/doku.php\">http://zfhelpers.com/doku.php</a>\n\nJust something that simple could work, but that assumes more of a one-file approach, and doesn't really help with \"packages\". It (unfortunately) doesn't really interface with SVN at all.","createdDate":"2008-11-12T19:08:52.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:386","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"New profile question","description":"I added a new question to the profile for AIM screen name. Feel free to fill that in if you'd like. Just another avenue for communication if you wanna.\n\nAny additional questions you'd like me to add to the profiles?","createdDate":"2008-11-12T18:33:36.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-12T21:21:21.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:409","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"hey - can you add another field to the profile for LinkedIn profile URL?","createdDate":"2008-11-12T21:21:20.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:363","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Adobe Acrobat eSeminars coming","description":"Hey folks-\nFor those of you who are interested in Acrobat, Adobe is hosting several eSeminars on related topics over the next month. Highlights include:\n- how to create Acrobat forms\n- using PDF portfolio\n- PDF collaboration\n\nLearn more and sign up here: <a href=\"http://www.adoberegistrations.com/education/2008/eSeminars/Acrobat9/2008_11/index.html\">http://www.adoberegistrations.com/education/2008/eSeminars/Acrobat9/2008_11/index.html</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-12T16:28:38.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-12T16:28:38.000Z","approved":"Y","groupId":"2486881:Group:255"},{"id":"2486881:Topic:305","contributorName":"19wgwss45yepg","title":"Drupal - tinyMCE vs power-HTML-users","description":"Don Schmidt has brought this problem to my attention. The OIT Drupal install assumes that our users want to use tinyMCE as the editor of choice, and let that application reformat HTML as it sees fit. The Drupal site itself is told that all node content is Full HTML, that is, Drupal applies no further filtering.\nThe problem is users like Don and probably others, who know their way around HTML and need to use special features that the tinyMCE editor is too stupid to recognize.\nThe example that he gave me is this: he wants to write a form, and it needs to include fieldsets. TinyMCE is right out... it doesn't have any way (as configured at least) to help him write forms. The work around with most complex HTML is use the raw HTML mode of tinyMCE, paste in the code from another HTML page editor, and then save the data to drupal. The problem is, tinyMCE destroys the fieldsets. Apparently it's built-in HTML cleanup code does not handle the tags correctly. So even though he has told tinyMCE to take the code as he wrote it, it still applies a cleanup filter before saving the data to drupal\nHas anyone else run into this sort of problem before? Is there an easy way to configure drupal to bypass tinyMCE and accept raw HTML? On a per-user or per-document basis would be better still.","createdDate":"2008-11-11T19:33:09.000Z","updatedDate":"2010-01-31T22:36:54.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:10628","contributorName":"e12vds0aqfkv","description":"Another option to webforms or forms api, is to create a custom content type with cck.\n\nFor tinymce settings (/admin/settings/tinymce), you can specify whether users have the option to use tinymce by default. If you allow this, then each user who has access to tinymce, can turn off tinymce by default.\n\nAnd to disable it per document / or node type.\n<a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/104879\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal.org/node/104879</a>","createdDate":"2010-01-31T22:36:53.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4053","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"I am not a fan of TinyMCE, in Drupal or anywhere else for that matter. It is anything but \"tiny\" and has sacrificed ease of use for ease of expansion. I just think it is a bloated product for 95% of what people generally use WYSIWYG's for (bold, links, images, etc). We have started integrating a jQuery WYSIWYG into our apps which is really simple and easy to use: <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/jwysiwyg/\">http://code.google.com/p/jwysiwyg/</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-27T19:34:23.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:4045","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I started using the \"<a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/webform\">webforms</a>\" module, see it in action here:\n<a href=\"http://cnr.ncsu.edu/it_services/help\">http://cnr.ncsu.edu/it_services/help</a>\n\nBut, in general, I'm still not 100% satisfied with tinymce, how it behaves and how it outputs.","createdDate":"2009-02-27T18:30:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:3861","contributorName":"1l94q89y956k5","description":"This is probably a dead thread, but as far as I know the easiest way to make forms in Drupal is to use its API and make them in PHP. That way you get the built-in verification for fields and it keeps the styling consistent with the theme. There are some verification issues for 'get' forms as opposed to 'post', which can be gotten around with multi-step forms, but I didn't explore that far.\n\nThis thread is a good place to start with a tutorial and links to examples: <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/68159\">http://drupal.org/node/68159</a>","createdDate":"2009-02-24T15:01:45.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:380","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I just did a quick search at <a href=\"http://drupal.org\">http://drupal.org</a>, but didn't find anything. Might be worth posting this question to their forums, the Drupal forums are really active!","createdDate":"2008-11-12T18:26:58.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:209","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","title":"Adobe on Campus","description":"I don't think Adobe was what Jason had in mind when he created the \"Applications\" Forum section but it works for what we need.\n\nAdobe did a demo at the OIT Expo of the recently-released CS4 Suite of products. Following that, Duke had the Adobe people out for a day-long session showcasing all the applications. I got some very positive feedback when I suggested restarting the Adobe Users Group on campus but I thought this site would be a great way to reach a larger constiutancy. That cannot possibly be spelled right.\n\nAnyway, I have two questions:\n1. Would you be interested in participating in an Adobe Users Group on campus and\n2. Would you be interested in attending a CS4 demo if we could get the Adobe folks to NCSU?\n-- And on that topic, what apps would you most like to see demonstrated?","createdDate":"2008-11-11T15:05:53.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-14T14:39:27.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Applications","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:612","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"I'm quite sure Jude, Rhonda, and I would attend as well.","createdDate":"2008-11-14T14:39:27.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:535","contributorName":"3h8vedhr1e7gr","description":"I think allowing students on here would be fine-- I see no reason to limit it.\n\nAs for students in the Adobe session. I'm not sure if we'd be able to handle that. The potential locations will probably be pretty tight for the faculty and staff audience we already have. I'm afraid students would put us over the top. That being said we might be able to request a second session if we're sure there's a large enough student audience for that kind of event.\n\nI'm in communication with the Adobe rep and I hope to be able to post Adobe event(s) very soon...","createdDate":"2008-11-13T18:22:04.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:504","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"My $0.02, we <i>should</i> allow anyone on campus (students, fac, staff, whoever) who is interested to be in any of these user groups, webdevelopers included. I think students often bring a fresh perspective and would give as much to the group as they get out of it.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T16:05:47.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:493","contributorName":"3f6w5e1hs2ifq","description":"I would participate in an Adobe Users Group. A CS4 demo would be very nice. I'd be interested in Photoshop, Illustrator, Flash, After Effects, and InDesign. Premiere Pro and Soundbooth would be cool too.","createdDate":"2008-11-13T14:54:37.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:377","contributorName":"3p7bzgj31hmap","description":"I am interested in both, thanks Jen. As far as a demo, I'm interested in Contribute CS4 and <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/contribute/server/\">Contribute Publishing Server</a>.\n\nI like the idea of specialized sub-groups under the big \"webdevelopers\" umbrella and this would be a great start. I actually think there could be even more specialization of groups. For example an Adobe Design group and an Adobe Web group. The designers are interested in Photoshop, Illustrator, Fireworks, ImageReady, etc - while the Web group are the Dreamweaver and Contribute bunch. I'm just thinking about how nice it would be if I could easily connect with everyone on campus who is using the Contribute model for their college/department. Just a suggestion, I really do like the idea of the general Adobe Group! Thanks for starting this conversation up!","createdDate":"2008-11-12T18:18:42.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:264","contributorName":"3hocxvb8cf1sa","description":"Just added a group on this site for Adobe -- check it out if you want to discuss all things adobe, that's probably a good place to have it :-)\n\n<a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/adobe\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/group/adobe</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-11T18:29:22.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:248","contributorName":"048o8i00t8d9v","description":"I would be interested in AUG on campus and the demo...interested in Photoshop and Dreamweaver.","createdDate":"2008-11-11T17:37:40.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:243","contributorName":"0sar17vraypai","description":"I think it would be interesting to hear what the Adobe people have to say. I would be particularly interested in the accessibility features of flash. The same would be true of Silverlight from MS.","createdDate":"2008-11-11T17:21:44.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:211","contributorName":"36mexpty3zftm","description":"I do the Photoshops fairly regularly, so I'd prolly show up to see a CS4 demo if they came to campus.","createdDate":"2008-11-11T15:49:46.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:194","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","title":"Triangle User Experience","description":"Hi folk! I'm bringing this up because I find that a lot of people aren't aware of it. I wasn't aware of it until, get this, a friend from Portland found it. Anyway, the Triangle User Experience is a developer community that focuses on discussions around user interfaces and such, primarily for web applications. I haven't been to one of their meetings yet but I'm \"a member\". (It's free) They pull in some interesting events periodically. Like they had one of the Adobe Flex developers come by about a year ago and talked about Flex 3, tips and tricks for user interfaces, etc etc. I missed it unfortunately, but wished I could have gone! Anyway, check it out, y'all might be interested:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.triangleuserexperience.org/tue/index.html\">http://www.triangleuserexperience.org/tue/index.html</a>","createdDate":"2008-11-11T13:38:06.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-11T14:07:03.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Web Programming","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:202","contributorName":"0cddqfx9u95kt","description":"SparkWeb is what we (when I was at Jive) did with it ... <a href=\"http://www.igniterealtime.org/products/sparkweb\">http://www.igniterealtime.org/products/sparkweb</a>\nIt's actually quite powerful, but at the same time is one of those languages that I find myself following the documentation to accomplish something, and despite following the docs it doesn't do ... anything! Mostly issues related to UI though. Flex Builder (eclipse with a slightly modded face) is unfortunately not free, but there's something else I'd come across ... what is it... aha Flash Develop. <a href=\"http://www.flashdevelop.org/community/\">http://www.flashdevelop.org/community/</a> It's.. an odd site. Looks just like a community but hidden in there are downloads for it. (windows only unfortunately) I've never used it, don't know how good it is, and am only 95% sure it handles mxml. ;)\n\n(actually you may be able to get flex builder free as a university employee, not sure, I know students and faculty can)","createdDate":"2008-11-11T14:07:03.000Z"},{"id":"2486881:Comment:199","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","description":"Ya know, I've been very interested to see what Flex has to offer. We played with it some after ZendCon07, but haven't had an opportunity to get back to it. Anybody on campus using Flex for anything cool?","createdDate":"2008-11-11T13:45:57.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:88","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Notes from the Delivering Web Services meeting","description":"Meeting: Delivering Web Services: Exploring new solutions for campus\nDate/Time/Location: 11/07/08, 1:30-3:00, David Clark Labs Room 101\nModerators: Jason Austin, Jen Riehle\n\nJason called the meeting to order at about 1:35, and introduced himself and Jen.\n\n<b>Why are we here?</b>\nTo explore campus needs for web service delivery and to brainstorm about solutions. This discussion was prompted as a result of the migration of the OIT website to Drupal and questions that came about as a result of that project. Questions like:\nHow do we deliver applications (like Drupal) to more than just a few folks?\nHow do we keep common applications secure and updated?\nHow do we manage support and training as the number of users grows?\nHow do we provide solutions when the \u201cflavor of the wee\u201d application is no longer wanted?\n\n<b>The \u201cState of Web Services\u201d address</b>\nCurrent web service delivery is: (1) AFS-based, managed by a central database server, (2) provides access to PHP and Perl, (3) is available via request, and (4) training and support for end users exists for it.\nThere are some issues with this model: (1) web server security issues via AFS, (2) limited to PHP and Perl (no Ruby, Python, ColdFusion), (3) technology upgrade issues (PHP4 to PHP5 transition), (4) limited access (costs, University affiliation, www4), (5) limited support for common applications, and (6) no centralized delivery for common applications.\n\n<b>What are our needs?</b>\nNeeds from a service-provider perspective include: (1) a scalable, secure solution for delivering web services, (2) an agile environment adaptable to changing needs, (3) the ability to deliver and update common applications, (4) a supportable infrastructure, and (5) an efficient strategy for deployment.\nNeeds from a consumer perspective include: (1) to be able to easily request and get access to the tools needed, (2) fast turn-around time, (3) lots of options for applications and technologies, (4) ongoing updates and maintenance, (5) uptime and backups, and (6) support and training staff to help along the way.\n\nIndustrial Engineering: We have a lot of issues with configuration options.\n\nBarry (from OIT): (1) Effective ways to manage permissions with whatever web applications we have, both individual access and group access. (2) It would be helpful to have a wrap-protected demo to just try out a product.\n\nGlen Waters of the Vet School: Sometimes commercial apps need to be supported, too. (e.g, Oracle, ColdFusion, etc.). They bought a hospital application that\u2019s supposed to work with Oracle, but when that didn\u2019t work easily, they needed support. Noted that commercial applications should be considered as well when interfacing with existing campus resources.\n\nAlan Gerber (from CNR) I\u2019d like to see an expanded effort in terms of collaboration. There is no community or forum where I can say, \u201cHey this is out there if you want to use it.\u201d\n\nAlan Shuler (with CALS): We have a diverse campus with different computing needs, but we tend to operate like it isn\u2019t. That is we tend to try and have a central way of doing things and that\u2019s what we focus on supporting. \u201cIf it\u2019s not the model, we can\u2019t do it\u201d approach can\u2019t work. We need to top-down model going from the outside-in model to the inside-out model.\n\n<b>A possible solution?</b>\nWe\u2019re interested in your thoughts on a few things:\nIs there even a need to change from the current model?\nWhat kind of solutions would work for your needs?\nAre we missing something that is important to you?\n\nJeff? from ?: I see the value of having a separate instance that I can control and modify. I\u2019ve been looking at things like what Google is offering. Like here\u2019s the version you can pick from. We run it. You can add stuff in. I don\u2019t know that I necessarily want to be stuck in \u201chere\u2019s the level we\u2019re going to stick to, support, and have\u2026\u201d\n\nJosh Gira (CNR): Looking at our college with a lot of extension services. We need a method to make things available to off-campus groups in the extensions. People come to them and say we want to do this, but that isn\u2019t available on campus.\n\nGlen Waters of the Vet School: An outside group would like to get into our services, like Vets that want to use our data. We would love to be able to let a vet look at the information for all of the patients they have referred, for example. The most useful thing I\u2019ve gotten from you guys was that listserv where everyone\u2019 introducing themselves.\n\nAnother person (didn\u2019t introduce): A way to know what\u2019s going on on campus in general would be good.\n\nDan: For Drupal. We already have modules. They exist. It would be good to know what they are, so people don\u2019t have to create themselves.\n\nJason: We\u2019ve thrown around the idea of going toward the \u201chosting model.\u201d One-click installs to be able to publish these centralized applications out. Someone asked if this would include students. Yes.\n\nJohn Martin (OCC): Mentioned the notion of a culture change to self-help first then there be an expert at the help desk.\n\nCharlie Morris from CNR: W/Drupal if there were a page with every drupal instance, who the owner is and maybe a summary page of what they\u2019re doing with Drupal. If OIT could create communities of users. Jason mentioned the challenge of keeping them updated. Someone mentioned making it a Wiki where we people can keep the list updated themselves.\n\nSomeone asked if OIT has asked how UNC and Duke are doing this. They are next to talk to. There might be some opportunity for that at UNC Cause.\n\nTed Gyro (Univ Housing and Greek Life): Just joined the listserv (webdevelopers). The school I came from, OIT was very centralized. 7 or 8 web developers did all of the web work for 30,000 students. I strongly support the notion of building community to help each other. I\u2019d rather go through that than through the help desk.\n\nLaura Thompson form EAS: Seconds the notion of communities. Social networking seems to be a recurring answer. Maybe we have a place with profiles (techies.ncsu.edu exists but is not currently heavily used).\n\nRay Kinsey (?) CALS Extension: Would like to second a couple of things: We need faster turnaround on versions (of some product they\u2019re using that I missed). We\u2019ve been on V5 for too long. MySQL would cost us a fortune if we had to pay for every single db. I think looking at the way you charge for db\u2019s needs to be looked at. The forums/social networking\u2026 I know more about what\u2019s going on in my particular role at other universities because I follow people at those universities who are doing what i\u2019m doing.\n\nLaura: One easy way to make sure people know about lists is to have HR include majordomo info in orientation. A monthly summary of things that are going out already from \u201ctop dogs\u201d to include a blurb in there.\n\nShawn Dunning from Textiles: I like the idea of talking about this. One thing that would be advantageous to doing it in-house . When you go to sign up for a hosting plan, here is a list of the things you should know\u2026 or include it in the package when someone signs up that it tells them where there are listservs related to that product/service.\n\nSomeone noted that the number of people actually controlling resources on this campus is pretty small. (Academic IT directors, which we established several years ago tells OIT\u2026) What we haven\u2019t seen is the same kind of initiative of OIT coming back to us. Proactively go out to the colleges and say, \u201cWho has an interest in this and would like to come help us with it?\u201d The help desk issue: he has two tickets about things he thinks are important, but he has no idea what their statuses are. As a \u201ccollege director(?)\u201d I would expect to not have to root around in Remedy to find out what\u2019s happening with my problems.\n\nBarry: Wanted to make a plug Wiki service that would have access controls. Let\u2019s say you have a project, and you need certain pages to be internal. We want to make some pages protected. I would suggest OIT look at something called \u201cCompliments\u201d (?). [Someone else seconded this.]\n\nJason: With services that you guys want that we can\u2019t provide support for: For you, would it be better for us to have a service that we can\u2019t support, or do you expect support if we do offer it.\n\nJohn (Advanced Analytics): Some kind of in-house knowledge repository, best practices, etc. would have helped us tremendously in coming onboard with who AFS lockers, etc. work. He agreed that they want to be programmers, not sys admins.\n\nPeople seemed to agree that if OIT said they would make sure you have a license and that it\u2019s up and running. OIT doesn\u2019t have to know all of the technologies. Some of the things that are campus-wide should probably have support.\n\nJason noted that training is an area where folks could help OIT out. If you\u2019re going to teach a class of 10 people in your area, considering opening it up to everyone to teach anyone who might be interested.\n\nNo name/dept: Here it is. Use at your own risk. As long as that\u2019s clear up front, that would be okay.\nFollowup on community aspect: Would like to see OIT provide a PHP/CPC list that people could share and maybe be associated with a repository. WRT looking at the teaching: Open up our classmate model where we always look internally for a class teacher, look outside into the community/campus to offer the classes.\n\nLaura: Wouldn\u2019t mind services if they weren\u2019t supported as there are often other ways to learn. The only concern I would have would be about how often do you update. For instance, I wouldn\u2019t want to get something from you that was at level x of Perl when I can only use it if it\u2019s at y level.\n\nAnother person from the Vet school: He\u2019s worried about things going away that they\u2019re using, for instance, streaming media services.\n\nAndy Raynor from the College of Education: would love to see Joomla available to manage web sites.\n\nA community site with links to these things that people have tried or are already using would be helpful.\n\nOld school: I prefer pull to push. Jason talked about personal preferences.\n\nSomeone mentioned providing a place to give feedback after this meeting. (<a href=\"http://xteams.oit.ncsu.edu/webservices/blog\">http://xteams.oit.ncsu.edu/webservices/blog</a>)\n\n\n<b>Next steps</b>\nCompile the results from today and share with the campus\nChoose a solution\nExplore funding models to make it possible\nCreate proposal to send to Dr. Hoit\nKeep fingers crossed\u2026","createdDate":"2008-11-10T15:55:43.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-12-17T18:41:22.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc.","comments":[{"id":"2486881:Comment:1704","contributorName":"27wih35ubsbiw","description":"A follow-up meeting to this one was held at UNC CAUSE '08 to bring the discussion to other universities. Information and notes about that meeting are here: <a href=\"http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/notes-from-delivering-web\">http://ncsuwebdev.ning.com/forum/topics/notes-from-delivering-web</a>","createdDate":"2008-12-17T18:41:22.000Z"}]},{"id":"2486881:Topic:21","contributorName":"17x8avmzkahg9","title":"Welcome and Getting Started","description":"Welcome to Ning, which is a custom social networking site. I decided to set us up here to see how it goes. No sense in re-creating the wheel.\n\nIf you have questions about how to use our Ning instance, ask em up!","createdDate":"2008-11-10T13:20:42.000Z","updatedDate":"2008-11-10T14:09:41.000Z","approved":"Y","category":"Campus Policy/Procedures/Misc."}])